<SLUG> BC-NY-JUDGE-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT CURMUDGEON BIDS A TYPCAL GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is possible thatJustice Burton Roberts, the
departing chief administrative judge of state Supreme Court in the
Bronx, has learned from his friend Tom Wolfe, who modeled the
irascible judge in ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' after him, that
it is always more effective to show than to tell. Thus, Roberts may
simply be trying to help out the reporter by displaying a flash of
his famous temper.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe he's just irritated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you do, pull out a story that's 20 years old?''
Roberts is yelling, in a voice that has been described by one Bronx
courthouse regular as a couple of decibels below the roar of an
airplane engine, and that is when he is not angry. ``The Times is
true to form! God forbid you write a nice story about me as I go
bye-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   The story later. First, the words that no story about Burton
Roberts can be without: ``colorful,'' ``outspoken,'' ``legendary.''
Also, as the judge reminds you, when you mention this to him,
``feisty.''
</P>
<P>
   He has spent five decades in the judicial system, first as an
assistant district attorney under Frank Hogan in Manhattan, then as
the Bronx district attorney, then as top justice in the Bronx, and
one thing nobody ever accused him of was lack of nerve.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki took
a swipe at him for setting a bail they considered low, Roberts
dismissed their comments as ``the bleating of public officials who
possibly are seeking political advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Roberts has been fighting mandatory sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the mandatory minimums, you make the sentences too harsh,
and the defense will opt to go to trial and one can only try 6.5
percent of our cases now,'' Roberts says in what sounds like the
beginning of a speech, and, as it turns out after about 20 minutes,
is.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to interject questions fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me finish,'' the judge says.
</P>
<P>
   So, while he's holding forth, the story _ which he did not
dispute _ that earlier got him bothered: Some years ago, Roberts,
who often called up reporters and alerted, praised or berated them
regarding coverage, had a case about which he was particularly
proud and scheduled a news conference. The New York Daily News,
either because of excellent reporting (The News' version) or
failing to honor an embargo (the Roberts version), ran an article
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the TV and newspapers that would normally show up at the
press conference showed up and Burt got very peeved,'' says Dick
Oliver, a reporter at WNYW-TV who was at the time the assistant
city editor at The News. ``At the press conference he railed on
about the `anti-Semitic Daily News, this rag downtown.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So the decision was made: For the next 90 days the words
`Burton Roberts' would not appear in The Daily News. It was
`according to the Bronx DA's office.' During the middle of this
thing, Roberts _ who I love _ he calls the reporter who, good
reporter that he was, taped the call and you can hear him pleading,
`Please give me a shot, it's too much,' so the decision was made to
commute his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also want to say he's the most straightforward judge and
person I've ever run into in 30 years in this business,'' Oliver
says.
</P>
<P>
   Another word frequently used about Roberts: ``caring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite his image as a tough guy, he's really compassionate,''
says the Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer.
</P>
<P>
   Where that temper and that compassion come from is hard to say.
One clue may lie with Roberts' mother, who raised him in Washington
Heights after she and his father separated. If a student was
trouble, Roberts said, his mother would escort him to the library,
pick up a big book, give him ``a shot in the head'' and he ``would
be good as gold.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who saw action in World War II, got through law
school on the GI Bill. A signal moment came later, when a law firm
withdrew a job offer after it learned that Roberts was Jewish.
``That hurt me terribly,'' he says. He took a job in the district
attorney's office and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Another old story now, from a 37-year-old man who first met
Roberts on the wrong side of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came before Judge Roberts when I was 16,'' says the man, who
asked to maintain his privacy. ``From a very young age I started
getting involved in some bad stuff. Robbing restaurants, things of
that nature. Life seemed sort of hopeless. I never thought I'd see
21.''
</P>
<P>
   His first meeting with Roberts was, the man says, ``not a pretty
meeting _ as a matter of fact he threw me out of the courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Later on,'' the man says, ``he came to me and said, `You're
just a kid and you have a long life ahead of you; this doesn't have
to be the end.' He started writing me. We wrote each other from
Rikers.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man served two years as a youthful offender. Later, he
graduated from Pace University with honors. When he needed
references, the judge wrote them. Today the man earns $60,000 a
year as an energy analyst in the New York Mercantile Exchange. He
has lunch or dinner with Roberts, or with the judge and his wife,
every few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just seemed to care what happened to me,'' the man says.
``It wasn't like the usual assembly-line type of approach in
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bye-bye, Justice Roberts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
