<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S INSTANT OFFENSE FOR WAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ If it was practice, Al Minahan would hit the
jump shot. No question about it.
</P>
<P>
   He's a shooter. It's his forte, which he developed at Inglemoor
High in Seattle. He's not a great defender, not a rebounder and not
a passing genius.
</P>
<P>
   Minahan's a shooter. Plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was his success in practice never transferred to the
game, and because he's a defensive liability, it wasn't feasible to
give the Pepperdine sophomore many minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the opponent was NAIA Southern California College,
Minahan was so good, he's forced Waves coach Lorenzo Romar to
reconsider the playing time factor. Minahan hit six 3-pointers and
scored 24 points in 21 minutes as Pepperdine beat the Vanguards
94-64 Thursday at Firestone Fieldhouse to end a losing streak at
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for someone to break out and make baskets
for us,'' Romar said. ``He's earned more minutes. That's what you
do. You come in and show the coach why you should be getting more
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   How unlikely was Minahan's outburst? Consider he scored 18
points in six contests before the game. And Minahan scored 26
points his freshman year, and made six 3-pointers that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised a little bit,'' said the 6-foot-3 Minahan.
``What I have to do is stay solid on defense. That's how I'll stay
in there. Usually, I'm in the right position, but on-ball pressure
is what I need to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense is rarely compensated for with offense. But given the
Waves' inability to score consistently, Minahan's shortcomings
might be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves (6-3) are atrocious from the perimeter, shooting a
hair above 30 percent for the season on 3-pointers. David
Lalazarian and Tommie Prince were supposed to supply that
ingredient of the offense, but Prince didn't play because of a sore
foot and Lalazarian is 5 of 28 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed a dreadful figure and one that signifies how wretched the
Waves have been. Just look back to the 1-for-13 performance on
3-pointers in the loss to Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Al can shoot it. He's a pure shooter,'' Pepperdine
point guard Jelani Gardner said. ``It's a little bit tougher when
you're coming off the bench getting limited shot attempts and
you're not in your rhythm every time you come in the game. But that
guy's a pure shooter, and every time he's on the court I'm looking
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Minahan's 6-of-8 shooting from 3-point range is a long-overdue
dividend from a few summers worth of work in his native Seattle.
During the average workout, Minahan would fire 400 to 500 shots,
mostly 3-pointers. He'd do it three times a week, mixing in a few
games of pick-up ball.
</P>
<P>
   Do the math and during Minahan's first season at Pepperdine, he
took 200 to 250 jumpers per summer workout week for every 3-pointer
he made with the Waves. The ratio wasn't quite that ugly this
season, but it wasn't sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes my arm would get tired,'' Minahan said with a slight
smile. ``I never worried about it. I've been doing it since I was a
freshman in high school. It paid off in high school so I figured
eventually it had to start dropping here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
