<SLUG> BC-BKC-PREP-PHENOM-MOVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTN. VIEW'S LATIMORE BEGINS ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, ARIZ. - Etched on Dennis Latimore's right shoulder is
``Kansas,'' a tattoo he obtained soon after leaving Halstead late
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a reminder of where I'm from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, home is Mesa, where the 16-year-old lives with his father
and plays basketball like no other sophomore in Arizona _ or most
of the land, for that matter _ for top-ranked Mountain View High.
</P>
<P>
   He looks and plays older than his years. He is 6-foot-8{, 235
pounds. He has soft hands and an aggressive nature around the
backboard, which he once shattered in eighth grade with a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he must focus on something bigger than just a game.
He is trying to develop a relationship with a man who has been only
an occasional visitor since he was 2.
</P>
<P>
   As he tries to adjust to a bigger universe than the one he left,
Latimore learns more each day about his father, Denver, who this
summer was awarded custody of Dennis from a Kansas court.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Dennis said, the judge left him to decide for himself
which parent to live with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to let go, but I knew it was my decision,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He left behind an older brother, many friends, a new coach at
Halstead High who was counting on him, and, more important, a
mother he loves dearly.
</P>
<P>
   He says he talks to his mother, Melinda, on the phone every
Sunday, and they communicate regularly via e-mail. She tries to
keep up with her son's basketball on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't the same. She was supposed to have him during
Thanksgiving, but Mountain View was playing in its tournament. It
was the first Thanksgiving they ever spent apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports is just a small part of life,'' said his mother, who
teaches special education at a high school in Wichita. ``We don't
have Thanksgiving tournaments. We don't have tournaments up to New
Year's Eve. Where is the family? That part was very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorce and custody battles are rarely easy. The children often
are victims.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Latimore Sr., who divorced his wife before Dennis was 2,
said he tried for years to gain custody of his two sons. Denver Jr.
recently joined his father and brother in Mesa after playing out
his senior football season at Halstead.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Sr., who teaches at Mesa Community College, said he moved
to Mesa in 1989 for a better career opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I regret when I left there, I didn't get a
chance to see them on a regular basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to make up for lost time. This summer, Dennis said
he wanted to know more about his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want what is important for me and him. I want him to be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The door is left open. Dennis says there is no pressure, that he
can go back to his mom any time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Melinda worries that the Valley might be too big for
her son, that he could fall prey to temptations that aren't found
in Halstead, a small, close-knit community 35 miles outside
Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   When Dennis returns to Halstead for Christmas, Melinda will see
a son who grew half an inch since he left and the tattoo that he
didn't tell her about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids don't get tattoos here,'' she said. ``If you do, you have
to cover it up during games.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, who averages 13.8 points and nine rebounds for the Toros
(8-2), who play in the Reebok Holiday Classic in Las Vegas starting
today, said the move hasn't changed him. He still gets up the
moment the alarm clock rings. He doesn't need a workout partner to
push him in the weight room or on the court.
</P>
<P>
   After a late workout, he studies in the Mountain View locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little more challenging out here, academically,'' said
Dennis, who left Halstead with a 4.0 grade-point average. ``It's a
good school.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said he's not sure if he'll finish his high school career
in Mesa. He says he worries about his mother now that his older
brother left. He said he wants to make sure somebody is there to
take care of her.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain View Coach Gary Ernst is happy to have Latimore but
realizes it may be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock to see him,'' Ernst said. ``All of a sudden he
just showed up in the gymnasium. He seems very well adjusted after
all he went through this summer. As good a player as he is, what
impresses me is the quality of the young man he is.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year his mother has missed one of Dennis'
games.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers how he first dunked in the sixth grade, how he
came home one day that year with a broken wrist for dunking the
basketball so hard. One of the first things she captured on a new
camcorder was Dennis shattering the backboard glass during a game
in eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Latimore is rated anywhere from the second- to 10th-best
sophomore in the country by everybody from ``The Sporting News'' to
``Street &AMP; Smith'' to ``Athlon'' to a recruiting Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't let that stuff get to my head,'' Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   His parents say they won't allow it.
</P>
<P>
   His father says he stresses the importance of an education and
being a good citizen.
</P>
<P>
   His mother prays that the change of lifestyle won't change her
son, that he'll remain modest with a strong work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting used to things now,'' Dennis said. ``Basketball is
going good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting to know my father, which is good. And my mother is
right there, in my heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
