<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-LETTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST NBA OFFER GOES POSTAL  
 MAILED LETTER DIVISIVE, SCHAYES SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB Young  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his latest effort to take his case directly to players, NBA
Commissioner David Stern Thursday sent them an outline of the
latest labor proposal from owners.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also was distributed to media outlets, including
``The Arizona'' ``Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Stern tells players it is ``important that there
be no doubt about the precise terms you consider to be such a `bad
deal' that you would prefer to lose the entire season.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, 45 days of the regular season and about $480 million in
player salaries have been lost to the lockout, and the earliest a
shortened season could begin is probably late January.
</P>
<P>
   All in a battle over how to split $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as another attempt to divide the players,'' said
Danny Schayes, a member of the players' negotiating team. ``It
seems like they're waving it in the players' faces, `Look how hard
we're trying. Contact your union representative.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to think the players are not informed, and they
certainly are informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern's letter outlines what the league perceives as concessions
that owners have made since the lockout began July 1, including
agreeing to keep the so-called Larry Bird exception to the league's
salary cap, backing off a ``hard'' salary cap, modifying their
position on ``timing rules,'' which would affect how the Bird
exception could be applied, and limiting an ``escrow'' system and
``luxury tax'' on players if the percentage of revenues that go to
salaries exceed a predetermined limit.
</P>
<P>
   The league also provided players several charts that illustrate
that the average salary of an NBA player is higher than athletes in
the NFL, NHL and Major League Baseball, another that plots a
projected increase in that average salary to $4.569 million by
2003-04 and a third that shows the maximum salaries players may
receive under the Bird exception over the life of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Kleine _ a former officer in the Players Association who
lives in the Valley _ said the letter fails to address one of the
major issues in the negotiations. It details at what percentage of
revenue an escrow tax would be implemented starting in 2001-02, but
it does not stipulate what percentage of salaries may be placed in
escrow. Nor does it say what tax would be imposed upon teams that
exceed the percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are big issues,'' he said. ``The amount of the tax and
how it will be paid go a long way in determining how hard of a cap
it is. Those are pretty huge links in the chain.''
</P>
<P>
   An NBA spokesman said that neither Stern nor deputy commissioner
Russ Granik would be available to comment on the letter.
</P>
<P>
   According to the league, the latest proposal would mean that
average player salaries will grow to $4.5 million by the end of the
deal, 10-year veteran players would be guaranteed a minimum salary
of $1 million, and superstars still could get contracts valued at
more than $100 million for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of big pieces of the puzzle left out,''
Schayes said. ``Unfortunately, in this sound-bite world we live in,
people don't get the details. You have to look at the details to
make heads or tails of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Schayes said a lot of veteran players will be
hurt, not helped, by a new minimum-salary scale and that owners are
claiming to be making concessions and compromises on items they
don't have.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's letter, he points out, says the owners have backed off
one proposal for splitting up group licensing money and instead
will accept the elimination of a guaranteed percentage of that
money for players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That agreement isn't up for another five years,'' Schayes
said. ``They're acting like they're giving something up when they
don't even have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kleine found the outline to be incomplete, he's still
optimistic that a deal can be reached before the season is lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we can tweak it just a little, we might have a
deal,'' he said. ``The biggest thing is still the percentage of
(basketball-related income applied to salaries).
</P>
<P>
   ``If both sides would just agree to meet halfway on that, say
54.5 percent or 55 percent, whatever it is, I think we would have a
deal pretty quickly. But the escrow makes me nervous. They seem to
want to gloss over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Stern allowed team owners to communicate directly
with players to inform them about the owner's proposals at that
point, and Kleine said the escrow issues were similarly ignored in
those conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Kleine said the current proposal would be good enough for him,
but players have to consider more than their own interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, what they've proposed is fine,'' he said. ``I'm at the
end of my career. But if you look at the young guys coming into the
league and the up-and-coming players, they would be hurt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
