<HEADLINE>
PLAYING WITH PAIN: SUCCESS, SUFFERING COIN CIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-three years later, Cardinals Hall of Famer Larry Wilson
remains the NFL's poster boy for playing hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who intercepted a pass in a 1965 game against Pittsburgh
despite having two broken hands, doesn't think he was tougher than
modern players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just in those days, if you could run, you played,'' said
Wilson, now a Cardinals vice president. ``The rest didn't make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals middle linebacker Ronald McKinnon can relate. He was
so furious when he suffered a sprained knee last month at Kansas
City, he grabbed teammate Mark Maddox's knee brace and placed it on
his injured right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie yelled, `Get it (the knee pad) off him (Maddox),' ''
defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said. ``He was told he couldn't
go back in. He said, `No, I can play. I can play.' I've never seen
anybody do that.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon eventually left the game and has been out the past two
weeks. He is expected to return Sunday against New Orleans at Sun
Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``McKinnon's college coach, Bobby Wallace, told me, `I never
could keep (McKinnon) out of practice,' '' McGinnis said. ``He said
they won a lot of games because he wouldn't come out.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon isn't the only Cardinals defender with a high pain
threshold. Outside linebacker Jamir Miller has played the past 11
games with a dislocated wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pain is relative to the person,'' Miller said. ``Some people's
threshold is a lot higher than others'. I think as athletes, we can
deal with pain more than average people. I just felt that if I
could go, I'd go. It hurt bad for a while, but it wasn't hindering
me to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of defensive tackle Eric Swann having
season-ending ``elective'' knee surgery last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people forget he tried to play hurt,'' a Cardinals
official said. ``His knees were sore, and he kept trying to play on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals physician Wayne Kuhl said that it's easier to play
with injuries at some positions than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood of a running back who has a fractured hand
benefiting a team is much less than a defensive lineman with a
fractured hand,'' Kuhl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football players, as a whole, are mentally very tolerant of
pain. Still, it's such an individual thing, and as a physician, you
have to have the acceptance and belief of what the player is
telling you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuhl said Cardinals offensive tackle Lomas Brown has the highest
threshold of pain he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Brown played at Baltimore despite a kidney stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a stent running from his kidney through the bladder to
the outside,'' Kuhl said. ``It was removed subsequently, without
anesthesia, and he played. It was amazing.'' &QL; 
A different era &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a 14-year pro, said the honor is one he'd rather not have
earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, more than anything, it was the era I was brought
in,'' Brown said. ``In the mid-1980s, there was no scout team. You
did all the offensive plays in practice. The game was built on
toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Vice President Bob Ferguson said the toughest guy he
has been around is Denver offensive lineman Mark Schlereth, who has
had 22 surgeries, including 17 knee operations.
</P>
<P>
   When Schlereth was with the Washington Redskins, he would often
wake up in the middle of the night, screaming in pain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when Ferguson was with the Broncos, Schlereth passed a
kidney stone in the morning and played that night against the
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he suffered torn knee cartilage at training camp
but continued to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only sissies need all their cartilage to play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said former Buffalo Bills offensive lineman Jim Ritcher
once played with a broken neck. ``We didn't know it was broken,''
Ferguson said. ``MRIs (magnetic resonance imagings) weren't
available in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, who formerly played with the Bills, said linebacker
Darryl Talley had such a bad back late in his career, he couldn't
sleep on a bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He slept on the wooden floor, a hardwood floor,'' Maddox said.
``Come Sunday, he was ready to go.'' &QL; 
The Bradshaw course &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive-line coach Joe Greene, a Hall of Fame tackle
with the Pittsburgh Steelers, remembered that Cleveland's Turkey
Jones spiked Steelers quarterback Terry Bradshaw on a sack in 1976.
Bradshaw suffered a bruised collarbone, an injury that was supposed
to keep him out for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw came back and played the next week, prompting a team
doctor to say, ``I'm going to have to go back to college and do the
course `Bradshaw.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Bradshaw played with a cast on his left arm. In another
game, he was carried off the field on a stretcher at halftime and
returned in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went down, we thought he was down for the count,''
Greene said. ``He flopped like a chicken. But he was there when we
needed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals center Mike Devlin said his roommate when he was on
the Bills, offensive lineman John Davis, was in such pain when he
played that ``both knees and shoulders were bone to bone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would get shot up, pilled up'' to kill the pain, Devlin
said. ``He would be down every play. You'd say, `He's not getting
up.' He'd be back up. Then you'd say, `He's not getting up this
time.' He'd get back up and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said former Lions defensive back Duane Galloway once had a
tooth knocked out and stayed in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked the tooth off the ground and put it in and played
the rest of the game,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying guys these days are not as mentally tough, but
it's different. You were expected to play with pain and injuries,
even in practice.'' &QL; 
Wadsworth a throwback &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth, the team's $42
million first-round draft choice, must be a throwback. He stayed in
the game against the New York Giants on Dec. 6 despite a calf
injury that prevented him from running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what's on the line,'' Wadsworth said. ``There's a
lot of stuff right now on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson smiled when he heard Wadsworth's remarks. Then he
explained how he broke the finger on his left hand against the New
York Giants in 1965 when he was trying to make a tackle. Doctors
taped it up, and he stayed in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was broke,'' he said. &QL; 
Look ma, broken hands &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Later in the game, he was lying on the ground when a Giants
player stepped on his right hand, breaking it. Again, trainers did
a taping job.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors placed a cast on his left hand the next day. They wanted
to put a cast on his right one, but Wilson convinced them to put a
``portable'' one on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I've got to go to the bathroom and do other things,'
'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   He intercepted Pittsburgh quarterback Bill Nelsen the next week
and returned the ball 34 yards despite the two broken hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``People played with a lot more pain during my era,'' Wilson
said. ``The money has gotten such that people think of their
careers every time they have pain and think that injuries will
shorten it. But that's not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``In football, you have to play with pain. If you don't have
some, you haven't played the game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
