<HEADLINE>
`MR. BEIGE' BREATHES LIFE INTO CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ask him whether he feels certain the Cardinals are
going to win Sunday, and this would be his reaction:
</P>
<P>
   First, he would squint, his blue Irish eyes narrowing into
slits. Then he would turn his head slightly to one side while his
lips formed the first words of a guarded reply which predictably,
invariably began, ``Oh, I . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know if I would use the word ``certain'' . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He never lets others put words into his mouth. He won't be
baited. Or steered with questions down a road he doesn't want to
go.
</P>
<P>
   He is thoughtful, careful, diplomatic. He reveals only as much
of himself as he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had beaten the Eagles. After the group interview,
after TV cameras left and writers on deadline rushed off to file
their stories, I asked him how he planned to unwind after what may
have been the most important win in his three seasons here.
</P>
<P>
   A glass of wine perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Vince Tobin gave a half-pained expression. Then he said, not
unkindly, ``Oh, I don't really want to get into that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   There I stood, pressing this man labeled by some as Mr. Beige,
for some personal tidbit I could put in the newspaper. Vince
glanced at my open notebook. A corner of his mouth turned up in a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a tomato juice.'' &QL; 
What he's not &QL; 
Since he took over the mess Buddy Ryan left, Vince Tobin has been
defined by who and what he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't colorful. Or very quotable.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't a ``personality'' who fills up a room, like Mike Ditka.
Tobin has talked at length this week about the Saints' coach, a
longtime friend. You can hear the admiration and affection in his
voice when he describes Ditka's quick wit and snappy one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wish you were more glib, Vince?
</P>
<P>
   Tobin paused, as if caught off guard by the question. He gave
that little smile, almost sheepish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, not really . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't a self-promoter. He doesn't have a TV show. Or a radio
show. (His predecessor once told a caller who had criticized him on
the air, ``There's a lotta good jobs in the NFL. Why don't you go
git yourself one?''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin is too much a gentleman to rip into a fan. He won't permit
himself to react to media criticism, the second-guessing, and he
has drawn his share.
</P>
<P>
   He's not rah-rah. He won't wrap his arms around a player in a
fierce hug. Nor will he berate a player in public view.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't run off the field after a win, pumping his fist in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Tobin what he likes most about his job. ``It's the
thrill of victory,'' he says. That moment after the gun sounds when
he removes his headset and looks at the scoreboard. ``That's what
makes it all worthwhile.'' He may not show his joy to our
satisfaction, but he feels it more intensely than we know.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Tobin is who he is.
</P>
<P>
   The fire's inside &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is the first person at the office the morning after a game.
Unable to sleep, he usually shows up on Mondays by 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   He is an organizer. A sound football coach with an attention to
detail.
</P>
<P>
   He is predictable in the best sense of the word. Players know
the man they deal with today is the man they will see tomorrow. He
is even-keeled. With Tobin, there are no surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Deep within, a fire is burning brightly. ``With Vince, it
doesn't matter if you're playing cards, pool or golf,'' one
assistant coach said. ``He wants to beat you. He's like one of
those snapping turtles that bite you. You've got to cut his head
off to get him to let go.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't see that Irish temper. But the coaches do. The players
do. He can't stand mental mistakes. He will not tolerate lack of
effort.
</P>
<P>
   All Tobin has done is slowly, quietly put together an
oh-I-don't-know-if-I'd use-the-word exceptional team. The Cardinals
are far from that.
</P>
<P>
   But they are improving. They are headed in the right direction.
They have a chance to make the playoffs. For that, the man with the
whistle deserves some credit. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
