<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS PURSUING TRADE FOR VAUGHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - While signing 10 minor league free agents on
Wednesday, the Diamondbacks continued to talk with the San Diego
Padres about a trade for slugger Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. confirmed the discussions but
shot down a rumored trade broadcast by a Valley radio station.
According to the report, the club was close to landing Vaughn, a
left fielder who hit 50 home runs last season, in exchange for
pitcher Brian Anderson, outfielder Bernard Gilkey and a player to
be named.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola acknowledged talking about Vaughn with San Diego
General Manager Kevin Towers but said the report was way off. He
said two of the components of the proposed trade, Gilkey and the
player to be named, were erroneous. He added that talks with Towers
will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola also is talking with Pittsburgh, but he ruled out
obtaining outfielder Jose Guillen, who previously had been
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Guillen thing is shut down,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks and the Cincinnati Reds have discussed
outfielder Reggie Sanders, but the Reds' asking price is believed
to be too high.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming names, Garagiola said he might be interested in
obtaining an outfielder and possibly a middle reliever. He said he
is willing to wait until spring training if the right deal doesn't
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the club signed former major leaguers Pete Incaviglia
and Ernie Young to minor league contracts, along with eight others.
</P>
<P>
   Incaviglia, a 34-year-old outfielder, has hit 206 home runs in
11 major league seasons with Texas, Detroit (twice), Houston
(twice), Philadelphia, Baltimore and the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   He played in seven games with Detroit and 13 games with Houston
in 1998, going a combined 3 for 30. He also played for Triple-A New
Orleans, batting .324 in 76 games.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 29, hit .189 for Kansas City in 25 games last season.
After hitting .242 with 19 homers for Oakland in 1996, he was the
A's opening day starter in center field the next season. But he hit
.223 for the A's and spent part of year at Triple-A Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Also signed were two former Firebirds, pitcher Dan Carlson and
first baseman Desi Wilson. Carlson appeared in 10 games for the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays last season. Wilson, who saw action in 41
games with San Francisco in 1997, played in Japan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Other free agents include infielder Scott Coolbaugh (Texas, San
Diego, St. Louis), catcher Izzy Molina (Oakland), pitcher Matt
Ruebel (Pittsburgh, Tampa Bay), pitchers George Glinatsis and Al
Kermode and catcher Marcus Hanel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
