</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN A FLOP FOR CUMMINS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Jim Cummins' anticipated return to the Coyotes'
lineup went about as well as waiting all day for your holiday
turkey dinner and then watching it fall off the stove and get
devoured by the family dog.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mess. And it almost made you want to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody feels as bad as Jimmy, I'm sure,'' Coyotes Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting out 13 straight games as a healthy scratch,
Cummins' lasted only four shifts in his first game back, getting
thrown out of Wednesday's game in Toronto for not having his jersey
tied down during a fight with the Maple Leafs' Tie Domi.
</P>
<P>
   Cummins, who was back in the lineup Thursday when the Coyotes
met the St. Louis Blues, cursed his misfortune, although he was
pretty sure he had his sweater fastened to the back of his pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty disappointed I got thrown out,'' Cummins said.
``What can you do? Things are going to happen. That's sports.
Sometimes, things are going to go your way. Sometimes they're not.
It's how you deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummins, who had declined to discuss his situation publicly in
recent days, dealt with being out of the lineup as well as could be
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough. I've never sat out this many games in a row,''
he said. He wasn't crazy about getting into a fight with Domi so
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me on the first couple shifts, `Cmon, let's go,' ''
Cummins said. ``I said, `Not right now, Tie. I want to get some ice
time first. I want to play some freakin' hockey first.' Oh,
well.'' &QL; 
Waite 'til next year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backup goalie Jimmy Waite, who made his ninth start on Thursday
in his 100th NHL game, will be a Group V unrestricted free agent
after the season and likely will draw offers from other clubs if he
continues to play as well as he has.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the possibility of him getting picked up by the
Atlanta Thrashers in the expansion draft in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens, there's a chance I could be a No. 1 goalie,''
said Waite, who was unbeaten at 6-0-2 before Thursday's 3-2 loss.
``If not, I wouldn't want to go anyplace else. If I can't be a No.
1 somewhere, I'd rather stay in Phoenix.'' &QL; 
Schoenfeld an All-Star? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes win three of their next five games, Schoenfeld
should be a lock to be one of the two head coaches at next month's
All-Star Game in Tampa Bay. The coach whose team has the best
winning percentage in each conference on the morning of Dec. 29
gets the honor. The runner-up in each conference will serve as an
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Schoenfeld should probably pack his bags and get
ready for a trip to the Sunshine State. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
