<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRAQ ATTACK (Moved in ``w'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GOALS (Undated) _ As American and British air strikes
continue, there are persistent questions, both inside the
Government and outside, over what American strategy toward Iraq
should be after the bombing stops. Despite a series of discussions
and the exchange of papers between London and Washington, there is
still no agreed, coherent strategy, officials of both countries
concede. By Steven Erlanger and Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TIMING (Washington) _ On the timing of Butler's report and
of the attack. By John M. Broder, Jeff Gerth and Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-POLL (Washington) _ Overnight poll shows support for
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GORE (Washington) _ With bombs falling on Iraq and an
impeachment vote nearing in the House, Vice President Gore has
taken an unusually visible role in defending President Clinton and
the military actions that have spurred deep skepticism from many
Republicans. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-IRAQ-REPUBS (Washington) _ The outpouring of
recriminations from Republicans questioning President Clinton's
motives in bombing Iraq threatens the party's effort to make its
vote to impeach President Clinton appear non-partisan and a sad but
simple Constitutional duty. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH (Moved in ``w'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-IRAQ-LOTT (Washington) _ Why Trent Lott, the Senate
Republican leader, broke with the code of supporting presidents
when American troops in action. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The wild day on Capitol Hill. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LAMEDUCK (Wahington) _ The lame ducks in the House, 21
Republicans and 17 Democrats, not including two Republicans and one
Democrat who won election to Senate seats. And with the House
taking up impeachment on Friday, they have streamed back into
Washington to vote one last time. Will they vote their consciences?
By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STANDARDS (Washington) _ What standards for impeachment
did the Judiciary Committee put before the House for debate.
Impeachable offense? Standard of proof? Public or private conduct?
Is all perjury the same? By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-JOHNSON (Undated) _ Swept up in rhetorical passion for
the sanctity of the Constitution and the Republic, the House of
Representatives debated for a scant 14 hours and then voted for the
first _ and then, the only time _ to impeach a president. A look at
the case of Andrew Johnson. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ The World Meteorological
Organization, in conjunction with other national organizations,
including NASA, announces that the average global surface
temperature in 1998 was the highest since they started keeping such
records in 1860, with global surface a degree and a quarter
Fahrenheit higher than at the turn of the century. Experts
attributed the record-breaking warmth to a combination of global
warming and El Nino, and said next year would probably be cooler.
By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GM (Shanghai, China) _ General Motors Corp. is making a
big bet on China, sinking $2 billion into 16 ventures here, mostly
for auto components. The Shanghai General Motors plant is the
biggest of them all and plans to build 100,000 Buick sedans a year.
The main question is: Who will buy the cars? By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-INTEGRATE (Undated) _ Citigroup, shaken by leadership
turmoil in the early days as America's largest financial services
company, has sped up the integration of its banking units in a
headlong effort to prove that commercial bankers and investment
bankers can mix. With code names like ``project leapfrog,''
investment bankers and commercial bankers from New York to
Australia are moving in with their commercial bank counterparts,
putting their product lines together and making joint calls on
major corporate clients like News Corp., Jos. A. Seagram &AMP; Sons,
and Monsanto. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
