<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSYCHICS WON'T PREDICT OUTCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - If you think the Cardinals showdown with the New
Orleans Saints is being met with raging apathy by the ticket buying
public, which had purchased just 41,126 as of 2 p.m. Thursday, it's
nothing compared with the reaction of Valley psychics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' searched Wednesday to find a Valley psychic
willing to forecast the outcome of Sunday's game and the Cardinals'
playoff chances.
</P>
<P>
   Even those claiming a 98 percent accuracy rate refused, one
saying, ``I'm not interested. I don't waste my time on trivial
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Valley of ``elitist'' psychics. Calls to several
psychics listed in the telephone book were greeted by, ``The number
you are dialing is no longer in service, or has been
disconnected.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes perfect sense. Why does a truly good psychic need a
phone, anyway? &QL; 
McKinnon improved &QL; 
Middle linebacker  &UR; Ronald McKinnon is on the cusp of providing the
Cardinals with their first good injury news in a month. McKinnon
practiced for the second consecutive day with the aid of a brace on
his sprained right knee.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook isn't so good for defensive tackle  &UR; Mark Smith and
cornerback
 &UR; Tommy Knight. Smith's sprained ankle kept him out of Thursday's
practice. Knight practiced, but Coach &UR; Vince Tobin is leery of
allowing him to play on an injured hamstring connector and adding
to the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's iffier for Smith, but McKinnon practiced a bit and looks
like he's moving all right,'' Tobin said. ``He's not 100 percent,
and we'll have to see where he is closer to game day.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon said he hopes to play. ``It feels pretty good right
now,'' he said. ``I have to get used to this brace, so I'll have to
see at the end of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon's replacement,  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Maddox, took some criticism and was pulled in the second half of
last week's victory over the Eagles. Guess what? After reviewing
his performance (10 tackles on 25 plays, including a touchdown
saving stop at the goal line), coaches apparently apologized to him
during Monday's team meeting. &QL; 
Mind games?
</P>
<P>
   Saints Coach  &UR; Mike Ditka was quoted as saying this about &UR; Jake
Plummer: ``If I didn't know better, I'd think it was the young  &UR; Joe
Montana. I mean it. He looks like Joe, and he throws like Joe. And
he moves around. He's just going to get better and better as time
goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was asked if he thinks Ditka has lost his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean has he recently lost his mind?'' Plummer asked,
smiling. ``He's a great coach, and he's been around a lot of great
players. Last year, he came up to me, hit me on the chest, and
said, `Stand in there. You're going to be a great quarterback.'
That's an honor coming from a guy who has coached so long.' '' &QL; 
Hands full &QL; 
Offensive left tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown expects a big challenge Sunday
from Saints defensive end  &UR; Joe Johnson, who has seven sacks and 49
unassisted tackles on the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough deal,'' Brown said. ``He's a Pro
Bowler who has been playing great. He was tough last year when we
played. He has the size and strength to be a defensive tackle, and
the quickness to play end. That's what makes him so tough on the
inside or on the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Tackle  &UR; La'Roi Glover, who profits from the constant double-team
attention given tackle  &UR; Wayne Martin, leads the Saints with 10
sacks. &QL; 
3rd time's a charm &QL; 
Tailback  &UR; Adrian Murrell needs 48 yards Sunday to become only the
eighth active running back to gain 1,000 yards in three consecutive
seasons or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's meaningful in that you've been somewhat
productive for a couple years,'' Murrell said. ``I guess 1,000
yards is a bench mark for running backs. Most running backs look
for more and beyond, but I'm satisfied with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1,000-yard mark has diminished somewhat with a 16-game
schedule, but it really will be only a 14-game season for me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
