<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLICKI MIGHT BE NEXT MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Less than a week ago, Los Angeles Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone signed Kevin Brown to the most lucrative
contract in baseball history _ a seven-year, $105 million
earth-shaker.
</P>
<P>
   But while baseball executives and players are trying to figure
out what it will mean to the game's financial structure in years to
come, Malone is moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have six legitimate starting pitchers _ Brown, Chan
Ho Park, Carlos Perez, Darren Dreifort, Ismael Valdes and Dave
Mlicki. They have a formidable lineup with Eric Young, Devon White,
Gary Sheffield, Eric Karros, Todd Hundley and Raul Mondesi. But
they do need help in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing now is fine-tuning,'' Malone said from his
Dodger Stadium office Thursday afternoon. ``We're trying to upgrade
the bench and the bullpen. It's what we've really been working on
all along.''
</P>
<P>
   With a surplus of starters, the Dodgers can use one _ probably
Mlicki _ in a trade to fill a need. There have been reports that a
trade with the Giants is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams have expressed interest in Mlicki,'' Malone said. ``I
can't be specific about the Giants.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed relief is a priority, and among the free agents
available are Mike Munoz and Norm Charlton.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the bench is concerned, the Dodgers are close to
coming to terms with infielder Dave Hansen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 0040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
