<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR     12-18 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SUCCUMB TO FATIGUE  
 DEMITRA'S GOAL ENDS BLUES' 6-GAME SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ They had no Keith Tkachuk, who is still nursing a
sore groin. They had no Shane Doan, who flew back to Phoenix to be
with his wife, who's nursing a baby boy born earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   But more than that, the Coyotes simply had no gas left in the
tank.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way Coach Jim Schoenfeld saw it after his team ended
a four-game trip with a 3-2 loss Thursday night to the St. Louis
Blues at the Kiel Center. It came on the heels of a win in Ottawa,
a tie in Montreal, and a 5-2 blowout loss Wednesday at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, I was thrilled with the effort because you
had to be on the bench to know how hard everybody tried,'' said
Schoenfeld, whose red-hot club finally cooled down, losing two in a
row for the first time all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just no fuel in the tank. We're a tired group right
now. It'll be good to get home and get a couple of days to regroup.
We didn't have a good performance in Toronto, and maybe that was
where fatigue was starting to set in. I'm not trying to make
excuses for our guys, but you get to know your players well enough,
and you get to know when they're giving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavol Demitra won it for the Blues, scoring the only goal in the
third period when he beat Jimmy Waite from the slot with 3:21
minutes to play. Rookie Lubos Bartecko, playing in his third NHL
game, was in and out of the crease during the play, but a review
upstairs showed the goal was legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Demitra, whose 15 goals lead the Blues, has had four similar
goals called back this season due to crease violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I got so happy. I got so nervous,'' Demitra said. ``They
never give me goals like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld wasn't sure it should count until he watched
videotape of the goal in his office after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bartecko) just got his skate out and went back in for the
rebound, which is a legal goal,'' Schoenfeld said. ``It was pretty
close. But that's why you have the video goal judge, and they made
the right call.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (17-5-4) got goals from Teppo Numminen, his sixth,
and Rick Tocchet, whose 10th gave Phoenix a 2-1 lead at the 5:37
mark of the second period, but they never really put a ton of
pressure on Blues goalie Grant Fuhr. The veteran faced just 22
shots, only six in the final period, when Phoenix truly seemed to
have lost its legs.
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing. Fatigue, after playing eight of their past
nine games on the road, is understandable. Losing your legs is one
thing. Center Jeremy Roenick, though, nearly lost his head at the
neck.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes star was the victim of what he freely referred to
later as a vicious cheap shot from Blues defenseman Chris Pronger.
Thirty-four seconds into the second period, the 6-foot-6 Pronger
wielded a two-handed slash that slammed across the side of
Roenick's head, just below the helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievably, Roenick wasn't injured. Pronger, though, got
kicked out with a match penalty for intent to injure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dumb play. It was a bonehead move, period,'' said
Roenick, the Coyotes' leading scorer with 31 points. ``That's
endangering somebody's health. . . . That's bush league, if you ask
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger left the Kiel Center without speaking to reporters.
Roenick, for one, expects the Blues player to get a stiff
suspension from Colin Campbell, the NHL's senior vice president in
charge of hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' he said. ``You've seen some of the incidents this
year. Rob Blake (of the Los Angeles Kings) got suspended for three
games (for a slash), but what (Pronger) did tonight was worse.''
</P>
<P>
   What was almost as bad was the Coyotes' feeble attempt on the
ensuing five-minute power play. Phoenix, which will meet the New
York Islanders on Sunday at America West Arena, could muster only
two shots during the golden opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way the power play has gone all season for the
Coyotes. They were 0 for 5 with the man advantage Thursday,
including a two-man advantage for 57 seconds in the first when they
failed to register a single shot on Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ends a six-game winless streak (0-4-2) for the
Blues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
