<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6240 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CLEMENS-HNS &LR;      12-18 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Speculation surrounding some provisions of Roger Clemens' contract
with the Toronto Blue Jays is expected to lead to an investigation
by Major League Baseball, sources said Thursday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At issue are the contents of a side agreement among Clemens, his
agents and former Toronto president Paul Beeston made when Clemens
signed with the Blue Jays in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In question are undocumented contractual rights _ a no-trade
clause, a must-trade clause and a clause that would grant Clemens
free agency if a trade is not completed within 90 days of his Dec.
2 trade demand.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, an official for Major League Baseball said no such
trade agreements are in the five-time Cy Young Award winner's
contract. Clemens has two years remaining on a four-year deal worth
$31.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Clemens does not have anything along those lines
attached to his contract,'' said Brian Small, the American League
director of waivers and records.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball prohibits side agreements that do not
accompany the contract when it is filed with the American League or
National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Side letters are technically not allowed,'' said Small, saying
a club could be fined if found in violation of baseball rules.
</P>
<P>
   If an investigation by MLB determines the presence of an unfiled
addendum to Clemens' contract, MLB could declare the agreement null
and void.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do side agreements, it's kind of impossible for them to
be enforced,'' Small said. ``When you shake hands, wink, pat on the
back, those are the type things that happen in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an existing (side) agreement (involving Clemens),
I couldn't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto general manager Gord Ash, who reopened trade talks with
the Astros on Wednesday, strongly denies any extra language exists
in Clemens' contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a misinformation campaign going on to lower his
(Clemens') trade value,'' Ash said before leaving the winter
meetings in Nashville on Tuesday. ``I know how this happens. There
are too many scouts and too many media standing around with not
enough going on. The kind of dollars mentioned that he is looking
for has been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there is the self-righteous talk from some clubs that `We
don't talk to agents' and how some agents are running the game. The
reality is that agents play a large part in this. Anyone who says
they don't does not understand the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Hendricks, one of Clemens' agents, called Astros owner
Drayton McLane Jr. on Saturday and suggested that if the Astros
were interested in Clemens, they could extend his contract for one
year at $27.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   That would amount to Clemens getting a $43.5 million, three-year
deal. Such a contract would make Clemens baseball's
second-highest-paid player ($14.5 million average), trailing only
the $105 million, seven-year contract signed last weekend by
pitcher Kevin Brown and the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, Yankees, Indians and Rangers continue to be the most
interested in acquiring Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker reopened
negotiations with the Blue Jays _ his first contact with Toronto
since the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed players, but I can't say we made progress,''
Hunsicker said. ``I can only say Toronto has a good understanding
about players we're willing to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said Clemens was given the contractual right by
Beeston, now president of Major League Baseball, to make the trade
request after any season when he signed two years ago. As for the
rumors, he responded by saying it would be difficult to explain
``every nuance'' of Clemens' complex contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``People start to ask, `What about this, what about that?'''
Hendricks said. ``I'm not going to confirm or deny one thing,
because it doesn't get us anywhere; it doesn't serve any purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this, an Easter egg hunt for a hidden clause?''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said the goal continues to be to restructure Clemens'
contract while at the same time providing the Blue Jays with
acceptable compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start asking about paragraph two, paragraph 10 (in
the contract), that seems to be missing the point,'' Hendricks
said. ``When all is said and done, Roger will be traded to
somebody,'' Hendricks said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens won Cy Young Awards with the Boston Red Sox in 1986,
1987 and 1991 and in his only two seasons with the Blue Jays in
1997 and 1998. He also was the American League Most Valuable Player
in 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
