<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6254 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CYNICS-AZR &LR;      12-18 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CYNICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYNICISM THRIVING IN WAKE OF CLINTON-DIRECTED BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN VAN DER WERF  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Lyndon B. Johnson's Vietnam policy was so unpopular
that he limited his public appearances to military bases and other
``safe'' venues. President Truman was a pariah for getting troops
involved in Korea, and he was lambasted as a failed haberdasher.
</P>
<P>
   Once, there was a bona fide crook in the White House, Richard
Nixon, whose errors were legion. But no one had the temerity to
suggest that he could, or would, manipulate the military to save
his political hide.
</P>
<P>
   That took President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   What was once a healthy skepticism about the president has
become for a growing number of people an overwhelming cynicism, a
belief that Clinton never does anything out of principle but only
out of self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the day after Clinton ordered the bombing of
Baghdad, the most popular debate in town was questioning his
motivation, his timing, his resolve. But then raising fundamental
questions about Clinton and his character has become the hallmark
of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Even among veterans groups, who arguably might be the most
supportive of American troops at war, there were lingering
questions and suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could have been orchestrated to create a diversion
from the fact that there was about to be an almost certain vote of
impeachment,'' said Paul Gaulocher, 53, of Scottsdale, who was an
Army infantryman in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He rejected the argument that such an action would require the
complicity of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the British government and
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you would have to do is to coordinate the time that report
is released,'' Gaulocher said, referring to chief U.N. weapons
inspector Richard Butler's criticism of Iraqi cooperation. ``And
that wouldn't be that hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler gave a strong defense of his report Thursday, denying
that it was timed to trump the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Melvin, 28, a Glendale locksmith who was a Marine sniper
during the Gulf War, said he, too, was suspicious about the timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have waited,'' Melvin said. ``It's been going on for
a long time, and they could have taken action long before now.''
</P>
<P>
   In most military actions, it is expected that criticism will
cease as Congress and the people join the commander in chief in
supporting the troops.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there were deep suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Had Clinton orchestrated this to stave off the House impeachment
vote and perhaps give himself the time to reverse the momentum?
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty for Clinton is, even when he does the right
thing, he opens himself up to questioning,'' said James W. Davis, a
professor of political science at Washington University in St.
Louis. ``President Clinton, by his own actions, has either
incredibly damaged or destroyed his credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., was quick to back
away Thursday from his comments Wednesday, when he said he did not
back the bombing because the timing of it was so suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be emphatic that I am in support of the troops,''
Lott said Thursday. ``I believe that there is no relationship''
between the bombing and the timing of the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott's cynicism was catching.
</P>
<P>
   At the Carl T. Hayden Veterans Affairs Medical Center in
Phoenix, just about every television was tuned to coverage of the
bombing campaign, and the air was filled with suspicion about
whether it was really necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton pulled this off to save his ass,'' said George L.
Smith, 82, of Queen Creek, a retired postal worker and World War II
Marine.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and most other veterans did not question the wisdom of the
action. If anything, the veterans wished it had happened long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to do this. We should have finished him (Iraqi
leader Saddam Hussein) off in Desert Storm,'' said Joe Makowski,
51, of Tempe, who was also in the Army infantry in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Holding back on Saddam was President Bush's decision.
Supposedly, Clinton's aim is to knock him from power this time. But
because it is Clinton, even an aim that most people agree with
raises what else? More questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there who think he (Clinton) is the first
cousin to the Antichrist. If he were to walk up to them and hand
them a $1,000 bill, they would wonder what part of the last
left-wing conspiracy he just passed on to them,'' said Mike
Breslin, a political campaign consultant in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules of the day have really changed from 20 or 30 years
ago. People are a little more fast, a little more rigid in their
opinion. The level of reasonable discourse in politics has really
gone down because we live in an age when there is so much
competition to get a message out. If you are going to be heard, it
pays to be hard-edged and sharp and polarizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton isn't helped any by his personal foibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a (expletive) draft dodger who can't keep his pants on,''
said Thomas R. Barnes, 47, a Vietnam veteran from Phoenix, who
otherwise believes Clinton is ``doing right by the country.''
</P>
<P>
   People criticized the failed military plot to rescue U.S.
hostages in Iran hatched by President Carter, but they couldn't
criticize him personally. He is a former Navy commander. Bush was
also seen as a weak leader, but his military record is impeccable
and heroic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has no heroic military background to recall in times of
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a lawyer to a fault, too slick by half,'' said
Davis, the professor. ``He has always been able to use words and
persuasion to talk his way out of jams, and that's all he has.
Slick is not a compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Strauss has been one of Clinton's biggest public supporters
locally, but now he has given up. He found he didn't know what
Clinton stood for anymore, other than self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The host of a talk show on KXAM-AM (1310), Strauss was a rare
voice among the conservative-dominated radio community in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss doesn't believe Clinton orchestrated the bombing raid to
save his hide, but he bailed out over Clinton's statements
regarding his relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have a problem with being lied to to my face,'' Strauss
said. ``I feel betrayed. I was on radio for hour after hour
defending his character. I was telling people they were crazy for
not giving him more credit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Strauss cannot forget Clinton wagging his finger at the
cameras in January denying that he had ``sexual relations with that
woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what? People believe less today than they did
yesterday,'' Strauss said. ``I believe less today than I did
yesterday. I'm sorry to say it, but it's true. It makes a horrible
statement about where we've come and where we're going.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
