<HEADLINE>
TOUTING CURRY'S TALENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walking on campus on her way to the library one afternoon
recently, Edniesha Curry encountered a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   The man walked a few steps with her before asking out of the
blue, ``So when's your next game?''
</P>
<P>
   Taken aback, Curry stopped and looked at him suspiciously. She
answered.
</P>
<P>
   The man asked, ``Aren't you Edniesha Curry?''
</P>
<P>
   Curry acknowledged herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Good luck and keep up the big numbers,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult for an athlete to become a known quantity on a
commuter campus like Cal State Northridge. But the sophomore from
Palmdale High School has accomplished it because the women's team
is winning (it's 4-3 heading into Saturday's game at Cal Poly) and
she is averaging 24.9 points a game. That's tops in the Big Sky
Conference and fifth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Her 40 points against Loyola Marymount is the third- highest
total by a Division I player this season. Her three and a half
3-point field goals a game leads the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just being an on-campus celebrity isn't enough. It's time
to take her show public. For the first time, and at the suggestion
of former coach Michael Abraham, there is an All-America campaign
being waged at Northridge on behalf of a women's basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   Some might wonder why, considering Curry was named All-America
by the Women's Basketball Journal last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to promote her as much as possible,'' said sports
information contact Bruce Christensen.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Northridge is doing what many Division I schools do
_ send out information packets to those voting for All-America
teams. The most prestigious of these is the award sponsored by
Kodak. So, every other week, Christensen sends out a Curry summary
sheet to the eight coaches and one chairperson who will select the
Kodak team.
</P>
<P>
   Included are Curry's national ranking, her All-America honor
last year as a freshman, her Big Sky Conference numbers, her school
records and what other coaches are saying.
</P>
<P>
   Quoted are Utah Starzz assistant and former USC head coach Fred
Williams, Northern Arizona coach Meg Sanders and Iowa coach Angie
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, Lee might carry the most weight. She is one of the
eight Kodak-selecting coaches and saw first-hand what Curry could
do last year, when Curry scored 28 points in the Matadors' 67-56
loss to the No. 20-ranked Hawkeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is just a great player,'' Lee said. ``She can shoot from
the outside, from the inside and drive to the basket. She is a
tremendous athlete who knows how to get the ball into the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Christensen said Curry is happy with the campaign, but Curry
added that it is worth less if the team doesn't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual accolades mean nothing if we're not winning,
and not until I make the big ones _ win the Big Sky and go to the
NCAA Tournament,'' she said. ``Until then, it will be like last
year: `I got All-America? Oh, thanks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   __ UCLA update: The UCLA women are in the midst of a six-game
win streak heading into Saturday's game at Texas. The No. 8-ranked
Bruins (6-2) have to be careful not to look past the 3-3 Longhorns
to Monday's matchup at at No. 2 Tennessee, the game in which UCLA
coach Kathy Olivier said, ``We'll see where we are as a basketball
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Where are they now?
</P>
<P>
   Strong in the post but weak on the perimeter and susceptible to
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Maylana Martin (18.5 ppg, 11.6 rpg) and Janae Hubbard (14.8 ppg,
8.6 rpg) have been solid inside, but the outside shooting hasn't
been at the same level. No guard averages more points per game than
backup LaCresha Flanagan's 9.4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to get in foul trouble,'' Olivier said. ``We need to
take better care of the ball. If we can come out of Texas with a W,
we'll give Tennessee a real run.''
</P>
<P>
   __ What it takes: The Bruins are the only Pac-10 team ranked
nationally. That's all well and good, and it surely brings some
excitement to the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Pat Summitt has noticed, saying the strong guard
play of Erica Gomez and the inside jobs Martin and Hubbard are
doing what is needed to begin to build a successful program.
</P>
<P>
   But, Summitt stressed, it's only a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it takes to be considered among the elite is to get into
the final eight and the Final Four,'' Summitt said. ``Once you
become part of March Madness, people recognize you as a national
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, a team has to do it year in and year out. Summitt
has led the Lady Vols to the last three national championships.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won the Association of Intercollegiate Athletics for Women
title in 1978. Last year, the Bruins just missed making the final
16 on a controversial call that cost them a second-round win over
Alabama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
