<SLUG> BC-BKW-PEPPWOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER FIGHT TO THE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Welcome to Pepperdine women's basketball, where
no lead is safe.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Waves are 7-2 after beating Florida State 75-72
Thursday at Firestone Fieldhouse. But it has been a struggle every
game.
</P>
<P>
   This time, against an aggressive and quick Florida State squad,
the outcome wasn't decided until there were 1.7 seconds left. With
Pepperdine leading 74-72, freshman forward Nadja Morgan missed two
free throws _ but grabbed the rebound and was fouled again. She
made one free throw to seal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't quit,'' Pepperdine coach Mark Trakh said. ``They
played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine has struggled because it has several transfer and
young players learning how to play together. Plus, the Waves lost
their point guard earlier this season with a knee injury. That has
left Trakh no choice but to move shooting guard Rasheeda Clark to
the point.
</P>
<P>
   Clark responded with 23 points, but she wasn't the only hero.
There was Dee Braxton muscling inside and getting nine of her 11
points in the second half. There was Kate Crane helping Clark at
the point and getting nine points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braxton, Clark, Crane, tonight, you saw them play,'' Trakh
said. ``They played hard. They played together.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that way in the first half. Florida State (3-5)
makes up for a lack of height with plenty of quickness and an
ability to get inside. The Seminoles played North Carolina to
overtime before losing and also made a decent showing against
Louisiana Tech, also a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Trakh knew all about the Seminoles' quickness and lousy outside
shooting (17 percent from 3-point land). So the Waves played a zone
and dared the Seminoles to shoot outside.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State didn't want to, instead opting to try and get the
ball inside. But Pepperdine read it and turned 10 first-half
Florida State turnovers (six by intercepting passes) into a 28-9
run. An 11-4 deficit became a 32-20 lead and the Waves led 36-27 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   In that span, Pepperdine also scored 10 straight points and held
the Seminoles scoreless for more than four mintues.
</P>
<P>
   Clark scored 12 points in the first half, and the defense held
Florida State's Latavia Coleman (she averages 20 a game) to eight.
Florida State shot 32 percent from the field, well below its
45-percent average.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half, Florida State's aggressiveness came out.
The Seminoles started intercepting Pepperdine pases inside and ran
off 10 of the half's first 12 points, then built the run to 19-7
and 23-9. With 12:39 to play, Florida State led 50-45. Coleman was
a key, scoring nine points in a span of 2:21. She finished with 21.
</P>
<P>
   Just as always, however, Pepperdine didn't give up. A 14-6 run
cut gave the Waves a 61-60 lead with 5:19 remaining. It was close
the rest of the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 0117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
