<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SENATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS OUTGUN SENATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Someday, when he retires and is ushered into the Hockey
Hall of Fame, Ray Bourque will look back proudly on the milestones
he reached during his two decades in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, the ever-youthful Bourque intends to keep
plugging along and will stop and smell the roses later.
</P>
<P>
   There were a couple of more Thursday night as he helped the
Bruins beat the Ottawa Senators, 5-2, at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, who became the 10th player in league history to play
1,400 games, set up a pair of power-play goals and tied Gordie Howe
for third on the NHL's all-time assist list with 1,049.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he plays,'' said coach Pat Burns, ``he has earned
everything he has. The loyalty of Ray Bourque to the team is
probably the best example across the board of any professional
sport. He capped that milestone. He never talked about it. He never
really came out and stated nothing. He goes out and plays the game.
He doesn't stop at those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, the Bruins' all-time leading scorer, played 21 shifts
totaling 24 minutes 26 seconds, and both his shots led to goals.
</P>
<P>
   Boston went into the game nip-and-tuck in the Northeast Division
standings with Ottawa. The Bruins ended their losing streak at two
games and are now 3 points ahead of the Senators.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins jumped into the lead just 23 seconds into the game
when P.J. Axelsson picked off former Bruin Shawn McEachern and beat
goalie Damian Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators tied it at 5:48, the result of a nifty move off the
rush by left wing Andreas Johansson, who signed with the club as a
free agent in late September. Johansson took a pass from Daniel
Alfredsson and charged down the slot. He deked defenseman Darren
Van Impe, lifting his stick in the process, and proceeded right to
the net, switching from his forehand to his backhand and sailing a
shot past Byron Dafoe inside the right post. It was the 11th goal
of the season for Johansson, who was with the Penguins last year.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, the Bruins took the lead for good
on a goal by sophomore center Joe Thornton. Bourque fired a slap
shot from the right point that Thornton redirected past Rhodes for
the 2-1 edge at 7:45. It was Thornton's third tally of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Bruins boosted their lead to 3-1,
thanks to Sergei Samsonov's seemingly infinite patience.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov, positioned along the left wing boards, worked a
give-and-go with Jason Allison. He dished the puck to Allison, who
gave it right back to him from the left circle. Samsonov then cut
from left to right, skating across the top of the crease and down
below the right circle. He had Ottawa's defense mesmerized, and
when he got all the way across, he flipped the puck into the far
side of the net at 6:18 for his 10th goal.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Bruins went to sleep. It was as if the ice had
tilted toward Boston's defensive zone. The Bruins had four shots in
the second, none after Samsonov's goal, which was the only shot by
a forward. It was all Ottawa as the Senators poured 12 shots on
Dafoe, although midway through the period, there was a four-minute
span when neither goalie faced a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins emerged from their slumber for the final period,
picking up the pace. McEachern pulled the Senators within one, 3-2,
at 13:33, but only 15 seconds later, Rob DiMaio came through with
his first goal of the season. The Bruins closed out the scoring at
17:38 when Dmitri Khristich beat Rhodes on a backhander, burying a
rebound of a Bourque shot from the right point. That assist tied
Howe's mark.
</P>
<P>
   At the 19-minute mark, DiMaio completed his Gordie Howe hat
trick (a goal, an assist, and a fight) when he battled Bill Berg.
He was ejected because the officials said his sweater wasn't tied
down. However, DiMaio said it was.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. For the team, it was a victory. More significantly,
it was Bourque's night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hockey,'' said Bourque, referring to Howe. ``It's pretty
special, I think. Not too many people get to enjoy something like
this. When it all started, you never think of these things. You
want to go out and establish yourself as a solid NHL player. So
many things have gone on through these years that you enjoy, but
maybe not as much as I will once it's all said and done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
