<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6316 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-SUNSHINE:MA     12-18 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-SUNSHINE:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS IN THE SUNSHINE STATE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By BILL MAXWELL 
 &HT;    (Bill Maxwell, African American, is an editorial writer and
columnist for the St. Petersburg Times in St. Petersburg, Fla. He
can be reached on the Internet at maxwell(at) sptimes.com) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In Florida, the Sunshine State, Christmas is an enduring
anomaly. The best Christmas is a day of belonging, of familiarity
and of old kinship, all of which make Florida an alien place for
the real thing.
 &HT;    Conventional wisdom tells us that nearly everyone here is from
``somewhere else.'' Reality or not, this impression has come to
define us, and even natives sometimes forget that they are the
natural children of the sun.
 &HT;    What I am leading to is this: Given time and place, Christmas in
Florida is a state of mind, causing many transplants to suffer
Yuletide angst in paradise. Indeed, the state itself is the source
of untold fantasies that routinely come tumbling down like
raindrops during a summer afternoon thunderstorm.
 &HT;    Florida is a peninsula, not quite an island, not quite
landlocked either. And so Christmas here is like the state itself,
an unfinished sculpture or painting _ a thing in search of meaning.
 &HT;    Like Florida, Christmas down here is a tropical bazaar.
 &HT;    As a native of Fort Lauderdale, I was condemned to perpetual
heat, humidity and year-round greenery until I moved away for short
periods. Even as a child, I knew that Christmas in Florida was a
substitution, a contradiction, an over-compensation.
 &HT;    We hung too many lights when I was a child. We still hang far
too many.
 &HT;    I knew what Christmas should resemble from magazines, books and
movies. I knew that it was a time for Jack Frost, hot chocolate,
snow and snowmen, horse-drawn sleighs and bells, kids sledding down
steep inclines, carolers braving bone-chilling cold.
 &HT;    Today, few things have changed in the Sunshine State. Like most
other South Floridians, I sweat on Dec. 25. We can be seen fishing,
golfing, tanning, water-skiing, swimming. And believe it or not,
many of us drink lemonade beneath sprawling banyans on Christmas
day. Some of us even mow the lawn, side-stepping plastic pink
flamingos all the while.
 &HT;    Nothing, however, captures the spirit of Christmas in South
Florida like our annual boat parades. Instead of sleigh rides,
Floridians deploy thousands of decorated water craft along our
natural rivers and channels gouged out of the ground by the Army
Corps of Engineers.
 &HT;    Whenever I am in Fort Lauderdale or Miami or St. Petersburg for
Christmas, I never miss the boat parade, a bona fide Florida
spectacle that attracts crowds as energetic as those at New York's
Time Square celebration on New Year's Eve. Most of the boats are
man-made wonders unto themselves. They are decorated with countless
blinking lights in complex designs and topped-off with live
Christmas trees fastened to their guide towers. Seasonal music
pumps from huge speakers.
 &HT;    The obscene, aerodynamic cigarette boats and their cargo are my
favorite. Invariably, handsome young men, their deep tans the
picture of health and wealth, guide these glossy, rumbling machines
over the lightly chopping water. The wake must be kept down, you
know, so as not to disturb the seawalls protecting million-dollar
homes along the route.
 &HT;    Hanging onto the men are beautiful, bikini-clad women, showing
off perfect teeth as they smile and flawless flesh as they wave to
the admiring crowds. Male parade-goers, many of them sloshed from
too much booze and the up-and-down motion of the scene, especially
love the flirtatious female boaters wearing those little
red-and-white Santa caps and tight tank tops.
 &HT;    As the evening grows darker, the colorful flotilla dips and
twists like a long water creature coming apart. This is Christmas
in sun-drenched South Florida.
 &HT;    So, too, are the mega-celebrations in and around Disney World,
in the shadow of the now-familiar Earffel Tower, the municipal
water tower decked out with Mickey Mouse ears. At the Magic
Kingdom, Epcot, Universal Studios, Sea World and other sites,
carolers and spectators holding candles throng the narrow walkways
and plazas. Parades, complete with elaborate floats and human and
animated celebrities, pass by with eye-popping regularity.
 &HT;    Here, commercial giants compete for who can do the grandest
public display of Christmas.
 &HT;    Some years ago, when I visited Mousedom during the Yuletide
season, Sea World boasted that its 400-foot metal sky tower was
Central Florida's biggest Christmas tree. Not to be outdone, the
folks over at Universal Studios hauled in tons of fake snow that
looked very real on the park's life-like New York Street set.
 &HT;    Disney-MGM Studios, never runners up on earth or in heaven,
sported a 70-foot tree with 2-million lights. This monstrosity,
called The Wall of Angels, blocks off a portion of the horizon.
And, still in the Yuletide spirit, Disney-MGM flew in Buzz
Lightyear, Woody, Bo Peep and other characters from the hit movie
Toy Story of that year.
 &HT;    This Christmas, I am not going near the Disney World area, so I
will not be able to count the lights or measure the height of the
metal trees or fight the gridlock that comes with this mass of
humanity. I will miss South Florida's boat parades, too.
 &HT;    I have come north, to Virginia, where the weather is cooler,
where the leaves have changed color or have fallen to the ground,
where most lawns are no longer green, where smoke rises from real
fireplaces, where people are actually wearing sweaters, coats and
headgear, where a hot drink in the middle of the day is not a
strange act, where snow may be on the ground.
 &HT;    Here _ where the weather is cold and life slows down at least
temporarily _ Christmas is not a mere state of mind. It is as real
as the spirit of the season.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Bill Maxwell 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
