A6321 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANUKKAH-CHRISTMAS:MA     12-18 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANUKKAH-CHRISTMAS:MARX-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLIDAY TREE FOR MY JEWISH HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By LINDA MARX 
 &HT;    (Linda Marx is a Florida-based columnist and talk-radio
commentator.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Why is our house different from all others on the block? Instead
of a traditional Jewish Menorah or Christian Christmas tree, we
have combined the two to create a universal religious display _ and
celebration.
 &HT;    Although this is only my second holiday tree, I have learned
after 14 years, that intermarriage does not have to be a struggle.
With proper respect and communication, it is more a campaign of
compromise.
 &HT;    Until last year, I was both stubborn and skeptical. While I
refused to consider a tree of any kind, I visited friends in
all-Jewish households who were proud to flaunt their glittering
pink and silver or blue and gold ``Hanukkah bushes.''
 &HT;    While I grew up in a reformed Jewish home, we celebrated
Hanukkah. Not Christmas. Decorations were limited to a modern
Menorah, dreidels, Jewish picture books, jewelry, and the
occasional blue and gold banner proclaiming the holiday.
 &HT;    We indulged all eight nights of Hanukkah complete with presents
and frosted cookies, candied fruits, colored bagels, flavored
popcorn, painted walnuts and dark chocolate fudge.
 &HT;    Despite the fact that we lived in a small Indiana town where
there were more schoolhouses than Jews, Christmas decorations or
gift-giving like the gentile children enjoyed, were way off-limits.
 &HT;    Unlike my classmates' homes, our wood burning stove was not
bedecked with a Christmas wreath. My mother, who grew up in Chicago
and Shreveport with only Jews as friends and family, was determined
to raise us in a Jewish home. We would celebrate all the Jewish
holidays, and not any of the Christian ones.
 &HT;    Obviously, my mother would not understand my flirtation with the
holiday tree. After her death in 1990, I continued her tradition
until last year when the two holidays fell on the same dates.
 &HT;    After living in New York and now south Florida, I am constantly
amazed at the number of Jewish homes which have made holiday trees
a part of their December decor. That, together with a little urging
from my husband, convinced me to finally relent. I agreed to a
holiday compromise.
 &HT;    I even invited my father over to inaugurate the blue, gold,
silver and white tree. He snickered, but made no disparaging
comments. I know my husband relished this neo-holiday scene as he
recalled past holidays from his boyhood homes.
 &HT;    We plugged in the lights of the tree and lit the candles of the
Menorah while singing ``'TWas The Night Before Christmas'' followed
by ``Rock of Ages.''
 &HT;    With Hanukkah beginning early this year, we have even more
opportunity to fully celebrate both holidays by enjoying and
exploiting our differences.
 &HT;    But American rabbis and other religious leaders are still
struggling with ever more frequent Jewish intermarriage. According
to recent surveys, intermarriage has increased from about 10
percent in 1965 to between 38 and 52 percent today.
 &HT;    The World Jewish Congress (WJC) has projected that the Jewish
population outside of Israel, which has about 8 million people,
will decline to about 4 million in the next 30 years.
 &HT;    In this country, the WJC reports that about half of all Jews
marry non-Jews. And the children of a large majority of those
intermarried couples do not remain Jewish.
 &HT;    Why is that? Conventional wisdom finds it easier to be
Christian. There is more publicity for Christmas celebrations.
Television programming for Christmas is much more frequent than
that for Hanukkah. And many divorced families celebrate Christmas
over Hanukkah because they are busy shuttling kids from one home to
another in different cities around the nation.
 &HT;    With all of these diversions, it is even more important for the
Jewish half of the intermarriage to make sure Jewish traditions
don't die out.
 &HT;    This year we have bought a Concolor Fir, a beautiful and full
branched tree grown in Michigan that glints with a blue-white
sheen. Decorations are seasonal and creative instead of religious.
 &HT;    We are trimming the tree with red, white and blue wooden sailor
children, pink ice scenes, tiny snowmen, sterling silver sleds,
gazebo candles, Finnish snowflakes, mini ice skates, twinkling
trinkets, gold and silver balls, bows, ribbons and ties, blue and
gold wreaths, porcelain dolls, and small silver satin slippers from
Miami City Ballet's Nutcracker.
 &HT;    We have a brick fireplace with a mantle for both the red and
green and blue and gold stockings. Our Jack Russell terrier has a
`mixed breed' stocking which celebrates the colors of both
holidays.
 &HT;    My husband bought me a new Menorah this year which depicts the
synagogues of Europe in loving memory of lost communities. Flanking
the long Menorah are wreaths adorned with berries, cones, colored
velvet bows, tiny wrapped packages and silver-blue frosted leaves.
 &HT;    I can't help but believe that my mother would understand that
days pass, years go by, and things change. We must live in the
present while remembering the past. It is the only way to ensure
our future.
 &HT;    I hope she would approve.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Linda Marx 
