<HEADER>
A6322 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-TOY:CHAPMAN     12-18 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-TOY:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOY'S GIFT FROM `SANTA'
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By KIRSTEN CHAPMAN 
 &HT;    (Kirsten Chapman writes a weekly column for the Columbus
Dispatch in Columbus, Ohio, and is the author of three books,
including recently published ``The Way Home,'' already in its
second printing, and on the internet at www.chapmanthewayhome.com) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Christmas couldn't always be left up to parents _ or even Santa
Claus. Sometimes an 8-year-old had to take matters into his own
hands, especially when what he wanted most was a Dick Tracy toy.
 &HT;    My brother, Chris, kept a No. 1 rule in mind: Begin to wear down
the opposition in early December.
 &HT;    ``A gun that shoots plastic bullets? Why, that's no plaything,''
my father announced at breakfast. ``It could put an eye out.''
 &HT;    The toy didn't become safer as the month gained momentum _ only
more familiar. Thanks to my brother, it showed up more often in
family conversation than the names of relatives. Did the rest of us
know, for instance, that it came with a shoulder holster? Did we
know that it came with a Dick Tracy wallet and badge?
 &HT;    Rule No. 2: To increase the chances of receiving your heart's
desire, add more items to your ``wish'' list.
 &HT;    By constantly updating and padding his gift suggestions, Chris
hoped that our overwhelmed parents would remember one item _ the
one that mattered _ when they stood, confused, in the toy store.
 &HT;    Rule No. 3? My brother was about to teach us.
 &HT;    In his day, instead of having to be driven to a far-away mall,
all Chris had to do was walk several blocks down to the toy store.
Parting with his hard-earned money was difficult. Even more so was
getting the Dick Tracy toy and all its glorious trappings through
the back door without their being detected.
 &HT;    Luck was on his side: Chris entered unnoticed and crept down to
the basement.
 &HT;    Next, as luck further had it, a family rule came to his rescue.
Each December, to protect anyone who might be wrapping presents in
the recreation room, anyone approaching had to ask at the top of
the basement steps, ``Is it OK to come down?''
 &HT;    ``No,'' came a squeaky response to my inquiry that day. ``I'm
wrapping a present.''
 &HT;    My brother spoke the truth.
 &HT;    ``The package took a long time to wrap,'' Chris recently
recalled, four decades later, ``because I had to make it look as if
an adult had done it. I tried making my handwriting look old, too,
when I signed the card, ``To Chris/From Santa.''
 &HT;    Who knows when he slipped his prized possession under the
Christmas tree, beneath the other presents? It remained hidden,
though, until something occurred that he hadn't anticipated.
 &HT;    Each Christmas Eve, the children were allowed to open one gift
apiece.
 &HT;    ``Look, Chris already has one from Santa,'' one said as the
others were sifting through the pile, trying to decide which to
open.
 &HT;    ``From Santa? How could that be? Santa doesn't leave presents
until later tonight,'' another said in case our brother still
believed.
 &HT;    Chris stayed cool. Better to wait until morning, he cautioned
himself, and open his present amid the confusion.
 &HT;    And so, early on Christmas Day, during a tumultuous moment of
merrymaking, his voice rose above the racket.
 &HT;    ``Wow _ thanks, Santa!'' he shouted as he strapped on the
holster.
 &HT;    My mother shot an accusatory glance at my father.
 &HT;    ``Don't look at me,'' he seemed to say, returning a similar
look.
 &HT;    ``Not me,'' her eyes darted back.
 &HT;    Both parents then studied their daughters, who shrugged their
shoulders. That left only Santa.
 &HT;    We marveled at the mystery of Christmas, all of us, that is,
except Dad whose irritation rose.
 &HT;    ``Never, ever aim that toy at someone,'' I heard him scold above
the din as my brother set us _ and the season _ in his sight.
 &HT;    That night, a tired but happy ``Santa'' clasped under his pillow
the Dick Tracy holster set, badge and wallet.
 &HT;    He had plenty of years left to learn that giving held even
greater joy than receiving.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Kirsten Chapman 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
