<P>
   ukbx
 &UR; BC-TAIWANESE-CHRISTMAS:WU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; CHRISTMAS: A BLEND OF TRADITIONS _ EAST AND WEST &QL; 
 &UR; (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANK WU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Frank Wu, Chinese American, is a columnist for Asian Week and
associate professor of law and supervising attorney at Howard
University.) &QL; 
 &UR; New America News Service &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing like a trip overseas to remind us how much we
are Americans. And to witness how Christmas has spread to other
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I, married this past summer, visited Taiwan
recently. As we traveled through the country, we saw how different
we are from our cousins, as well as how Christmas has translated
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, Taiwan has become very much like the United
States. We could not avoid the fast food restaurants with familiar
logos and menus, the 7-Eleven convenience stores on every corner in
the city, and advertisements for the movie ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Taiwan remains its own society. The sight of hundreds of
motorcycles and scooters lined up at intersections during rush
hour, the sounds of the Mandarin Chinese conversations, the smell
of tofu sold by street vendors, all contrast with even the busy
crowds of America's Chinatowns. You would not mistake Taipei, with
its three million inhabitants, for New York City or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   As we walked around, we could not help but realize how much we
were tourists. While we looked like everyone else, it didn't take
long for everyone else to recognize that we somehow didn't belong.
We didn't know the customs and could barely speak the language.
Many people eventually asked, ``where are you from?''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have a notion of ``overseas'' Chinese, a global
diaspora that remains essentially Chinese no matter where its
location. To them, I am an ``ABC,'' an ``American Born Chinese,''
or in a Chinese phrase, someone who is ``over the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Their idea that we are bound together across generations and
geography is literally foreign to the United States. In the New
World, we imagine that all of us are able to claim our own
identity, that the race does not overwhelm the individual.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, who is a third generation Japanese American, was
especially puzzling. Some people guessed, perhaps based on vague
stereotypes about facial features, that she was of Japanese
ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   As Dec. 25 draws near, the Taiwanese are preparing for
Christmas. Many thousands are converts to Christianity. For them,
the season has special meaning.
</P>
<P>
   For most Taiwanese, however, Christmas is simply another ritual
borrowed from Western civilization. They may have the day off from
work. A few will exchange token gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But Lunar New Year, which falls in February of next year, is a
much more important occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The major hotels, which have more Western business travelers
than native Taiwanese vacationers as guests, all had holiday
decorations. Where we stayed, several Santa Clauses strolled
through the lobby ringing bells; tinsel hung from the ceiling; and
a gingerbread house graced the hallway. But their celebration was
the secular version, abbreviated to ``Xmas'' on their banners; it
was as devoid of religious significance as American Christmas now
often seems.
</P>
<P>
   We also visited the east coast, where there is a spectacular
series of gorges, and which explains why the Dutch called the
colony Formosa, meaning beautiful island.
</P>
<P>
   Though a recent typhoon had damaged some of the roads, the
resort was still open. And the signs of Christmas were no less
subtle: They blared German classical carols all day long. Christmas
good cheer had carried over.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be the same as firecrackers and the red envelopes
of money for the Lunar New Year, but the trappings of Christmas
inspire people to be friendly and festive.
</P>
<P>
   The adaptation of Christmas in Taiwan shows how a new
international culture is developing. It blends parts of various
traditions, mixing and matching, weaving them together _ sometimes
with more sincerity than success.
</P>
<P>
   As for us? Returning to the United States, we are planning to
spend the weekend putting up a real tree, roasting chestnuts as our
mothers did when we were children, and writing our cards to family
and friends in front of a blazing fire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998 Frank Wu &QL; 
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
