   nt22 nt26
</P>
<P>
   ukbx
 &UR; BC-GAY-CHRISTMAS:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; GAY RUDOLPH THE RED-NOSED REINDEER &QL; 
 &UR; (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) &QL; 
 &UR; By CHUCK COLBERT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) &QL; 
 &UR; New America News Service &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone knows the story of Rudolph the Red-Nosed
Reindeer. The 1939 Christmas classic, written by Robert L. May,
tells the tale of a good, little reindeer, teased by his peers for
his unusual bright red nose and not allowed to ``play in any
reindeer games.'' Rudolph gets a chance to prove himself, however,
when Santa Claus chooses him to lead the sleigh through the fog,
one special Christmas Eve Night.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in the form of story or song, Rudolph is primarily a
children's parable. Like all good parables, it teaches us _
children and adults alike _ important lessons about life. What,
then, does a closer reading of Rudolph teach us about being gay?
</P>
<P>
   Well, like ``poor, little Rudolph'' gay people know what being
different is all about. We can relate: we've cried, too, as
children, when ``all of the other reindeer used to laugh and call''
us ``names.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us still get called ugly names. Others fare far worse,
the victims of anti-gay violence. Even as adults we still feel like
Rudolph because we are not yet permitted to participate in the
institutions of civil marriage and the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Rudolph, though, whose difference was visible, our
differing sexual orientation was primarily invisible during
childhood and early adolescence. Whereas he stood out, we had not
yet come out of the closet. Like Rudolph, though, many of us knew
we were different; and we knew that at least some of the other
reindeer sensed that difference, too.
</P>
<P>
   But being different did not dampen Rudolph's holiday spirits.
Though ridiculed, rejected, and lonesome, Rudolph ``always was
good, obeying his parents as good reindeer should!''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is for gay people, growing up, feeling different,
yet trying hard to fit in. There is an adult book on this subject,
too, called ``The Best Little Boy in the World.'' Published in
1973, it tells the real-life story of one gay man. The book is
all-about coming to terms with being gay and being good when the
rest of the world says you are not.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rudolph is luckier than some gay reindeer. His parents truly
love him. This unconditional parental love is illustrated vividly
in my storybook by one picture where Rudolph's mother kisses him on
his shiny red nose _ with a doting father at their side.
</P>
<P>
   In real life gay people are not always so lucky. Rarely is our
differing sexual orientation so readily accepted or understood by
our parents, although some good families eventually come around to
full acceptance. When the holiday season rolls around this time of
year, for many of us those lonely and painful Rudolph-like feelings
_ being shunned and cast outside the reindeer fold _ often surface
unexpectedly. In the worst cases, our families of origin have long
ago abandoned us _ simply for being gay. In other cases, the
stress, loneliness, financial worries, dead-end or lost jobs,
broken relationships, and loved ones lost to AIDS pile up, one on
top of the other, making the holiday season a matter more of
survival than of celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In Rudolph even Santa Claus becomes ``filled with gloom,''
overwhelmed at first by the various and demanding tasks of
Christmas preparation. The gray skies and darkness, however, did
not stop Santa, who worried about how to get his sleigh through the
fog and recognized the potential in Rudolph's unusual bright red
nose.
</P>
<P>
   When given the chance to prove himself, our hero Rudolph comes
out of the closet on the job the minute Santa hires him for that
special work assignment on Christmas Eve. It's all right here in
the story:
</P>
<P>
   ``So Rudolph pranced out through the door, very gay,
</P>
<P>
   And took his proud place at the head of the sleigh.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the night ... well, what would you guess?
</P>
<P>
   Old Santa's idea was a brilliant success.
</P>
<P>
   And brilliant was almost no word for the way
</P>
<P>
   That Rudolph directed the deer and the sleigh.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the fog, they flew quickly and low,
</P>
<P>
   And made such good use of the wonderful glow.''
</P>
<P>
   In the make-believe world of reindeer and rhymes, a bearded, old
white man, dressed in a funny red suit, sees the worth of the
wonderful glow, giving one good, gay reindeer a chance to use his
difference for everyone's benefit.
</P>
<P>
   It's Rudolph who makes Christmas possible ``for good little
animals, good girls and boys.'' By the end of the story, all the
other reindeer come around to respect him and prize his special
talents for the holiday task at hand. That's why the other reindeer
``shouted out with glee: Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, you'll go
down in history.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be this way in real life, too. There are lots of
Rudolph's out there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998 Chuck Colbert &QL; 
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
