<HEADER>
A6325 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-PINATA:CONT     12-18 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-PINATA:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN AMERICAN CHRISTMAS: THE PINATA RULES
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The pinata, a Mexican invention, is specially designed for
Christmas. It can be found everywhere in the Southwest, where it
preceded the Anglo-Saxon Christmas tree in the former Mexican
territories of Texas, Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, Nevada, Utah
and California.
 &HT;    And, following the path of Mexican immigrants to the Midwest,
the Southeast and even New York City, the ubiquitous Mexican pinata
has surfaced everywhere and is fast becoming part of the American
culture of birthday parties and Christmas celebrations.
 &HT;    So, what is a pinata? In Mexico, the pinata is an `olla' (a clay
pot) that is covered over with gaily painted paper mache in the
form of animals, stars, birds and cartoon characters. In the clay
pot are candies, fruit, nuts and sometimes even small toys.
 &HT;    At the party, the pinata is tied to an overhanging rope that is
controlled by someone at each end pulling it in different
directions. A child is blindfolded and given a stick with which to
swing at the forever moving and manipulated `Big Bird' or `Star of
Bethlehem.' Onlooking partygoers hoot and holler, yelling
encouragement to the child blindly flailing at the evasive swinging
pinata.
 &HT;    Children stand ready to pounce on the candy and goodies when
their blindfolded sibling, cousin or friend makes a `hit,' cracking
open the pinata. The candy and toys spill out to the delight of all
the children who dive for the goodies.
 &HT;    On America's southern border and in the United States, the
pinata and its use has been transformed as it moved north. Tijuana,
Mexico, probably the most visited tourist city in the world, is
also, probably, the pinata capitol of the world. In Tijuana,
efficiency, mass marketing and costs have changed the pinata into
an all paper mache creature that mirrors American pop culture far
more than Mexican culture of old.
 &HT;    Donald Duck, Daffy Duck, Mickey Mouse, Bernie, Big Bird, the
good ship Titanic, Navy jet-fighter planes, glittery disco-style
balls and myriad other contemporary pop icons abound on the streets
of Tijuana and in the pinata markets where thousands of pinatas
hang from ceilings. They are hand-made by Indians in their shacks,
Indians who have moved to Tijuana from the interior of Mexico for
work and a better life. A cottage industry in Tijuana, it employs
as many as 5,000 people, mostly women and children. They wholesale
for a dollar or two, retail for $4 to $10.
 &HT;    U.S. Customs reports that as many as 10,000 pinatas are declared
by individuals every day at Christmas time and bona fide importers
bring across up to 25,000 a day for commercial sale in
Mexican-oriented shops and mainstream American supermarkets.
 &HT;    We know what a pinata is, how they are used and we know that
they are used thoughout Mexico and now widely in the United States.
But, a pinata didn't just spring from a corn field.
 &HT;    It's chief role is in ``las posadas,'' Christmas celebrations of
Spanish-America that start in early December and run through the
``Dia de Los Reyes,'' Day of the Three Kings on Jan. 6, the
traditional day that children receive their toys.
 &HT;    The ``posadas'' are easy to stage. A boy plays the role of
Joseph and a girl that of Mary, the mother-to-be of the baby Jesus.
Family and neighbors follow the costumed boy and girl, the Holy
Family, as they go from house to house singing the question, ``Do
you have room in the inn?'' They are answered by other participants
from behind closed doors who sing back ``no,'' until finally Joseph
and Mary settle in a stable. Lots of songs, lots of singing.
 &HT;    In America, the posadas aren't as ubiquitous as they once were
as Mexicans become more assimilated. Energies are directed more to
the Christmas feast _ tamales (corn meal, stuffed with pork or
chicken and salsa, wrapped in corn shucks and steamed), bacalao (a
dish brought from the `Old World' Spain, made from dried codfish,
olive oil, tomatoes, onions, garlic, olives and herbs) and other
delicacies that are time consuming to make _ and to the family
gatherings on Christmas Eve and the overflowing Roman Catholic
midnight Mass.
 &HT;    Christmas Eve, rather than Christmas Day, remains the core of
the Mexican and Mexican American Christmas, when gifts are
exchanged and Christmas dinner is served. In Mexico, children
receive all their presents then, except for toys, which they
receive on Jan. 6.
 &HT;    So, how does a pinata fit into the feasts of food, Midnight
mass, presents, the German Christmas tree, the English fruit cake
and mistletoe?
 &HT;    Professor John O. West of the University of Texas, El Paso,
wrote in his ``Mexican American Folklore'' about the origin of the
pinata:
 &HT;    ``One parish priest noted that the pinata ... is just something
the Mexican people threw in for the kids ... They added the pinata
to try to get kids to come to the celebration and maybe learn
something about the true meaning of Christmas.''
 &HT;    Worked for me.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
<TEXT>
