<HEADER>
A6334 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-CHRISTMAS:GIAG     12-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-CHRISTMAS:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS: A TIME FOR FAMILIES TO GATHER NEAR
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is publisher and editor-in-chief of
Indian Country Today. His Indian name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Do Indians celebrate Christmas? Most of us Indians have been
asked that question at some point in our lifetime.
 &HT;    Let me respond from my perspective.
 &HT;    The celebration of Christmas was one Christian holiday that fit
very comfortably into the lifestyles of the Indian people.
 &HT;    We seldom visited friends or relatives without taking gifts.
When tribal leaders met for a conference, or a pow wow as the white
man calls it, they always began with an exchange of gifts.
 &HT;    When a young Indian seriously courted a young lady and wanted to
ask her to be his mate and companion, he gave gifts to her parents.
 &HT;    I recall attending a meeting many years ago when Ada Deer, who
would later become assistant secretary of Indian Affairs in the
Clinton administration, was standing at the podium about to give a
speech. Any of us old timers (male) would surely tell you that Ada
was an extremely beautiful Menominee woman. Of course, she is still
beautiful. Just prior to her speech she heard three Lakota men
seated at a nearby table comment, ``I would give one dozen horses
for that one.'' Horses, of course, were the most valued of gifts.
 &HT;    Creating and hanging beautiful decorations during Christmas also
fit into the ancient lifestyles of the American Indian. Every
longhouse, hogan, or tipi was decorated with various items of the
cultural creations of each tribe during special occasions. The
exterior of the tipis of the Plains Indians were often painted with
beautiful scenes of buffalo, horses and eagles.
 &HT;    Preparing sumptuous feasts for special occasions was also very
much a part of the Indian culture. At weddings, wakes, or to
commemorate a special day, great feasts were prepared.
 &HT;    Tribal people would travel for many miles to attend these
feasts. They would bring their leather pouches to take home
``wateca,'' food that was left over after the feast concluded. We
often joke amongst ourselves that in these modern times, some
Indian people show up with hubcaps for their wateca.
 &HT;    So, you see, it was very easy for the Christian missionaries to
impress the Christmas spirit upon the hearts and minds of the
Indian people. Especially after Indian missions were constructed on
Indian reservations across this land, where Indian children were
institutionalized for nine months of the year. It was at these
missions that we attended mass or other Christian services and we
were instructed in the teachings of the Bible.
 &HT;    After Indians began moving away from their reservations to
attend college, join the military, or to take jobs in other states,
many Indian families took advantage of the vacation days offered by
the holiday to return home to the reservations and to, once again,
be with their family and friends. And so, Christmas became a time
of family reunions. This was true across most of Indian country.
 &HT;    As many tribal people restored their traditional spiritual
beliefs _ practices that were at one time outlawed by the
government of the United States _ they took a new look at the
process that forced them to accept a religion not a part of their
traditions or culture.
 &HT;    They knew Christmas was a Christian holiday to celebrate the
birth of a Jewish baby named Jesus Christ; and there are many
Indians who have embraced Christianity as their own and are quite
comfortable celebrating the birth of Jesus as a significant
religious event.
 &HT;    Many Indian people, however, are returning to their traditional
spirituality. But I believe that although most will no longer look
upon Christianity as a part of their religious practice, they will
still continue to celebrate the holiday of Christmas as a time to
gather together as a family and to exchange gifts.
 &HT;    Many have already incorporated the custom of decorating their
homes as something that is fun to do and beautiful to look at, so I
believe this Christian practice will continue to be a part of what
Christmas means to Indian people today.
 &HT;    Honoring Tanka (the Lakota words for Great Spirit) is something
most traditional Indians do every day.
 &HT;    There is no single day set aside for this. Wakan Tanka was
always here. He is timeless. There is no day set aside to honor his
birth.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, I would like to wish people of all religious
beliefs _ Jews, Christians, Muslims, Buddhists, Hindus and others _
Peace On Earth!
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
