</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6337 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KWANZAA-CHRISTMAS-MON     12-18 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KWANZAA-CHRISTMAS-MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `HOLIDAYS' THEN AND NOW
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa, African American, is a freelance writer and
journalist living in Oakland, Calif. She is a contributor to the
forthcoming book ``Seductions of Justice: Lesbian Legal Theories
and Practices.'' (1999) Routledge Press.)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As a child I never had peaches that were not from a can and
packed in syrup. Likewise our Christmas tree was not green unless
the color wheel was passing the green segment and reflected on the
aluminum Christmas tree.
 &HT;    I never understood the drama of purchasing and decorating a
Christmas tree. When my family was ready for the tree, we simply
removed the box from the storage area, set up the pole and inserted
the branches in their matching color coded slots. We didn't have
special ornaments, just multicolored metal balls. But culturally,
in our community, that's how everyone decorated for Christmas.
 &HT;    I don't recall ever believing in Santa Claus because we never
had a chimney. Our presents, which were plentiful were all neatly
wrapped under the aluminum tree with name tags clearly marked
``to'' and ``from.''
 &HT;    I grew up until the age of 11, in an African American (then
`black' or sometimes still `Negro' or `colored') middle-class
household originally in Kansas and then in Alabama. I do recall
seeing Santa at a shopping center, but not being allowed to
approach, make requests or stand in line because that was reserved
for ``whites only.''
 &HT;    So maybe it wasn't so much the lack of a chimney but rather
segregation that caused me not to believe in Mr. Claus. I do recall
seeing black Santa Clauses but I knew that they were fake because
all of the images in print or in the movies were of white Santa
Clauses.
 &HT;    Maybe I thought that the notion of wanting a ``white Christmas''
was just that, a Christmas for whites only. Certainly at that time,
George Wallace, the governor of Alabama, would have wished for such
a white Christmas.
 &HT;    But then a scant nine years after my birth, Kwanzaa was created,
in 1966 to be exact. I probably wasn't immediately aware of its
existence, but when I first heard of it, it was referred to as the
``black Christmas'' Surely this was invented in the segregated
south, where for so long there had only been ``white Christmases.''
At age 19 I moved to New York and learned more about this ``black
Christmas.'' But it wasn't really a ``black Christmas'' despite the
fact that it was celebrated by and invented by and for African
Americans. And it hadn't been invented in the south, but rather in
California.
 &HT;    But now as our societies and communities become more
multicultural and cross-cultural we all celebrate numerous holidays
in December even those historically or originally reserved for
ethnicities other than our own. There is Hanukkah, Winter Solstice,
Christmas, and Kwanzaa all usually in the second half of December.
 &HT;    I regularly get invited to Hanukkah gatherings and I am never
the only non-Jewish person there. Christmas is not relegated to the
Christians anymore, and it is a cultural phenomenon unto itself
replete with all its commercialism.
 &HT;    And now, Kwanzaa is constantly being attacked for being
separatist and even worst, black nationalist. But, at the last few
celebrations I have attended there have been quite a few
non-African Americans present.
 &HT;    I do not see Kwanzaa, a Swahili word meaning ``first fruit'' as
separatist or promoting black nationalism. Rather, I celebrate
Kwanzaa as a nod to my African roots. An acknowledgment that I am
of African descent despite the fact that I do not know from which
country in that vast continent I am from. In many ways this is why
Kwanzaa is so attractive to me. That it borrows from numerous
African cultures is appropriate to the nonspecificity of the
cultural and ethnic heritage of most African Americans. There is
cultural pride in Jewish holidays, Irish holidays, and so the
descendants of the African diaspora should also have and celebrate
cultural pride.
 &HT;    Kwanzaa has seven principles which many of us try to embody year
round and not just during the seven days of Kwanzaa, Dec. 26 to
Jan. 1. Umoja/unity, Kujichagulia/self-determination,
Ujima/collective work, Ujamaa/cooperative economics, Nia/purpose,
Kuumba/creativity, and Imani/faith. The symbols of Kwanzaa are
representative of the history and future of African Americans,
those of race, bloodshed and struggle, family, and hope.
 &HT;    Now in its third decade of celebration, Kwanzaa is recognized by
more than the 18 million who celebrate it annually. Last year the
United States Post Office honored Kwanzaa with a stamp. Hallmark
sells Kwanzaa cards and many media outlets mention Kwanzaa in the
same breath as Hanukkah and Christmas.
 &HT;    But after my painful beginnings of ``white'' Christmases, it is
liberating and joyful to celebrate Kwanzaa and to have public
recognition of it. So many images in the media beyond Santa Claus
are white and exclusive and not reflective of people of color.
 &HT;    I am an advocate of acknowledging and celebrating our
multicultural roots. So there is room for Hanukkah, Christmas, and
Kwanzaa. I will celebrate them all to various degrees, but Kwanzaa
is the one I feel most connected with.
 &HT;    So I simply wish everyone: ``Happy Holidays!''
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Akilah Monifa 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
