A6341 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFT-FROM-CUBA:GONZAL     12-18 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFT-FROM-CUBA:GONZALEZ-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VISIT TO CUBA FINDS A TRUTH: 'TIS THE SEASON OF LOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By BARBARA RENAUD-GONZALEZ 
 &HT;    (Barbara Renaud-Gonzalez, Mexican American, is a Dallas-based
columnist and writer for several leading Texas and California
newspapers. She is also a commentator for National Public Radio,
and is currently working on a book called ``Mestiza.'') 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mr. Jose Marti, the customs agent, won't let me in. ``You don't
have a hotel or registered address while you visit Cuba,'' he
scolds me while I cool my sandals at the airport in Havana.
``You're a tourist, and we can't just let you stay anywhere you
want.''
 &HT;    But of course I did. After several hours of talking politics and
explaining why a Chicana from Texas decided to take the long way
from her mother's Mexico to visit Cuba, Mr. Marti and I became good
friends. As his black eyes glistened with old humiliation, he knew
that I knew his country was desperate for my dollars. He let me
pass.
 &HT;    So where's the white people, asks my friend, Gerald, whose
scheme it was to come here. Havana is like an American inner city
with Hispanic colonial arches instead of brownstones. There are
black people everywhere who seem poor by our standards, only here
they swallow my Spanish instead of English, so that the vowels are
gulped smoothly like my first mulata rum.
 &HT;    Slavery entered the new world through Cuba in 1513, and ended
almost 400 years later in 1886. ``We were not allowed in Habana
before the Revolution,'' my new Cuban friends tell me. Now they
hang their clothes to dry on the balconies of the palatial homes
that the Spanish descendants had to abandon after Castro's
takeover.
 &HT;    Cuba may be a Communist society, but it is free from billboards,
traffic jams and MTV in this self-made nation. There is no `Just Do
It' on the Malecon, the ocean-front boulevard that curves like a
rhumba dancer's hips to where you can almost touch the sky between
here and Miami. But then Cuba has already done it, hasn't she? Just
do it. The revolution happened. And it wasn't a dream.
 &HT;    ``People pick up guns when there is no hope left,'' the Cubans
tell me. Forty percent of them had no education at all before the
Revolution. Now 97 percent of the population can read. Didn't
George Washington rebel against foreign tyranny? ``The mafia and
the United States controlled Cuba during the Batista regime,'' they
tell me. They know that they have paid a high price for their
independence. During the ``Special Period,'' before the dollars of
tourism, they barely had one chicken to eat in a month. I tell them
that many children in the United States go hungry, but that the
rest of Americans are still fatter than ever. If that is the price
of our prosperity, then they don't want it, they say.
 &HT;    ``Is America a racist country,'' they ask me. ``Yes and no,'' I
answer. Yes, if you recognize that race is the reason we have
suffered as a nation, and no, if you have Black friends. Of course,
if you are a millionaire, race hardly matters.
 &HT;    My new friends tell me that they are afraid of what the Cuban
exiles will do, with America's support, if they ever return. But
the old Cuba, the one the exiles dream of, is gone forever.
 &HT;    In the United States we have the American dream, and that means
that we are free to watch television night after night, go
shopping, and forget about voting. Most of the Cubans I met hunger
for a conversation with a foreigner or a good book. A luxury for
them would be a taxi ride or a leotard for a daughter's dance
class. Here in the United States, one can get rich while children
go hungry, people sleep in the streets, and teenagers drop out of
high school. We have our choice of museums, symphonies and
theaters, but often they starve for visitors, while millions obsess
over football.
 &HT;    To me, Cuba and the United States each have a truth about
humanity, half of a heart that needs the other to become whole.
Can't we honor the paradox of freedom as we face our inevitable,
and mutual destiny?
 &HT;    As I departed from the airport, I ran into Jose Marti. ``Ay,
forgive me for thinking that you were named after the airport
dedicated to Cuba's greatest poet.'' I give him one of my
contraband cigars. He laughs and pretends to stamp my passport.
 &HT;    ``Tell the U.S. that the only blockade I fear, is the internal
one. That is the one that keeps us from being truly free.'' Jose
Marti taps his heart.
 &HT;    In America we agonize for the simple life, too much stuff, we
say, enslaved by our fashions, junkfood and a Christmas that begins
at Halloween.
 &HT;    Most of all, we ache for something that we can't name. I see it
in the faces of the crowds who have so many gifts and so little to
give. It is a season of love, but to find it, the Cubans taught me,
we will have to surrender our hearts to those we have not loved in
the past.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Barbara Renaud-Gonzalez 
<TEXT>
