<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-FLAVORS-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's Christmas Flavors
Special from New America News Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448; fax: 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS IN THE SUNSHINE STATE. Christmas in Florida is a
tropical bazaar, writes columnist Bill Maxwell. ``As a native of
Fort Lauderdale, I am condemned to perpetual heat, humidity and
year-round greenery,'' he grumbles. As a child, he knew it was a
time for Jack Frost, hot chocolate, snow and snowmen, sleighs-bells
and sleds, carolers braving the freeze. ``But like most other South
Floridians, on Dec. 25 we can be seen fishing, golfing, tanning,
water-skiing, swimming, and drinking cold lemonade beneath
sprawling banyans,'' he says, with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-CHRISTMAS-SUNSHINE:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   A HOLIDAY TREE FOR MY JEWISH HOME. Instead of a traditional
Jewish Menorah or Christian Christmas tree, columnist Linda Marx
and her non-Jewish husband have come up with a compromise. ``My
husband bought me a new Menorah which depicts the synagogues of
Europe in loving memory of lost communities,'' she writes.
Alongside the Menorah are Christmas and Hanukkah decorations. ``I
can't help but believe that my mother would understand that days
pass, years go by, and things change,'' she adds. ``We must live in
the present while remembering the past. It is the only way to
ensure our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-HANUKKAH-CHRISTMAS:MARX-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   A BOY'S GIFT FROM `SANTA.' Christmas couldn't always be left up
to parents. Sometimes an 8-year-old had to take matters into his
own hands, writes columnist Kirsten Chapman, especially when what
he wanted most was a Dick Tracy toy gun. After pursuing several
strategies in his quest to acquire it, her brother decided on a
novel approach: `Santa.' And much to the consternation of his
mother and father, he was successful!
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-CHRISTMAS-TOY:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN AMERICAN CHRISTMAS: THE PINATA RULES. The `pinata' can
be found everywhere in the Southwest, where it preceded the
Anglo-Saxon Christmas tree in the former Mexican territories,
explains columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras. ``Following the path of
Mexican immigrants to other areas, the pinata is fast becoming a
regular feature of American Christmas celebrations nationwide,'' he
writes. He tells you how they're made, by whom, what they're filled
with and what makes it so much fun to smash them!
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-CHRISTMAS-PINATA:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   THE `HOLIDAYS' THEN AND NOW. As a child, columnist Akilah Monifa
thought a ``white Christmas'' was really for whites only. But in
1966 Kwanzaa _ often called the ``black Christmas'' _ was created.
Celebrated by more than the 18 million Americans annually, Kwanzaa
was featured on a U.S. Post Office stamp last year, and Hallmark is
selling Kwanzaa cards. ``So there is room for Hanukkah, Christmas,
and Kwanzaa,'' she writes. ``And I will celebrate them all to
various degrees, but Kwanzaa is the one I feel most connected
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-KWANZAA-CHRISTMAS-MONIFA-NU-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS: A TIME FOR FAMILIES TO GATHER NEAR. Do they celebrate
Christmas, Indians are often asked. ``Traditionally, we seldom
visited friends or relatives without taking gifts,'' columnist Tim
Gallego writes, ``and there were always feasts prepared for great
occasions, and tipis decorated for special events.'' So, he
explains, the celebration of Christmas was one Christian holiday
that fit very comfortably into the lifestyles of the Indian people.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-INDIAN-CHRISTMAS:GIAGO-NU-NYTSF in ``k'' commentary,
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS: A BLEND OF TRADITIONS _ EAST AND WEST. Many thousands
of Taiwanese are converts to Christianity, and so for them
Christmas has special meaning, notes columnist Frank Wu who
recently visited the country of his parents. But for most
Taiwanese, however, Christmas is simply another ritual borrowed
from Western civilization. ``There is nothing like a trip overseas
to remind us how much we are Americans. And to see how Christmas
has spread to other cultures,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-TAIWANESE-CHRISTMAS:WU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   GAY RUDOLPH? THE RED-NOSED REINDEER. Everyone knows the
children's tale of Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer. And Rudolph, who
was different from the other reindeer, teaches us important lessons
about life and diversity, writes columnist Chuck Colbert.
``Embracing these differences,'' he says, ``is what gives Christmas
meaning for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-GAY-CHRISTMAS:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   A VISIT TO CUBA FINDS A TRUTH: 'TIS THE SEASON OF LOVE. In
America we agonize for the simple life, columnist Barbara
Renaud-Gonzalez muses, ``too much stuff, we say, enslaved by our
fashions, junkfood and a Christmas that begins at Halloween.'' In
Cuba people go hungry for a good book, a conversation with a
visitor. ``Christmas is a season of love, but to find it, the
Cubans taught me, we will have to surrender our hearts to those we
have not loved in the past, '' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-GIFT-FROM-CUBA:GONZALEZ-NU-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
