<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RAY OF ACHIEVEMENT FOR BOURQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It took 10 minutes to play the final minute of Thursday
night's Bruins-Senators game. Half the delay was caused by
penalties. The other half was devoted to a salute from the
FleetCenter crowd for the hero of the festivities, Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard flashed Bourque's grinning face and the crowd
reacted, cheering as loudly as they had at any time during the
preceding 59 minutes of action. His Bruins teammates slammed their
sticks against the boards approvingly and looked toward their
captain.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the 20-year veteran raised his stick and acknowledged
his fans, all 13,646 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard all sorts of cheers here,'' he said afterward.
``Some for just stepping out on the ice and others for my wife
having a baby. It's always a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque reached his first milestone when he stepped on the ice
for the opening faceoff. He thus became the 10th NHLer ever to play
1,400 games. Among active players, he trails only Wayne Gretzky and
Larry Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   At 17:38 of the third period came milestone No. 2. Bourque
registered his second assist of the game, setting up Dmitri
Khristich with the final goal in the Bruins' 5-2 victory. It was
the 1,049th assist of his career, tying Gordie Howe for third place
on the all-time NHL list.
</P>
<P>
   In between those achievements, he was the Bourque of his youth _
checking opponents into the boards, dousing potential breakaways,
firing blistering slap shots from the point, and saving shots
before they got to the net.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, coach Pat Burns lauded his dedication. ``It
seems as if I talk about him on a weekly basis,'' said Burns.
``It's such a proud thing to coach him. I think the way he plays,
he has earned everything he has. His loyalty to the team, his
dedication. Everything about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque savored the moment. ``The milestones are something I'll
enjoy tonight and tomorrow,'' he said. ``But come Saturday, it's
another game and all this will be behind me. You've got to move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   And it seems there is always another milestone for Bourque, who
tries to minimize his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this level, the only thing that is important is winning,''
he said, ``and if we didn't win tonight, these milestones wouldn't
mean as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns agreed. ``I'll tell you, he wouldn't be happy if we
lost,'' said the coach. ``Between the first and second periods, he
was shouting at the team. Winning is important. Other players worry
about ice time, how many points they get, how many shots they get.
But not him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said milestones are part of the game. One does not mean
more than another. ``Except one,'' he said. ``The Cup. You want to
win the Stanley Cup because it is the last game of the year and you
can enjoy it for the whole summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it worth leaving Boston to join a team with a better shot at
the one prize that has eluded Bourque?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said emphatically. ``If it is going to happen, it is
going to happen here in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's memories of his first NHL game are as fresh as those
of his 1,400th. ``I can remember everything about it,'' he said.
``I was paired with Dick Redmond. I guess that shows how long ago
it was. But playing in that first NHL game is something all hockey
players dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns compared his star to the other legends of the game. ``You
don't know you are in the presence of greatness when they are
here,'' he said. ``It is when they are going that you realize how
great they really were, and Ray Bourque is one of those players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to be lucky to last as long as I have,'' said Bourque.
``You have to avoid serious injuries, and I appreciate going out
there every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
