<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WISH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS EMBRACE 3-YEAR-OLD CANCER PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ He arrived at the team's complex in a police
car driven by former Seahawk safety turned Seattle cop Vic Minor.
Lights flashing and siren squealing.
</P>
<P>
   He and his entourage were escorted to the locker room, where he
changed into his uniform before hurrying out to practice.
</P>
<P>
   He was called into the team's post-practice huddle by Dennis
Erickson, where he helped the coach lead the traditional ``1-2-3,
Seahawks'' chant and was greeted by applause and high-fives from
the players.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' newest free-agent acquisition?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. The ``player'' in the miniature No. 84 uniform Thursday
was 3-year-old Sterling Grover, who has rhabdomyosarcoma, which is
a long name to describe the malignant cancer cells that are
ravaging Sterling's bones and soft tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling's day among his heroes was made possible by the
Make-a-Wish Foundation and the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool,'' he said when asked he was enjoying himself.
</P>
<P>
   The coolest player, as far as Sterling is concerned, is wide
receiver Joey Galloway. Sterling was wearing Galloway's number and
using a locker that was set up next to Galloway's just for him.
After being welcomed by the players at practice, Erickson asked
Sterling if he wanted to say anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Sterling said. ``I want to see Joey Galloway.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Galloway? ``Cuz I like him,'' Sterling offered, a
how-can-you-even ask? expression replacing the look of wonderment
on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling's mother, Lisa, explained that her youngest son's
infatuation with Galloway started last month after he attended the
Seahawks' game against the Raiders at the Kingdome. Since then,
Sterling has watched the team's other games with his grandfather,
Jed Grover, at the Ronald McDonald House.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad's down here with us, so he and Sterling watch football
games together on Sundays,'' Lisa Grover said. ``Sterling puts his
uniform on every Sunday and runs around the Ronald McDonald
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling has been living at the Ronald McDonald House since
July. He has had surgery and is now receiving chemotherapy
treatments. As a show of support, his 10-year-old brother, Spencer,
has shaved his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was bald first,'' Sterling quickly pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   As Sterling darted from player to player in the locker room,
having his picture taken with each, it was difficult to tell who
was having more fun, Sterling or the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different, but it's exciting,'' Galloway said as he
watched Sterling work the locker room as if he belonged there. ``As
you can see, all the players are smiling. When he first came out,
we were all laughing. It's cute.''
</P>
<P>
   Offered Erickson, ``This is something special. It's a great
thing. That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling's big adventure is far from over. He will attend
Sunday's game at the Kingdome and ride in the team's helmet cart _
the second part of his Make-a-Wish request. Sitting next to
Sterling as he circles the Kingdome will be Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   But then that shouldn't be too surprising. Sterling and his
family are from North Pole, Alaska.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 0150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
