<HEADLINE>
TAR HEELS STOMP HOLY CROSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ North Carolina has better leapers, faster
players, stronger shooters, and a much deeper bench. That's why the
Tar Heels are ranked No. 7 in the country in women's basketball.
Holy Cross, with only its freshmen having athletic scholarships, is
not in that class.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise that North Carolina did everything better
in Thursday night's 89-66 rout of the Lady Crusaders at the Hart
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels outrebounded HC, 57-35. They outshot HC, 43.9-42.4
percent, including 46.7-35.3 in the first half. And they harassed
HC into 21 turnovers, 12 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It all made for a sweet homecoming for UNC senior point guard
Jessica Gaspar of North Dartmouth, who helped her team build a
20-point lead late in the first half and keep the Lady Crusaders at
bay.
</P>
<P>
   Five Tar Heels scored in double figures. Chanel Wright led the
way with 20 points. LaQuana Barksdale added 16 to go along with an
arena rec-ord of 19 rebounds. Juana Brown (13), Jackie Higgins
(12), and Nikki Teasley (12) joined them in twin figures.
</P>
<P>
   For Holy Cross (6-5), Amy O'Brien collected a game-high 32
points on 12-for-19 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off exams Wednesday, North Carolina looked quite ordinary
early, hitting on one of five field goal attempts and committing a
turnover. There were five ties in the opening seven minutes, the
last at 10-10 when O'Brien canned an 8-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to pick up the tempo,'' said UNC coach Sylvia
Hatchell. ``We didn't want them to get into a half-court game. We
were trying to make it uptempo, which is in our favor. We wanted to
take advantage of our quickness through the transition game. We had
the open shots, but we just weren't making them.''
</P>
<P>
   But then North Carolina (12-1), getting fast breaks when a
player switched to offense each time Holy Cross shot, started
rolling. The lead gradually reached double figures, climbing to 11
points, 28-17, on a Wright 3-pointer from the top of the key with
8:15 left in the first half. It got to 20, 43-23, on two Brown free
throws 2:37 before the break and was a comfortable 22, 50-28, at
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got lax late that first half,'' said Holy Cross coach
Bill Gibbons. ``We knew about their cutter and we didn't do a good
job on that, plus we missed a lot of layups as well as foul shots
(2 for 8 in the first half, 7 for 13 in the game). Once we missed,
they got out on the fast breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Tar Heels kept grabbing rebounds _ 25 on the offensive
boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wore them down with our rebounds,'' said Hatchell. ``Our
quickness helped, as did our bench.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
