<HEADLINE>
RACE NO ISSUE IN NBA LOCKOUT, JUST SUBTEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The race card has now been played in this NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, it was a real quick hand, with both sides sanguinely
reporting that the most important color in this fight is green, not
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Not a big surprise, since about $2 billion is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   After a week's worth of news clippings that caused this issue of
race to come trickling to the surface, NBA players union chief
Billy Hunter gave the union's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think race is (the problem),'' Hunter told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem is you've got a group of extremely
successful businessmen who own these teams, most of whom are
billionaires. On the other side of the table, you've got a group of
players who are predominantly African-American in origin, so I
think people can read into it anything they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subliminally, it may be there, but I think it's about dollars,
it's all about hard economics,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for a few days, the door was cracked open on an issue
that is imbedded in almost every aspect of American life and
certainly in sports. It began when an NBA union leader, Alonzo
Mourning, was quoted in a Newsweek article. Mourning's comments
gave rise to an examination of the role race might be playing in
the NBA negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owners think we're blacks who should be happy with what we
got. I'm not saying it's all about race, but it plays a factor,''
Mourning said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, any time a contentious dialogue such as this NBA
battle gives the appearance of breaking down along racial lines,
the issue is tough to avoid. No doubt, perceptions and stereotypes
about race are laced somewhere in these tense talks, just as they
are laced through so many aspects of sports.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, why do assistant coaches in the NFL who happen to
be African-American have a harder time getting a shot as a head
coach? Same in the NBA or Major League Baseball, where the
overwhelmingly majority of owners are white, most of whom are
obviously more inclined to hire and recycle familiar _ and mostly
white _ coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Double standards exist that make at least a hint at the race
issue unavoidable. For example, if Latrell Sprewell was given a
full-year suspension (later reduced by an arbitrator to a
season-long suspension) for choking Golden State coach P.J.
Carlesimo, then what about Carolina linebacker Kevin Greene?
</P>
<P>
   After physically attacking his position coach _ Carolina
assistant Kevin Steele _ on the sideline last week, Greene, who is
white, was given a one-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   One game vs. basically a year's worth of salary.
</P>
<P>
   Granted we are talking different leagues, but some would argue
that Greene deserved to sit out longer.
</P>
<P>
   And granted, Sprewell's actions were pre-meditated. He came back
into the gym after already having a skirmish with the acid-tongued
Carlesimo. But Greene's attack looked no less menacing, especially
on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mourning and Patrick Ewing and any other NBA union
member, they would have been dishonest if, in the face of questions
from the media, they had completely shrugged off the question of
how perceptions and stereotypes might come into play, even if they
are far from being the main stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about money and what bothers me most is that the
fans and the media are misinformed about the issues of this
lockout,'' said Eric Goodwin, an agent who represents Gary Payton,
Damon Stoudamire and Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, there are some comments that I think have been unfair or
stereotypical. I might question the comments directed at Kenny
Anderson, who might have said tongue-in-cheek that if he could not
earn a living this season because of the lockout, then he might
consider selling one of his cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the stereotype portrayed in the widely publicized story
of Anderson during the lockout has been the crux of the NBA owners'
strategy. An African-American player with ``lavish'' spending
habits was portrayed in the media as a representative for all or
most NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of thing might be why most fans think this is a
strike, not a lockout.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the belief by NBA officials and owners that these
so-called lavish spending habits will be the reason why the rank
and file will be broken.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see John Stockton or Hersey Hawkins flaunting those
things. Not every NBA player has oodles of platinum and diamonds
dripping off their bodies,'' Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   All these issues _ about race, stereotypes, who spends their
money where _ are subtext, hardly the main point. Goodwin said the
owners' unwillingness to make the same sort of concessions as the
players has stood in the way of a deal. Still, he is optimistic
there will be a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both sides understand that it is in the best interest
of basketball not to lose the season. Everyone knows the risk is
losing fans if the season is canceled,'' Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally _ a message pulsing from the lockout fight that everyone
can agree upon.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
