<HEADLINE>
KELLEY FINISHES OFF RAMIREZ AFTER CAUTIOUS BEGINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The punch came fast, hard and by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Cautious for 8{ rounds, New York lightweight Kevin Kelley put
veteran Jorge Ramirez away for a good with an overhand left that
ended their main event with one a single punch at the Country Club
in Reseda on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the same punch I've used to knock out a lot of
fighters,'' said Kelley (48-3-2, 23 KOs), who needed a win after
losing two of his last three.
</P>
<P>
   Both were cautious in the early going, extending the feeling-out
process through four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley got more busy as the bout progressed, but he had trouble
nailing Ramirez with anything worthwhile. Ramirez showed good
quickness and just enough snap in his punches to give Kelley
something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fight as consistently as I used to,'' Kelley said.
``So it was hard to comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez of Sonora, Mexico, fell to 67-13-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the undercard, junior lightweight Roger Medal (8-1)
outclassed Angel Mata (6-2), winning all six rounds. Medal used a
series of short, sneaky lefts and rights to keep Mata at bay.
Neither fighter was hurt, but Medal was in control all the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Richard Gonzalez-Thomas Hinde middleweight match was called
after two rounds when managers and seconds from both sides brawled
in the ring. The melee started after the fighters continued
punching following the end of the second round. Both fighters
officially were disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to pull their manager off my fighter and I got
cold-cocked,'' said Eddie Gonzalez, manager of Richard Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Yguado (1-0) beat Norris Ellington (0-4) by technical
knockout at 3:00 of the fourth round in a wild super-welterweight
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Holewyne (3-2) defeated Robyn Covino (1-7) by technical
knockout in the third round of their female welterweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   Light heavyweights Jose Chico and Rigoberto Plascencia of
Pacoima fought to a four-round draw in the professional debut for
both.
</P>
</TEXT>
