A6566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-FUTURE19-COX     12-18 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-FUTURE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rabbi's predicted reforms welcome converts, gays
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO (mug)
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The next generation of Jews will be
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to elect to be Jewish because there is so much
freedom for Jews in America and countless options available to
them.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer corps will wrestle with God in an emerging Jewish
life driven by compassion and justice rooted in authentic spiritual
experience.
</P>
<P>
   And it will shape a Judaism that energetically recruits
converts, recognizes women fully, welcomes and ordains practicing
homosexuals, presides over same sex unions and embraces
intermarried couples.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Alexander Schindler thinks that's what the future holds
for the ancient religion. And what Schindler thinks has shaped much
of American Jewish thought for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   He was president of the governing body of Reform Judaism from
1973 to 1996. He continues to influence Jewish ideas in significant
ways.
</P>
<P>
   He is a sought-after speaker on the lecture circuit, frequently
a scholar-in-residence and serves on a half-dozen national and
international Jewish organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler, 73, came south from his home in Connecticut last week
to speak in honor of the 75th anniversary of Temple Israel in West
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he preached at Temple Beth Torah in Wellington and
blessed the 30-year marriage of Rabbi and Mrs. Stephen Pinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He honors the past on both occasions as he honors the tradition
of his faith, but both must give way to the future as necessary, he
insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judaism is always changing,'' Schindler said in an interview.
``Reform means that Judaism is always in the process of becoming.
It is never a state of being. It is always a relentless going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Unparalleled freedom, increased knowledge and the imperative of
compassion will shape the future of Judaism, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jews are no longer forced to be Jewish through persecution and
prejudice. They are no longer defined by others. But freedom has a
price. Jews may choose not to be Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``To them, Judaism in the future can only issue an invitation,
not a summons,'' Schindler said.
</P>
<P>
   And that invitation must be rooted in an embrace of Torah
(Jewish scripture) that is informed by contemporary understanding
and the search for justice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Orthodox Jewish conviction, Schindler believes the Torah
is the record of a ``God-inspired people to know God'' and was
fashioned by human beings.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the holy book is not a record of God's dictation to
Moses and must be interpreted. Scripture includes both soaring
ideals and human ignorance, profound truth and deplorable bigotry,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right and, indeed, the obligation to make
distinctions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, responsible studies demonstrate that homosexuals do
not choose to be gay. Their sexuality is a given, he said.
Compassion insists they be embraced by the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that discerning God's will is demanding. He recalled
the story of Jacob wrestling through the night with an angel in the
book of Genesis.
</P>
<P>
   God changed Jacob's name to Israel, which means ``struggle with
God.''
</P>
<P>
   But the root of the word implies the future tense, Schindler
said. All Jews must wrestle with God.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the task imposed upon us when we accept the name,
Israel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His own journey is an example of that challenge. He escaped to
the United States from Nazi Germany in 1937 and served as a ski
trooper in Europe during World War II. He planned to study
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   While stationed near Yugoslavia at war's end, he went to Munich
on a pass to search for surviving family members, if any, and found
himself at the death camp, Dachau.
</P>
<P>
   ``There, unconsciously, I knew I wanted to know why what
happened happened.''
</P>
<P>
   He told another story to explain his perspective from that
extraordinary experience.
</P>
<P>
   A rabbi asked Elijah, the prophet, where to find the Messiah
expecting to see him surrounded by glory. The Messiah would be
found at the city gate, Elijah said.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi asked what the Messiah was doing at that unlikely
place. Elijah replied that the Messiah was sitting among the
wounded changing their bandages one by one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the essence of Torah,'' Schindler said. ``Compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
