A6567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD19-COX     12-18 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rustic furniture just needs the right woodworker for great
results
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sitting here at my desk looking at a new book called
``Simple Rustic Furniture,'' subtitled ``A weekend workshop with
Dan Mack,'' I had a sudden change of heart about this stuff.
</P>
<P>
   I have not actually seen much of this stuff, which is called
rustic only euphemistically. It used to be called twig furniture,
which sort of downsizes it, but is closer to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Basically it is furniture made of green found wood, generally
altered only just enough to get the pieces together.
</P>
<P>
   As I said, I haven't seen much, and most of what I have seen has
been relegated to odd dark corners of people's houses and allowed
to collect a lot of dust, which it does with a vengeance. Bark,
after all, is hard to keep clean.
</P>
<P>
   I expect much of what I've seen hasn't been very well finished,
either, or perhaps the finish was never renewed. At any rate, it
had that sad gray look of old kindling.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look very strong, either.
</P>
<P>
   So I always looked upon this rustic furniture as something young
adults might be forced to construct during summer camp, just to
prove that, by Neddy Dingo, it can be done. If you're set adrift in
the limitless forest with nothing but a hatchet and a pocket knife,
you can make yourself a nice chair and a table, whether you want to
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I've been missing something. I can see now that if the
right woodworker gets into this stuff, the results can be something
remarkable. But it requires an honest-to-goodness artist, because
everything has to be original. You couldn't copy most of this stuff
if your life depended on it, because you couldn't find the same
sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Thus there is no telling where some of the ``weekend projects''
in Mack's book are going to end up.
</P>
<P>
   But one of them, a bentwood chair by a gentleman named Andrew
Gardner, is just about as handsome a seating piece as I've seen
anywhere. It's a very graceful, regal thing, with a classic sort of
sweeping design.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably fairly brutal to sit in _ most of these chairs
look that way _ and since it is largely held together with nails, I
suspect a lot of sitting in it is going to turn it into firewood.
(I'm sorry, but I just don't believe nails can hold things together
if they're subject to racking stresses.)
</P>
<P>
   Some things here are more rustic than others. There are some
very attractive pieces which don't look rustic at all until you
realize that a few pieces are, in fact, somewhat lumpy sticks with
the bark peeled off, sanded and finished.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of furniture is going to appeal to relatively few
people, and look at home in relatively few houses. But real art is
possible within its confines.
</P>
<P>
   The book that brought about this little epiphany is published by
Lark Books, 50 College Street, Asheville, NC 28801, at $19.95 in
hardback.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes a column about woodworking every week for The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. He can be reached at
jwarner(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
