<HEADER>
A6569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MAIL19-COX     12-18 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MAIL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We've got `Mail,' but its cute idea doesn't deliver
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Cute is: Meg Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Cute isn't: Meg Ryan mugging so hard you want to mug her.
</P>
<P>
   Charming is: Ineffable.
</P>
<P>
   Charming isn't: Earnest. And it isn't ``You've Got Mail,'' a
listless romantic comedy set in the age of e-mail, but with all the
carry of a canceled stamp.
</P>
<P>
   The film reunites the crew who made ``Sleepless In Seattle'' _
Ryan, Tom Hanks and director Nora Ephron. The story is based on
``The Shop Around the Corner,'' a 1940 movie starring Jimmy Stewart
and Margaret Sullavan as feuding shopworkers who don't realize
they're lonely-hearts pen pals. Very charming.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Kathleen Kelly (Ryan) and Joe Fox (Hanks) are in the book
business. She owns a tiny bookstore called _ you guessed it _ The
Shop Around The Corner. He runs a chain of superstores. When he
opens one near her, it threatens to run her cute little
establishment right out of New York's cute little Upper West Side.
The pair do not get along.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but all along they have been exchanging anonymous, computer
e-mail. They live contentedly with others (Hanks with bratty Parker
Posey; Ryan with Greg Kinnear, in another good performance as a
rather feckless soul). At least the pair think they're contented
until they become infatuated with each other's thoughts. This
attraction is a mystery, since their e-mail reads like the musings
of Andy Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Hanks learns the identity of his
mistress-of-the-modem. This gives him an advantage over her, and
gives the film some oomph and the possibility of good-natured
deviltry. But the Pillow Talk premise isn't exploited, and the
movie grinds to a predictable _ and predictably cute _ conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? Director Ephron, who also co-wrote the
screenplay, is intent on imposing charm from the top down.
Everything feels forced, including the dog who sits watching Hanks
compose his messages. Schmaltz isn't a brand of yeast, and it
doesn't make a film rise.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ryan and Hanks seem more like ciphers than full-bodied
characters. And the dialog isn't very sprightly. It's smart-alecky
rather than smart; smug rather than sassy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the movie drags with unnecessary scenes that seem
included because the filmmakers thought they were, well, cute. An
example is a bull session about women between Hanks and his father
(Dabney Coleman).
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who always seems to have a saintly aureole of light around
her, overacts in spades. Bored viewers might amuse themselves by
counting how many different faces she makes without once looking
into the camera with any sort of conviction. Hanks is blase and
bemused, but doesn't bring anything to the film we haven't seen
before.
</P>
<P>
   Even New York looks cute and over-scrubbed, as if the film were
produced by Mayor Giuliani and the city's tourist board. But is
this the image New York really wants to project? Not ``Sleepless in
Seattle,'' but ``Witless on the West Side?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
