A6570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PRINCE19-COX     12-18 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PRINCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gorgeous and star-studded, `Prince of Egypt' delivers
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Deliver Us'' is the opening musical
number in the visually spectacular animated Bible story, ``The
Prince of Egypt.'' And by the movie's mood, look and subject
matter, it clearly wants to deliver us from the omnipresent Disney
model for feature-length cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Ten Commandments'' remake, boiled down to an
hour-and-a-half and souped up with action sequences, is impressive.
Still, it is best defined by what is not there: the usual cutesy
sidekick characters or ingratiating comic interludes. And it takes
such a grown-up approach to the story of Moses leading his people
to freedom that its reverent, serious tone is virtually unleavened
by humor.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``The Prince of Egypt'' knows it is an
entertainment, not an illustrated Sunday school sermon. It
emphasizes adventure aspects: Baby Moses' travel down the Nile in a
basket is so fraught with peril it could be a sequel to ``The River
Wild.''
</P>
<P>
   When the story doesn't have enough action opportunities, they
are invented. A teen-age Moses and pharoah-to-be Rameses are
depicted as boisterous sibling rivals, particularly in a
thrill-ride chariot race with terrific perspective-shifting
computer graphics. In one of the film's few playful moments, their
reckless hot-rodding suggests a new theory on how the Sphinx statue
lost its nose.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, though, the script is walk-on-eggs careful.
The movie shouldn't feel so strait-jacketed. And while the look of
the characters is highly realistic, one wonders exactly what was
gained by making this story in animation. Some cost-cutting on the
parting of the Red Sea?
</P>
<P>
   Only one scene is truly re-imagined for animation, and it is
stunning. As Moses awakens to his Jewish heritage, the wall
hieroglyphs come alive and menace him with evidence of the
pharoah's murderous ways. It is the best sequence in the movie and
the best argument for its existence.
</P>
<P>
   With live-action special effects having evolved so much since
Cecil B. DeMille's ``Ten Commandments'' days, other moments seem
less awe-inspiring. Moses turning his staff into a serpent is no
better than Saturday morning cartoons. But the burning bush has a
downright heavenly glow, a sandstorm in the wilderness will parch
your throat, and the climactic Red Sea crossing is a marvel.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks did not stint on hiring voice talent, including Val
Kilmer (Moses), Ralph Fiennes (Rameses) and Michelle Pfeiffer
(Moses' wife Tzipporah, who looks like a cousin of Hunchback's
Esmeralda). Whether encouraged so or not, they all lose themselves
in their roles rather than letting their star personalities come
through. This is most evident with Rameses' Mutt-and-Jeff magician
henchmen, voiced by Steve Martin and Martin Short but without any
of the antics such casting seems to promise.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, after telling a story of squabbling brothers who
grow up, with one continuing a dynasty and the other serving a
heritage he had long denied, ``The Prince of Egypt'' does become a
cartoon about faith and spirituality. It ends abruptly without any
mention of what is written on those tablets Moses carries down from
the mountain, but it certainly suggests the Jews' deliverance came
about from their belief and adherence to a higher being.
</P>
<P>
   Now, quick: What's the last animated movie that tried to send
out that message?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
