<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-LOVE19-COX     12-18 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-LOVE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for love in all the cyberspaces
 &HT;    WITH CYBERSEX, MOVIES-MAIL
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``I'm not some Internet weirdo,''
SirCoffee insists. ``I'm not some nerd who doesn't have some social
skills who has to hide behind the computer. I just thought it'd be
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   We can't look into SirCoffee's eyes and evaluate the truth of
his protests. But we can stare at the photo he posted on line when
he was looking for love via the Internet classifieds, an
increasingly popular pastime.
</P>
<P>
   And there he is, an attractive 27-year-old from New Jersey who
had broken up with his 22-year-old girlfriend and wanted to move
on.
</P>
<P>
   He began navigating through the online chat rooms _ he hated
them _ and the ever-widening world of online romance. Then he
discovered that hotbed of cybermating on America Online:
Love(AT)AOL.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people have posted classified ads at this
extremely popular meeting place since America Online opened it on
Valentine's Day 1996, according to Bill Schreiner, director of
programming for Love(AT)AOL.
</P>
<P>
   And many more are apt to gravitate there and to other online
love connections when the new movie ``You've Got Mail,'' with Meg
Ryan and Tom Hanks as two online addicts who find love.
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't just the nameless masses that play on line.
Talk-show host Rush Limbaugh hooked up with wife Marta online. And
author Tom Clancy found himself facing divorce after his online
trysts moved off-line, his wife said. (He's now hoping to marry
another woman, whom he didn't meet online.)
</P>
<P>
   SirCoffee is a classic cyberlover. He says he fell hard for his
lady before they ever met in person.
</P>
<P>
   Her online name was She 11 Ra, and she turned out to be a
beautiful 28-year-old blonde with a great smile.
</P>
<P>
   SirCoffee admits he would never have approached her if they had
met at a bar or a party. Too beautiful and intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   But online? Well, they searched each other's profiles and
classified ads. They talked through instant messages that flashed
on their computer screens and communicated via carefully
constructed e-mail notes. And, eventually, they talked by phone.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's Schreiner says this is the appeal of online connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you actually get to know somebody slower, it gives you
more opportunities to get a sense of truth of how somebody is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something about the written word that reveals a lot.
If you're a jerk or not funny, it will come across in written
communications. People are very self-revealing online.''
</P>
<P>
   After just three months of cyber-courtship, SirCoffee and his
lady were ready to take it to the next level: meeting in person.
</P>
<P>
   SirCoffee, aka Erik Jacobsen of Essex County, N.J., flew to
California in late October to meet Cherokee (She Ra), the woman of
his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   He waited impatiently to find out whether flesh and blood could
equal fantasy and ``cybersex.'' (Cybersex is a way of being
sexually intimate, but instead of talking or touching, you type.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let's just say we're very happy!'' he said via an
e-mail. ``Everything we told each other was absolutely true! We're
compatible on every level! For what it's worth, you can chalk this
one up as a definite match!''
</P>
<P>
   AOL's Schreiner says the classified-ad site acquires 700
personals every day. ``It's a reflection of how much unmet demand
and desire there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Ketly Blaise-Sapp and her husband of two years, Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   The couple lives in West Palm Beach, but they, like Erik and
Cherokee, had a distance problem to resolve before their online
matchup ended in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   And they had more baggage to carry into their relationship than
the never-married twenty-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby was divorced, with a teen-age son, when he found Ketly's
online ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't been dating anybody really seriously for two years,''
Ketly, 41, says. ``I was kind of coming to a peace about it. But my
sister, Joanne, encouraged me to go on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ketly posted an ad on AOL looking for an African-American from
the Northeast. She figured she had worn out her prospects nearby,
she jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby lived in New Jersey and fulfilled Ketly's qualifications
for a single man who was ``spiritually based'' and family-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Technology, while the facilitator of this affair, was also
almost the death of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby typed too slow!'' Ketly says of her husband's ability to
communicate through instant messages. She was ready to call it all
off.
</P>
<P>
   But Bobby kept e-mailing her until she responded. It was a lark
for him, he said, a fun way to get in touch with someone new.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they started talking by telephone. Ketly, always a
cynic, was not overly impressed until that pivotal one-hour phone
call he placed while driving to see a newborn nephew.
</P>
<P>
   She liked the way he talked about his family and the way he
revealed himself to her. It had taken a lot to get to that point.
Ketly had given him beeper numbers and cell-phone numbers, always
careful not to give out too much personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he arranged to meet her on his way to a vacation in the
Bahamas. She had not even seen a photo of him at that point. Bobby
was new to the Internet and didn't know how to post a photo online,
so he mailed it. Confusion over addresses kept the picture from
arriving before Bobby did.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if he's ugly?'' Ketly kept worrying.
</P>
<P>
   But three days before he arrived, Bobby sent her three roses
with an endearing message: ``Take a deep breath. It's gonna be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Ketly, ``The photo actually came two days after I met him.
It was a good thing. The photo looked nerdy!''
</P>
<P>
   Their meeting went well, and they flew back and forth getting to
know each other. Ketly was nervous about taking on his 15-year-old
son, but then Bobby decided he would move to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they eloped nine months after meeting online, they
hadn't spent more than 10 days together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first year was very difficult,'' Ketly confesses. ``It
hasn't been a picnic.'' Eventually, Bobby's son returned to New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But neither regrets how they met.
</P>
<P>
   Says Bobby, ``I think our situation is unique. I do see it as a
viable way to meet people. But you need to know what you're looking
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Dupree, a University of Florida graduate who now
lives in Washington, wasn't looking for any kind of love match when
she met her live-in beau of five years, Bill Walsh, through a
tennis bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   This was back in 1992, when online connections weren't so
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   But they ``talked'' back and forth on the board, posting
messages, and eventually chatting by phone the night before they
met for lunch in D.C. They hadn't even exchanged photos when they
got together, not the way romances are usually cooked up online
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up and said, `hello,' and lunch was 2 1/2 hours long,
and (then) he called in to take off work. That was pretty much it.
We realized very quickly we were extremely compatible.''
</P>
<P>
   They recently bought a house together and have a ``30-year,
fixed commitment,'' Dupree laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before 1995, it was hard to explain to people how we met,''
she says. ``We were trendsetters.''
</P>
<P>
   Today? Well, just go to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
