<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSEX19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is Web romance cheating? Not always, expert says
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ All your clothes are on. So are the
lights. There's no one else in the room _ especially not your
significant other. It's just you, your computer, a keyboard and a
few million impure thoughts screaming through your head. There's a
name on the computer screen, an anonymous love bird with whom
you've been flirting on line. Your naughty repartee would make a
White House intern blush, but you don't even know what the person
looks like, much less what he or she feels like in the dark or
sounds like the morning after.
</P>
<P>
   Does this qualify as cheating?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, says cybersex expert Deb Levine. Her new book, ``The Joy
of Cybersex'' ($12, Random House), is both a sexual rule book and a
guide for getting it on online. Think of ``The Joy of Sex'' without
all those embarrassing charcoal drawings and with a modem instead
of motion lotion.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the question at hand. Levine fields it down the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each situation is different,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone goes online to have a sexual experience or a
fantasy or to push their creativity a little farther, and they do
it once and process it and then decide to move on from there and
not do it again ... I do not consider that cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   But...
</P>
<P>
   ``But if a person goes on line for a regular rendezvous with the
same person for an intimate relationship ...'' she says, pausing
for a breath. ``Yes ... That would be cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine, 35, has carved a niche for herself online as a referee
on a sprawling social playing field that has few boundaries. A
combination of Miss Manners and Dr. Ruth, she provides sexual
advice in a persona known as Delilah on her World Wide Web site
(www.thrive-online.com/sex/delilah.today.html). Levine got her
start at Columbia University five years ago, when she developed the
Go Ask Alice site, which was designed to answer questions about
safe sex and relationships. She's not a trained sex therapist, but
much of what she espouses comes from years spent observing behavior
on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Levine's book provides a how-to for using the Internet to
enhance your sex life, as well as tips on flirting and suggestions
for sites to visit when looking for an online partner.
</P>
<P>
   As Levine sees it, whether cheating or not, the ultimate goal
should be to use cybersex as an aid, not a replacement or
substitute for the real thing. Whatever thrill you might get from a
temporary dip into the murky waters of cyberfantasy should be
channeled back into your existing relationship.
</P>
<P>
   That clears it up, right?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no, since people keep finding new ways to play online.
</P>
<P>
   Dicey thing, this Internet. As easy as it is to find a recipe or
a stock quote or even a funny joke or two, it can plug a computer
user into a subculture where sex and intense relationships are just
a few keystrokes away. Chat-room conversations, message-board
correspondence or even a few spicy volleys of e-mail can quickly
evolve into a relationship that has all the emotions and mindplay
of sex, if not any of the physical contact.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of accessibility is changing the sexual landscape,
Levine says in her book.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the privacy of your own home, you can get the advice and
support you need to overcome shyness. You can even flirt with
strangers in your pajamas! No one will ever know if you haven't
slept a wink, if you have stubble on your face or if you haven't
put on your makeup. The anonymity also means you never have to see
a particular person again if you flub it.''
</P>
<P>
   But assuming the real thing is available, why would someone opt
to pluck forbidden fruit in such a sterile den of iniquity, where
the most common pickup line is: ``Are you hot? What are your
measurements?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me the No. 1 reason for going on line is to feel
desired,'' she said. ``They say they've been in a relationship
off-line and have started to take each other for granted, and
they're not feeling like a sexual being. Going online allows them
to be in a nonjudgmental place where they can be considered a
sexual being and be desired.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the emotions felt during online encounters can be brought
to a person's primary relationship,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I encourage is that the computer not take the place of
real life, that it instead complement real life,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
