</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GODS&AMP;MONSTERS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gods' peers inside forgotten Hollywood
 &HT;    By Staff report
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ An aging, nearly forgotten Hollywood
fixture sits at home in repose, until a young man arrives and
becomes involved in the icon's twisted existence. And by the
fade-out, there is a dead body floating ominously in the swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Sunset Boulevard? Of course, but it also applies to an
engrossing new movie, ``Gods and Monsters,'' about a real-life
equivalent of silent star Norma Desmond. Based on a novel by
Christopher Bram, it is a fictional speculation on the last months
of director James Whale, who carved out a monster of a career with
the 1930s horror films ``Frankenstein'' and ``Bride of
Frankenstein'' and then was left to flounder on the dream factory's
reject pile.
</P>
<P>
   As Whale, a snowy-haired Ian McKellen gives a haunted, haunting
performance as the stroke-impaired, prissy Brit on the verge of
physical and mental decay, unable to control the monstrous images
that run through his brain. Left ambiguous by director Bill
Condon's clever script is whether Whale was ostracized for some gay
sexual scandal or the more heinous Hollywood crime of making an
unprofitable movie.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the movie is set in 1957, as Whale whiles away the
time in his Pacific Palisades home, chasing the demons in the
movies of his mind. His main human contact is his doting but often
disapproving housekeeper Hannah (a stolid, dumpy Lynn Redgrave with
a thick German accent) and the occasional, fawning interviewer,
avid for Whale to spin out stray recollections of the Frankenstein
films.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day, Whale notices the newly hired gardener, a slab of
uneducated, ex-Marine beefcake named Boone (Brendan Fraser).
Whale's first thoughts are carnal, but as he lures Boone inside to
pose for his sketchbook, an unexpected symbiotic relationship
begins, not unlike that between Dr. Frankenstein and his laboratory
creature.
</P>
<P>
   Boone's fascination with Whale's moviemaking lore seems to
unlock other buried memories _ bitter recollections of his
brutalized childhood, horrific flashbacks of World War I combat,
tender thoughts of his foxhole lover and wistful remembrances of
all-male pool parties.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the movie's dark recesses, Condon maintains a tone of
ironic and occasionally playful humor, not unlike the comic serum
that Whale injected into his Frankenstein movies. In a few
instances, the comedy gets too broad, as in Whale's early encounter
with a fan-reporter.
</P>
<P>
   But a Hollywood garden party scene is sublime. First, there is a
whimsical encounter with a bewildered Princess Margaret and a
fuming, closeted George Cukor. This leads to an awkward, but
touching surprise reunion between Whale and ``his monsters,'' Boris
Karloff and Elsa Lanchester. Initially buoyed by this return to the
Hollywood social whirl, particularly with the hunky Boone on his
arm, Whale's energy eventually flags. And with simple, telling
gestures, McKellen masterfully grows ashen and recedes into his
shell.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser, an underrated actor best known for George of the Jungle,
holds his ground remarkably well alongside McKellen. Although not
terribly verbal, he lets us see Boone's awakened inner feelings,
again paralleling Whale's cinematic monster. Still, when McKellen
is off the screen, the movie tends to go slack, as in a hollow
subplot with barmaid Lolita Davidovich, seemingly included to
underline Boone's heterosexuality. Also unpersuasive is an epilogue
featuring a mature Boone with his wife and child.
</P>
<P>
   Such lapses aside, ``Gods and Monsters'' is an unexpected treat,
an illumination of a life worth some recognition, a period perfect
look at bygone Hollywood, a surprisingly touching friendship and a
brush with death. It is entertaining and thought-provoking in equal
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
