</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-PRINCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Prince' just a Sunday School lesson with stadium seating
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In DreamWorks' thunderous and magnificently
sandy cartoon epic ``The Prince of Egypt,'' no animals talk or
sing, but a flaming bush is sure a Chatty Cathy.
</P>
<P>
   And what attitude. Buffeting a young Moses with haughty demands,
the shrub acts like it thinks it's God or something.
</P>
<P>
   You get a twinge that the makers of ``The Prince of Egypt'' _
Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg, et al. _ are also afflicted
with a tiny God complex, cocksure their version of the Moses tale
is carved in stone: final, permanent, encrusted in stentorian
self-importance.
</P>
<P>
   And, may we add, not bad. If not quite the knee-buckling opus it
believes it is, the stunningly handsome Exodus retelling erupts on
the screen for the first hour with a tonic exuberance sprung from
the liberating terrain of speculative fiction _ namely, imagining
Moses as a rambunctious, prank-hatching adolescent in Pharaoh's
court. (Funny stuff, Moses, until someone gets hurt.)
</P>
<P>
   But then, in the last third, the story unfurls in halting
episodes, ticking off those highly cinematic miracles from the Good
Book in a finish-line sprint. This part of ``Egypt'' could be
dubbed Exodus' Greatest Hits, and that's a small problem. Most of
us know what happens next, and we start peeking around the corner
for each familiar stunt _ the surly bush flambe, the
staff-cum-cobra, the wacky plagues _ checking them off in
anticipation of the granddaddy of all magic tricks, ripping the Red
Sea asunder.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, it gets tedious. The sights are marvels of imagination
and state-of-the-art animation (the sea-parting is a wet, wondrous
bit of cartoon majesty), but the narrative thins drastically here,
building as it does to more important climaxes the movie doesn't
get to, such as Moses' earth-rumbling receipt of the ``Ten
Commandments,'' glimpsed in a fast-forward blink just before the
end credits.
</P>
<P>
   So, Moses rescues his people from the maw of Pharaoh, and then
it's over. Cue credits and a very loud blast of synthetic R&AMP;B,
courtesy of Boyz II Men. (This is Satan's single appearance in the
film.)
</P>
<P>
   After a lovely sequence showing baby Moses' perilous journey
down the Nile to Pharaoh's palace, the movie unleashes an
exhilarating rush of images and gasping Spielbergian action in a
chariot race between the teen-age Moses (voice by Val Kilmer, all
generic virility) and his ``brother'' Rameses (the
mellifluous-tongued Ralph Fiennes).
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie is directed by a trio of animation veterans,
Spielberg exerted his expert instincts on this scene, specifically
adding the vertiginous downhill plunge of the barreling chariots
that has the effect of a gut-gulping roller-coaster dip.
Spectacular 3-D computer animation gives the sequence dioramic
intensity. But the scene isn't all about eye-popping tableaux.
</P>
<P>
   Providing a cyclonic tour through ancient Egypt, it is packed
with narrative information, denoting time, place and wonderful
characterizations of the two rowdy brothers who, we learn, are
bound as much by a healthy rivalry as by deep-seated love.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Moses and the exotic Rameses (the
Egyptians are as golden brown as baked chicken, with spiffy
geometric haircuts) is the crux of the story, and the inevitable
circumstances that threaten it provide narrative thrust. That and,
of course, the fireproof bush, whose directives Moses carries
through with more than a dot of skepticism. Enter all those
miracles.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of forgettable songs by Hans Zimmer (``The Lion
King'') and Stephen Schwartz (``Pocahontas'') waft through the
movie to mixed effect. Many of the stars are enlisted to handle
their own vocal duties, including Steve Martin and Broadway crooner
Martin Short, Michelle Pfeiffer, and even Fiennes. They're all
fine; it's the songs that are blah.
</P>
<P>
   The sumptuous visual buffet far outclasses the show tunes. Like
recent breakthroughs in computer-animation, the film heralds an
evolutionary step in traditional animated features. An elaborate
beauty suffuses every scene in a palette of golds, bronzes and
browns. When Moses makes his initial departure from Egypt, he
draggles through a desert that conjures the craggy, burnt-orange
surface of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' is finally a vibrant but dowdy
spectacle. That's really no fault of the minds at DreamWorks but of
the ossified narrative, which no one wants to get too cute with,
hence the almost 600 experts, Bible scholars to Egyptologists, the
filmmakers summoned for counsel.
</P>
<P>
   And hence the cartoon's sometimes stifling gravitas and
cute-creature-free stodginess _ no singing donkeys, no wisecracking
camels _ which will surely glaze the little ones. Think of it as
Sunday school. With stadium seating. Chris Garcia is the film
critic for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
