<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: So long, BB's Mexican Cafe r&AMP;r to design
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin lost a funky little family business
Thursday when Andrew ``B.B.'' Castan(tilde)on closed his
restaurant, BB's Mexican Cafe, at 616 Nueces St.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody will ask me what B.B. stands for and I'll tell 'em it
stands for Bird Brain,'' said B.B., who is known for his goofy
quips. Actually, B.B. doesn't stand for anything. It's a nickname
B.B. picked up as a baby.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, B.B. will auction off his furniture and supplies at
the restaurant. B.B. is getting out for a couple of reasons. For
one, he had lease problems with his landlord. Also, the man needs a
break. B.B. has been slinging migas for so long that he may have
developed migas-slinger's elbow. He's been working in Austin
restaurants since the day the spatula was invented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hanging it up right now,'' said B.B., 64. ``Maybe in
a year from now we'll come back. I'm going to take a little rest.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing you could never accuse B.B. of was being trendy. I
don't know of any other place in town that served a sandwich called
an ``Egg Burger.'' ``I've never seen anybody else,'' B.B. said.
``And enchiladas with the eggs on top _ a few other restaurants may
have that, but I think I started it.''
</P>
<P>
   Decor at B.B.'s no-frills Tex-Mex restaurant included a sign
outside that told you flour tacos were 85 cents on Wednesday _
``all makes, all day.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no blue corn tortillas in this place, folks. And
nowhere on the menu would you find the words ``vegetarian
choices.'' Dinner types included ``regular,'' ``short'' and
``special.'' French fries were listed under appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   And when the waiter or waitress brought your food to the table,
he or she uttered the two-word warning that tells the diner he's in
an authentic Tex-Mex joint: ``hot plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows, B.B. deserves a rest. The restaurant he closed
Thursday was his third in Austin. In 1948, at age 14, he started
his career busing tables at El Matamoros, on the southbound
frontage road of I-35. B.B. recalls that the place had an outdoor
patio with a sawdust floor. The delivery truck wasn't much to look
at, either.
</P>
<P>
   Veronyca Castan(tilde)on-Horst, 38, B.B.'s eldest daughter,
remembers riding around in the '60s as a 5-year-old in El Mat's
junky pickup while her dad was making deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truck had no seat,'' she said. ``There were springs
sticking out. So my dad had to put telephone books in there so I
could sit down. I loved the smell of the food in the cab of the
truck.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, B.B. opened his own place _ Instant Burger, on Sixth
Street where Maggie Mae's is now. These days, this address is in
the heart of what we call the entertainment district. Back then, it
was in the middle of a beer joint zone. You had the Wander Inn, the
E.G. Bar and the Green Spot, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a beer permit there 'cause I already had enough
drunks coming in as it was,'' B.B. said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, B.B. went a little more upscale when he opened a place
on South First Street that started out as a burger joint, then
later became a Mexican food place. Ten years ago, B.B. moved the
restaurant to the location he closed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of folks ate at B.B.'s. Autographed photos of retired
U.S. Rep. Jake Pickle, Longhorn football legend Earl Campbell and
former Gov. Ann Richards hang on the wall by the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, most of the customers were regular Joes. On many
days, said Carmen Belmarez, a waitress who has been working for
B.B. off and on since the 1970s, the same penniless guy would come
in for a bean and egg taco. Since the guy was broke, Carmen and
waiter Joey Carmona would cover it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to tell him today was his last taco,'' Carmen said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's column appears on Sundays, Wednesdays and Fridays
in the Austin (Texas) American-Statesman. He can be reached at
445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
