<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN19-COX     12-18 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Leaves are dropping at a rapid clip
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The leaves are falling quickly now, after
an unexpected fine autumnal display. Turns out the drought made the
fall colors even brighter than usual. Trees under distress, because
of too much heat and too little water, quit producing chlorophyll
early on, resulting in a riotous display of dying foliage.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Ma Nature has put on an impressive cabaret
of color for several weeks, even if the rest of the weather hasn't
cooperated until lately. I have a half-cord of firewood recently
purchased but hardly used, and the air conditioner still runs
regularly. But I won't complain, as long as the good Lord keeps
bringing rain and holds the temperature under 90. That's the deal I
made with God during the midst of our summer season of hell, to
never complain about rain or cold weather again. I've kept my part
of the bargain thus far.
</P>
<P>
   The warm winds of last weekend stripped most of the trees in my
neighborhood of their leaves, save for stubborn red oaks, which
stubbornly try to hold on as long as possible. The pin oaks that
border my house on the west side gave up the battle easily and now
stand stripped and stark against a gray sky. Small, pear-shaped
leaves blanket the lawn, resistant to either raking or mulching.
</P>
<P>
   There's a game I played as a child, and I played it again the
other day while taking a break from reading outside. As a kid, I
would choose a large oak leaf, and then take a twig and puncture it
in two to three places, depending on its size. Then I would pull up
blades of grass and weave them through the holes in the leaf, three
blades horizontally, then three more vertically. As a child, I
considered this Leaf First-Aid, as if I was bandaging a wounded
soldier. Soon I would have a platoon of MASH patients, all doctored
up.
</P>
<P>
   The game doesn't last as long these days, but it's not a bad
diversion _ safer than whittling, for example.
</P>
<P>
   I'm lucky to be immune in this neighborhood from Leaf
Maintenance Mania. I only have one neighbor whose yard I can see.
Tall wooden fences separate my house from those behind, so their
lawn obsessions, if they have any, are of no concern to me. The lot
to the west and across the street are both vacant, still heavily
wooded. The neighbor whose yard borders mine has the same laissez
faire attitude about leaf maintenance I have. My philosophy is to
let all the leaves fall, chop up as many as possible with the lawn
mower, and eventually get around to raking the rest. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   In some neighborhoods, Leaf Maintenance Mania runs rampant. A
subdivision
</P>
<P>
   where all the yards are covered with leaves has a certain charm
to it. Then an overly ambitious resident ruins the ambience by
cleaning his yard, leaving an oasis of green amidst a sea of brown.
The other neighbors, within a few days, grudgingly join in, though
there's always at least one house whose curmudgeonly owner refuses
to bow to peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, I was never the curmudgeon when I lived in town. I
aspire to be a curmudgeon, but I'm afraid I don't have the proper
sour disposition. Maybe that will come with age.
</P>
<P>
   I was never the first to clean up the yard, either, but I was
easily shamed into going along with the crowd. An entire weekend
would be wasted raking and bagging, mulching and blowing. Then by
Sunday afternoon, a warm front would bring in a 30-mph wind that
sent down a new cascade of pine needles and oak leaves, so that the
yard looked just as windswept as before.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, I passed through a subdivision and spied a
pretty, small blond woman using a leaf blower. It was one of those
high-dollar affairs that require the user to strap the motor on his
or her back. The poor woman looked like one of the characters from
the movie ``Ghostbusters,'' leading me to make up a new ditty:
``Who you gonna call? Leaf Busters!''
</P>
<P>
   I'm quite sure she wasn't enjoying herself.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf blowers are obnoxious machines. I own one and use it
reluctantly and rarely. (It's not the backpack model, thank
goodness.) The sound disrupts an entire neighborhood, and I'm quite
sure eventually a medical study will disclose that leaf blowers
cause impotence, impetigo and irascibility. Give me a broom and
some time. The swishing of the whisk against concrete is a good,
honest sound.
</P>
<P>
   I won't burn leaves either, or bag them. I dump them in the
vacant lot next door and let them turn back to earth. There's
nothing worse than a cacophony of leaf blowers and a few smoldering
piles of wet leaves to send one inside on even the most glorious of
days.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I am turning into a curmudgeon. I felt like stopping,
shaking that poor Leaf Buster woman by the shoulders, and telling
her to stop this foolishness, let the leaves fall until they're
through, then rake them into a compost pile and let them rot.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt she would have thought I was mad.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
