</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Journalists need the courage to change
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ A few weeks ago a relatively new Marshall News
Messenger reporter came to me with an exciting report: Someone had
agreed to tell us what had gone on in a closed-door meeting of a
local governmental agency.
</P>
<P>
   It was good, if odd, news. Newspapers can print almost anything
that is true, but public officials in private meetings can get
charged with a misdemeanor for telling us. If some public official
is willing to take that remarkable step, I might well print what
they have to say if it is newsworthy _ and if they understand that
we are going to use their name.
</P>
<P>
   When I related this to the reporter, his enthusiasm fell. ``We
have to use the person's name?'' he asked me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' I told him. ``We don't use stories with unnamed
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a lie, of course. For most of the last year our paper
has had at least one story every day using an unnamed source. It is
how the press _ and the Republicans _ built their case against
President Bill Clinton. Come next year, somebody is going to win a
Pulitzer Prize based on stories they wrote rarely naming anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne corks will pop and journalistic legends made because
almost all of the really important facts were correct. Forget the
few big times that we screwed up; forget the dozens of minor errors
that subtly misled the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Because, by golly, were it not for the bending and breaking of a
few journalistic rules, the world never would have known about
Monica Lewinsky. We would never have known she performed oral sex
on Bill Clinton had not these brave reporters brought it all to
light.
</P>
<P>
   Say what? You mean we could have perhaps avoided this national
nightmare, this absolutely meaningless scandal, this televised
impeachment drivel, if only any of us had had some standards?
</P>
<P>
   I hope that Pulitzer will not be for Meritorious Public Service.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. This is not an indictment of the reporters.
Oh, no, for a fact, there was a cadre of sub-editors, editors and
publishers who could have _ and should have _ stopped this long
ago, or at least stopped it until people were willing to go on the
record.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, there were wire service editors who could have
said: ``This doesn't meet our standards. We aren't going to ship it
to the rest of America.'' So far as I know, there is not one wire
editor so brave.
</P>
<P>
   But do you know where the cowardice finally comes home to roost?
</P>
<P>
   Me.
</P>
<P>
   Me and several thousand journalists like me across the country
who don't believe in using unnamed sources except in the most
extreme of circumstances. (Forget it. You'll never convince me that
any two people on Earth having free and consensual oral sex is
newsworthy, much less extreme.)
</P>
<P>
   All of us had the power to make individual judgments not to run
these stories and every one of us still published every word. We
did it because we worried that everyone else was running the story
and heaven forbid that we do anything differently. We must be like
everyone else, lest our journalistic brethren think we are somehow
odd or, worse yet, going soft.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the report by special counsel Kenneth Starr was
released, all of us rushed to print the prurient details because
this was an Official Government Report. As an open record we had a
duty to print it.
</P>
<P>
   Never have so many journalists been so brilliantly manipulated.
Not even Bill Clinton has done it so well.
</P>
<P>
   Polls from every source show that, blah, blah, blah, the
American people, blah, blah, blah, are beginning to hate the press
and all journalists, blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares what the American people think?
</P>
<P>
   What concerns me is that I am beginning to hate myself.
</P>
<P>
   The people can adore you, worship you, but you still have to
face yourself in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   What all of us did was wrong, wrong, wrong, and I can't help but
wonder when I'm going to muster the courage to stand up against
this frightening wave.
</P>
<P>
   Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. He can be reached by email at platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
