<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Ill will from the nation's capitol
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - I call them Christmas messages we didn't want our
children to hear.
</P>
<P>
   While church bells toll good will to men, ill will resounds from
our nation's capitol. The president's lies are bad example enough
for America's children. The response from partisans in Congress is
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the wrong lessons our elected representatives
are teaching:
</P>
<P>
   In one nation under God, representatives must take sides
according to political party.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Bill McCullum of Florida, a member of the House
Judiciary Committee, speaks always of what ``the other side'' is
doing. But his ``side'' and ``the other side'' are us, Americans
all. We teach our children in civics that a representative votes on
behalf of all constituents, not just those of one political party.
</P>
<P>
   Do as I say, not as I do.
</P>
<P>
   That lesson from from Georgia GOP Rep. Bob Barr, who claims the
moral high ground as well as the cloak of ultimate legal authority.
(Nevermind that Justice John Marshall declared in 1803 that it's up
to the judiciary not the legislature to decide what's
constitutional.) Barr saw nothing immoral about agreeing to be the
keynote speaker at a meeting of the Council of Conservative
Citizens, an avowed white supremacist group. In his closing remarks
in the Judiciary Committee, he said, ``It's time for America to
learn Constitution 101.'' It may also be time for him to read the
Fourteenth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to listen to the president even if national
security is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, House majority whip, said
on ``Meet the Press'' that if President Clinton alerted
congressional leaders to a serious threat from Iraqi leader Saddam
Hussein, he, for one, wouldn't believe him. The presidency isn't
the only institution for which DeLay shows disrespect. He regularly
calls the federal Environmental Protection Agency, ``the Gestapo.''
</P>
<P>
   No need for politicians to acknowledge hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mary Bono of California has publicly attributed her
husband's death in a ski accident to his prescription drug
addiction. The late Rep. Sonny Bono, whose seat she took, was
taking 20 different drugs, she said. She asked Gregory Craig, one
of the lawyers who presented the president's defense to the
Judiciary Committee, what he was going to tell his young children
about the president's behavior. What did she tell her children
about her husband's drug habit? Craig said he told his children the
reason the president is in so much trouble is because he didn't
always tell the truth. Children probably get that _ and they also
associate wrongdoing with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joanna Adams, pastor of Atlanta's Trinity Presbyterian
Church, told me of the 7-year-old who piped up in her Sunday School
class as the teacher talked about the Ten Commandments and said,
``Adultery_that's Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams believes some religious leaders have been hasty to defend
the president, to confirm his penitence. ``Only God knows if he has
truly repented,'' she said. Nevertheless, Adams doesn't believe a
political body is suited to taking a referendum on a leader's
character. She's critical of the self-rightousness of many House
members. ``It's scoundrels responding to a cad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As I listened to the president's opponents, I couldn't help
thinking how out of sync the tone with the humility the Christmas
story teaches. I read again the penitence references in the prayer
Rev. Adams sent me: ``We have done those things we ought not to
have done. And there is no health in us ... Spare Thou those, O
God, who confess their faults. Restore Thou those who are
penitent.'' Words worth considering as religious observances
commence amidst a national tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:mezzard(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
