<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Fully compensated county officials need to put in a
full day's work
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``What is enough for a public official?'' asked
Montgomery County Recorder Joy Clark, in response to a reporter's
questions about her irregular office hours. ``Enough to get the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may take A.J. Wagner an hour a day, it may take me two
hours a day, it may take Joe Litvin 12 hours a day. I think I've
done an excellent, excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark went on to defend her record, saying she often works at
home and it's a ``24-hour job.'' But it was her initial quote _
``it may take A.J. Wagner one hour a day, it may take me two
hours'' _ that stopped me. Could she be more out of touch with the
average worker? With her own employees?
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, but nobody who works two hours a day should be
earning $53,292 a year. Not on the taxpayers' tab, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's remarks showed little understanding of what most people
have to do to scrape together a living. Ironically, the story
appeared on the same day as the newspaper's ``Equal Work, Less
Pay'' series, which documented the two-tier pay system developing
in many workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Lieffring of Miamisburg, 25, is at the bottom of the pay
tier at the GM plant in Moraine. His wife is expecting the couple's
second child. ``We got sold out,'' he said. ``And the future
doesn't look any better for guys like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Flaherty makes $8 an hour on the assembly line at the
Dayton Chrysler Corp. plant. The guy on either side of him makes
$20 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Colette Smith of Kettering quit her job at Taco Bell, with
dreams of earning big bucks at the Chrysler plant. A year later,
she earns $8.50 an hour _ a dollar raise.
</P>
<P>
   These workers, one suspects, would be thrilled to work full-time
_ heck, overtime _ for $53,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the county recorder's appearances are apparently so
infrequent they are referred to as a ``Joy Clark sighting.'' Clark
can talk all she wants about her comfy ergonomic chair at home, and
her many appointments in the community, but this is an office job.
It's a record-keeping job. It's not the kind of job that requires
the official to be out talking to schoolkids or visiting nursing
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The recorder's office, as Clark argues, seems to be running
well. ``I'm obviously putting in the time and doing what is needed
to run one of the top offices in the state,'' she said. But is that
because of her leadership? Or is it because she has a good staff?
Current low-interest rates have created an avalanche of work.
Chances are staffers are putting in long weeks, for a lot less pay,
than Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the job for 15 years, and it was a 40-hour-a-week job,
and in peak times, more than that,'' said former county recorder
Vicki Pegg, now a Montgomery County Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike you or me, county officials can't be fired if they fail
to show up for work. Show up once every 90 days, as state law is
now written, and county elected officials are in the clear.
</P>
<P>
   That might have made sense when the law was drafted, and the
officeholder may have been a farmer coming in from the fields. Not
now. State law should be changed to reflect modern times, and
modern salaries. The day of the political sinecure should be just
about done.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, though, the taxpayers are the only real boss.
We're paying their salaries so we need to pay better attention to
who they are and what they're doing. Maybe party chairs could use
some of their muscle as well, if elected officials aren't doing
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Am I picking on Clark? Her office runs well, after all, despite
her frequent absences.
</P>
<P>
   She earns $53,292 a year. For my tax dollar, that's a full-time
wage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
