<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amid rumblings over Clinton's Iraq motviation, give benefit of
doubt
 &HT;    By Roland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ On the eve of Monica Lewinsky's scheduled
testimony before a federal grand jury, my editor notified me that
President Clinton had ordered missile strikes against terrorist
bases.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped what I was writing and instead wrote that Americans
should support their commander in chief once U.S. troops are
ordered into harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of President Clinton's scheduled impeachment vote in
the House of Representatives, my editor notified me that Clinton
had ordered missile strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   I spiked what I had written and instead wrote that once the
bombs start to fall Americans need to put aside their political
differences and rally behind their men and women in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   It's a coincidence, I'm sure, that this reluctant-warrior
commander-in-chief studiously avoids the use of military force
until those moments when they conveniently provide him with needed
political cover.
</P>
<P>
   While denying that Clinton would manipulate national security
issues and jeopardize American lives for personal political
advantage, Clinton supporters nevertheless have been quick to point
out that those same accusations have been leveled at Republican
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   No excuse today
</P>
<P>
   If past presidents _ Republican or Democratic _ ordered military
combat for personal political benefit, their actions constituted a
betrayal of a sacred trust, not an excuse for future presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's the Pentagon's job to constantly be on the lookout
for enemies and be prepared to meet all threats, presidents will
never have a hard time justifying an order to send troops into
action. Generals and admirals would be out of a job if they
reported there were no threats to U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein richly deserves the
missile attacks launched against his dangerous war machine, it's
natural that people will question Clinton's motives since the man
has systematically squandered his credibility with his near
pathological inability to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times describes Clinton as ``a man blessed with
great talent and afflicted with a mysterious passion for lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Partisan Democrats defend Clinton by first admitting that his
repeated lies ``violated the trust of the American people'' and
dishonored the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   With that sort of rousing defense of Clinton's character, no one
should be surprised that many Americans find it difficult to
believe a man who has never shown a reluctance to lie when a lie
would benefit him.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the troops Clinton sends into battle would feel better
about putting their lives on the line if they could trust the
motives of their commander in chief. It was telling that Clinton
felt it necessary to defend the timing of his decision to attack
Iraq when he addressed the nation.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk that Clinton pulled a ``Wag the dog'' trick the
last time he was in political trouble and ordered the missile
attack on terrorists bases in Sudan and Afghanistan. It didn't help
his credibility when the plant blown away in Sudan did nothing more
threatening than make vitamins and nutritional supplements and that
Osama bin Laden was elsewhere when U.S. missiles hit the targeted
terrorist camps in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to this latest attack on Iraq buttresses the belief of
many governmental scholars who say a president's most valuable
asset is his moral authority. With it, presidents can lead the
nation through the worst of times. Without it, they have no ability
to lead.
</P>
<P>
   All Americans should support their troops while they are risking
their lives to defend this nation.
</P>
<P>
   And, as difficult as it may be, they should give their president
the benefit of their considerable doubts that this time he really
meant what he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway's columns appear on Wednesdays and Fridays in
the Waco Tribune-Herald. His e-mail address is
RNethaway(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
