</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kudzu putting the squeeze on Christmas spirit
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kudzu. The name rings ominously. Thinking of it this
time of year always reminded me less of the spirit of peace and joy
than of the grinch that spreads misery. Until I met Dorothy
Greason.
</P>
<P>
   I visited her southwest Atlanta home on a recent Saturday and
discovered a kudzu Christmas; she collects the evil weed and turns
it into symbols of the season, including trees and wreaths and
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Greason, a retired elementary school teacher, began her kudzu
craft in the 1980s in Memphis after noting the ``awful prices''
that artisans charged for baskets and other items at arts and craft
shows. ``I was going to take a basket-weaving class,'' she recalls,
``and then, one day I was walking by a field of kudzu, and I said,
`I can weave a basket from this.' I never took the class.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, James, moved to Atlanta (back, for him)
about 10 years ago, and she began collecting kudzu from a nearby
tennis court, which amounts to performing a public service. She
strips the vines of leaves, then works with them while they're
fresh and flexible.
</P>
<P>
   To baskets she added the Christmas items, which look much like
those woven from grapevines (ironic, as the kudzu blossom smells so
much like the Nehi grape soda that I still can taste from
childhood).
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a huge wreath, decorated with plastic black and
green grapes and red birds, Greason showed me a strand of lights
woven into red-painted kudzu vines, a piece she recently had
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The piece de resistance, however, is at a friend's house.
(Greason used to make kudzu Christmas gifts for all her friends but
has cut back in recent years.)
</P>
<P>
   Off we go, driving to the other side of I-285, to Dorothy Jones'
home near Niskey Lake. There, hanging from the ceiling is a
10-foot-tall spiral tree made of kudzu. Greason made it five years
ago, and Jones has displayed it every year since, patching it when
necessary to keep it hanging tall. Too, she decorates it in
different colors each season.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the imposing tree, erected for Thanksgiving, has gold
decorations with white lights and drips dozens of carefully chosen
ornaments, including stars, birds, balls, each repeated several
times on the tree. ``Next year, I'll probably go red,'' says Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual tree naturally draws attention from holiday guests.
``Usually, it's the topic of conversation,'' Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, anything connected to kudzu inspires talk _ and in
many cases, fear. Gallows humor surrounds it: How do you make kudzu
grow? Feed it daily with used motor oil.
</P>
<P>
   Like dwarf bamboo, this vine wants to be the only plant in any
space. Yet, both can be as beautiful as they are invasive. Few
sights along the highway captivate like trees covered in deep
green, undulating drifts of kudzu _ trees getting smothered to
death.
</P>
<P>
   So much kudzu. Even as Greason and other artisans collect it all
through the year, it relentlessly marches north. Still, I ask
whether she's ever considered growing her own, to have a handy
supply right at her back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, no,'' Greason says quickly, chuckling. ``My husband
says, `Please make sure there are no seeds on any of the vines you
bring home.' If I started growing kudzu, he'd run me away from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   I take comfort in knowing that, as we joke, there is a serious
message: Not even the Christmas spirit can make anyone embrace the
vine we love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May's column appears each Saturday in Home &AMP; Garden section
of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. He can be reached at
leemay(at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
