<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-WASHINGTON-EXHIBIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SWORDS! THAT KEY! THOSE TEETH! 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evidently the people who came up with the George
Washington exhibition now at the New-York Historical Society had
two things in mind. First, they were moved by the assumption that
despite the more than two centuries in which the Father of Our
Country has been wildly lauded and lionized, few of us really know
him, or like him very much. Then they concluded that this state of
affairs might be changed if they showed us stuff like his false
teeth and his letters to his tailor ordering new breeches.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I have seen ``Treasures From Mount Vernon: George
Washington Revealed,'' I think both these notions were good ones.
As I walked in, I realized that although like all Americans, I had
probably been exposed to more icons, legends and lore about
Washington than about any other figure of national renown, my
feelings for the man were not really very different from those I
had for, say, James Madison or James Polk, respectful but hardly
warm. His image was at once as commonly accessible as a dollar bill
and as distantly aloof as that serious face looming from Mount
Rushmore. This was in contrast to the far more likable, maybe even
lovable, likes of Lincoln, Jefferson, Franklin and the Roosevelts.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I left the show, not only was I less estranged from
Washington, but in ways not unknown to aging sons, I had also come
to feel something close to sympathy for our venerable progenitor. I
even came up with a theory to explain why he has been held in such
tepid and less-than-heartfelt esteem, but more of that later.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which is at the museum until Feb. 22 on the
first leg of a nationwide tour, includes items both predictable and
surprising. There are several portraits by Charles Willson Peale; a
life mask made as the president breathed through tubes stuck up his
nose, and the Spartanly outfitted tent he used in battle with an
intricate folding camp bed. There are swords and the key to the
Bastille that Washington received from Lafayette. There is the
battle sash that the wounded and dying Gen. Edward Braddock gave to
Washington along with the command of his British troops, then
besieged by French and Indian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Much more revealing are the various letters written by
Washington that are interspersed through the exhibition. For
instance, on July 18, 1755, nine days after Braddock's death.
Washington wrote to his brother John: ``As I have heard a
circumstantial account of my death and dying speech, I take this
early opportunity of contradicting both, and of assuring you that I
now exist and appear in the land of the living by the miraculous
care of Providence, that protected me beyond all human expectation;
I had 4 Bullets through my Coat, and two Horses shot under me, and
yet escaped unhurt.``
</P>
<P>
   How delightful. Here is the 23-year-old Washington, clearly
flushed in the excitement of battle, subordinating clear evidence
of bravery and boldness to expressions of modesty and piety. With
subtlety and grace he had combined the stoic ``aw, shucks, there
was nothing to it,'' sentiment with the rather dramatic facts of
the case, which involved four bullets and two horses.
</P>
<P>
   Uncharitably, it occurred to me that the youthful Washington,
unaware that Parson Weems would one day fabricate the legend of his
never lying about chopping down cherry trees or anything else, had
perhaps been tempted to exaggerate. After all, a year earlier in
another letter to his brother that is on display he had exulted,
``I heard the bullets whistle, and, believe me, there is something
charming in the sound.'' What if, in fact, only one horse had gone
down under him and only two bullets went harmlessly through his
jacket. I had no reason to doubt his account other than human
nature, life experience and self-awareness. Of course it could have
happened just the way he wrote it, but the very idea that in his
active youth he might have succumbed to an impulse to embellish
further endeared him to me.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the letter Washington wrote to Charles Lawrence,
his London tailor, in 1763 while he was managing Mount Vernon and
his vast land holdings. ``Be pleased to send me a genteel suit of
clothes made of superfine broadcloth handsomely chosen; I should
have enclosed my measure but in a general way they are so badly
taken here that I am convinced it would be of very little service;
I would have you therefore take measure of a gentleman who wears
well-made clothes of the following size _ to wit _ six feet high &AMP;
proportionally made; if anything rather slender than thick for a
person of that height and pretty long arms &AMP; thighs.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrific. Here is Washington, sending away to Old Fish Street in
London, willing to wait for the months it must have taken for his
letter to get there and more months for the suit to be made and
come back. Clearly impatient with the inability of finding good
help who could get the inseams right, he improvises a way to
communicate his needs. As the exhibition makes clear, once he
became president, he had his clothes made in the country he
fathered, sacrificing European style and craftsmanship to set a
patriotic example. Also commendable. One of Washington's
British-made suits is included.
</P>
<P>
   There are also letters by others that convey a Washington much
less standoffish than the one commonly portrayed. After a dinner at
Mount Vernon in 1777, Martha Dangerfield Bland, the wife of a
colonel, wrote to her sister: ``Gen. Washington throws off the hero
and takes on the chatty agreeable companion. He can be downright
impudent sometimes _ such impudence, Fanny, as you and I like!!!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   So let us sum up what we have learned so far. Washington does
not shy from derring-do and knows how to project himself favorably
though modestly. He is vain about his appearance and clothes. And
he knows how to flirt quite well. All of which is to his credit.
</P>
<P>
   Now is there any mystery or are there any unexplained details
that might add to his mystique? Well, what about the hundreds of
letters he wrote to his wife, which she burned upon his death? One
was tucked behind a drawer and survived, and it is in the
exhibition. Written in 1775 as the general was leaving Philadelphia
to take command of the army in Boston, it reads, ``I retain an
unalterable affection for you, which neither time or distance can
change.``
</P>
<P>
   What was in the burned material? Was it hot? Did he ask her to
burn the letters? Did Martha, who by the way always called her
husband the general, at least in front of others, do it on her own?
Was it right of her to do it? Did she violate posterity's right to
know? If so, to know what? Did she protect her husband's privacy or
his reputation? Without belaboring the issue, these are obviously
timely questions.
</P>
<P>
   And now we come to the unquestioned highlight of the show. The
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at George Washington's false teeth, George Washington's
bridge, so to speak, is a profound experience. It evokes a feeling
not unlike the one that dawns with the realization that your
parents and even your grandparents must have had sex at least once.
You cannot look at the teeth and not realize the humanity of their
owner. They are not of wood as some have described them; they are a
quite handsome set of choppers, fashioned from human teeth, cow
teeth and elephant ivory all embedded in seemingly heavy plates of
gray lead-based metal. The uppers and lowers are hinged at the
corners by small springs. Washington told John Adams that he had
lost his natural teeth after using them to crack too many walnuts
in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the teeth there is a letter Washington sent to Dr.
Greenwood, their maker, in 1797 when he was president. Like the
others on display it is written in his own hand, a forceful, neat
and legible script free of the curlicues and flourishes that then
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must again resort to you for assistance. The teeth herewith
enclosed have, by degrees, worked loose; and, at length, two or
three of them have given away altogether. I would thank you for
returning them as soon as possible for although I now make use of
another set, they are both uneasy in the mouth and bulge my lips
out in such a manner as to make them appear considerably swelled.''
</P>
<P>
   As I observed the teeth and read the letter, I felt another
surge of sympathy. I also began to develop my theory why I and
maybe others had not been more inspired by Washington and his life.
Bad teeth and swollen lips are not a tragedy, but they do reveal
suffering and they are just about the only sign of something having
gone wrong with Washington's life, unless you also consider the
line in his will in which he wrote that his ``Expectation of having
Issue has ceased.''
</P>
<P>
   As generally portrayed, his was a life of successive triumphs
and compounded virtues and what challenges there were, like that
winter at Valley Forge, always led to greater victories. Washington
performed truly great deeds, salvaging a revolution and defeating
the army of the world's most powerful state and later spurning
offers to make him king. But without humanizing weaknesses and
without the touch of tragedy, can heroes be lovable, particularly
in our time?
</P>
<P>
   What in Washington's life was comparable to Lincoln's depression
and marital conflict and to the national tragedy of his
assassination or FDR's wheelchair? It occurred to me as I left the
museum that those who had handled Washington's spin, either by
burning his letters or writing the hagiographic early biographies,
had done a brilliant job, at least for the 19th century, when a
blameless life of steady triumphs tended to enhance a leader's
popularity. But after Freud, when sins and guilts and failures
became so much more important in taking the full measure of a man,
that obviously no longer worked so well.
</P>
<P>
   Quite correctly, the exhibition stopped short of turning the
first president into a complex modern hero deserving of compassion
as well as admiration. It was not at all an iconoclastic case of
warts and all, and the subject emerged still eminently worthy of
respect. But he is brought down to earth and humanized. With teeth
like that, it is very hard to remain a plaster saint.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Treasures From Mount Vernon: George Washington Revealed,''
will be at the New-York Historical Society, 2 W. 77th St.,
Manhattan, through Feb. 22, along with two displays organized by
the Historical Society. ``The Power and the Glory: George
Washington and the Birth of Fame in America'' explores how the
president has been depicted in American culture, using objects from
the society's collection. ``George Washington: A Man of His Time, a
Man for All Times'' is a display of manuscripts, maps and documents
from the Historical Society and the Gilder Lehrman Collection.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Vernon exhibition's national tour is sponsored by the
Ford Motor Co., and its appearance in New York was made possible
with support from the Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History.
The New-York Historical Society is open Tuesdays through Sundays,
11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $5; students and the elderly, $3; 12
and under, free.
</P>
<P>
   Families may celebrate Washington and New York City history in a
series of crafts workshops at the Historical Society from Dec. 26
to 31; all are at 2 p.m. and are free with admission. Other
programs in conjunction with the Washington exhibitions include
symposiums in January and a walking tour in February. Information:
(212) 873-3400.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 23, ``Washington's New York'' will open at the Museum of
the City of New York, Fifth Avenue at 103rd Street. This
exhibition, which focuses on the late-18th-century city, will run
through July 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
