</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Dec. 18, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   REPORTER-MURDERED (Undated) _ Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
ordered a second autopsy of San Antonio Express-News journalist
Philip True after authorities said he died of strangulation, not a
fall down a mountain slope as originally believed. By CARMINA
DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BIRTHS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ San Francisco residents have
fewer babies than anywhere else in the state, making the city the
only place in California destined to lose population over the next
40 years, a new state report predicts. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOLARS-IMPEACHMENT (San Francisco) _ The majority of Americans
may think a vote to impeach President Clinton is unfair, but
presidential and constitutional law scholars say Congress has every
right to buck public opinion and vote to oust the president. By
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you want to look into someone's
soul, just take a close look at his face. According to a
self-styled face reader, the wrinkles, dimples and droops reveal a
life of happiness, tragedy and everything in between. Eyelids are
the barometer of life, said Mac Fulfer, a lawyer from Fort Worth
who taught himself how to ``read'' faces. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ It's gearing up to be another banner
season for shopping on line. Some analysts estimate that 40 percent
of all Internet users will buy something over the World Wide Web.
Two masters of direct consumer-PC sales, Gateway and Micron
Electronics, have made the process of selecting and purchasing a
computer system on the Web not just painless, but fun. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about the
rumors he has heard about Windows 95 and 98 and it not being able
to hold more than 64 megabytes of memory. It's not true. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FASTFOOD-MINORITIES (Houston) _ The fast-food industry is
sizzling with talk of ``emerging markets.'' These hotbeds of
opportunity are not in Brazil, Thailand or Poland. Their emerging
markets are minority neighborhoods in urban America, according to
International Franchise Association lingo. But while the largest
fast-food restaurants have been adding minority owners, minority
ownership still lags. By REBECCA MOWBRAY (Photos available on the
NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THEME-RESTAURANTS (San Antonio) _ San Francisco, a perennial
contender for world's greatest restaurant city, is curiously short
on one kind of restaurant that has swept over much of the rest of
the world: the big-bang, big-theme, show-biz restaurant. Actually,
the city _ with its 3,400 licensed restaurants, only two of which
are themed _ may not need the theme restaurants that flourish
elsewhere. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   MONOPOLY-NAVY (Houston) _ Millions of landlubbers have fallen
under the spell of its pastel-colored paper money and plots of land
from Mediterranean Avenue to Boardwalk. Now Monopoly is reeling in
sailors with a new U.S. Navy edition and the opportunity to buy
aircraft carriers and the Blue Angels. By DAI HUYNH.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-EGYPT (Undated) _ ``The Prince of Egypt'' is a hard
sell. Critics know it. The studio knows it. Probably even Moses
knows it, or he would if he were around to dwell on such things. A
biblically inspired, resolutely unsilly animated musical aimed at
grown-ups is not the sort of movie generally paired with the term
``blockbuster.'' By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EGYPT-PROFILE (Dallas) _ Will ``Prince of Egypt'' be king
of the box office? DreamWorks' Jeffrey Katzenberg talks about the
studio's gamble with the animated Biblical epic. By LOUIS PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-MONKEYS-PROFILE (Undated) _ Actor Michael Ontkean talks
about ``Summer of the Monkeys,'' a family film that went straight
to video and is being issued under Disney's name. By BRUCE
WESTBROOK
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MAIL (Undated) _ ``Youv'e Got Mail'' has two
absolutely beguiling stars in Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan, a clever,
straight-from-the-news premise, and New York's Upper West Side at
Christmas time. That's a lot for any movie to have going for it. By
JANE GAHAHL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ISLAND (Undated) _ ``The Island on Bird Street,'' a
movie about a boy who survives on his own for week after week in
the ruined shell of the Warsaw Ghetto, is maddeningly true to its
hero. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Count me out. I never got the
memo. I'm not impeaching anyone and I'm not launching cruise
missiles at anyone. But I've thought about the latter. Just as I
was making my list of people who deserve to be hit by cruise
missiles, unlike Iraqi civilians, one landed on House
Speaker-designate Robert Livingston. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Two are selling scotch, one a
luxury car, another an inexpensive wine and the worst of the bunch,
tequila. What the five current ads have in common is, they drive me
seriously nuts. Each insults my intelligence, two insult my dignity
as a woman and one is a raised middle finger to all but a
privileged, white, upwardly mobile class. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ATTACK (San Francisco) _ Watching President William
Jefferson Clinton give his speech on Wednesday, an hour after Iraqi
bombing was initiated, I realized I haven't been this upset
listening to a president since the days of Lyndon Johnson. I wanted
to rush out and yell, ``No! You can't slaughter people to save your
career. Stop, stop, stop!'' By JOAN STEINAU LESTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
