<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, December 19 and Sunday,
December 20, 1998 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The leaves are falling
quickly now, after an unexpected fine autumnal display. Enjoying
them necessarily means leaving them on the ground. (Borders,
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA - I call them Christmas messages we
didn't want our children to hear. While church bells toll good will
to men, ill will resounds from our nation's capitol. The
president's lies are bad example enough for America's children. The
response from partisans in Congress is worse. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin lost a funky little family
business Thursday when Andrew ``B.B.'' Castan(tilde)on closed his
restaurant, BB's Mexican Cafe. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ The cowardice shown by
printing unnamed sources and unworthy news of the Clinton ordeal
has yet to be conquered. (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ All Americans should support
their troops while they are risking their lives to defend this
nation. And, as difficult as it may be, they should give President
Clinton the benefit of their considerable doubts that this time he
really meant what he said. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ State law should be changed to
reflect modern times, and modern salaries. The day of the political
sinecure should be just about done. Am I picking on Montgomery
County Recorder Joy Clark? Her office runs well, after all, despite
her frequent absences. But she earns $53,292 a year. For my tax
dollar, that's a full-time wage. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The bombing in Iraq not only degraded Saddam
Hussein's ability to wage chemical, biological and nuclear war. It
also further degraded American politics _ however much that might
have seemed impossible beforehand. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ ``General Faversham is a director of Her
Majesty's Royal Chelsea Flower Show and senior fanfare officer for
Desert Fox who will now report to you on the effectiveness of our
strikes.'' (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
