<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT1219-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Saturday, December 5 and
Sunday, December 6, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-XMASDINNER _ What's in that Christmas dinner you're about
to wolf down that causes that full, lethargic feeling? (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ I've been missing something about
rustic furniture. I can see now that if the right woodworker gets
into this stuff, the results can be something remarkable. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RABBI-FUTURE _ The next generation of Jews will be volunteers.
The volunteer corps will wrestle with God in an emerging Jewish
life driven by compassion and justice rooted in authentic spiritual
experience. And it will shape a Judaism that energetically recruits
converts, recognizes women fully, welcomes and ordains practicing
homosexuals, presides over same sex unions and embraces
intermarried couples. Rabbi Alexander Schindler thinks that's what
the future holds. And what Schindler thinks has shaped much of
American Jewish thought for more than 20 years. (Gushee, Palm Beach
Post). 20. WITH PHOTO (mug). MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-LOVE _ Profiles of folks who fell in love on line, pegged
to movie ``You've Got Mail.'' (Susman, Palm Beach Post). 20. MOVED
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSEX _ Interview with cybersex expert Deb Levine, who has
just published ``The Joy of Cybersex.'' (Houck, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MAIL _ Review of ``You've Got Mail.'' (Schwann, Palm
Beach Post). 15. MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ A special Celestine Sibley Christmas column: You
don't have to have Christmas. You can miss the riches and he glory
and the fun of the great day. Soldiers on battlefields do. People
in hospital intensive care unitts do. And many poor people do.
(Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   HERRERA _ Photo-driven centerpiece on designer Carolina Herrera,
who staged a show recently at the Ritz to show her spring/summer
'99 collection. Herrera, 58, didn't start designing until age 40,
and now that her most loyal clients are aging, she's shifting gears
and targeting women under 40. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-PRINCE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Favorable review of
``The Prince of Egypt.'' (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-PRINCE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Review of ``The Prince of
Egypt.'' Given 3 stars by reviewer. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-GODS&AMP;MONSTERS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Favorable review of
``Gods and Monsters.'' (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-ARTS _ Was 1998 the Year of Atlanta in arts and letters?
And, if so, was it a good one or a bad one? The city served many
purposes for the bi-coastal engines of national media and
communiations. Tom Wolfe and Alfred Uhry (twice) used it as a pulpy
story setting, a well of ambition, greed, intolerance and animal
high spirits; Disney used it as test-market without a troublesome
sense of discernment; D.C.-based Americans for the Arts booked it
for their June 99 confab. Kenny Leon, Pearl Cleage and other local
figures jumped to the national stage, while the NBAF fell off it
(and the Arts Festival, never having made it, fell, period). Are
there meaningful patterns to be read in these entrails? What if
anything does it say about Atlanta? (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS . FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   GODS-DIRECTOR _ Writer director Bill Condon talks about ``Gods
and Monsters,'' his complex, sorrowful meditation about the final
days of the life of ``Frankenstein'' director James Whale, who was
found drowned in his pool in 1957. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-BOOKS _ The books we keep are ones that read us as much as
we read them. More than any gift that comes to mind, they are a
reflection of our taste and our curiosity, our capacity for
discrimination and enjoyment. On my shelves are books read and
unread, books by the hundreds that I want to keep for as long as I
live and at least as many that I should winnow out before the start
of a New Year. But there are seven that at various points of my
life meant, and still mean, something special. They sit, unnoticed
on most days, like signposts to Christmases past _ and to ties
everlasting. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PETS _ Gatsby never had it so great. Natalie Spalding of
Atlanta and her faithful Jack Russell terrier had a grand time in
France on a Dordogne Doggie Walk organized by Europeds. The
Monterey, Calif., tour operator, which has organized walking and
cycling tours in Europe for 17 years, became an industry pioneer
when it inaugurated doggie walks in Dordogne and Provence last
year. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PETS-BOOKS _ A roundup of books and other resources for
folks traveling with pets. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   BALSAMINN _ The Balsam Mountain Inn is a place of comfort and
joy throughout the year, but at Christmastime, a special cheer
enfolds the 42,000-square-foot North Carolina inn nestled on 26
acres less than a mile from the Blue Ridge Parkway and surrounded
by peaks rising to more than 6,000 feet. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and B/W LAYOUT. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   LANDSCAPE-DESIGNER _ Meet Dan Franklin, the Atlanta landscape
architect whose tongue is as acid as Georgia soil and as well known
as his award-winning designs and much-visited garden. Gardening is
what keeps him young (he's 83) _ that and enjoying his work,
staying active in his industry, peddling his stationary bike 20
minutes a day and swilling a cocktail in his Collier Hills back
yard. There, he spent eight years developing the bones of a garden,
which Franklin knew was critical before the first daffodil could
ever be planted. A How the Pros Live. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS and LAYOUT. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MAY-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Kudzu. The name rings ominously. Thinking
of it this time of year always reminded me less of the spirit of
peace and joy than of the grinch that spreads misery. Until I met
Dorothy Greason. I visited her southwest Atlanta home on a recent
Saturday and discovered a kudzu Christmas; she collects the evil
weed and turns it into symbols of the season, including trees and
wreaths and baskets. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
