<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS THAT DRIVE US NOT TO DRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two are selling scotch, one a luxury car,
another an inexpensive wine and the worst of the bunch, tequila.
</P>
<P>
   What the five current ads have in common is, they drive me
seriously nuts. Each insults my intelligence, two insult my dignity
as a woman and one is a raised middle finger to all but a
privileged, white, upwardly mobile class.
</P>
<P>
   Let's discuss that one first.
</P>
<P>
   The product: an upscale scotch. Pictured in the ad is a smiling,
chiseled-face man, toasting someone with a glass of whisky. His
aura shouts, ``Prep school, Ivy League college, job on Wall Street,
family money, summer house in Tuscany, and a well-bred wife already
ripe with the first of many kidlets to perpetuate the dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad copy: ``Politically correct? Here's to just being
right.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be a more arrogant and smug put-down of the economic
and social struggles of ethnic and racial minorities, the working
class and anyone else who isn't white and rich, but I haven't seen
it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's to just being right? According to whom, the ruling-party
elite? So much for listening to one another, for respecting
differences, for affording each person value and intellectual
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think this is all about class envy, let me describe the
radio ad for inexpensive wine.
</P>
<P>
   A woman with a disgusted, had-it-up-to-here voice delivers a
prolonged screed about how hard ``they'' make it to buy a ``good
bottle of wine.'' Vintages, grape varieties, growing regions and
the conditions that affect the quality of wine, well, all of that
stuff is just pretentious b.s., according to the tough-talking
whiner.
</P>
<P>
   She likes to go into a store and pull something off a shelf; the
only effort she wants to put out is to choose red or white. The
monologue is a paean to self-perpetuating stupidity, to the belief
that ignorance is a badge of honor. Just what we need more of in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of ignorant: a radio commercial for a $30,000 imported
luxury car. Two parents are worried sick because their little
darling is so depressed, he won't get out of bed. The doctor comes
and discerns the cause: The boy (with a piping grade school-age
voice) wants his family to buy a specific model of the luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   Is that all? The much-relieved parents promise to acquire the
car, and the little darling bursts into a shrill song of joy.
</P>
<P>
   This ad is about as cute as an open sore.
</P>
<P>
   The other scotch ad just bums me out. It shows a nice-looking
young couple, photographed in Woody Allen black-and-white. She,
long of hair and swollen of lips, is deep into bliss, trying on
clothes in a boutique. He, with tip-tinted short hair and sweater,
sits at his lady's knees, his arms already overloaded with filled
shopping bags. Chin in hand, he stares, wistful and bored, at the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A full day of shopping?'' says the ad. ``Now that calls for a
drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Who turned the time machine back to 1954, when poor, put-upon
males got dragged around like check-writing packhorses by their
dippy, frock-crazy little women? Is this how the Ally McBeal
generation relates? As their grandparents did?
</P>
<P>
   Are there pretty young women so desperate for male companionship
that they can't even go shopping for their own clothes without
being joined at the hip to a thoroughly uninterested beau? Did I
dream the women's movement?
</P>
<P>
   The tequila ad tells me I did.
</P>
<P>
   It features a dark-haired beauty, lying on her back and looking
up with a slight defiance. Her shoulders and chest are bare as far
as you can show on a public billboard. Next to her head is a bottle
of tequila. On one of her shoulders is a shot glass, on the other,
a wedge of lime. Ad copy: ``BODY SLAM.''
</P>
<P>
   If I need to explain what is so offensive about this ad, may you
find a seat in that luxury automobile and enjoy the ride to the
bottom of the San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
