<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONOPOLY-NAVY-HNS &LR;      12-18 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONOPOLY-NAVY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOOKS FOR MONOPOLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAI HUYNH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Millions of landlubbers have fallen under the spell of
its pastel-colored paper money and plots of land from Mediterranean
Avenue to Boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   Now Monopoly is reeling in sailors with a new U.S. Navy edition
and the opportunity to buy aircraft carriers and the Blue Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be an excellent marriage between two
colorful organizations,'' Carman Cedola, business development
director of USAOPOLY, said of the first Monopoly game dedicated to
a military service.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Brothers has sold more than 200 million copies of the
classic board game since 1935. Translated into 26 different
languages, it's the best-selling game in history.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro-owned Parker Brothers granted USAOPOLY the license to
develop different versions of the game in 1994. The company has
hatched 65 so far, half of which were released this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the games that came out this year have been very well
received,'' said Dane Chapin, chief executive officer of the
family-owned business.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the special editions, retailing for $30 and up in
specialty stores, have been good. The California-based company
expects to sell more than 1 million games in 1998 _ up about 50
percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge national affinity for the Monopoly game,''
Chapin said. ``Now that we've personalized it for a lot of people,
I think they're more apt to get involved with the game again.''
</P>
<P>
   The first specialty versions created by Chapin and his two
sisters were for the cities of Atlanta, Boston, New York, San Diego
and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The company now has 25 cities, including Chicago, Dallas,
Denver, Detroit, Houston, Indianapolis, Kansas City, Mo., Las
Vegas, Philadelphia, Seattle, St. Louis and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the city-themed games, USAOPOLY has universities,
states and special-interest editions for fans of everything from
bass fishing and dinosaurs to Harley-Davidson, NASCAR, national
parks, ``Star Trek'' and the U.S. space program.
</P>
<P>
   NASA doesn't endorse commercial products, but it does review
them for accuracy. The verdict on the space program edition?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's historically accurate,'' said Burt Ulrich, the NASA
visual identity coordinator in Washington who evaluated the game.
Game pieces include the space shuttle, Hubble Space Telescope and
the Mars Sojourner rover.
</P>
<P>
   USAOPOLY spends six months to a year developing, designing and
researching each new version.
</P>
<P>
   The company hired a dedicated Trekker, or Trekkie, to pore over
the volumes at Paramount's ``Star Trek'' library for its ``Star
Trek: The Next Generation'' edition. Characters from the popular
show _ Captain Jean-Luc Picard, Commander William T. Riker and Data
_ take the place of the top hat, thimble and car from the original
game.
</P>
<P>
   For the U.S. Navy edition, USAOPOLY enlisted help from several
U.S. Navy sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I appreciate about the game is the accurate presentation
of all the elements of the U.S. Navy,'' said Petty Officer 1st
class Todd Stevens, a Navy spokesman in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the photos. They bring the game to life,'' he added
about the game's artwork by U.S. Navy photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated to the men and women in the Navy, the game's pewter
playing tokens include an anchor, jet fighter plane, sailor hat and
a partially submerged submarine.
</P>
<P>
   As in all Monopoly versions, the traditional four corners of the
game remain the same: Go (Collect $200), Free Parking, In Jail and
Go to Jail. No ``Go to the Brig'' on the Navy version.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Fleet and Pacific Fleet cards, however, have replaced
the Chance and Community Chest cards in the Navy game. And as in
all the special versions, properties on the game board are
different. They include the Naval Academy, Norfolk Naval Base,
Seawolf submarine, a sub-chasing P3 Orion and the aircraft carrier
USS Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   So far, people have responded positively to the nautical
version.
</P>
<P>
   It has sold out at many of the Navy stores, Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
