<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6810 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-ATTACK-HNS &LR;      12-18 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ATTACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO END CLINTON'S WAR IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOAN STEINAU LESTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Watching President William Jefferson Clinton
give his speech on Wednesday, an hour after Iraqi bombing was
initiated, I realized I haven't been this upset listening to a
president since the days of Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson got up, repeatedly, to defend the U.S. military
role in Vietnam, we used to chant, ``Hey hey, LBJ, how many kids
did you kill today?''
</P>
<P>
   One of my most ecstatic memories was hearing the news that
Johnson wasn't going to run for re-election. I was in a movie
theater on the Lower East Side in New York City. The show was
interrupted, the announcement made, and the theater broke out in
wild cheers. We had made it impossible for him to govern! We
thought the war would soon be over.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't wanted to get out in the streets to demonstrate for
years, but as soon as I heard about the Iraqi bombing _ on the eve
of the scheduled House impeachment vote _ I wanted to rush out and
yell, ``No! You can't slaughter people to save your career. Stop,
stop, stop!''
</P>
<P>
   There are no surgical strikes in war. Thousands of Iraqi
citizens could die _ on top of 6,000 expiring each month from lack
of food and medicine (a result of the vigorous U.S. blockade). So
saying that ``our quarrel is not with the Iraqi people'' is
meaningless. The deja vu is astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's stated goal of ``bringing change in Baghdad'' through
this massive air attack is reminiscent of Johnson's similar (and
ultimately futile) rationale: The U.S. will bring democracy to
Vietnam through war. Surely we have learned new skills since those
dark days: How to begin cooperative relationships with Third World
countries, how to resolve conflict without bombs and how to assist
local people in making democratic change rather than imposing it,
literally, from above.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder how the American people will grapple with casualties
this time around. Immediately after the bombing started, thousands
began protesting publicly in many cities.
</P>
<P>
   Peace workers _ and those of us who haven't been involved _ are
activating telephone trees all over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 20 years, I say, ``Take it to the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   We have to vote with our feet.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped the war in Vietnam. Let's stop this one too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Steinau Lester the author of ``Taking Charge: Every
Woman's Action Guide.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
