<SLUG> BC-FILM-EGYPT-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL `PRINCE' BE A BOX-OFFICE KING? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In 1956, movie audiences were eager to accept Charlton
Heston as Moses in Cecil B. DeMille's ``The Ten Commandments,''
making that Bible-based film a major hit.
</P>
<P>
   Will 1998 audiences be willing to do the same for an animated
Moses with the voice of Val Kilmer in ``The Prince of Egypt?''
</P>
<P>
   Will viewers accept a singing Bible story aimed at adults with
themes of slavery, sacrifice and heavenly vengeance in an art form
that has usually been the playground of cute comic animals and
happy children's songs?
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen _ the SKG
of DreamWorks SKG _ are betting they will. They aren't quite
betting the farm, but close to it.
</P>
<P>
   Only 4 years old, with many of its major setup expenses yet to
come _ including a major new studio in Playa Vista near Los Angeles
_ DreamWorks can use another hit, like its ``Antz'' and ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' and can ill afford a major failure.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Prince of Egypt' is a very important corner stone,'' said
Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The studio did even better than expected with ``Antz'' (about
$145 million worldwide to date), its first animated film. Like
``The Prince of Egypt,'' ``Antz'' was aimed at a more mature
audience than Disney animated films. But it was still of the
familiar fantasy adventure format, not far from the animation norm,
that children could enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' is something else again.
</P>
<P>
   The PG-rated movie offers the usual animated mix of comedy,
adventure and plenty of songs, not to mention a fabulous look,
capped by a show-stopping hieroglyph dream sequence.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall tone is serious and sincere. There are no cuddly
singing animals. There are plagues, beatings, suffering and even
The Almighty, as personified in a cleverly animated burning bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a kiddie movie,'' said ``Prince'' co-director Brenda
Chapman. ``Kids can go, but a parent needs to be there with them
(to explain) what happens with the death of the first-born and the
plagues. It will probably bring up some questions.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Hebrews' enslavement in Egypt to their arrival in the
Promised Land, ``Prince'' tells the story of Moses, who progresses
from a babe set afloat in a wicker basket through wild teen years
as an adopted prince to an aged and wise leader of a wandering
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses is such a dynamic character,'' said Kilmer of his role.
``I really loved thinking about him when I was a young man, because
it's a story of hope. It's such a human story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here he is thinking he is in the most elite group in Egypt.
But out of his frustration and anger, he kills a man. It always
gave me hope in Sunday school that you could do something that bad
and still things could work out in your life. I loved that.''
</P>
<P>
   The central focus is the loving relationship between Moses and
his brother by adoption, Rameses (voiced by Ralph Fiennes), and how
that relationship is affected by Moses' attempts to lead the
Hebrews from bondage.
</P>
<P>
   Disney may be able to alter fairy tales and even give ``The
Hunchback of Notre Dame'' a happy ending, but this is a story from
the Old Testament and you fiddle around with that at your own risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first moment, we recognized how important this story
is to many people around the world, and we had an obligation to
become knowledgeable,'' Katzenberg said. ``David Geffen gave me the
best advice I've ever been given by anybody in my professional
career. David said, `Jeffrey. if you are going to tell this story:
one, it must be absolutely faithful; two, it must be absolutely
accurate.'''
</P>
<P>
   Religious groups of the '90s are far more outspoken and more
easily offended when they disagree on fine points of faith than
when ``The Ten Commandments'' was released. In trying to make an
animated musical film from the Bible, however serious the effort
is, DreamWorks is treading on potentially treacherous ground.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the story-development process, the studio began
consulting with experts from a broad range of fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Egyptologists, archaeologists, Bible scholars,
religious leaders from the far right to the far left, educators,''
said producer Penney Finkelman Cox of Patchwork Productions,
DreamWorks' animation division. ``People were very generous.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the advice was not what they wanted to hear, as with
the scene in which Moses and Tzipporah (voice of Michelle Pfeiffer)
marry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Moses do the traditional breaking of the pot,'' Cox
said. ``It was a beautiful moment. One of the educators said, `Yes,
but that signifies the destruction of the first temple, which
didn't happen for another thousand years.' So that's an anachronism
in the movie. It was really painful for us (to remove). We had
already created it in storyboard form.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's creators had Egyptologists go over their hieroglyphs
``with a microscope'' to make sure they were accurate. One scholar
found that one of the Egyptian gods depicted in the film's
background paintings was from the wrong period and had to be
removed.
</P>
<P>
   For inspiration, Katzenberg took his creative team on a visit to
Egypt to better understand their subject.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty pyramids and other structures of classical Egypt are
constantly on display in the movie, and they have never looked
grander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our production designer, Darek Gogol, was doing these huge
drawings of the monuments and pyramids and temples,'' said Chapman.
``I said, `Darek, I think we should pull back a little bit.' But
once we went there and stood at the foot of the columns, they felt
that big. I said, `Go for it. Make it as big as you want.'''
</P>
<P>
   Detail and accuracy and faithfulness to the Bible may or may not
satisfy religious audiences. For the vast majority of the large
crowds DreamWorks hopes to attract, none of that will matter unless
they find the story exciting and involving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is the key to a good film, whether it is live-action
or animated,'' said Chapman. ``The visuals are there to support the
story. If you don't care anything for those characters or what's
happening to them, the best animation in the world can't save a bad
story, but the worst animation in the world won't hurt a good
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to make this a human story, because we need to
relate to Moses. He can't just be this icon who walks through this
preachy Bible movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman, the first woman to direct a major animated film and
head of story work for Disney on ``The Lion King'' and other films,
admitted that she was skeptical when Katzenberg approached her to
direct the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, an animated musical Bible story about Moses? Who
wants to go see that? I've seen some really bad Sunday-school stuff
that makes people want to go screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to meet with Jeffrey and Steven Spielberg (and
others) I saw the possibilities. Jeffrey is not going to allow
something to be of a lesser quality.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks would not give out production costs. But large-scale
animated films can cost $50 million to $75 million or more to
produce. Add to that tens of millions more for promotion and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Antz'' (like ``A Bug's Life'') was done in computer
animation, ``The Prince of Egypt'' is DreamWorks' maiden showcase
in traditional animation. Aside from some of the massive crowd
scenes, where digital techniques were employed, most of the movie
is hand-drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense of acting, a sense of fluidity that you get
with hand-drawn animation,'' Chapman said. ``You get
inconsistencies and imperfections. That's part of the charm of
classically done animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The digital is still working out bugs, no pun intended. They
can feel a little weightless or puppet like.''
</P>
<P>
   Can DreamWorks compete in this tricky field, and make a success
of a film that goes so contrary to accepted animation style and
subject? Will religious audiences accept a Hollywood film? Will
nonreligious audiences accept a Bible story?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answers, Katzenberg said the studio is committed to
a more adult approach to animation, not trying to beat Disney, but
to creating its own animation niche.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the animation side, we are committed for the next four
years,'' Katzenberg said. ``What we have to do is maintain an even
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a little divine intervention would help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
