<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MONKEY-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIT OF `MONKEY' BUSINESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks like Disney.
</P>
<P>
   It feels like Disney.
</P>
<P>
   It even has Disney's beloved chimps.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Summer of the Monkeys,'' a family film new on video (rated
G, closed-captioned, $19.99), wasn't made by Disney, although it's
being issued under Disney's name.
</P>
<P>
   The film was independently produced last year in Canada, with
Michael Ontkean (``Twin Peaks'') starring and Michael Anderson
(``Around the World in 80 Days'') directing.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an award-winning novel by Wilson Rawls, ``Summer of the
Monkeys'' depicts 1800s farm boy Jay (Corey Sevier), who tries to
capture some escaped circus chimps in order to collect a reward so
he can buy his own pony.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Jay learns a lot about chimps, faith, family and
what's truly important in life.
</P>
<P>
   Ontkean and Leslie Hope play the boy's parents, Katie Stuart is
his handicapped sister, and Wilford Brimley plays the boy's
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   The star of the tube's twisted ``Twin Peaks'' might seem like a
long shot for such a film, but Ontkean, 48, was ready for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up one day and realized my youngest daughter was 9, and
in her lifetime I had not made a movie that she could see,''
Ontkean said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I drew a line in the sand and said, `That's it. I'm not
making another movie until it's something she can see and there's
nothing ugly or twisted about it.' Then I had to wait a year until
this came along.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer of the Monkeys'' was shot in Ontkean's native Canada
``on quite a stunning landscape in remote Saskatchewan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as you could see, the prairie land is so flat. We built
our own sets, and there was nothing else for 50 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Things might have gotten dull, but there were always the film's
four chimps, supervised by animal trainers. The chimps are the true
stars.
</P>
<P>
   For all the warm family sentiments straight out of ``Little
House on the Prairie,'' Summer of the Monkeys has ample monkey
business (as did Disney's ``Toby Tyler'' of 1960 and ``Rocket Man''
of last year).
</P>
<P>
   Those chimps could be fun off-camera, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the middle of nowhere, with no diversions, so we
spent a lot of time hanging out with the monkeys on the set,''
Ontkean said.
</P>
<P>
   He found the animals ``very much like humans. You quickly
develop a real respect for their intelligence _ and not just what
they can do, but their feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney didn't see the product until it was finished, at which
point the studio picked the film up for distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real tribute to the filmmakers, because Disney likes
to generate its own material,'' Ontkean said. ``But this does look
like a Disney movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Ontkean's other recent work has included ``A Chance of Snow,''
another family film, which premiered last week on cable's Lifetime.
His earlier work included the films ``Slap Shot,'' ``Postcards From
the Edge'' and ``Making Love.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's perhaps best known for playing Sheriff Harry S. Truman
in the ``Twin Peaks'' TV series of 1990-91, probing the bizarre
death of prom queen Laura Palmer while sharing doughnuts with FBI
Special Agent Dale Cooper (Kyle MacLachlan).
</P>
<P>
   ```Twin Peaks' still follows me around,'' Ontkean said with a
wry laugh. ``There are some pretty intense and rabid `Peakies' out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fans don't bother me. It's all very friendly. Nothing
strange has ever happened out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ontkean said he's ``proud'' of ``Twin Peaks,'' just as he's
``proud'' of ``Summer of the Monkeys.'' But his favorite film to
make was 1977's ``Slap Shot,'' a raw comedy in which he played a
hockey player opposite Paul Newman.
</P>
<P>
   ``By working with Newman, in six months you learn 25 years'
worth of acting lessons,'' said Ontkean, who grew up playing hockey
in Montreal, hockey's birthplace. (He now lives in Southern
California.)
</P>
<P>
   Ontkean said it was also ``a real honor'' to star in one of the
early mainstream movies about homosexuality, 1982's ``Making
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bold movie in its day, and now it's very tame,'' he
said. ``But it was a real learning experience for me. I grew up in
Canada, and I'm a little backward in a lot of ways. This was a
whole culture for me to explore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he hopes to continue his family-film string, even if it
means breaking a major rule of acting: Never work opposite kids or
animals (since they'll constantly upstage you).
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really mind,'' Ontkean said of his experience on
``Summer of the Monkeys.'' ``The chimps were so much fun, and the
kids were lively and energetic. You just can't find fault with that
kind of life force.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
