<HEADLINE>
QUICK CLICKS DELIVER TWO DECENT SYSTEMS &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   All indications are that this is going to be another banner
Christmas season for shopping online. Some analysts estimate that
40 percent of all Internet users will buy something over the World
Wide Web, and probably a lot more than that will use the Net for
research before buying.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that computer equipment is one of the most
popular online purchases. If you already have a computer, you're
comfortable with buying over the Web and you need to upgrade, it's
a natural progression to click your way to a spanking-new system.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy computer makers have set up user-friendly sites that let
you configure your own system online. Two masters of direct
consumer-PC sales, Gateway and Micron Electronics, have made the
process of selecting and purchasing a system via their Web pages
not just painless, but fun.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at two systems you can buy online. If you click
quickly, you might even be able to get them delivered in time for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gateway G6-450, $1,998, Gateway: Looking for the most solidly
built, best-value, high-end consumer PC available this year? This
is it. Gateway has hit a home run with a system that packs a
powerful punch at an impressively low price.
</P>
<P>
   The starting configuration comes with Intel's top-of-the-line
450-megahertz Pentium II processor, 64 megabytes of memory, a
10-gigabyte hard drive, a DVD-ROM drive, a 3Dfx Banshee video card
with 16 MB of video memory, a PCI-based SoundBlaster card with
Boston Acoustic speakers and a US Robotics 56K Winmodem.
</P>
<P>
   And for that price, you also get a 17-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   I added a network interface card for connecting to a home
network, and a Voodoo2-based 3-D add-on graphics card for playing
games. I also switched out the Winmodem for a traditional modem _
more on that in a minute _ which brought the total to just under
$2,200, still a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The G6-450 is very, very fast _ easily the fastest 450-Mhz
system I've used. Give it more RAM, and it would probably do even
better. It easily handled every game I threw at it, from Half-Life
and Quake II to Sierra Pro Pilot 99, a flight simulator with some
challenging graphics.
</P>
<P>
   It is also is well-designed. There are three available PCI
slots, and the case is solid and roomy. There's room to work
inside.
</P>
<P>
   I have only three complaints about the G6-450, and they are
minor.
</P>
<P>
   First, the software bundle is relatively stingy, but that's
probably one way that Gateway keeps the price low. You can add
software as part of an upgraded configuration. However, don't
expect this system to come with all the programs you'll need _ it's
more for folks who already have their own software.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it comes with a winmodem, which stores its software
instructions on a file on the hard drive rather than in a chip on
the modem's circuit board. I'm on the verge of going on a crusade
against these things. I've never found one that works as well as a
traditional modem. If you buy a G6-450, take the option for a
regular modem.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the hard drive is noisy, making a loud clattering time
every time it's used.
</P>
<P>
   But, as I said, these are minor points. Overall, this is the
best consumer machine I've seen this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Millennia Max, $1,999, Micron Electronics: Like Dell Computer
Corp., Micron focuses on business sales, though like Dell, it's
always had a solid base of savvy consumer buyers. Micron makes
decent machines inexpensively, though the one I tried was not quite
as solid or fast as the Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried had a 450-Mhz Pentium II, 128 MB of memory, a
10-GB hard drive, a Diamond Viper V550 card with 16 MB of memory, a
DVD-ROM drive, US Robotics 56K Winmodem and a 128-voice wavetable
sound card with Monsoon M-100 speakers. Like the Gateway, this
price includes a 17-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Micron came with twice as much memory as the
Gateway, it wasn't quite as fast. It also wasn't as stable, thanks
to buggy drivers that came with the Diamond Viper V550 card.
Although Diamond is working on new drivers, this card suffers from
serious problems. For example, America Online 4.0 users will find
the screen may freeze when they have the card's color depth set to
more than 256.
</P>
<P>
   I also did not specify that I did not want a winmodem in this
system. It had trouble connecting both to America Online and a
local Internet provider. Fortunately, a traditional modem is
available.
</P>
<P>
   I also did not care for the speakers, which look intriguing with
a set of flat-panel satellites complemented by a jet-black
subwoofer. But volume control was flakey _ it was either too loud
or too soft _ and the subwoofer delivered punchless bass.
</P>
<P>
   This system would be an excellent buy if you avoided the
winmodem, went shopping elsewhere for your speakers or chose one of
the two alternate video cards available at Micron's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
