<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 95/98, DESPITE RUMORS, ABLE TO HANDLE PLENTY OF MEMORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I was about to go to the computer store and buy some more
memory to put in my system when a friend who I think is pretty
knowledgeable about PCs told me not to bother.
</P>
<P>
   He said Windows 95 and 98 can only handle up to 64 megabytes of
memory, and I would be wasting my money. I was thinking of going up
to 128 MB. What's the truth?
</P>
<P>
   A.: I've heard this from several readers, and fortunately, it's
not true. Windows 95/98 can handle a lot more memory than 64 MB _
up to four gigabytes!
</P>
<P>
   You see plenty of systems sold with 128 and 256 megabytes of
RAM, so that should be a clue right there that 64 megabytes is a
false limit. The amount of memory your particular machine can use
may be limited by your hardware, such as your motherboard and
system BIOS.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure where this rumor came from, except that there was a
similar one about Windows 3.1, that it could only handle 32
megabytes. MS-DOS did have a 64-megabyte limit, so that may be the
source.
</P>
<P>
   Some users have reported that if they have the old EMM386 device
from DOS still included in their config.sys files, their systems
will say they have 64 megabytes, even though the machine obviously
has _ and is making use of _ more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been told that it is better to close a window using
File, then Close/Exit, rather than using the X in the upper right
hand corner to avoid possibly corrupting files. Is that true or
does it only apply to certain windows like Word?
</P>
<P>
   A: Using the X box is basically the same thing as doing a
File/Exit menu command. You won't hurt your files doing it this
way. It is a good idea, though, to use the Save command before
shutting down a program if you have a document active in the
application.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I currently have a Pentium 100 and I'm going to be upgrading
very soon. On the P100 I have about 3 gigabytes of storage spanning
three drives. Is there a convenient way to transfer the files from
the P100 to the new computer? I thought that the easiest way would
be removing the drives one at a time from the old machine,
installing them in the new machine and copying the files to the new
drive, but I'm open to suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's one way to do it. Another suggestion _ buy a couple of
network cards and some Ethernet cable. Make a two-machine network
and copy the files that way. When you're done, you'll have all the
files on your new machine _ and you'll have a home network to boot!
</P>
<P>
   You can read my instructions for setting up a home network, from
a column I wrote last April, at
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/98/04/24/compute.html.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you can also use a program such as LapLink for Windows
(www.travsoft.com), which lets you transfer files between two
computers using a serial or parallel cable. This is the slowest
method, but doesn't require that you open your computer's case.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in adding a new 3-D card. My system came with
a 4-MB NVidia AGP graphics card. I want the STB Velocity 4400 16-MB
3-D card. Should I get the PCI version of this card and run both
cards together or get the AGP version and replace the original
graphics card?
</P>
<P>
   A: Replace the original AGP card if you want to use that
specific video card. AGP graphics cards are faster, so you would
not want to use the PCI card if your system has an AGP slot.
</P>
<P>
   The only kind of card that augments an existing graphics adapter
is the kind that uses 3Dfx's Voodoo or Voodoo2 chips. They connect
to your current card and take over only when 3-D is required.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
