<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S UNSAFE SEX, LIES AND MISSILE TAPES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Count me out. I never got the memo. I'm not
impeaching anyone and I'm not launching cruise missiles at anyone.
But I've thought about the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I was making my list of people who deserve to be hit by
cruise missiles, unlike Iraqi civilians, one landed on House
Speaker-designate Robert Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   He said he ``on occasion strayed from his marriage,'' but added
that ``these past indiscretions were not with anyone on my staff,
and I was never called to testify on them.''
</P>
<P>
   And they were cuter than Monica, he could have added.
</P>
<P>
   As the House starts impeachment hearings, the Republic teeters
on such distinctions. After all, you can't get rid of a politician
for just having an affair, or Washington would be empty.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's not a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason Livingston was never called to testify on his
affairs. He didn't have a special prosecutor chasing him for six
years, cornering him in courtrooms and gathering dresses and secret
tape-recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Let's target that cruise missile on his glass house anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bomb them all and let God sort them out. The most fanatical
Republican Guard is in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bill Clinton is so wonderful. But there are rational
reasons for disliking Clinton, and irrational reasons for hating
him and wanting to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Just as an example of a rational reason to dislike Clinton, he
tends to use cruise missiles as weapons of mass distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise missiles make for a good show on CNN and invariably raise
Clinton's poll ratings when he's in trouble. However, they also
raise Saddam Hussein's ratings in Iraq because of the civilians
they kill and wound.
</P>
<P>
   A cruise missile is a coward's weapon that doesn't risk American
casualties, but can't do the job that only can be done by
commitment to ground war.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the irrational hatreds of Clinton. The Republican
Party should be on the couch having their hatreds examined. One of
those obsessions is the need to wage retroactive culture war with
Woodstock Nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans don't know whom they're dealing with. Many of us
took acid back then. We can deal with the country's bad trip. We
already went down the rabbit hole.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Saddam Hussein has already attacked us with a chemical
weapon. Maybe he put thousands of gallons of LSD in our water
supply.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain everyone's weirdness? Retired Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf joined the Democrats, saying ``By golly, troops are
committed, and we can't have people second-guessing them the way
they did in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh no, we can't have that, not in a democracy led by a former
opponent of the Vietnam War. We must keep heading for the light at
the end of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri shouted:
``Our sons and daughters are in harm's way while we're beginning a
debate on impeaching a president. That is wrong. That is wrong.
That is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. I seem to remember a debate on impeaching a
president during another undeclared war. But he deserved it, and
the war had already gone on for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   So they're going through with it, even if Clinton can make the
cruise-missile supply last until Jan. 6, when the new Congress is
sworn in. We're almost assured of seeing Linda Tripp and Monica
Lewinsky testify before the Senate. Talk about a bad trip.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam Hussein will be laughing his head off, as his government
becomes more entrenched while ours shatters.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate won't just be impeaching Clinton. They'll
be establishing law and setting precedent. Impeachment could become
a standard political tool for reversing elections.
</P>
<P>
   Just wait until a Republican becomes president again. After
this, though, you may have to wait a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans didn't have to do this. They could have used the
bombing as an impeachment halt, and let their hatred of Clinton
cool down for a while.
</P>
<P>
   But no, they've been feeding their irrational hatred of Clinton
for six years, and they're not about to quit now, Operation Desert
Fox, or no Operation Desert Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can't seem to do anything right at this point. His
glorious little green night-vision war has the same nickname as
Nazi Germany's greatest general, Erwin Rommel.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government protested the name, as well as the
cruise-missile attacks. One member of the Russian parliament even
introduced a motion appealing to Monica Lewinsky ``to restrain the
emotions of Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, he's on the phone, and it doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   How bad are these times? So bad that it's a relief to get back
to the basic issues of government _ like which politicians
committed adultery.
</P>
<P>
   They all did, I suspect. But you know how it is with sex. One
thing leads to another.
</P>
<P>
   One moment you're having meaningless sex, and six years later
your life, the government and parts of Baghdad are destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   That, my friend, is not safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
