<HEADER>
A6858 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-EGYPT-HNS     12-18 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-EGYPT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMWORKS TEMPTS FAITH IN ITS MOSES PORTRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' is a hard sell. Critics know it. The
studio knows it. Probably even Moses knows it, or he would if he
were around to dwell on such things. A biblically inspired,
resolutely unsilly animated musical aimed at grown-ups is not the
sort of movie generally paired with the term ``blockbuster.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the sort of movie generally made.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here it is, DreamWorks' startling new look at the Book of
Exodus, and the powers that be in production are crossing their
fingers and their toes, and their hearts, and their split ends,
probably _ in skittish anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely concerned that it's a hard sell,'' said
Penney Finkelman Cox, who produced the film with Sandra Rabins.
``Yes, we feel that it's going to be a real challenge to get people
to choose this movie. . .. The whole fear from day one was that if
people saw it as a Sunday school lesson, as something that was,
quote, `good for you,' it'd be the last thing in the world they'd
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, she said, the studio aimed from the start for
a more human _ and dramatically compelling _ portrait of Moses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about having this very well-known story is, you
know, there are two things you have to include: There's no doubt
that the Red Sea has to part, and the bush has to talk. ... But the
only way to make (`Prince of Egypt') a film experience as opposed
to a Sunday school lesson is to find the drama in it as well,''
said Cox, speaking in a recent telephone interview from Los
Angeles. ``The man Moses _ that's what we set out to discover, the
man and his vision and his goals. And we tried to discover what
made him such a unique figure.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's biggest leaps is its depiction of the
relationship between Moses and the Pharaoh Rameses, who are
portrayed as adoptive brothers. This gives the movie much of its
dramatic tension, requiring Moses to renounce his Egyptian family
before he can obey God's call. ``(Moses) was the first reluctant
hero he was the first very fallible, very human hero who said,
`What difference can I make? I'm just one man. I'm not sure I want
to take this job.' He's a man who committed murder, he had all the
faults and all of the weaknesses of all of us. He asked all the
questions all of us ask in our lives: `I'm just an individual; do I
have a responsibility to society as a whole, or can I just hide in
my life?'''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who produced DreamWorks' computer-animated ``Antz'' as well
as such live-action films as ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids'' and (as
co-producer) ``Terms of Endearment,'' described the four-year
creative discussions behind ``Prince'' as ``an incredibly yeasty
stew of conversation'' that covered mythology, identity and the
nature of religion. She quickly brushed off questions about her own
or anyone else's religious beliefs, and swore the film ``was not
made from a point of view of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the movie's creators were careful to treat the
story of Moses with respect, delicately balancing elements from
Exodus with their own new twists. ``The whole nature of religion is
about commentary the basic rule is that every Saturday and Sunday
across the world, priests and ministers and rabbis are basically
making commentaries,'' she said. ``And one of the first
understandings we came to was that when the Bible is silent on
something, that allows for commentary, that allows for the midrash
that evolved, for the speculation on what might've happened. But
when the Bible is specific, then the specificity has to be
understood and respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``As lay people, it really was a challenge,'' she said. The
bottom line was a matter of moviemaking: how to make the film
respectful ``while making it entertaining, while making it dramatic
and effective and not a Bible lesson. We just didn't want to string
icons together.''
</P>
<P>
   A more mundane worry was how to avoid imitating ``The Ten
Commandments,'' Cecil B. DeMille's 1956 benchmark. Cox said the
film's executive producer, DreamWorks honcho Jeffrey Katzenberg,
asked everyone early on not to watch the older film. ``He really
made a plea for us not to see it,'' Cox said. ``Because if we saw
it again, we might be tempted, inadvertently, to copy it in ways
that we couldn't even predict. Or we might be tempted to strongly
go in an opposite direction, which would also color our choices.
But it's really hard to say what subliminal influences it might
have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said she sees a marked difference between the complexity of
``The Prince of Egypt'' and the simplicity of the average animated
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we came to understand the story, the more we grew
inspired by it by the depth of it, by the amazing richness of the
cinematic material,'' Cox said. ```The Prince of Egypt' has so many
dimensions, it's such a multidimensional story, that for us that
was the challenge and the fun of it. We had such a good time
allowing ourselves to layer it on.''
</P>
<P>
   What about audiences? Will they respond? Cox hopes so. Recalling
an early screening of the film, she said, ``My favorite comment was
the comment of a 7-year-old boy, who said, `Gosh, the Red Sea
rocks.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I want: I want a 7-year-old to say, `The Red Sea
rocks.' I want it all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
