<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAVE OFF END, FORM NEW LEAGUE FOR THE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For many, the withdrawals are already starting.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL season is dwindling down to a precious few games, and
you know what that means _ the end of fantasy football.
</P>
<P>
   Horror of horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Without fantasy leagues, the NFL is much like the inside of
Kevin Greene's skull: a bleak void, bereft of all meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Or not. Anyway, you get the picture. When your fantasy team hits
the wall, it's really hard to get up for this week's Carolina-St.
Louis tilt. This is the No Fun League, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But I feel your pain. If the shakes get too bad, you can always
take desperate measures. Like watching the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Just a little joke there.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm talking about playoff fantasy football. This is an
even more depraved version, where you hold a draft between
Christmas and New Year's Day (very popular with the spousal unit,
by the way) and pick players from playoff-bound teams such as
Denver, Minnesota and maybe even, yipes, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   There are a million ways to do it, but I've developed a
blueprint which can be borrowed at no personal cost to you.
</P>
<P>
   Each owner drafts a quarterback, two running backs, two wide
receivers, a tight end, a kicker and a defense/special teams unit
from a team that has made the playoffs. There are no backups, since
the season is so short and the pool of players is going to shrink
as teams lose.
</P>
<P>
   There are no head-to-head games. A winner is determined by the
cumulative total points amassed by each team. Points are counted
right through the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, strategy plays a huge part in a playoff league. You
want players from teams favored to reach the Super Bowl, such as
Denver and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Do you take a chance on a player who may get great numbers for
one or two games, like Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre, or
someone who will have lesser numbers but play in more games, like
Denver quarterback John Elway?
</P>
<P>
   We at Fantasy Central are here to help. Some handicapping for
the sure-bet playoff teams:
</P>
<P>
   Denver: If running back Terrell Davis isn't your first pick,
immediately submit yourself to the commissioner for drug testing.
I'm not as fired up about the Broncos passing attack, though Elway
should ring up numbers just because he'll play a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota: Randall Cunningham. Randy Moss. Cris Carter. Robert
Smith (injured, but he'll be back). The Vikings are an
embarrassment of riches, and I don't see anybody keeping them out
of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta: Jamal Anderson should go in the first round. Tony
Martin and Terance Mathis are nice players, as is Chris Chandler if
his glass body doesn't shatter on impact.
</P>
<P>
   New York Jets: Coach Bill Parcells should keep the Jets around
for a couple of rounds, so quarterback Vinny Testaverde, running
back Curtis Martin and receivers Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet
are worth drafting.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco: Steve Young and Garrison Hearst might last only
two games, but they'll put up monster numbers that could sustain
you through the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas: The Cowboys are in if they beat either Philadelphia or
Washington at home. Trouble is, they'll only win one game.
Quarterback Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith are the picks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Waiver wire &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd take a look at Washington wide receiver Albert Connell, as
well as running back Skip Hicks, who is subbing for a dinged-up
Terry Allen. Rams running back June Henley had a nice game against
the Patriots. Cowboys receiver Patrick Jeffers would be a nice
pickup. &QL; 
One-hit wonder &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, it's New York Giants quarterback Kent Graham, who
threw for 265 yards and two touchdowns against Denver. I've seen
the future, and it's not Kent Graham. &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
