<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR TAKES A HOLIDAY, BUT RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - For a minute I felt frightened, a soul-chill that drew
me back to boyhood, to the age of 10, 11, 12. To nights when I
regularly snapped out of sleep to a vision of shadows, ashen
blemishes cast on charred concrete. Nuclear silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't felt such a fear in 20 years, maybe longer. Then I sat
at my desk staring at the television set Wednesday afternoon,
taking in the face of our president and the greenish glow of
Baghdad at night. These images made me feel young again but not
youthful; young, but at the same time, too old.
</P>
<P>
   It lasted a minute only, this fear, then quickly turned to
surprise. Not surprise because I had experienced a minute's chill,
but surprise because I had gone two decades without it.
</P>
<P>
   Without a hint of The Bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Detonated not (begin ital) there, (end ital) somewhere far off
and evil, but here, on American soil. Killing not them, but us.
</P>
<P>
   It is an idea long gone from our culture, almost quaint. It
disappeared with the end of the Cold War and the mounting years _
some 53 now _ between today and the flight of the Enola Gay.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we talk of war without thought to reprisal, about bombs
dropped as political strategy to stave off impeachment or to wag
some Hollywood-conjured dog. War is a prime-time show, a reason to
pre-empt the sitcoms. Bombs are ``smart,'' damage to the innocent
is ``collateral.'' Every mission has a testosterone-drenched name
and a TV logo.
</P>
<P>
   Today, war is media fodder, something to chew over at the water
cooler, to speculate about with the call-in hosts. War is like
cancer, or a fatal car crash, or a drive-by shooting. Such a
cataclysm will never happen to us, not in America.
</P>
<P>
   We have come far in this culture, and fast, but not so far as we
think. Wednesday afternoon, the face of Saddam Hussein reminds me
of this. Of the fear.
</P>
<P>
   We can kill him, make Baghdad disintegrate, but we can't kill
them all _ every madman with access to a lump of something
radioactive. There are too many of them, and they believe in their
own truths too deeply. So one day they will extract a price.
</P>
<P>
   Not with missiles, most likely, or by full-frontal assault. By
something planted somewhere, something with deadly force enough to
make the World Trade Center or Oklahoma City and the coring of a
Federal Building look positively mild.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's long minute, I see the aftermath, as I did as a
boy.
</P>
<P>
   I was 11 the first time I read John Hersey's ``Hiroshima,'' old
enough to unpuzzle the words, but too young to really understand. I
pulled the book off the shelf of the library at Public School 209,
a blond brick building with a yellow and black sign that denoted a
fallout shelter.
</P>
<P>
   My mother had told me stories of her grade-school days, sirens
and A-bomb drills, but I was too late for that. Instead I had
Hersey and his six survivors, the clerk and the doctor, the
tailor's widow and the priest, the surgeon and the pastor.
</P>
<P>
   I read that book in my head many nights for months.
</P>
<P>
   Saw the flash of light, the mushroom cloud. Saw hanging flesh
and bare trees, day turned into night.
</P>
<P>
   I have read the book many times since. Every page makes me feel
11 years old _ small in the face what we have the capacity to
inflict. Frightened.
</P>
<P>
   Like I felt for a minute Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   I watched and listened to bombing coverage as the night wore on,
waiting for another minute like that one. It never came. Baghad's
nighttime green gave way to daylight. The streets looked largely
undamaged. The talk in Washington balanced the mission with the
president's self-made distress.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I opened my eyes in the dead of one more night, it
wasn't to shadows burned into the sidewalk, but to the sound of my
wife's breathing.
</P>
<P>
   I listened to her a long time. I felt so young and so very old.
The bombs felt far away and all too close. Twenty years never felt
shorter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
