<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6909 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR &LR;      12-18 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'LL SURVIVE IMPEACHMENT  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE DEC. 18 ARIZONA REPUBLIC)  
 (FOR USE BY N.Y. TIMES NEWS SERVICE CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   By XXXXXX  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - At long last, the full House of Representatives has
begun deciding whether to impeach President Clinton. For all the
fits and starts, unseemly revelations and even bombing attacks, we
have arrived at this historic vote with the president having had
any number of opportunities to explain himself honestly, to present
his case candidly.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Clinton has done neither.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year, the president has twisted and dodged and
sought to evade accusations that he violated the law. In plain
language, he has yet to fess up to much of anything. Now Clinton's
lack of credibility clouds even the motives behind his decision to
bomb Baghdad on Wednesday. If anything, the timing of that foray
into Iraq has stiffened the resolve of House Republicans to deal
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It may be, as even some of his apologists argue, that Clinton is
incapable of telling the truth or of expressing real remorse over
his efforts to conceal his relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. That is a failing, and, however papered
over by supporters, it is hardly a reason to hand the president a
free pass or allow him to duck the legal consequences of his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming vote is a rendezvous with truth and conscience. The
House will vote on four articles of impeachment that accuse Clinton
of perjury in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, perjury
before a federal grand jury, obstructing justice and misusing or
abusing the power of his office. All four stem from Clinton's
efforts to cover up his affair with Lewinsky. If the House votes to
impeach, as seems likely, the matter will go to the Senate for a
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who has alternately been fascinated with and
anguished about his place in history, is about to land next to
Andrew Johnson, who was impeached by the House, and somewhere near
Richard Nixon, who underwent his own presidential impeachment
crisis and resigned. Is it any wonder Clinton signaled last week
that he was ``ready to accept'' the rebuke and censure of Congress?
</P>
<P>
   (Even that _ ``ready to accept'' _ connotes an arrogant
assumption that Clinton has a choice in the matter.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's many defenders contend that while he has not been
truthful, his lies have been about a rather trifling matter in the
scheme of things _ sex. They contend that perjury and obstruction
of justice do not rise to the level of high crimes and
misdemeanors. In fact, theirs is a world where the president enjoys
executive privilege and is above the law. Committing perjury, on
videotape, is just one of those things that happens, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the very foundation of our justice system _ the
value of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen one argument after another against impeachment
topple over, Democratic leaders and liberal intellectuals now warn
of dire consequences for the nation if Clinton is impeached and the
Senate begins a trial on whether to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintonian mantra is that impeachment puts America on the
brink of a crisis. The nation will be plunged into months of pain
and despair. Why, even the stock market, the only barometer of
importance to some Americans, is allegedly quaking because of
political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   This nation has survived wars, assassinations, riots and any
number of corrupt politicians. It certainly is big enough to handle
an impeachment trial. In a decade of highly publicized trials,
maybe it is appropriate that the Clinton presidency should wind up
in the town stockade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fears of Clinton supporters and perhaps others, it
is hard to see the Senate dwelling for months on a trial. This body
will want to dispose of the issue as quickly as possible, opening
the door to some sort of tough censure. That would allow Clinton to
hang onto his tarnished office and contemplate what might have
been.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton supporters, who have been quick to cite polls showing
public opposition to impeachment, can't be encouraged by the latest
polls. A ``Wall Street Journal''/NBC News survey shows that 44
percent would prefer that, if impeached, Clinton resign.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he should or not, Clinton seems likely to survive the
impeachment process _ just as the nation will. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
