<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-FUTURE-BOS &LR;      12-18 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOALS OF THE AIR ATTACKS SIGNAL A US POLICY SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS AND COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What happens after the bombing stops?
</P>
<P>
   Under fire for launching missile against Iraq without a
long-term strategy, President Clinton's national security team
Thursday responded by disclosing a broad plan: aiming to crush
Iraq's defenses, destroy biological and chemical weapons
production, increase unrest in the Iraqi army and ultimately topple
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   In public statements and briefings to Congress, officials
described the plan as a dramatic change in what had for years been
an effort to ``contain'' Hussein and control his weapons
development.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration has been reluctant to reveal details,
plans under consideration include drastic measures such as
declaring all of Iraq a ``no-fly, no troop-movement zone'' so that
Hussein cannot use his warplanes or dispatch his soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a seminal shift in the attitude of the
administration, as I read it,'' said Joseph R. Biden Jr. of
Delaware, the top-ranking Democrat on the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, who has been in regular touch with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. ``Put it this way, I'd be surprised if at the
end of a three- four- or five-day air campaign the adminstration
said, `Well, we've done our job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the strike say that President Clinton launched
strikes merely to punish Iraq or deflect attention from impeachment
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Said Al-Sahaf
accused the US and British governments of exaggerating reports of
Iraq's weapons development and telling ``cheap lies in order to
deceive the world, in order to have the pretext to commit
aggression against Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is not alone. Some of the most virulent criticism came
Thursday from Russia. The State Department Thursday announced that
Russia had recalled its ambassador to Washington to protest the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Organization of the Islamic Conference, a group
representing Muslim countries, issued a statement saying, ``Iraq
finds itself subject to military strikes which come under
mysterious circumstances with no clear objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has given mixed messages about its
objectives in this campaign. Just a month ago, Clinton called off
an attack on Iraq, saying it would lead other countries to end
inspections by the UN Special Commision, or UNSCOM. But Thursday,
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said the ``medium-term
goal'' of the attack is to have ``a strong, professional,
functioning UNSCOM with unfettered access to be able to continue to
do its work.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate objective of the bombing is to ``degrade''
Hussein's ability to make biological, chemical and nuclear weapons
and attack his command and control centers, Albright said. The
ultimate objective, she indicated, is to overthrow Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key word is `degrade' because it allows them to declare
any victory at any point,'' said Howard Diamond, an expert with the
Arms Control Association in Washington. ``If you bomb two targets
and hit one, you can still say that you have degraded Iraq's
capacity to build weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Even supporters say the administration is taking a risky turn
that could, at the very least, lead to an expensive commitment of
US troops near Iraq for years to come. Also, the effort could cause
a backlash that isolates the United States at the United Nations
and leads to the end of weapons inspections and an easing of
economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, a senior UN official predicted that
Russia, China, France and other countries critical of the attack
would lead an effort to derail or end the UN Special Commission, or
UNSCOM. ``There is good reason to believe we could get totally
thrown out period _ buzz off,'' he said. ``No oil-for-food (deals).
No UNSCOM, and the erosion of economic sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its limits, the inspection team has served as an
important group of eyes and ears in Baghdad for the past seven
years. Even when the Iraqi government turned away inspectors from
sites, that was a tip to Washington that Saddam Hussein wanted to
hide something, said Richard Shultz, a professor of international
politics at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts
University and former consultant to the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the inspections could deprive the US government of
one of the few reliable sources of information it has inside Iraq,
he said. ``If you change your strategy and now you're going to try
control Saddam's weapons of mass destruction production through
military strikes, then will you ever have the intelligence you
need?''
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, Russia started lobbying to remake a less
aggressive UNSCOM with fewer British and American inspectors.
Russia called for a more ``professional'' and ``objective'' group
of inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Albright and Clinton have called top officials from
more than 20 countries to rally support. The effort has taken the
edge off of some of the sharp words. Although China and Russia
condemned the strike, France muted its criticism Thursday. ``I
don't know the solution to this problem,'' Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's new government voiced strong backing for the attack,
as Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said, ``There is no question
whatsoever about our solidarity with the international community,
and with our alliance partners the United States and Great
Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab countries have reacted cautiously to the strikes, which
might continue through the first days of Ramadan, the holy month,
this weekend. But American diplomats said the Arab leaders have
been supportive in private countries because they are so wary of
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   The attack has provided encouragement to fractious Iraqi
opposition, which is seeking undercover assistance as well as $97
million in military aid that money the US Congress set aside to
help seize power in Baghdad. But the administration, concerned that
the opposition groups have scant support inside the country, has
not been able to settle on any .
</P>
<P>
   Senator Biden said Republicans have criticized President Clinton
for failing to choose an opposition group, yet Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott and other critics also have been unable to settle
on a group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Fine, give me a name... Come on Trent, say it out
loud, ' '' Biden told reporters Thursday. ``Come on fella, speak
up. You say, `I have a plan to overthrow (Hussein)'? Okay, tell
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
