<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6943 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MINORITIES-BO     12-18 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MINORITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME BLACKS, NEW FEARS OF AN ALLY'S FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most Americans see the vote on whether to impeach
President Clinton as a unique event, something they might see once
in a lifetime, or even once in a century. But for some black
Americans, it all has a familiar ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many African-Americans fear now that anybody that stands up
for us like Bill Clinton has, that someone always tries to come and
get them,'' said the Rev. Earl Nance Jr., who raised the point in
his sermon last Sunday at the Greater Mount Carmel Baptist Church
in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, Kennedy was shot. Carter did only one term,''
said Hank Thompson, a Missouri political consultant and black-radio
talk show host. ``This is almost the same soup warmed over. Any
elected official that shows any kind of interest in equity or fair
play and diversity _ something inevitably happens to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the House moves toward an impeachment vote,
African-American leaders are divided over whether the effort to
eject Clinton from office would energize black voters with anger,
or only increase feelings of alienation.
</P>
<P>
   The debate comes in a year that African-American leaders battled
a frustrating and false rumor that blacks would lose the right to
vote in eight years, when the Voting Rights Act of 1965 comes up
for renewal. Many were also forced to repeatedly knock down a false
rumor that federal regulators planned to ban gospel programs from
radio.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the rumors illustrated the insecurity that some blacks
feel about their place in American society. They fear those
feelings might grow if Congress removes a president who is
overwhelmingly supported by black voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People believing this hoax about their voting rights having to
be renewed _ that comes from black people knowing their own history
of being left outside the mainstream,'' said Representative James
Clyburn, the South Carolina Democrat who is incoming chairman of
the Congressional Black Caucus. Impeaching and removing the
president, he said, ``would reinforce that and give those feelings
legs.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment battle has also spawned rumors. Waiting for the
bus at the Dudley Square station Tuesday, John Pight offered one of
his own: That White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky was, in fact, a
Republican plant whose job was to prey on the president's
weaknesses and discredit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they had to do was get some intern in, knowing how he
is,'' said Pight, 30, a cook at Northeastern University. ``The
Republicans are for the rich and the Democrats are for the poor.
That's why they tried to get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won loyalty from the black community years ago, and he
has cemented it by initiating a dialogue on race and highlighting
the pain of the US slave trade during a trip to Africa. His Cabinet
has included black members like Alexis Herman at the Labor
Department, Hazel O'Leary at Energy, Michael Espy at Agriculture,
and the late Ronald Brown at Commerce. A black man, Vernon E.
Jordan Jr., is among his closest friends. A black woman, Betty
Currie, is among his top personal staff.
</P>
<P>
   Only a month ago, black voters produced their largest turnout at
the polls in 10 years as they helped Clinton's party make
unexpected gains in Congress. About 89 percent of the black vote
went to Democrats this year, up from 82 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Today on black radio, a pro-Clinton novelty song has become one
of the most-requested tunes. ``Leave Bill Clinton Alone,'' croons
Larry Shannon Hargrove. ``Everybody's done something wrong. You
just don't like him 'cause he wears dark glasses and plays the
saxophone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People love that record,'' said Travis Gardner, program
director at KCOH radio in Houston. ``They constantly ask for it.
Even on our talk shows, they're playing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, in Missouri, said, ``Some people hated what he did in
signing welfare reform, but Clinton has a real affinity'' for the
African-American community. ``He just seems very, very comfortable.
You contrast that with 12 years of Reagan and Bush, and he's almost
like a black angel.''
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers took up the impeachment debate, it was hard to
ignore the black support for Clinton. The Rainbow/Push Coalition,
led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson, held a prayer vigil outside the
Capitol Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If the effort to block impeachment fails, some fear that black
voting could decline. ``It doesn't do any good for the morale of
the African-American community, when they see a president forced
out who is sensitive to their issues, who has a Cabinet that
reflects them,'' said Nance.
</P>
<P>
   But state Representative Byron Rushing, a Boston Democrat, said
any disappointment would be overshadowed by the victory blacks feel
in having produced a large voter turnout last month. ``The reaction
in the black community in this last election was that they had done
something good,'' Rushing said.
</P>
<P>
   Tavis Smiley, host of a weeknight talk show on Black
Entertainment Television, said Republicans could ultimately be hurt
the most by voting for impeachment. The GOP could find it difficult
to maintain a majority in a nation that is increasingly brown and
black, Smiley said.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, impeachment could undo any benefits that House
Republicans won by naming a black congressmen, Representative J.C.
Watts of Oklahoma, to the coveted position of GOP conference
chairman. ``This effort to crush the president takes away anything
they might have picked up with the elevation of J.C. Watts to a
leadership position,'' Smiley said. ``It's going to hurt the
Republicans tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   (Zitner reported from Washington and Kornblut from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
