<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FRIENDS-BOS &LR;      12-18 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FRIENDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO CLINTON FRIENDS, LOYALTY AN OPEN QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the day the Gennifer Flowers story nearly
destroyed Bill Clinton's presidential campaign in 1992, Clinton
survived with the help of ``Friends of Bill'' such as
Representative W. J. ``Billy'' Tauzin of Louisiana. Tauzin endorsed
Clinton and helped keep the campaign alive among skeptical Southern
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood by him at his moment of crisis,'' Tauzin said about
the Flowers episode. But, as president, Clinton lied to get
Tauzin's vote for a budget bill, the lawmaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, a Democrat-turned-Republican, announced Wednesday he was
leaning toward voting for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, perhaps more than at any time in his life, Clinton needs
help from his FOB's, the Friends of Bill who have guided him
through so many crises. But it may be too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take friends who helped you and tried to work with
you and then you burn them, where do you turn to in this crisis?''
Tauzin said in an interview. ``I'm convinced that there isn't a
friend he wouldn't sell out for his own purposes. I'm convinced
that he doesn't even recognize the consequences of those acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Hillary Rodham Clinton, who famously stood by her husband
in a ``60 Minutes'' interview in the 1992 campaign and who earlier
this year blamed a ``right-wing conspiracy'' for Clinton's
problems, has been silent. An NBC News report this week caused a
buzz in Washington by saying that Mrs. Clinton ``was seen brushing
away her husband's arm'' when the couple visited the grave site of
Yitzhak Rabin, the former Israeli prime minister. But White House
officials insisted the movement was subtle and misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, according to her spokeswoman Marsha Berry, is
``very engaged'' in the strategy to stop impeachment, including
discussions with some members of Congress. Asked why Mrs. Clinton
hasn't talked publicly about whether she has forgiven her husband,
Berry responded: ``Mainly because she considers it a private
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton's supporters in the House appear strained in
their defense. Most Democrats who oppose impeachment quickly add
that they condemn the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the start of his presidency, Clinton has had a
reputation for dumping friends when it suited his political
purposes. He walked away from his first two nominees for attorney
general, Zoe Baird and Kimba Wood. Then he dropped the nomination
of Lani Guinier to be the Justice Department's civil rights chief
when critics labeled her _ unfairly, she said _ ``quota queen.''
Clinton also failed to fight for a number of his judicial nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Clinton's friends came with him from Arkansas, only to
be beset by troubles in Washington. Former White House deputy
counsel Vincent Foster committed suicide, and former associate
attorney general Webster Hubbell was jailed for embezzling funds
from law firm clients.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin's relationship with Clinton provides a case study in how
a friendship failed. The Louisiana congressman vividly recalls the
day reports surfaced that Flowers had an affair with Clinton,
because Tauzin stood on a platform with the Arkansas governor and
endorsed him during the primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got many conservatives and Republicans to support him in his
first bid for the presidency,'' Tauzin said. ``It is hard not to
like the guy. He is one of the most charming people you will ever
meet in politics. That is probably one of the reasons he remains as
popular as he is. People want to be his friend from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after Clinton was elected, the president promised
Tauzin and others he would eliminate a proposed energy tax if they
would support his budget. Tauzin and the others agreed, only to
learn later that Clinton was retaining the energy tax, which later
was dropped for other reasons. Tauzin turns angry as he recalls the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lied to me and they stole my vote, took it under false
pretenses,'' Tauzin said. ``That to me is a worse offense than what
he is charged with now . . . I ought to be public about this
prejudice.'' As Tauzin was deciding how to vote on impeachment, he
said he would not talk with Clinton because ``I wouldn't believe a
word he says.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Clinton is not ousted from office, it might be because
he has been able to count on a small circle of friends who remain
loyal. Unlike during the Watergate years, when former White House
counsel John Dean and others provided incriminating evidence
against President Nixon, no one has come forward in a similar way
to hurt Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, friends such as lawyer Vernon E. Jordan Jr.,
who helped Monica S. Lewinsky get a job, and White House deputy
counsel Bruce Lindsey, who has refused to testify about what he
considers to be privileged conversations with Clinton, have done
their best to back up the president's version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, such help has not been enough to avert the pending
House vote on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, Ark., meanwhile, some of Clinton's closest
friends say they will be by his side no matter what happens in the
House or during a possible Senate trial. Some of the original
``Arkansas Travelers,'' who traveled throughout the nation in 1992
to boost Clinton's candidacy, met this week at the local Democratic
Party headquarters to demonstrate their support.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the president's friends recalled being upset when
Clinton admitted in August that he had an inappropriate
relationship with Lewinsky. One of his closest friends, Arkansas
lawyer Joe Purvis, said, ``There is no question that Clinton let
his friends down. There was a period of time right after the
announcement that you were really mad, then you come back and you
put it in perspective.'' Purvis said he remains friends with
Clinton and called the impeachment effort ``absolute insanity.''
Skip Rutherford, a Clinton friend who chose to remain in Arkansas
rather than take a job in the Clinton administration, said the
current scandal has only reinforced friendships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The friends of the Clintons are stronger now than ever
before,'' Rutherford said. ``Friendship runs very deep, and it is
not based on whether there are good times or bad times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
