u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-18 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERSHIP STUBS ITS TOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton-haters running Congress made it two-in-a-row in
committing colossal blunders this week, and it's still only Friday.
So blinded are they by hate that they risk alienating all but the
most rabid voters. The Sun Belt Commandoes running this lynch mob
displayed a shaky grasp as they launched their anti-Clinton
impeachment coup.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi led off with an
incredible gaffe. Even before the first US cruise missile zeroed in
on Iraqi military targets, Lott denounced the strike. ``I cannot
support this military action in the Persian Gulf at this time,''
Lott declared defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted a day; Thursday he summoned a CNN crew to hem and
haw: yeah, sure, of course I support the troops, ``We want to make
sure we have a united front in this effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott can be smarmy on even his best days, but Thursday he was at
his smarmiest. ``We should have acted &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (against Iraq) in February, and November,'' he rambled. Then he
coughed up a half-baked apology of sorts. ``I believe that there is
no relationship,'' he said, between the impeachment threat and
Clinton's decision to order military action.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he had been convinced &UR;  &LR; by Defense Secretary William
Cohen, a former GOP senator, and the joint chiefs of staff, that
politics did not play a key role. ``I am satisfied this was a
military decision,'' oozed Lott, backing away from his stance of
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Judy Woodruff would not let him off the hook so easily. In
1990, she reminded Lott, you said senators who refused to support
the Gulf War ``could be giving aid and comfort to Saddam Hussein.''
Lott winced, then fell back, mumbling about how the Democrats
opposed President Bush's Gulf War launch. He was only one of a
couple of hundred Republicans who had to scramble to regain their
political equilibrium after the Iraq strike upset the GOP's
impeachment applecart.
</P>
<P>
   Initial polls showed 3-1 support for the strike against Iraqi
chemical and biological weapons sites. Clinton's job approval
rating of 68 percent is the year's highest. Impeachment is still
opposed by a solid majority of all polled. Yet the GOP then made
Blunder No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bob Livingston of Louisiana, the man elected to
replace Newt Gingrich as speaker, emerged from the House Republican
Caucus to declare that Clinton would win only a 24-hour delay in
his impeachment. Thursday, Livingston, who has ducked most public
appearances since toppling Gingrich, took the House floor to
announce that on Day 3 of war with Iraq, Clinton would face
impeachment in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston and Lott: two of a kind. This pair raise backstabbing
to a whole new level. They and their lieutenants, busily
undermining Clinton as he presides over a shooting war, have
shattered the century-old American political practice of shelving
partisan differences when troops are in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   The public's verdict all year has been that the ambushing of
Clinton was a partisan deal from the get-go. Livingston tried to
duck his role, but cannot hide any longer after being drawn into
the impeachment morass.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of Americans don't know Livingston from Adam,
polls show. And the Bayou Bookkeeper is clearly not ready for prime
time. He was nervous and barely articulate in a news conference
announcing he'd push for a quick impeachment vote. Livingston, who
once donned a red clown nose and a blue clown hat on the floor of
the House in a debate about campaign finance reform, is not nearly
as nimble-witted as Gingrich, driven from office by the same
right-wingers he personally recruited for his majority.
</P>
<P>
   Head bobbing like Big Bird, babbling about how the Democrats
were against the Vietnam War and opposed aid for ``the Freedom
Fighters'' of Central America under Reagan, Livingston did not make
a reassuring impression. He had been similarly obdurate in hosting
a meeting of feminists, who left his office furious over his
dismissal of their objections to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   With hard-line Texans like Majority Leader Dick Armey and whip
Tom ``The Hammer'' DeLay knuckling moderate Republicans into the
impeachment press gang, the Republican Party is risking its future
on this hotheaded, intemperate, unfair, and unpatriotic bid to dump
Clinton with a war going on.
</P>
<P>
   The backstabbing is disgraceful. It cannot fail to galvanize
public support behind Clinton. The lesson of the week is what
Clinton said of Saddam: ``If you act recklessly, you will pay a
heavy price.'' Saddam stiffed the UN weapons inspectors and is
eating cruise missiles as his price. Clinton was reckless with
Monica Lewinsky and is still paying his staggering price.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Belt firm of Lott &AMP; Livingston is also acting
recklessly, and the price they pay will not be exacted for 23
months, the election in which the control of House, Senate, and
White House is at stake. They will reap what they sow.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
