<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6953 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-18 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCENES OUT OF ORWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On Wednesday, George Orwell's hand was on Page One of the
Globe, printing All the Doublespeak That's Fit to Print.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut General Assembly, which oversees horrific gaps
between rich and poor, threw $375 million of corporate welfare at
the Patriots in the form of a new stadium. Despite all the analysis
that stadiums lose big money for taxpayers, Governor John Rowland
said the stadium will ``change the landscape of this community for
the rest of our lifetimes.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Republicans, unshamed by their losses in the
midterm elections, sped toward the impeachment of President Bill
Clinton. Speaker-elect Robert Livingston went so far as to claim
that Clinton's lies to cover up an affair were worse than the lies
of President Nixon to steal democracy itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Nixon's crime was covering up a crime he did not
commit,'' Livingston said. ``Clinton is covering up a crime he did
commit, and that is a large difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, running away from impeachment and from the fact that
his barely postpubescent acts with a subordinate, while hardly
Nixonian, would have been a fireable offense in his own military,
was marching us toward Wednesday night's bombing of Iraq. So far,
America applauds Clinton, who has made us believe Saddam Hussein, a
chump in 1991 when we overran his troops in mere hours, is suddenly
again Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, we have been made to believe that this is war by
video game. Send in a few missiles, show no pictures of US soldiers
at risk, and you have the instantly acceptable war.
</P>
<P>
   With Orwell's hand at work, it was fitting that Page One also
featured the demise of board games. Today's children, because of
rushed or disintegrating families, now seek solitary confinement in
the hyper hypnosis of action-packed and often murderous video
games. How better to prepare America for surgical strikes?
</P>
<P>
   Since I do not believe in smart bombs or surgical strikes,
especially since we have yet to hit Hussein himself, Clinton should
be shish kebabbed in history for killing yet more innocent Iraqi
women, children, and civilians, and especially so if we come to
find that the timing had anything to do ultimately with the fact
that he could not keep his pants zipped up.
</P>
<P>
   If Orwell really were the editor, the accompanying editorial for
these events could be lifted right out of his 1949 novel ``1984,''
from the part where Winston Smith is reading ``WAR IS PEACE'':
</P>
<P>
   ``War, however is no longer the desperate, annihilating struggle
that it was in the early decades of the 20th century. It is a
warfare of limited aims between combatants who are unable to
destroy one another, have no material cause for fighting, and are
not divided by any genuine ideological difference . . . in a
physical sense war involves very small numbers of people, mostly
highly trained specialists, and causes comparatively few
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fighting, when there is any, takes place on the vague
frontiers whose whereabouts the average man can only guess at . . .
In the centers of civilization war means no more than a continuous
shortage of consumption goods, and the occasional crash of a rocket
bomb which may cause a few scores of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no longer, in a material sense, anything to fight
about. With the establishment of self-contained economies, in which
production and consumption are geared to one another, the scramble
for markets which was a main cause of previous wars has come to an
end, while the competition for raw materials is no longer a matter
of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary aim of modern warfare (in accordance with the
principles of doublethink, this aim is simultaneous recognized and
not recognized by the directing brains of the Inner Party) is to
use up the products of the machine without raising the general
standard of living . . . In the early 20th century, the vision of a
future society unbelievably rich, leisured, orderly, and efficient
_ a glittering antiseptic world of glass and steel and snow-white
concrete _ was part of the consciousness of nearly every literate
person. Science and technology were developing at a prodigious
speed, and it seemed natural to assume that they would go on
developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was also clear that . . . if it once became general,
wealth would confer no distinction. It was possible, no doubt to
imagine a society in which wealth, in the sense of personal
possessions and luxuries, should be even distributed, while power
remained in the hands of a small privileged caste.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in practice such a society could not long remain stable.
For if leisure and security were enjoyed by all alike, the great
mass of human beings who are normally stupefied by poverty would
become literate and would learn to think for themselves; and when
once they had done this, they would sooner or later realize that
the privileged minority had no function, and they would sweep it
away. In the long run, a hierarchical society was only possible on
the basis of poverty and ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
