<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6959 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALTIMORE-CRIME-ART-B     12-18 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-CRIME-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMICIDES HAUNT BALTIMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ This city is in a race against time to save lives _
12 of them, to be precise. The problem is, no one knows whose lives
are at risk, where they live or why they are in peril.
</P>
<P>
   All anyone knows is that if all 12 die in the two weeks before
the new year, the loss would extend far beyond the sorrow of
families and friends. Their deaths would be a blow to this city's
latest attempt to save itself.
</P>
<P>
   While other cities large and small have been basking in the
glory of plummeting homicide rates, Baltimore's widespread poverty,
entrenched drug trade, and a shoot-first culture in certain
neighborhoods have conspired to buck the national trend.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with pressure and criticism mounting, police officials have
declared they will do everything in their power _ primarily
flooding the streets with formerly desk-bound officers _ to keep
the number of homicides below the 310 recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
   But with two weeks to go, the death count is 298 _ 12 away from
the fateful total. The latest was a man found Tuesday night, dead
in a truck with gunshot wounds, the 15th homicide since the
lifesaving initiative began Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I know we have wrung every possible officer out of
administrative jobs and put them out there, then I know we have
done everthing we can do to bring down that (1997) number,'' said
police Commissioner Thomas C. Frazier. Almost as an afterthought,
he added: ``The goal here is public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   As Frazier's comments demonstrated, the motivation is a
combination of concern for life and the knowledge that in the world
of big-city policing, there is little that counts more these days
than falling crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   Crime statistics _ particularly homicide rates _ have become
national news and a benchmark for municipal quality-of-life
comparisons. To civic boosters, low crime rates mean tourist
dollars, economic development, local pride, and job security for
politicians and police chiefs. High rates jeopardize all that.
</P>
<P>
   Cities including New York, Chicago, and Boston have seen sharp
drops in homicide numbers. Baltimore is among the also-rans,
trailing only Gary, Ind., New Orleans, and Detroit for the highest
rates. Last year, Boston's 44 homicides equaled about eight per
100,000 people; this year, there have been 35 homicides to date in
the city of 558,000 people. By contrast, in Baltimore, with its
population of 675,000, 310 homicides last year translated into
about 46 per 100,000 people, more than five times Boston's rate.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is ghoulishly fitting that Baltimore is the
scene of the NBC series, ``Homicide: Life on the Street.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no single reason for Baltimore's homicide problem,
though observers often cite an unusually high concentration of poor
people, IV drug users, and cocaine dealers _ the crack epidemic
arrived in the early 1990s, several years after it hit other
cities. Police blame three-quarters of the killings on drug dealers
and users.
</P>
<P>
   However, others downplay the role of crack by noting that in the
past 25 years there have been more than 200 homicides in every year
but two, and more than 300 in each of the past eight years. They
cite an entrenched culture in which violence is seen as the
problem-solver of first resort, particularly among some residents
in the row houses of West Baltimore, East Baltimore, and Park
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baltimore represents some of the best in urban America, but
also faces some of the worst problems of urban America,'' said
three-term Mayor Kurt L. Schmoke. Though he supports the police
effort, he acknowledged it would be foolhardy to declare victory
simply for keeping the homicide total below 310.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply a psychological barrier. In order to come to grips
with the problem, we need a series of years in which the homicide
numbers are going down significantly,'' Schmoke said.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, Baltimore has enjoyed a drop in other violent and
nonviolent crime rates, and the number of homicides is down from
the peak years in the early 1990s. But the city knows that isn't
enough for public safety or public relations, particularly since
Baltimore also has been in the news recently for having the
nation's highest rates of syphillis and gonorrhea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an obsession with crime statistics, and police
departments are under tremendous pressure right now,'' said Jack
Levin, director of the Brudnick Center for the Study of Violence at
Northeastern University. ``Police are being pressured to do the
right thing _ partnerships with residents, community policing,
supervising youngsters _ so I don't think it's all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But some cities, including Philadelphia, have responded to the
pressure by allegedly fabricating their crime data to make the
numbers look rosier. Homicide rates, however, are rarely open to
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   In quiet conversation, Baltimore police acknowledge they are
playing with fire by setting the goal of keeping the homicide total
below 310. While eager to reap the benefits of a decline _ even one
as statistically meaningless as one or two fewer killings _ there
is a down side to the high-profile effort. If the 1998 total
exceeds 310, Levin said, the department risks a further erosion of
public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   At roll call Tuesday night at the Tactical Section Room in the
department's downtown headquarters, Lieutenant Donald E. Healy
rallied his troops to keep that from happening: ``Make the drug
dealers' lives miserable,'' he urged them. ``Let's keep those
shootings down. Another 15 days and we'll be all right.'' Behind
him was a bulletin board with 224 Polaroid photos of guns seized
this year during arrests; one more would be added before the night
was out.
</P>
<P>
   Before the antihomicide initiative, a night shift would consist
of about 240 uniformed officers citywide, not including drug units,
plainclothes officers, and detectives, out of a total of 3,200
sworn officers. With the homicide initiative, up to 100 extra
police officers per shift have been pulled from administrative jobs
and put on the street; paperwork is piling up on empty desks.
</P>
<P>
   A tour on the night shift with Officers Chris Timms and Guy
Thacker offered a window on the problems linked to the homicide
rate. The pair drove relentlessly and aggressively through the
roughest parts of West Baltimore, brooming young men off street
corners only to see them reassemble soon after nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood varied from neat, attached-brick homes with
marble stoops, to burned out, boarded up, falling down row houses
that serve as temporary homes for crack users. Young men stopped by
Timms and Thacker were familiar with the routine, quickly pulling
up their shirts to show no weapons in their waistbands.
</P>
<P>
   During the shift, the pair recorded one arrest, charging a
23-year-old man with possession of narcotics with intent to
distribute. Citywide that night, police recorded 11 arrests, one
seized gun, 112 field interviews, 65 car stops and 14 moving
violations. The worst event seemed to be a head-on crash between a
police cruiser and a Toyota Tercel that left no one seriously
injured. But then, after midnight, police received the report of a
man with the gunshot wounds to the back. That brought the total to
297. Later in the day, it rose to 298.
</P>
<P>
   Community activists have supported the police department's
December drive, though some said it was not enough. ``I think it's
great, but it should be all year. We shouldn't get to the point
where the last minute you're trying to keep your numbers down,''
said funeral home owner Samuel Redd, director of Operation Pulse, a
crime-prevention group in East Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, who became police commissioner here five years ago
after a 28-year career in San Jose, Calif., acknowledged that
point, noting that even his wife had asked him what would happen on
New Year's Day and beyond. He said the department will assess the
program's success and decide what to do then.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the street-level efforts, a multiagency task force has
been seeking strategies with help from David Kennedy, senior
researcher at the John F. Kennedy School of Government and director
of the Boston Gun Project, which has been credited with helping to
stem violence in Boston. Kennedy declined to outline results of the
Baltimore study, which will be unveiled next year, but offered hope
that this city does not have to fix all its problems at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the pieces of good news out of the Boston experience is
you can at least hope to intervene against violence without
believing you first have to get rid of all the drugs and the drug
trade,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the rate of killings approaching one a day here,
officers such as Timms and Thacker have grown skeptical. As Thacker
put it, ``If somebody wants to kill somebody, they're always going
to find a way to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
