<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV-IMAGE-BOS &LR;      12-18 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV-IMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION IS HIS HOLE CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - As the media's attention bounced from the bombing
of Iraq to the prospects for Bill Clinton's impeachment, NBC news
anchor Tom Brokaw asked Clinton biographer David Maraniss if the
president had any more cards to play to ward off impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Maraniss replied, ``but Bill Clinton has
more than 52 cards in his deck.''
</P>
<P>
   The 53d card in Bill Clinton's deck has always been television.
No one can say what the ultimate effect of the raids will be, but
at Clinton's greatest times of trouble his mastery of the medium
has had a dramatic effect on his popularity. From his ``60
Minutes'' and ``Arsenio'' appearances that helped rescue his
initial candidacy through the presidential debates to his televised
testimony before a federal grand jury, Clinton has controlled
attention when he has controlled the television image, perhaps even
more so than John Kennedy or Ronald Reagan. Giving Clinton access
to Americans in their living rooms seems to give him access to
their approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's recent appearances have not been his most impressive,
although perhaps even his weariness has worked to his favor _
underscoring the burdens of leadership in a time of crisis. He has
appeared emotional when necessary (as during his recent trip to
Israel), but also in control of his emotions (his cool rebuke to
Republican skepticism about the timing of this attack).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his Wednesday night address and his quasi-impromptu
give-and-take with reporters Thursday, Clinton rode the rising
polling waves on the basis of what the country was seeing on their
televisions. The media backdrop of Baghdad featured a large yellow
poster of Saddam Hussein, as if to underline Peter Jennings's
assertion that ``it has been clear, going back to George Bush, that
if a president wanted to pick on a foreign leader, Saddam Hussein
would be the easiest target.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening images of the attack were even more antiseptic than
those during the Gulf War, giving the illusion of a war largely
without casualties. When an Iraqi family was standing on a street
corner as the air raid was sounding, Brokaw even joked, ``If you
think it's hard getting a cab in New York City . . .'' before
realizing he had been too flip and correcting himself: ``It's not
comical, it's tragic.'' If all this supposed calm gave the illusion
of a war without casualties, it also made it apparent this was a
military action without any negative consequences for Clinton.
Quite the opposite, at least so far.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, of course, there were scenes of destruction in Iraq,
although nothing as heart-rending as the grief over the death of
civilians in a shelter during the Gulf War. The newscasts were
basically respectful of Republican skepticism over the timing of
the bombing, although ABC's John Cochran ended his report on the
subject with, ``Go outside of Washington and it's hard to find
people who think President Clinton could order air strikes just to
delay (the impeachment process).''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republicans were having a generally terrible time
on television. It began with Tom DeLay and other House Republicans
announcing they weren't supporting the mission only to have cold
water thrown on suggestions that Clinton was lauching the strike as
part of a ``Wag the Dog'' scenario. Anchors announced that
Republican Senator Jesse Helms had voiced his support for the
president. Gulf War hero Norman Schwarzkopf said, ``From a military
point of view, the timing was right for this mission.'' Brent
Scowcroft and others who had served in Republican administrations
echoed Schwarzkopf, although former Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger remained irate and skeptical. While American networks
and cable services tried to play their coverage down the middle
between the president and the Republicans, the BBC didn't hold
back. ``Isn't it inconceivable,'' asked the bemused anchor, ``that
(the Republicans) would look so partisan by withholding support?''
``It isn't inconceivable,'' replied the reporter, ``because it's
already happened.''
</P>
<P>
   As for House speaker-designate Bob Livingston _ buffeted by
revelations of his own infidelities _ he has done his party few
favors with his recent media appearances. Displaying a rather lean
and hungry look, Livingston fairly shouted out the news that the
GOP majority would only briefly delay impeachment proceedings _ as
if the microphone hadn't been invented.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton needs no such coaching. His ease in front of the camera
is a constant. His enemies wonder why people can't see through that
ease, but so did Ronald Reagan's. His ability to look into the
camera and convince people that he's one of them (talking about the
difficulties of modern marriage on ``60 Minutes'') and is on their
side (his debates with Bush) is clearly one key to his success,
although he obviously overplayed that card with his finger-pointing
classic: ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   What he doesn't have, unlike Reagan, is the ability to make
people like him. A Washington Post-ABC News poll released before
Thursday's bombing reported that 56 percent had an unfavorable view
of Clinton as a person, even as his approval ratings climbed over
60 percent. Like all national leaders, Clinton looks particularly
presidential at the onset of a military action despite his lack of
military service. ``Whatever else you think,'' said Maraniss,
``he's calm and collected.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ability to use television to rally people to his side
isn't likely to stop his impeachment in the House, but it may be
enough to save his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   As Maraniss said, ``Every time he's on the precipice, there's
something that pulls him back.'' That ``something'' could be that
Clinton was born for television as much as for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   (Ed Siegel is the Globe's theater critic and critic-at large,
and a former television critic.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
