<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST NOT IN HARMONY WITH HYMNODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an especially tiresome kind of churchman _ my father
was one _ who cannot slide into a pew without bemoaning the
intrusion of novelty into church practice. Among Episcopalians,
this takes the form of nostalgia for the 1928 prayer book,
beautifully written but long out of use. In Catholicism, these are
the people who natter on about the lovely Latin Mass, etc.
</P>
<P>
   I have become one of these people.
</P>
<P>
   The battle of the Bible, of course, was lost many years ago. The
Protestant denominations slid away from the elegant 17th-century
prose of King James's England, through the pedestrian cadences of
the Revised Standard text into the Classics Illustrated jabber of
the more recent Good News! pabulum. One anticipates the Rappers'
Bible to take its place in this continuum.
</P>
<P>
   I have suffered through the loss of the gorgeous US Navy Hymn
(``O, hear us when we cry to Thee/For those in peril on the sea'')
from my hymnal. More recently, I've endured the bowdlerizing of
such great Thanksgiving hymns as ``We Gather Together,'' which in
the modern version contains these lines, more appropriate for a
Marin County hot tub:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You draw us away
</P>
<P>
   from self-centered complaining
</P>
<P>
   You lead us and guide us
</P>
<P>
   in ways that are true.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But all this was bearable. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   It is fair to say that my wife and I nearly choked on these
nouveau lyrics to the familiar Christmas carol:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joy to the world! The Lord has come
</P>
<P>
   Let earth its praises sing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Huh? At least five generations of Americans have sung the second
line, ``Let earth receive her King.''
</P>
<P>
   Or what about ``Good Christian Friends, Rejoice'' instead of the
loathsome, patriarchal ``Good Christian Men, Rejoice''? I suppose I
can handle that. But when we arrived at ``O Come, All You
Faithful'' _ yes, ``You'' instead of ``Ye'' _ I gagged again.
</P>
<P>
   ``O come, let us adore Him'' was now ``O come in adoration.''
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here? Several things at once. Archaisms are out:
``Ye,'' ``thee,'' etc. are apparently too challenging for modern
Christians. The Lutherans turfed out the hymn ``Lo, How a Rose E'er
Blooming'' in favor of ``Lo, How a Rose Is Growing'' _ a line you
might find in a Burpee catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Gender bias is out. We've known this for some years, having
witnessed the gelding of numerous beautiful songs. For example, in
``Now Thank We All Our God,'' the line ``who from our mothers'
arms'' has become ``. . . our parents' arms,'' as if mothers no
longer gave birth to children. Worse still: The word ``sons'' has
been deleted from this memorable line of ``God Our Help in Ages
Past'':
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time, like an ever-rolling stream,
</P>
<P>
   Bears all its sons away
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Now it's:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bears all our years away
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as many liturgies no longer refer to the ``Holy Ghost''
(too pagan! too spooky!), some now seem to be suggesting that Jesus
Christ wasn't male. In liturgical newspeak, he's not Him and he's
not a king. It seems OK to call he/she/it ``Lord,'' even though
this is a male title.
</P>
<P>
   A man partially _ but only partially _ to blame for some of this
clunky ``inclusive'' language is Arthur Clyde, who helped collate a
new hymnal for the United Church of Christ. He says he's persona
non grata (quite rightly!) in his home parish for ditching the Navy
Hymn, and he gets quite an earful at Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we know this would be painful for some people? Yes,'' he
concedes. But he points out that the United Church of Christ and
other confessions have added excellent new songs to the hymnal, for
example, an amusing New Zealand carol about a meteorologically
``upside down'' Christmas. Furthermore, he notes that lyrics I
consider to be sacrosanct were themselves adaptations. The words to
``Silent Night'' were quite different 100 years ago (``Still the
night, Holy night'') and ``Hark! the Herald Angels Sing'' was
originally ``Hark, How All the Welkin Rings.''
</P>
<P>
   That has a nice sound . . . maybe we can change it back.
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe. &QC; 
com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HEARST-BOS &LR;      12-18 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HEARST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST IS FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ By the end, Steve Mariucci was virtually
apologetic, almost sorry the 49ers had to win a game this way. ``I
guess,'' said the San Francisco coach, ``this is a new version of
the West Coast offense.''
</P>
<P>
   New?
</P>
<P>
   This way, this running the football play after play, this
pushing the line of scrimmage 3 yards downfield before quarterback
Steve Young even handed off the ball, this punishment of the Lions
by the 49ers' offensive line, is as old as football itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' Young said when told of his coach's
label. ``I take a lot of pride in our West Coast offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The old West Coast offense, that is. Bill Walsh's child, now
grown into an adult of many disguises, but an offense that still
passes and passes. Still, Mariucci spoke with almost wonderment in
his voice when he said, ``We really won the game at the line of
scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   New?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearst'' was the reason last Monday for San Francisco's fame
and easy game, but ``Hearst'' is a name that has been associated
with San Francisco longer than the Golden Gate Bridge. William
Randolph Hearst ran the city's newspapers since the turn of the
century, Patty Hearst held up banks in San Francisco's and
Berkeley's wild times some 25 years ago, and the Hearst Castle is a
must-see for any tourist who ventures south of Carmel and Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   And now? Garrison Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   The man who turned San Francisco football back 20 years, 30
years, maybe even 40 years, all the way back to Hugh McElhenny and
John David Crow and Joe Perry, when the 49ers could and would and
did run the football. But nobody knows what to make of this in 1998
_ the San Francisco 49ers running the football.
</P>
<P>
   Six or seven or eight times Young would step up to the line of
scrimmage Monday, scan the Lions' defense, and call an audible from
a pass play to a running play. The Richter Scale has no numbers
high enough to measure the magnitude of this San Francisco
earthquake. Bill Walsh is said to be resting comfortably after the
initial shock of seeing this . . . this . . . this San Francisco
sacrilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't plan on running the ball as much as we did,'' said
Mariucci, almost as if he were confessing to a football sin. ``But
because it was working, we stayed with it. For us to throw for less
than 100 yards . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Is a blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but Bobb McKittrick, the 49ers' offensive line coach, could
not contain himself. ``This is the way football should be,'' said
McKittrick, the last of Walsh's assistants, saying what every line
coach dreams of saying and seeing, ``and Garrison Hearst is a great
running back.''
</P>
<P>
   How great?
</P>
<P>
   ``With apologies to Roger Craig _ but not with any apologies to
Ricky Watters _ Garrison Hearst is probably the best running back
we've had since I've been here,'' said McKittrick. ``He can run, he
can catch, and he may be the best blocker on the team. I'll tell
you, if he never ran the ball once and you asked him to block on
every play, Garrison would do it and he wouldn't say a word.''
</P>
<P>
   No arguments there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garrison Hearst is a lunch-bucket type of guy,'' said
McKittrick. ``You ask him to do something and he does it. And he
does it well.''
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Bobb McKittrick, Roger Craig was a very
valuable member of the great 49ers offenses of the 1980s, but Craig
was not a great runner. Dependable and very good, but not great.
And perhaps only San Franciscans can fathom McKittrick's need to
still dig at Watters, a flashy but undependable runner who seemed
so un-49er-like in his concern more for himself than his team.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst set the club record with 198 yards rushing last Monday, 4
more than Delvin Williams's previous standard, established in 1976.
Which, of course, was two years before Bill Walsh arrived with his
West Coast offense. Even more, the 49ers gained an astounding 328
yards rushing Monday and only 81 yards through the air, the third
straight game they have gained more than 200 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Which hadn't happened since 1954, 24 years before Walsh arrived
with his passing offense, his West Coast offense in which the
running play seemed like an asterisk or apostrophe in the 49ers'
game plans, there but hardly noticed.
</P>
<P>
   As his father, Gary, held his duffel bag and waited for his son,
Hearst would say little about his running. ``It's great to win the
game,'' he said, offering nothing about how effortlessly he swooped
around the Lions' cornerbacks time and again, how deftly he slipped
inside tackle for huge chunks inside, how quick and smooth he was
on virtually every run.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Edwards, the sociologist and consultant to the 49ers, gave
a hint of the Hearst that, apparently, is seldom shown to the
media. With the Lions in town and Barry Sanders the center of much
attention, Edwards recalled that ``Garrison said something to me
before the game: `People are coming expecting to see No. 20
(Sanders) run wild. I'll try not to disappoint them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now football fans know there is another No. 20 who can run, even
if he doesn't like to expound to the media. ``I can't rate my
games,'' Hearst said when asked to do just that. ``If we win, I'm
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   What is so satisfying about playing for the 49ers is the
attitude of the team. ``I've been in places (Arizona) where they
don't win games,'' said Hearst, ``and all they want to do is win
one more game than last year. You come here and they say, `Let's
win the Super Bowl. Again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely this lack of ego that makes Hearst stand out in
San Francisco. With Jerry Rice pulling rank to get more passes
thrown his way, with J.J. Stokes and Terrell Owens also unhappy
that more balls are not thrown their way, Hearst is just happy to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing in my career was when I went (to Arizona),''
said Hearst, ``and the best thing was when I left there.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing his college career at Georgia, Hearst was the star
runner of the 1993 draft, the fourth player taken overall, but he
tore a knee ligament and Arizona coach Buddy Ryan nearly tore
Hearst's spirit from his soul. The Cardinals released him after the
1995 season, thinking they could pick him up again, but Cincinnati
claimed him.
</P>
<P>
   And going from one losing team to another was made even worse
when then Bengals coach Dave Shula told Hearst that he'd be only a
backup to Ki-Jana Carter, the first player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's second to none.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough,'' said McKittrick, ``and he can run any play in
America's favorite playbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Including, as shocking to San Francisco as it is, the running
play. Any running play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
