<HEADLINE>
SUSAN TEDESCHI PUTS MILES ON THE VAN, HITS ON THE RADIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Does she or doesn't she sound like Janis Joplin? That's a
question that Susan Tedeschi is often asked these days. The Norwell
native has had a dream year _ opening national tours for Buddy Guy
and B. B. King and watching her solo career soar _ but the Joplin
question keeps popping up.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been raised especially by Tedeschi's tune ``It
Hurts So Bad,'' which has become a triple-A (adult album
alternative format) radio hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think it's a Janis Joplin track that they haven't
heard before,'' says Tedeschi. ``People have been calling radio
stations from their cars to find out if it's a Joplin song.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many people think I'm here as the
reincarnated Janis Joplin,'' adds Tedeschi, now 28. ``People come
up to me and say, `You are her!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, one of those people was Sam Andrews, who played guitar
in Joplin's band, Big Brother &AMP; the Holding Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's involved in a movie of Janis's life and asked me about
playing the role of Janis,'' says Tedeschi. ``I'd consider it, but
I'm not dying to do it . . . I don't want to be known as Janis
Joplin the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some interesting historical notes that some people
point to. Tedeschi was born Nov. 9, 1970 _ a month after Joplin
died. And some of her stage mannerisms are similar. ``The way I
kick my foot when I sing and play is similar to what Janis did,''
admits Tedeschi, though she says that's a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked Janis when I was growing up _ and my dad had footage
of her and a bunch of her records. But I liked Linda Ronstadt
better,'' she says. ``I don't have Janis as a singing influence
that much, but the way I emote with my voice is similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the key thing is that the two of us are both trying
to sing like Etta James!'' says Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   Joplin comparisons aside, Tedeschi has gotten ahead this year by
sheer hard work. She and her band have put 35,000 miles on their
van since June. Her latest album, ``Just Won't Burn'' (on
Boston-based Tone-Cool Records), has sold more than 70,000 copies,
according to SoundScan. She's had another triple-A hit with the
erotic ``Rock Me Right.'' And she's forged a close family-style
bond with the blues deans with whom she's toured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with Buddy Guy on his 63d birthday and got to bring
him a cake. And I played with B. B. King on his 73d birthday and
got to bring him a cake, too,'' says Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   So how is she holding up after such a long, road-filled year?
``I'm barely alive,'' she says with a laugh. ``No, really, I'm
doing surprisingly well.''
</P>
<P>
   She's doing particularly well in the Northwest, where her radio
play has been the strongest. In Seattle, she sold out a 1,400-seat
theater. In San Francisco, she packed John Lee Hooker's Boom Boom
Club and 600 people were turned away. In Portland, she did a radio
station gig for KINK-FM and was asked to headline over John Hiatt
and Keb' Mo'. ``I freaked out, because John Hiatt is an idol of
mine,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The only major negative this summer was her breakup with her
boyfriend, guitarist Sean Costello. Since he left the band after
doing her Harborlights show in August, she's assumed all guitar
duties herself.
</P>
<P>
   Tedeschi, who attended Berklee College of Music and played all
the blues jams around Boston and Cambridge when she started out,
has recently moved back to Boston from Atlanta, where she met her
backing band, known as the Jive Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I moved my stuff into storage back in Boston,'' says
Tedeschi. ``I'm really living on the road right now. I won't have
time to get my own place until February.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buffett aims high: First, there was the $650 package to see the
Rolling Stones at the FleetCenter on March 22 and 23, which
consists of a ticket, parking, tour merchandise, and a party before
and after the show. Now Jimmy Buffett is offering the same thing,
but for $400 for his Feb. 28 show at the Fleet. There are 500 of
those packages available, but guess what? They haven't sold out
yet, unlike the Stones's $650 counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it means that Buffett is less popular. I think
it says that a lot of money has already been taken out of the
market for concerts,'' says FleetCenter president Richard Krezwick.
Or maybe it means the Parrotheads have more sense after all.
They're opting for other tickets to the show, which are under $60.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
