<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THUMBS UP FOR THE REVAMPED INFINITI Q45 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, December 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Special interests present special problems to the car buyer. To
complicate things, automobiles have shrunk considerably from what
they once were, thanks to clean-air imperatives and the badgering
of environmental extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the problem that confronted Martha, the very tall woman
who plays a very tall instrument: the harp. A good harp costs more
than a good car and fits in none of them. A van, however, fills the
bill. Martha's devotion to the queen of stringed things dictated
van.
</P>
<P>
   The van is also the solution for the hobbyist devoted to big
things winged _ large- or giant-scale model airplanes, frequently
with wings spanning seven, eight, or nine feet. Sometimes the hobby
requires trailer rental or purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Antiques collectors, too, run into problems _ the drop-leaf
table or antique desk won't quite make it into the trunk of an
econobox _ one shudders to consider the potential of that
much-heralded electric thingamajig.
</P>
<P>
   Even the annual Christmas tree gets to be a transport headache
when the living space demands a seven-foot fir and the car
available is . . . well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   For the columnist, lately, the choice of test vehicle has
revolved around the particular capacity problem to be solved, the
annual forays into those joyful celebrations known as Tuba
Christmas. This being the 25th anniversary of the first TC, and the
columnist being addicted to disturbing the peace from time to time
with a euphonium and joining others so inclined, the desire was
vehicles that would adapt well to carrying these formidable
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   A euphonium is a modest-sized member of the tuba family (roughly
defined here as any instrument with conical bore playing mostly
below middle C), and so there is wide choice _ except when
traveling with friends. But consider some of the heavier members of
the clan, those full-size standing behemoths of the band that
require a case bigger than a small car! It is no mean feat to
assemble 130 tubists in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Now there loomed Essex, Conn., and Wickford, R.I., and your
columnist was traveling in concert (if you will excuse a mild pun)
to both; there was need to place three large brass, bass-clef
instruments in the trunk of the available car, a 1999 Infiniti Q45.
The Q is a large car by today's standards, but the trunk obviously
was not designed with three euphoniums (or is it euphonia?) in
mind, one a double-belled instrument. At first glance, it was no
go.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Collins is an engineer, and he quickly figured a way to
place the bulky, odd-shaped cases into the somewhat narrow confines
and still have room for stands, music, and a couple or three
cornets, if anybody had a mind to bring them. At the Essex Steam
Train Museum, 78 tubists gathered in the engine shed to sound out a
merry Christmas _ a group also gathered on the platform to serenade
revelers on the excursion train. At Wickford, some 50 or so solved
the transport need with a variety of automobiles _ Taurus wagons
seem popular among musicians with large instruments, brass and
electronic.
</P>
<P>
   In between Tuba Christmasing, the Infiniti was called upon for
hard duty in middle and coastal Maine, a lot of New Hampshire, and
a generous bit of the Bay State. It is a pleasant car, but
Nissan/Infiniti seems to have mixed feelings about just what it is
that an Infiniti is supposed to be. It has been a model in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   The Q started as a magnificent ugly duckling, a luxury car
looking like a cross between an old Pontiac and a new BMW but with
a wart on its nose. But what a car to drive! It was splendid on the
road. Then, it got prettier and less fun _ softer, squishier. The
1999 reincarnation is just about right _ it's time to quit
tinkering and out the effort into solid marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The styling for '99 is restrained, refined _ hey, it's a classy
boat. The 4.13-liter V-8 this year puts out 266 horsepower (278
ft/lb torque) and is mated to a 4-speed, electronically controlled
gearbox. The tested car is the standard model, a $48,695-delivered
car with all the bells and whistles, Bose sound, CD player, 16-inch
wheels, ABS, and traction control. There is a touring model, the
Q45t, for $1,700 more, with a new electronically managed suspension
system.
</P>
<P>
   The headlights are new, halogen bonfires which cast a blue light
that apparently irritates other drivers, if one is to judge by the
number of bright lights flashed at me on the road. There have been
interior modifications, too. The signature gold-rimmed clock has
returned to center dash after a two-year hiatus, and the controls
have generally been modified larger for the benefit of gloved
fingers _ except for tuning and scan/seek functions on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Interior storage is still an issue; the glove box is barely
adequate for the fancy packet of owner's manual and other
literature. Bins grace the doors, and there is a two-piece storage
bin under the armrest that would better serve if it were one useful
storage space. A small lidded compartment forward of that is either
two cupholders or an eyeglass storage bin. Seat-back pockets pretty
much complete the storage picture _ don't ask where one might
connveniently place a purse.
</P>
<P>
   Wood accents and supple leather attest to luxury; interior room
makes somewhat less of a case _ a Rolls-Royce this is not _ but
unless the front-seat occupants are NBA pros with overly long legs,
the kneeroom in the rear is generous. Headroom is good.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the Q45 is sheer pleasure. It is quick, quiet,
responsive _ not quite crisp, perhaps, but nice in the corners and
nimble in traffic. The ride is firmer this year but hardly stiff;
the Q soaks up the ruts on a dirt road admirably, still offers
decent road feel and feedback to the driver.
</P>
<P>
   The Q45 is EPA-rated 17 miles per gallon city, 24 highway; in a
bit more than 600 miles tracked, the tested car delivered 21.02
m.p.g. overall in varied driving, mostly with a good load _ three
tubas, three tubists for more than half that distance.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs up for the Q45 _ and a very Merry Christmas to you all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
