<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION SHOWER ROD DROPS AFTER 6 HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When I put up a tension shower rod on new tiles in my
bathroom tub surround, it stayed up for about six hours, then fell.
After a few failures, I took it back to the store and got another
one. It too fell. What's wrong, and how can I keep that rod up?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Maybe both rods were defective. A tension rod has an inside
spring, which is turned to tighten and loosen. Try tightening the
spring so that the rod fits with great effort; you can telescope it
slightly to get it in place. The rod should be heavy duty, the
heaviest you can get, although a lighter one should hold as well as
a heavy one. If that doesn't work, take it back and buy a
heavy-duty rod at another store. The handyman has one that has
worked very well for years; he bought it at Caldor. Make sure the
new rod, if you buy it, has rubber tips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 1899 house has some great pocket doors; they are huge,
each is six feet wide and mighty heavy. They close OK, but when I
go to open them, they jam six or seven inches out of the pocket. Is
there any easy way to get to the blockage so I can fix it?
</P>
<P>
   BOB PERRY, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No easy way. Possibly no way except to take down the wall,
because they were installed before the wall finish went up. At
least the mechanism lasted 100 years, not bad for something built
in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   But before you take down a wall finish (plaster and all), open
the door as far as it will go, right to the opposite end of the
opening. Then you can check the top for rail or wheel damage, and
look into the pocket to see what has happened. You can also take
off the door casing that surrounds the pocket opening and peer in
with a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   The door might have jumped the rail; if so, you might be able to
lift it back on the track by putting a pry bar on the bottom.
Maybe. Or, the rail might have come loose at the far end
(naturally) of the pocket, causing the door to drop, dragging and
blocking any movement. If you take the door off its rail, you can
screw the railback on. Or, one wheel might have loosened, and, if
it is accessible, can be refastened.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, removing the plaster and lath may be necessary.
And, instead of taking off all the wall finish, you could cut a
smaller area for limited observation and repair, so there would be
much less wall finish to replace.
</P>
<P>
   If you need to replace hardware, check these places: Restoration
Resources Store, 200 A Webster St. (Route 123) Hanover, Mass.,
781-878-3794; Classic Restorations, Watertown, Mass., 617-926-0505;
Restoration Resources, retail store, 31 Thayer St., Boston,
617-542-3033. Also, Stanley makes hardware for pocket and other
kinds of sliding doors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In my condo building, the neighbor's shower stall is directly
above ours. He put in a new pan, and now water gushes through the
ceiling of our shower stall, which is tiled. But it happens only
four or so times a year. What is wrong and how can it be fixed?
Could this gushing water collapse the ceiling? And could it spread
to the rest of the bathroom? The installer of the new pan said it
is not leaking.
</P>
<P>
   DEBBIE ONIE, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Short answers to the first two question are: Who knows what's
wrong, and most anything can be fixed, once one finds the cause. As
for the cause, it could be the pan, in spite of what the installer
says; it could be a leaking drain pipe. It could be the upstairs
shower is leaking through the tiled walls. It could even be a
pinhole leak in the water pipe. But what is mysterious is why the
gushing occurs so rarely. I think the reason is this: The pan is
set in a depression, and when water leaks through it or the drain,
it collects in that depression above the ceiling of your stall.
That tiled ceiling is probably a mud job (installed in mortar) and
is quite leakproof, until the water gets heavy enough to break
through.
</P>
<P>
   This gushing water could spread to the rest of the bathroom
ceiling, and either ceiling _ bathroom or stall _ can collapse,
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   To fix the cause, you have to find it, and that may mean taking
down the ceiling of your stall and inspecting the drain pipe, water
pipes, and the pan itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a peculiar garage with a 16-foot-wide door under a
jury-rigged 4 x 4 header under a 4 x 6 with a 2 x 10 beam. It
sagged about two inches in the middle. I don't want to put in a
middle post, so I am jacking up the middle until it's level and
will add a heavy steel beam. When I started jacking up the beam, I
noticed a crack in a rafter on top of it, so I stopped jacking. Is
there a formula for how fast to jack up that beam? I have 1 1/4
inches to go to level.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES CARTER, Dover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Some say to do a half turn once a day, others say faster is
OK. There is no hard and fast rule; it's a matter of slow enough
not to crack rafters and other members, and not to raise the whole
beam and roof. Jack up the middle a tad, then wait a day for the
beam to adjust. You might be done by the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
