<HEADER>
A6990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PRINCE-BOS &LR;      12-18 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PRINCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMMANDING BUT CONSTRAINED `PRINCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
PRINCE OF EGYPT 
Directed by: Brenda Chapman, Steve Hickner, Simon Wells 
Screenplay: Philip LaZebnik 
With the voices of: Val Kilmer, Ralph Fiennes, Michelle Pfeiffer,
Sandra Bullock, Jeff Goldblum, Danny Glover, Patrick Stewart, Helen
Mirren, Steve Martin, Martin Short 
Running time: 99 minutes 
Rated: PG (intense depiction of dramatic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DreamWorks' new ``The Prince of Egypt'' at least solves the
problem of how to produce a biblical epic without the ponderousness
that has suffocated all but a few of the usual Hollywood
treatments. Its mix of traditional animation and com- &QC; 
MovieReview
</P>
<P>
   puter-generated effects unfolds in a succession of magnificently
rendered designs and captures a momentum that all but eluded the
campy and leaden film that seems to have served as its source,
Cecil B. DeMille's second (1956) version of ``The Ten
Commandments,'' starring Charlton Heston as Moses. That effort
sacrificed the immediacy of DeMille's earlier but much more
modern-seeming 1923 film. This new effort generates its own brand
of visual splendors and high-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   Every drawing, every design, every panoramic sequence of this
new retelling tells you that DreamWorks has a lot riding on ``The
Prince of Egypt.'' But it's more imposing than stirring, more
likely to be respected than loved. Still, the drawn Moses (voiced
by Val Kilmer) is a lot easier to take than previous incarnations.
He looks more convincing than Charlton Heston ever did. And while I
wish Rameses (voiced by Ralph Fiennes), as he's called here, looked
less like Yul Brynner, he and all the characters look more
indigenous than any Hollywood cast ever did. It has taken Hollywood
nearly a century, but at last its Hebrews and Egyptians have lost
the ludicrous Anglo look peculiar to the Hollywood Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, animation does things that the special effects of
De Mille's day couldn't do as well. The parting of the Red Sea
works better here than in what now seems the primitive matte
process of the film. Ditto for the burning bush. And the Angel of
Death sequence, when God visits plagues upon Egypt to punish
Rameses, is one of the most striking in ``The Prince of Egypt.'' So
is the dream sequence in which the adult Moses learns of his
origins and of the genocide that drove his mother to float him down
the Nile to safety. A revelation appears to Moses as hieroglyphs,
and temple reliefs come to life to act out history in bloodstained
hues.
</P>
<P>
   The film, buttressed by a list of advisers consisting of dozens
of scholars and religious leaders, changes the story of the
bullrushes. After Moses' floating basket eludes crocs and hippos,
it's plucked from the water by Pharaoh's wife, who adopts the baby
and raises him as Rameses' younger brother. They're close enough in
age to become playmates, then adolescent cutups, racing chariots,
dropping water balloons, pursuing the desert version of la dolce
vita, until Moses meets the adult his sister has grown into, and
her husband, and is brought face to face both with the suffering of
the Jewish slaves under Pharaoh and with his own Jewishness. When
Moses leaves, he meets a spirited shepherdess (voiced by Michelle
Pfeiffer, who sings her own songs, as Kilmer does). DreamWorks has
sprung for an A-list of voices, signing on Helen Mirren, Sandra
Bullock, Jeff Goldblum, Steve Martin, and Martin Short.
</P>
<P>
   When the estrangement deepens between the two men who once were
brothers, it's Rameses' anguish we feel. But his pangs are eclipsed
by his arrogance and his callousness toward the slaves, whose
condition he regards as natural. Fiennes's Rameses is as close as
the film comes to generating real feelings. Pfeiffer's fiery
shepherdess, Tzipporah, registers, too. But when big feelings are
required, they do run up against the limitations of the animation.
They didn't have to. While ``The Prince of Egypt'' succeeds
brilliantly in rendering the funerary splendors of the Egyptian
empire and the undulating shapes and tints of the desert, it's
artistically less imaginative and more compromised than it had to
be.
</P>
<P>
   I wish ``The Prince of Egypt'' had lost the silly songs that
hang like cinder blocks around the necks of too many animations,
especially this one. For that matter, I wish DreamWorks had been
more truly daring instead of merely competitive and worked a little
longer at evolving a drawing style that departed more radically
from the Disney house style than this film does. It seems less an
artistic alternative to Disney than a proliferation of it. On the
other hand, the studio takes a few chances, conceiving a
full-length animation that clearly is not skewed to very young
viewers. This worked to better effect with ``Antz,'' which isn't
nearly the big deal that ``The Prince of Egypt'' is, yet shines
with more spontaneity and wit _ and with a look of its own. ``The
Prince of Egypt'' is frankly more involving and less boring than I
expected a Hollywood biblical outing to be. But, DreamWorks, let
your animators go!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
