<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6997 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MAIL-BOS &LR;      12-18 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAIL' DELIVERS PASSWORD TO ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
YOU'VE GOT MAIL 
Directed by: Nora Ephron 
Screenplay by: Nora and Delia Ephron 
Starring: Tom Hanks, Meg Ryan, Parker Posey, Jean Stapleton, Dave
Chappelle, Steve Zahn, Greg Kinnear, Heather Burns 
Running time: 116 minutes 
Rated: PG (some language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail'' answers the date-movie question for the
holidays _ and months beyond. Nora Ephron's remake of the classic
romantic comedy ``The Shop Around the Corner'' is warm, smart, and
funny. Perhaps more to the point, it has performances of enormous
appeal from Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks as lovers who have no idea how
mismatched they are, since they meet and intensify their
relationship in an Internet chat room. They have no idea that they
live within blocks of each other on Manhattan's richly textured
Upper West Side, and in fact pass each other several times on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   The trick here, of course, is to not let the love come too
easily. Ephron, Ryan, and Hanks have traveled this route before, in
``Sleepless in Seattle,'' and know just how to do it. This outing
could be subtitled ``Nervous in New York,'' given that Hanks is
playing the millionaire owner of a bookstore chain wiping out small
independents, such as the children's bookstore Ryan's Kathleen
Kelly inherited from her mother. This plot twist provides the only
real roadblock to credibility. We're asked to believe that Kathleen
could fall in love with the guy who's driving her out of business.
</P>
<P>
   But we do. That's because Hanks's and Ryan's performances give
the film such a core of undentable decency that they carry the film
past this and a couple of other roadblocks, one being that he
learns she's his mystery correspondent on the Internet before she
learns he's her correspondent. Hanks's character, Joe Fox, exploits
this advantage to play a few mind games with Ryan's devout romantic
before all is revealed. And if the film is also a hymn to the Upper
West Side by Nora Ephron and her co-screenwriting sister, Delia,
who have lived there for years and know the territory, it's also a
symphony of product placement, especially for America Online and
Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   In the acerbically sentimental Ernst Lubitsch 1939 original,
lovers-to-be Jimmy Stewart and Margaret Sullavan were co-workers
who didn't realize that each was also the other's pen pal. The new
film's Internet update works even better. It's a pleasure to
encounter a movie where the romantic connection is made solely
through sensitive, nimble, witty language, which we hear in
voice-overs as the electronic communiques take on ever-increasing
importance to Kathleen and Joe. As the film begins, each is living
with somebody else, he with Parker Posey's publishing careerist,
she with Greg Kinnear's politically correct reporter.
</P>
<P>
   They can't wait for their respective partners to leave for work
in the morning so they can sign on and click to the e-mail that
fosters growing intimacy along with the risk that a meeting might
prove devastating in proportion to the difference between the
imagined person and the actuality. Not that this is their only
problem. Faced with the imminent extinction of her cute-as-a-button
shop in this cute-as-a-button film, Kathleen maintains a superhuman
sweetness as she transcends the shop's almost certain demise, to
say nothing of the overdue demise of her comfortable but lukewarm
relationship with the crusader that Kinnear is allowed to make just
goofy enough to be likable.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks's wary Joe has even less difficulty in conveniently ending
his live-in relationship with Parker's pushy exec, who's rendered
in shrill, one-note terms to soften any pangs we might feel about
her loss. The film is nothing if not shrewdly constructed, making
one right move after another. It'll deepen the perception of Hanks
as the contemporary Jimmy Stewart, partly because Hanks is
permitted the same kind of prickly edge Stewart had in the
original. He's a take-charge guy, but takes the sting out of his
character's ways by convincing us that he's a fundamentally good
guy and not a vicious power-tripper. Similarly, Ryan has to
convince us that Kathleen is not too sweet for her own good and
doesn't cave in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail'' doesn't set itself any problems that the
charm and appeal of its leads _ and Ephron's savvy behind the
camera and in front of the word processor _ can't handle. ``You've
Got Mail'' is the kind of film that likes its characters and likes
New York, too. It looks a lot easier to bring off than it actually
is _ further testimony to the Ephron sisters' secure grip on the
world of the film and the emotions of its characters, especially
yearning. Nobody does yearning better than Ryan when she scrunches
her face into an interim expression between a smile and scowl of
concentration. If ``Sleepless in Seattle'' was your kind of
romantic comedy, ``You've Got Mail'' will be, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
