<HEADLINE>
AT BROOKSTONE, IT'S AS CLEAR AS GLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY&AMP;  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The windows of the Brookstone store at Copley Place in Boston
are carefully arranged. One window features health aids as well as
a plug for the company's Web site. Another shows off some high-tech
massage wands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest piece of advertising for us is our windows,'' says
Michael Anthony, president and chief executive of Brookstone Inc.,
a chain of gift stores based in Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   About three times a year, Brookstone takes out a print ad in the
New York Times Sunday Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   One recent print ad was the cover of a Brookstone catalog, which
in turn is designed to resemble the front of a Brookstone store.
One ad plumps ``the Tempur-pedic pillow, just one of 700 unique
gifts you'll discover at our 200 stores nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   A second print ad shows a man giving his young son a bath. The
featured product is a digital shower radio.
</P>
<P>
   Most Brookstone products, from air-injection wine-bottle openers
to barbecue forks with built-in thermometers, are promoted as ideal
gifts for men. As a result, many customers are women, and ad
imagery shows happy couples and young families.
</P>
<P>
   Print ads aside, Brookstone's chief marketing vehicle is its
windows, which are remodeled about once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Most Brookstone stores are based in malls, and sometimes the
stores will put one of their $3,000 vibrating chairs out front,
where weary shoppers can plop down for the purported equivalent of
a shiatsu rubdown.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that pleasantly shaken-up shoppers will then be
lured inside to buy a $40 TheraSpa folding turbo massager or a $30
electric tongue cleaner, supposedly the last word for passionate
advocates of oral hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an impulse buy,'' says Anthony, who notes that nearly
two-thirds of Brookstone products cost $40 or less.
</P>
<P>
   As Anthony sees it, Brookstone also partly ``brands itself'' by
coming up with new products and attempting to stay a step ahead of
copycats that offer off-brand knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, shortly after Anthony joined the company, only 12 to 15
percent of store inventory was made expressly for Brookstone; now
that number is near 50 percent, and of the roughly 750 products
available in stores, a third of them are new.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the new products are upgrades,'' Anthony says.
``Sound relaxation systems, for instance, we obsoleted our entire
line, going from analog to digital systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these systems offer soothing sounds _ the gentle ebb and
flow of the surf, a summer shower in a rainforest.
</P>
<P>
   But when some city customers complained that the sounds of
nature weren't the most restful, Brookstone dutifully added a track
full of wailing want sirens and honking horns. Without the roaring
traffic's boom, it seems, these demanding sleepers couldn't snooze.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work with a sleep therapist on all these products,''
Anthony says.
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers these days are seeing an evening out of their
sales cycles with consumers shopping steadily all year round.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Brookstone is a throwback; it will see a major
chunk of its sales in the last 14 days before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 31, the company was $9.4 million in the red, but it
still expects to report a handsome profit for the year on projected
full-year sales of $270 million to $275 million.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to smooth out a cycle that has big spikes at Father's
Day and Christmas, Brookstone is testing airport kiosks and stores
and now looks to expand a site at Logan International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brookstone has high hopes for selling products on its
Web site. Holiday sales have tripled from last year, though they
still amount to less than 1 percent of overall sales.
</P>
<P>
   One bit of bad news: Rising rents are forcing Brookstone to
close a store near Downtown Crossing, Anthony says.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a store full of gadgets, Brookstone has one that
counts the number of visitors to each store.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic is down so far this year, perhaps because warm weather
is keeping people away from the malls. Fortunately, for Brookstone,
customers those who make purchases are spending more than last
year, Anthony says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, it gets later and later,'' he says of the holiday
rush.
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers resort to advertising to unload unwanted
merchandise. When goods pile up, they'll run ads saying, ``Take 25
percent off.''
</P>
<P>
   But because it offers ``unique'' items, Brookstone can sell at
full price. As a result, it can use a different ad strategy. ``Our
store windows are our biggest marketing effort,'' Anthony says.
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Reidy is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
