<HEADLINE>
WARNINGS READY GILLETTE HOLDERS FOR THE BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind those holiday shopping crowds. The world's consumer
markets are not turning out to be a very merry place in the last
months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest global consumer marketing companies, Procter
&AMP; Gamble Co. and the Coca-Cola Co., have already warned investors
that their performance for the fourth quarter will be a
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Our question: If Coke and Procter &AMP; Gamble are coming up short,
how can Gillette Co. do that much better?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: it probably can't. But Gillette's warnings in
September, covering results for the second half of the year, have
put most investors on notice and cost-cutting may help the bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gillette's fourth quarter has all the makings of being an
extremely ugly quarter,'' said analyst Andrew Shore of PaineWebber.
``But it should take no one by suprise, Wall Street is well
prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Razor blades aren't soda or soap suds. But the same weak global
economies that are dragging down performance at other consumer
product companies has to have an impact on Gillette. About
one-third of Gillette's sales take place outside the United States
and Western Europe, in Asia, South America and Russia, among other
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly, everyone had discounted a lot of the
international problems we had over the summer,'' said Robert
Izmirlian, a Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. analyst who follows Gillette.
``But they aren't going away all that quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some money managers like John Snyder of the John Hancock
Soverign Investors fund, which buys large-company stocks, are
shying away from global marketing companies now because of weaker
economies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that there is no top line (revenue) growth, no
volume growth per se,'' said Snyder. ``Part of that is obviuosly
the slowing in the global economies and slowing in Euorpe.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's sales for the first three quarters of 1998 are
slightly below comparable figures for last year and less than 3
percent better than 1996 results. Gillette shares slumped over the
summer with the rest of the stock market, falling from more than 62
to 36 1/4, but have failed to bounce back like many other big
issues. Gillette stock finished Thursday at 43 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Coke said it would earn as much as 20 percent less
than expected in the fourth quarter due to weak international
sales. Procter &AMP; Gamble said its sales were running below
expectations, but cost savings may preserve anticipated earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette had announced disappointing third-quarter expectations
and an aggressive cost-cutting plan at the end of September. At the
time, Gillette said it expected fourth-quarter earnings growth in
the ``low double digits'' and analysts have taken that at its
minimum. Their consensus forecasts for fourth quarter profits of 39
cents per share would be up from 36 cents a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't be bad, under the circumstances, and Gillette does
not appear to be guiding analyst estimates lower so far. Only a few
forecasts have been modestly trimmed in the last few weeks, but
their aggregate recommendation on Gillette stock has slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gillette is focused on the rollout of expensive new
products that it hopes will be big winners in 1999. Sometime next
year it will become clear whether the heavily promoted Mach3 razor
and the new $4.99 Oral B toothbrush, the most expensive mass
marketed toothbrush ever, are successful products.
</P>
<P>
   Not suprisingly, Gillette officials wouldn't tell us much about
their fourth-quarter business. But we did pry loose bits of
information, including:
</P>
<P>
   --Currency translation, a serious problem created by the strong
dollar this year, continues but is ``less negative'' than in the
third quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
   --The battery business is doing fine at home. Around the world,
business should be up in local currencies but ``most likely'' down
in dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
   Mach3, the shaver with the billion-dollar development and
marekting budget, has seemed to do well in its early months.
Gillette said Mach3 was the best-selling razor with a 13 percent
share of the US market in November.
</P>
<P>
   Citing data from A.C. Neilson Co., Gillette said all its razors
and blades last month acheived a 70 percent share of US dollar
markets for the first time since 1962. The market share figure a
year ago was 67.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the crucial question for Mach3 is whether men will buy the
expensive replacement blades once their original supply that came
with the razor runs out. A four-pack of replacement blades costs
about $6.68 in retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't know until the first quarter whether the repurchase
data is fine, which I suspect it will be,'' said Shore. ``That
should allay all fears about Mach3. If it's weak, Gillette will be
a very bad stock. But I think Mach3 is going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's alive! Artificial Life Inc. of Cambridge, Mass. soared 176
percent to 23 1/2 in its first session Thursday. The young Internet
software company, raised $11.9 million in the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
