<HEADLINE>
PARITY LINE IN THE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the excitement generated by the tight AFC East race,
Matt Millen has three words _ St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' the Fox commentator said. ``The Rams have
to be saying to themselves that they could be the champs if they
were in the AFC East.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams have beaten the Jets, Dolphins, and Patriots, and they
symbolize, at least in Millen's mind, the nature of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now anybody can beat anybody,'' he said. ``First of all,
there are no dominant defenses out there, certainly not like the
1985 Bears. In addition, no one has a totally dominating offense.
Everybody has holes. Even Denver. For example, you can say that
Denver has a better team than the Jets. But you can't say with 100
percent certainty that the Jets can't beat Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen will be the analyst for Fox's Patriots-49ers telecast at
Foxboro Stadium Sunday at 1 p.m. He doesn't rule out a Patriots
victory, arguing that backup quarterback Scott Zolak is bound to do
better than his one-play-one-fumble performance against the Rams
and that running back Robert Edwards has the ability to control a
game if given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots also are unpredictable, and Millen says the
cause is free agency. ``I know the NFL and the union don't like to
hear it, but teams nowadays have to protect a core group of guys,''
he said. ``Back in the old days, teams had a core but were able to
build on that core. Great teams are not made solely with great
players but with supporting people who know each other and play
well together. That is when a team can become really good. But now
a supporting player on one team can become a starter somewhere
else. It leaves teams in a state of flux and it's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen called the Patriots-Falcons game earlier this year.
``They got blown out early, so it really wasn't a good example of
the Patriots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The former Raiders and 49ers linebacker said injured quarterback
Drew Bledsoe has made big strides this season, especially after
engineering last-minute drives to beat the Bills and Dolphins. ``He
has put on his big boy pants,'' Millen said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's Beasley Reece called the Patriots-Rams game last week and
said he is unsure whether New England can pull it together to win
its last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked horrible against the Rams,'' Reece said. ``But now
it's not a question of performance or effort. It's a question of
injuries. The Patriots could be a team that shot all of its bullets
a few weeks ago. They can't stay in the race unless they are
shooting with a full arsenal of talent. And right now the Patriots
are a very good football team limping into the critical period.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Super seller
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox stands to gain about $93 million in advertising revenues
from the Super Bowl. The network has sold all but four of the 58
available 30-second spots for the annual ratings bonanza, to be
played Jan. 31 in Miami. Despite the 23 percent increase over last
year's price, advertisers have lined up to pay an average of $1.6
million a spot. Some have paid as much as $2 million to secure
prime exposure. For Fox, which pays the NFL about $550 million a
year to broadcast NFC games, the $93 million does not include
revenues from ads run during the pregame, halftime, and postgame
shows . . . Fox's local affiliate, Channel 25, will have a
``Patriots Fifth Quarter'' show after its telecast of Sunday's
game. Steve Grogan and Jeff Cawley will be in the studio, while Bob
Halloran will work from Foxboro Stadium. At 10:30, Channel 25's
``Sports Sunday'' will feature Patriots defensive tackle Chad Eaton
. . . HBO will present the bout between Floyd Mayweather Jr. (18-0,
14 knockouts) and Angel Manfredy (25-2-1, 20 KOs) Saturday night at
9:45. Jim Lampley, Larry Merchant, and Roy Jones Jr. will be at
ringside for the collision of 130-pounders. The undercard pits
heavyweights David Tua (32-1, 27 KOs) and Hasim Rahman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
