<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECEMBER: THE A-10'S CRUELEST MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's going on in the Atlantic 10? The conference that had four
teams in the preseason Top 20 now has none. No team in the league
is more than two games above .500, and Fordham, of all teams, has
the best record in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   More important, all of the supposed power teams _ Rhode Island,
Temple, Massachusetts, Xavier _ all struggling, none so more than
UMass, which is 2-5 and needs a major push to get back to .500,
much less in the Top 20.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not going to get any easier or better for the Atantic
10.
</P>
<P>
   December is when teams solidify their reputations and power
rankings for the season. Traditionally, teams from powerful
conferences fatten up on nonconference opponents in December,
allowing some leeway for losses when the league races begin in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The argument used is that our conference is so tough, the losses
are quality losses.
</P>
<P>
   And that works when you are talking about the Atlantic Coast
Conference, where losses to Duke, North Carolina, or Maryland will
not hurt; or the Southeastern Conference, where losing to teams
such as Kentucky and Arkansas and in recent years South Carolina
also will not be fatal to NCAA tournament hopes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Atlantic 10 may be in trouble this season. If everyone
goes into the conference season with a slightly better than .500
record, what value will a win or a loss against UMass or Temple
have when March arrives?
</P>
<P>
   This does not diminish the quality of either team, which should
improve if the preseason prognostications are correct, but it could
and probably will hurt when the 64-team NCAA field is being
discussed by the selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   For now, one of two reasons would seem to explain the Atlantic
10's drop in status. Either the teams were vastly overrated or they
are all having very slow starts.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line also seems clear: The uneven play in December
will cost the Atlantic 10 in March when only three or four teams
make the NCAA tournament instead of the five or six the conference
had hoped for at the start of the season. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A coup for Dartmouth &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina at Dartmouth Saturday? How did this happen? Word
has it that it developed as a Carolina recruiting ploy when the Tar
Heels were after Winchendon School's Randell Jackson a few years
ago. One of the favorite tricks of then Carolina coach Dean Smith
(among others) was to schedule a nonconference game in a recruit's
home area, allowing his family and friends an opportunity to see
him play at least once during his career. Only problem is that
Jackson went to Florida State. Carolina, which hosted Dartmouth
three years ago, now is simply fulfilling the second part of the
home-and-home deal. Needless to say, it gives New England fans a
rare opportunity to see The Tar Heels . . . Is the Big East back?
Consider. Syracuse and Pittsburgh are 0-2 in league play but ranked
in the Top 25. St. John's has its highest ranking (15) since
December 1991 . . . If you look at the Big East standings now,
you'll see Rutgers, St. John's, Seton Hall, and Connecticut at the
top. Those were the four bottom seeds in the 1997 Big East
tournament . . . Individual scoring has not been a big factor in
Big East play this season. Villanova is a surprising 8-2, but the
Wildcats have had a player score more than 20 points twice. In
UConn's tough victories over Pitt and UMass, no Huskie scored as
many as 15 points . . . Scheduling a game on the Saturday before
Christmas involving two bad teams is no way to attract fans, but
Boston College athletic director Gene DeFilippo has a visit from
Holy Cross on tap Saturday. The crowds at Conte Forum have been
sparse all year despite a season ticket base of more than 5,000,
and don't expect a great gathering for Saturday's match between two
of the worst teams in Division 1 (according to the Sagarain
rankings, at least). DeFilippo's take on the game: ``With a lot of
Christmaas and holiday parties on Saturday night, we figured this
might be a good opporunity for a dad to take his kids to a game in
the afternoon before going out on Saturday night with Mom, or just
a good family opportunity to get together at a college basketball
game.'' With the BC students on holiday break, the Eagles need
someone to show up.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing wealth &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local basketball guru Ted Sarandis is pushing an expansion of
the Commonwealth Classic next year when it returns to the
FleetCenter. He wants to make it a doubleheader _ UMass vs. BC and
UConn vs. URI _ in the equivalent of a New England college
basketball Beanpot Tournament. Maybe you could call it the Red
Auerbach Classic, says Sarandis, who is the loudest supporter for
college basketball in the area. Makes sense to me. Having UConn
would guarantee fans, and UMass, BC, and Rhode Island could bring
enough people to create a near sellout. The only thing missing
would be sensible ticket costs. The tickets for last week's
BC-UMass game at the Worcester Centrum started at $22. That should
be the maximum for the FleetCenter next year. Even if some tickets
are scaled down to $10, it's better to have a full house at lower
prices than an empty one at outrageous prices . . . Rutgers is 7-1
going into Saturday's game against Temple. In 92 seasons of
basketball, no other Rutgers team has had seven victories this
early . . . College basketball is experiencing a revival in
Chicago. With Michael Jordan and the Bulls idle, DePaul, which is
off to a quick start under new coach Pat Kennedy, Illinois-Chicago,
and even Chicago State all show signs of life. Chicago State, which
has had only two winning seasons since upgrading to Division 1
status in 1984-85, is relying on new coach Bo Ellis, the former
Marquette star, to show it the way. It will be a tough journey,
since Chicago Sate won a total of eight games in the last three
years. It lost five of its first six this season, but the interest
level is up. In their opening home game against Loyola-Chicago, the
Cougars, who play in 2,500-seat Jacoby Dickens Athletic Center,
drew a crowd of 2,514, only 312 short of their total home
attendance last season . . . Next week's Jimmy V Classic featuring
South Carolina-Purdue and Duke-Kentucky has become the toughest
regular-season ticket in the history of the Meadowlands. The Big
Ten has two Top 10 teams and six teams that are ranked . . . Purdue
coach Gene Keady on one reason he loves his job: ``I love watching
Big Ten football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
