<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES LIKE TO ATTACK ON LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Western Illinois held ``Amazin'' Adrian Peterson, who had rushed
for 200 or more yards six times this season, to 102 in its NCAA
Division 1-AA semifinal last weekend at Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Only one problem.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles quarterback Greg Hill went to work, firing four touchdown
passes, including a back-breaking 11-yarder to slotback Corey
Joyner that gave Georgia Southern a 21-8 lead with 17 seconds left
in the first half. The Eagles went on to a 42-14 rout of Western
Illinois, a team that came into the game with the No. 1 defense in
Division 1-AA.
</P>
<P>
   Citadel coach Don Powers and his staff also know all too well
about Georgia Southern's explosiveness. Powers's team held a 27-10
lead at home in the third quarter after scoring on a fake punt. The
Citadel had the momentum and a whipped-up crowd of nearly 15,000
hoping for the upset.
</P>
<P>
   Final score: Georgia Southern, 51, Citadel, 34.
</P>
<P>
   Held to 49 rushing yards in the first half, the Eagles rolled
for 303 in the second. Fullback Peterson scored a school-record
five touchdowns and rushed for 231 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very special back in Adrian Peterson,'' said
Powers of the team that will take on the University of
Massachusetts Saturday in Chattanooga, Tenn., for the national
title. ``He has the ability to take control of a game, and that's
what he did against us. With their option game, they always seem to
find a way to reduce it to a one-on-one ratio (runner to tackler),
and with a back of his quality, you need more than that one man to
stop him defensively, especially if he has space to his right or
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``But their offensive line may be the most overlooked portion of
their program. They're experienced, they've got more than one
All-American there, and they're probably the best offensive line in
1-AA in the country. To beat that team, your offense has to control
the ball, because if Southern plays with the ball long enough, bad
things will happen to the best of defenses. And you've got to play
great assignment, gap-control defense.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Western Carolina, coached by Bill Bleil, did for
most of its game _ but lost in crunch time, 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play great defense, and by that, I mean try to
hold them to 28 or 30 points and try to outscore them, because
teams can throw the ball and move on them,'' said Bleil.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Georgia Southern has won the last 28 games in
which it has outgained its opponents on the ground. One need only
glance at the statistics sheet from their perfect season (14-0) and
look at two lines _ 384.9 yards per game rushing, 113.4 passing _
for a quick education about the Eagles' offense.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst is Peterson, the redshirt freshman who has amassed
2,445 yards and 32 touchdowns on 337 carries (7.3 yards per carry),
shattering school records for yards and touchdowns in a season.
Peterson isn't the only concern for the UMass defense. Hill, a
junior, ran for 22 touchdowns and passed for 10. And, said Bleil,
``they do a lot of things out of their Wing-T. Defensively, you
have to take their fullback out of it, but Western Illinois put an
extra man up front to try that and they got burned by the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for UMass's defense?
</P>
<P>
   Said Bleil, ``You're simply not going to stop all three
components of their offense, Peterson, Hill, and a couple of their
slot guys (Joyner, who caught three TD passes last week, and Bennie
Cunningham). Heck, on fourth and 2, you might as well give them the
first down.''
</P>
<P>
   When Furman took it on the chin, 45-17, Peterson picked up 183
yards, but he wasn't the top ground-gainer. Hill, who has rushed
for more than 1,300 yards this season, picked up 222.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for UMass's offense?
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, people have been able to score on them this
year,'' said Bleil. ``They don't take many chances defensively.
They'll kind of try to slow the pace down on defense because they
know their offense will score.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles own the second-ranked total offense and rushing
offense in Division 1-AA. Let them into your red zone and you've
got serious problems. The Eagles have crossed their opponents'
20-yard line 64 times this season and have scored on 60 of those
possessions, a whopping 93.8 percent success rate. When they cross
midfield, they've scored on 83 of 114 trips, a 72.8 percent success
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hamilton, whose East Tennessee State team was racked for
334 rushing yards in the first half of a 47-26 loss to Georgia
Southern, coached against current Eagles coach Paul Johnson when
Hamilton was at Air Force and Johnson was at Hawaii and Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing to do against Georgia Southern is contain
their offense,'' he said. ``Their personnel really fit into it,
especially Peterson and Hill. If you beat them, you'll just have to
outscore them. We had success against them offensively by mixing
our attack, and if UMass can do that, they have a chance. But it
would probably wind up as a scoring contest. Paul and I have
coached against each other in some barn-burners. We're good
friends, and I have to say he's matched speed and athleticism to an
outstanding scheme that he has great knowledge of.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of players like freshman free safety Arkee
Thompson, a former basketball player who has eight interceptions
and a team-leading 140 tackles; senior defensive ends Benjy Harris
and Eric Davis, who has 14 quarterback sacks; and junior tackle
Voncellies Allen, the key to its defensive line, Georgia Southern's
defense can be vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can throw the football, which UMass can do, and mix up
your plays and get into the fourth quarter of a close game, you've
got a chance,'' said Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles rank 37th nationally in total defense, allowing an
average of 323.9 yards per game. And while Georgia Southern has
exploded for 47.7 points per game in the playoffs, averaging 519
yards in victories over Colgate, Connecticut, and Western Illinois,
it has surrendered an average of 404.3 yards per playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your defense has to try and match up speedwise with their
offense,'' said South Florida coach Jim Leavitt, whose team also
gave the Eagles a battle before losing, 28-23, ``and you'd probably
want them to be throwing the ball instead of running it. The other
half of having any chance against them is to keep the ball away
from their offense. You have to be able to either run the ball on
them or control the ball through a short passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And playing at a neutral field could also help UMass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
