<HEADLINE>
THE SEASON FOR SOME MUSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emptying Out The Desk Drawer Of The Sports Mind.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the only way I go to Atlantic City for that NBA fiasco
they're planning Saturday: Da Boss says, ``Get your butt down there
or start consulting the Help Wanteds.'' Las Vegas? AC? Hey, fellas,
let me spell it for you: c-l-u-e-l-e-s-s.
</P>
<P>
   International Olympic Committee poobah Juan Antonio Samaranch
says he'd consider expelling bribe-taking members. His copy of
``Casablanca'' is in the overnight mail (``Gambling? I'm
shocked!'')
</P>
<P>
   Roger ``I Just Want A Ring'' Clemens might already be sporting
the requisite jewelry had he gone to Cleveland two years ago. (P.S.
I still say he didn't know Toronto was located in a foreign
country.)
</P>
<P>
   Early Dick Vitale ``Sure Lottery Pick'' count: 37.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of bribes, I suspect Jim Calhoun wishes he could lay
some cash on voters to stop picking his bull's-eyed Connecticut
Huskies No. 1. He can wait till the final poll.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of the Huskies _ male and female _ it is very
difficult to conceive of Storrs, Conn., as the basketball capital
of the known amateur basketball world. What hath Jim and Geno
wrought?
</P>
<P>
   Late December just isn't gonna be the same without the Poulan
Weedeater Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A Holly Jolly Christmas to the sophomoric US Olympic hockey
players who still have not had the decency to 'fess up for
embarrassing their country in the Great Room-Trashing at Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   Plus Ca Change, Etc. Dept.: The Tuna gets a journalistic kiss in
Sports Illustrated and then whines because he's on the (supposedly
unlucky) cover. But that's all part of the charm, and nobody can
say the man can't coach.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Greene's Sprewellian attack on assistant coach Kevin
Steele last Sunday merits a mere one-game suspension? Or do we just
assume it's a little 'Roid Rage (he does wrestle, you know) and
move on?
</P>
<P>
   Our school maven Bob Holmes says he's waiting for when Kentucky
(Michael Bradley), Maine (Andy Bedard, Nate Fox), Ohio State
(Scoonie Penn), Clemson (Adam Allenspach), Miami (Elton Tyler),
Massachusetts (Jonathan DePina), Providence (Sean Connolly),
Rutgers (Billy Collins), and Nevada-Las Vegas (Brian Keefe) _ in
other words, all the Boston College hoop escapees _ are on the
telly the same evening, preferably one when BC is also playing, and
losing. Al Skinner cannot say he didn't know what he was getting
into.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonseca, Counsell, Floyd, and Hernandez? No, it's not a
diversity-minded law firm. They go by the first names of Antonio,
Craig, Cliff, and Livan, and they're all that's left of the 1997
champion Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Separated at birth: Bud Selig and Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry if it appears I've got UConn on the brain, but Khalid
El-Amin, who looks like one of those little dormitory fridges with
a head, has become my new favorite college player.
</P>
<P>
   Do John Harrington and John Buckley not have the slightest hint
of common sense enough to realize, in advance, that cashiering the
street vendors will make them look mean, petty, greedy, and
downright un-American? Who handles their corporate PR? Saddam
Hussein?
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe-Rick Mirer was one thing, but early returns suggest
that the Peyton Manning-Ryan Leaf gap may be the most important 1
vs. 2 discrepancy since it was a choice between the then Lew
Alcindor and Neal Walk 29 years ago. In terms of poise and personal
class, Leaf is Bledsoe's evil twin.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody explain to me why the IRS is so vengeful toward these
hapless NBA refs who tried to sneak home a few extra bucks by
downgrading their first-class airline tickets. Make 'em pay up, but
is it necessary to ruin their lives, too?
</P>
<P>
   Listen closely and you can hear the pitchers and catchers
warming up.
</P>
<P>
   Please join me in hoping the Veterans Committee finally does the
right thing and puts Bill Mazeroski, who might have been the
greatest defensive player of all time, into the Baseball Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   How sad they're bringing back professional baseball to
Springfield when the great Ray Fitzgerald won't be around to see
it.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask me, the Los Angeles Clippers have never had a finer
season.
</P>
<P>
   Who has communicated to Yours Truly as follows? ``How many times
is the `Duke' going to set the market? (O'Leary? P. Martinez,
Wakefield, Offerman (underlined four times)? Ha! Ha!'' A major
league general manager, that's who. Sorry, that's all I can tell
you.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio (84), Williams (80), Feller (80), Musial (78). Can any
other sport equal that quartet of living royalty?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone at Sports Illustrated who says the mag hasn't picked up
the level of its game since the ESPN publication hit the stands is
in denial.
</P>
<P>
   Our supposed great American golfers aren't much for road
encounters, are they?
</P>
<P>
   As a child of the '50s, I am, as Don King would say, shocked and
chagrined to learn that neither Joe ``The Jet'' Perry nor
``Hurryin' '' Hugh McElhenny ever gained as many yards in a 49ers
game as Garrison Hearst did against the Lions last Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Next I suppose you're gonna tell me somebody's going to hit 62
home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dunleavy can tell us that kid of his heading to Duke is a
more talented player than he ever was, but no way he's going to
convince me he's a smarter player unless he shows me the basketball
equivalent of a MENSA certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, suppose they had gone ahead and restored instant replay
for the playoffs. Who was going to make it right for the Bills, who
ought to be 10-4, a game ahead of the Jets?
</P>
<P>
   You simply cannot say this too many times: If even one-fourth of
all American professional team sport athletes had half the standup
class and dignity of Dennis Eckersley, the sports world would be a
thoroughly pleasurable place to inhabit, rather than the
suspicious, hostile, and adversarial war zone it has become. And
Tim Naehring makes two.
</P>
<P>
   Using two hockey refs has always made sense to me, but just
remember that one great anything is far preferable to any number of
mediocre officials.
</P>
<P>
   Let me guess. Kevin Brown will average $15 million for the next
seven years, but I bet there's some sort of bonus if he manages to
make an All-Star team or two. How's about he kicks back half a mil
if he (itals)doesn't(unitals) make the team?
</P>
<P>
   Attention, Fenway area neighborhood activists: The ballpark was
there long before you were. Deal with it. (See Samaranch reference
above.)
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead. (itals)You(unitals) pick against Jackie Parker in the
Beanpot. I won't.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
