<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ISLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIRD ISLAND' LEAVES TOO MANY STONES UNTURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``The Island on Bird Street,'' a movie about a
boy who survives on his own for week after week in the ruined shell
of the Warsaw Ghetto, is maddeningly true to its hero.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in the film _ every single thing _ is seen through
the eyes of 11-year-old Alex, played by newcomer Jordan Kiziuk.
When Alex's everyday life is tedious _ and it is very tedious at
times _ the movie is also tedious. When Alex is confused, the movie
is confused. When Alex is awkward, the movie is awkward.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with the acting. Kiziuk, who received a
special mention at last year's Berlin Film Festival, is
outstanding. So are Patrick Bergin as his father, Jack Warden as
his uncle, Simon Gregor as a wounded resistance fighter, and every
other actor on the screen. The direction by Soren Kragh-Jacobsen is
solid. The music, by Zbigniew Preisner, won a Silver Bear at the
Berlin Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Island on Bird Street,'' a Danish-German-British project,
suffers from a decision to film in color and have everyone speak
English. Black and white would have served the movie better, and
the clash of accents, from Warden's flat American to Kuziuk's
Oxford English to a mishmash of European voices, is distracting. To
make up for extended dead periods, the movie also loads up with
false suspense, those patented scenes where soldiers stare and
stare at a hiding place before turning away.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem with ``The Island on Bird Street'' lies
with the screenplay, adapted from Uri Orlev's semi-autobiographical
novel of a boy trying to survive in the ruins of the Warsaw Ghetto
during World War II. Screenwriters John Goldsmith and Tony Grisoni
give you a constant barrage of Alex while brushing past other
characters in the film, leaving one unanswered question after
another.
</P>
<P>
   During a Nazi sweep of the ghetto, Alex's father is taken away,
but not before telling his son to ``stay put. I shall come back for
you.'' Alex takes that order to heart, burrowing into an
underground bunker, grabbing food and water where he can, talking
at length with his pet white mouse, reading and rereading his copy
of ``Robinson Crusoe'' and finally setting up a loft in one of the
ruined houses _ a loft where he watches while Jews are rounded up
for the camps, only yards away from the bustle of Warsaw on the
other side of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Alex monitors Warsaw beyond the ghetto, looking on from his loft
to see a doctor at a chess table, alone, or a girl staring out her
window, or children playing among the rubble. He takes care of a
wounded man for more than a week, finding enough money and enough
courage to cross the street and ask the doctor for help. But the
movie isn't really interested in these other people _ it's only
interested in Alex.
</P>
<P>
   Would you like to know if the doctor crosses into the ghetto
because of that roll of money or his own sense of decency? The
movie won't tell you. Would you like to know why Alex stops
appearing at a regular rendezvous with a girl who is taking a risk
to be with him? The movie is silent on that score. Would you like
Alex to say, in his own words, why he'll stay behind in the ruins
of the ghetto rather than accept an offer to escape to the country?
He won't.
</P>
<P>
   In a final double-cross, the ending demands a massive leap of
faith from the audience without offering a reason why people should
make that leap. It wants to transcend the Nazi terror without
talking about how it could happen. Like everything else in ``The
Island on Bird Street,'' the ending leaves the audience to fend for
itself _ to come up with its own answers to what goes on beyond the
walls, trying to grasp the world outside the singular mind of an
11-year-old boy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
