<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS &LR;      12-18 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMAS STRIVES TO AVOID FLASHBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ Judging from its success this season, you
would never know that the University of Massachusetts football team
is still being harassed by demons of last year's dreadful 2-9
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen's dramatic turnaround, culminating with Saturday's
NCAA Division 1-AA championship game against unbeaten Georgia
Southern, shows they're is not paralyzed by memories of troubles
past.
</P>
<P>
   Haunted is more like it. For all their unprecedented success,
all the records set, all the obstacles scaled, and all the memories
achieved with arguably the most successful season in school
history, UMass (11-3) still often struggles to put 1997 behind it.
When things have gone well this season, players have become
complacent. When mistakes occur, frustrations have set in.
</P>
<P>
   Both situations sometimes prompt players unaccustomed to such
success as a team to revive last season's bad habits _ not enough
to hurt their cause, but enough to make things often more difficult
than they should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things go wrong on a play, and then when we go back
into the huddle, people start blaming other people, and that's the
same thing that happened last year,'' said senior tight end Kerry
Taylor, a cocaptain. ``But then (fullback) Matt Jordan or
(quarterback) Todd Bankhead will step up and then someone will say,
`Listen, we're still winning.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I don't know if the offense even scored 200 points
all year and I know the defense gave up tons of points. So when the
offense goes out and explodes for big plays and the defense makes a
stop, sometimes we're overwhelmed with what just happened. Then we
relax and then we see the other team make a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the reasons first-year coach Mark Whipple continues
to put pressure on the Minutemen, convinced that not doing so often
leads to such problems. Whipple's relentlessness is a primary
reason a team which lost 10-point leads five times this season and
suffered at least three turnovers in 11 outings has weathered
adversities and still believes it can reach the pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as coaches have to coach them hard,'' said Whipple. ``I'm
worried about everything, every day of the week. We sit in meetings
that can't let these guys get away with anything. And we have to be
on them all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with 58 seconds left in last Saturday's 41-31 semifinal win
over Northwestern (La.) State. Whipple was doused with Gatorade at
that time, and he let everyone know he wasn't pleased, that the
game was far from over. ``Knowing (Northwestern State), I know
anything can happen,'' he said. ``They could have gotten 21 points
on them with their skill. Not until nine seconds left did I feel
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to change anything we've done. We will stay
hard on them all the time, in meetings and practice. I think even
more so now, because that's a natural tendency for humans, when
they're doing well and everyone is patting you on your back, to
slip back into bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was hired, I told the kids our ultimate goal was to win
the championship. They were kind of like kids at Christmas, very
eager, wanting to come in and meet, and really worked very hard.
But I don't know if they knew how hard they had to work or the
demands we were going to put on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a couple of weeks, that excitement wore off, and some
guys left the program. But the guys like Khari (Samuel, another
cocaptain) and Kerry knew what it was about, stayed, and I just saw
them get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is it so difficult for a team which set a school record
for victories to put last year behind it? Because it was the worst
season for a Minuteman team this century. It included lopsided
defeats, bickering, and infighting. And players say that what made
it frustrating was that they knew they had the talent to do what
they've done this season all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were always looking for answers,'' said senior
linebacker Samuel. ``This year we come out. We're explosive. We'll
put up two or three touchdowns first, and then it's as if maybe we
relax a bit and play comfortable. That is why I like it in those
situations'' when UMass enters as the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple said UMass will have to play its best game of the season
to beat Georgia Southern, whose option offense and speedy defense
have earned it three playoff victories by an average of 24 points.
That includes a 52-20 second-round victory over Connecticut, which
edged the Minutemen twice this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're mistake-free, then we'll win the game,'' said
Whipple. ``But on the other hand, with football, with that many
plays, you're going to make mistakes, and how do you handle them?
What this team has done so well all year is handle the adversity
and use that as a motivation, not a negative.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was voted to the 1-AA Coaches All-America Team and Samuel
was voted to the Associated Press All-America team. ``It's pretty
special; I didn't expect it to happen,'' said Taylor. ``I thank my
players because they've made me a better player, and it will feel a
lot better if we win (Saturday).'' . . . With the success teams
like Georgia Southern have had in recent years with the option,
it's a wonder why the offense _ once one of the most popular in
college football _ hasn't made more of a comeback. ``I think that,
in all honesty, I'm not sure a lot of people understand it,'' said
Georgia Southern coach Paul Johnson. ``I think football goes in
trends. It went from where everyone runs some option to the West
Coast offense, wherever that is. Now I think it's going back to
where everyone's running some option.'' But don't expect UMass to
follow the trend. ``I know why I don't run it. I ran it in college
and I got my butt kicked all the time,'' said Whipple, a former
quarterback at Brown. ``I got two bad knees and two bad shoulders
because of it.'' Georgia Southern will be the first option team
UMass has faced this season . . . Expect Saturday's game to have a
Georgia Southern flavor. Johnson said Thursday the school has
already sold 8,000 tickets and added, ``We should have at least
10,000 people here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
