 Friday, Dec. 18, 1998    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ With the House debating the
impeachment of a president for the first time since 1868, First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton breaks her public silence to praise her
husband and urge Americans to devote the holiday season to
``reflection and reconciliation'' and to ``end divisiveness.'' By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON-REAX (Washington) _ A day after House
Speaker-designate Bob Livingston confessed to his own adultery,
Republicans say there's no similarity between him and President
Clinton, but House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., calls
for an end to ``the politics of smear and slash and burn.'' By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SHAYS-IMPEACH (Washington) _ We profile Rep. Christopher Shays
of Connecticut, a moderate Republican who is scheduled to meet
today with President Clinton. Shays, one of the last fence-sitters
on the impeachment issue, has a record of defying Republican
leaders. By MARK HELM and STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   REHNQUIST-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, an impeachment-history buff, will preside at the
expected trial of President Clinton in the Senate. We examine
Rehnquist's record and writings for clues to how he might handle
the case. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following story was filed Thursday for Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Like Richard Nixon a quarter
century ago, Bill Clinton is not going to give up the power and
perquisites of the presidency without a struggle. But if the
``comeback kid'' is to save his presidency, he is going to have to
give the performance of a lifetime when the 106th Congress convenes
in January. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
