<HEADER>
A7054 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASTFOOD-MINORITIES-A     12-18 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASTFOOD-MINORITIES-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY OWNERSHIP LAGS IN FAST-FOOD INDUSTRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By REBECCA MOWBRAY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The fast-food industry is sizzling with talk of
emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   These hotbeds of opportunity are not in Brazil, Thailand or
Poland. They are minority neighborhoods in urban America, according
to the International Franchise Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest jewel we have left untouched in the U.S. is the
inner cities,'' said Michael Seid, managing director of Michael
Seid &AMP; Associates, a West Hartford, Conn., consulting firm that
specializes in franchising and works with the franchise
association.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that minority ownership of fast-food
franchises is growing in kind.
</P>
<P>
   While fast-food companies have programs designed to back up
ethnic marketing campaigns with more diverse ownership of
franchises, significant gains in minority ownership of franchises
are hard to document.
</P>
<P>
   The largest fast-food restaurant chains have been adding
minority owners, but the percentage of minority ownership is about
half what it is in the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, minorities were stuck with older restaurants in
less-profitable locations. Failing equipment, heightened security
problems and lack of good help cut into their profits.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring how big a share of the fast-food franchise business is
held by blacks, Hispanics, Asians and Native Americans is difficult
to document.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Women in Franchising, a Chicago consultant that helps
women and minorities slide into franchising, estimates that 10
percent of all franchise units _ a figure that includes more than
just fast food _ are minority-owned, and that proportion remains
flat.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Census Bureau figures indicate blacks, Asians, Native
Americans and Hispanics are 29 percent of the U.S. population and
growing.
</P>
<P>
   The International Franchise Association doesn't keep statistics
on minority ownership of franchises _ referring callers to the
individual companies _ and neither does the U.S. Small Business
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Kezios, president of Women in Franchising, said that this
omission is telling. Kezios thinks the fast-food industry's
commitment to diversity trails far behind other concerns. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The reason, Seid said, is that the fast-food companies pay more
attention to the color of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason franchise companies are going into inner cities is
pure economics. There's a need for it,'' Seid said. ``I'm not so
naive to think that franchisers are running around thinking, `I've
got to increase minority ownership by 10 percent this year.' They
don't care. They're colorblind, and that's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Franchising is like a professional sports team:
They're picking the best people they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   From the fast-food company's point of view, its future depends
on the management skill and financial strength of its operators.
Franchise owners are the ones who innovate and make their
restaurant a part of the community. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A lawsuit filed recently in Houston by an angry Wendy's
franchisee shows how race can still become an issue in this
business.
</P>
<P>
   Theldon Branch, an African-American businessman who owns three
Wendy's restaurants, sued the No. 3 hamburger chain in U.S.
District Court in Houston on Oct. 22, alleging racial
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   His lawsuit says Wendy's refused to sell him existing locations
because he is black. The company wanted him to build new stores _
which is a much more expensive proposition _ then sold the stores
he wanted to a white owner. Branch is trying to have his suit
certified as a class action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wendy's denies this allegation,'' said Houston lawyer Gene
Locke, who has been retained by Wendy's. ``This is really a dispute
between Wendy's and one franchisee who wanted to buy additional
stores in the Houston area. Wendy's made a business decision to
sell those stores to other people who met the business criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy's response to the lawsuit says that Branch bounced checks
to the company and did not demonstrate the financial strength
needed to get more restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Of Wendy's 3,717 franchised U.S. restaurants, 262 are
minority-owned. Sixty-seven _ 13.4 percent _ of its 499 franchise
owners are minorities, and 26 are African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy's said it has stepped up its diversification efforts this
year. Five new minority franchisees joined the company in 1998, and
the company awarded more stores to minorities already in the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Such programs run up against corporate pressures peculiar to
franchising that stack the odds against new store owners, said Tim
Bates, a professor of labor and urban affairs at Wayne State
University in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real opportunities go to insiders,'' Bates said. Behind
every fast-food restaurant are some powerful operators owning a
large number of locations.
</P>
<P>
   Because they understand the business and have a proven track
record, these players often get the first crack at new locations.
``If they pass, what does that say about the opportunity?''
</P>
<P>
   But there are several minority franchisees in Houston showing a
well-heeled minority investor can get into this business in a big
way.
</P>
<P>
   With 32 Taco Bell restaurants throughout the Houston area, Shawn
Taylor, a former Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co. consultant and an African
American, has become co-owner of the largest Taco Bell franchise in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and his business partner, Duni Hebron, a former Taco Bell
market manager, started Family Eats two years ago with 19 stores.
It's a lucrative business that gives them the chance to create
opportunity for others in all sorts of neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us an opportunity as African Americans to create 30
jobs (per store) that today don't exist in those communities, of
which several of those jobs will be salaried positions with
bonuses, health insurance, retirement plans, you name it. And a
fringe benefit is that we are minorities going in and building a
successful business in those communities. You become role models.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fast-food franchises say having more minority-owned restaurants
at a time when patrons are increasingly diverse makes good business
sense.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a limited number of people who are likely owners in
a business where opening a big-name fast-food restaurant such as
Burger King can cost between $300,000 and $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Companies emphasize how they work to support new &UR;  &LR; operators
within the system _ which can help minority entrepreneurs _ but the
money is still a barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies will reduce the upfront cost by starting owners
off with a lower-cost kiosk location, leasing a restaurant, or
allowing them to use a low down payment to buy an existing
restaurant. But some analysts caution that financing programs can
carry expensive terms and carrying a heavy debt can make business
precarious.
</P>
<P>
   This savagely competitive franchise industry has moved into new
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The industry recently began to see the opportunity in inner
cities after many suburban strips became so overpopulated with fast
food that restaurants began to cannibalize each other's business.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the fast-food industry has underestimated the
potential of lower-income areas. But as urban areas have begun to
revive, the industry realized that these neighborhoods are more
densely populated than the suburbs and are served by fewer nearby
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   While residents in these areas have lower incomes on average,
they spend a higher proportion of their earnings eating out. These
families often see a meal out at a fast-food restaurant as a treat.
</P>
<P>
   As the restaurant chains change their view of the cities, groups
that once were known for championing civil rights issues are now
pushing to be sure minorities share in the profits.
</P>
<P>
   They see franchises as important business opportunities because
the franchises have a higher rate of success than independent
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH coalition, which works with Burger
King on diversity issues, reasons that since African Americans are
20 percent of a chain's customer base, they should own 20 percent
of that chain's restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The National Urban League sees opportunity for economic
advancement in franchising, and devoted its national economic
development summit last spring to franchise opportunities for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   All of the major fast-food companies have diversity programs,
and strive to support owners in different ways. Burger King
committed in 1994 to increasing minority ownership of its
restaurants by one percentage point a year.
</P>
<P>
   Taco Bell seeks out a small number of strong owners who are
capable of managing a large number of restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy's participates in the IFA's Franchise Trade Delegation
Program _ a venture that seeks to drum up new franchise owners in
emerging market areas of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the company with the most aggressive program is
Atlanta-based AFC Enterprises, whose ownership of the Popeye's
Chicken and Churchs Chicken chains makes it the No. 2 fast-food
chicken chain.
</P>
<P>
   Theldon Branch's wife, Ester Branch, is opening 10 Churchs
Chicken stores because they're profitable and hospitable to African
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary difference over at Churchs is that diversity is
more than just a buzzword,'' Theldon Branch said.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 37 percent of AFC's franchised restaurants are owned
by minorities because of the company's active recruitment efforts
at historically black colleges and in black newspapers and business
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   To make opening a store as affordable as possible, AFC seeks out
prospective franchisees who can use government programs that
encourage investments in low-income neighborhoods to reduce the
start-up costs.
</P>
<P>
   They are encouraged to open restaurants in existing buildings,
which may halve the cost of starting up. AFC refers candidates to
its strategic partner, Banco Popular, for financing. Based in
Puerto Rico, Banco Popular operates in six states with large
Hispanic populations and is a top SBA lender to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The company also assigns a business consultant to work with each
prospective franchisee on starting the store, and that consultant
remains the franchisee's permanent resource within the company.
</P>
<P>
   Seid, the business consultant, said AFC's strategy of diversity
is paying off. ``AFC dominates in some markets because KFC didn't
get into it early,'' he said. ``It has benefited them tremendously.
They have a diverse franchise base; they tailor their products.''
</P>
<P>
   AFC tries to reach blacks, Hispanics and whites in equal
proportion and targets its advertisements accordingly. One campaign
featured gospel singer Kirk Franklin, who became so enthusiastic
about Churchs, he opened 12 of them after doing the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Hartman, AFC vice president for corporate communications,
said diverse ownership also reinforces the marketing campaign.
``They see people who look and are like them in the restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   That point raises a thorny question for those pushing for more
minorities in the business. Strategies to tap emerging markets
can't be so zealous as to limit the franchisees' choice of store
location based on their race or ethnicity, according to Robert
Zarco, a Miami franchisee attorney. ``That's redlining if you have
a black operator and you put them in a black neighborhood instead
of in a white suburban neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
