at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACHMENT COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ The House debates impeachment of
President Clinton. (Carr/Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE _ WASHINGTON _ History humbug! That was the
prevailing attitude of ordinary Americans touring the Capitol as
the House debated impeachment Friday. The scene of members reciting
their now-familiar arguments to a mostly empty chamber did not live
up to most visitor's expectations of the solemn occasion. But
elsewhere on Capitol Hill, in the hallways and offices of
congressional buildings, there was a sense of the historic
importance of what was happening in the House chamber. (Dart, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ The situation at the White House,
where Clinton remained in seclusion amid hints that he and his
staff already were mapping out a strategy for how to blunt expected
stepped-up calls for the president's resignation if the House votes
for impeachment. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESSURE _ WASHINGTON _ A week packed with tough peace
talks in Jerusalem, political battling against impeachment and a
war on Iraq has subjected President Clinton to an excruciating set
of pressures that few chief executives could imagine. How he's
holding up. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Reskedded from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LAREACT _ Reaction of suburban New Orleans district to
news of Livingston's marital infidelity and the impeachment
debate/vote. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-GADEL _ Highlights from the Georgia delegation; what
they said and what they did. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV _ ATLANTA _ Coverage of Friday's TV, expected to be a
constant split screen between impeachment and Iraq. (Jubera,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BAXTER _ WASHINGTON _ Column from the scene. (Baxter,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   NON-IMPEACHMENT COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MONEY _ WASHINGTON _ Any candidate who wants to win
either major-party presidential nomination in 2000 will have to
raise $22 million to $25 million in 1999, leading campaign finance
experts tell us. That's more than $60,000 a day, 7 days a week. And
that's just the so-called ``hard'' money. Enforcement of federal
limits has become so haphazard that another expert says he can't
even guess at how much unregulated ``soft'' money will be raised
and spent. An explainer of why candidates must raise so much so
early, what the money is spent for, and which candidates are
favored in what pundits call ``the invisible primary.'' (Mollison,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DATA _ For graphic or box.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wedneday and to be repeated Friday. Shelf-life for
this story: Dec. 20-Jan.1.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   US-IRAQ _ BAGHDAD or WASHINGTON _ American and British bombers
began a third day of bombings amid indications that the U.S.
strategy is to remove Saddam Hussein by turning his military and
security forces against him. U.S. aircraft dropped leaflets in
southern Iraq warning Iraqi forces there that they will be targeted
if they try to attack neighboring Kuwait or Saudi Arabia, but will
be spared if they stay in their bases. Meanwhile, the Pentagon said
it is widening its list of targets. Developing. (Deans/Kaplow, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ATTACKS _ BAGHDAD _ The stories of some of the several
dozen Iraqi people who have been injured in the three days of
attacks by U.S. and British forces. The story will be topped with
an Iraqi marine engineer who has visited, and liked the United
States. That is, until one of the missiles literally landed in his
living room. He now wants Saddam to take revenge. Developing.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin was
joined by leaders from across the country Friday in denouncing the
U.S. and British attacks on Iraq and demanded an immediate halt to
the campaign. Top military leaders warned that Russia's relations
with the United States and the West may be seriously damaged by the
U.S. attack on Iraq, wiping out years of progress since the end of
the Cold War. And the Foreign Ministry said it had recalled
Russia's ambassador to Britain for urgent consultations -- a day
after it did the same thing with the Russian ambassador to
Washington. Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-WOMEN _ WASHINGTON _ Seven years after the U.S. Senate
lifted a 43-year-old ban on female pilots in combat, several women
on the USS Enterprise are flying fighter aircraft in the Persian
Gulf. The conflict marks the third time in American history women
have flown fighter planes under fire. Developing. (Monroe, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to begin moving by 5 p.m. EST in both the
International and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   TOBBACCO-FARM _ DURHAM, N.C. _ Big Tobacco meets Dec. 18 with
governors and agriculture commissioners from tobacco states to
discuss how to help tobacco farmers survive cutbacks. (Chamberlain,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by NYT
clients).
</P>
<P>
   TX-CLEMENCY-BUSH _ Amid what has become international clamor
about the state's clemency system. Gov. George W. Bush says it
would take a ``compelling argument'' to get him to support any
changes. The current system, says Bush, works fine. He fears that
opening the system would lead to another trial. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TELEMARKET-FRAUD _ Federal and state investigators hold a news
conference concerning results of and undercover operation that
targeted fraud among telemarketers. Charges have been filed against
nearly 1,000 telemarketers. (Tanamachi, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS If a budget line or story is marked
with photos or graphics, those are available from the New York
Times News Service at 212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more
information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
