<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MAIL-HNS &LR;      12-18 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ROMANTIC COMEDY LASTS TOO LONG FOR COMFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail'' has two absolutely beguiling stars in Tom
Hanks and Meg Ryan, a clever, straight-from-the-news premise, and
New York's Upper West Side at Christmas time. That's a lot for any
movie to have going for it.
</P>
<P>
   But what it also has is too many minutes _ 115 of them. In my
book, no romantic comedy should ever be more than 90 minutes. At
two hours, the froth on the comedy starts to dissolve like foam on
a latte left standing all day. At that length, the filmmakers are
either begging a question, sustaining a conflict beyond the
audience's attention span, or too in love with their own movie.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo! When Nora Ephron is in charge _ she is both director and
co-writer with her sister Delia _ these things tend to happen. They
did in ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' another film starring Hanks and
Ryan (potentially one of the screen's most enduring duos) that
failed to realize its merits for the same reason. It took forever
for the couple to meet, and when they finally did, it felt
anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   But Ephron is nothing if not a woman in tune with popular
culture. Where ``Sleepless in Seattle'' was about Ryan being
attracted to Hanks after hearing him on a radio talk show, now we
have Hanks and Ryan as two e-mail pen pals who don't know that they
know each other in real life. It's a clever premise, since nearly
everyone these days has ``met'' someone this way.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's character, Kathleen Kelly, owns a bookstore that has been
in the family for years, The Shop Around the Corner. This is an
affectionate nod to the classic 1940 comedy by that name starring
Jimmy Stewart and Margaret Sullavan, and upon which this screenplay
is based. Those characters, however, communicated by snail mail.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks' character, Joe Fox, is scion of a family who runs
enormous bookstore chains (think Borders or Barnes &AMP; Noble). Where
Joe's store offers cappuccinos and huge discounts, Kathleen's
offers children's story time and personal service.
</P>
<P>
   They inadvertently meet, and despite the fact that sparks fly,
eventually she discovers that he is the guy bringing a store into
her neighborhood that could force her out of business. This throws
the proverbial bucket of ice water on their romance.
</P>
<P>
   What she does not discover, however, is that Joe is the dream
man she ``met'' anonymously in an on-line chat room, and she's been
communicating with him daily. As their spite toward each other
grows in real life, so does their affection in their fantasy life _
which includes rules like no names, no specifics, just pure
thoughts and feelings.
</P>
<P>
   For the first third of the film, the premise works splendidly.
You like both of them, you realize they are mismatched with their
significant others, you root for a satisfying solution. But when
Joe finds out that Kathleen is his e-mail dream woman, the movie
starts to go wrong, and too many questions are raised with no good
answers.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing now who Kathleen is, why would Joe continue to put her
out of business? Is he actually a jerk? And if he's a jerk, why
should she kick the hunky Greg Kinnear (whose character is fairly
simpatico) out of bed for him? Why doesn't Joe reveal himself to
her once he finds out the truth?
</P>
<P>
   Because Ephron wants to sustain the tension as long as possible.
Unfortunately, that leads to overlong scenes in which Joe attempts
to woo Kathleen without coming forth with the truth, and eventually
the audience's patience is tried.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, Hanks and Ryan are good as ever _ he of
the potato face and smile you want to fall into, she of the witty
cuteness. Although Ryan is in danger of wearing out her welcome as
America's Sweetheart if she makes one more film in which she (A)
gets the sniffles cutely, or (B) pads around in flannel jammies
cutely, or (C) wrinkles up her nose more than 150 times.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting cast members are also excellent, although the plot
bogs down occasionally with their subplots. Dabney Coleman as Joe's
womanizing father is as dry and soulless as we imagine all moguls
to be, Parker Posey is a breath of fresh air as Joe's Type Triple-A
girlfriend, and Kinnear is a scene-stealer as a vain newspaper
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   If Ephron had been directing someone else's script, she might
have had the objectivity required to lose about 20 minutes worth of
unneeded scenes, or trim some that meander endlessly. As it is, by
the time Joe and Kathleen finally meet in the rose garden for the
long-awaited denouement, we are relieved. But we should have been
thrilled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
