<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-WOMEN-$ADV20-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHOMING THAT COMPLEX CREATURE, WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ My moment of enlightenment happened as I stood at a
railing on the third floor of the Marshall Field department store
here in the Loop recently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was looking down through the Christmas decorations onto the
first-floor cosmetic counters. There I saw two women sitting on
tall chairs. Other women who worked in the store were applying
makeup to these women as countless Christmas shoppers wandered by. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, I thought. I do not know one male who would subject
himself to such a public spectacle in pursuit of looking better
through chemistry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That, clearly, is one of the primary differences between the
sexes. Try to imagine a man you know _ or even you yourself, if,
like me, you are male _ sitting in a busy department store and
having some clerk brushing here and painting there to improve the
looks of that man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have seen too much in life to insist it would never happen.
But I have never seen it happen. I did not see it happen in
Marshall Field's store. And I don't expect to see it happen before
I get carted off to the home and equipped with my own drool apron. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking about the differences between males and
females as the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal has unfolded, including why
it was so easy to believe that the Tripp-Lewinsky conversations,
caught on tape, were real. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I grew up as the only boy in a house full of four children,
which, by my count, means three were sisters. (And to the best of
my recollection, they were.) And I helped rear two daughters and no
sons. So I know some things about women that men without my vast
experience may not appreciate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing I know _ and love _ about women is that they often are
really good at talking with each other about private things.
Somehow women find it helpful and maybe even therapeutic to discuss
with other women their feelings about deeply intimate emotions. I
envy that, though I recognize that I may not be capable of it
because of some genetic structure related to my being male. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Men may be better about engaging in this kind of talk than they
used to be, but as a rule, the level of sharing about such things
among men rarely rises above the level of this question: ``So,
Harvey, tell me: You keeping as busy in the bedroom as you always
want us to believe?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, in turn, is likely to respond: ``You guys only wish you
were a stud like me.'' The next question, with barely time for a
breath, is likely to be: ``Yeah? Well, how about them Denver
Broncos?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's why, when women send daughters out into the world, they
prefer a long weekend together in which they may share private
hopes, dreams and advice. Men, generally, are content to walk a son
to the door as he leaves the nest, pat the kid on the butt and say,
``Go get 'em, Ace.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My own father was even briefer. As I left home permanently in
1967, he walked me out to the 1964 Rambler he had traded me for my
1958 Chevy, looked to see that the tires were full of air, shook my
hand and said, ``Write.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the paper hiring me is paying me to do,'' I said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that, knuckle-head. Write HOME once in a while.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My mother, meanwhile, stood behind him crying. I didn't
understand then why she was crying. But I know now she was upset I
wasn't a daughter who would engage in deep emotional sharing with
her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was the same mother who, when I reached the age when I had
quit growing in length and would grow only in breadth, took me to
this same Marshall Field's store in Chicago to buy me a decent
sports coat I could take to college and not embarrass myself if I
had to get semi-dressed up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a deep forest-green, herring-bone coat. All wool. I was
aghast at its cost _ $60 or so, an unimaginable fortune to me in
1963. I loved that jacket so much as an 18-year-old kid that I
wanted to wear it home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So I put it on and went down to Field's first floor cosmetic
counter to see if it would attract women. But they were too busy
getting made up to notice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I should have stood up on the third floor and whistled
down at them. Or told them some day we'd have a president named
Bill and it might be me. (Would that have risen to the level of
impeachable perjury?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, Dec. 20, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
