<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING FACES IS ANOTHER LANGUAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If you want to look into someone's soul, just take a
close look at his face. According to a self-styled face reader, the
wrinkles, dimples and droops reveal a life of happiness, tragedy
and everything in between.
</P>
<P>
   Eyelids are the barometer of life, said Mac Fulfer, a lawyer
from Fort Worth who taught himself to read faces. Fulfer was in
Houston recently to teach a roomful of human resource managers how
to interpret the lines and bumps on the faces of employees, bosses
and job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   The technique is about as scientific as astrology, with phrases
that can be used to describe just about anyone. Nurturing.
Competitive. Focused. Anyone can think of an instance when we can
use those words to define a part of our personality.
</P>
<P>
   Human resource managers were rather skeptical that the lines
between the nose and mouth indicate a strong libido or see deep
personal tragedy in a line that runs from the corner of the mouth
to the chin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm apparently a provider because of my wide nostrils,'' said
a professor of communications attending the seminar. ``I find it a
bit difficult to see, but there you are.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman let out a scream when she found her libido line. It's
true, she said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 45 muscles in the face, which can create more than
5,000 facial expressions, Fulfer said. People tend to use the same
patterns over and over again, which tends to shape your face, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Droopy eyelids indicate someone is pushing himself too hard,
said Fulfer. If the lids sag on the left eye, there's too much
intensity in his personal life. A sag on the right eye signals too
much pressure at work.
</P>
<P>
   Both eyes? Watch out, he needs a break, said Fulfer.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfer said he learned to study faces when he was working as a
lawyer because it helped him pick sympathetic juries. He said he
``validated'' his research by setting up a tent at festivals such
as the Rattlesnake Round-up and Octoberfest and offering to read
faces for $5 and later, when he got popular, $10.
</P>
<P>
   He said he read thousands of faces and the feedback that he
received helped him pick up on general traits which he has
chronicled in a book, ``Amazing Face Reading: An Illustrated
Encyclopedia for Reading Faces.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JOWLS OF POWER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jowls, for example, are a symbol of power, Fulfer said.
President Nixon had them and when he was threatened with
impeachment, they flattened.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfer said that jowls are such a well-recognized symbol of
power that if you ask a bell boy to give a package to ``the
president'' at a convention event, he'll look for the man with the
biggest jowls.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfer offered a tip for women who want power: Don't complain
about the glass ceiling. All you need are jowls _ just look at
Madeleine Albright or Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Face reading works even if someone has had a facelift or plucks
her eyebrows (which, apparently, indicate how a person thinks).
</P>
<P>
   People change appearances based on the environment they're in,
said Fulfer, who recounted a story about a lowly clerk at a bus
company who didn't have much of a chin. After gaining a chin in
plastic surgery _ and therefore, gaining an aura of power and
authority _ people started treating her differently, Fulfer said.
No more meek and mild; she suddenly began moving up and now she is
an executive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SKEPTICS WEIGH IN
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Webb, personnel officer at the Harris County Appraisal
District, was interested in what face lines can say but isn't
willing to throw out the personal interview, reference checks and
drug screenings when she evaluates job candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The lines apparently change based on stress, said Webb, so lines
that appear on a candidate's face may just be the result of
worrying about the interview or worrying that his parking meter
just expired.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Webb said she went to church the night of Fulfer's
presentation and noticed that everyone has a mouth that turns down.
Maybe everyone in the congregation is skeptical, Webb said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Miller, legendary Houston trial lawyer, said he closely
watches potential jurors but focuses on their head tilts, facial
expressions and mannerisms _ for example, someone who crosses his
arms gives the signal that he's made up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Even with other people watching reactions, it's impossible to
read a jury correctly all the time, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   But looking at wrinkles, nostril size and dimples? You've got to
be kidding, Miller said with a laugh. Facial features are based on
genetics, he said. ``It's so phony.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
