<P>
   PHILIPPINES-AIRLINES (Manila) _ With $2.2 billion in debt,
plunging revenues and losses of close to $1 million a day,
Philippine Airlines, Asia's oldest airline, is in desperate shape.
But Philippine Airlines is also the crown jewel in the empire of
Lucio Tan, a tycoon who is a leading supporter of the new president
of the Philippines, Joseph E. Estrada. In the murky world of Asian
business, where friendships often count more than solvency,
Philippine Airlines would seem to be the classic candidate for a
government bailout. The catch is that Estrada, wanting foreign
investors to view the Philippines as having a level playing field,
has ruled out injecting any public money. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Today is a ``triple-witching'' day. At
midday, the industrial average was down 5 points but the Nasdaq
index was up 17 points, or 0.8 percent. Elsewhere, prices climbed
half a percent in Tokyo and 1.4 percent in Hong Kong. They fell 1.4
percent in Frankfurt but rose 0.8 percent in London. Brazilian
shares were off 0.1 percent, and Mexico's market was flat. On the
American debt market, the long bond was off 11/32 point, with the
yield at 5.03 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
