<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-QUEENOFCUTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH `YOU'VE GOT MAIL,' MEG RYAN CONTINUES HER REIGN AS
GIRL-NEXT-DOOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To be honest, ``You've Got Mail'' isn't a very good movie. It's
predictable and manipulative; it comes across as one big ad for
America Online. Also, it's way too long.
</P>
<P>
   But it does have Meg Ryan. So you'll go.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there's also her co-star, that Tom Hanks guy. (Those
Oscars, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' blah, blah, blah.) And
writer/director Nora Ephron, who wrote the book on romantic
comedies with her triptych of ``When Harry Met Sally, Sleepless in
Seattle'' and ``Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   But at its core, ``You've Got Mail'' is all about Meg Ryan, the
reigning practitioner of Movie Star Cute.
</P>
<P>
   If you know anything about this movie _ and you can just hear
the pitch meeting: ``Meg and Tom are secret E-mail pen pals, but
they hate each other in real life!'' _ you know what happens. No,
if you've ever been to a Meg Ryan movie, you know what happens. She
wrinkles her nose; she hovers on the edge of tears, those big blue
eyes almost brimming over; she is sweet to children and just sassy
enough to men. She is terminally, though not insufferably, cute.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard that Meg doesn't like to be called cute. Too bad.
She is what she is. And we're glad she got those ``serious roles''
out of her system. Meg Ryan as a helicopter pilot? Get out. As a
children's bookstore owner? That's more like it.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing at all deep about her appeal, mind you. Cute
isn't deep. That's one of the things we like about her.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing too glamorous about her either. We like that,
too. Here is a movie star who acts like we might if anyone ever
made a movie starring a prettier, thinner us.
</P>
<P>
   She sits around in baggy jammies. (Hey, WE like to sit around in
baggy jammies!) She gets excited about getting E-mail. (Hey, WE get
excited about getting E-mail!) She has a soft spot for Tom Hanks.
(Hey, WE _ well, you're on to us now.)
</P>
<P>
   Men, of course, love her, too _ they are crazy about cute. But
she's one of the few actresses that men love that women like just
as much.
</P>
<P>
   Ephron _ who wrote ``Harry'' (1989), directed ``Sleepless''
(1993) and co-wrote and directed the new ``Mail'' _ understands
this. She told one interviewer, Meg ``has no vanity. The women that
women love are those who don't walk around full of their own
self-love. You know when you see Meg on screen that if you found
yourself next to her, you might become friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is the way our parents felt about Doris Day; really,
that's who she is, with a messier haircut and a slightly sharper
edge. (I don't think Doris Day ever slept with anyone in her
movies, even after marriage. But you have to make some concession
to the '90s.)
</P>
<P>
   And as far as romantic comedies go, particularly the subset
starring Meg Ryan, ``You've Got Mail'' is better than ``Sleepless
in Seattle,'' not as good as ``When Harry Met Sally.'' As if it
really matters.
</P>
<P>
   It's sweet. It's out just in time for Christmas. It's got Meg
Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Save us a seat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
