<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEME-RESTAURANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEME RESTAURANTS SCARCE IN CITY OF FINE DINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in financial sted lifestyle category.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco, a perennial contender for world's
greatest restaurant city, is short on one kind of restaurant that
has swept over much of the rest of the world: the big-bang,
big-theme, show-biz restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The city _ with 3,400 licensed restaurants, only two of which
are themed _ may not need the theme restaurants that flourish
elsewhere. But the theme concept, starved for visibility and
dedicated to brand-building and related merchandising, needs
prestigious, tourist-rich San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is central. It's intuitively where we would like
to be,'' said Chris Stephenson, senior vice president of sales and
marketing for House of Blues, a minichain of music clubs with
full-service restaurants and bars, which has yet to expand here.
</P>
<P>
   Theme-restaurants typically cater to tourists hungry for
predictable decor, familiar menus and reasonable prices _ the
average per person bill at the Hard Rock Cafe is $13.50, according
to company executives.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by the San Francisco Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau, tourists dropped an average of $34.18 per person per day in
San Francisco's restaurants in the first half of 1998. The bureau
doesn't break out figures for theme restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Only Hard Rock Cafe and Planet Hollywood now operate in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1970 in London as the first major theme-restaurant
chain, the Hard Rock, which is based in Orlando, Fla., has 98
restaurants in 34 countries; all feature burgers and barbecue on
the menu, and rock music memorabilia on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Hard Rock Cafe International spent an undisclosed sum renovating
its San Francisco outlet last year. According to Linda Frigerio,
general manager of the San Francisco Hard Rock, the restaurant
lowered seating capacity from 200 to 160 to upgrade its
entertainment system and expand its on-site retail operations.
Frigerio estimates that 300,000 people chowed down in the eatery in
the past year, with another 100,000 stopping by just to buy
T-shirts and other items.
</P>
<P>
   The chief operating officer of the Hard Rock chain, Pete
Beaudrault, said San Francisco was in the Hard Rock's global top 10
in revenue, though he wouldn't cite dollar amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Block, a restaurant consultant in Sausalito, Calif., said
that Hard Rock ``still has a cachet of hipness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of branded merchandise, Block said, are what drive
successful theme restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been about food,'' he said. ``It's always been
about retailing. At theme restaurants, people don't come back for
the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Block said that in San Francisco's fiercely competitive
restaurant market, chain restaurants in general do not survive.
``In New York, which has 7 million people, there are 7,500
full-service restaurants. San Francisco, with 750,000 people, has
3,400 restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's only other chain theme restaurant is Planet
Hollywood, which opened three years ago with a riot of flashbulbs,
a red carpet and personal appearances by Planet Hollywood investors
Arnold Schwarzenegger and Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   However, parent company Planet Hollywood International is
spinning on a wobbly axis, having put its Orlando, Fla., corporate
headquarters and restaurant on New York's Times Square up for sale
this week to pay creditors. The company lost $10.1 million in the
third quarter of 1998, and chain-wide revenue was down 26 percent
in the quarter, according to recent filings with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Planet Hollywood spokesmen declined to discuss the corporation's
travails. Planet Hollywood operates 80 eateries, including the
sports-themed Official All Star Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Block attributes Planet Hollywood's eclipse to its too-rapid
worldwide expansion. In contrast, he praised ``the cautious growth
of the Hard Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Other theme operations include the Rainforest Cafe, House of
Blues and the Minnesota Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1501EST &QL; 
