<HEADER>
A7187 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-AIR-STRIKE-OPTIO     12-18 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-AIR-STRIKE-OPTIONS-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Why are the United States and Britain conducting air strikes
against Iraq? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why isn't the West sponsoring the Iraqi opposition in a ground
assault to topple Saddam Hussein? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In this series of three articles adapted from ``The Rollback
Fantasy,'' a major article in the current Foreign Affairs, three
top policy analysts counter critics of current U.S. policy in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   They tell what is drastically wrong with the ``rollback
fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   __ All three commentaries, described in more detail below, have
moved on the wire in the ``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news
categories. __
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part I: THE `ROLLBACK' FANTASY _ WHY DIDN'T THE U.S. and
BRITAIN LAUNCH AN IRAQI BAY OF PIGS? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In October, Congress rushed to embrace an Iraq Liberation Act,
authorizing a whopping $97 million in military aid to democratic
Iraqi resistance groups. President Clinton's staff was
unenthusiastic, but Clinton signed rather than pick a fight. The
basic idea behind it? That the United States should refuse to
accept the continued rule of Saddam Hussein and help install the
Iraqi opposition in his place. (slugged:
BC-IRAQ-OPPOSITION-GROUPS-ONE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part II: THE `ROLLBACK' FANTASY _ WHY NOT HAVE THE IRAQI
NATIONAL CONGRESS SEIZE CHUNKS OF IRAQ? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of current U.S. policy argue that the United States
should help the opposition umbrella group known as the Iraqi
National Congress (INC) seize and hold large enclaves inside Iraq,
from which it would proceed to undermine Saddam's rule. But this
plan is militarily ludicrous and would almost certainly end in a
massive bloodbath. (slugged: BC-IRAQ-REBELS-INCOMPETENT -TWO-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part III: THE `ROLLBACK' FANTASY _ HOW ABOUT SPONSORING A
GUERILLA WAR? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One more option for toppling Saddam Hussein's regime in Iraq is
known as ``the Afghan approach.'' It stipulates that the United
States could help the Iraqi opposition mount an insurgency on the
model of the Afghan mujahideen, the Nicaraguan Contras or the Viet
Cong. Iraq's neighbors, however, aren't terribly relieved at this
prospect. (slugged: BC-IRAQ-GUERILLA-WAR-THREE-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ..................
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABOUT THE AUTHORS: Daniel Byman is a policy analyst with the
RAND Corp. Kenneth Pollack is senior research professor at the
National Defense University. Gideon Rose is deputy director of
national security studies and Olin Fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
