<SLUG> BC-HOT-TIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTO THE MALL, ONE MORE TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Crazed, frazzled, feel like you've got the
shopper's equivalent of snow blindness from looking at too much
stuff in the stores?
</P>
<P>
   First, try to avoid being testy. Miz Hot Tips has seen too much
mall madness already, like a checkout line fight at the J.C. Penney
Outlet in West Hills, and she wants you to know it wasn't a pretty
sight. A woman accused another of pushing her child while waiting
in line (she didn't), and suddenly both were hurling insults, which
shocked the other ladylike customers.
</P>
<P>
   Relax. We'll all get our turn. Peace on Earth. Good will to all
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, take a list so you can check it off as you go. It really
works. And if you're desperate for offbeat gift ideas, read on.
</P>
<P>
   DESK SET: It may not make them whistle while they work, but
career types love status-heavy accessories, like Montblanc's Le
Grand fountain pen for $12,600.
</P>
<P>
   Miz Hot Tips spotted water globes at Saks Fifth Avenue, which
make great desk toys with Eiffel towers and other city landmarks,
for $35. And at all Old Navy stores, you can buy a snow globe for
$5 that can be personalized with your own picture.
</P>
<P>
   Another deskmate idea is the metal classic Rolodex in hot colors
like pink or orange for $95 at Orange, 245 S. Robertson Blvd.,
Beverly Hills. While you're there, check out some of the other
retro office supplies in rainbow colors, including file cabinets
and in-and-out trays. And keep an eye out for celebs. Word is that
Brad Pitt shops there.
</P>
<P>
   PUPPY PANACHE: The friends who throw birthday parties for their
dog will probably want to take it on vacation ... or to your house
... so give them a stylin' dog carrier. Miz Hot Tips learned that
all the major purse companies _ from Kate Spade to Louis Vuitton _
now have carriers, but Asprey &AMP; Garrard carries the most clout with
a real alligator-covered carrier for $19,000, according to Vogue
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Less pricey pup stuff includes red rain slickers and holiday
place mats and water bowls at the new Animal House at The Oaks
mall, 222 W. Hillcrest Ave., Thousand Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   And the Santa suit Rover's been begging for is available for
$10.99 at PetsMart stores.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Petco stores, you can buy Angel Dog (and Angel Cat)
ornaments designed by L.A. artist Joe Monroe with the help of his
greyhound Jaxson. They cost $20 and benefit Pets Are Wonderful
Support (PAWS), which provides veterinary care, pet food and pet
sitting for HIV patients. For more information, call (323)
876-7297, Ext. 116.
</P>
<P>
   A FROSTY MAKEOVER: OK, it's relatively toasty in Los Angeles,
but somewhere it's snowing. For this winter experience, you'll need
an official snowman kit, and the Horchow Collection catalog has
one. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   The kit includes a corncob pipe, eyes, a bow tie (or red feather
boa for a snow woman), wire-rimmed glasses, a hat, eyes and buttons
for $90. To order, call (800) 456-7000.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!A few good books:!off! You may think they're boring and
merely something to cover the scratches in your coffee table, but
surely you've got a literary friend or two.
</P>
<P>
   For them, Miz Hot Tips has rounded up a bunch of
oh-so-fashionable books. They include ``The Power of Glamour'' by
Annette Tapert (Crown Publishing; $40), which focuses on some of
Hollywood's most famous stars, from Greta Garbo to the lesser-known
Kay Francis. There's also Janet Wallach's new book, ``Chanel: Her
Style and Her Life'' (Doubleday; $35), which takes the reader from
Coco Chanel's poverty-ridden childhood to the top of a fashion
empire.
</P>
<P>
   For him, take a gander at John Bridges' very enlightening (and
short) book, ``How to Be a Gentleman'' (Rutledge Hill Press;
$12.95). It's packed with tips on cellular phone etiquette (turn it
off at the opera) and less-known subjects like ice. On the latter,
Bridges says a gentleman never crunches on ice except in the
privacy of his home.
</P>
<P>
   Other good reads are the gigantic _ and gorgeous _ ``Botanica's
Roses'' (Random House; $50), which is quite literally an
encyclopedia of 4,000 types of roses and how to grow them; and a
charming little book all about a local child actress now seen in
reruns of ``Father Knows Best'' and ``The Andy Griffith Show.''
It's ``In the Kitchen with Elinor Donahue'' (Cumberland House;
$16.95) and it's packed with nostalgia and celebrity recipes. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
