   (Adds: CLINTON-IMPEACH; IRAQ-US; IMPEACH-DEBATE; IMPEACH-MOOD;
and JASPER-GRAVE.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Democrats and Republicans in the
House launch a debate of momentous historical importance,
deliberating for only the second time over whether the president
should be removed from office. We gauge White House reaction to the
day's arguments. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FIRST-LADY (Washington) _ With the House debating
impeachment, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton breaks her public
silence to praise her husband and urge Americans to devote the
holiday season to ``reflection and reconciliation'' and to ``end
divisiveness.'' By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-US (Washington) _ The United States and Britain begin a
third wave of airborne attacks on Iraq, while in the House, a
debate rages over removing the commander in chief. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEBATE (Washington) _ A look at what is said by the key
players in the impeachment debate _ the moderate Republicans and
conservative Democrats who could decide the outcome. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MOOD (Washington) _ A look at the atmosphere in the
House of Representatives as the debate unfolds. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON-REAX (Washington) _ A day after House
Speaker-designate Bob Livingston confessed to his own adultery,
Republicans say there's no similarity between him and President
Clinton, but House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., calls
for an end to ``the politics of smear and slash and burn.'' By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SHAYS-IMPEACH (Washington) _ We profile Rep. Christopher Shays
of Connecticut, a moderate Republican who meets with President
Clinton. Shays, one of the last fence-sitters on the impeachment
issue, has a record of defying Republican leaders. By ERIC
ROSENBERG and MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-GRAVE (Jasper, Texas) _ A marker on the grave of a black
man dragged to death in East Texas has been stolen, family members
say. James Byrd Sr. says the small metal nameplate marking the
grave of his son, James Byrd Jr., has been missing for about a
month. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
