<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-EDWARDS1219-C     12-18 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-EDWARDS1219-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WACO'S EDWARDS DENOUNCES IMPEACHMENT EFFORT
 &HT;    575 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Waco Democratic Rep. Chet Edwards denounced the
GOP-led effort to impeach President Clinton as an unfair trampling
of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will surely judge this process as a combination of
Kafka, ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' and Keystone Kops,'' he said
Friday, on the floor of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the name of the rule of law, this process ignored the
fundamental principles of due process and fairness that form the
foundation of that rule of law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was among the first speakers Friday morning as the House
debated four articles of impeachment against the president. His
comments reflected those of many Democrats who spoke of a fiercely
partisan process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who among us, Democrat or Republican, in this House would want
to be a defendant in the case where the rules of law and fairness
were ignored, where secret grand jury testimony against us was
released to the world, where there was not one direct witness,
where your defense attorney was limited to one hour of
cross-examining your chief accuser, where your attorney was forced
to give your final defense even before one charge had been formally
presented against you...,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely no member of this House would want to be judged by that
process. We should not judge this president by that process,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards also blasted GOP House members for their efforts to
block a vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some to speak of their vote of conscience today even as
they deny others a deep vote of conscience is, in itself,
unconscionable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Texas Democrats objected to the timing of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, said having the debate
concurrent with a U.S. military attack on Iraq ``may wind up
costing American lives'' because it could encourage Saddam Hussein
to resist longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority may well have blood on its hands by starting this
proceeding today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republicans said the nation will survive no matter what
the Congress decides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens _ whether the president is impeached or not _
our nation will endure. We are a strong people, and we have a
Constitution that works,'' said San Antonio Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has called for Clinton to resign, said the
impeachment is not about a private relationship but ``it involves
the most public of relationships _ that between a citizen and the
justice system and that between the president and the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's about respect for the law, respect for the
office of the presidency, respect for the American people, respect
for the officers of the court, respect for women and our own
self-respect.''
</P>
<P>
   A simple House majority of 218 votes is enough to impeach
Clinton. If the House approves articles of impeachment, the Senate
would be forced to hold a trial. It takes a two-thirds Senate
majority to convict a president and remove him from office, and few
people believe the Senate, which will have 55 Republicans and 45
Democrats next year, will find the 67 votes needed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In expressing his opposition to impeachment, Edwards said no
citizen should be treated below the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the name of justice, this process ignored the pillar of
justice: that in our nation every citizen is innocent until proven
guilty, not guilty until proven innocent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Final votes on the articles of impeachment are expected by
midday Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
