<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7253 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSES-MANORMYTH-TEX     12-18 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSES-MANORMYTH-TEX </SLUG>
 
SCHOLARS DEBATE HIS EXISTENCE, BUT MOSES HAS BEEN INSPIRATION
THROUGH AGES (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name of Moses resounds through Western civilization, echoing
ancient themes of freedom, faith and the founding of a nation. His
image _ bearded and sometimes horned (because of a tradition grown
out of a mistranslation) _ has inspired great geniuses to paint and
chisel. Words attributed to him have been known and recited by
nearly every person who has lived in Western civilization since
Christianity became the dominant religion.
</P>
<P>
   Even in 1998, Moses is deemed worthy of a mass-market animated
motion-picture feature, ``The Prince of Egypt,'' which opened
yesterday after much media fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   But did he really exist?
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago, when skepticism reigned among scholars
of the Bible, the answer by many experts would have been a
confident ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, that answer has changed to ``yes,'' though the vote is by
no means confident or unanimous. Moses does not meet modern
standards of historical evidence: There are no contemporaneous
written documents to back up the stories that, as far as can be
determined, were written down 200 to 500 years after the time in
which the historical Moses would have existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All but the true believers among contemporary Bible critics
are willing to concede that the `historicity' of Moses remains open
to question,'' writes Jonathan Kirsch in his recently published
``Moses: A Life,'' the latest in a long line of popular and
scholarly studies of the ancient leader.
</P>
<P>
   But many believe that Moses _ or someone upon whom the Moses
stories were based, or maybe several people upon whom the stories
were based _ must have existed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``true believers'' willing to make a scholarly case
for Moses are members of the faculty of Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the type of corroboration historians use to
write history,'' says Rick Johnson, an associate professor of Old
Testament at the seminary and an admitted conservative. But Johnson
can point to several aspects of the Moses story that support the
idea that Moses really lived, even though there is no written
record.
</P>
<P>
   His colleague at the seminary, historian and archaeologist Tommy
Briscoe, points out the evidence of new settlement and sociological
change in Palestine in the late 13th century B.C. _ just the right
time to match the move of the Israelites from Egypt into Canaan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were changes at that time, evidence of small settlements
... '' he says. ``Some of them must be connected with the influence
of the Israelites.''
</P>
<P>
   From another religious perspective, historian Michael Meyer of
Hebrew Union College in Cincinnati defends the historical Moses,
without insisting on his existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no historical evidence outside the Bible,'' says
Meyer, whose wife, Margaret Meyer, commutes to Texas to serve as
rabbi at Congregation Kol Ami in Flower Mound. ``But the Jewish
tradition holds that there was a historical character named
Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer points to several compelling aspects of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that his name is Egyptian attests to the historical
background,'' Meyer says. Scribes in Israel 200 years after the
fact would not have used an Egyptian name for a national hero in a
work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, some interesting conjectures of the nature of
the real Moses have emerged. Tradition calls Moses the author of
the Pentateuch, but any reader must obviously wonder why, if Moses
wrote those first five books of the Bible, he is always referred to
in the third person _ and included a narration of his own death.
Seventeenth-century Jewish-Dutch philosopher Benedict Spinoza drew
the wrath of both Jews and Christians for asking that obvious
question, though just a century later, the outspoken Voltaire also
questioned the existence of Moses.
</P>
<P>
   By the 20th century, German scholar Martin Noth speculated that
Moses was a local leader in Palestine to whom the other stories
were attached; Sigmund Freud speculated that Moses was an Egyptian
who learned his religion from the pharaoh Akhenaton, who built a
cult that could be regarded as monotheistic around the sun god
Aton.
</P>
<P>
   According to Freud, the original Moses was killed in the
wilderness by the Israelites and replaced by a Hebrew leader who
took on his name.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a real Moses, what was he like?
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the chronology one chooses, he lived either in the
13th century B.C., at the time of Rameses II _ the choice taken by
the makers of ``The Prince of Egypt'' _ or about 200 years earlier.
But the impish individualism that might have produced a chariot
drag race between two teen-age princes depicted in ``Prince of
Egypt'' was unknown in the ancient Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Was Moses monotheistic in the modern sense?
</P>
<P>
   The world in which he lived was steeped in polytheism, but Moses
clearly moved beyond the belief in many gods, even if those around
him never did.
</P>
<P>
   For that concept alone, whether he was a prince of Egypt, a
leader of a wandering tribe or several people who came together in
one character, he occupies a unique place in human history and must
be regarded as a genius who saw far beyond the accepted beliefs of
his own time.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, tales once regarded as pure myth _ King
Arthur, the Trojan War _ have come to be regarded as having a basis
in fact. So is there a chance that historical evidence of Moses
will be found?
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe sees the faint possibility that something may be
discovered in the family tomb of Rameses II, currently under
excavation. A single word, a hieroglyph chipped on a stone in
Egypt, could place Moses squarely within the framework of history.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1623EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7254 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSES-MANORMYTH-TEX     12-18 0990
