A7275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOLARS-IMPEACHMENT-     12-18 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOLARS-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLARS SAY CONGRESS DOESN'T NEED TO FOLLOW PUBLIC OPINION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While opinion polls show that many Americans are
ambivalent about impeaching Bill Clinton, presidential and
constitutional law scholars say the Congress has every right to
buck public opinion and vote to remove the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that many people want Clinton punished but not
removed from office for his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
And the surveys show that Clinton's job approval rating remains
high.
</P>
<P>
   But constitutional law experts say that if the founding fathers
had wanted the public to decide impeachment, they would have
required the president to be recalled by popular vote. Instead,
they gave the power to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no indication that the framers thought impeachment
amounted to a popular referendum,'' said Evan Gerstmann, professor
of political science and specialist in constitutional law at Loyola
Marymount University in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw it as the members of Congress exercising their
constitutional responsibility to do what, in their best judgment,
is best for the country,'' Gerstmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some analysts suggest that the faith in government could be
damaged by politicians acting in apparent defiance of public will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are thinking, `Even if we do vote, they're not
listening to us,''' said Ann Crigler, director of the Jesse Unruh
School of Politics at the University of Southern California.
``People are quite suspicious of Congress anyway ... This can only
hurt that.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote goes to the heart of whether representatives to
Congress should be delegates or trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delegate's main job is to do what the people tell him to
do,'' Gerstmann said. Under the trustee model, ``the people
delegate authority and they entrust the representative to use that
authority in the interests of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstmann noted, ``There is no consensus within political
science circles about which theory is correct.''
</P>
<P>
   There are political theorists who believe representatives must
balance the two concerns when making decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans favoring impeachment have argued that the rule of
law should outweigh the shifting sentiments of public-opinion
polls. Democrats say ignoring the public's views is undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some of the more, if you will, right-wing members
use the phrase, `We don't live in a democracy, we live in a
republic.' That has sent shivers up and down my spine,'' said Sen.
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif. ``How can you do something that's against
the will of the people? I will tell you something. This is a
democracy. The form is a democratic republic, but I have never
heard people say this is not a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Robinson, chairman of the department of government at
Smith College in Northampton, Mass., teaches a course on the effort
to impeach Richard Nixon. He said one of the little-known facts
students have been puzzling over is that opinion polls, especially
in early 1974, showed that the public did not support impeaching
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been very much impressed with public-opinion polls
saying Clinton should not be removed from office,'' Robinson said.
He said Nixon's own tapes showed he was convinced the public would
never allow impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have great respect, or even reverence, for the office
of president and are desperate not to believe that he has committed
grave enough offenses to overthrow two popular elections,''
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that House Democrats ignored the polls and kept
pushing the charges against Nixon. It was only after the discovery
of the ``smoking gun'' tapes _ revealing Nixon's role in the
cover-up of the Watergate break-in _ that bipartisan support for
impeachment began to grow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reading of the Federalist Papers shows that Alexander
Hamilton, like other founding fathers, expected the impeachment
process would be political and partisan. Robinson said the House
was given the responsibility of voting articles of impeachment,
knowing that members would have to explain their decision and face
voters again within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The framers also made sure a two-thirds vote in the Senate would
be needed to convict.
</P>
<P>
   But those who believe that the charges against Clinton don't add
up to impeachable offenses see a danger: Impeachment could be used
more frequently by the majority party against leaders of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment now becomes part of the arsenal of Congress to
hold a president of the opposite party to account,'' said Robert
Post, a professor at the University of California at Berkeley
School of Law and a specialist in constitutional law. ``It ought
not be that. I predict that it will be used that way in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Lowenstein, a law professor at the University of
California at Los Angeles, said there are enough safeguards in the
impeachment process to keep it from being used irresponsibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not Clinton is impeached, whichever side is right
... it does seem to me that our system works pretty well because it
really does entitle (representatives) to think about a whole lot of
things,'' Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's just concern about the next election, they need
to think about what people are going to be thinking about this in
the future,'' he said. ``That's a good thing. Maybe all of us will
have a better perspective on this 20 years from now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
