<HEADER>
A7288 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-YOGA-ART-$ADV20-N     12-18 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-YOGA-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD THAT LINE! HOLD THAT STRETCH! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Dec. 20)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ROB BUCHANAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 6-feet-4, 241 pounds, with the tightly packed musculature of
a freshly caught bluefin tuna, Bill Romanowski, a linebacker for
the Denver Broncos, does not appear to be naturally built for yoga.
Yet, in his hotel room at the Newark Airport Hilton Saturday before
last, he gamely assumed the position known as the Pigeon. Kneeling,
with his back to the wall, one leg bent beneath him, he strained to
breathe rhythmically while keeping his face from contorting into
what Danny Poole, his instructor, disdainfully called ``a weight
lifter's grimace.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole, who has been training Romanowski in yoga for seven
months, seemed pleased. ``His flexibility has really improved,'' he
said. ``He used to have to put six inches of block under his elbows
just to do the Can Opener'' _ a deep hip-flexor stretch _ ``but now
he's right down on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski, 32, bent his bulk into the Swan, followed by the
Cobra. ``Keep your butt soft,'' Poole reminded his pupil, who ended
his routine with the ultimate hamstring stretcher, the
Downward-Facing Dog. The football player then directed his
attention to his stack of three room-service dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Poole, a rock-jawed former Montgomery Ward catalog model, was in
town to watch the Broncos take on the New York Giants last Sunday.
He trains half a dozen Broncos players, usually during the week.
But the Saturday evening before the Giants ended the Broncos'
13-game winning streak with a 20-16 victory, Poole was summoned to
the rooms of Romanowski and Shannon Sharpe, the Broncos' tight end,
for last-minute tuneups.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga and ashrams have become almost as mainstream as treadmills
and day spas. Still, it seems surprising to see the National
Football League's gladiator corps folding their heavily muscled
bodies into delicate pretzel shapes and hunkering down to seek
their inner light as they prepare for combat on the field.
</P>
<P>
   But Poole, who looks a decade younger than his 49 years, is no
saffron-robed yogi. He is an amiable ex-college basketball player
whose colorful career has included stints as a soul food
restaurateur, a sports columnist and, lately, a real estate
salesman. His association with the Broncos started as a friendship
with Detron Smith, a 5-feet-9-inch, 231-pound fullback he met at
Jimmy's Bar and Grill in Denver, on a ladies' night. Smith, known
among his teammates as ``the human bowling ball,'' invited Poole to
teach a few classes at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most jocks I see don't know anything about yoga,'' Poole said.
``They think it's some guy chanting with his leg behind his neck,''
a maneuver he insists is beyond him. ``I can't even do a full
lotus,'' he said. ``I've had surgery on both knees. But that's what
I'm up against: the leg-behind-the-head thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole has won over some of his skeptics. When the regular season
began, Romanowski and Sharpe put Poole on retainer. He works five
days a week with Romanowski and three with Sharpe, at his regular
rate of $50 an hour. Other players float in and out of sessions
with less regularity.
</P>
<P>
   After working with Romanowski before last week's game, Poole
walked down the hall to do a quick routine with Sharpe. More
naturally limber than his teammate, Sharpe was able to put the
palms of his hands flat on the floor without bending his knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys tease me,'' Sharpe said. ``They say, `That's
gymnast stuff _ only girls are supposed to be that flexible.''' He
snorted. ``They're just jealous because they can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' quarterback, John Elway, has missed several games
this season with hamstring problems, and Poole thinks yoga could
help him avoid injuries. ``John has got the trainers doing him,''
Poole said. Don't get me wrong, I don't think anything these
trainers is doing is bad. There's just some better stuff out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole believes in yoga's benefits, but he doesn't push its
touchy-feely aspects on his NFL students. Although he begins his
classes with candle gazing, a traditional exercise that entails
quietly focusing on a burning flame, he has scaled that back from
10 minutes to a less demanding 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I try to steer clear of the spiritual aspects,'' he
said. Instead, he focuses on intense stretching, along with
rigorous breathing and visualization exercises. Where most NFL
stretching regimens work a muscle between 10 and 15 seconds, Poole
said, his program requires that poses be held for anywhere between
45 seconds and 2 minutes. ``Mainly, the idea is to prevent
injuries,'' he said. ``We focus on hamstrings, hip flexors, groins
and backs _ the things that usually knock athletes out of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Without throwing around too much chakra and dharma talk, Poole
does have a yogic philosophy with its own catchword: dwelling. Or,
rather, not dwelling. ``It's stress management,'' he explained.
``You let whatever comes up, come up. You thank it for coming up,
and then you say, `I'll see you later _ bye.' After a while, things
will come up and go away without you dwelling on them. You've got
to learn to catch yourself, just as physically, you have to catch
yourself grimacing, hunching your shoulders, holding your breath.
That's my homework assignment to my students: catch yourself
dwelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all Poole's students, Romanowski would seem to be one of the
ones most in need of ``dwelling'' awareness. Known as one of the
league's most hot-tempered players, he provided a memorable
television moment last year when, in a Monday night game against
the San Francisco 49ers, he spit in the face of an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the personality type expected to meditate on the
words ``Om Shanthi,'' the Hindu peace mantra. In fact, Romanowski,
an 11-year NFL veteran, is adamant that his interest in yoga has
nothing to do with searching for inner calm. ``It's not a
relaxation strategy,'' he said. ``It's not about self-control. You
can't relax out on the field.'' What IS it about, then? ``I just
feel looser,'' he said. ``Can you measure it? No. But if you feel
good, you play good. And if you play good, you'll have a job the
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   With four minutes left in the final quarter of the
Broncos-Giants upset, Poole became so elated when the Broncos
scored what looked like the winning touchdown that he stood up in
the stadium and assumed a Tree pose, impervious to the catcalls
from fans behind him. ``Hey, stork man,'' one yelled. ``Down in
front!''
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants fumbled on the Broncos' 20-yard line, Romanowski
dived fearlessly into the pile and recovered the football _ a feat
Poole attributed to yoga-induced confidence. Romanowski paraded
around the field brandishing the ball as if it was an infidel's
severed head. Bad karma, perhaps. Three plays later, the Giants got
the ball and scored the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
