A7298 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV20-     12-18 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISTLETOE'S MAGIC GOES WAY BEYOND THE KISSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 20)  
(lb) 
 By MARTY ROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The holiday season always started with a bang around my
grandmother's house _ usually coming from my great-grandmother's
big back yard next door, where my father and his cousin Tommy were
out with their squirrel rifles, shooting great clumps of mistletoe
out of an old oak. This was the boys' way of bringing home
Christmas, and they generally bagged enough for the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   That was before I was born. By the time I was old enough to
appreciate the mysteries of mistletoe, my father had packed away
his guns and Tommy had moved to Texas, but traditions were
rigorously maintained.
</P>
<P>
   There was always an enormous bunch of mistletoe dangling from
the flagpole over my grandmother's front door during the holiday
season, tied up with an impressively wide red ribbon. It swung
violently about in the cold winter wind but never came down. I was
fascinated by it, a magical bush overhead, green in the dead of
winter, full of luminous white berries, inspiring kiss after kiss
in the enchanted week between Christmas and New Year.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother lived in northwest Arkansas, where mistletoe is a
common parasite on trees, usually oaks. There are several species
of mistletoe, but the best known and most common is Phoradendron
leucarpum, North American mistletoe, found from New Jersey south to
Florida and all the way to the Great Plains wherever winter
temperatures rarely fall below zero.
</P>
<P>
   It is an evergreen plant with beautiful leathery leaves not much
larger than a thumb print. It grows into 3- or 4-foot clumps high
in the branches of oak, hackberry, elm, pecan, black gum, maple,
tupelo and sycamore trees. After the trees lose their leaves in the
fall, the mistletoe is easy to spot. It grows on the lower
branches, too, and sometimes appears on the trunks of young trees,
but it rarely persists where it can be reached easily from the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   European mistletoe, Viscum album, is another genus altogether,
similar in appearance and habit but unknown here. It is said to
prefer the shady side of old lichen-encrusted apple trees, but it
also establishes itself in lindens and hawthorns, and occasionally
in oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Mistletoe was sacred to the druids of antiquity, who ascribed
potent supernatural powers to the thick clusters of mistletoe in
oaks. According to Pliny the Elder, white-robed druids cut the
mistletoe down with golden sickles, and two white bulls were
sacrificed on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   In the Prose Edda, the Icelandic epic written down in the 13th
century, mistletoe figures in the account of the death of Balder,
the Norse god of light, Odin's son. Balder dreamed of his own
death, and his mother extracted a promise from everything in nature
never to hurt her son. She overlooked the lowly mistletoe, and the
inspired troublemaker Loki made a dart from its wood. This weapon,
thrown in jest by Balder's brother, killed the gentle Balder.
</P>
<P>
   (The Danish chronicler Saxo Grammaticus, however, writing in the
12th century, had it that Balder was slain in a rivalry between the
brothers for the lovely Nanna.)
</P>
<P>
   Herbalists regarded mistletoe as an ``all-healer,'' Mary Durant
wrote in ``Who Named the Daisy? Who Named the Rose?'' (Dodd, Mead &AMP;
Co., 1976), a rich little compendium of wildflower lore. ``It
protected against witchcraft and nightmares; it evoked ghosts and
caused them to answer your questions,'' she wrote. Mistletoe was
said to have the power to open locks, and it guarded dairies from
trolls and could point the way to buried treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Culpeper's ``Herbal,'' published in 1653, reported that
the dried berry of the mistletoe ``doth mollify hard knots, tumors
and imposthumes,'' or abscesses; mixed with equal parts rosin and
wax, it could heal ulcers and sores. A necklace of mistletoe sprigs
cured apoplexy and palsy ``very speedily.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, mistletoe is listed as a poisonous plant; eating a
couple of berries or leaves may make a person a little sick, but
acute poisoning is rare, according to the American Association of
Poison Control Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Culpeper attributed to the botanist Carolus Clusius (1526-1609)
the instruction that mistletoe ``should not touch the ground after
it is gathered,'' but this injunction was forgotten by American
pioneers. Early settlers laid green branches of it on fresh graves
in winter in Oklahoma, where mistletoe, the state flower, once grew
as thick as Spanish moss.
</P>
<P>
   There is a wintry darkness about mistletoe. In Shakespeare's
``Titus Andronicus,'' Tamora, queen of the Goths, describes the
trees in a forest near Rome as ``o'ercome with moss and baleful
mistletoe.''
</P>
<P>
   The etymology is not straightforward: The ``mist'' in the
Anglo-Saxon ``misteltan'' also means ``dung.'' ``Mistel'' is a
diminutive, and ``tan'' meant twig. The word translates roughly to
``the little dung twig,'' Mary Durant wrote. Early observers
thought that mistletoe seeds could not germinate until they had
passed through the digestive system of birds.
</P>
<P>
   Botanists now think they know better: The seeds are planted when
birds rub their beaks on branches to rid themselves of the berries'
residue. The seeds germinate on the branch, and after a couple of
years, the root penetrates into the wood of the tree and the
mistletoe leafs out.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Post does not provide guidance for 20th-century observers
of the ancient tradition of kissing under the mistletoe, but the
correct procedure, according to Brewer's Dictionary of Phrase and
Fable, is to remove a berry after every kiss. When the last berry
is gone, there should be no more kissing.
</P>
<P>
   Mistletoe is still harvested by crack shots in the backwoods for
big-city markets, but I found a good bunch growing within my reach
not long ago along a new road near my parents' home in Arkansas. It
snapped off in my hand.
</P>
<P>
   Mistletoe even wards off lightning, I understand, and in that
stormy period between the winter solstice and Twelfth Night, my
mistletoe will be hanging from the beam by the stairs, right below
our lucky old horseshoe: You can't be too careful these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
