<HEADER>
A7315 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-GIFTS-$ADV21-     12-18 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-GIFTS-$ADV21-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE PRACTICAL GIFTS THIS YEAR _ LIKE VEGETABLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is, by now, way too late to do your holiday gift-buying early
_ unless you are so repugnantly well organized that you are already
shopping for 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In which case, I invite you to spend your spare time bringing
order to the chaos of my garage, my desk, my bookshelves at home,
my. . .the list is as nearly endless as it is sad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But I know that most of you, even at this late hour, still have
Christmas gifts to buy. And, undiscerning as you are, you are even
willing to take advice about these last-minute gifts from someone
like me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying I'm a worthless source of gift ideas, but should
you trust someone who, as a child, used to sneak under the tree and
add his name to labels already on presents so it looked as if he
was at least partly responsible for some of them? Notice my
Clintonesque stance here: I'm not admitting, exactly, that I did
that. I'm just raising the question. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I may be no better organized today than I was as a stripling,
but I've at least had some practice in acquiring St. Nick-of-time
gifts that the recipients accepted without laughing in my face. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My main advice: think simple and be practical. This would lead
you to: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Toothpicks. They're surprisingly affordable _ and they may be
the only real wood in houses that feature ever-pink
almost-biodegradable Christmas trees made from spun vegetable
protein. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Toothpaste. People are always running out of it when it's
least convenient. And imagine how grateful the recipients will be
on their next trip when they look in their cosmetic travel cases
and find that teeny little tube of travel toothpaste you were
thoughtful enough to wrap for them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Wax lips. Sticking with the mouth area for cheap and quick
gift ideas, I find that hardly anyone ever thinks to give wax lips
for Christmas. Oh, you get them now and then at Halloween, but it's
Christmas now and it's often so darn cold outside that your real
lips could use some protection from the weather. A gift of wax lips
will make you a memorable giver. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Post cards. Did you have a post card handy when you last
wanted one? Almost certainly not. So why not meet the unanticipated
needs of people on your Christmas list by picking up a few post
cards? If you're a really thoughtful giver you'll even preaddress
one to yourself with this note: ``Say, thanks a lot for the great
post card(s).'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Thumbtacks. I can't tell you how often I've needed one and not
been able to find one. If someone had given me a little box of,
say, 100 of them for Christmas, my chances of finding one in the
house would have shot up by a lot. And just for fun, you can put a
few of them on chairs near the Christmas tree so people will
remember the point of the gift. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Asparagus. Perhaps you've noticed that so far most of the
gifts I've suggested have started with letters from the second half
of the alphabet. Not this one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Bratwurst. This idea is included for the same reason. Plus,
it's not that bad with asparagus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Drums. A set of these can be found in the basement of the
house in which I am permitted to dwell. They are played with
regularity _ and considerable skill _ by another resident of the
same house. It seems to me others might want to share this
experience, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Hacksaw. This thoughtful gift can help the recipient make
quick work of other gifts that didn't suit his or her fancy. Each
home should have one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Monday, Dec. 21, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
