<SLUG> BC-STEALTHBOMBER-IRAQ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B-2 STEALTH BOMBER ON THE SIDELINES IN IRAQ CONFLICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The B-2 stealth bomber was designed to be the most
feared plane in the Air Force, able to slip undetected through
enemy radar and deliver a lethal payload.
</P>
<P>
   But when the United States launched the biggest air assault
since the Persian Gulf War, the $2 billion boomerang-shaped plane
was at home in a hangar.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. warplanes and cruise missiles pounded Baghdad over the
past two days, the nine B-2s the Air Force considers operational
were at Whiteman Air Force Base, near Sedalia, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's decision to leave the B-2 out of its Iraq battle
plan has raised eyebrows among defense industry experts and members
of Congress, who recall how the Air Force touted the bomber on
Capitol Hill. Congress poured billions into developing an airplane
that was supposed to be so formidable that it would make much of
the U.S. arsenal obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon chose to carry out its aerial attack on Iraq
with tried- and-proven aircraft, such as the F-15 Eagle and the
B-52 Stratofortress, which first flew in 1952 and was a mainstay of
the Cold War bomber fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is the B-2?'' asked Tim Lomparis, a weapons technology
expert at St. Louis University in St. Louis. ``If the B-52 is a
better aircraft for this purpose, then what is the purpose of the
B-2? If they can't bring it out and strut it around, it's a nice
piece for an air museum somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force spokesman, Maj. Tyrone Woodyard, would not rule out
use of the B-2 in Iraq, but he added: ``At this point in time, they
have not received an alert order or deployment order.''
</P>
<P>
   That has left some lawmakers and others wondering when the Air
Force might unleash the plane or how serious the mission must be to
require its services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have those 50-year-old B-52s over there flying all those
missions,'' said Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., chairman of a House
subcommittee on military aviation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fear of taking the B-2 over there. If we lost a B-2
in Iraq it would be a multibillion-dollar loss and create an
international scandal the president would not be able to recover
from. But this is the kind of activity the plane was designed
for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has become accustomed to hearing criticism of the
B-2. It has become a symbol of Pentagon excess, and last year the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress,
reported that the B-2's stealth capability would deteriorate in
rain, heat and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force says it has solved the problems, and in October,
it sent three B-2s to Guam for more than a month of exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials said the B-2 wasn't used in Iraq because
mission planners relied largely on aircraft already in the region.
It would take about 18 hours for the B-2, which was produced in
part at Northrop Grumman's plant near Grand Prairie, to fly from
Whiteman to the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts said the planners apparently didn't believe it
was worth waiting for the B-2 because it would not give the United
States any particular advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The B-2 does not have that much to offer in this type of
environment,'' said Richard Aboulafia, defense and aerospace
analyst for the Teal Group in Fairfax, Va. ``You use the B-2 to
penetrate a very well protected network. The air defense network
the Iraqis have is pretty darn crude.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
