A7344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-1219-COX     12-18 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-1219-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA WARNS TIES WITH U.S. ENDANGERED BY ONGOING STRIKES
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 500 words.
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1219.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's foreign minister warned U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright on Friday that further air strikes against
Iraq could seriously damage U.S.-Russian ties.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday, the State Department announced that Albright will
travel to Moscow next month in an effort at damage control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this action is not stopped, Russian-American relations can
seriously suffer,'' Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov told Albright in a
telephone conversation, according to a statement released by his
office in Moscow. ``Everything must be done to rule out a setback
in our relations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This would not be our choice,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The direct reproach followed two days of harsh criticism from
across Russia's political spectrum, a unified front critical of
America and reminiscent of Cold War rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sent a letter to Russian President Boris
Yeltsin explaining the U.S. rationale for the attacks. Force was
necessary after diplomacy failed, Clinton said. He urged Yeltsin to
place their disagreement over Iraq in a broader context of the
critical U.S.-Russian relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Russia's defense establishment warned that the U.S.-British
strikes in Iraq threatened relations with NATO and could force
Moscow to shift its defense posture to a Cold War standing.
</P>
<P>
   Russia ``will be forced to change its military-political course
and may become the leader of a part of the world community that
disagrees with the (U.S.) dictate,'' Gen. Leonid Ivashov was quoted
as saying by the ITAR-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we talk about cooperation and partnership with the
alliance now, when Russia's opinion is openly ignored?'' Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, economically and politically weak, has little pressure
to bring to bear on the Clinton administration. Yet the angry
response by Moscow marks a low point in relations since Russia
became an independent state after the fall of the Soviet Union in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin said it would not sever diplomatic relations with
America and Britain, perhaps mindful that Russia is reliant on
Western aid to see it through its deep economic crisis. The U.S.
and Russia are currently negotiating the details of a $600 million
American pledge of food aid to help Russia through its coldest
winter in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks on Iraq are ``impermissible, they must be stopped,''
Dmitry Yakushkin, Yeltsin's spokesman, told a news conference. But
he added: ``There can be no talk of a break in relations with
Britain and the United States . . . We must not let things slide
into confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia, a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council and a
key broker in previous confrontations between the United Nations
and Iraq, was distressed that it was not consulted prior to the
United States and Britain launching their attacks on Iraq.
Frustrated as a former superpower, Russia has been unable to
influence policy and safeguard its longtime ally, Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian commentators suggested that Russia's sharp
criticism of America and Britain was disingenuous and that the
country could benefit economically from the strikes on Iraq by an
expected increase in the world price of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Cash-strapped Russia depends on its oil and gas exports for much
of its badly needed revenue. Iraq also owes Russia about $7 billion
for arms purchases dating back to Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Objectively, as cynical as it sounds, bombings can bring
profit to Russia. No OPEC can raise world oil prices as Bill
Clinton did, the result of his order to bomb Iraq,'' wrote the
Kommersant business daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia could not wish for a better present for the New Year,''
wrote the daily newspaper Sevodnya, calling the tough talk from the
Russia's defense establishment ``an event of rather theatrical
character than real.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia on Friday recalled its ambassador to Britain for urgent
consultations -- a day after it summoned home its ambassador to
Washington. The action is a diplomatic form of protest, but rarely
has been used by Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of parliament, the Communist-controlled Duma,
called Friday for Russia to unilaterally break the U.N. trade
embargo and provide aid to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
