<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAYS-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGTIME REPUBLICAN MAVERICK REMAINS MUM ON IMPEACHMENT DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM and ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After meeting with President Clinton for an hour
Friday, Republican Rep. Christopher Shays did what he often does:
He annoyed his party's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, a moderate from Connecticut, refused to bow to pressure
from House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who wanted him to announce he
will vote for Clinton's impeachment. Instead, Shays said he would
wait until Saturday's historic vote on the matter before announcing
his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not be saying anything until after he has voted,''
Shays spokesman Seth Amgott said.
</P>
<P>
   Until last weekend, Shays had said he was against impeachment,
but he wavered after Clinton said again that he had not lied. ``I
think his remarks show that he just doesn't get it,'' Shays said
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday at a town meeting in Norwalk, Conn., Shays appeared
to be leaning against a yes vote when he told the crowd that
``impeachable offenses ... have not been proven and I believe the
proven offenses are not impeachable. But it is darn close.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Shays maintained then that he had not made a decision
on the vote.
</P>
<P>
   His decision Friday to keep House leaders guessing came as no
surprise to those who know him. For many of his 11 years in
Congress, he has been an iconoclastic champion of reform and
moderate causes, challenging his party's conservatives on issues
from abortion to gun control to the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial last spring, the Hartford Courant called Shays a
``rebel with a cause,'' with one of the most independent voting
records among congressional Republicans. In fact, Shays' tendency
to cross party lines has earned him only a 43 percent favorable
rating from the American Conservative Union on his voting record in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Shays enraged Republican leaders when he
teamed up with Massachusetts Democrat Martin Meehan on a bill to
toughen campaign finance laws. The unsuccessful bill would have
banned ``soft money,'' which is used for party expenses like voter
registration drives and can be collected in unlimited sums. The
measure also would have restricted campaign-related advertising by
groups like the Christian Coalition, the National Rifle Association
and unions.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, a leader in the effort to impeach the president, said at
the time that Shays was ``endangering the Republican Congress'' by
attempting to strip away the GOP's fund-raising advantages.
</P>
<P>
   But Shays argued that his legislation would restore public
confidence in the electoral system and would ``help to save the
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his troubles with many Republican leaders, the
53-year-old Shays has maintained support among most members of his
party through an unfailing drive for fiscal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the core Republicans who fought for balanced
budgets in the 1980s, before it became a safe issue,'' Amgott said.
</P>
<P>
   Shays entered Congress in 1987 after winning a special midterm
election to replace Republican Stewart McKinney, who died in May of
that year.
</P>
<P>
   Amgott said that ``when Shays arrived, there was a sense that
Congress had become an island unto itself, and he wanted to change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he helped write and pass the Congressional
Accountability Act, which requires members of Congress to live by
the laws set for all citizens. The act was the first item of the
House Republicans' ``Contract with America'' to be signed by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Shays threatened to vote against Newt Gingrich in
his re-election bid for House speaker because of questions raised
by an ethics investigation of the Georgian.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich settled the issue by admitting he violated House rules
in using tax-exempt money for political purposes and providing
false information to a congressional committee about the case. For
the offenses, the House reprimanded Gingrich and fined him
$300,000.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Shays has found that his independence served
him well. In November, he won his race with nearly 70 percent of
the vote _ an impressive achievement for a Republican from an urban
district where about 50 percent of registered voters are
Democratic.
</P>
</TEXT>
