<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SADDAM-POWER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSSEIN'S IRON GRIP ON POWER THWARTS BEST U.S. EFFORTS TO TOPPLE
HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saddam Hussein's game of hide-and-seek _ his palaces by the
dozen, not sleeping in the same bed two nights in a row _ would end
quickly enough with the help of a single snitch.
</P>
<P>
   But consider what happens to those who cross the Iraqi
strongman.
</P>
<P>
   He has killed his own sons-in-laws _ the fathers of his
grandchildren _ for flirting with rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   As an ambitious young man working in for a secret police outfit,
he was said to enjoy interrogation and have an affinity for a
torture device made to cut off fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Or there's the story of a time near the end of the Iran-Iraq war
when his health minister suggested that Hussein step aside, only
temporarily, to gain concessions from the Iranians. The advantage
won, the man suggested, Hussein could grasp the reins of power once
more.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein calmly ushered the adviser to the side, fired a bullet
in his face and resumed the meeting. When the man's widow, best
friend to Hussein's wife, asked for her husband's body, a plastic
bag containing his dismembered remains was dumped in her living
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a message to the family, and beyond that, to all Iraqis
that if you waver in the slightest way, you will pay a horrendous
cost,'' said James Phillips, a Middle East expert at the
conservative Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Through terror and cunning, in ways that resemble a combination
of Josef Stalin and a mafioso, Hussein for decades has survived
rivals at home and a world enraged to keep an iron grip on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Coups too numerous to count have boomeranged every time. Even in
1991, when 88,000 tons of munitions left his infrastructure in
tatters, when an international army war machine shooed his troops
from Kuwait, when the airspace over his country was sliced apart
with no-fly zones, Hussein endured.
</P>
<P>
   He is the proverbial cockroach scrambling through the rubble
after a nuclear explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to crack this wall of protection Saddam has built
around himself for years now and failed,'' Scott Ritter, a former
U.N. arms inspector in Iraq said on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the United States were to mark him for assassination _
an executive order in place since 1975 bars such deliberate
killings of heads of state _ experts believe Hussein would pose a
nearly invincible target.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policy would allow his death as part of a military action,
would find no fault with dropping a bomb on his hideout during a
war. But killing him that way is no easier.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's resilience is part logistical and part political,
experts said, and the two overlap.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, he's a moving target. In quiet times, Hussein
tends to spend only a few days in the same place in a country that
is bigger than California. During the last war, his minions cleared
three houses each day for him to hide.
</P>
<P>
   His personal safety is a constant obsession, Phillips said. On
his rare travels abroad, he brings his own chair with him because
he holds a mortal fear of sitting upon a needle planted by an
opponent. He surrounds himself in look-alikes to confuse potential
assassins with multiple targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``At most,'' said Middle East scholar Guilain Denoeux, ``maybe a
dozen people have direct access to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Denoeux describes Hussein as an Arab Stalin. Raised poor in the
countryside, both men rose through party structures _ the Communist
Party for Stalin and the Arab socialist//pan-Arab Baath Party for
Hussein _ and then went on murderous purges of intimidation once
they gained power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each man made sure that no one else in the country had any
other source of power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The political and ethnic factions that pose a threat within Iraq
are mostly divided. The Kurds in the north _ the ethnic minority
that Hussein smothered with mustard gas during the Iran-Iraq war _
fight too fiercely among themselves to pose a serious challenge to
Hussein and his Sunni Muslim faction.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1996, the Democratic Party of Kurdistan invited
Iraqi troops to help fight their rival, the Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan, which was backed by Iran.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, prompted President Clinton to launch cruise
missiles on Baghdad, far from the attacking forces in the Kurdish
areas. Within weeks, then-Central Intelligence Agency Director John
Deutsch told a Senate panel that Hussein's position at home had
only been strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, CIA agents were forced to flee the Kurdish territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, the people we relied on...in Baghdad were
executed,'' said Denoeux, who served in the French Embassy in the
Iraqi capital during the Iran-Iraq war. ``We lost our best sources
of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise in southern Iraq, the Shiite Muslims who might pose a
challenge lack the cohesion to take on Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Ousting Hussein _ whether by rivals from within or by Tomahawk
missiles from without _ is not necessarily a prescription for
Middle East stability. In fact, it could disrupt a balance of
tension between Iran and Iraq that the West has exploited for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take out the center, and the whole country flies apart,''
Denoeux said. ``You could have the Kurds controlling the north, the
Shiites in the south and the Sunnis in the middle. One big county
then becomes splintered into three parts and there's the fear among
some people that Iran could move in and dominate the region.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason that President George Bush gave for ending the
Gulf War of 1991 before toppling Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't,'' Bush said at one point, ``shove one soldier or
airman into an Iraqi civil war that's gone on for ages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
