A7391 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTAMINATED-WATER-KA     12-18 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTAMINATED-WATER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE WATER DISTRICTS FOUND TO BE CONTAMINATED WITH VINYL CHLORIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas regulators have found 11 rural water districts where
samples of tap water were contaminated with a cancer-causing
chemical.
</P>
<P>
   In total, high levels of vinyl chloride, a chemical known to
cause cancer in humans, have been found in 17 rural water districts
in Missouri and Kansas. Older plastic water distribution pipes have
been blamed for the contamination.
</P>
<P>
   But it's too early to say how many homes might be affected by
vinyl chloride. Contamination found in samples from individual
homes does not mean the entire system is contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know more when we do some more sampling,'' said Don
Brown, a spokesman for the Kansas Department of Health and
Environment. ``We need to know whether the one house is it, or if
there are other problems in the system,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has notified each homeowner where high levels of the
vinyl chloride were found, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 rural water districts: Franklin County No. 4; Anderson
County No. 4; Mitchell County No. 3; Dickinson County No. 1 and No.
2; Republic County No. 1; Ottawa County No. 1; Russell County No.
3; Comanche County No. 2; Harper County No. 2 and Sumner County No.
4.
</P>
<P>
   The rural water districts serve a few thousand rural Kansas
residents. Anderson County No. 4, for example, has 310 customers.
Dickinson County No. 2 serves 1,509, and Russell County No. 3
serves 480.
</P>
<P>
   The district closest to Kansas City is Anderson County,
southwest of Johnson County. Most of the other districts are in
sparsely populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators tested 125 of Kansas' 250 rural water districts
between June and October, taking two to four tests at each. The
highest reading was in Comanche County, 13.6 parts per billion. The
federal limit is 2 ppb.
</P>
<P>
   Officials chose the 125 districts that appeared to be most
likely to show vinyl chloride contamination, said Dave Waldo, who
heads the public drinking water section of the Kansas Department of
Health and Environment.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear yet whether the 125 other rural water systems in
Kansas will be tested. Those would be considered less likely to
have problems, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, regulators reported in September that they had
found high levels of vinyl chloride in five rural water districts,
but they hoped to investigate further. The Missouri official in
charge of that effort could not be reached late Thursday for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Three rural water districts in Iowa were found this summer with
high levels of vinyl chloride, but follow-up testing has found that
those were the result of ``unusual circumstances,'' such as low
water usage, said Roy Ney, an engineer in Iowa's Water Quality
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   In each case in Iowa, the situation has been corrected, Ney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about the levels of vinyl chloride and other
contaminants within public water systems' distribution lines,
because testing isn't required beyond the point where it leaves the
water plant.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, high levels of vinyl chloride found in these
systems have so far not been considered to be a violation of
federal drinking water limits.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic pipe made from polyvinyl chloride, or PVC, before 1977
can release the chemical into drinking water if water sits long in
the pipe, especially during warm weather. The dead-end sections of
sprawling rural water systems are most prone to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rural water districts across the Midwest began this summer to
test for vinyl chloride in drinking water after federal regulators
suggested the testing.
</P>
<P>
   In February, The Kansas City Star reported that state and
federal agencies that regulate public drinking water had known for
at least six years that parts of a rural water system in Doniphan
County, Kan., were contaminated by vinyl chloride. The agencies
didn't act to reduce customers' exposure until the newspaper
inquired about the contamination.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, EPA officials made a $50,000 grant available to
help pay for the testing. Kansas and Missouri split that money.
</P>
<P>
   The Vinyl Institute, an industry association, and a PVC pipe
industry group have taken steps this year related to the vinyl
chloride problem.
</P>
<P>
   They have offered to help states pay for follow-up testing.
</P>
<P>
   In Doniphan County's Rural Water District No. 5, they have
provided bottled water for most of the year to about 30 residents
whose water tested high for vinyl chloride.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has also offered District No. 5 free replacement
pipe or two other alternatives that might reduce vinyl chloride
levels below the federal limit of 2 parts per billion.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Patterson, who until recently represented the Vinyl
Institute on this issue, has said he was not surprised to find that
a small percentage of the systems with pipe made before 1977 had
high levels of vinyl chloride.
</P>
<P>
   That is because industry tests had shown that the plastic resin
used to make the pipe back then contained enough vinyl chloride to
contaminate water at levels above the federal limit under certain
conditions, Patterson said. The industry switched to a new
manufacturing method after 1977.
</P>
<P>
   But other industry representatives on Thursday pointed to recent
data as evidence that the vinyl chloride problem may not extend far
beyond Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri and Iowa found few problems, most of them caused by
such unusual circumstances as someone not being home for an
extended time, causing the water to sit in the pipes for unusually
long periods, said Dave Eckstein of the Dallas-based Uni-Bell PVC
Pipe Association, which represents PVC pipe producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to say this is a limited situation,'' Eckstein
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
