<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7394 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-SOCIAL-LADN     12-18 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-SOCIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A STAND AT THE SHUBERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sounds of freedom rang through the Shubert Theatre at the
debut presentation of the concert version of ``Masada, the
Musical,'' a benefit for DARE America and the Masada Preservation
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, which the producers plan to take to Broadway in the
future, tells the story of a band of first-century Jewish zealots
who take a stand against the Romans in a mountaintop fortress and
choose death by their own hands rather than the slavery that
awaited them.
</P>
<P>
   The pairing of ``Masada'' and DARE, the now-worldwide drug
education and resistance program for schoolchildren, was a natural,
said Glenn Levant, president and founding director of DARE America.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Masada's' theme is `Let no man be another man's slave,' and
DARE is keeping children from being slaves to drugs and the fear of
violence,'' Levant said. He also noted that when ``Masada'' is
staged on Broadway and worldwide, a portion of its profits will
always go to benefit DARE.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that Levant is married to the musical's executive
producer, Jayne Levant. ``I had the inside track'' for the benefit,
Levant quipped. And his wife added, ``I hope you brought plenty of
Kleenex _ it will be a moving experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The reception, held in a narrow foyer of the Shubert,
appropriately was themed with Middle Eastern fare, a pianist
playing melodies from the upcoming performance, and even a display
of antique jars from Masada that were on loan from the collections
of the Institute of Archeology of Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Hors d'oeuvres tables were laden with stuffed grape leaves, filo
pastry topped with carmelized onions and goat cheese, tabbouleh,
fresh vegetables, pita and assorted dips. Tiny servings of caviar,
smoked salmon, potato pancakes, spanakopita, and other treats were
passed on orchid-trimmed trays throughout the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Among the eclectic crowd was ``Masada'' composer Shuki Levy, Lee
Iacocca, Marla Maples, Larry King, Fred Dryer, Donna Mills, Donny
and Marie Osmond, Monty Hall, Corbin Bernsen, Sugar Ray Leonard,
Jerry Buss, Paul Mazursky, District Attorney Gil Garcetti, Sheriff
Lee Baca, Los Angeles police Chief Bernard Parks and even the
Israeli consul general, Yoram Ben Ze'ev. Making the highest profile
arrival, however, was Jon Voight, the program narrator, wearing a
black scarf around his head and a white scarf draped around his
shoulder ... and a full beard.
</P>
<P>
   The performance itself _ set on a stark stage with full
orchestra _ featured Davis Gaines, known for his long-running
performances in ``Phantom of the Opera,'' in the role as leader of
the zealots. The concert ended with members of the Children of the
World Choir, wearing culturally diverse costumes and each holding a
flickering candle, in a performance that got the audience to jump
to its feet for a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ELSEWHERE IN THE CITY were numerous holiday-themed parties,
including Geary's 12 Days of Christmas party to benefit the
Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation. The charity's national
spokeswoman Mary Steenburgen was among the guests who helped raise
$1 million for the charity by bidding on jewels and gifts donated
by Cindy Crawford, Tiger Woods, Helen Hunt, Mel Gibson and Tom
Hanks. The event was held at Geary's in Beverly Hills, and
co-hosted by In Style magazine.
</P>
<P>
   AND AT THE REGENT Beverly Wilshire Hotel in Beverly Hills, the
United Hostesses' Charities presented Dr. Alfred Trento with the
1998 Humanitarian Award. Trento is chairman of Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center's Cardiothoracic Surgery division.
</P>
<P>
   The 56th annual dinner dance was planned by Donna Weintraub and
Roya Geiderman as a benefit for Cedars-Sinai and the Didi Hirsch
Community Mental Health Center in Culver City.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar De La Hoya Foundation held its second annual Evening
of Champions gala at the Beverly Hilton Hotel and honored Sylvester
Stallone. According to De La Hoya, ``He was an inspiration to me
while I was growing up. Watching him in the first `Rocky' movie
taught me to never give up and always go for my goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Also honored were Richard Naula, president of Starwood Hotels
and Resorts; Jim Lampley of HBO Sports; and Robert Alcazar,
co-founder of the Oscar De La Hoya Youth Center. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
