<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A BIG UPSIDE TO DOWNSIZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When economist Timothy Martin offered his perspectives at the
Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce economic outlook breakfast
last week, he provided an interesting insight that helped explain
how a low jobless rate coexists with relentless corporate
downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, senior economist with NationsBank Corp., mentioned in
passing a phenomenon he characterized as ``trophy layoffs.'' The
implication was that when companies trumpet plans for massive
layoffs, they're playing to Wall Street in hopes of a favorable
reaction by stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual reality, however, is that subsequent downsizings
don't prove as devastating to the employees at risk as the
announcement portends. The downsizing is often achieved largely by
attrition, and actual layoffs aren't nearly as extensive as
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   If Martin's insight is valid, it makes some sense of one of the
most puzzling economic developments of the '90s. While downsizing
has continued apace, the unemployment rate has declined to levels
not seen in a generation. Meanwhile, the economic expansion is
nearing a record duration for peacetime, and job creation has been
extremely strong.
</P>
<P>
   While these events are obvious, most average Americans tend not
to question the apparent anomaly of plentiful jobs and
announcements of massive layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Martin know that the rest of us don't?
</P>
<P>
   He probably knows to look beyond media coverage for his economic
insights. MediaNomics, the Media Research Center's periodic
critique of business and economics reporting, recently noted how
journalists usually fail to make the connection between
restructuring and U.S. economic strength.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the biggest companies are boasting of getting leaner and
meaner, the small and mid-sized companies continue hiring at a
``stupendous clip.'' The article quotes a recent Investor's
Business Daily story explaining how ``new jobs are being created
faster than the government can count in sectors of the economy that
barely existed two decades ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin reminds us that there may be a lot less to the announced
Big Business layoffs in recent years than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Why do reporters fail to get beyond what big corporations are
saying and what's really happening? It probably gets back to the
media's traditional mind-set. First of all, bad news gets a lot
more attention than good news. Beyond this, journalists generally
don't cut Big Business much slack. When megamergers occur, this
leads to the obvious themes of how the robber barons are banding
together to take over the world and crush the proletariat under
their oppressive heels.
</P>
<P>
   What nobody seems to notice, though, is that America's
proletariat has become the beneficiary of the most prosperous
economy in the world. The expanding economy is the result of
businesses doing what's necessary to become more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The reason most of the rest of the world is struggling is
because business leadership elsewhere couldn't summon the resolve
to meet the challenges of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're looking for something to be thankful for this
holiday season, try a decade of downsizing. Without it, America
might be in the same boat as Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1720EST &QL; 
