<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARD-STRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS CARD CUSTOM UNDER STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has the Christmas card become a ball and chain?
</P>
<P>
   As busy as Americans have become, hardly anyone wants to face
the annual chore of penning individual greetings and signing dozens
of cards, addressing envelopes, and licking them shut. Not to
mention tracking down zip codes. Can't e-mail suffice?
</P>
<P>
   It's a modern quandary over a time-consuming tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Some people try to get off the hook by sending a picture of
their children, attached to a pre-printed greeting card. Others
have their names engraved in fancy lettering inside stationery.
There's no personal message, but they figure it's the thought that
counts. Still others send form letters on decorated computer paper,
recounting their family's accomplishments for the year.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who use the Web site, www.beyond.com, that sends
electronic cards via the Internet. Then there are the folks who
unabashedly send their cards after Christmas. And others are simply
cutting back.
</P>
<P>
   June Tarter doesn't want to give up on cards completely but has
trimmed her list, eliminating some of her husband's business
contacts and people she hasn't heard from in years past. ``I don't
want to be petty and say, `You didn't send me one,' '' she says.
But Tarter has already devoted several nights this month to the
task. Besides she says, ``You have such easy access to people now,
through the fax, the telephone, and e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Tarter's friends are cutting back too. Last year, she
received a note from someone saying they would send a newsletter
only every three years and, in the off years, they would send the
money normally spent on the cards to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas card sales are steady, says Michelle Buckley, a
spokeswoman for Hallmark Cards. Since about 70 percent of Americans
typically send cards, she says, the market is basically saturated.
According to Hallmark research, on average, 38 to 40 cards are sent
per celebrating household and, industrywide, 2.6 billion cards were
exchanged nationwide in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   So just what are the rules these days? What's considered tacky
in the world of Christmas card etiquette? And what exactly _ with
just six days left until the big day _ can you get away with doing
this year?
</P>
<P>
   Well, forget engraved cards. While they're a great time-saver,
they're just too impersonal, say etiquette experts. ``I can't stand
it when cards just have people's names printed on them. I would
rather not get one,'' complains Nancy Tuckerman, co-author of ``The
Amy Vanderbilt Complete Book of Etiquette.'' ``If they can't write
a few things _ `Hoping to see you. Have a great New Year's' _
forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, preprinted address labels are problematic. Says Peggy
Post, author of ``Etiquette,'' ``Sure, they cut back on time if
someone has the time to type in all those addresses. I only caution
that sometimes the envelopes don't look like personal mail. They
can look like junk mail and get tossed out.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the family form letter? Keep it short, maybe just one
page, etiquette authorities advise. ``Are people that interested in
whether your dog had puppies? Do they want to know the grades of
your children? If you just stop and think . . . the answer is no,''
says Tuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   Most people agree that pictures of children are charming.
However, if the greeting arrives after the holidays, the meaning is
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have completely given up on the tradition of card
giving. Nancy Michaels, for example, hasn't mailed Christmas cards
since 1990. Last year, she gave out Valentine's Day cards instead.
``Initially, it was a fluke. I couldn't make the deadline,'' says
the marketing consultant. Now, in business seminars, she advises
clients not to send out Christmas cards for business because she
believes they are a waste of time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've discovered that to send a holiday card out is not the
most memorable thing you can do. You're stuck in the deluge of mail
that everyone else is sending,'' she says. ``When you send a card
out at an unexpected time, it stands out. It creates a bigger
memory. Can you remember who sent you cards last year?''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are many people who still take the
Christmas-card custom seriously _ even as prices for cards have
risen to $17 a box, and even higher. Mary Lou Andre, president of
the Organization by Design, a wardrobe management company, reports
that at least 10 of her customers requested her help in selecting
outfits for their Christmas card family portraits this year. ``The
pictures are a big deal,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Boskin, a Boston University history professor, says that
one of his close friends _ who will remain unnamed _ plans to mail
out 1,750 cards this year to business associates and family, down
from 2,500 in the past. ``These people start in August at the
beach,'' he jokes.
</P>
<P>
   How many cards will Boskin send out this year? ``Zero. I send
out no cards. I celebrate Christmas. I just can't do cards. I don't
have the time and I must say I've gotten lazier. I don't want to,''
he says. Rather than cards, he says, ``I just say what I want to on
the telephone. It's much more personal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
