<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7427 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-SOLD-LADN     12-18 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-SOLD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURE FOR A BAD AIR DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Get a whiff of this.
</P>
<P>
   It took long enough, but someone finally did it.
</P>
<P>
   Air, one of the last of life's necessities still freely
available to everyone, has been commodified _ packaged, marketed
and sold by a celebrity pitchman.
</P>
<P>
   At O2, Los Angeles' first oxygen bar, customers can order 20
minutes of purified, pleasant-smelling air for $13.
</P>
<P>
   Co-owners Woody Harrelson, wife Laura Louie and Richard ``Dr.
D'' DeAndrea are banking that you'll be willing to pay through the
nose for it.
</P>
<P>
   Breathing air with a high oxygen content, enthusiasts say, has
health benefits that range from boosting energy and the immune
system to relieving headaches and stress.
</P>
<P>
   No one needs this more than in Los Angeles, where bad air
actually makes the nightly news. The brownish gas we're breathing
is causing ``slow suffocation,'' O2's brochure warns. A few snorts
of oxygen can undo some of the damage, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very cleansing,'' DeAndrea said. ``It creates a
meditative balance ... People who come in here who are very
energetic get calm. People who come in here who are very calm get
more energetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, an oxygen bar has its appeal. Oxygen is low-cal and
low-fat. You can go &UR;  &LR; on a bender _ without risking a hangover!
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, many mainstream medical experts are turning up
their noses at those claims, saying no medical study supports such
assertions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no benefit to be gained, other than some vague
emotional idea you are doing something good for yourself,'' said
Dr. Bertrand Shapiro, professor of clinical medicine at UCLA's
School of Medicine. ``You're paying for a placebo effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eat. Drink. Breathe. Love.'' With a motto like that, O2 is
right at home on the trendiest portion of the Sunset Strip, between
the Sky Bar and the Viper Room in West Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   DeAndrea, who has disavowed traditional medicine's reliance on
technology and pharmaceuticals, fits the part as well, looking more
like a grunge rocker in his brown ski cap and flannel shirt than a
physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life can be an endless party,'' he says, reclining on comfy,
colorful pillows with a two-pronged tube up his nose to deliver his
daily dose of canned oxygen. ``That would make everybody much
happier.''
</P>
<P>
   DeAndrea graduated from the State University of New York Health
Science Center at Brooklyn in 1991 with a degree in medicine. The
young doctor gave up meat when a woman he was interested in dating
said she would only kiss him if he promised to go vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a profound change in the way I felt,'' DeAndrea said.
``I felt stronger and more focused.''
</P>
<P>
   He soon took a job as medical director of Century Freeway
Medical Center in the Watts section of Los Angeles. What he found
there would reinforce his interest in vegetarianism. Many of his
patients, he said, were obese and suffered from chronic diseases,
including diabetes, hypertension, heart disease and arthritis. He
became convinced that their meat-based, high-fat diets were slowly
killing them, and he challenged his patients to give up meat and
dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Harrelson _ best known for his role as the lovable dolt
of a bartender on the retired sitcom ``Cheers'' _ and his wife were
listening as DeAndrea promoted his holistic medicine and vegetarian
beliefs on a now-defunct public radio show.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity couple, outspoken advocates of legalized
marijuana, invited him to their home in Beverly Hills, where the
threesome hatched the plan: Develop a concept for a place where
people could gather socially and improve their health at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the trio is peddling oxygen on tap. Customers
can listen to soothing music, gaze at the painting of the planets
on the rotunda ceiling and sample herbal elixirs or raw-food dishes
from the all-organic, nondairy, vegetarian menu.
</P>
<P>
   For $12, try Yoda's Wish pizza for one, made from sun-dried
tomatoes, spinach, pesto sauce, garlic, basil and olives on crust
made from dehydrated kamut seed _ all of it uncooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking food destroys its enzymes, the life force in the food,
and alters its nutrients,'' said John Wood, O2's chef. ``Our food
is all alive ... You don't see any other animals cooking their food
except us, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   You can also sample a variety of herbal drinks for $6, such as
Jah Creme _ amaretto and java nut milk on the rocks, mixed with
kava kava, valerian, chamomile and hops for a ``meditative
meltdown'' in a martini glass.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like a mud slide, but tastes more like mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to taste herb-y,'' said the bartender helpfully.
</P>
<P>
   You can also order totally legal carrot cake made with hemp,
hemp burgers and blueberry hemp smoothies. Food made with this hemp
seed does not produce the same effects as, say, a hashish brownie,
since it contains no THC (tetrahydrocannabinol), the primary
psychoactive ingredient in marijuana, DeAndrea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to mention that just in case anyone wanted to
smoke our drapes,'' DeAndrea said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time for the main attraction _ the oxygen _
customers insert a cannula, a device with two prongs that shoots
gas into the nostrils.
</P>
<P>
   The gas _ which you can ``flavor'' with lemon, lime, orange,
joy, clarity, or energy for an extra $2 _ contains upward of 85
percent oxygen. Air normally contains about 21 percent oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Sound extra healthy? Not when you consider all the oxygen
healthy people need is right under their noses, said Shapiro, who
specializes in pulmonary disease.
</P>
<P>
   The hemoglobin in our blood is already 98 percent to 99 percent
saturated with oxygen. Upping that another percentage point isn't
going to make a significant or long-term difference in our health,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   People with pulmonary disease such as emphysema or chronic
bronchitis can benefit from breathing pure oxygen because their
blood oxygen levels are low to start with _ but they're typically
hooked up round-the-clock to a portable oxygen system.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side: there is probably nothing harmful about
breathing in purified oxygen for 20 minutes a day, Shapiro said.
While breathing 100 percent oxygen for too long can be toxic,
Shapiro said, there's little chance of that happening to anyone at
O2.
</P>
<P>
   To get the full impact of the tanked gases, you'd need a
tight-fitting mask. Using the two-pronged cannula allows most of
the oxygen to escape or to be diluted by air from the room.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, you're inhaling air that's at best about 24 percent
to 35 percent oxygen, Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of medical evidence to support any health benefits of
breathing concentrated oxygen doesn't keep bars like O2 from
sucking in new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real skeptical,'' said Los Angeles resident Daniel
Costello, 30, sampling oxygen for the first time at O2 recently.
``But it's kind of cool. I do feel relaxed and energized ...
They're going to make a profit selling good things rather than
alcohol or cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Gina Pucci, 32, of Santa Monica: ``It's not like being
stoned or high or drunk, but it's relaxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen bars are hardly new on our polluted planet. Kevin
McFarland, chief executive officer of the O2 Zone, a Reno-based
company that manufactures oxygen bar equipment and trains new
proprietors in using it, claims that as far back as 1957, street
vendors in Tokyo offered ``shots'' of oxygen to passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland said oxygen bars opened in the late '80s in the United
States but were shut down by local, state or federal authorities
for making medical claims or using medical-grade oxygen improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Medical-grade oxygen, which has to meet stringent purity
requirements, is regulated by the FDA and can only be dispensed by
a doctor or with a prescription, said Brad Stone, spokesman for the
U.S. Food and Drug Adminstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't heard of any oxygen bar that would be in compliance
with our regulations,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, more are on their way. Las Vegas' first oxygen bar,
Breathe, opened last week. Denver and Portland are each scheduled
to get their own early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens more small-scale oxygen outlets are operating out of
tanning salons, hair salons and day spas in small cities, including
Rockford, Ill., Scottsdale, Ariz., &UR;  &LR; Jonesboro, Ga., and Cincinnati,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But how will the oxygen bar concept float in Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   Hyper health-conscious Los Angelenos, pioneers of questionable
self-help therapies, are already primed for it.
</P>
<P>
   We hand over a couple of bucks to men in little red jackets to
move our car 2 feet. We buy $80,000 Humvees to cruise Ventura
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   We buy bottled water that costs far more more than what comes
out of the tap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analogy of bottled water is the best,'' McFarland said.
``In the early days, I said, `Who would pay for bottled water when
you can get it out of the tap for free?' And now look.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
