   STEALTH BOMBER-IRAQ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The B-2 stealth bomber was designed to be the most
feared plane in the Air Force, able to slip undetected through
enemy radar and deliver a lethal payload. But when the United
States launched the biggest air assault since the Persian Gulf War,
the $2 billion boomerang-shaped plane was at home in a hangar. As
U.S. warplanes and cruise missiles pounded Baghdad over the past
three days, the nine B-2s the Air Force considers operational were
at Whiteman Air Force Base, near Sedalia, Mo. By MICHAEL D. TOWLE.
Story has moved in ``w'' Washington category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
