<HEADER>
A7435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERRERA20-COX     12-18 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERRERA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 20
 &HT;    Designer takes humorous, light approach
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What can one write about Carolina Herrera that hasn't been
written already?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very difficult question to answer,'' Herrera recently
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Before a ponderous silence could fully blanket the Ritz-Carlton
Buckhead suite she occupied while waiting for a runway presentation
of her spring summer '99 designs to start, Herrera's 29-year-old
daughter traveling companion fragrance collaborator, Carolina
Adriana, chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it is,'' she said, turning admiringly toward her
mother. ``You're hysterically funny. I can vouch for that. That's
never been written, but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Herrera, 58, matures, she seems to grow more
whimsical. She responded with laughter when asked about entering
the design business so late in life (age 40), about her love-hate
stance on public appearances, her plans for 2000 and the challenges
of staying relevant in the fickle fashion industry.
</P>
<P>
   There's an increasing lightheartedness to Herrera's designs as
well. Among the 500 women who showed up to see her Saks Fifth
Avenue-sponsored show at the Ritz, the average age was at least 45.
Yet the clothes had that sassy, clingy, sprightly look befitting
women half that age.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, black and white are the base shades of Herrera's
spring/summer '99 collection, but she livens it up with leather
pieces in lavender and fuchsia. Skirts are slit high in the front;
pants are slung low on the hips. Tops are either funneled at the
neck, or they plunge deeply in back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a younger collection because I'm inspired by the youth of
the world,'' Herrera said. ``Everything they do is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And at this stage in the Venezuelan designer's career fun is the
main object of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a good sense of humor,'' she said. ``I think
anything you do with a sense of humor is perfect. Someone can say
to you, `Do you remember such and such a man? He's so
good-looking.' To me, he may or may not be. But you never forget
someone who makes you laugh. Never, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Herrera on . . .
</P>
<P>
   Her Atlanta clients' tastes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose they're looking for what Carolina Herrera's given
them for years. . . . I give them styles that are very feminine and
sophisticated but at the same time modern. It's easy to wear. It's
not complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Her evolving design philosophy:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion should have an extravagance to it, yet it should also
be simple. Simplicity is the basis of elegance, and that's the way
women want to look, no?''
</P>
<P>
   Her plans for 2000:
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is . . . what's new? We don't know what's going
to be new in the year 2000. Let's arrive there first, then see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Collaborating with daughter Carolina to formulate the new
fragrance 212:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an all new concept, from the packaging to the bottle to
the ad campaign to the fragrance itself. It's very light and fresh
and young, and we thought it was a great idea to bring Carolina in
to develop it.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
