<HEADER>
A7437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-BOOKS20-COX     12-18 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-BOOKS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTILDECEMBER 20
 &HT;    The gift of a book a reflection of who we are to the giver
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I own, or rather am owned by, roughly 2,000 books, of which
exactly seven were given to me at Christmas. It's curious how gifts
to family and friends reflect not the people they truly are but who
we think they are _ or who we are. Over the years, I've warehoused
large stocks of cologne and after-shave, grown rich in underwear,
found myself the owner of a clock that will hang on my wall only
when Time runs out and not a second sooner, lined by closets _ if
not my pockets _ in things woolen and warm.
</P>
<P>
   All of these were expressions of sincerest generosity, and were
appreciated for the thought that lay behind them. We all know
that's what counts, much more than the everyday utility of cotton
briefs.
</P>
<P>
   But the gift we appreciate like no other is the one that
reflects us. In such a case, the thought means all the more because
the giver has glimpsed something of the person we are. Among the
books that have taken over my den, study and bedroom is a copy of
E.F. Benson's ``Make Way for Lucia,'' given me 10 years ago and
inscribed by my friend and former colleague Bill Morrison.
Elsewhere is a copy of Hugh Thomas' ``The Spanish Civil War'' that
my father gave me one Christmas when he was younger than I am now.
At the time, I couldn't have told you anything of that war's
origins or its consequences, and even now couldn't write more than
a passable paragraph about it. But Thomas' book, brightly jacketed
in yellow, red-orange and black, had caught my eye and to this day
I can call up the smell of its pages when it was new. It cost all
of $10, about what I made each week delivering newspapers. My
father wasn't much of a reader, but he knew that I was, and in his
bold script (so different from my styleless scribble) he expressed
the kind of Christmas sentiments that need no ribbons or bows.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, giving books as gifts can be chancy; they are more
personal than even jewelry, to say nothing of toiletries. Unless
you know him well, you don't want to spring a novel of any
complexity on a man. He's not likely to be up to it. Men, by and
large, don't read literary fiction, just as women, by and large,
don't read serious nonfiction. Most men don't read that either,
come to think of it. When they read at all, their tastes run to
management manuals, sports biographies, stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   Disagree? Check out what the people you know read and decide for
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet books are popular Christmas gifts, from readers to
nonreaders, from nonreaders to readers baffled that someone would
think they'd want to read . . . . that?
</P>
<P>
   If it's better to give than to receive, it's also easier.
Receiving, in fact, can be excruciating. What writers would one be
horror-struck to find beneath the tree? Stephen King, obviously,
but that's his stock-in-trade; he wants you to be. All things
considered, I could manage a truer and brighter face for Stephen
King, maybe even Anne Rice, than I could for the pensees of certain
talk-show hosts, recycled for the congregants.
</P>
<P>
   There are books and then, of course, there is merchandise. They
might be one and the same to the clerk taking inventory. But once
in our hands, they present themselves as one or the other _ as one
more material possession, less valuable than a new sweater or new
software, or as something that speaks to what is most vital within
us.
</P>
<P>
   I don't quite believe this, but a few years ago the Gallup Poll
reported that three in five adults hoped to receive books for
Christmas. Imagine that: In a country of nonreaders, afflicted by
attention-deficit disorder, 60 percent of us are hoping there's a
book under the tree.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, the poll _ which was conducted for the
American Booksellers Association _ reported some interesting
findings. Geographically, people read more in the Northeast and the
West than we do down here in the South, but we read more than folks
in some uncharted territory identified as ``North Central'' (the
Dakotas plus Minnesota?). Places I would call the Southwest _ Texas
and wherever there's cactus _ got left out entirely. Maybe no one
reads out there.
</P>
<P>
   The rich read more than the poor, the educated more than the
uneducated and, of course, women more than men. And the young,
surprisingly, read more than the old (well, 55 and up). Exactly
what they read was not reported. For the merchandiser, it's beside
the point. All books are equal in the sight of God and the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   But for the receiver, that's precisely the point. The books we
keep are ones that read us as much as we read them. More than any
gift that comes to mind, they are a reflection of our taste and our
curiosity, our capacity for discrimination and enjoyment. On my
shelves are books read and unread, books by the hundreds that I
want to keep for as long as I live and at least as many that I
should winnow out before the start of a new year.
</P>
<P>
   But there are seven that at various points of my life meant, and
still mean, something special. They sit, unnoticed on most days,
like signposts to Christmases past _ and to ties everlasting.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
