 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Bombing Iraq is a tactical tantrum rather than part of a
well-thought out strategy. It is also as ineffective as it is
morally dubious.
</P>
<P>
   The air raids have alienated much of the rest of the world while
weakening the United Nations and the already creaky system of
international order. The bombs may rattle windows in Baghdad, but
they will not dislodge Saddam Hussein from his throne. And while
the United States and Britain can bomb on their own, they need the
rest of the world to hold the line on sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, it was bad manners to start the bombing in
the name of the United Nations without telling Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, who sounded understandably miffed that there was too
little warning to pull out the entire staff he had in the target
zone.
</P>
<P>
   It is also stretching international law to the breaking point to
invoke U.N. resolutions to justify the U.S.-British action, which
is precisely why the Russians and Chinese are so upset. If it had
been proposed anew to the Security Council, they would have vetoed
it.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of the U.N. Security Council is collective
security: that there should be a consensus on action to avert
threats to international peace. Could Russia take action against
Indonesia and Morocco because of their defiance of Security Council
resolutions on East Timor or Western Sahara, or against Israel for
the U.N. resolutions it has defied?
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it is not just the GOP at home who suspect that the
timing of the raids tarnishes them with the suspicion of domestic
expediency in the face of impeachment. The rest of the world is
already weary with an American foreign policy that all too often
seems to be driven by domestic influences.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the legality, and the expediency, there is the
question of efficacy. There is no doubt that Saddam Hussein was
``asking for it'' by reneging on his latest promise to cooperate
with the U.N. inspectors. But since when have we decided to give
him what he asks for?
</P>
<P>
   The first casualty of the bombing is likely to be the U.N.
inspection regime, which will give Saddam even more leeway to
develop his chemical and biological warfare capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the bombings, there was a strange confluence of
interests developing between Washington and Baghdad. On the one
hand, Washington had decided that the inspections were ineffective
and left events hostage to Iraqi whims. On the other, Baghdad's
weapon-fetishists worried that the shell game they had been playing
would fail sometime and that the inspectors would produce damning
evidence of their dissimulation.
</P>
<P>
   So the current policy seems to have just evolved. The bombing
implies abandoning the inspection regime, trying to maintain
sanctions, perhaps plugging the considerable leaks which benefit
the regime directly, and hoping that someone, sometime, will topple
Saddam. However, that is almost as much of a non-policy as the
bombing itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has often implied that the aim of
sanctions is the overthrow of Saddam Hussein. But that is not what
other members of the United Nations think, no matter how much they
would like to see the back of him. Without the inspection regime
that sanctions are supposed to enforce, it will be difficult to
persuade cooperation from the rest of the international community.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, apart from its dubious morality, starving
populations into rebellion has not worked in Cuba, nor is it likely
to work in Iraq. Even if it did, in the Darwinian world of Iraqi
politics, anyone who replaces Saddam Hussein is likely to be even
nastier.
</P>
<P>
   If sanctions are to be maintained with continued international
support after the bombing, the relevant U.N. resolutions need
revision. This means refining the sanctions so that they target the
regime rather than its Iraqi victims, which would offer a trade-off
to Russia, China and other critics of the effect of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will also have to promise ``light at the end
of the tunnel'' for Iraq, the eventual lifting of sanctions in
return for cooperation on disarmament. This might then allow the
inspectors and monitors to reenter Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is a crumbling of the sanctions regime and a
further erosion of the U.N.'s standing, with occasional salvos of
hundreds of millions of dollars worth of hardware against a defiant
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Williams is vice president (and former president) of the
U.N. Correspondents Association, U.N. correspondent for Middle East
International magazine and for The Nation. He is also the author of
``The Alms Trade'' and ``The U.N. for Beginners.'' He has written
for the Independent, the guardian, the London Telegraph, the
European, the New York Observer and other U.S. and international
newspapers and magazines.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
