<P>
   KULMAN _ ATLANTA _ Borg-Warner Automotive, the world's largest
maker of automatic transmission parts, will buy Savannah-based
Kuhlman for $660 million, or $39 a share, to get Kuhlman's
turbocharger business. Borg-Warner said it will sell Kuhlman's
electrical transformer and electric wire and cable businesses. The
purchase allows it to expand into the market for turbochargers
(Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   AUS-TOOTS -MANSFIELD-DEATH _ AUSTIN _ Coy ``Toots'' Mansfield, a
seven-time world champion calf roper and first-ever rodeo inductee
into the Texas Sports Hall of Fame, died at 84 Wednesday in El
Paso. Born on a ranch in Bandera, he dominated his 10-second-long
event during the 1940s, coming in first or second in the standings
for 13-straight years. He taught roping in Big Spring in his later
years and was Big Springs' Man of the Year in 1995. Might want to
send this one to Waco because of the Hall of Fame there. (Wear,
Austin American-Statesman) FOR SATURDAY
