<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INGRID-TEACH-LADN     12-18 2663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INGRID-TEACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE OF A LIFETIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; With her Cover Girl complexion and prom-queen
smile, it might seem perverse that Ingrid Boydston's all-time
favorite character role was a repulsive swamp hag in the immortal
drama ``Terror by Gaslight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to murder this girl on stage,'' says Boydston, her dark
eyes gleaming happily at the memory. ``It required a lot of
burping, so I had to guzzle cream soda all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, nobody said this was Shakespeare, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Her directing debut? ``I Only Have Fangs for You,'' a Halloween
spoof that even Boydston admits had ``a terrible, terrible
script.''
</P>
<P>
   Saintly teachers. Pure-hearted saloon girl. Naughty housewives.
Merry murderesses. In the world of small-town community theater,
the 33-year-old schoolmarm with the personality that would make
Pollyanna sound like a cynic may be the closest thing going to
Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   Why, out here in Canyon Country folks still talk of Boydston's
tour-de-force as Anne Sullivan in last summer's Canyon Theatre
Guild production of ``The Miracle Worker.'' Never mind that the
theater's dirt-gravel remoteness, at the edge of the Angeles
National Forest, often makes passers-by mistake it for a biker bar.
</P>
<P>
   If Michael Ovitz had been in the audience one of those nights,
who knows? Maybe Boydston wouldn't still be working at Santa
Clarita Elementary School, where two months ago she was named one
of five California Teachers of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In live theater, it's very hard to make people cry, but they
were crying at `The Miracle Worker','' says Canyon Theatre Guild
artistic director Ben Boydston, who happens to be Ingrid's husband.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Boydston's true-life roles have been equally
gut-wrenching. Like the time two years ago when one of her
students, a bright, gentle boy named Paul Youhanian, was shot dead
off-campus for no earthly reason.
</P>
<P>
   Or back in 1990, when Boydston _ then a 20-something Hollywood
party hound and celebrity wannabe _ was cruising Sunset Boulevard
in a midnight blue convertible, wondering why her super-cool
lifestyle was leaving her so empty and miserable.
</P>
<P>
   That was around the time when Ben Boydston first walked into
Ingrid's life and helped her realize that her true calling wasn't
to be found in trendy nightclubs, but in a sun-streaked classroom
on Seco Canyon Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband calls it `wounded bird syndrome','' Boydston
explains. ``He has it, too. You want to save the world. Because he
saved me, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   But we're getting ahead of our story.
</P>
<P>
   In the dizzying weeks since she was named a Teacher of the Year
_ the only person from L.A. County so honored _ Boydston and her
school have been basking in the afterglow. Practically every TV
crew in town has beaten a path to Room 15 of Santa Clarita
Elementary, where Boydston has taught sixth grade for nearly 11
years.
</P>
<P>
   To call Boydston prime TV material would be an understatement.
She seems a figure straight out of central casting, this upbeat,
ferociously dedicated young woman with the long blond hair and the
goofy sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could bottle her enthusiasm in the classroom, you could
sell it,'' says Karen Blackwell, the school's head teacher. ``A
down day for Ingrid is a good day for other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Boydston's camera-ready persona even caught the attention of the
``The Donny and Marie Show,'' which invited her entire class in for
a taping session last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited, because that's my age group,'' Boydston gushes.
``We grew up with Donny and Marie lunch pails!''
</P>
<P>
   Then the date got postponed. Indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids were so deflated,'' Boydston sighs. ``I felt
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she has enjoyed the spotlight enormously, Boydston says
she's now eager to ``get back to normal,'' both in and outside her
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd be really bad at being famous,'' she says
modestly.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, when the Canyon Theatre Guild wraps up its year-end
production, ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' Boydston will be glad to be
just another pretty face in the Potterville mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seven lines and six costume changes,'' she says
cheerfully. ``If you blink, you'll miss me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that's show biz. One minute you're the star, the hometown
hero. The next, it's back to the daily grind, working unseen
miracles here and there, but mostly just trying to get 28
hormonally restive kids ready to inherit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, there's the 8:20 a.m. bell! We'll be late for class!
</P>
<P>
   Clap! Clap! Clap! Clap! Clap!
</P>
<P>
   Whenever someone visits Room 15, Mrs. Boydston and her students
stop whatever they're doing and break into applause. Even if it's
only Myron Groch, the school's vigilant yet easygoing principal.
Clap! Clap! Clap!
</P>
<P>
   It's one of many small touches that make Room 15 feel more like
a home than a learning factory.
</P>
<P>
   On the room's south wall, Boydston's students have painted
vibrant murals of the Hanging Gardens of Babylon, the Great
Pyramids and other Wonders of the World they'll be studying this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the teacher's desk is the class motto: ``Take PRIDE in
yourself, have CONFIDENCE in your Abilities, the COURAGE to do your
Best and COMPASSION for Humankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Another chart lists the duties of class officers, including Hero
of the Week. This accolade goes for top all-around citizenship, an
achievement Boydston rates higher than a perfect test score.
</P>
<P>
   ``For being such a wonderful community and a great district, in
my 10 years here I've dealt with murder, suicide, incest, divorce,
abandonment and substance abuse,'' Boydston says. ``In our valley!
That's (why) I feel so strongly that half my job is teaching them
things they need to know _ and the wisdom to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason students like Mrs. Boydston so much is that she's a
terrific ham. Strolling the classroom, she reads aloud from books
like ``Charlie and the Chocolate Factory,'' nailing the
Oompa-Loompas' accents on the very first take.
</P>
<P>
   She's forever dreaming up new incentives and gently probing for
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can disagree, and it can still be right,'' she'll tell the
sea of quizzical faces. ``Think, think, think! You can't be wrong,
so take the risk!''
</P>
<P>
   When the classroom gets too noisy, a steady look from Mrs.
Boydston is all that's needed to restore calm. Spend a day in Room
15, and you begin to wonder: Does this woman ever stop smiling?
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to hate science and social studies, and she makes it
fun,'' says Jessica Oliver, 11. ``Mrs. Boydston just makes
everything so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though seldom as easy as it looks, of course.
</P>
<P>
   When her pupil Paul Youhanian was killed in October 1996, many
of his classmates were ``incapacitated with anger,'' Boydston says.
They drifted into her class seeking comfort. What could she do but
sit and listen?
</P>
<P>
   ``The private side of Ingrid is that she was devastated, but she
never missed a day of school,'' says principal Groch. ``Every day,
she put on that happy face. And then when it was time to cry, she
cried with them, and then went on.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul's death wasn't the first severe test of Boydston's chronic
optimism. A few years ago, another of her students showed up at the
annual holiday party armed and planning to harm a classmate.
Boydston somehow talked him out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Then last July, a Saugus mother was charged with four murder
counts after she allegedly dressed her four young daughters in
their pajamas, had them lie down in sleeping bags on the kitchen
floor, then doused her home with accelerant and set a fire. All
four youngsters died; three of the girls, ages 5 to 11, attended
Santa Clarita Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like we don't have a year go by without a
tragedy,'' Boydston says. ``But it has pulled the staff together.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, among the dozen PCs and Macs in Room 15 is one donated by
Paul's parents as a gesture of remembrance and thanks to Boydston
and the school.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the wondrous high-tech classroom of the 21st century is
upon us. But some stuff never changes. Remember Elmer's Glue,
Boston Ranger pencil sharpeners, the Pledge of Allegiance,
``chocolate'' vs. ``regular'' milk for lunch, and the Dell
Paperbacks version of ``Johnny Tremaine''? They're still around,
mixed in with the in-line skates and the Bart Simpson sweatshirts.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's been the best and worst of years at Santa Clarita,
made tougher by the recent death of Boydston's beloved mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then my mind flies to some of my kids who don't have their
mom anymore or have a mom who's nothing like my mom was,'' Boydston
says. ``And then I can only be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, certain readers must surely be thinking: Enough
already! This woman's a saint! If we wanted fairy tales, we'd go
read Hans Christian Andersen!
</P>
<P>
   Boydston knows some people at first may be suspicious of what
they perceive as a cheerier-than-thou approach to life.
</P>
<P>
   So we'll let you in on a deep, dark secret: Boydston can't
resist Rice Krispies squares or chocolate doughnuts, both of which
she proceeds to wolf down during morning break in the teachers'
lounge.
</P>
<P>
   There!
</P>
<P>
   Following her luxurious 15-minute sabbatical, Boydston is back
on her feet again, leading her class in a discussion of Betsy
Byars' classic book ``The Pinballs.'' It's one of those
``realistic'' children's novels that came into vogue in the '70s,
and at first Boydston's students tittered at the characters' dated
slang and silly haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   But when Boydston gets them talking, it's clear the tale of a
girl's troubled family life has hit home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that when I get married I should really want kids,
so they'll really feel wanted,'' says Emily Bush, 11.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett Randall, whose parents named him for jazz pianist Keith
Jarrett, pipes up next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that you should never give up hope your whole
life,'' Jarrett says, ``because you've probably got about 80 years
to live, and when you think about it, one out of 80 isn't all that
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Boydston nods in agreement while managing to stifle a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Later, she whispers: ``I live to hear what he's going to say
next!''
</P>
<P>
   Lunchtime!
</P>
<P>
   En route to the cafeteria, Boydston grabs her black Rubbermaid
lunch pail and dashes out the door. One side bears an inscription
that Ben gave Ingrid for their first Christmas. It reads: ``Ingrid
_ Making a Difference by Teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, this wasn't exactly what Boydston had in mind when
she came west from Grand Junction, Colo., a 21-year-old theater
major out to conquer the world rather than save it.
</P>
<P>
   Always, always, she had wanted to be an actress, ever since her
parents named her after Ingrid Bergman, whose performance in the
1945 schlockfest ``Saratoga Trunk'' enchanted Boydston as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had black hair and a bad foreign accent, and I still
thought it was the greatest thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   With five daughters to support (Ingrid was second oldest),
Boydston's family didn't have much disposable income.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't know we didn't have any money. If we wanted to
play an instrument, we got music lessons. If we wanted to be in
Brownies, my mom would become the troop leader.''
</P>
<P>
   From childhood on, greasepaint coursed through her veins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd do `Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs' and call it `Wo
Snite and the Deven Swarves.' We thought we were hysterical.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, while majoring in theater at Mesa College, Boydston met
actress Margaret Avery (``The Color Purple''). Avery advised that
if Boydston was moving to California, she could earn money
teaching, because the state needed teachers so badly it was
allowing accelerated accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a month after landing in Southern California with a
suitcase and a $50 bus ticket, Boydston landed a job
substitute-teaching in Santa Maria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the classroom before they knew I wasn't an ax
murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   She also was holding down two other part-time jobs and taking
evening acting classes.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later, she was hired by the Saugus Union
School District to teach at Santa Clarita. But her heart still was
serving two masters.
</P>
<P>
   Her fiance at the time was an aspiring director in the film
program at the California Institute of the Arts in Valencia. The
couple had hooked up with an actor friend, and the trio began
writing and filming five-minute video shorts for Showtime's The
Movie Channel, mostly involving bogus activities performed by
celebrity look-alikes.
</P>
<P>
   Those shorts were to be their ticket into Hollywood. Almost
before she realized it, Boydston was swept up in the party-hopping,
status-digging frenzy that The Industry requires of those who covet
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to these really hideous things, like Sylvester
Stallone was throwing this fashion show for his girlfriend to be in
it, and it was like this crush of people all wanting to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   One evening, while driving to some or other club ``where some
ex-punk rocker just out of rehab was going to be appearing,''
Boydston had an epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling very disillusioned that all the events and
activities I was doing should've been making me feel wonderful and
happy and given me a sense of accomplishment, and they were empty
and fake and tragic, really.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas before if somebody had told me I was going to be in
the classroom, it would've felt like a letdown. In the classroom it
was vibrant and fun, and I felt not only did I have my own
identity, but I was helping other people find theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all it took for Boydston to give herself over, body and
soul, to her sixth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   Well ... it also helped that by then she'd met Ben while
auditioning at the Canyon Theatre for Larry Shue's comedy ``The
Nerd.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben was playing The Nerd.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid thought: ``There's no way I could like this guy, because
he had a little ponytail back then. He had a personalized license
plate and a cell phone, and those things scared me. But I could
also see he was very talented and very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben thought: ``I want to be you, because you don't care what
anybody thinks, you're just so happy in your bubble world, and I
want to be in there with you.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, they were married.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, several other couples and their children make up
the Canyon Theatre Guild's core membership of about 40. It's a
cozy, family affair though, like most families, not without
squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things aren't going right here, I get very nervous _ if
people's marriages aren't working out or whatever,'' Boydston says.
</P>
<P>
   More wounded bird syndrome?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' she admits. ``But I can't help it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving school for a dress rehearsal, Boydston shows a
visitor the little memorial garden that the school built for Paul
Youhanian, the boy who was killed. It's a lovely oasis of native
California plants and shrubs, with a short brick path and a
solitary bench. Principal Myron Groch did all the brickwork
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that little teddy bear topiary that gets to me
sometimes,'' Boydston finally says.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 o'clock, the theater is humming with activity _ costumes
being fitted, sets hammered, lines loudly rehearsed. Boydston won't
be needed for a while, so she offers her visitor an impromptu
backstage tour.
</P>
<P>
   She pushes open a rickety door and steps outside. It's a perfect
California winter night, cool and serene. Not a breath of wind can
be heard in the surrounding canyons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll sit out here and just hear the audience
laughing,'' she says softly, ``and it's so quiet, and you can see
the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimly, the voices of her fellow thespians drift through the air.
Soon, Boydston will rejoin them. But for now she's happy savoring
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a good idea. Because, as Jarrett reckoned, you've
probably got about 80 years to live.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes one moment of quiet reflection can make all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
