<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-WOMEN-1219-C     12-18 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-WOMEN-1219-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN FIGHTER PILOTS BREAKING GENDER BARRIER ON IRAQI MISSIONS
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1219.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seven years after the U.S. Senate lifted the ban on
using female pilots in combat, several women on the USS Enterprise
are flying fighter aircraft in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Although their names are not yet being released, nine female
pilots and seven naval flight officers are serving on the
Enterprise aircraft carrier, said Lt. William Day, a spokesman in
the U.S. Navy's Office of Information.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States and Britain launched a third wave of air
strikes on Iraqi military targets on Friday, the crew on the
aircraft carrier continued to play an integral role in what has
been dubbed, Operation: Desert Fox. The air strikes began
Wednesday, following an order by President Clinton, with the goal
of reducing Iraq's capability to threaten neighbors with weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   According to Day, the female pilots and naval flight officers on
the Enterprise have been flying the F-14B Tomcat, F/A-18C Hornet
fighters, EA-6B Prowler radar jammers, E-2C Hawkeye early warning
aircraft, S-3B Viking anti-sub aircraft and HH-60H Seahawk
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The use of women in combat is not without precedent, but until
recently was an extremely rare occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1991, the Senate voted to lift a 43-year-old law that
banned military women from flying combat missions. Although the
measure did not require the Navy and Air Force to use female
pilots, the Pentagon announced in 1993 that it would let women
pilot combat aircraft and assume other front-line roles.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1993, women had flown transport and tanker aircraft for
some time. However, the first time they served as pilots in combat
planes was from 1993 to 1995 during the Bosnia peacekeeping
mission, ``Deny Flight,'' Navy officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Women have also flown in the ongoing Operation: Southern Watch,
where they helped monitor the ``no-fly'' zones in Southern Iraq
after the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Although women have become an increasingly significant part of
the armed forces, critics were skeptical of exposing women to
violence by putting them directly in the line of fire. Women argued
that the prohibition against using their skills in combat hurt
their chances to be promoted.
</P>
<P>
   Day balked at the past controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its a non-issue for us,'' Day said. ``They're all pilots
whether they are male or female. We have great aviators, we have
great sailors, and gender is not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 222,000 women in the 2,034,000-member U.S.
armed forces. About 35,000 women served in the Gulf War. Eleven of
them died there, five in combat, according to news accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
