<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-XMASDINNER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Food a major source of holiday comfort and joy
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not necessarily the family and friends that make
you feel so good during holiday celebrations _ it could be the
food.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday meals are a particularly strong concoction of
stimulants, sedatives and chemical aphrodisiacs. And between large
portions _ the average meal can contain up to 4,500 calories _ and
a heavy leaning toward carbohydrates, the traditional Christmas
feast can be a boon to diners' bodies and moods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're power-packing all the nutrient supplies in your body,''
said Kathleen Zelman, a Marietta(Ga.) dietitian. ``But let it be an
occasional indulgence because along with all those nutrients, come
a lot of excess calories.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, about a third of a traditional turkey holiday
meal is made up of carbohydrates, another 30 percent in protein,
and another 35 percent in fat, Zelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbohydrates, found in the desserts, rolls and the cranberry
sauce, can raise the levels of serotonin in the brain. Serotonin is
an organic compound that at high doses gives a sense of calm and
well-being, according to Mitchell Ghen, a doctor of osteopathy at
the Atlanta Institute of Anti-Aging and Chronic Disease in
Dunwoody(Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   ``They stimulate the part of the brain that makes you feel kind
of good, kind of relaxed,'' he said. ``That's why Christmas is so
hard, because everyone is giving out the carbohydrates of the best
kind _ Godivas and the like.''
</P>
<P>
   Some historians even speculate that the rich meals in the fall
and winter were actually used as a natural buffer to the winter
blahs.
</P>
<P>
   A carbohydrate-rich, not a protein-rich, meal also increases the
level of tryptophan in the brain, making diners sleepy, according
to the National Turkey Federation. ``They often associate the
drowsiness they feel with the turkey,'' which contains tryptophan,
the federation wrote in ``The Book of Thanksgiving.'' ``To be more
accurate, they should associate their sleepy feelings with the
increased amount of carbohydrates consumed.''
</P>
<P>
   But carbohydrates aren't the only factor contributing to the
holiday mood.
</P>
<P>
   Other stimulants lead to a sense of joy; from caffeine, found in
coffee and soda, to theobromine, found in chocolate. ``All that
caffeine consumption is like putting your foot on the gas pedal and
taking it to the floor board of the car,'' said Ghen. ``It might be
fun, but in the end, it can be pretty wearing on the body.''
Theobromine, similar to caffeine in its effect, is a diuretic and a
smooth muscle relaxant.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there are those holiday staples that have been found
to make men and women more amorous.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 30 men and 50 women, the Smell &AMP; Taste Treatment
and Research Foundation in Chicago found that pumpkin pie _ for men
_ and banana bread and Good &AMP; Plenty candy _ for women _ increased
blood flow in sexual organs.
</P>
<P>
   The spice in pumpkin pie, for example, increased penile blood
flow by about 40 percent. Women's perfume, in contrast, only
affected physiological functioning by 3 percent, said Dr. Alan
Hirsch, the institute's director and author of ``Scentsational
Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch said they did the studies to find out whether odors
affected sexuality. In men, all odors caused a sexual response; but
in women, the smells were more specific. In fact, barbecued meat
and some men's colognes decreased blood flow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diners' moods aren't the only thing boosted by the holiday meal.
They're also getting a bevy of vitamins and minerals from the
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   A serving of sweet potatoes gives the average man four times the
recommended daily allowance of beta carotene, an antioxidant
considered to be a deterrent to cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberries are packed with vitamin C, as well as ellagic acid,
which boost the immune system as well as warding off certain types
of cancer. And the green leafy vegetables have compounds called
indoles, isothiocyanates and flavones that seem to give some
protection against lung and gastrointestinal cancers, according to
the ``Good Health Fact Book.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hirsch said if you want to truly have a merry Christmas, the
best recipe is ``Good &AMP; Plentys in a jar, pumpkin pie for dessert
and banana bread on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
