<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDSCAPE-DESIGNER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For landscape architect Dan Franklin, gardens happen one step at
the time
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Franklin's late getting all his pansies planted
this year. Last year, he never got all his tulip bulbs in the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   It's all because the Atlanta landscape architect stays so
swamped with work he has little time to garden. That may not seem
unusual for folks who enjoy Franklin's level of success _ unless,
of course, they're his age, 83.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great,'' he says. ``I have 45 jobs on the books right
now. Busier that I've ever been in my life. I'm kicking ass and
hope it stays that way until I drop dead. And I hope that happens
right here in my garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Meet Dan Franklin, whose tongue is as acid as the soil and as
legendary as his award-winning designs and much-visited garden.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening is what keeps him young _ that and enjoying his work,
staying active in his industry, pedaling his stationary bike 20
minutes a day and downing a few cocktails in his Collier Hills back
yard.
</P>
<P>
   There, he spent eight years developing the bones of a garden,
which Franklin knew were critical before the first daffodil could
ever be planted. He knew he needed to blend the house with the
garden (he added a glassed-in gallery for viewing the landscape),
to solve drainage problems (he laid pipes all over the back yard)
to amend the poor earth so that plants would flourish (he hauled
out three dump trucks of clay and replaced it with wheelbarrow
loads of his own recipe for compost).
</P>
<P>
   Only then did he begin to plant, carefully selecting shrubs and
perennials that would perform during different times of the year.
And Franklin's garden has never wavered from his original plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the idea _ to have a plan,'' Franklin says. ``People
waste so much damn time and money not having any idea of what they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's been planning since childhood, when an accident led
to an appreciation for homes and gardens. When he was 8, he broke
his arm so severely he was confined to an upper-body cast for three
years. ``I was so weak I couldn't play with other kids, so I helped
my mother with her gardening,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   In their Ansley Park yard, his mother grew roses and cut flowers
and his dad raised vegetables, giving Dan a basic knowledge of
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Franklin also began to admire homes being built
around town, especially those of Atlanta architect J. Neel Reid,
whom he came to know. ``He really encouraged me,'' says Franklin,
who still has a floor plan he drew at age 12 for a house featured
in a magazine photo.
</P>
<P>
   By high school, he wanted to become an architect. But because of
the Depression, Franklin was discouraged from entering the field,
so he got an economics degree at the University of Georgia. He then
worked for Royal Crown Cola for 23 years until deciding to pursue
his original career goal _ design.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Athens 25 years after graduating and in three
years earned a degree in landscape architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 40 years, Franklin would gain a reputation
throughout the Southeast for small residential designs, though he
also took on large-scale projects such as the restoration of
Barnsley Gardens and the Swan House grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people on the national level command his knowledge
and skill of small-scale design,'' says professor Allen Stovall,
development director for the University of Georgia School of
Environmental Design.
</P>
<P>
   Since hiring him to landscape her Morningside yard, Mary
Seawell's been most impressed by Franklin's ability to visualize a
design. ``He has a great eye and is so fascinating because he knows
every plant,'' she says. ``I feel honored to have him here.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin insists there's no one project he's enjoyed more than
others because he says no two are alike. ``I don't try to copy
anything. I don't want anyone to know I've been there,'' he says.
``That's what keeps it fun. And if you don't have fun in your work,
it's not worth doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, who never married, has always worked from his home,
always employing one assistant, usually an intern seeking
on-the-job training. In his attic are drawings from the hundreds of
plans he's drafted over the years _ ones he's donating to the
university's archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a warrior,'' Stovall says. ``As a frequent lecturer, he
tries to impress upon students all the opportunities there are in
residential landscape architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, who has established a scholarship in his name at the
school, is proud of how his industry has grown in only 100 years
since Frederick Law Olmstead, designer of New York's Central Park
and Atlanta's Druid Hills, established the first training course at
Harvard University. ``The environment has become so important to
people, and the landscape profession can solve so many problems
with it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the industry isn't without its challenges.
``He comes over here every few weeks raising hell about
something,'' Stovall says. ``He's cantankerous, but we love him
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest thorns in Franklin's side is people who waste
money on landscaping by not first developing a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he recommends hiring a professional to prevent costly
mistakes. ``But if you can't afford one, read a magazine or
newspaper, or attend a seminar,'' he says. ``There's plenty of free
help out there if you just ask.''
</P>
<P>
   His own garden presents quite a strong case for planning.
</P>
<P>
   The garden, featured in Southern Living magazine and PBS' ``The
Victory Garden'' series, had been in Franklin's mind for years when
he bought the house in 1984. He looked at more than 200 before
finding what he wanted _ a house that could be opened on the back
to flow into a terraced garden.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin designed a 5-foot-by-32-foot solarium across the back
so that visitors are lured into the garden upon entering the house.
Then, work began on the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin first made the lot sunnier by taking out all but three
of the lot's 35 trees. He then graded the back yard, poured the
slab for the terrace and built block walls and steps to the upper
garden. After two years, he began digging beds, but at 2 feet
encountered standing water so spent six months laying drainage
lines. The third year, Franklin set out to amend the soil, digging
out 18 inches and replacing it with a nutrient-rich mix.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth year brought a white latticed fence, cobblestone bed
edgings and a side wildflower garden filled with bulbs, ferns and
native plants. In year five, Franklin built his ``outhouse,'' a
free-standing screened and furnished room for enjoying the garden,
stuccoed the terrace walls and planted boxwoods in the corners.
Along the way he filled the beds with bulbs and perennials such as
irises, jonquils, foxglove, yarrow, daylilies and dianthus.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth year, Franklin set out zoysia grass, which he's
since replaced with fescue after the original lawn fell victim to a
garden tour that drew hundreds. And over the next two years, he
built a water garden and paved the terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin describes the design of the main garden, roughly 36
feet wide by 58 feet deep, as ``formal simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who come here seem interested in the smallness of the
place,'' he says. ``It's the perfect size because at my age I can
take care of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if there are still a few flats of pansies awaiting his
weathered hands.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is home to one of the country's largest design
communities. To suggest an architect, builder or designer for How
the Pros Live, call 404-526-5969 or send an e-mail to
dflanders(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER SNAPSHOT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vitals: Atlanta native, 83.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Activities: Member, American Society of Landscape Architects,
Southern Garden History Society, University of Georgia's Heritage
Society and Alumni Association.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dan's advice: 1) Develop a long-range plan, and don't rush to
implement it at once;
</P>
<P>
   2) Learn as much as you can about plants appropriate for your
site
</P>
<P>
   3) Don't plant anything until you amend Georgia's heavy clay
soil by digging out at least 18 inches (Franklin recommends
replacing it with Mr. Natural Complete Landscape Mix, a mix of
expanded slate, fine granite sand, coarse river sand, bark humus,
worm castings and Mr. Natural hen manure compost).
</P>
<P>
   Danny Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
