<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-MOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US GIVES NO PROMISES ON END TO BOMBING DURING RAMADAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ From the high perch of a minaret, four leaders of a
local mosque Thursday night searched the Western sky for the first
sign of the crescent moon. They did not find it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after Saudi Arabia announced that the new moon had been
sighted in that country, Iraq joined joined other Muslim nations in
ushering in Ramadan. The holy month, a time of fasting and
prayerful contemplation, was to begin at dawn Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan carries added significance here this year, as many
Iraqis believe the United States could not continue missile attacks
during the holiest period on the Muslim calendar. Indeed, they pray
it brings the end of Operation Desert Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But US officials say they have made no such promises. And two
hours after a pink-gray sunset turned to darkness Friday, the third
night of punishing air strikes and missile attacks was getting
under way with no sign of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Moselm and as an Iraqi, I would hope they would not bomb
on Ramadan,'' said Abdel Hamid, the leader of the call to prayer,
after climbing down from the spiraling stairs of the minaret at the
Takwa'a, or Fear of God, Mosque.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't trust America to live up to any promises. We can
only hope that this Ramadan, God will harshly judge America and
pour His anger out upon them,'' added Hamid.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein Aboud, 28, a chemical engineer and a leader of the
mosque, pointed to a home just across the street in the Al Adel
neighborhood that had been struck squarely with a cruise missile.
He said America was not targeting military sites, as it claimed,
but the homes of Iraqi civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The back of the house had a roughly 6-foot-diameter hole punched
through it from what Iraqi officals identified as a cruise missile.
It was guarded by Iraqi secret service and military officials
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another crusade against Iraq _ the first by Richard
the Lion Heart and this time by Bill The Liar,'' said Aboud,
referring to the British leader of the bloody 12th Century
Christian Crusades against the Arabs to President Bill Clinton and
the perjury scandal that threatens his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   For many Iraqis and Muslims throughout the Arab world, the US
and British bombing campaign is cast in religious terms, because of
its proximity to Ramadan. Many seem to see the attacks as a kind of
``clash of civilizations'' between the Muslim East and the
Christian West, backed by the Zionists of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clash of civilizations,'' a phrase coined by Harvard
historian Samuel Huntington, refers to the global phenomenon of
modern conflict defining itself in religious terms. The idea has
currency in the region, heard not just in academic circles but
among taxi drivers and hotel doormen in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   With a good ear for the cresting religion-based anger among
Muslims, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein included heavy religious
imagery in a brief, taped message Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the third day of enlightened days. We are not afraid
of anyone other than God. Cursed be the evil followers. America is
evil and so are the Zionist entity,'' said Hussein, who has built
his dictatorship on solidly secular Baath Party power, but who
recently has embraced a more religious tenor in his speeches of
defiance against the West.
</P>
<P>
   The same tone came from Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz,
who belongs to the small Christian minority in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about a recent statement by Pope John Paul expressing
sadness at the ``aggression'' of the US-British attacks on Iraq,
Aziz said, ``Frankly, those committing the aggression are Christian
in name and Zionist in their practices. There is no bond beyond the
Iraqi people and these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz repeatedly referred to Clinton's ``Zionist clique'' of
advisers, making specific references to Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, National Security Adviser Samuel R. Berger, and
Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Within the haze of religious symbolism, the four men who stood
in the Takwa'a Mosque Friday could not see the crescent moon
because it was obscured by a layer of low clouds. But the Saudi
royal palace announced its sighting.
</P>
<P>
   Under Islam, Ramadan marks God's revelation of the Koran,
Islam's holy book, to the Prophet Mohammed some 1,400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia, home of Islam's holiest shrines in Mecca and
Medina and a pillar of the US-led coalition against Iraq in 1991,
was the first Muslim country to announce that Saturday will mark
the start of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf nations generally follow the kingdom's lead on the start of
Ramadan, but most other places in the Islamic world make their own
determinations. This year, under attack, Iraq decided to follow the
Saudi palace's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   So Friday night the Religious Ministry here carried out the
tradition of firing cannons to mark the start of Ramadan, and the
Iraqi people hoped that the arrival of dawn would mean the end of
the bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
