<HEADLINE>
U.N. RELIEF WORKERS FLEE BAGHDAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAQ-RDP, IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-RUSSIA, IRAQ-INSPECT,
IRAQ-WESTBANK, IRAQ-VIDEO-GAME, IRAQ-SOLDIERS, IRAQ-BOMBER.) (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ More than 100 U.N. relief workers left Baghdad
early Friday after two nights of bombing raids made their situation
precarious, officials said here.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement from the office of the Iraqi program that
oversees all nondisarmament work said 106 people had gone by road
to Jordan, leaving behind fewer than 30 essential officials,
including Prakash Shah, the secretary- general's special envoy, and
Hans von Sponeck, the relief aid coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 232 foreign relief workers will remain in the
autonomous Kurdish areas of northern Iraq, where they are
considered relatively safe.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Friday also said that oil exports were
continuing uninterrupted through the port of Mina al Bakr, but that
the absence of border inspectors checking goods purchased through
the ``oil for food'' program would mean interruptions in incoming
deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The border inspectors, who work for the private British customs
service, Lloyds Register of Shipping, were withdrawn from most
crossing points and the port of Umm Qasr on Wednesday, before the
bombing began.
</P>
</TEXT>
