<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV20-B     12-18 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAWNS FROM THE SNAKEPIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know. Can't figure this out. Thinking of turning in my
punditry merit badge. Can't get a grip.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm not used to getting things wrong. I never would
have believed that you could buy a gallon of gas at 93.9 cents per
gallon at the end of 1998. That gasoline would be cheaper than
bottled war. In the week that the House voted on impeaching the
president. While there was a war on in the Middle East. With the
stock market going up two days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. I can't anymore. Beats me.
</P>
<P>
   For something the TV people kept hyping as the ``high drama'' of
``this historic moment,'' the Impeachment Show was oddly flat.
Maybe we've been spoiled by the entertainment culture. It's hard
for a windy legislative body to compete with Cruise missiles coming
down live on Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the congressmen are held to too high a standard. Could we
be accustomed to 500 channels of world-class entertainers, highly
attractive and articulate folk, and that mere run-of-the-mill
politicoes look like sadsacks by comparison?
</P>
<P>
   Watching your House of Representatives in action is a task
requiring an effort to focus, the kind of effort required when
tuning in to ``your dental hygenist in action,'' ``your automatic
transmission specialist in action,'' or ``your sous chef at work on
the head of lettuce.'' I've seen Norm Abrams, TV's ``Yankee
Workshop'' carpenter, get more eloquent over a straight and true
length of quarter-sawn red oak.
</P>
<P>
   The officeholders weren't in their seats. Nor were the
spectators clamoring for admission to the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Led into battle by two confessed adulturers, the House
Republicans coalesced behind a very simple idea: we can get this
guy! If you voted for Clinton in '92 or '96, you might challenge
this sort of Rolling Coup to Reverse '92.
</P>
<P>
   As the Globe's White House correspondent when Richard Nixon's
fingernails were screeching down the Oval Office blackboard in '74,
I went to Tip O'Neill, the Democrats' Majority Leader during that
impeachment, to check on rumors that Nixon was going to pull some
kind of national security stunt. I asked: Would Nixon or his
hard-line intimates manufacture some kind of crisis _ foreign or
domestic _ to derail the impeachment freight train then bearing
down on him?
</P>
<P>
   With a wave of his great friendly paw, O'Neill cheerfully
scoffed at my fears. Naw, he said; the sensible people in both
parties would never let that happen. ``This is no banana
republic,'' he concluded with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years later, Banana Republic is a garment chain,
O'Neill is dead; and his successor, Joe Kennedy, gave his final
speech Friday decrying the Congress's lack of concern with the poor
and the left-behind in its obsession with Clinton's sexual affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Tip O'Neill would be heartsick at the conduct of the House that
expires in two weeks. The Republicans are in the saddle _ but only
barely. Their leadership was repudiated in the November election,
where they lost some of their majority. Newt Gingrich rolled the
dice for 10 million bucks worth of anti-Clinton Monica ads, and
wound up repudiated himself by his own members.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was dumped in favor of Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.), but
Livingston's reign may be perilously short. He may be undone in
turn by his Impeachment-eve confession that he, too, like Judiciary
Chairman Henry Hyde, has been unfaithful to his wife. So far this
year four Republican House members have been unmasked as
adulturers. The Scarlet Letter keeps turning up in Washington like
a bad penny.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone believe that only four of the 220-plus Republicans
engaged in the same sort of immorality that brought Clinton low?
</P>
<P>
   In the sulfurous snakepit that the House became under Gingrich's
cruel reign, comity, amity and consideration evaporated. Both
parties have adopted the fang-and-claw style Gingrich introduced.
After Nixon's resignation, strong bonds of personal friendship and
mutual regard helped leaders like O'Neill and Gerald Ford bind up
the partisan wounds and heal the riven government. That atmosphere
no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill always kept a weather eye turned to the geographical
balance in Congress. For decades, there was a ``Boston-Austin''
axis, balancing regional and ideological differences, knitting
together a vast and disparate country of fiercely competing
rivalries. But the Republican Revolution of 1994 which brought
Gingrich to power tipped all the power in the House south and west,
to the Sunbelt.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans from the north and east withstood
considerable pressure from their leadership to oppose impeachment.
But the vast majority of the majority marched in lockstep in
support of the creeping coup.
</P>
<P>
   The polls show most Americans didn't approve of what was being
done, by Hyde and his henchpersons had the gavel, and that's all
they needed to control the debate, and choke off the censure
proposal that might have spared Clinton the ignominy of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   By throttling the censure motion in its legislative cradle, the
Republicans made and up-or-down impeachment vote the first order of
business. They ignored the argument that ``you have blood on your
hands'' for trying to decapitate the administration in the midst of
a shooting war.
</P>
<P>
   For those Americans who did not like what was being done, the
chance for revenge will not come till year after next, when these
representatives and their Republican colleagues at other levels
come back before the voters. Can you remember then how you feel
now? On that will depend the custody of the Congress and the White
House. Unless I'm figuring it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
