<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS &LR;      12-18 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLARS DIFFER WITH LAWMAKERS OVER USE OF IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was among the most incendiary statements of the House
Judiciary Committee's ever-fiery impeachment hearings: Sean
Wilentz, a historian at Princeton University, warned that ``history
will track . . . down and condemn'' those lawmakers who vote to
evict President Clinton from the Oval Office, but don't really
believe he should or will be ousted.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans angrily rejected that prediction as an unfair,
partisan attack on their motives. Its accusatory tone
notwithstanding, Wilentz's assessment of the constitutional intent
of impeachment seems to reflect the consensus of legal scholars,
political scientists and historians, regardless of their opinions
on the merits of the debate that began in the House Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment was designed as a device for removal and not for
punishment, the scholars agreed, but they said some House members
seem intent on using it as ``censure-plus'' or ``supercensure.''
They added that impeachment wasn't meant to be a vehicle for
legislators to demonstrate party loyalty or to express disapproval
of a president's behavior, yet some legislators appear to be
employing it in those ways _ believing their votes are ``safe''
because the Senate won't convict.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they vote for this, they should do so only because they
think he should be tossed out and think the Senate will finish the
job,'' said Hans Trefousse, a professor emeritus at Brooklyn
College who has written books about Andrew Johnson, the only US
president to be impeached. Trefousse argued strenuously that, based
on his study of Johnson's case and of deliberations by the
Constitution's authors, House Republicans are misreading their
authority in trying to oust Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a congressman, I should think I'd need to believe
there has to be enough there to actually remove him from office . .
. and not just punish him,'' added Robert Bork, the conservative
Supreme Court nominee who is now a scholar at the American
Enterprise Institute in Washington. Bork added that, based on an
``overabundance'' of evidence, he favors the president's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Whether to make Clinton the first president to be thrown out of
the White House is obviously at the core of the historic decision
Congress must make when it deliberates his fate. Since only the
Senate ultimately decides whether the president stays or goes,
however, the question of intent _ whether those voting truly want
him out or are casting their pro-impeachment ballots for some other
reason _ applies uniquely to the House.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear to weigh most heavily on those members,
predominantly Republicans, who have yet to announce their
intentions. But the scholars said it also should be considered by
lawmakers who, whatever their public pronouncements, planned to
approve articles of impeachment principally because they weren't
being offered a censure option and believed the Democrats' strength
in the Senate would prevent a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one thing for the House of Representatives to say, in
good conscience, that the Senate vote is not in stone,'' said
Jeffrey Abramson, who teaches politics and constitutional law at
Brandeis University. ``What is constitutionally out of bounds is
for members to say, in a stage whisper, that we don't even want the
Senate to remove this president; all we want to do is use
impeachment as censure-plus . . . with no expectation or even
desire for the president to be removed. That, I think, is a
violation of the spirit of the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed agreed on another key point: that it was
unfortunate, at a minimum, that the sentiment on impeachment is so
starkly divided along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Some said the main result of that split is to increase public
cynicism by reinforcing a perception that the process is based
solely on partisanship _ a view that conservatives, including Bork
and Duke constitutional law professor William Van Alstyne,
dismissed as incorrect. ``Any tangential negative effect is
unfortunate . . . but the only test is whether the aggregate
misconduct of the accused is such as to render this person unfit to
continue in office,'' said Van Alstyne.
</P>
<P>
   Others saw the chasm as having more significance. They said it
not only showed a Republican Party intent on deposing an elected
leader, but also provides evidence that impeachment has been
whittled down into a political tool _ a usage they said the
Constitution's framers had sought to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who will preside
over any Senate impeachment trial, wrote a book on impeachment in
which he agreed, at least in concept, with the notion that
partisanship undermines the process.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the impeachment trials of Andrew Johnson in 1868 and
of Supreme Court Justice Samuel Chase in 1805, Rehnquist said their
critics' motives were so overtly political that convictions would
have cast ``a long shadow . . . over the independence of the
judiciary and the president.'' He added in his 1992 book, ``Grand
Inquests,'' that impeachment successfully used in this way would
have turned the constitutional remedy into ``a sword of Damocles,
designed not to fall but to hang.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Carter, a law professor at Yale University who has used
the book in his classes, said Rehnquist's point is essentially that
``if two parties are duking it out, it's a power struggle rather
than a decision about right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was alone among those interviewed to assert that the
Constitution's authors didn't have a firm view of what actions
constitute an impeachable offense. He said that House Republicans
therefore can reasonably decide that Clinton had committed ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   He nevertheless criticized them for doing so, saying they were
acting with the strong belief that the president probably will keep
his job. ``I'm not sure, historically, that we've ever had a
situation where members voted on impeachment while believing the
chances for success were so small,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Tribe, the constitutional scholar and professor at
Harvard Law School, suggested some Republicans were misled by their
leaders into believing it was acceptable to vote for impeachment
essentially as a means of chastizing Clinton and then passing the
controversial issue to the Senate for a fuller investigation. That
sort of maneuver, Tribe and several others argued, is far from what
the Constitution's framers intended and could lead to undesired,
unpredictable repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should understand that the effect of voting to impeach is
not simply to authorize further inquiry,'' said Tribe. ``It
certainly does impose a permanent brand for all time . . . but it
also opens up the process of a protracted and potentially
paralyzing trial in the Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1841EST &QL; 
