<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY APPEALS FOR RECONCILIATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Breaking her public silence, first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton appealed Friday for reconciliation as Congress
opened debate on articles of impeachment against her husband and
White House aides fought back with broadsides at Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A strange atmosphere gripped the White House _ its cheerful
Christmas decorations belying the turmoil inside. President Clinton
remained out of public view as he dealt for a third day with the
U.S.-British military mission against Iraq. Some aides worked to
stem the Republican tide against Clinton in the House and others
went about their daily chores.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillary Clinton provided the surprise of the day, ending the
silence she has maintained since January when she initially
defended her husband against accusations of his infidelity only to
learn later they were true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the vast majority of Americans share my approval and
pride in the job that the president's been doing for our country,''
the first lady said, standing at the White House South Portico with
the Capitol dome visible behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in this holiday season, as we celebrate Christmas and
Hanukkah and Ramadan _ and at the time for reflection and
reconciliation among people _ we in our country ought to practice
reconciliation, and we ought to bring our country together. We
ought to end the divisiveness because we can do so much more
together,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She answered a reporter's question following an event promoting
Mothers Against Drunk Drivers' ``red ribbon'' campaign. She walked
away after answering the first question.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, her spokeswoman, confirmed the first lady has been
talking to House members about the impeachment issue. Berry said
the first lady spoke to members traveling with the president to the
Middle East and has been making telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman, offered a terse
assessment of the Republican strategy, not just on Capitol Hill but
within the national Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about politics and all about cynicism,'' Lockhart
told reporters in his morning briefing. ``What you see especially
in the last few days is a shift in what has been a very cynical
political strategy by the Republican leadership of the House from
impeachment to a building drumbeat to force the president to leave
office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lockhart stopped short of using the word ``coup d'etat''
that many of Clinton's supporters used during debate. ``I have not
used that word,'' Lockhart said, but he suggested House Republican
leaders deliberately engaged in a strategy to initially downplay
the importance of an impeachment vote. He quoted several members
saying the House action was similar to a grand jury and that the
Senate would be the place where Clinton would have a chance to
defend himself in a trial.
</P>
<P>
   But step two, Lockhart alleged, began last week with Republican
leaders demanding that Clinton resign if he is impeached by the
House, short-circuiting Senate action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm discussing a strategy where a conscious effort was made
to, in effect, dumb down impeachment, to dumb down and say the
process wasn't important, that the real action was someplace else,
and then, having gone through it, turn 180 degrees in the other
direction and say, `it's so important to this country and it's so
damaging that the president should resign,''' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also pointed to messages sent from the Republican
National Party and the Christian Coalition to more than 200
newspapers urging a call for Clinton's resignation in editorials.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman maintained that Clinton had little time Friday to
view the televised House debate. He said Clinton also had done
``very little'' to lobby House members. He made a couple of calls,
which Lockhart refused to detail, and he met with Rep. Christopher
Shays, the moderate Republican from Connecticut rumored to be
rethinking his opposition to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides had suspended their lobbying of members when
the United States launched ``Operation Desert Fox'' against Iraq.
The military action resulted in a one-day delay of the impeachment
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton kept his daily schedule, attending the MADD event,
meeting with European Union officials and consulting with his
HIV/AIDS Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very serious time, but the work goes on,'' said Richard
Socarides, a senior aide preparing to brief the president on the
HIV/AIDS Council session. ``I think the overall mood is one of
seriousness, one of some disbelief. I think people are starting to
realize more and more that this isn't really any longer about the
president's inappropriate conduct but really about whose political
agenda will succeed and survive in the coming months.''
</P>
<P>
   Socarides said Clinton's personal appearance at a senior staff
meeting Thursday bolstered staff morale. The president urged the
staff to continue the work they were doing despite the actions in
the House. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
