<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNCIVIL ACTION IN AN UNCIVIL TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chaplain quoted St. Francis of Assisi, bidding
the lawmakers to sow love where there was hatred. The presiding
officer beseeched speakers to avoid ``personally abusive'' comments
about the president of the United States or other members of the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the appeals from the chaplain and the chair, for all
the talk about the legacy of Roman law and the lessons of the Magna
Carta, for all the allusions to the American founders and to
Americans yet unborn, Friday's remarkable House impeachment debate
served mostly to underline how uncivil American civil life has
become.
</P>
<P>
   If the House votes by midday Saturday, as expected, to impeach
President Clinton, it will be making an indelible mark on the
president and on history. But this moment _ coming amid the most
bitter partisan discourse since Reconstruction _ is also a marker
in America's political passage.
</P>
<P>
   Every element of the following sentence would have been
inconceivable only a decade ago: The House of Representatives met
in a lame-duck session a week before Christmas, prepared to impeach
the president on a party-line basis for having an affair with a
one-time intern in the Oval Office suite and then conspiring to lie
about it.
</P>
<P>
   And though major debates over the size and role of government
and the place of the United States in world affairs have raged for
two decades, modern politics more than ever is about trust and
truth and how the men and women who fill our political life do not
fulfill our expectations. ``The people's trust has been betrayed,''
House Judiciary Committee chairman Henry J. Hyde of Illinois said
Friday as he opened the impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   The road to this moment was paved by distrust and suspicion,
some of it rooted in Watergate, some of it reflecting cultural
changes in American institutions, some of it growing out of
evolving views of authority. But a body that for more than two
centuries has prided itself on being the ``people's House'' now
represents all the people's resentments under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   And though the discussion in the House chamber Friday was about
perjury and obfuscation and the rule of law, the dozen hours of
debate provided a portrait of an institution and a nation suddenly
bereft of the old rules, the old assumptions, the old folkways,
and, most of all, the old courtesies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now at the height of a cycle of negative attack,
character assassination, personal smears of good people, decent
people, worthy people,'' House minority leader Richard A. Gephardt
of Missouri said as the impeachment debate began. Representative
Diana DeGette, a freshman Democrat from Colorado accustomed to
being neither seen nor heard, put it crisply: ``Decency and
civility have been sacrificed.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't only Democrats, defending a president who has been
subject to constant attacks and whose private life invited even
more, who were complaining of the raw meanness in political
discourse. House majority leader Richard K. Armey of Texas, citing
``quite caustic and harsh characterizations of the motives of the
members,'' warned lawmakers that unless they showed respect for one
another, the proceedings would have to be interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   There have been flashes of passion and anger in Congress before,
of course. In 1798, Roger Griswold, a Federalist from Connecticut,
attacked Matthew Lyon, a Republican from Vermont, with his cane,
only to have to stave off Lyon's attack with fire tongs. In 1856,
Representative Preston Brooks of South Carolina stormed into the
Senate and beat Senator Charles Sumner of Massachusetts so
viciously that Sumner was unable to return to Capitol Hill for four
years.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than a century, comity _ a word seldom used outside
Capitol Hill, where for generations it was used with reverence and
pride _ prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Then 40 years of Democratic rule in the House begat resentments
that Representative Newt Gingrich of Georgia harnessed, an action
that in turn begat the attacks that drove House Speaker James C.
Wright Jr. from office, which in turn begat a new era of new
resentments.
</P>
<P>
   All these pent-up passions and resentments were on full display
on nine television networks Friday, reinforced by the latest furor,
the admission of Speaker-designate Robert L. Livingston of
Louisiana that he had not been faithful to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only word that comes to mind,'' said Representative Maxine
Waters, a California Democrat, ``is `hypocrite.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the bitter harvest of all the resentments. ``It's a
day,'' said Fred Zuercher, a political scientist at the University
of South Dakota, ``that will live in infamy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
