<HEADLINE>
MUSLIM HOLY MONTH BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ramadan, the holy month of dawn-to-dusk fasting in the Islamic
calendar, begins this weekend for Muslims around the world. Its
start depends on the sighting of the new crescent moon.
</P>
<P>
   Because the U.S.-led attacks on Iraq have taken place just
before the holy month, some Muslims have been particularly
incensed. Though President Clinton said on Wednesday when the
attacks began that ``to initiate military action during Ramadan
would be profoundly offensive to the Muslim world,'' Washington has
suggested that the attacks may continue into Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 30 days, Muslims are enjoined from eating, drinking
and sensual pleasures like sexual activity, during daylight hours.
On a spiritual level, the ritual fast is a sacrificial act that
points to purification and renewal. It is accompanied by close
study of the Koran, the Islamic holy book, which the faith teaches
was revealed by God to the prophet Mohammed during the last days of
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   Observance of the fast is one of Islam's Five Pillars, the
foundational rules of the faith. The daily abstention from food is
broken after sundown with an evening meal.
</P>
<P>
   In Saudi Arabia, officials announced the sighting of the new
moon on Friday night, signaling that observance of Ramadan would
begin there on Saturday. According to news reports, the lunar month
will also begin Saturday in Iraq, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait,
Bahrain and Qatar. But Egypt and the south Arabian nation of Oman
will begin observance of Ramadan on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
