<SLUG> BC-MA-JOBLESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY HIRING KEEPS JOBLESS RATE DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Holiday hiring by retail stores helped push the number
of unemployed people in Massachusetts to lows not seen since the
economic boom of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The state Division of Employment and Training in its November
report said Friday the jobless rate fell by a half percentage
point, to 2.9 percent. The number of unemployed fell to an 11-year
low of 95,700 last month as the holiday season got under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``News could not be better for our working families during this
holiday season,'' Gov. Paul Cellucci said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   The state's jobless rate is now 1.5 percentage points below the
US jobless rate of 4.4 percent. Further, the national recession
that had been widely predicted last summer _ because of economic
contraction abroad, financial-market turmoil at home, and a sharp
slowdown in US manufacturing _ is becoming remote, though not
impossible, for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs report ``is a very welcome development,'' said Richard
DeKaser, senior economist for BankBoston Corp. But, he added, ``it
would be hasty to conclude the state is not on a slowing
trajectory.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, business, engineering, and management services
continued to be the biggest creator of jobs, adding 3,000 jobs
during the month, the state said.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when the labor force is already critically short
of skilled workers, stronger-than-average hiring by retail stores
preparing for the holidays also fueled an unusually sharp,
one-month decline in the unemployment rate. Retailers added 1,800
jobs last month.
</P>
<P>
   Economists two months ago were predicting job growth in
Massachusetts would slow by half next year, to less than 1 percent.
But with unemployment so low, there is now a danger a slowdown
would be triggered by the constraints of an extremely tight labor
market. If companies can't hire, they are unable to complete orders
or provide customer service.
</P>
<P>
   This presents ``a dilemma for the state economy,'' DeKaser said.
``Labor force restrictions are _ arguably at the present are _ a
binding constraint on future expansion activity,'' suggesting a
``return to past rates of growth is highly unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers in Massachusetts continued to shed jobs _ 2,000 _
in November, amid softness in exports. But while high-tech
manufacturing employment has shrunk over the past year,
non-manufacturers in high tech have more than made up for the tech
industry's losses, adding nearly 10,000 jobs in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The second-biggest area of job growth, after services, was
construction, which is enjoying mild weather. Construction
companies added 2,500 jobs last month.
</P>
<P>
   Construction was followed by 2,300 new jobs in the retail- and
wholesale-trade sector, and 1,000 jobs in the financial and real
estate sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
