<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7558 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGSTON-REAX-HNS &LR;      12-18 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON-REAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS AND DEMOCRATS FEAR POLITICS OF SMEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans insisted Friday that there was no
similarity between House Speaker-designate Bob Livingston's
confessed adultery and the legal problems that have brought
President Clinton to the brink of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Retiring Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., chairman of the House
Rules Committee, maintained there was ``absolutely no connection''
between Livingston's adultery and Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This impeachment procedure is not about sex,'' Solomon said.
``It is about obstruction of justice, perjury and abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Two leading Democrats, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt,
D-Mo., and Rep. Charles. E. Schumer, D-N.Y., decried the toxic
atmosphere in the House as the lawmakers began debating four
articles of impeachment against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt drew a standing ovation from both Republicans and
Democrats, a rare sight these days, when he made an impassioned
plea for a truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now at the height of a cycle of the politics of
negative attacks, character assassination, personal smears of good
people, decent people, worthy people,'' Gephardt said. ``It's no
wonder to me and to you that the people of this country are cynical
and indifferent and apathetic about our government and about our
country. The politics of smear and slash and burn must end.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who moves to the Senate next month, complained that
normal political disagreements have escalated into vicious personal
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot forcefully advocate our positions without trying to
criminalize or at least dishonor our adversaries,'' Schumer
lamented. ``We are routinely using criminal accusations and scandal
to win the political battles and ideological differences we cannot
settle at the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston admitted to his fellow Republicans Thursday night
that he had ``strayed'' several times during the course of his
33-year marriage. Livingston reminded his colleagues that he was
running for speaker, ``not for sainthood'' in the new Congress that
convenes next month.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's acknowledgement of adultery _ triggered by imminent
news media disclosure _ was the talk of the hallways of the House,
though not on the House floor. Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., who
presided in the speaker's chair during the debate, warned members
that ``proper decorum'' prohibited them from referring to
``personal misconduct on the part of the president'' or to make
comparisons to personal conduct of sitting House members.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Livingston steered clear of reporters and spent much
of the time pacing in the back of the House floor as the
impeachment debate continued. He was frequently surrounded by
Republican members who patted him on the back and shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   But members had plenty to say about the adultery issue off the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., a member of the House Judiciary
Committee who supports Clinton's impeachment, said he saw a big
distinction between Clinton and Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about criminal misconduct _ tramping on legal
systems as opposed to private misconduct,'' Graham said. He also
predicted that Livingston's martial indiscretions won't jeopardize
the likelihood that Livingston will be elected speaker when the new
Congress convenes next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't say `Bob, you can't be speaker because you violated
your vows with your wife,''' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Edward Porter, R-Ill., said Clinton, as the chief law
enforcement officer, was different from Livingston because the
president undermined the justice system by lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about human frailties,'' Porter said. ``All
of us have human frailties. We're talking about covering them up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said Livingston's confession of
adultery pointed out hypocrisy on the part of Republicans and will
make it more difficult for Clinton's political opponents to
criticize the president for moral shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indignation factor and the moral superiority factor
diminish some'' in light of Livingston's acknowledgement, Frank
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II, D-Mass., said Livingston's confession
``just heightens and highlights the dual standard'' of the
Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the witch hunt for the sexual infractions of
government officials will continue ``unless we stop talking about
morality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We isolate sex _ that's the one bad thing,'' Kennedy said.
``This is just hogwash... When you start down the path of morality
in this place, you better be on your best behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's admission follows that of a parade of lawmakers who
have been forced to divulge marital indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J.
Hyde of Illinois, admitted to an extramarital affair in his past,
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., a constant critic of Clinton, acknowledged
that he had a child out of wedlock years ago. Rep. Helen Chenoweth,
R-Idaho, also admitted to a sexual relationship with a married man
when she was unmarried.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
