<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7559 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-MURPHY-BOS &LR;      12-18 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MURPHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY MAKES THE DIFFERENCE FOR THE WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The time is embedded in Scotty Bowman's memory. It was
the NHL trade deadline, March 18, 1997, and it appeared the
afternoon would pass quietly, unceremoniously, for a team that
didn't appear to need much help in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting right here, and the phone rang at 10 minutes to
2,'' recalled Bowman, sitting in his office at Joe Louis Arena
earlier this week, pinpointing the very minute that the Red Wings
took one giant step toward their first Stanley Cup in 45 years.
``It was Cliff Fletcher. And he said, `Look, we're dumping salaries
up here. Do you want Larry Murphy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hold on, Bowman told the then Maple Leafs general manager.
Bowman didn't have to be convinced of Murphy's value, how he would
enhance an already impressive blue line, but he would have to run
the numbers by Red Wings owner Mike Ilitch.
</P>
<P>
   The coach hung up the phone, jerked it back up, called Ilitch,
and went into a short dissertation on blue line vs. bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line was this: It came down to an $800,000
gamble,'' said Bowman. ``He had another year left on his deal at
around $1.8 million. But the Leafs were putting in some money, and
the way his deal was written, we could have bought out the final
year at $800,000. That was it _ $800,000.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Ilitch, never tightfisted when it comes to his hockey
team, said something like this: ``So, Scotty, why are you
calling?''
</P>
<P>
   Deal done.
</P>
<P>
   ``And by the end of the season,'' said Bowman, ``we'd re-signed
him for another two or three years. When you look at it, the whole
thing was very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, now 37, also earned his third Stanley Cup ring only some
10 weeks after arriving in Detroit. A year later, he had his
fourth. Is he the reason the Wings, in Boston to face the Bruins
Saturday night, are two-time defending Cup champs? Not entirely.
But for what now seems a ridiculously cheap, virtually no-risk
gamble, the Wings added a significant piece of experience and
stability to a back line that might not have withstood the grueling
pressures of playoff hockey without him.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Detroit has been a perfect fit for Murphy. At
most, Hockeytown might not be on the map without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know, I think it's a case of the rising tide lifts
all ships,'' said Murphy, who Wednesday night rammed home a
power-play goal, the 269th strike of his career, to help the Wings
rub out the Bruins, 5-3, in Detroit. ``I've seen that consistently
through my career. A good team makes everyone better.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit No. 1 in Murphy's career, of course, was Pittsburgh, the
fourth stop on his meandering itinerary. He came to the Penguins in
December 1990, in the heart of Mario Lemieux's prime and just as
Jaromir Jagr arrived, and within six months, Pittsburgh had its
first Cup. A year later, it had No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone picking up the theme here? Twice in Murphy's career, some
very good things have happenend to some very good teams when he
arrived in town. In the '90s, he's become the game's Cup closer. He
has won more Cup rings this decade than any other player. Not the
greatest skater, not the biggest hitter, not in possession of the
hardest shot, Murphy has spent nearly 20 years being vastly
overlooked and undervalued in the NHL, and all he'll have in the
end is at least four Cups and a polished plate in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe to the press and to the people outside the game, he's
been overlooked,'' said Bruins captain Ray Bourque, who began his
career in Boston in the fall of 1979, only 12 months before Murphy
launched his career in Los Angeles. ``But the guys who've played
with him and against him know what he's accomplished. You don't
keep putting up the numbers he's put up, doing the job he's done
all these years, without being a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Headed into Friday night's action, Murphy led all NHL defensemen
in scoring this season (4-19_23) and had 1,126 career points,
ranking third on the all-time list among defensemen and 36th
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's even more remarkable this year,'' said Bowman, ``is
that he's leading the list and I don't even have him on my first
power-play unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's goal against the Bruins came on the man advantage, the
veteran cheating down low from the right point and roofing a relay
to the top shelf as he approached the inner edge of the right
faceoff circle. It took a blend of timing and touch, two of
Murphy's strongest suits.
</P>
<P>
   These are the twilight years for some great NHL defensemen, a
group that could be considered, collectively, the best ever to work
the blue line: Paul Coffey, Al MacInnis, Scott Stevens, Chris
Chelios, Bourque, and Murphy. Coffey was the sweetest skater in the
bunch. MacInnis had the hardest shot. Stevens had the rage,
especially in his earlier years, and the strength. Chelios had the
snarl, the switchblade attitude. Bourque had the best package, the
blend of power and finesse, offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   What has Murphy had? A lot of all those things, but no single
distinguishing trait, a bunch of 8's, 9's, and 9.5's on a scale of
10. The critics _ especially a tough Capitals home crowd that
mocked his skating in his five-plus years with Washington _ pointed
to his lack of jump and speed. But his longevity has shown that
moderate speed, blended with positioning and savvy, often can win
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed is definitely not my game,'' said Murphy, who recalls
being branded slow when he was 5 years old and finished in the back
of the pack in a race around his hometown rink. ``But the key on
defense is that you've got to move laterally, and I can skate
laterally with anybody. If a guy outskates me, that's unacceptable,
because I should never put myself in a position where a guy can
outskate me.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Murphy is paired mostly with Nicklas Lidstrom, the
hard-shooting Swede who is far less likely to jump into the play
than the more mobile Murphy. When at their best, the Wings play the
most uptempo game in the NHL, attacking with four lines that cannot
be matched for quality or depth. Murphy is right about the rising
tide. It is a very talented squad, but one enhanced by his ability
to orchestrate play when he's on the ice. He has that Brad
Park-like sense and skill to skate into the action, move to exactly
the right spot, and make it look like his freeze frame is doing
more than everyone else's fast forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say that it's never been a situation in my career
where accolades have been heaped upon me,'' said Murphy. ``I've
always taken pride in doing my job, satisfied that I've done it
effectively and to the best of my ability. There's no real flash
involved, I guess. I don't shoot 100 miles an hour. I don't skate
100 miles an hour. I don't run anyone through the boards. The truth
is, it's a real kick for me, an honor, whenever I'm even mentioned
in the same breath as some of the great defensemen.''
</P>
<P>
   If he has been overlooked, said teammate Brendan Shanahan,
perhaps it has been because of the teams he's played for, the
cities in which he's played. The Kings were woeful, the Caps ever
looking for an identity. The North Stars were laughable. Pittsburgh
was a great team but hardly a media mecca. And then of course,
there was Toronto, where Murphy took the brunt of the fans' ire, a
homeboy who got lynched by the locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he was going there to finish his career,'' said
Shanahan, ``but it didn't work out like that. You get out of a
situation like that, it's like you're a rookie all over again.
Sure, he's been overshadowed, but look at his career: He gets the
Cups, he gets the points. The truth is, he's one of the best
defensemen ever to play in the NHL.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
