<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS &LR;      12-18 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS AN UNDERDOG WITH POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ University of Massachusetts football coach
Mark Whipple ran into Georgia Southern coach Paul Johnson outside
the press conference room Thursday, and they congratulated one
another for making it to Saturday's 2 p.m. NCAA Division 1-AA title
game.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the coaches was prepared to receive such praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not where you guys are,'' said Whipple, the first-year
coach whose team has rebounded from a 2-9 debacle last season to
advance to its second championship game in school history while
posting an 11-3 record. He was alluding to the fact that Georgia
Southern is 14-0, ranked No. 1 in the nation, and seeking its fifth
national title.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson paused after Whipple's comments, then gazed at his
surroundings. ``Yes, you are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Southern coach is correct. Both teams have earned
their way to east Tennessee, having overcome obstacles in the
regular season and playoffs. And though Georgia Southern is favored
Saturday, Johnson knows UMass is capable of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure (UMass) would like to lull everyone into thinking
that they're the underdog and they have no business being here,''
said Johnson. ``But I tell you for one, we're not going to fall for
that. We've watched them play and we know they have a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson knows this is a most intriguing final, a contrast in
styles. Both teams feature high-powered, record-setting offenses
that average more than 400 yards a game, but UMass is primarily a
passing team. Georgia Southern runs the first option offense the
Minutemen will have faced this season, although Atlantic 10 foe
Delaware, which beat the Minutemen, 33-30, in the season opener,
runs a variation of it with its Wing-T.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern's attack has set 49 offensive records,
including 11 national 1-AA marks. It finished the regular season
ranked second in the nation in rushing (378.7 yards a game) and has
scored 69 of its 82 touchdowns on the ground. The Eagles reached
the final with a 42-14 victory over Western Illinois, which boasted
the top-ranked defense in 1-AA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia Southern can run, they have great speed, and they're
well coached,'' said Whipple, who should be familiar with the
option _ he ran the offense as a quarterback at Brown. ``They don't
have any weaknesses. We have to play close to a perfect game in
order to win.''
</P>
<P>
   While the option might cause some problems for the Minutemen, it
could also be seen as a UMass advantage because it is
rush-oriented. Delaware is the only rush-oriented team to beat
UMass this season. All the others, including favored postseason
foes McNeese State and Northwestern (La.) State, lost in part
because they were forced to pass more than normal just to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys to the contest will be whether the UMass defense
can contain an offense that wears down opponents in the second
half. Georgia Southern has scored at least three touchdowns in the
second half of each of its three postseason contests while holding
its opponents to a total of 19 second-half points.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles are led by quarterback Greg Hill, a decent passer (90
of 150, 1,527 yards, 10 touchdowns, 7 interceptions) who is the
team's No. 2 rusher (262 carries, 1,359 yards, 22 TDs). Freshman
fullback Adrian Peterson (337 carries, 2,445 yards, 32 TDs) is
arguably the best rusher the Minutemen have faced since New
Hampshire's Jerry Azumah, the 1-AA player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the speed of UMass's linebackers will help against
Georgia Southern, Whipple said, ``From what I've seen on film, I've
seen Colgate (Georgia Southern's first-round opponent) get close to
them and I've seen UConn (the Eagles' second-round opponent) get
close with their linebacker play.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's no doubt (UMass linebacker) Kole Ayi has to play
tremendous. Khari Samuel has to stop the middle, and Matt Dawson
has to be in the right position, and those guys have to make
tackles on the perimeter. Their offense forces you into so many
one-on-one situations where their athletes are better than the
other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple makes no bones about the fact that in order for the
Minutemen to win, quarterback Todd Bankhead (286 for 500, 3,767
yards, 34 TDs, 20 interceptions) must have an exceptional outing.
Once again, the Minutemen face one of the quickest defenses in
1-AA, and the junior, who often struggles once flushed out of the
pocket, will be harassed all day.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore running back Marcel Shipp (393 carries, 2,298 yards,
15 touchdowns) must also have a solid outing. After sitting out the
McNeese State game with a knee injury, he has rushed for 349 yards
on 74 carries and scored two touchdowns in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Jimmy Moore, the Minutemen's leading receiver (86
catches, 1,431 yards, 16 TDs), has drawn much double and triple
coverage in the playoffs. All-America tight end Kerry Taylor (70
catches, 832 yards, 5 TDs) will also attract a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   That means Saturday could be big for speedy freshman tight end
Adrian Zullo (27 catches, 465 yards, 7 TDs), who surprised McNeese
State with a 31-yard touchdown catch, one of the biggest plays in
that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out and play sound defensively,'' said Georgia
Southern lineman Eric Davis (60 tackles, 11 sacks). ``We have to
stick to our game plan, and everything will come out fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple is banking on the same approach. ``We can't make a
statement and change the whole philosophy just because we're
playing Georgia Southern,'' he said. ``We're going to play football
UMass style. I don't want our kids to think they have to play
perfect; I want them to play perfectly with emotion, intensity, and
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do that, we will be right there in the fourth quarter.
And if we're there in the fourth quarter against Georgia Southern,
anyone who has seen us this year can tell you that anything can
happen with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
