</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE TO NURSE FINGER FOR AT LEAST ANOTHER WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There's still another week to go before a
final decision is made, but as of now, it appears Drew Bledsoe will
not play against the New York Jets Dec. 27 in the regular-season
finale. In fact, he might not be seen again until the playoffs _ if
then _ should the Patriots get that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in a good way right now,'' said coach Pete Carroll
Friday. ``The more time we can buy him, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, looking as down as he's ever been in his career, is
pessimistic about the immediate future as he continues to
rehabilitate his broken right index finger, which will force him to
the bench Sunday when Scott Zolak faces the San Francisco 49ers at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not optimistic about playing next week,'' he said. ``The
reason is it's like a brand new injury. They just put the pin in
there and they have to allow for it to heal. Now that I've been out
for an extended period, I have to practice before I can play. If it
was a week or two weeks, a veteran quarterback can go that long
without practicing. I've had two practice days in the last month.
If I'm gonna play, I have to have the practice reps. It would be
foolhardy to go into the game next week with no practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who sports a wrap around the injured finger, with a pin
sticking out of the top, said, ``I'd have to have the problem
resolved by Wednesday or Thursday of next week. That's highly
unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was asked about the possibility of resting Bledsoe if
the Patriots qualify for the playoffs this weekend via a win over
the 49ers and a Tennessee loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much can (the finger) progress between now and then?'' the
coach said. ``It's not going to really repair itself. It's going to
be difficult for him to play next week, and Drew knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said that while he's optimistic about the team's chances
without him, ``I figured out today I've only been on the sidelines
for three games since 1990. I didn't know how it would be going
into a game knowing I wouldn't play. I've tried to help Scott and
been involved in the game plan with Scott and I'll be out there
rooting for Scott and supporting him. Right now that's all I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to be able to play in the playoffs three weeks from now
but has no idea whether he will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' said Bledsoe. ``I would hope that would be the
case. I would have to see what our medical staff has to say _
whether that's next week or the week after, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   So it all comes down to Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran backup will likely have every opportunity to get the
rust out of his system. And then he may have a chance to beat Bill
Parcells at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see Drew playing against New York,'' said Zolak. ``Not
with that pin sticking out of his finger. At some point, you have
to worry about permanent damage to the finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and Zolak have had a love-hate relationship. Two years
ago, Parcells was on Zolak about losing weight. Zolak also took a
big pay cut in the final year of Parcells's New England tenure,
from $800,000 to $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   When Ernie Zampese took over as offensive coordinator, there was
some talk about bringing in Jim Everett as the backup, but the
Patriots thought they were fine with Zolak and Tom Tupa.
</P>
<P>
   Now the team is trying to break in Northeastern's Jim Murphy,
who's on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak said he's received more attention this week than ever
before. ``More than I deserve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exciting. It's been a short week, really. Sunday we
go to the hotel and Sunday we play the game. It can't come soon
enough. I just want to go out there and do some positive things,
not try and win the game by myself. They're going to try and
confuse me. I've heard the comments from them that they'll treat me
like they do Drew, but I know that's just talk. They'll be coming
at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak says he can't look beyond Sunday, even though he's aware
he'll likely be the starter in both of the remaining games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get both, but you have to worry about this one
first,'' he said. ``It's a short two-game season for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak has distributed about 20 extra tickets to friends and
family. His father, who was his high school coach, will be at the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak said the team had a good week of practice, and it appears
his teammates are rallying around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's usually a guy who kids around and has some fun, but this
week he did none of that,'' said Chad Eaton. ``He was all business.
The guys on the team watch him in practice all the time, and he
does a great job. I think everybody knows Scott can get the job
done. Now we have to help him out. We have to have a great
performance by the defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
