<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIZENS-FISH-BOS &LR;      12-18 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIZENS-FISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS' FISH EARNS BIG PAYCHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lawrence K. Fish, chief executive of Citizens Financial
Group, continued his status as one of the highest-paid bankers in
New England by pulling in $5.5 million in the bank's 1998 fiscal
year ended Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The figure, which represents a 47 percent raise from last year's
compensation, includes $789,600 in base salary, $4.62 million in
performance-related bonuses, and $137,760 in pension contributions
and other benefits, according to the company's proxy statement
released Friday. The proxy listed Fish's pay in British pounds,
which Friday exchanged at a rate of 1.68 US dollars to the pound.
</P>
<P>
   Bank analysts said Fish earned his big paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worth every penny,'' said James Moynihan, senior vice
president of Advest Inc. in Boston. ``He's done a remarkable job.
If you look at his numbers, it just keeps getting better and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Citizens had a banner year, Moynihan noted. The Providence,
R.I.-based bank posted a record $244 million in net income, up 32
percent from $185 million in fiscal 1997. Assets grew to a record
$17.3 billion in 1998, up 6.7 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Citizen's parent company, the Royal Bank of
Scotland, issued a statement defending Fish's pay package.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted to have the opportunity to pay this level of
compensation to Larry Fish,'' said George Mathewson, group chief
executive of the Royal Bank. ``The compensation package is formula
driven based on a pre-determined set of growth targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with those of his peers, Fish's $5.5 million salary is
both above and below average. Terrence Murray, chief executive of
Fleet Financial Group Inc., last year earned $3.8 million in salary
and bonus. BankBoston's CEO, Charles K. Gifford, made $3.3 million
in salary and bonus in 1997. (Their 1998 salaries will not be
disclosed until next year, when the companies will issue proxy
statements on their 1998 financial performance.)
</P>
<P>
   However, when stock awards and other stock incentives are taken
into account, Fish's salary is dwarfed by Murray's estimated $22
million total 1997 compensation package, which included a one-time
stock payment if Murray stays with Fleet until 2001. In addition to
his salary and bonus, Gifford also received a stock award of $1
million and stock options worth between $3 million and $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fish, by contrast, receives no stock awards, noted Gerard
Cassidy, an analyst with Hancock Institutional Equity Services.
``Larry Fish's compensation is different than some of the others
because he doesn't have the access to the stock options available
to some of his peers,'' Cassidy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
