u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REHNQUIST-IMPEACH-$AD     12-18 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHNQUIST-IMPEACH-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHNQUIST, JUDGE AT SENATE TRIAL, IS AN EXPERT ON IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a Senate trial of President William Jefferson
Clinton early next year, the man with the gavel will be Chief
Justice William Rehnquist, a staunch conservative, a history buff
and an expert on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution vests the chief justice with the responsibility
of presiding over Senate impeachment trials of presidents. It is a
role that seems well suited to Rehnquist, 74, author of the 1992
book ``Grand Inquests,'' which, among other things, recounts the
1868 trial of President Andrew Johnson, who was impeached by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very familiar with role he'll be undertaking,'' said
Charles Cooper, a Washington lawyer and former Ronald Reagan
administration Justice Department official who served as a law
clerk to Rehnquist. ``If he hadn't done all that research already,
he'd have to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is a scholarly treatment of what Rehnquist sees as a
watershed event in U.S. history that did much to flesh out the
Constitution's division of power between the executive, legislative
and judicial branches.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the stridently partisan Clinton impeachment debate
can take heart from portions of the book dealing with the Johnson
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a Southern Democrat who went to the White House in 1865
after the assassination of President Lincoln, incurred the wrath of
congressional Republicans over his opposition to post-Civil War
reconstruction in the South. Johnson's removal of War Secretary
Edward Stanton was the final straw, leading the
Republican-dominated House to impeach Johnson for violating a law
barring such dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist praises key senators who participated in the 1868
trial for treating the case, not as a political issue, but as a
``judicial proceeding'' dealing with violations of law.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, this bolsters their contention that the case
against Clinton essentially is a legal one involving a president
violating the law, which he has sworn to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Johnson ultimately died because not enough
senators thought Johnson's firing of Stanton violated the law or
felt that it was a close call, Rehnquist wrote. A guilty vote
requires two thirds of those voting, and Johnson escaped such a
verdict by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say that on a factual level the charges against
Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky matter will be easy to prove.
Democrats disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist sees the Senate's acquittal of Johnson as an important
triumph of what he calls the American ``tripartite federal system
of government,'' where, unlike the parliamentary system, the
president is not subject to easy removal by the legislature for
political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   That view is good news for Clinton backers, who see the
impeachment and removal from office process as a politically
motivated ``coup d'etat'' by Republicans seeking to turn back
Clinton's two electoral victories.
</P>
<P>
   Some liberals are cautiously hopeful about how Rehnquist will
handle the trial of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have mixed signals on where (Rehnquist) would be,''
said Nan Aron, executive director of the Alliance for Justice, a
liberal judicial watchdog group. ``He has a background as a very
political justice, but his book urges caution and raises concern
over impeachment. One would hope he could rise above partisanship
to be fair..MDNM/''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the interpretation, Rehnquist's power at the Senate
trial will be limited. The 100 senators who serve as jurors are
free to submit written questions through the chief justice to
witnesses and lawyers. And senators irked by the chief justice's
rulings on the evidence or on procedural matters can call for votes
to overturn them.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist has a reputation as a crusader who has done much to
advance a conservative legal agenda in almost 27 years on the
Supreme Court. He wrote the dissent in Roe v. Wade, the landmark
1973 opinion legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a stalwart opponent of affirmative action and
expanded rights for criminal suspects, as well as a proponent of
the death penalty and efforts to lower the wall between church as
state.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist also authored the court's 1988 opinion upholding the
law authorizing independent counsels to investigate high government
officials. Under the law, Kenneth Starr was appointed in 1994, and
his investigation brought to light the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal
that led to the charges against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A Milwaukee native, Rehnquist practiced law and became active in
Republican circles in Phoenix in the 1950s and 1960s. There he met
Richard Kleindienst, who was deputy attorney general and later
attorney general under President Richard Nixon. Kleindienst brought
Rehnquist to Washington to serve in the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   He was appointed to the high court in 1971 and sworn in on Jan.
7, 1972. Two years later, in the burgeoning Watergate scandal, the
court voted 8-0 to compel Nixon to turn over tape-recorded
telephone conversations to the special prosecutor. Rehnquist
abstained.
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan named Rehnquist chief justice in 1986 to
replace the retiring chief, Warren Burger. During his contentious
confirmation hearing that year, Rehnquist's own veracity came under
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, opponents charged that he had not told the
truth about his days in Phoenix in the 1960s as a GOP poll watcher.
They said he harassed and intimidated likely Democratic voters.
Rehnquist denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   James Brosnahan, now a San Francisco lawyer, testified at
Rehnquist's confirmation hearing that as a young assistant U.S.
attorney in 1962 he observed Rehnquist at a polling place and that
some voters accused him of challenging their right to vote. But
Brosnahan told the Senate Judiciary Committee that he did not
observe the alleged harassment himself.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his law office in San Francisco, Brosnahan said he
has no reason to doubt Rehnquist's ability to preside over an
impeachment involving allegations of perjury. ``That was then, this
is now, and he's the chief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist won Senate confirmation as chief justice on Sept. 17,
1986, by a vote of 65-33.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
