<HEADLINE>
AT THE BIG BOARD, THE STORY OF `A'  
 INDIVIDUALS HOLD MOST FOREIGN STOCKS  
 TWO POPULAR CATEGORIES BEATING THE S&AMP;P 500 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Dec. 20) 
(Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the New York Stock Exchange can only watch from afar the
frenzied activity these days in Internet stocks, which generally
trade on Nasdaq, the Big Board is ground zero for intense
speculation of another kind: Which company is going to get ticker
symbol ``A''?
</P>
<P>
   Could it be Amazon.com?
</P>
<P>
   The issue arises because it seems likely that A _ possibly the
most coveted symbol among the single-letter elite _ will soon
become available with the completion of a merger between the
present holder, Astra AB, Sweden's biggest drug company, and
Britain's Zeneca Group.
</P>
<P>
   Given how quickly Citigroup moved to snap up Chrysler's recently
abandoned symbol _ ``The C went so fast it was incredible,'' a
spokeswoman said _ the sparring over A is already thought to be
fierce. But the Big Board is officially coy, the bargaining
presumably being conducted at such a high level that someone in the
symbol trenches, speaking on condition of anonymity, would say
only, ``It hasn't hit my desk'' yet.
</P>
<P>
   With companies increasingly eager to extract maximum public
relations and marketing mileage from easy-to-remember or clever
symbols, the exchange has a powerful recruiting tool for new
listings. Although there is no official monopoly, the Big Board has
all the single-letter symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the single letters are currently unassigned. I and M are
rumored to be lures in the exchange's campaign to attract Intel and
Microsoft, while Q has long been unassigned because, the
spokeswoman said, of a traditional association with bankruptcy. The
fourth is V, which would seem to be a natural for Venator, formerly
Woolworth, which so far has stuck with its Z.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the single-letter club is far less exclusive than it used
to be. Barnes Group (B) and Realty Income Corp. (O) are hardly
household names, and Jackpot Enterprises (J) somehow seems a pale
substitute for Standard Oil of New Jersey, now Exxon (XON), which
once endowed the letter with blue-chip appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can call it elite,'' one exchange official
said of the single-letter designation. ``We try to be very
accommodating.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals, Not Institutions, Hold Most Foreign Stocks
</P>
<P>
   For years, institutional investors were the ones that ventured
abroad. Now, according to a study by Citibank, the banking
subsidiary of Citigroup, individuals hold the majority of foreign
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released last week, found that individuals, either
directly or through mutual funds, controlled 55 percent of U.S.
investment in foreign stocks in 1997. By contrast, in 1991,
individuals accounted for just 21 percent of that investment.
</P>
<P>
   The study said the figure was expected to grow to 59 percent by
2003. One reason for the shift: individuals' interest in increasing
returns for retirement, according to James P. Donovan, Citibank's
global managing director for depository receipts. ``They can create
greater wealth by diversifying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, overseas investing has been treacherous this year.
That is reflected in Citibank's estimate that the dollar volume and
number of American depository receipts, or ADRs, issued by foreign
companies is down sharply this year. Overall, the bank estimated
that 83 companies would raise $9 billion by year-end, vs. 144
companies that raised $18.6 billion in 1997. ``It's the instability
of the markets,'' Donovan said. ``Nobody is going to raise capital
at a subpar value if they don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Two Popular Categories Beating the S&AMP;P 500
</P>
<P>
   A curious phenomenon has bolstered some stock mutual funds
during the 1998 home stretch. On average, two of the more popular
stock fund categories are beating the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index, the benchmark that has been trouncing active fund managers
for years.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lipper Inc., the S&AMP;P returned 7.63 percent from the
end of October through last Thursday. The average capital
appreciation fund, by contrast, returned 8.86 percent over that
time and the average growth fund returned 7.69 percent. (Micro-cap
funds, which would never invest in a company in the S&AMP;P 500, really
surged, providing a 10.55 percent return over the same period.)
</P>
<P>
   The source of the smart showing by these funds? ``We've begun to
see some giveback by the large caps,'' said Michael Lipper,
chairman. ``The S&AMP;P is not as all-powerful as it has been.'' The
surging telecommunication and technology sectors have had a
salutary effect, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
</TEXT>
