<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-FLYNT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSTLER PUBLISHER REVELS IN ROLE IN LIVINGSTON SEX DISCLOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was, in some ways, perhaps inevitable that
Hustler publisher Larry Flynt would immerse himself in the
infidelities of President Clinton and other Washington politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Raunchy, flamboyant, self-serving and defiant, Flynt was fully
enjoying his notoriety Friday just as he did more than 25 years ago
when he leveraged a string of Ohio strip clubs into the start of a
publishing empire that pushed _ and is still pushing _ the limits
of sexual tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt is taking credit for the disclosure by House Speaker-elect
Bob Livingston that he had carried on adulterous affairs in his
past. Apparently the disclosure was made after Livingston learned
that Hustler was set to publish a story that says that the
Republican lawmaker had the affairs with at least four different
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we were getting ready to go with this story and are
disappointed he scooped us,'' Flynt said in a statement Friday
morning, hours before he held a news conference in his offices
overlooking Wilshire Boulevard. He has said he will publish it in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago Flynt paid $85,000 for a full-page ad in The
Washington Post offering up to $1 million to any woman who could
prove that she had a sexual relationship with a member of Congress
or a high government official. The ad was vintage Flynt. More than
20 years ago he placed a similar ad in The Post after two
congressmen, Reps. Wayne Hayes, D-Ohio, and Wilbur Mills, D-Ark.,
were caught in sex scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Although Flynt has been fond of saying, ``All I wanted to do was
make some money and have some fun,'' his aspirations and obsessions
have seemed a little deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt has raged against what he views as sexual hypocrisy and
became an improbable champion of the First Amendment when the
Supreme Court in 1988 overturned a jury's $200,000 award to the
Rev. Jerry Falwell for ``emotional distress'' over a Hustler
magazine parody that portrayed him as an incestuous drunk. The 8-0
ruling broadly re-affirmed and extended the court's rules
protecting criticism of public figures as free speech, even if the
criticism was ``outrageous'' and offensive.
</P>
<P>
   What has stamped Flynt's life and career was not only
controversy _and the outrageous style of ``Hustler'' _ but a
virtual obsession with self-promotion and publicity. He has been in
and out of court on obscenity trials. He even ran for president in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Alexander, co-author with Larry Karaszewski of ``The
People vs. Larry Flynt,'' the Milos Forman-directed film about the
publisher, once said that when Flynt campaigned for the presidency,
he ``practically hijacked the front page of the daily newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, you'd open the paper and he was doing something
outrageous,'' he said. ``One day he'd be running for president, the
next he would show up in a courtroom wearing a diaper. After that,
he'd pay his fines with garbage bags loaded with one-dollar bills,
delivered by hookers. He just kept topping himself, as if he was
addicted to getting in the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynt's life has been marred by tragedy. His wife, Althea
Leasure, died of AIDS. Flynt himself was paralyzed below the waist
in 1978 when a drifter who once belonged to the Ku Klux Klan and
the American Nazi Party shot him during a pornography trial in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt, who has lived in a 24-room Bel Air mansion for years,
later became addicted to painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   His associates have said that, in recent years, Flynt has turned
into a relatively serene figure, especially in contrast to his
earlier years when he brought the sex industry to America's
heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, it seems that his earlier stated goal of having
money and fame are only a small part of what drives Flynt now.
``People have a very sketchy idea of my life,'' he said last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
