<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION: MANDELA PRAISES CHURCHES' ROLE IN EDUCATION AND
LIBERATION
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early generations of Christian missionaries from Europe and the
United States often fared poorly in the popular media. They have
been depicted in novels and films as arrogant or, worse, tools of
colonial adventurers.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, the work of missionaries, specifically in
education, received a word of praise from a source widely regarded
as one of the late 20th century's moral leaders, President Nelson
Mandela of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela turned up as a nearly unexpected but quite welcome guest
on Sunday, Dec. 13, at the Eighth Assembly of the World Council of
Churches, meeting in Harare, Zimbabwe. The assembly, whose
delegates represent 339 Protestant and Orthodox Christian churches
worldwide, had been expecting South Africa's deputy president,
Thabo Mbeki. But Mandela sent word a couple of days before the
assembly that he would be going instead.
</P>
<P>
   In part, he went to thank the council for its support in the
1970s and 1980s for organizations like his African National
Congress, in their struggles against white-minority governments in
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, the council initiated its Programme to Combat Racism,
which eventually called for an end to bank loans to South Africa's
apartheid government, advocated economic sanctions against South
Africa and, in a contentious move upsetting some of the council's
own members, gave cash grants (for humanitarian purposes, the
council said) to groups fighting for majority rule in South Africa
and in the former Rhodesia, now Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your support,'' Mandela said to delegates gathered at the
University of Zimbabwe, ``exemplified in the most concrete way the
contribution that religion has made to our liberation, from the
days when religious bodies took responsibility for the education of
the oppressed because it was denied us by our rulers, to support
for our liberation struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he singled out the work of missionaries in education,
ad-libbing his thanks to missionary teachers who worked in South
Africa when he was a child. ``My generation is the product of
church education,'' Mandela said. By contrast, he said, the
government of his day ``took no interest whatsoever'' in educating
Africans, people of mixed race or Indians.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were the second by a prominent African on the
subject of church-sponsored schools recently. In November, United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan received the World Methodist
Peace Award, and in response he favorably recalled his education in
a Methodist school in Ghana. Annan is quoted in the current issue
of the magazine The Christian Century saying he was fortunate to
have had teachers ``who understood the value of knowledge infused
with a moral purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   At the assembly, Mandela's arrival generated enough excitement
to pack the hall with delegates wrapping up their 12-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Before they adjourned Monday, delegates put the council on
record as favoring cancellation of the foreign debts of the world's
poorest countries and also released a statement on human rights,
calling for the elimination of the death penalty, condemning
violence against women and declaring religious freedom to be a
fundamental right. They also passed a statement condemning the use
of children as soldiers in conflicts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they issued the declarations, delegates were made
aware of a potentially difficult financial future for the council,
which has twice reduced its staff to eliminate budget deficits in
the A report by the assembly's finance committee showed the council
relied on western European churches for 82 percent of its budget.
</P>
<P>
   The report said those churches were under financial pressure,
facing changes in tax policies in their nations or declining
membership. It recommended measures like the replenishment of
reserve funds and the improvement of fiscal forecasting, while also
warning that the council had ``no room for complacency'' on this
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-SOLDIERS-NYT &LR;      12-18 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SOLDIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY FAMILIES COPE WITH POSTPONED HOMECOMINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (mk) 
(See also IRAQ-RDP, IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-RUSSIA, IRAQ-U.N.,
IRAQ-INSPECT, IRAQ-WESTBANK, IRAQ-VIDEO-GAME, IRAQ-BOMBER.) By RICK
BRAGG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT STEWART, Ga. _ All along the thin ribbons of blacktop that
connect Fort Stewart with the rest of the world, homemade signs
hang from the pines to welcome home soldiers returning from
postings overseas. The welcomes, to ``Leigh'' and ``Boo-Hoo'' and
others, are painted in giant letters on bedsheets, so that the
returning husbands, wives, mothers, fathers and sweethearts cannot
possibly miss them as they drive in.
</P>
<P>
   But when some of these soldiers finally get home this time, the
painted messages will have faded. The loved ones put them up just a
little too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Fort Stewart, headquarters for the 3rd Infantry Division
(Mechanized), as at other military bases around the country,
President Clinton's decision to bomb Iraq has canceled the
homecoming of many from the Persian Gulf and will probably cause
others to ship out to the gulf over the next few days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was supposed to come home today,'' Stefanie Terrell said of
her husband, Sgt. Terrence Terrell, who has been stationed in
Kuwait since August.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, just as Terrell was planning to board a plane for home,
the missiles began to fall on Baghdad and his unit got new orders:
Stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt panic,'' Mrs. Terrell said. And also some anger. Why
just now, she wondered. Why, after so many months of standoff and
diplomacy?
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Terrell, a lot of people here do not want to believe
that the soldiers of their own families could be put in harm's way
because Clinton needed a diversion to try to forestall impeachment.
But the timing, they say, does look bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was right,'' said Mrs. Terrell, whose
husband had promised the middle of their three children, 8-year-old
Dominic, that he would be home by Saturday, the boy's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell will instead be with the crew of his Bradley Fighting
Vehicle _ a fast-moving fortress of armor equipped with an antitank
missile, a cannon and a machine gun _ although his wife does not
know where.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me at four this morning,'' said Mrs. Terrell, who
works as a maid at the Holiday Inn in Hinesville, a town bordering
this base just west of Savannah. ``He told me not to worry, and
that he loved us. I asked him if he was going to be where there was
any fighting, but he couldn't say. It was hard. I immediately
thought of the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the attack on Iraq has been limited to air strikes,
there is always the fear here that ground soldiers like Mrs.
Terrell's husband will have to take part later on, even as officers
and social workers tell her there is nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   The same frustration can be found up and down the strip
developments that make up Hinesville, where spouses wonder whether
Clinton's decision to bomb Iraq was purely a strategic one, or
whether he is playing politics with lives.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Herrera's husband, Porfirio Herrera, is a track mechanic
who planned to spend Christmas here with his family, but now he has
begun preparing to ship out. He is expected to be ordered to the
Persian Gulf sometime in the next few days, said Mrs. Herrera, who
works in the produce section at a Kroger supermarket in Hinesville.
They have two children, ages 7 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to tell them, and I don't know what to
think,'' she said when asked whether she was angry with the
president. After a few minutes, she added, ``I think they should
send Clinton to Iraq and send our men home.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were worried, but not angry. They believed that Clinton's
decision was based not on political strategy but on that of his
military advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Roseberry, a manager at Kroger, is married to a soldier
based in Kuwait. ``He's a gunner on a Bradley,'' she said. ``If
there is a war, he'll be the one pulling the trigger. He was
supposed to be home this week.''
</P>
<P>
   But her husband, Sgt. David Roseberry, told her by telephone
that he believed the decision was a military one. ``It's something
that just happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many families here that had expected to have their loved ones
home for the holidays are disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Hall's boyfriend, Matthew Neely, is a tank crewman who is
now expected to ship out immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got the call,'' she said. ``Christmas is not a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Terrell, though brokenhearted, knows that this is all part
of being married to a military man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always waiting for him to come back,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
