u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FIRST-LADY-1S     12-18 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FIRST-LADY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STICKS TO TIGHT SCHEDULE AS HOUSE DEBATES IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Recasts lede, pickup 2ndgraf: The first.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House debating the impeachment of a
president for the first time since 1868, Hillary Rodham Clinton
broke months of silence on her husband's plight Friday with an
appeal to ``end divisiveness'' this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's appeal contrasted to the public silence of
President Clinton on a make-or-break day in his presidency. White
House officials said the president was too busy working to make
public remarks or monitor the House debate on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, citing the confluence of the Jewish holiday of
Hanukkah, the Muslim holy month of Ramadan and the Christian
celebration of Christmas, said the holidays are ``a time for
reflection and reconciliation among people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton spoke as she draped her arm around Julian Hill, 11,
whose 4-year-old brother was killed by a drunken driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in our country ought to practice reconciliation and we
ought to bring our country together and we ought to end
divisiveness because we can do so much more together,'' Mrs.
Clinton said, the Capitol dome in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that we as a nation would turn our attention to
what we could do together, what we could do positively and how we
could build each other up,'' Mrs. Clinton said in remarks after an
event to highlight the holiday efforts of the Mothers Against Drunk
Driving.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore rejected GOP appeals for Clinton to
resign. ``People can forget about that,'' Gore declared.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart lambasted a ``cynical
political strategy'' by Republican congressional leaders to force
Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will ``absolutely not'' step aside, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Philip Wogaman, pastor at the Foundry Methodist Church in
Washington, said in a broadcast television interview with the
Public Broadcasting System's Religion &AMP; Ethics Newsweekly that
Clinton remains ``a man of great resiliency'' who is ``determined
to continue leading the nation in the midst of all this.'' The
Clintons attend Wogaman's church.
</P>
<P>
   With the president's crowded schedule, Lockhart said Clinton was
not watching televised coverage of the House debate. Instead, the
president reviewed U.S. combat operations in Iraq, held a summit
with two European leaders, mapped federal spending for fiscal year
2000 and met with advisers on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is ``clearly an issue that impacts him,'' Lockhart
conceded, adding: ``He does not have the luxury of not staying
focused on his duties (and) on the things that he's promised the
American public he'll do _ and that's what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton notably skipped an opportunity to use a meeting with
moderate Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., as a public platform to
address GOP moderates in an effort to staunch the threatened
impeachment vote on Saturday. Shays entered and left the White
House without public comment.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said that Clinton, who relishes the minutia of
policy and politics, was finding comfort in the details of official
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he goes into a budget meeting, he quizzes his advisers
closely,'' Lockhart said. ``He's clearly conversant in all the
particular minutia of budget issues that (budget) people need him
to be fluent in to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's mood appeared to change during the day. The president
appeared pensive and determined as he walked past a pair of
reporters in a White House corridor as he escorted Shays to the
Oval Office area.
</P>
<P>
   A little while later, Clinton was jocular, bantering with
photographers escorted into the Oval Office to take pictures of his
meeting with European officials.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said White House officials are hoping that ``with a
couple of weeks off for Christmas and New Year's, we can all have a
New Year resolution that Congress will come back in the spirit of
bipartisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were pressing the Republican-led Congress
to approve a bipartisan resolution of censure to punish Clinton for
covering up his sexual affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky and lying to two federal court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton would return to work after a holiday
break determined to work for a bipartisan compromise to avoid a
protracted trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be up to Congress to decide if they can create a
spirit of bipartisanship and a spirit of putting America's
interests before their own political interests,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The House last debated the impeachment of a president after the
Civil War when President Andrew Johnson, a former governor of
Tennessee, was impeached by the House in a dispute over the
president's effort to ease the harshness of the federal occupation
of the defeated Confederacy. Johnson prevailed in the Senate trial
by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   President Richard M. Nixon, who faced articles of impeachment
approved by the House Judiciary Committee in 1974, resigned from
office before the House took up action on his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces four articles of impeachment lodged by the House
Judiciary Committee, charging him with two counts of perjury,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power in connection with his
cover-up of the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
</TEXT>
