s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     12-18 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOY MAKERS SCRAMBLING JUST TO STAY IN PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 20) 
(bl) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attention: just five more days until Christmas. But even as
children of all ages and sizes cram the malls in a final frenzy,
there are signs of unrest in toyland.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 14, Mattel, the world's biggest toy maker, warned that
its results for the fourth quarter and the year would be
disappointing. In the next breath, the company announced that it
was issuing $3.8 billion of its stock to buy The Learning Co., a
leading consumer software maker. Wall Street, unimpressed, gave
Mattel shares their worst one-day pasting in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, Hasbro, No. 2 to Mattel, said it had tapped
Herbert Baum, the chief executive of Quaker State Corp., as its
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McGowan, an executive vice president at Gerard Klauer
Mattison, an investment banking and research firm, took some time
last week to discuss where in the world this $22 billion industry
is going.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does Mattel's earnings warning presage a cold Christmas for
all toy makers?
</P>
<P>
   A. The whole industry will not do as badly as Mattel, even
though it may be a flat year. This year is a tough one by
comparison with 1997, because last year was above normal. You had a
lot of hot toys last year, like Batman and Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about the retailers? Are there changes on that side of
the business?
</P>
<P>
   A. There is continued consolidation. The biggest surprise of
1998 will be that Wal-Mart is a bigger retailer of toys than Toys
``R'' Us. And if that does not happen, it will be true that
Wal-Mart is a bigger buyer of toys than Toys ``R'' Us. In terms of
share, five years ago Wal-Mart was about half as big.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the purpose behind the Mattel-Learning Co. deal?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think there is a lot of logic in putting the two companies
together. The consumer software-entertainment business has evolved
in ways that make it very much like the toy business. Brands and
licenses are more important, as is the use of television
advertising, managing retail inventories and managing a shrinking
retail base.
</P>
<P>
   Also, this is a business of constantly coming up with new ideas
in order to generate growth. For a $5 billion company like Mattel,
that means coming up with a $1 billion idea, which is about as big
as the third-biggest toy company. They have to look outside the toy
business for that sort of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do these companies need to look elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   A. Kids are not buying toys the way they used to. They are
graduating out of toys at a younger age. If a 10-year-old spends a
lot of time downloading on the Net, it is hard to go back to
Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   Toy companies are facing three options: They can sell more
products to existing customers, sell more products to new
customers, or they can sell new products. As I said, the companies
have maxed out in the first area. And they are trying hard in the
second, as the effort to market collectible Barbies to 50-year-old
women shows. New products are the next big push.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What sort of products?
</P>
<P>
   A. Blends of video and software. But also I could see toy
companies buying sporting goods companies, comic book and gum
companies, apparel companies. These businesses will become
increasingly horizontally integrated. It might make sense for Walt
Disney Co., which licenses most of its toys through Mattel, to
branch out and buy a toy company. And Hasbro is already a fairly
significant candy company.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Speaking of Hasbro, what about its hiring the head of Quaker
State? It's hard to see the connection between motor oil and toys.
</P>
<P>
   A. Herb Baum's hire is the logical move in the sense that Hasbro
is looking at itself as more than a toy company. Before he was at
Quaker State, he ran the North and South American operations for
Campbell Soup. So while he doesn't have an entertainment
background, he is someone who can provide advice on how to grow the
company.
</P>
<P>
   I think Hasbro has excellent prospects for next year. I like the
management change, and they have a new line of ``Star Wars'' toys
coming out in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are toy stocks good investments?
</P>
<P>
   A. One of the things that attract investors to the toy industry
is to find the company that can come out of nowhere and do very,
very well. That happens, but every toy stock that has gone public
in the last 15 years has experienced some period of sharp
volatility. The barriers to entry and exit are very low in this
business. So it is not a place for long-term investors. And it is
not an industry to look at going into December, which is a reliably
tough month for the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Aside from Hasbro, are there other toy stocks that you like?
</P>
<P>
   A. Noodle Kidoodle, a tiny retailer. They sell specialty toys
and educational products. They are having a terrific Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
