<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCEDES ENTERS LUXURY STATION WAGON MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sport-utility vehicle might have become the vehicle of
choice for many upscale buyers, thanks to luxury models from
Toyota, Lexus, Infiniti, Land Rover, Lincoln, Mercedes-Benz, GMC,
Isuzu, Acura, Mitsubishi and even Jeep.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone who needs extra space in a family hauler wants
to drive a truck, and most of the sport-utilities are trucks
underneath, no matter how fancy they are.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves a market for a luxury station wagon, hence Mercedes'
introduction last year of its latest high-end wagon, the E320.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, paying $50,000 or more for a midsize station wagon
seems a bit extravagant, especially considering that a Lexus LX 470
or Range Rover costs about the same but offers a whole lot more
bulk for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes is selling the E-class wagons at a rate of about 3,500
a year, so apparently there are enough customers to make the
vehicle worth producing. Personally, I'd go for the Lexus or Range
Rover for the same money. But if I were looking to spend that much
on a wagon, the E320 would deserve consideration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's the only wagon in that price class. The nearest
competitors are the Volvo V70 and V90 wagons, which list for under
$40,000. And Mercedes' M-class sport-utility with the same engine
as the wagon costs about $10,000 less than the E320, which is
probably why the company is selling about 40,000 of those per year.
</P>
<P>
   A popular option on the Mercedes wagon is the full-time
all-wheel-drive system, a $2,790 extra that raised the base price
of our test vehicle to $49,990 (plus $595 transportation).
</P>
<P>
   This is a full-time system that uses a 35/65 front-rear torque
split and requires no driver action. Mercedes says that half of the
wagon buyers opt for the all-wheel-drive. With some other goodies
tacked on, our vehicle's bottom line was a whopping $54,935, which
put it above the Lexus LX 470 but slightly below the Range Rover.
</P>
<P>
   The E320's best attributes are its luxury-sedan ride and
handling, something you won't find in a truck-based sport-utility
such as the LX 470 or Range Rover. Close your eyes in the E320
wagon and you can't tell the difference between it and the E-class
sedan. It's not a bulky vehicle like most sport-utilities, either;
it's just six-tenths of an inch longer than the E-class sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Power comes from a high-tech, 3.2-liter, aluminum V-6 engine
rated at 221 horsepower and 232 foot-pounds of torque _ the same
engine used in the E-class sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The engine has two platinum-tipped spark plugs for each cylinder
and three valves per cylinder. Sequential fuel injection and a
drive-by-wire throttle make for acceleration that is smooth as
silk. Coupled with the Mercedes five-speed automatic transmission,
this engine will move the all-wheel-drive E320 from zero to 60 mph
in just 8.2 seconds (7.8 seconds with standard two-wheel drive).
</P>
<P>
   Like several of the high-end sport-utilities, the E320 wagon is
equipped with a standard folding third-row seat, giving it seating
for up to seven people. Also like many of the SUVs, the third seat
is best left to children or pets; it's hard for adults to get in
and out of this one.
</P>
<P>
   Because the wagon was all new last year, there are few changes
for 1999. Among them are a new-generation radio system that uses
fiber-optic technology and integrates controls for the sound system
and optional telephone. Our test vehicle came with a dash-mounted
AM/FM/cassette unit with weather band, and there was a separate
remote-mounted compact-disc changer (a $750 option)..
</P>
<P>
   Safety features abound on the E320 wagon. As with all 1999
Mercedes-Benz passenger vehicles, it comes with antilock brakes,
dual front air bags and door-mounted side air bags. It also comes
with ``brake assist,'' which Mercedes says is ``the only safety
system in the world that can actually shorten stopping distances in
emergency braking situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Brake assist is designed to detect a `panic' stop by how quickly
the brake pedal is applied. Then it applies full braking force
faster than the driver can. In addition, there is a three-point
seat belt for each of the seats.
</P>
<P>
   For people with small children who have to ride up front, the
E320 comes with the ``BabySmart'' automatic child-seat detection
system, which turns off the front passenger-side air bag if a
compatible infant or child safety seat is placed there. It has to
be one of Mercedes-Benz's infant, toddler or child-booster seats
that contains a transponder to alert the system to the seat's
presence. The three seats, each designed for a different age and
weight group, are available from Mercedes dealers. Of course, for
safety's sake, all children should be in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Traction control is standard on all E-Class models. In the
all-wheel-drive model, this system allows one wheel to deliver
driving power if it has traction, even if all three of the others
are spinning on slippery surfaces. The optional Electronic
Stability Program or ESP, a $1,000 extra, is available on the E320
wagon. It can detect an impending spin or slide and apply selective
braking on any of the four wheels to keep the car going where the
driver is steering it.
</P>
<P>
   There is lots of cargo room if you don't need the third seat for
passengers, and the rear hatch flips up for easy loading. With the
third seat folded down, there is 44 cubic feet of room for luggage
or camping gear. With the middle and rear seats folded, the space
expands to 83 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension system _ double wishbones up front and a
five-link rear arrangement _ is the same as in the Mercedes E320
sedan, providing the carlike ride and handling of the wagon. Also
included is automatic rear level control to let the wagon carry
heavy loads without overtaxing the suspension system.
</P>
<P>
   Among standard features of the E320 wagon are automatic
dual-zone climate control, leather seats, 10-way power front seats
and head restraints, one-touch (up and down) power windows, power
tilt and telescoping steering column, three-position memory (for
the front seats, mirrors and steering wheel), walnut interior trim,
integrated three-button garage door opener, and high-performance
eight-speaker cassette audio system.
</P>
<P>
   There is no conventional ignition key; an infrared signal from
the high-tech ``key'' allows you to start and run the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Our car came with a several options. Xenon gas-discharge
high-intensity headlights, headlight washers and automatic
rain-sensor windshield wipers were included in a package for
$1,200; parchment-leather seats cost $1,325; and the dark turquoise
paint job was an extra $750.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings for the wagon certainly are better than
those of the average sport-utility: 20 miles per gallon in the city
and 26 mpg on the highway (28 mpg highway with two-wheel drive).
The tank holds 18.5 gallons of fuel, down from 21.1 gallons in the
E-class sedan.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
