u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-IRAQ-ADVISORY     12-18 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-IRAQ-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times will lead Saturday's issue with a 6-column,
2-line hedline on the House impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, The Times plans 5 pages of stories and 5 pages of text
from wire services.
</P>
<P>
   The lede story will move by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. Eastern time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall: For the first time since Feb.
24, 1868, three years after the United States emerged from an awful
Civil War, the House of Representatives debated the impeachment of
a President today. It scheduled for Saturday a vote on four
articles of impeachment ``for high crimes and misdemeanors''
against William Jefferson Clinton. Although they protested bitterly
and ardently, Democrats acknowledged that passage of at least one
of them, and a Senate trial next year that could result in the
president's removal from office, had finally become inevitable. By
R.W. Apple Jr. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   These are the other stories in the impeachment package:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-FLYNT (Los Angeles) _ It was, in some ways, inevitable
that Hustler publisher Larry Flynt would immerse himself in the
infidelities of President Clinton and other Washington politicians.
Raunchy, flamboyant, self-serving and defiant, Flynt was fully
enjoying his notoriety today just as he did more than 25 years ago
when he leveraged a string of Ohio strip clubs into the start of a
publishing empire that pushed _ and is still pushing _ the limits
of sexual tolerance. By Bernard Weinraub. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 7:30 &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RESIGN (Washington) _ The next battle the White House
will face is an anticipated campaign to pressure President Clinton
to resign. White House aides charge that Republicans are
orchestrating a resignation push, because House leaders expect
their impeachment drive to falter in the Senate. By Jill Abramson.
(800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MOOD (Washington) _ The President, some of his aides and
friends say, is devastated. He has withdrawn, they say, even
cutting off some of his usual circle of friends. One, who talked to
him daily, hasn't heard from him since Thanksgiving. Another tells
of calls among the inner circle about how to get Bill Clinton's
political fires burning again. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LAHOOD (Washington) _ Rep. Ray LaHood of Illinois,
presiding over the House during the impeachment debate: How he got
there and how he did. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV (Undated) _ What the networks and news stations did.
By Bill Carter. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LAMEDUCKS (Washington) _ They are the lame ducks in the
House, 21 Republicans and 17 Democrats, not including two
Republicans and one Democrat who won election to Senate seats. And
as the House took up impeachment today, they streamed back into the
Capitol to deal with what for many is the most momentous issue of
their careers in public service, one they variously view as
unfortunately necessary or just unfortunate. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
