<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: A Medical Walkout
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of German doctors and dentists went on a one-day
strike protesting the government's plans to cap medical spending.
Health Minister Andrea Fischer charged that the demonstrators were
confusing patients by saying the proposed changes would lead to
cutbacks in medicine supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Overture to Basque Rebels
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish government said it had made ``significant'' contacts
with people close to the Basque separatist group ETA, which has
observed a cease-fire since September in its 30-year fight for
Basque independence. Madrid also agreed to transfer 21 Basque
separatist inmates to prisons closer to their homes, but two Basque
nationalist parties called the gesture insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican: Pope Hit with Flu
</P>
<P>
   Ill with influenza, Pope John Paul II had to cancel all his
appointments Friday, including a meeting with the Catholic
patriarch of Iraq and an official of the Arab League. The
78-year-old pope is scheduled to celebrate midnight Mass on
Christmas Eve and deliver his annual address on Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Congress Party Makes Changes
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party, an increasingly powerful opposition in
Parliament since its recent state election victories, set aside a
third of all its party positions for women and a fifth for
religious minorities, including members of lower castes and tribes.
The party president, Sonia Gandhi, said the changes would help
rebuild its role as champion of the oppressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
