<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-PENTAGON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS LEAVE MANY TARGETS LIGHTLY DAMAGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If US and British forces intend to wreak much
damage on Saddam Hussein's military power, the bombing of Iraq will
have to go on a while longer _ well into the Islamic holiday of
Ramadan, which starts at dawn Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually detailed data released by the Pentagon Friday show
that the air strikes Wednesday and Thursday struck some of their
targets with deadly force, but left many more just lightly damaged
or untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Air-strikes have steadily been stepped up over the past three
days, not just from cruise missiles fired by B52 bombers and ships
at sea, but also from combat planes dropping laser-guided bombs.
Baghdad has been hit, so far, only by cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Even the B1 bomber made its first entry into combat, though it
amounted to a cameo, a single plane flying one sortie. The
aircraft, which can carry 84 500-pound iron-bombs, unloaded a
barrage on an unspecified military target outside of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   True to the modest claims he has made for this campaign from the
start, Secretary of Defense William Cohen said Friday that he was
``satisfied'' with the results of Operation Desert Fox so far. But,
in one of several official hints that the assault may continue into
the Islamic holy month, Cohen added, ``The strikes are not
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry H. Shelton, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
heralded ``some very good success with our strikes,'' and showed a
few videotapes of direct hits. ``Not all of them have gone
according to plan,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said that the purpose of the air strikes
is to ``degrade'' and ``diminish'' Hussein's ability to threaten
his neighbors with nuclear, chemical or biological weapons. By that
vague criterion, the president could call the troops home now, but
the results have not yet been what any military analyst would call
substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the situation on the ground in Iraq, the information
released by the Pentagon Friday was noteworthy on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe it was the first time during any military
operation that US officials had released comprehensive data on
``bomb-damage assessment'' and _ just as unusual _ spy-satellite
photographs showing how a number of targets looked before and after
an attack.
</P>
<P>
   The data showed that, over the first two nights, US and British
forces attacked 89 targets in Iraq, striking 77.
</P>
<P>
   Of those hit, eight were destroyed, 10 were severely damaged, 18
moderately damaged, and seven only lightly damaged. The damage
inflicted on 33 targets, over one-third of those attacked, had not
yet been assessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very, very early in the assessment,'' Rear Admiral
Thomas Wilson, the Joint Staff's director of intelligence, told
reporters. ``It is a very incomplete picture. ... We haven't even
looked at all the targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, by any military criteria, the data available suggest the
operation itself is at an early stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're off to a really encouraging start, but it looks to me
like they've got a long ways to go,'' John Pike, a weapons analyst
at the Federation of American Scientists, said after examining the
data. ``There's an awful lot of `light to moderate damage,' but I
don't see very much in the `destroyed' or 'severe damage'
columns.''
</P>
<P>
   The results seem particularly unimpressive for the attacks on
the main target of this campaign _ the facilities that develop,
produce, store, and protect Hussein's nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons. Of 19 targets attacked that relate to the
security of these weapons, two were destroyed, one was severely
damaged, four were lightly damaged, and one was missed.
</P>
<P>
   Of 11 targets attacked that involved the production of weapons,
none were reported destroyed or severely damaged, though eight of
them are still being assessed for damage by intelligence
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether many weapons are missing their targets
or whether the weapons are simply too small to do much damage to
these targets, many of which are quite large.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise missiles and laser-guided bombs range from 1,000 to
2,000 pounds in explosive energy. That's enough to demolish small
structures or punch holes in large ones, but not enough to wreck,
say, a large office building or a blast-resistant airplane-hangar.
</P>
<P>
   Targets included missile-production factories, intelligence
headquarters, communications transmitters, airfields,
security-guard barracks, air defense sites, and _ the only
``economic'' target _ a refinery in Basra that reportedly has been
used to export oil in violation of United Nations sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials declined to comment on reports that they have
avoided bombing Iraqi chemical plants, for fear of releasing deadly
substances. However, Shelton noted they have not gone after
``dual-use'' facilities that make both chemical weapons and
civilian products.
</P>
<P>
   There has apparently been no resistance by Iraqi military
forces, other than scattered and ineffective anti-aircraft
artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
   Officials refuse to say how many weapons have been launched at
these targets, though they have acknowledged that over 300 cruise
missiles have been fired _ at roughly $1 million apiece. They have
also said over 80 strike aircraft have dropped weapons, with most
carrying two to four laser-guided bombs; that's at least an
additional 200, or over 500 weapons in all.
</P>
<P>
   All this suggests each of the 89 targets has received, on
average, the firepower from at least five weapons. Some no doubt
were hit by more, others with fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials have raised the possibility of an early end to
the air strikes, due to the start this weekend of the Islamic
Ramadan holiday. Both Clinton and Cohen have promised to be
sensitive to this factor, but they haven't disclosed how long the
campaign might continue.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan has not stopped wars in the past. The 1973 Arab-Israeli
war took place during Ramadan. The Iran-Iraq war went on for eight
years with no breaks for the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   National security adviser Sandy Berger said Friday that Ramadan
``is not an automatic deadline'' to end the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign that military officers are looking toward a much
longer operation was the announcement Friday that more armed forces
are continuing to come into the Persian Gulf area.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Carl Vinson aircraft-carrier battle group was slated to
steam into the area Friday night. Additional troops and weapons
just started to load up from US shores Friday, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon Friday announced that bombs aren't the only thing
US aircraft were dropping on Iraq. They said A10 attack planes have
dropped leaflets on Iraqi soldiers in the southern part of the
country, warning them not to invade Kuwait again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraqi soldiers, save yourselves!'' one pamphlet reads. ``Only
those units who support the Baghdad regime were targeted. Your unit
was not targeted, but it is being watched. ... Stay in your
positions. Do not head south.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
