<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA-BOS &LR;      12-18 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT MEDIA STANDARDS BRING DIFFERENT COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Emerging from the US Capitol Friday after watching
the impeachment proceedings against President Clinton, Toni
Peterson shook her head in disgust when she glimpsed a legion of
television reporters across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so blown out of proportion,'' declared Peterson, 54, of
Salisbury, Md. ``The TV networks are a mess. I wish they would take
it completely off the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance. The appetite of networks and newspapers for the
White House sex scandal, insatiable all year, has been intensified
still further by the current impeachment drama. It is a drama in
which the media themselves have played a central, perhaps
unprecedented, role.
</P>
<P>
   L'affaire Clinton has illustrated how much the media culture has
changed since the last time a president was threatened with
impeachment, transformed into a national echo chamber by the
emergence of 24-hour cable news channels, with their indefatigable
talking heads, and by the increased willingness of reporters to
play pundit on weekend talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standards have changed tremendously,'' said Jack Nelson,
chief Washington correspondent for the Los Angeles Times, who
covered the final days of Richard Nixon's presidency in 1974. ``The
media has been aggressive in pushing for prosecution in this case.
I've never seen anything quite like it. In the Nixon case, they did
an objective job in covering it.''
</P>
<P>
   But one reporter/pundit whom Nelson singled out for criticism,
Cokie Roberts of ABC News, pointed to the impeachment proceedings
themselves as proof that the story of Clinton's affair with former
White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky _ and the charges of perjury,
abuse of power, and obstruction of justice spawned by the affair _
justified the media's unrelenting attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our point all along,'' Roberts said emphatically
Friday as she monitored the impeachment debate. ``You cannot have
staring you in the face the possibility of the removal of the
president of the United States and not cover it. The fact that the
details were tawdry is not our fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary McGrory, a columnist for The Washington Post, said that
``people are always telling me this story is media-driven. I think
in the beginning it was, but it acquired a momentum of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Most TV and print reporters interviewed during another hectic
workday Friday said they were just doing their jobs, that the
nature of the Clinton scandal demanded comprehensive coverage, and
that public hostility toward their role is not surprising because
the citizenry often takes a kill-the-messenger attitude toward
bearers of unwelcome news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots of times in our history that people have
been unhappy with the media, and thought the media is out of
step,'' said Roberts. ``What's different now is the pervasiveness,
now that we've got the 24-hour channels reporting every teeny
little factoid.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the magnitude of the moment began to sink in Friday,
there were also stirrings of media introspection.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said half-jokingly that she was ``proud of the fact that
the most explicit word I used all year was `breast.' '' while
reporting and analyzing the sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Franken, the respected congressional correspondent for CNN,
said he believes his own network behaved creditably in
distinguishing fact from ``self-serving leaks'' by insisting on two
credible sources for each story. But Franken expressed misgivings
that other members of the media did not hew to similar standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very easy to get too ambitious and cut corners, and
some people did,'' said Franken. ``There have been a lot of people
out there who have used this as a ratings ploy. ... There are many,
many, many reporters who are careless.''
</P>
<P>
   As he wrote his story on the House impeachment debate Friday,
Frank Aukofer, the veteran Washington bureau chief for the
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, mused about how much more attention the
media now pay to the personal lives of politicians than it did when
Aukofer covered the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we got here,'' said Aukofer. ``It's a
chicken-and-egg thing. Did we create it, or did the public demand
it?''
</P>
<P>
   There is little question in the mind of Nelson, the Los Angeles
Times correspondent, that the answer is the former when it comes to
the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media has done a lot to feed the fire of impeachment,'' he
said. ``An awful lot of them don't like Clinton, have never liked
him. A lot of what I've seen on television is unbelievable. There's
an intense competition to be first and wittiest. In the Nixon
impeachment story, the media was much more sober in the way they
approached it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roberts of ABC maintained that the story of the sexual
relationship between a president and an underling had ramifications
far beyond the political realm where it is now being thrashed out.
``One of the questions I brought up is what it means for young
women in the workplace,'' she said, adding that the president's
conduct sent a message that could create ``a hostile work
environment for other women.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the media's role in the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal
began almost as soon as the story broke. White House correspondent
Sam Donaldson was roundly condemned for saying after the story
erupted in January, that ``Mr. Clinton, if he's not telling the
truth and the evidence shows that, he will resign, perhaps this
week.'' NBC Washington bureau chief Tim Russert also drew flak for
booking Internet gossip Matt Drudge as a guest on ``Meet the
Press'' in January. (Drudge now has his own talk show on the Fox
News channel.)
</P>
<P>
   But the Washington media have also had to contend with an
unprecedented barrage of leaks, spin, and rumor throughout this
year, and have often been forced to chase stories aired or printed
by the competition. Reporters made clear Friday they are not
overjoyed at having been transformed into a ``sleaze patrol.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lister of the BBC's Washington bureau said he has
noticed how many thinly sourced stories the American media have
floated this year, but said that is partly due to the elusive
nature of the truth when it came to the Lewinsky matter. ``The BBC
has always been particular about sources, but so much about this
story is difficult to pin down,'' said Lister.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans alike have aggressively worked the
Washington media throughout this year, jockeying for spots before
the microphone at places like the ``elm tree site'' where Franken
and other TV reporters were stationed Friday. At one point Friday,
Representative Patrick Kennedy, Democrat of Rhode Island, was
denouncing the impeachment proceedings in an interview with Franken
while, footsteps away, Representative J.D. Hayworth, Republican of
Arizona, was defending them.
</P>
<P>
   As the interviews ended, the spin continued. Hayworth cracked to
Franken: ``If you want the real story, I'll talk to you.'' A few
moments later, Kennedy drew Franken aside and asked if he could do
another interview after the debate, vowing to ``come in swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Franken and Carl Cameron of the Fox News channel voiced
qualms Friday about the growing prominence of talking heads on
network talk shows, who they said often know less than they pretend
to know and seldom have contact with the principals of stories they
opine about.
</P>
<P>
   But despite those qualms, and his concerns over some parts of
the media handled the story, Franken defends the coverage overall.
``Was all this coverage appropriate?'' he asked. ``You bet. Because
of the high stakes involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
