<SLUG> BC-BOXER-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. BOXER SEEKS A SPEEDY RESOLUTION TO IMPEACHMENT IN THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., held out the
possibility Friday that President Clinton might avoid a Senate
trial after an expected impeachment vote by the House on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that six or more Republicans might defect and team
up with Democrats to abort such a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senate rules don't compel lawmakers to automatically conduct a
trial, Boxer said. The rules allow lawmakers to scuttle the
proceedings and devise a penalty, short of removal from office,
such as censure or a fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many colleagues want to go that route,'' Boxer said.
But she declined to name any Republicans who might be in that
group.
</P>
<P>
   A simple majority, or 51 votes, is required to pursue the
no-trial option, she contended. In January, when the Senate takes
up the impeachment issue, it will have 55 Republicans and 45
Democrats, meaning that at least six Republicans would be needed to
avoid a trial.
</P>
<P>
   If a trial is held, Republicans may find it difficult to convict
Clinton on any article of impeachment. In order to gain the
necessary two-thirds majority required by the Constitution to
convict and remove a president from office, 12 Democrats would have
to break ranks, assuming all 100 senators vote.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's remarks run counter to comments by Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who has said that if the House
impeaches Clinton, the Senate will hold a trial rather than quickly
settle on a punishment short of removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the Senate would proceed if Clinton is impeached, Lott
said this week that it would take the first ``preliminary steps''
toward a trial shortly after it convenes Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   As attention shifts to the Senate, Boxer said that Clinton's
support runs high among Democrats. ``I don't know any Democrats in
the Senate that say he should resign,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer is related to Clinton by marriage. Her daughter Nicole is
the wife of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's brother Tony
Rodham.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., predicted Thursday that the
Senate ultimately will settle on a punishment less severe than
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president will always have the stigma of being impeached''
by the House, Feinstein said. ``I don't know how much blood, so to
speak, one feels you have to get out of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   She rejected the idea that the Senate might be able to conduct
regular business during the day and devote evenings to an
impeachment trial. ``The Senate, during time of impeachment, will
be consumed by the matter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's Aug. 17 admission of an inappropriate
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern,
Feinstein was highly critical of the president, asserting that her
faith in his credibility had been ``shattered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
