<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SOLDIERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD DRAMA CAN'T BREACH CADETS' HOLIDAY JOVIALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ As their commander in chief was nearing
impeachment, as their comrades in arms were pounding Iraq, 11 men
and one woman tossed their caps high in the air Friday and stood
before a tumultuous world as the newest graduates of the United
States Military Academy.
</P>
<P>
   The brief graduation ceremonies, for West Point cadets who
missed the larger and more traditional May commencement, were a
celebratory reminder that the nation's underpinnings remained in
place and its civic and institutional lives carried on, even as
Washington smoldered and Baghdad burned.
</P>
<P>
   In other countries at such unsettling times, West Point might
easily be imagined as the seat of dissent for a restive and
independent military. Instead, the academy built on the site George
Washington called ``The Gibraltar of America'' was a hotspot of
holiday cheer, a bunker of best wishes.
</P>
<P>
   At the graduation in Eisenhower Hall, named for the academy
graduate-turned-president, families and friends basked in the
achievements of the 12 newly minted Army second lieutenants, who
stood at attention in their finest uniforms, white gloves, dress
sabers and the maroon sashes that signified their ascent into the
ranks of officers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the academy's walls, the adjacent town of Highland Falls
looked almost suspiciously like the fictional Bedford Falls from
``It's a Wonderful Life,'' its stores bedecked with wreaths and
ribbons, its residents shopping and dining, laughing and calling
greetings to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, beneath the surface, there were deeply held beliefs
about the impeachment proceedings and the bombing campaign, as well
as the revelations the night before about the next House speaker's
own infidelities. But they could be elicited only from civilians
and only with prodding, in keeping with the military's prohibitions
on speaking out publicly against a superior officer or elected
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their own private thoughts about it, of course.
But I haven't seen too much heated, open discussion of it here, and
I doubt you will, either,'' said Col. Rick Machamer, director of
West Point's new Center for the Professional Military Ethic.
</P>
<P>
   The center was organized to promote character development and
help enforce the West Point Honor Code, whose words seemed to have
been written by the House Republicans pressing toward President
Clinton's impeachment: ``A cadet will not lie, cheat or steal, or
tolerate those who do.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, those words rolled off the tongue of Toni Parry, 49,
owner of The Okemo Inn in Ludlow, Vt., whose son graduated from
West Point in 1997. She returned to the academy to watch a friend
of her son graduate Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For four years, they lived here under a code of honor. They
take pretty much the same oath that the president takes,'' said
Parry, who was picking out West Point Christmas tree ornaments in
the academy's gift shop. ``We should expect nothing less of our
president than we do of our cadets.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Ortland of nearby Newburgh, a 1982 West Point graduate who
now works as an IBM engineering manager, saw a silver lining in the
president's problems. ``It's heightening awareness of morality.
Maybe it will make the country a more moral place,'' said Ortland,
38. As he spoke, his wife picked through Army-themed gifts, from
stuffed bears wearing West Point shirts to framed posters with the
phrase, ``Eat, Drink and Beat Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not one of nearly two dozen people interviewed Friday on or near
the academy grounds said they thought the Iraq attack was a ploy to
delay the impeachment vote, though several declined to comment,
citing their own or their relatives' military oath. Several said
impeachment should have waited until American forces were out of
harm's way, but there was general confidence the country would not
be damaged by its current travails.
</P>
<P>
   There also was near-unanimity that Clinton and Saddam Hussein
deserved their respective fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was head of any major corporation, he would have been
fired and sued,'' said Wallace Gibbs, an airline trainer from
Dallas. ``It's embarrassing to the country, but he needed to be
impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Williams, 25, a hotel manager from Chicago, said the Iraq
bombing was overdue: ``I think it's scary, but I think it was the
only choice, the right thing to do. At first I wondered about the
timing, but I don't think it was just for politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was so focused. At the Park Restaurant, across
Main Street from the academy, waiter Donald Pozo spoke for those
who cared neither about impeachment nor Iraq: ``It has nothing to
do with me, my life, so I'm not paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   At the graduation ceremonies, no mention was made of either
issue. In blessing the new lieutenants, Rev. Edson J. Wood spoke of
``this afternoon's drama'' but it was clear he meant only the
culmination of more than four grueling years of cadet life.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when the commandant of cadets, Brigadier Gen. John P.
Abizaid, told the dozen members of the graduating class and their
250 guests to ``lead by personal example'' and ``put selfless
service above self-interest'' it was hard not to think of the
debate going on in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the graduation, West Point's granite buildings and cadets
in gray tunics stood as tall and straight as ever, buffeted but
unbowed by cold winds that whipped past Bear and Breakneck
mountains and onto the academy fields. Clusters of cadets raced
across The Plain, a parade ground that dates to Revolutionary days,
and onto waiting buses to catch holiday flights home.
</P>
<P>
   During a bus tour of the academy, there were snickers when the
guide pointed out the ruins of Fort Clinton. She quickly noted that
it was named for Gen. George Clinton; its original name, Fort
Arnold, was changed after the honoree _ Gen. Benedict Arnold _
tried to betray the Colonial forces.
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid was that Fort Clinton leads to ``Flirtation Walk,''
a wooded trail reserved for cadets and their most personal guests.
There is a huge pair of painted lips on a rock halfway down the
trail; according to legend, if a guest refuses a cadet's request
for a kiss, the entire academy will crumble into the Hudson River
below.
</P>
<P>
   At the West Point Museum, which celebrates the academy's
196-year history as well as the much longer history of warfare,
homage is paid to alums with names like Lee, Grant, Patton,
Bradley, MacArthur and Schwarzkopf.
</P>
<P>
   Display cases bulge with dioramas of battle scenes, muskets and
M16s, mementos from bygone Army-Navy games, and a saber carried by
Gen. Thaddeus Kosciuszko, a Pole who served with the Continental
Army and who helped design West Point. On it, in Spanish, is an
inscription that seemed metaphorically applicable to both the
impeachment debate and the bombing of Iraq: ``Do not draw me
without reason; Do not sheath me without honor.''
</P>
<P>
   But another, more modern name was also prominent in the museum.
In the gift shop, seven copies of Kenneth Starr's Report to
Congress stood on an eye-level shelf, waiting for buyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
