<HEADER>
A7631 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COPPER-PAINTING-AZR &LR;      12-18 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPPER-PAINTING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OLD MASTERS' FIND DEPTH IN COPPER CANVAS  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The new show at the Phoenix Art Museum is called
``Copper as Canvas,'' but forget the copper, you can't really see
it, anyway. It is covered up with paint.
</P>
<P>
   But what paint! The show is one of the best in years at the
museum and is a must-see for anyone who loves art.
</P>
<P>
   It began as a piece of scholarship. Museum curator Michael
Komanecky and his colleagues have done an exhaustive amount of work
on the question of when, why and how artists used copper as a base
to paint on.
</P>
<P>
   We know a great deal about the canvases and wood panels most
artists used, but until now, we knew much less about the sheets of
copper that were sometimes used from the 16th to 18th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   For that research, gathered in a spiffy catalog that will be
published in February, we must thank Komanecky and the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as I said, you cannot see the copper in question, because
so many artists have hidden it with really wonderful images.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the show special are those images, and the artists
who made them.
</P>
<P>
   And there are some big names: Rembrandt, El Greco, Claude,
Chardin, Guido Reni and others. This is a show of what used to be
called ``Old Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the copper does mean something; you (BEGIN ITAL) can (END
ITAL) see a difference.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that artists chose to paint on copper was
that the metal was very smooth, flat and dimensionally stable. With
canvas, you cannot paint images more detailed than the weave of the
fabric; it is a limiting factor. With wood panels, you can make the
surface smooth, but you always run into the warping and checking of
the wood as it is subjected to temperature and humidity changes.
</P>
<P>
   Copper solved both problems.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most of the paintings in this show are notable both
for the incredible detail and for the smoothness of their paint _
almost like enamel.
</P>
<P>
   Few artists used copper exclusively, but Jan Brueghel the Elder
came close. The son of the more peculiar Pieter Brueghel and father
of the more obscure Jan Brueghel the Younger, he was also the
younger brother of the painter Pieter Brueghel the Younger.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dynasty of artists, but a confusing clan, made slightly
more coherent by their nicknames. The paterfamilias was known as
``Peasant'' Brueghel for the many peasant paintings he made; his
son, Pieter the Younger, is known as ``Hell'' Brueghel for the
popular depictions of perdition he created. And Jan the Elder is
known as ``Velvet'' Brueghel for his incredible ability to produce
detail and texture.
</P>
<P>
   It was copper that made the detail possible.
</P>
<P>
   And it is that ability that is so stunning in this show. Over
and over _ and he is the best represented painter in the show _ he
creates paintings of such incredibly fine detail that you are
reminded of modern microsurgery. He must have painted with a brush
with only one bristle, and what is more, that single bristle must
have been somehow sharpened like a tiny pencil into an even more
delicate point.
</P>
<P>
   As you look into his ``Harbor Scene With St. Paul's Departure
From Caesarea,'' painted in 1596, you can hardly find St. Paul in
the crowd. Although the painting is only 14- by 21-inches, it
depicts at least 200 people on the dock, and you can make out the
faces and expressions of most of them.
</P>
<P>
   There are also more than 30 ships and boats in the scene, about
50 newly caught fish, a city and a mountain range. That's a lot of
information to store in such a small picture. Gigabytes.
</P>
<P>
   But the surface is smooth and incredibly beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the issue of another important contribution made by
the copper. Whether it is, as claimed, the reflection of the light
off the metal below the pigment, or just the creamy smoothness of
the paint on such a polished surface, the paint nevertheless seems
to glow with rich, glorious color.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's installation helps this, with each painting _ most
of them small _ lit like a jewel so it sparkles.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, you come up with a start as a painting seems more
exquisite than you had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   There is the tiny ``Allegory of Painting'' by Frans van Mieris
I, from 1661, which is a stunning portrait of a Dutch woman in a
steely blue satin dress. She holds a dramatic mask, a painter's
palette and a plaster statue that is so white it almost seems
incandescent.
</P>
<P>
   Or the ``Floral Still Life With Shells'' from 1622 by Balthasar
van der Ast, which is rich as pastry.
</P>
<P>
   Or the profoundly moving face in the 1750 ``Portrait of an Old
Woman'' by Christian Seybold, with skin as translucent as the real
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The use of copper petered out around the time of the American
Revolution for several reasons. Perhaps the most obvious from the
show is that painters, with their brushwork loosened up and their
subjects more generalized, no longer were concerned with profuse
detail. They simply no longer needed the copper.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious in the paintings: When you get to the time of
Chardin, you begin to see the origins of Impressionism that would
follow a century later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copper as Canvas'' is notable for a couple of other things,
too. Included are a large number of New World paintings, mostly
Mexican, that show the importance of copper among Spanish Colonial
painters.
</P>
<P>
   And there is considerable background information on the mining
and smelting of copper, with large chunks of the stuff on view,
including several raw ingots and a tall wisp of native copper that
might as well be a 20th Century sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   But over and over, I come back to the work of Brueghel. In
``Ceres and the Four Elements,'' painting in 1604 in collaboration
with Hendrick van Balen, you fall into a sybaritic reverie of
animals and textures. Van Balen painted the figures, and they are
rather conventional, but Brueghel surrounded them with a veritable
Eden of finny, furry, feathered life and intensely colored
wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   It is the work of a man obviously in love with the things of
this world, and he communicates that love to us, standing in
appreciation in front of the painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copper as Canvas'' will travel to the Nelson Atkins Museum in
Kansas City, Mo., after it closes here, and then will move on to
the Mauritshuis in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for a show to originate at a prestigious
European museum and travel through the United States. It is a
wonderful thing for Phoenix that we can mount a show worthy of
returning the favor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
