u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANFRAN-HOMELESS-DEAT     12-18 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-HOMELESS-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO REPORTS RECORD NUMBER OF HOMELESS PEOPLE DIED IN
1998 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL STAGGS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More homeless people died in San Francisco in
the last 12 months than in any year since the tracking began, an
increase that has alarmed and frustrated advocates for the homeless
and city health workers.
</P>
<P>
   The 157 deaths were detailed in the Homeless Death Review,
issued this week by the San Francisco Department of Public Health
and covering the period from December 1997 through November 30.
Last year's report counted 104 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The review, the third such analysis since the city took over the
annual project from a neighborhood newspaper, is compiled from data
released by the medical examiner's office. The breakdown indicates
how deadly life on the streets has become in San Francisco, where
the mayor's office estimates that 4,000 people are homeless on any
given night. There are at most 2,000 emergency shelter beds.
</P>
<P>
   The causes of death range from drowning to asthma, but substance
abuse is the leading killer.
</P>
<P>
   Drug overdoses were responsible in 62 cases, either from heroin
alone or in combination with other drugs. Ten died from
alcohol-related problems. Seven had heart disease, and two died
from AIDS. Seven committed suicide, six were murdered, and five
died after being struck by cars. The average age at time of death
was 42.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials and advocates were reluctant to name specific
reasons for the increase. Many cited the intense winter, while
others blamed police sweeps that displaced many homeless from
places like Golden Gate Park.
</P>
<P>
   Housing is scarce, too, according to Marian Pena, director of
the Department of Public Health's homeless program.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just can't find housing,'' Ms. Pena said. ``Hundreds of
units have been lost to fires or to tourism, with a room with no
bath renting for $600 and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Heroin also played a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a huge increase in the number of heroin-related
deaths in the past two years,'' Ms. Pena said. ``It has been more
pure, cheaper and in some cases contaminated.''
 &UR; OPTIONAL CUT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kandace Bender, Mayor Willie Brown's press secretary, said the
major role of drugs and alcohol in the deaths was something Brown
has made efforts to address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last three years,'' Ms. Bender said, ``the mayor has
provided $11 million for substance abuse programs and mobile
outreach programs. The mayor is very concerned about this problem,
and continues to work on a continuum of care that combines shelter,
outreach, counseling, jobs, and transitional housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Boden, director of the San Francisco Coalition on
Homelessness and a participant in the report's creation since its
inception, said he would like to see city officials find a way to
better use the information agencies have gathered on the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so frustrating,'' Boden said, ``is that for all these
folks that they are finding dead in the city, there is a lot of
information available about them. They have been through intake
programs, screenings, for substance abuse, for housing. All that
information is centralized. But the information is simply not being
used.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; END OPTIONAL CUT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a modest attempt at intervention, the public health
department last year initiated a Death Prevention Program, made up
of three health care workers and a nurse, an under-funded program
that does not even have a vehicle for its rounds of the city's
poorest areas. The team attempts to identify high-risk cases and
get individuals into treatment quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some resources,'' Ms. Pena said, ``but we don't have
enough. We need to stop pretending that we do have enough. And it's
absolutely futile to talk about substance abuse without dealing
with the housing issue.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
