<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-DEBATE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GSU Senate condemns Holocaust ads
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the first time in the three years since its
student newspaper began running ads questioning whether the
Holocaust actually happened, a cross-section of the entire Georgia
State University community this week condemned the advertisements
and the group paying for them.
</P>
<P>
   By passing a resolution that ``categorically rejects the
position ... that the Holocaust did not take place,'' the
University Senate _ comprising students, faculty, staff and
administrators _ hopes to pressure the student newspaper, the
Signal, to stop running ads provided by the Committee for Open
Debate on the Holocaust, based in San Diego. The University Senate
has no power over the Signal. ``It has run three times in our
student paper and it became clear that it would continue to run on
an annual basis, so we tried to do something,'' said Carol Winkler,
chairwoman of the Senate Executive Committee.
</P>
<P>
   This year's ad, which appeared Sept. 8, offered $250,000 to
anyone who can arrange a nationally televised debate between CODOH
and the Anti-Defamation League, which combats anti-Semitism and
other forms of discrimination, on such issues as whether gas
chambers were used to exterminate Jews and if ``The Diary of Anne
Frank'' is fiction, not fact.
</P>
<P>
   Signal editor Jennifer Smith said the paper's ad policy states
that ads will not be rejected because of the political or personal
views of the person or group running it. It's also a First
Amendment matter, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``As supporters of free speech, the Signal does not feel any
paper, administrator, faculty group or individual has the right to
determine which opinion is worthy of being heard and which is
not,'' Smith said. ``The fact that a particular opinion might be
offensive to some does not excuse censorship in any form.''
</P>
<P>
   Several college newspapers, including those at Georgia Tech and
Emory University, have refused the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler, who, as chairwoman of GSU's communications department,
supports free speech, said the Signal has to look deeper at how the
decision to run the ad affects other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Jewish members of our community, to have their history
denied is offensive to them and makes them question whether they
are fully integrated into our community,'' said Winkler. ``And the
community needs to send a strong signal that we are aware of what
happened. Our heads are not buried in the sand on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said no one at the Signal believes the Holocaust never
happened, adding that the issue is old news and that it is time for
the paper and university to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Signal is well aware of the plethora of evidence proving
the existence of the Holocaust and believes the CODOH ad calls for
the debate of some issues, not the denial of the Holocaust,'' said
Smith. ``As with any newspaper, the acceptance of an ad for
publication is not an indicator of the paper's position of the
content of the ad. Accepting the CODOH ad for publication is in no
way to be construed as acceptance of or agreement with the opinions
expressed in the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
