<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kuhlman bought by Borg-Warner
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Savannah-based Kuhlman Inc., which has been on a
five-year acquisition spree, will itself be bought by Borg-Warner
Automotive Inc. in a deal valued at as much as $750 million in
cash, stock and debt.
</P>
<P>
   For Chicago-based Borg-Warner, the prize is Kuhlman's booming
Schwitzer Group subsidiary, which makes turbochargers that add
power to diesel engines. The unit accounted for $346 million, or 54
percent, of the company's 1997 sales of $643 million.
</P>
<P>
   Borg-Warner, the world's largest maker of automatic transmission
parts, said it would sell the rest of Kuhlman's businesses once the
acquisition is completed. The company also makes power and
instrument transformers and electronic wires and cables.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhlman shares jumped 18 percent Friday to close at $37.37 1/2,
up $5.87 1/2. Borg-Warner shares closed at $50.75, down 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is subject to Kuhlman shareholders' approval as well as
regulatory approval. It is expected to close in the first quarter
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, at Kuhlman Corp., found Borg-Warner's offer attractive and
felt compelled to accept it as being in the best interests of our
shareholders,'' said Roger S. Jepson Jr., chairman and chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent and continuing changes in the transportation and
automotive industries favor larger and internationally-based
organizations,'' he added. `` Our Schwitzer Group and its employees
will now be part of a much larger organization which will be
well-positioned to thrive and to be more responsive to the global
needs of its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuhlman spokesman Rick Walker said Borg-Warner also intends to
close Kuhlman's Savannah headquarters, which moved to the coastal
city from Lexington, Ky., in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhlman employs a total of 4,454 people at 30 facilities in five
countries. The only Georgia facility is a Schwitzer Group plant in
Gainesville that employs 220 workers. Schwitzer's total employment
is 2,803, while Kuhlman Electric and Coleman Cable together employ
1,633 and account for $300 million in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhlman has acquired six companies since December 1993,
including the 1995 acquisition of Schwitzer that put it in the
turbocharger business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do at least one a year,'' Jepson said earlier this year
when the company was ranked fifth in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's annual Best of Business top 10 survey of
Georgia public companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dream no small dreams,'' said Jepson, a former banker who
operates Jepson Vineyards in Ukiah, Calif., in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   The Kuhlman purchase is Borg-Warner's second in a month. The
company completed its purchase last week of Germany's AG Kuhnle,
Kopp &AMP; Kausch's turbocharger division for an undisclosed amount of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Turbocharger sales are booming, driven by the need for fuel
economy and mandated clean air standards. Makers of auto and truck
parts have been consolidating to broaden their product lines and
offer complete parts systems as automakers seek to cut
manufacturing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew LaGrone, an analyst at Birmingham-based Sterne, Agee and
Leach who follows Kuhlman, said the company's sales have been
growing by 22 percent and net income by 57 percent, compounded
annually, during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   But stock performance has not kept pace, said LaGrone. The stock
remains well off its 52-week high of $51.37 1/2, reached in March.
LaGrone has forecast 16 percent net income growth for Kuhlman in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted more acquisitions of smaller, high-performing
companies like Kuhlman by larger firms, because the stock market
does not favor the smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the market won't reward them with valuation, another
company will by buying them up,'' LaGrone said.
</P>
<P>
   Borg-Warner offered $39 per share, or $660 million. The
transaction includes both cash and $150 million of stock, which
will be issued to Kuhlman shareholders. The company will pay $510
million in cash and assume about $80 million to $90 million of
Kuhlman's debt, John Fiedler, Borg-Warner's chairman and chief
executive, told Bloomberg News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
