<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deadline on water extended for a year
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Georgia, Florida and Alabama now have another
year beyond the original Dec. 31 deadline to settle their
decade-old water war.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the governors of the three states, meeting in
Montgomery on Friday, signed agreements to extend until Dec. 31,
1999, the deadline for devising a water allocation formula to
divide up the waters of two river basins: the
Alabama-Coosa-Tallapoosa basin (ACT) and the
Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint basin (ACF). The ACT basin flows
through Georgia and Alabama, but the waters of the ACF are shared
by all three states.
</P>
<P>
   Under two interstate water compacts approved last year by
Congress, negotiators for the three states began deliberations in
February to come up with a formula that would guarantee each state
an equitable share of the waters from the basins. However, devising
such a plan has proved complicated, and the three states still have
major differences over how much water each state will get.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a long way to go, but there is a light at the
end of the tunnel,'' said Richard Laird, the chief negotiator for
Alabama. Each state has its own different proposal for how the
waters will be divided, and the negotiators are trying to work out
a plan that all three states can agree on.
</P>
<P>
   No state will get all the water it wants. ``If each of the
states cannot agree to give up something, then we will face
failure,'' said Bob Kerr, Georgia's chief negotiator. ``A year (to
come up with a formula) is a short time; the tasking is immense.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake for Georgia in the negotiations is enough water to
nurture metro Atlanta's growth and most of the growth of North
Georgia. In exchange for guarantees of enough water for growth
during the next 30 years, Georgians may have to pay higher
electricity rates as hydropower production is reduced. Strict
limits on water for irrigation may be imposed on southwest Georgia
farmers. In metro Atlanta, permanent restrictions on outdoor
watering and other stern conservation measures may be put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Thomas, who was appointed by President Clinton to
represent federal agencies in the negotiations, said that while the
deliberators are concerned most about water quantity, they also
must be concerned about keeping the water clean and enough of it
flowing in rivers and streams to support fish and other aquatic
life.
</P>
<P>
   If the negotiators fail to agree on a water allocation formula,
then the water war will be thrown into the Supreme Court for
settlement. Thomas also has the authority under the interstate
compacts to veto an agreement if it is not acceptable to federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
