<HEADLINE>
SEN. KENNEDY WANTS CIGARETTE TAX TO PAY FOR MEDICARE DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ US Senator Edward M. Kennedy Friday said he will file
legislation for a 70-cent tax on a pack of cigarettes to help pay
for the uncovered drug costs of Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy unveiled the plan at a State House press conference
during which officials also announced that four major HMOs have
agreed to help subsidize seniors' prescription costs not covered by
the federal health insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a loophole in a 1997 federal law that allowed
Medicare HMOs to begin capping drug benefits in Massachusetts,
seniors and lawmakers have been scrambling to find a way to bridge
the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, Governor Paul Cellucci and Mayor Thomas M. Menino have
been pressuring the state's largest HMOs to put aside their bottom
lines and help ease what could be a financial crisis for thousands
of elderly people in the state when the policy change takes effect
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Fallon Community Health Plan became the fourth HMO in
the state to establish a financial assistance program to aid
seniors with high drug costs. Fallon said it would commit $2
million to help seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon officials said that figure could increase depending on
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new transitional plan gives seniors with high prescription
costs an opportunity to continue receiving medication they need
without undue financial harship,'' said Fallon co-executive
director James J. Egan. ``Short of offering unlimited prescription
benefits, we believe this is the best alternative for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   With Fallon now on board, all four will provide some additional
coverage _ but just for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains, then what?
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months ago, a federal judge barred Massachusetts from
implementing its own law guaranteeing seniors the option of
unlimited prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he will ``continue to demand that Congress allow
us to reimplement our own law that provides unlimited drug benefits
to seniors at no cost to the state or federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kennedy said he wanted a new 70-cent tobacco tax to fund
Medicare drug coverage nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine percent of the private sector companies provide
(drug coverage) but the federal government does not,'' Kennedy
said. ``I'm a strong believer that we should. And I'm going to
introduce legislation that will. And I'll pay for it by an
additional 70 cents on the tobacco tax. That will provide the
funding for all of this need nationwide for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's plan could put Cellucci, who has taken a no new taxes
pledge, in an awkward spot while trying to find a solution for the
drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't support raising taxes here in Massachusetts.
I think I've said in the past the extent that raising taxes here
puts us in an uncompetitive position, I don't think that's a good
thing,'' Cellucci said. ``Because it would be a national situation,
I find that less objectionable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
