<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7642 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DICTIONARIES-AZR &LR;      12-18 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICTIONARIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SHOW! BUT DICTIONARY ISN'T LAST WORD  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I have often thought of simplifying my life, dumping
most of my possessions in a misguided attempt to make living
easier. I hear Henry Thoreau's voice in the back of my head:
``Simplify, simplify.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the shedding of the snakeskin, and the urge hits strongest
for most of us right after a divorce, or just before we move to a
new house.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this scheme for me has always been to get rid of the
mountain of books in my house and slim down to those I would
consider essential. That means a King James Bible and a complete
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   But when I make such schemes, I know that there are other things
I cannot do without: Among them is a dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   And immediately, things start getting complicated. For no single
dictionary is sufficient. To this day, 243 years after Samuel
Johnson brought out the first popularly successful English-language
dictionary, not one is entirely satisfactory. The best is the
Oxford English Dictionary _ a huge multivolume tome _ but it has
two strikes against it. It is English rather than American, and it
was completed in 1928 and even with its supplements is dreadfully
out of date in an MTV world.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as the Random House Webster's Dictionary, market
their book as a repository of all the newest, trendiest words. If
you want to know what a ``pop-up video'' is or a ``valley girl,''
you need to have one of these with-it word books.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, none of them is as scholarly or inclusive as the
OED.
</P>
<P>
   So that has always meant that I need more than one. So much for
simplifying one's life.
</P>
<P>
   And now, another kind of dictionary has come out: one that
features lots and lots and lots of pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The Illustrated Oxford Dictionary (DK Publishing, $45 until
January; $50 after that) is this season's flashiest new entry into
the field. It is chock-a-block with helpful drawings and
photographs, showing you rather than merely telling you, what a
forceps is, or a hansom cab.
</P>
<P>
   Older dictionaries often had illustrations, too, mostly
postage-stamp size pictures of black-and-white aardvarks or
dibbles. But they were usually dated and inadequate _ although they
often maintain the attraction of nostalgia we have developed for
them from the first dictionaries we consulted in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   The new IOD, however, uses illustrations as a primary means of
defining some words. It is certainly easier to see a murex shell
than to understand one solely from the defining words. Once you see
one, all spiky and purple, you are not likely to forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, there is no aardvark picture, only a definition
that calls it a ``nocturnal animal of southern Africa . . . with a
tubular snout and a long tongue, that feeds on termites.''
</P>
<P>
   Compare this with Sam Johnson's definition of a rhinoceros: ``A
vast beast of the Indies armed with a horn on his front.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new dictionary is generally promiscuous with pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The entry on golf shows a photograph of a man in plaid trousers
_ what else? _ holding a 5-iron. Under him are all the clubheads
currently used in the game, from wood to wedge, and a map of a
schematized 18-hole golf course. It takes up half a page.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the entries are more like brief encyclopedia articles
than dictionary definitions. One very pretty page is given over to
showing the different kinds of fruit, all in full color, with whole
and halved fruits spread out graphically on the paper.
</P>
<P>
   It contains 180,000 definitions and 4,500 full-color
illustrations. It includes such current words and phrases as
``voice mail'' and ``velociraptor.'' Some 600 entries are full- or
half-page ``feature illustrations'' that depict, for instance,
eight kinds of dolphins, both oceanic and river, and a separate
cutaway view of dolphin anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   The book is out just in time for Christmas gift giving; and no
doubt, it is an excellent dictionary to give to a young student.
Perhaps it is the best for a grammar-school pupil.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the dictionary I have been looking for. It will
not simplify my life.
</P>
<P>
   Although, it does simplify the language: It is only interested
in defining words and showing pictures of them. A real dictionary
does much more.
</P>
<P>
   There are no etymologies in it, for instance, and no quotations.
A dictionary like this leaves its readers asea when it comes to the
fine points of what a word means. And it is those fine points that
are not only most interesting, but carry the emotional weight of
the language.
</P>
<P>
   For words are not merely the equal of their definitions. They
are like ink spots dropped on a blotter, with a clearly defined
center, but a spreading nimbus of meaning diffusing out in
irregular patterns.
</P>
<P>
   There are no synonyms in the English language. The very idea is
a phantom. Each variation of an idea carries with it a different
connotational universe.
</P>
<P>
   If you think a ``collier'' is a coal miner, think again. You
cannot think of a coal miner without thinking also of banjoes and
guitars; or a collier without his brass bands playing
``Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   They even have different literatures, with D.H. Lawrence on one
side and Loretta Lynn on the other.
</P>
<P>
   A dictionary like the OED gives us so many quotations _ usage
examples _ that as we ferret through the book, we learn some of the
finer distinctions that allow us to use the word with a proper
appreciation of its perfect cultural pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The IOD is, by that standard, tone deaf.
</P>
<P>
   So, when I slough off that lizard skin and fulfill my fantasy of
an unencumbered life, this new dictionary will not be part of it.
But I may have to cart around the sheer poundage of the OED.
</P>
<P>
   Life is never simple. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Richard Nilsen can be reached at richard.nilsen(at)pni.com  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
