<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA CONSTITUENTS SHRUG OFF LIVINGSTON NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   METAIRIE, La. _ News of infidelities by the House speaker-elect,
Robert L. Livingston, was instant fodder for the morning talk shows
in his congressional district Friday, and judging from the
reaction, Livingston is in no political trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As the chatter bubbled over WWL radio's ``The Andre Show,''
broadcast live from Livingston's hometown of Metairie, callers
rallied to his defense and railed instead at President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy from Kenner observed that ``if every congressman who had
an affair turned to dust then Washington would look like a desert.
. . . On personal matters, the media should lose freedom of the
press.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger from Metairie asked the show's hostess, Andre Trevigne, to
``use your investigative powers to find out who's going to get the
million dollars from Larry Flynt. Maybe Bill Clinton's going to get
the money.''
</P>
<P>
   News reports had identified Hustler magazine as the source of
disclosures about Livingston. But the magazine's publisher, Larry
Flynt, who had offered up to $1 million for tips on infidelities by
congressmen, denied his publication was behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most radio talk shows have a conservative
constituency, but so does Livingston's district. Although President
Clinton carried Louisiana in 1996, he won only 37 percent of the
vote in Livingston's 1st congressional district. Livingston, on the
other hand, has been re-elected without opposition in the last two
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The district covers three rural parishes north of Lake
Pontchartrain as well as the predominantly white suburbs
surrounding New Orleans, where the warrens of bungalows and
stretches of strip malls have little of the character of the
state's colorful politics.
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as Louisiana repeatedly returned Edwin W. Edwards to
the governor's office even as he boasted of his extramarital
affairs, a groundswell rising against Livingston seems that much
more unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   A forgiving editorial Friday in The Times-Picayune of New
Orleans, which commended Livingston for being ``forthright about
what he had done,'' seemed to sum up local sentiment. ``There is a
feeling of disappointment, of course. But his willingness to take
responsibility for his actions is arguably part of what makes him a
leader,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's Republican allies also were quick with expressions
of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably a lot of people are disappointed, but that's not to
say that he will have to step down,'' said Jon Gegenheimer, clerk
of the Jefferson Parish court system and a prominent Republican.
``I think it will blow over just like the case of Henry Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, admitted
earlier this year to an adulterous affair. The disclosure had
little effect on his role in Congress or his stature in his home
district in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson Serio, a Metairie accountant who serves on the state's
Republican central committee, said the news of Livingston's
indiscretion ``came as a surprise, but it won't have much impact on
his constituency.'' Serio, a member of a Christian right faction
that controls the committee, called Livingston ``an extraordinarily
honorable person, and people appreciate the honorable way he stood
up and spoke out.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Livingston's announcement would disminish the
congressman's popularity, Steve Swain, another member of the state
GOP committee, said, ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of Livingston's friends, Swain turned the topic toward
Clinton. ``I have to be really partisan and say that the Democrats
want to destroy the messenger. Clinton's problem is based on
perjury, not adultery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Renwick, director of the Institute of Politics at Loyola
University in New Orleans, said he doubts Livingston will suffer
much political damage. ``This might bring somebody out of the
woodwork to challenge him in the year 2000, but if he does a good
job as speaker he shouldn't have any trouble. This is not that big
a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Powell, a professor specializing in Louisiana history at
Tulane University, sounded one of the few discouraging words:
sanctimonious. ``That's the thing that bothers me, Livingston being
so sanctimonious,'' Powell said. ``But I don't think the people
will give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Charles Lancaster, a Metairie Republican,
said Livingston has such a ``reservoir of good will'' that he can
overcome his current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Even the executive director of the state Democratic Party, Trey
Ourso, minimized the political consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a really secure district,'' Ourso said. ``It's been so
long since he was challenged, I don't know if he could ever be
beaten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
