<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAGAN-KIDNAPPING-BOS &LR;      12-18 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAGAN-KIDNAPPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER IN ALLEGED KIDNAP READY TO MAKE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE AND ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Stephen Fagan's attorney and two daughters will meet
Monday with Middlesex District Attorney Thomas Reilly to discuss a
deal in which Fagan would plead guilty to parental kidnapping
charges but escape jail time.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which sources said is likely to be accepted, would
mark an abrupt turnaround from the public stance of prosecutors who
had pledged to bring the case to trial.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with the daughters' unwavering support for Fagan _ who
took the children from their mother 19 years ago and raised them
under new identities in Florida _ prosecutors felt that they would
have a difficult time convincing a judge or jury that Fagan
deserved to be jailed, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The session between Fagan's daughters and prosecutors will
follow an 11 a.m. meeting in which Barbara Kurth, the girls' mother
and Fagan's ex-wife, will be updated by Reilly, the outgoing DA,
his successor Martha Coakley and assistant DA Lynn Rooney, who is
prosecuting the case.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan has argued that he felt compelled to take the girls, then
5 and 2 years old, from Kurth, whom he described as an alcoholic
and a neglectful mother. He told the girls, Rachael and Lisa, that
their mother had died in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Fagan changed his name to William Martin, married
two wealthy women and lived a luxurious life as a social-climbing
socialite who passed himself off as a consultant and CIA agent.
However, Fagan does not appear to have worked since he fled
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, 56, was arrested April 16 at his oceanfront mansion in
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth, who adamantly rejects her ex-husband's portrayal of her
as an unfit mother, has not seen her daughters since Fagan's
arrest. They have refused to visit her while charges are pending
against their father.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth,, 48, is a molecular biologist at the University of
Virginia Medical School. Her attorney, Jacob Atwood, said Friday he
was surprised by reports of a possible plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lynn Rooney and I remain in close contact, and she told me
repeatedly that the case is going to trial,'' Atwood said. ``I've
talked to Tom Reilly in the past, and he told me that this case
would never be plea-bargained and would go to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said that Fagan's attorney, Richard Egbert, recently met
with Reilly and Rooney, but the meeting was not productive. Then
about 10 days ago, Atwood said, Egbert asked the district attorney
if Fagan's daughters ``could plead their case that they don't want
their father to go to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara's brother, Peter Kurth, said Friday that no one from the
district attorney's office has contacted him or his sister to
discuss the possible deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara is perfectly willing to see this go to trial. She is
not frightened. But, in the end, it isn't her decision,'' Peter
Kurth said. ``Speaking for myself, there is no punishment that can
fit this crime, so I'm not sure what difference going to jail would
make.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Heffron, a spokesman for Reilly, declined to comment on
the proposal. However, he said that discussions about plea
agreements are routine in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   A previously scheduled preliminary hearing is scheduled for Dec.
28 at Middlesex Superior Court in Cambridge. Prosecutors are
believed to want a compromise hammered out before then.
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement is reached, Fagan would recover the $250,000
cash bond he posted in April in Cambridge. Last month in Florida,
he paid a $12,000 fine and surrendered a 1998 Honda on charges that
he falsely identified himself when he registered that car and a
Bentley worth more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan's carefully constructed life in Florida unraveled in
April, when was arrested by Massachusetts state troopers and police
from Framingham, where Fagan had lived before his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Fagan never returned Lisa and Rachael Martin from a
weekend visit with him to the North Adams home they shared with
their mother. A contentious divorce ended their marriage in 1978
and Kurth was granted custody of the children.
</P>
<P>
   The daughters, now young women, apparently heard that their
mother was alive when Middlesex County prosecutors visited them.
Since then, the sisters _ known to former teachers, coaches and
neighbors as well-adjusted, determined, successful and happy _ have
publicly supported their father.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, Barbara Kurth received a phone call from a
Palm Beach lawyer who said Fagan's sister had confided his secret
identity to him. Kurth allegedly phoned Atwood immediately,
triggering the investigation into Fagan's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Both daughters have said repeatedly they would testify for their
father despite any crimes he may have committed. Barbara Kurth also
made a public appeal, asking her daughters to visit when they were
ready.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1944EST &QL; 
