<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7654 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-DECLINE-AZR     12-18 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-DECLINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOOM LOOMS FOR CLASSICAL MUSIC  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The death of classical music ain't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and '70s, the death of classical music referred to
the inability of living symphonic and chamber-music composers to
connect with an audience. Orchestras and chamber groups became
museums of music written by the moldering dead. This process, which
had begun long before, reached a peak in those first decades of pop
culture hegemony.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s and '90s, the phrase broadened to indicate the
commercialization of classical music through marketing and
cross-over, especially as limned by English critic Norman Lebrecht
in his celebrated (if that's the word for the announcement of an
art form's termination) 1997 book of that name.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern established, you might think this is a never-ending
morbidity, a dying without death. But with the coming of a certain
event, I am convinced the ``death of classical music'' will come to
mean a kind of transformation into something else. Classical music
will surrender its identity, and ease into the mainstream of pop
culture.
</P>
<P>
   In many places, that transformation is already under way. One of
those places is the United States of America outside its major
cultural capitals such as New York, Chicago, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to New York, I barely managed to get a ticket
to a sold-out New York Philharmonic concert. Walking down Fifth
Avenue, I overheard someone singing to himself a snatch of
Schubert. Back in Phoenix, I walked into Phoenix Symphony Hall for
a concert and had my choice of seats. I have never overheard anyone
singing or whistling anything from the classical canon on the
streets of Phoenix _ or even of Tempe in the area of the Arizona
State University School of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Classical music exists in little packets in places like Phoenix,
among communities of those who care for it the way others care for
origami or chess. It's a passion for a few people and a pleasant
alternative to pop music for some, while for most it is something
heard on occasion on PBS, or transmogrified into television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   An upcoming watershed will make everywhere more like Phoenix and
less like New York.
</P>
<P>
   What is this nuclear bomb ready to explode in the face of
classical culture?
</P>
<P>
   The millennium. The big 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on classical music of the millennium will be akin to
the infamous Y2K problem. Y2K is the knot created by a lack of
foresight on the part of those who designed IBM-clone computer
chronometers. Only two digits indicate the year, so there is no way
the computer can ``know'' it is the year 2000; it will read ``00''
as 1900. It has been programmed to jump back a century.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto classical music.
</P>
<P>
   But while computer scientists are working to unleash the cyber
future from its virtual past, real-life classical music is stuck
forever in reverse, because it is definable only in terms of past
values.
</P>
<P>
   Even the name dates it. ``Classical'' music must belong to a
bygone time, else it is not classical. Yet, bygone is relative, and
until now we have been enjoying music of composers from two
centuries ago, or a century ago, or early this century.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 will push everything farther away. Looking back
over our shoulders, Mozart and Haydn will be slipping over the
horizon, with Beethoven barely visible. The 19th century _ the last
century dominated by Western art music _ won't be ``last century''
anymore. ``Last century'' will refer to the century that initiated
pop music's international dominance. Brahms, Wagner, Tchaikovsky _
even Debussy and Mahler, who lived into the 20th century _ will be
buried in another hundred years of history overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Naysaying? Doomspeaking? Indigestion?
</P>
<P>
   Item: Polygram Records, a company comprising among others the
prestigious classical labels Deutsche Grammaphon, Philips and
London Records, was sold this year to Seagram, the ``entertainment,
spirits and wine'' corporation that also owns Universal Music, a
pop music giant. Rumblings from within indicate fears that
bottom-line priorities will mean fewer serious recordings. A press
release from Polygram following the restructuring refers to
``classical'' music as ``an art form which appears completely at
odds with a dominant, flashy and hubris-laden pop culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Item: Record label BMG's classical division has dropped
conductor Leonard Slatkin from its roster of artists, along with
Slatkin's orchestra, the Washington, D.C.-based National Symphony.
Slatkin has recorded for BMG for more than 20 years, and his and
National's recording of John Corigliano's Symphony No. 1 won the
Grammy for Best New Classical Recording in 1996. BMG cited
financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   These are just proverbial iceberg tips. The real damage to the
titanic store and tradition of Western art music goes much deeper.
It has to do with fundamental ways of thinking and feeling, with
the traditional Western values classical music exemplifies and
their replacement by other, new values.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``classical music'' covers a lot of ground, from high
medieval plainchant to the most recent symphonic essays. But from
chanting monks to living composers Aaron Kernis and Bright Sheng,
with music between as different as Bach fugues and Schubert lieder
and Stravinsky ballets, the music has operated on the assumption
that such things as beauty, order and some level of complexity are
essential to expression.
</P>
<P>
   Those things are no longer thought essential. In some quarters,
they are even considered to be negatives: Beauty is equated with a
vapid ``prettiness,'' order is suspect as the cultural equivalent
of fascism, and complexity is elitist. In pop music, the beat _
steady and unending _ has taken on a supreme and unquestionable
function, supplanting harmony as the defining feature of music.
Social and political content have become important. Whole new
theoretical structures have grown up around rock music and its
derivatives. It's a new aesthetic that contradicts the old.
</P>
<P>
   What does that have to do with classical music? Everything, not
only because pop music has so much muscle and money, but because
when the average, well-educated person thinks of music, especially
new music, they think of pop. Composer-author Ned Rorem has pointed
out that when talk at a party turns to new novels, the names that
come up are John Updike or Joyce Carol Oates. But when talk turns
to new music, it's Madonna or The Symbol Formerly Known as The
Artist Formerly Known as Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Pop music is no longer an alternative to classical music; it is
its replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Item: Perry Meisel, a professor of English at New York
University, having written books about Thomas Hardy and Virginia
Woolf, turns his writing gifts to a book about contemporary music.
The subject: the roots of rock and roll. From the (classical)
musician's point of view, it is as if someone who has written about
Stravinsky and Charlie Parker (jazz being close to classical music
in many ways) turns to literature and decides to write about the
origins of romance novels.
</P>
<P>
   Item: The ``Wall Street Journal'' recently reported that more
than 14,000 students graduate annually from our country's
conservatories and music schools, many of these with specialization
in instruments. Yet fewer than 200 positions at America's full-time
symphony orchestras come available each year on average.
</P>
<P>
   It's necessary sometimes to whistle in the dark. People who have
put their lives and careers into classical music have to ignore a
lot, to keep going in spite of things, or they'd simply give it up
and go to law school. Some have.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not good not to face the facts, either. And the facts
pertaining to classical music's health are not good. A huge
psychological event such as the turning of a century/millennium
will almost certainly not make things better.
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Greene, president and CEO of the National
Association of Recording Arts and Sciences (the Grammy people) was
in Phoenix last year, I asked how it was that the Rolling Stones,
geezers even by baby boomer standards, had a huge following among
the young. Greene said it was because the Stones had come to
``symbolize rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how pop culture works. It puts things in slots and keeps
them there. You've got your official music of rebellion, and don't
even think of rebelling against it. You've also got your rap, your
country, your various other subdivisions, including your classical.
</P>
<P>
   Classical is quickly becoming a slot in pop culture. It's the
Three Tenors and Yo-Yo Ma. It's dead people's music performed by
media personalities.
</P>
<P>
   After the millennium, classical music to all but a small handful
of people will be a symbol of the past, just as the Stones are a
symbol of rebellion. Its absorption by pop culture will be
complete.
</P>
<P>
   To a classical music lover, Bach's B-minor Mass is something the
angels sing before the throne of God, the Beethoven string quartets
are essays in the very nature of Mind, and Shostakovich's Symphony
No. 10 is an individual's cry of ``Shame!'' in the face of the
almighty State.
</P>
<P>
   After the millennium, those pieces and great works like them
will be, for almost everyone who counts, for the educated and the
economically powerful, symbols of a sensibility disappearing over
the hills of yesterday, ``choices'' among myriad others in the vast
table of diverse symbols. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
