<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, Dec. 19. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLINTON-SENATE (Washington) - It turned out to be one of the most
intensely partisan debates in memory, and the House vote seemed
certain to be almost along party lines. And, if it continues to
unfold that way, impeachment is certain to fail in the Senate for a
very important historical reason: The founding fathers
intentionally made the Senate a brake on impeachments like this one
that don't attract broad support. Alexander Hamilton said that the
Senate's right to review the House's impeachment action ``guards
against the danger of persecution from the prevalence of a factious
spirit in either of those branches.''
</P>
<P>
   By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLINTON-RHODES (Phoenix) - Former House minority leader John
Rhodes, who was part of a contingent of Republicans who convinced
Richard Nixon to resign, said he believes President Clinton should
be censured, not impeached. By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-CLINTON (Undated) - At long last, the full House of
Representatives has begun deciding whether to impeach President
Clinton. For all the fits and starts, unseemly revelations and even
bombing attacks, we have arrived at this historic vote with the
president having had any number of opportunities to explain himself
honestly, to present his case candidly.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Clinton has done neither. This nation has survived wars,
assassinations, riots and any number of corrupt politicians. It
certainly is big enough to handle an impeachment trial. Story moved
in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FANTASY-FOOTBALL (Undated) - For many, the withdrawals are already
starting. The NFL season is dwindling down to a precious few games,
and you know what that means _ the end of fantasy football. Without
fantasy leagues, the NFL is much like the inside of Kevin Greene's
skull: a bleak void, bereft of all meaning. But I feel your pain.
If the shakes get too bad, you can always try playoff fantasy
football. By BILL MULLER. Story moved in the ``S'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLASSICAL-DECLINE (Phoenix) - As 1999 arrives and the countdown to
a new millennium begins, a ``classical music'' culture that is
already creaking faces the prospect of aging a century overnight.
With a new century - not to mention a new millennium - Beethoven,
Brahms, and company will seem still further in the background,
still less relevant to today. That is, unless something is done
about it. By KENNETH LAFAVE. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DICTIONARIES (Phoenix) - I have often thought of simplifying my
life, dumping most of my possessions in a misguided attempt to make
living easier. I hear Henry Thoreau's voice in the back of my head:
``Simplify, simplify.'' But when I make such schemes, I know that
there are other things I cannot do without: among them is a
dictionary. And immediately, things start getting complicated. For
no single dictionary is sufficient. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved
in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COPPER-PAINTING (Phoenix) - The Phoenix Art Museum's ``Copper as
Canvas'' show opens this week. The exhibition brings together for
the first time 105 of the most spectacular and best-preserved
examples of painting on copper. It surveys the works of 65 masters
- including Rembrandt and El Greco - and covers allegory and
mythology, portraiture, landscapes, still life and sacred themes.
By RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
