<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE GOLD RUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Universities move science from the laboratory to the
marketplace, supporting 250,000 jobs and contributing $30 billion
to the economy. Academic research improves the quality of life and
creates jobs.'' It was under that headline that the Association of
University Technology Managers last week released the results of
its annual survey.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to disagree, in general, with that?
</P>
<P>
   The data from its survey of the licensing activities of 175
member institutions are always interesting. But beyond the
commonplace that universities and hospitals are nurseries for for
new science that has practical applications, there is relatively
little in the report to support the authors' choice of verb.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to say it is the universities that are doing the
``moving?''
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly 20 years since the United States declared a
pell-mell gold rush on the intellectual property frontier. The time
has come to begin toting up the results. The vigorous association,
composed of lawyers, scientists, and other professional
intellectual property managers within universities, is one of the
indisputable fruits of the scramble. A lot of rich PhDs are
another.
</P>
<P>
   What else have we got to show for it?
</P>
<P>
   University and hospital technology managers date their modern
charter to 1980, when Congress passed a law directing them and
small businesses for the first time to patent and license
inventions developed under federally funded research programs. This
was the Bayh-Dole Act, sponsored by Senators Birch Bayh (D-Ind.)
and Bob Dole (R-Kan.); before it, technology transfer had happened
_ but haphazardly and lackadaisically.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Congress rationalized the patent procedure for
the first time in in 150 years, establishing a specialized
appellate court to hear patent cases, the Court of Appeals of the
Federal Circuit. Previously, patent cases had been heard in each
district in quite inconsistent ways. The new court quickly
strengthened patent protection.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, patenting surged in the United States. Having
fluctuated at a level of around 60,000 a year from 1945 until 1980,
patents by American inventors doubled in the 15 years after 1982.
Neither Japan, France, Germany, nor the United Kingdom display a
pattern since the mid-1980s anything like that. The European trends
remained flat; the steady Japanese increase that had been going on
since the 1950s leveled off in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the frontier of knowledge expanded
dramatically. The personal computer was invented. The Internet
boomed. The biotech revolution unfolded. And the health care system
underwent a dramatic transformation. And of course the US economy
grew vigorously, adding jobs and sending asset prices to record
levels.
</P>
<P>
   So what caused what? Did a stronger protection of intellectual
property rights precipitate a technological revolution? Or vice
versa? How well have the university middlemen managed their stream
of deals? What credit belongs to the shrewd money managers who,
starting in Boston and California in the years after World War II,
learned how to breath life into the markets for new technologies?
Only in the last few years have economists begun to measure and
assess the gold rush with a view to answering these questions.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting attempts to appear is a paper by
Josh Lerner and Sam Kortum that asks, ``What's Behind the Recent
Surge in Patenting?'' Because Lerner is representative of a new
approach in the nation's leading business schools _ until recently,
they were citadels of self-delight _ it is worth briefly
considering the arc of his career.
</P>
<P>
   A 1982 graduate of Yale, he worked for several years in
Washington on issues in technological innovation and public policy
_ at the Brookings Institution, for a public-private partnership,
and on Capitol Hill. Then he did a PhD in economics at Harvard for
Zvi Griliches, the guru of R&AMP;D research, and moved to Harvard
Business School to teach venture capital with William Sahlman.
</P>
<P>
   Economists in the early 1990s were struggling to come to grips
with the mechanics of technological change. For many years, they
had simply assumed that it would take place at a fairly steady
rate, come what may; but new work had placed technology squarely
within the economic system.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to grips empirically with these ideas is not easy, as
Adam Jaffe of Brandeis University has written. Investigation
``requires confronting the reality that many of the relevant
activities...are carried out in institutions such as universities
and government laboratories, and may not be amenable to analysis
with the standard tools of the theory of the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lerner teamed up with Boston University's Kortum with a view
to identifying and measuring some of the components of the ``black
box'' that previously had been labeled ``technological change.''
They started with the patent system, and quickly identified three
major theories of what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Friendly Court'' hypothesis held that the change in the
legal environment was crucial. A ``Fertile Technology'' hypothesis
saw a burgeoning technological revolution at the heart. A third
notion _ ``Regulatory Capture'' _ suspected that that the American
patent system had suddenly become far less friendly to foreign
inventors after 1982; hence a surge in ``home cooking'' by domestic
inventors.
</P>
<P>
   After the usual number of statistical and theoretical trials and
errors, Lerner and Kortum concluded that Friendly Court and
Regulatory Capture could be rejected, and that the Fertile
Technology hypothesis seemed to apply generally across the board.
It seemed therefore appropriate to credit ``changes in the
management of innovation'' for the surge in patents, including the
shift to more applied science.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what changes? Lerner himself has moved on to the next
likely suspect: venture capital and equity funding. He is among the
organizers (Brandeis' Jaffe and Yale's Jean Lanjouw are the others)
of a conference on patent policy and innovation in Santa Barbara.,
Calif., next month, sponsored by the National Bureau of Economic
Research. The idea is to bring together intellectual property
practitioners with well-equipped economic students of their work _
the better to gauge the effects of public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Sample paper titles: ``Do Patents Matter? Evidence After the
General Agreement on Tarrifs and Trade''; ``The Determinants of
Patenting in the Computer and Semiconductor Industries''; ``Private
and Public Responses to the US Plant Variety Protection Act of
1970''; and ``Optical Patent Length and Breadth.''
</P>
<P>
   A great deal rides on the results of such new work. The great
gold rush into computers, telecommunications, biotech, and medicine
that commenced in earnest in the late 1970s may be winding down.
Soon the territories are going to have to settle down and become
the equivalent of law-governed states. Programs designed to
stimulate the settling of these frontiers will have to stand up to
a much higher level of scrutiny in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
