<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multiple breaking stories send networks scurrying to keep up
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Depending which station you watched at what time
Friday, you saw just about anything: the impeachment hearings from
Washington; the latest bombing news from Iraq; the press conference
of recovering Falcons coach Dan Reeves; ``The People's Court,''
with TV judge Ed Koch presiding.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you saw at least two of those things on the same
channel at the same time. And if you were speed-surfing through the
different channels, there were times when you could catch almost
all of those things at once.
</P>
<P>
   What's been called the ``split-screen presidency'' turned into
wildly splintered TV coverage on Friday. The unprecedented
impeachment debate was often met by networks and local stations
with the news equivalent of attention deficit disorder. One minute
the impeachment debate was ``something you have not seen in your
lifetime'' (ABC's Peter Jennings); the next minute it was replaced
by the soap opera ``All My Children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting news day. The whole event is surreal,''
said WAGA general manager Gene McHugh, whose Fox-owned station
carried ``The People's Court'' and ``The Sally Jessy Raphael Show''
(topic: family feuds during the holidays) before it aired part of
the impeachment hearings at 11 a.m., 90 minutes after they'd
started. WAGA then stuck with the hearings until early in the
afternoon, even after most of the other networks had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to avoid the dreadfully dull, and basically if we
see something happening have the opportunity to go live,'' McHugh
added. ``We feel our role has modified in the last few years, to
reporter and summarizer. It's what our audience seems to prefer. My
role is to provide the community an option and not just turn the
camera on an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of a historical event such as Friday's impeachment
debate no longer is a clear-cut, gavel-to-gavel proposition for the
major broadcast networks and their affiliates. Either they have
their own cable entities, such as MSNBC or the Fox News Channel, to
give viewers continuous coverage, or they've ceded continuous
coverage to the all-news networks, such as CNN, which along with
C-SPAN and Atlanta public station WPBA, stuck with Congress
throughout most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's media environment, there are other places for
people to go who want to see all the details of that kind of
procedural stuff,'' WXIA general manager Bob Walker said of his
station's in-and-out coverage of the impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   WXIA, Atlanta's NBC affiliate, didn't take the network's news
feed until 40 minutes after it began _ 10 minutes after the
impeachment hearings started _ and instead aired the locally
produced kaffeeklatsch ``Peachtree Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said WXIA gave viewers the NBC feed as soon as the
articles of impeachment were read _ a purely procedural event _ and
the debate in Congress got under way.
</P>
<P>
   The station then left Congress again at 11 a.m. to cover the
press conference at Piedmont Hospital of Falcons coach Dan Reeves,
his first since heart surgery early this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make decisions based on whether (an event) is boring
or not,'' Walker said. ``We make it based on whether this
information is breaking news that the community needs to have right
now. We are in a business where people have a wide array of
opinions, and we just try to make the best decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the day of niche television for people who want to
tune in to pure political arguments all day from both sides,''
added WXIA news director Dave Roberts. ``When major developments
occur, such as the start of the attack in Iraq, NBC will use all of
its affiliates and cable outlets to bring the big story to
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It set up MSNBC following the Gulf War because of the
advantage CNN had.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
