<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, Dec. 19, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact David Brady at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   PERJURY-PUNISHMENT (Los Angeles) _ Rep. James Rogan, R-Glendale,
told the House of Representatives that 16,000 people in California
alone have been prosecuted for perjury, and 155 people are in
federal prisons now for the crime since Bill Clinton was first
elected president. He's right, according to federal figures. By
Peter Hartlaub. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE1219-COX     12-18 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE1219-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE SCENE IN THE CAPITOL
 &HT;    1450 words
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ History, humbug!
</P>
<P>
   On this bright, cold December day, they had come from across
America and waited in line for an hour to watch the full House of
Representatives debate the impeachment of a president for only the
second time since the founding of the nation. They expected to hear
soaring rhetoric and sound reasoning. They envisioned a chamber of
statesmen advancing arguments for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   But in an era of split screens and sound bites, and on an
occasion in which only the bile was bipartisan, they listened a
while and then left disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem like it was the historic, solemn occasion that
one might think,'' said Jonathan Shazar, a senior at Valley Stream
Central High School on Long Island, N.Y. ``Both sides just want to
get in a shot at the other. It's more spiteful than serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bitter _ nothing that I would consider an historic
debate,'' echoed Elisabeth Williams, 83, a docent at the Washington
state capital in Olympia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ho-hum. Everybody was inattentive, and the place was
three-fourths empty,'' complained David Janzen from Ontario,
Canada. ``Where was everyone? Why even have the debate? The only
people paying attention were in the visitors gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the day began with almost all the 435 House members
seated, but by midmorning, the House chamber was largely deserted.
Drama would have to await a vote on Saturday. A few floor leaders
from the Judiciary Committee directed the stream of speakers to the
podium, and Republican Rep. Ray LaHood, a parliamentary expert from
Peoria, Ill., wielded the gavel.
</P>
<P>
   As ever in the era of C-SPAN, representatives spoke more to the
TV cameras than to each other. On the floor, the sparse audience of
members read papers and chatted _ occasionally reaching a noise
level at which LaHood would direct them to take their conversations
to the cloakroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It upset me that (LaHood) had to repeatedly ask for order. I
thought 'how rude.' I teach eighth- and ninth-grade art, and the
people in my classroom pay more attention than the people in the
House of Representatives,'' said Barb Newman of Aberdeen, S.D. She
was in Washington to see the ornament she had made for the White
House Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all kinda had their own agenda,'' said Holli Hotchkiss of
Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hundreds of tourists who took a turn at watching the
debate over articles of impeachment filed against President Clinton
had come to the nation's capital on other matters. But the chance
to witness history had drawn them to the marble corridors of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll tell your grandchildren about this day,'' Janet Lee Hay
told her flock of gifted elementary school students from Sommerset,
Pa. Hay takes her students on a Christmas cultural outing every
year. They went to the White House on Friday morning and then
raised hands on whether to visit the FBI Building or the House
debate. The vote was split.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is history in the making,'' said Hay, explaining the
tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong bickering between Democrats and Republicans
disturbed many of the observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see such partisan lines drawn in the sand,'' said
Bob Wolfe, a retired industrial arts teacher from Santa Cruz,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution itself is a document born of compromise,''
said his wife, Bonnie, a retired history teacher. ``Now to see such
a lack of any willingness to compromise is discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I taught this stuff passionately for 25 years,'' she said,
explaining that she intended to return Saturday to watch the
impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   In congressional offices, staffers munched on holiday goodies
while they divided their attention between work and the floor
debate occurring on their TV screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whichever side members are on, they view it as an historic
occurrence,'' said Christopher Ptomey, a legislative aide for Rep.
Mac Collins, R-Ga. ``Mac certainly does.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karleen Mahn, a staffer for Rep. Jack Kingston, R-Ga., had
pragmatic concerns of moving into a new office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get any boxes unpacked'' with all attention directed
at the impeachment debate, she said. ``It's too bad they're up
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The representatives are rarely on Capitol Hill so close to
Christmas, of course, so unusual provisions had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   The Members Dining Room opened with a very limited menu: Stuffed
shells marinara for $7.25. Chicken breast teriyaki for $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   Providing for the comforts of his charges, Majority Whip Tom
DeLay of Texas provided pizza and salad to Republican members.
</P>
<P>
   On the Capitol grounds, the importance of the day was documented
by a forest of microphones, satellite dishes, lights and TV
cameras. But the mood was curiously subdued.
</P>
<P>
   A few demonstrators held placards, and an anti-impeachment
activist strung together letters on a long cord to form various
messages. ``No HIGH CRIME'' hung out for a while, then was replaced
by ``HATE &AMP; HYPOCRISY.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I doing this? Because our democracy is in danger,''
said Beverly Roberts, the message maker. ``They're going to totally
mess up the separation-of-powers doctrine. If I wasn't doing
something to try to stop it, I couldn't sleep at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the rhetoric did soar on the floor of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, it's your country. The president is our flag bearer,''
said Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stands out in front our people when the flag is flowing.
Catch the falling flag as we keep our appointment with history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The events of the last days sadden me,'' said Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. ``We are now at the height of a cycle of
the politics of negative attacks, character assassination, personal
smears of good people, decent people, worthy people. It's no wonder
to me and to you that the people of our country are cynical and
indifferent and apathetic about our government and about our
country. The politics of smear and slash and burn must end.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Turner, an English teacher from Long Island, savored such
phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish my students would speak like that,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   But more often, spectators left feeling let down at having heard
the same arguments that have been propounded on TV talk shows for
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty repetitive,'' said Jane Clemons, a Democratic
state representative in New Hampshire. ``We have a little more
enthusiasm in our debates. This subject has gotten so old that it
is probably hard for them to be enthusiastic about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., _ who has been leading the
anti-impeachment effort on the Judiciary Committee for months _
left the debate early to go home and nurse a cold, Scripps Howard
Newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little anti-climactic,'' he explained. ``The leading
actors have all been talking about it, and we all know the outcome.
This is not an emotional event for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they had heard the arguments before, the visitors in the
gallery listened intently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very clear there are intense differences between the
Democrats and Republicans,'' said Deborah Kraft, who took her two
children out of school in Andover, Conn., for this trip to
Washington. ``The Democrats were outraged and insulted that the
debate was even taking place while we are bombing Iraq. And I
understand their point very well about wanting censure to be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a parent, I was listening more to the other side,'' she
continued. ``No one is above the law. No one can commit perjury
regardless of the subject. We teach our children not to lie. So how
can we make an exception to that?''
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth Williams had heard it all before, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought up the same points over and over and over again.
Neither side is going to give up one inch,'' she said. ``I think
the Republicans have wasted the last six months over this. I've
been voting for 62 years, and November was the first time I voted
for nearly all Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   It all seemed a bit subdued to Sandra and Stephan Barden, who
are visiting from their home near London.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Parliament, Sandra said, ``They're very
well-behaved.''
</P>
<P>
   While Congress is generally less raucous than Parliament, LaHood
had begun this day with a warning for members to mind their
manners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the personal conduct of the president is at issue,''
he cautioned, ``the rules prohibit members from engaging in
generally personal abusive language toward (him), and also engaging
in comparison to personal conduct of sitting members in either
house of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   That final admonition was aimed at anti-impeachment speakers who
might point out that Hyde and House Speaker Bob Livingston, R-La.,
-- two impeachment leaders -- had admitted to sexual affairs of
their own. It drew a chorus of boos from the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
