<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-MURDERED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AUTOPSY SCHEDULED FOR SLAIN JOURNALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Refiling to some points.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mexican authorities will allow an FBI-hired medical examiner to
observe a second autopsy of an American journalist who was slain in
a mountainous region of western Mexico, a U.S. Embassy official
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   An initial autopsy performed Thursday indicated that Philip
True, 50, had been strangled with a cord or neckerchief. True was
the Mexico City correspondent for the San Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy also indicated that True had been sexually
brutalized.
</P>
<P>
   True's body was discovered Wednesday in a makeshift grave in a
canyon of the Sierra Madre Occidental. He had been missing for a
week after failing to return from a solo backpacking trip.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Emma Lew, a Miami-based forensic pathologist who does work
under contract with the FBI, was headed to Mexico City on Friday
and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lew, an assistant medical examiner with the Miami-Dade County
Medical Examiner's Office since 1991, will observe but not
participate in the autopsy, said a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy
in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican Attorney General's Office has requested that the
FBI send a pathologist to observe the autopsy,'' said the
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   David Najera, a spokesman for Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo,
said the president ordered a second autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will determine the date and time of death, the origin of
the wounds and the true cause of death,'' Najera said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Washington, a State Department spokeswoman said
the United States was following ``very closely'' the Mexican
government's investigation into the slaying of True.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen the news accounts indicating that Mr. True was
murdered, and have been informed by the coroner in Guadalajara that
the cause of death is strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we reserve making a judgment until the final report of
the Mexican authorities is made, we are very disturbed by what
appears to be the violent demise of a journalist who had undertaken
an effort to report on a little-covered region in Mexico,'' the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   True left Mexico City on Nov. 29 for a trek into the Sierra
Madre range in the states of Jalisco and Nayarit to report on the
life and customs of the Huichol Indians.
</P>
<P>
   He was reported missing by family and colleagues when he failed
to return home on Dec. 9. A Huichol Indian found True's body
Wednesday and led a search party to the location. By the time the
search team got there, the body was gone, but followed a trail of
feathers from True's sleeping bag some distance to a hastily dug
grave.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials praised the Mexican government for
allocating 250 men, five helicopters and four dogs to the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate further excellent cooperation as the Mexican
authorities continue their investigation,'' the State Department
spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
