A7675 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-CHAPLAINS19-COX     12-18 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-CHAPLAINS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chaplains tend to their flocks' holiday, deployment needs
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For military chaplains, the day-to-day duties of
ministry are intensified in times of action. Some chaplains are
with troops in the Persian Gulf. Others are with military families
back in the States. Still more are with military personnel who are
awaiting a possible call to duty.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Stewart and Hunter Army Airfield near Savannah, Ga.,
holiday activities are in full swing _ along with preparations for
possible deployment to the Persian Gulf for action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   As Jews continue celebrating Hanukkah, the eight-day festival of
lights, Chaplain Avrohom Horovitz, an Orthodox rabbi, is conducting
two services a day. A Muslim congregation on the base is preparing
to celebrate Ramadan, a monthlong observance of fasting and prayer,
under the leadership of a soldier who is also a lay religious
leader. And Christians, under dozens of chaplains, are getting
ready for Christmas and performances of Handel's ``Messiah'' on
Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplain (Col.) William Morrison, installation staff chaplain at
Ft. Stewart-Hunter, said he sees little difference in chaplains'
responsibility as a result of military activity in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldiers are always deployed, so as chaplains we have to be
prepared to provide ministry to family members as well as soldiers
who are not deployed to make the holidays as happy and meaningful
as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the several Southern Baptist chaplains already in the
Gulf, ``I'm finding there's high morale,'' said Chaplain Bob
Vickers, a retired colonel who serves as director of chaplaincy for
the Southern Baptist Convention. ``Our chaplains are feeling very
good about the preparation and the quality of the soldiers, the
sailors, the Marines and the airmen who are with them. I think they
sense that they're on a very important mission and they're doing
what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   For chaplains actually in the Gulf, Vickers said, the primary
focus is only helping the military personnel stay focused on their
duties. Chaplains are also called upon to help military people
under stress deal with philosophical issues, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of questions occur at times like this _ What if I'm
injured? What if it's worse than that? There are a lot of questions
about ultimate things.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people seeing actual military action, perhaps for the
first time, may also have moral and ethical concerns about people
who may be injured or killed as a result of their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes we have a tendency to think we have bred
war-mongers,'' he said. ``But it's incredible the kind of
compassion service persons have for people on the receiving end.
You kind of see yourself in that. They're doing what they must do,
but they're always hoping there's not personnel there, or at least
not civilian personnel. The face of the enemy is constantly in the
mind of the combattant.''
</P>
<P>
   As they deal with the everyday issues of life, intensified by
danger and separation from family, some military personnel become
more interested in religion.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplain Charles McMillan, a retired Army chaplain and director
of Presbyterian Council for Chaplains and Military Personnel, said
he has been in touch via e-mail with some of his denomination's
chaplains aboard ships in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have noted an increase in attendance at religious
functions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
