<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7690 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-18 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MOVE SHOULD BE BLOCKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no way the Patriots should be allowed to move to
Hartford, and someone of stature in Massachusetts should take a
lawsuit to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   If the National Football League owners vote in favor of such a
move, they will be in violation of their own guidelines, set down
by the late commissioner Pete Rozelle, who first stated them under
oath in court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The top two guidelines as laid down by Rozelle in court
basically said:
</P>
<P>
   (1) If the fans in a community are supporting a team, the league
would not vote approval to move. Since Bob Kraft has owned the
team, the Patriots have not played to an empty seat in five years.
</P>
<P>
   (2) If the business community is supporting the team, the league
should not permit a move. The most recent audit of the NFL,
completed in the last two weeks, shows that the Patriots are one of
the top revenue-producing teams in the league, certainly in the top
10 overall and second in stadium revenue among 30 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the fans who buy the tickets and the local businesses
_ radio, television, advertising, etc. _ have unquestionably given
the Patriots tremendous support.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Rozelle said under oath in the case against the
Oakland Raiders when the league tried to stop Al Davis from moving
the team to Los Angeles in 1982-83:
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the NFL has some `moral' responsibility to
geographical areas which loyally supported exisitng franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about the Raiders: ``They were the fifth highest in the
league in revenue, I think, so that is clear indication they were
getting strong support from the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about Raider fans: ``With the support they have given,
we cannot bail out on them. We feel that we are interlocked with
them and that they are deserving of our support.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about the city of Oakland building a stadium for the
Raiders: ``(The fans) were told that if they supported the team,
they would have the team forever. I do not believe that any NFL
team ought to transfer to a different city unless there are good
reasons for making such transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   The court in Los Angeles allowed the Raiders to move and told
the NFL it did so basically because the NFL had no guidelines for
such a situation, so its attempt to stop the Raiders was arbitrary.
This prompted Rozelle to set up formal guidelines, and he didn't
take long to enforce them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Leonard Tose, then the owner of the Philadelphia
Eagles, announced abruptly late in the season that he was going to
move his team to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Rozelle immediately called a league meeting and told Tose he
wouldn't allow the move because the fans and the city of
Philadelphia had supported the Eagles. Tose backed down, even
though he left a very lucrative deal on the table in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   We have heard in the last month or so, since the Patriots'
potential move became public, that Hartford is in the ``region.'' I
wrote at the time that this was a new word in the NFL lexicon. I
don't find any ``regions'' in the NFL constitution, but there is
the word ``territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is what the league constitution says about territorial
rights:
</P>
<P>
   (4.1) Home Territory Defined: ``Home Territory'' with respect to
any club means the city in which such club is located, and or which
it holds a franchise and plays its home games, and includes the
surrounding territory to the ``extent'' of 75 miles in every
direction from the exterior corporate limits of such city.''
</P>
<P>
   This franchise was granted to Boston and belongs to Boston.
Boston is 100 miles from Hartford. Hartford is not in Boston's
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Boston has played an important role in NFL history. In 1966, the
AFL, of which the Patriots were a charter member, and the NFL
agreed to merge. However, that merger could not go through unless
approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the merger ran into trouble in Washington. At that
time, the late, great John W. McCormack of South Boston was the
Speaker of the House, one of the most powerful politicians in the
land.
</P>
<P>
   Rozelle asked the late Bill Sullivan, then the owner of the
Patriots, to go to McCormack for help. There were also threats that
if the Patriots could not find a permanent place to play, they
would move. McCormack reportedly told Sullivan two things: Tell
Rozelle to grant the next expansion franchise to New Orleans
because Hale Boggs of Louisiana would hold up the merger until it
did so; and promise that the Patriots would not leave the Boston
area. That deal was made, and McCormack shepherded the legislation
to passage, setting the stage for the modern NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Even though current owner Bob Kraft has made a deal with
Connecticut to move the Patriots to Hartford, it is not a deal
until the 31 NFL owners vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way they should approve it because it would break
their own rules, and if they do, the state of Massachusetts should
sue for damages. Kraft and his son Jonathan are on the record
numerous times saying that the state would lose more than $10
million in direct revenue, and much more than that in indirect
revenue, if the team left.
</P>
<P>
   The state should go after them for all that money, times 30, the
number of years on the Patriots' lease in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   When the Colts left Baltimore and headed to Indianapolis, they
were playing to an average of 35,000 fans in a 60,000-seat stadium.
When the Cardinals left St. Louis for Arizona, there were 25,000
empty seats per game; ditto when the Rams left Anaheim for St.
Louis. These moves preceded the most controversial move of all,
that of the legendary Browns from Cleveland to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   America went bonkers. The league was so embarrassed that it made
the team leave behind the name and all logos and markings of the
Browns, considered synonymous with Cleveland. It also promised
Cleveland a new team, which will begin play in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the rub. Cleveland played to an average of 15,000 empty
seats a game the last few years. The Browns' season ticket base had
fallen under 40,000. The present Patriot season ticket base is
57,000, and Jonathan Kraft said recently the team has a waiting
list of 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of their stay, in no way did the city of
Cleveland offer the Browns the corporate support the Patriots enjoy
in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   The facts are there. No team in history has moved when it has
been supported the way the Patriots have been for the last five
years. It will be a disgrace and total hypocrisy on the part of the
NFL to do so. Get the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn has hit .284 lifetime in Anaheim (40 for 141), with
eight home runs. He has batted .327 at Fenway Park . . . Nice
gesture. Referee Bob McElwee's crew, in Boston to work Sunday's San
Francisco-Patriots game, will throw a party for some youngsters at
Children's Hospital Saturday. Pizza, cake, and gifts from the NFL
will be on the menu, and the crew will even wear the tops of their
uniforms to give the youngsters a better idea of what they do . . .
If the Patriots do wind up in Hartford with their present
sweetheart of all sweetheart deals, BankBoston will make a score
with them. Reportedly, the bank, which funded the Krafts' purchase
of the team, has an agreement giving it 10 percent of the value of
the team above what the Krafts paid for it. The Krafts paid $160
million. Estimates are that in Hartford, the money-making machine
will be worth $500 million, so the bank's end of the deal will
appreciate by about $35 million on paper, and it will collect when
the team is sold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We have said all along that it doesn't make any difference how
much money you spend in the NFL if you don't pick the right players
in the draft or sign the right ones in free agency. Case in point:
the spending in the league for this season.
</P>
<P>
   (! used as a column separator) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Team ! Payroll ! Record
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. San Diego ! $70 million ! (5 -9)
</P>
<P>
   2. Carolina ! $67.7 million ! (2-12)
</P>
<P>
   3. Minnesota ! $66.8 million ! (13-1)
</P>
<P>
   4. Seattle ! $65.4 million ! (7-7)
</P>
<P>
   5. San Francisco ! $64.l million ! (11-3)
</P>
<P>
   6. Patriots ! $63.6 million ! (8-6)
</P>
<P>
   7. Washington ! $63.6 million ! (5-9)
</P>
<P>
   8. Arizona ! $63.4 million ! (7-7)
</P>
<P>
   9. Denver ! $63.4 million ! (13-1)
</P>
<P>
   10. Cincinnati ! $62.5 million ! (2-12)
</P>
<P>
   This money includes base pay and bonuses. The NFL salary cap is
$53,388,000; anything over that is paid out in bonuses. At present,
only three of these teams have qualified for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least, congrats to David D'Alessandro of John
Hancock for being named one of the 100 most influential people in
sports by The Sporting News this week. D'Alessandro ranked 47th,
and no one does more behind the scenes for good causes in Boston
than he does.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
