<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ARABS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDWIDE ARAB CYNICISM OVER BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT CITY _ A government official was reiterating his
country's mantra of cautious support for the US attack on Iraq
Friday when, abruptly, he ended the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about Iraqi weapons of mass destruction, of
course,'' he snapped. ``It's about saving your president; everyone
seems to realize this except Americans. Even those with great
reason to distrust Saddam Hussein find it hard to countenance this
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Middle East and around the world, Arabs and
Moslems displayed similar cynicism, and frequently rage, toward the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Across the West Bank, though Palestinian authorities tried to
contain the protests, crowds bellowed anti-American and pro-Iraqi
slogans. In Manger Square in Bethlehem, where President Clinton was
greeted almost as a hero a few days ago, demonstrators chanted,
``Saddam, Saddam, our beloved'' and ``Death to America, death to
Clinton, death to Britain!''
</P>
<P>
   Other Arabs and Moslems demonstrated from the Netherlands to
Hong Kong. In Malaysia, seldom infected by the virulent
anti-Americanism commonplace in other Islamic nations, protesters
outside the US Embassy in Kuala Lumpur hoisted placards that read:
``US is ruled by Lust and Lies'' and ``Iraq People shouldn't have
to pay for Clinton's Zippergate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in Kuwait, which provides a crucial base for allied
fighter-bombers and for thousands of American troops, cynicism
toward US policy is rampant, though inhabitants of the oil-rich
emirate still despise and fear the Iraqi dictator next door.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of those who lambasted the US-British assault Friday
made it clear that they do not believe Hussein and his government
are faultless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We condemn this attack which is part of crimes committed by
America and England against the Islamic world,'' a senior cleric in
Iran, Ayatollah Mohammed Emami Kashani, said in a sermon at Friday
prayers. ``We hope God will rid the Islamic nation of these
arrogant oppressors.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Emami Kashani, a spokesman for one of the
nation's senior clerical organizations, told worshippers at Tehran
University: ``Of course Iraq's government is also responsible and
is condemned. Why does it not cooperate with the United Nations and
carry out United Nations resolutions?''
</P>
<P>
   Across Pakistan, militant Moslems shouted ``Death to America''
during a series of small but angry protests. And in The Hague,
Dutch police charged Iraqi demonstrators with batons when some
started throwing rocks outside the US Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   While there were protests across the West Bank and Gaza Friday,
Palestinian authorities seemed intent on preventing a repeat of the
widespread pro-Hussein demonstrations that captured worldwide
attentiond during the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the denunciations of the United States, and especially of
Clinton, were striking in light of the warm reception he received
from Palestinians just days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very strange for me that we've just been waving the
American flag and I saw the same flag burned today,'' Nasri Abu
Jheish, 28, one of the demonstrators in the West Bank community of
Nablus, told journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The anger was deepened by the coincidence of the Israeli
government's abrupt suspension of an American-brokered deal that
would require the Jewish state to relinquish control of additional
territory to the Palestinians in return for security.
</P>
<P>
   Many Palestinans, and Moslems elsewhere, view the US attacks
against Iraq as utmost hypocrisy _ punishing an Islamic nation for
failing to abide by UN resolutions while sticking by Israel when it
also snubs international opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian protesters in Gaza implored Hussein to strike Israel
with Scud missiles, as he did in the 1991 Gulf War, while jeering
Clinton for the sexual escapades that appear increasingly certain
to result in his impeachment. ``Clinton, you coward, go look for
women,'' crowds of youths chanted.
</P>
<P>
   At Jerusalem's al-Aqsa mosque, Islam's third holiest shrine,
Moslem cleric Mohammed Hussein characterized the assault on Iraq on
the cusp of Ramadan as ``an aggression on all humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among Persian Gulf states warm to the United States and
favoring economic sanctions against Iraq, official support was
lukewarm, at best, for bombing waves that have struck Baghdad and
other Iraqi targets for three successive nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray a peaceful solution to this crisis could be reached to
spare the Iraqi people a lot of misery and suffering,'' said a
spokesman for Qatar's Foreign Ministry, in an official government
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Only a month ago, when Washington and London were poised to
attack, even Islamic countries traditionally opposed to US policy
seemed to accept that it was Hussein who was bringing international
rage down on his people by defying UN arms inspectors. Now,
however, there seems almost universal sympathy in the Moslem world
for Iraq, if not for Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   A view expressed by ordinary people and governments alike is
that the wrongs cited by the chief UN arms inspector, Richard
Butler, did not warrant the swift retaliation, and that Baghdad
should have been allowed a bit more time to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be there should be a time of military reckoning with
Saddam Hussein,'' said Ahmad Mutawa, a Kuwaiti academic educated in
the United States and generally a supporter of US policy in the
region. ``But this is too much, too soon. There is an obscenity to
these attacks against Iraqis who have become so helpless they can
hardly lift a weapon to defend themselves. It is especially
offensive as we enter Ramadan.''
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian university students took to the streets in Cairo,
chanting pro-Iraqi slogans and warning that any attack by the West
against an Islamic country represents a threat to all Moslems.
``Egypt, wake up!'' the youthful crowds repeated. ``Your turn might
come next!''
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus, a group of Syrians staged a sit-in outside the US
Embassy, a rare public display of political outrage in the tightly
ruled state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to express our anger at the strikes which were
mainly directed against the people of Iraq, who have been suffering
for eight years due to sanctions,'' said Jamal Mahmoud, one of the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed an almost universal view across the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In Yemen's capital, Sanaa, where police increased security
around the US mission, thousands took to the streets following
Friday prayer services, yelling anti-American slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic preachers, in angry sermons, stood at the head of
mosques and branded the United States and Great Britain as
``infidels.''
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
