<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF UN INSPECTION TEAM IN DOUBT IN WAKE OF RAIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A secret computer video feed that enables UN
inspectors in New York to monitor Iraq's weapons facilities went
dead Friday, probably the result of the US bombing campaign,
according to UN sources.
</P>
<P>
   The technical breakdown was the latest setback for an
organization whose future has grown increasingly uncertain since
Washington launched its missile strikes on Iraq. In the first two
days of the air raids, the Pentagon says it has destroyed 75 key
military installations, raising questions about whether the UN
Special Commission will have anything left to inspect if it ever
returns to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The target list _ which included Iraq's defense ministry,
intelligence headquarters, the Republican Guard barracks, and the
Al Taji and Ibn Al Haytham's missile production factories _
contains many of the locations under the inspectors' scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the documentary evidence may have been blown up,''
said a senior UN official. ``If UNSCOM ever goes back in, it's
almost like they were in '91 starting from scratch trying to put a
trail together.''
</P>
<P>
   As the UN arms specialists in New York came to grips with their
predicament, the chairman of the UN Special Commission, Richard
Butler, said Friday that he is worried that the future of his
mission is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about where we will go next, and will we still be
able to do our job,'' said Butler, who has insisted that he will
not give up his post until Iraq is a weapons-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   Butler's staff declined to confirm the existence of video
monitoring station at UN headquarters _ which is classified.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Duelfer, the UN Special Commission's deputy
chairman, signaled that the UN's capacity to monitor Iraq weapons
facility had been eroded by the American campaign. ``There is a
coincidence of location between our cameras and America's bombs,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States' insitence that the Special Commission
will play an important role in Iraq when the bombs fall silent,
inspectors in New York remain anxious over the prospects of its
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I going to be here in a month's time? Possibly yes,'' said
one official who requested anonymity. ``Six months time? I don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
