<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-ATTACKS-1219-COX     12-18 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ATTACKS-1219-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR STRIKES VICTIMS EMBITTERED BY TRAUMA OF HIGH TECH WARFARE
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1219.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ Jassim Ghelan says he used to like doing business with
Americans, but that was before an American missile slammed through
his wall. It crashed through the kitchen and bathroom and sent
pieces flying into the bedroom where he slept with his wife and
frightened children.
</P>
<P>
   The missile demonstrated, in one way, the ultra-high-tech nature
of this series of the air strikes the United States and Great
Britain launched on Iraq this week. It did not explode, possibly
because missiles can be deactivated when they run off course, as
this appears to have done. Had it exploded, there might be nothing
left of the Ghelan family household.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the murky casualty counts through the start of another
round of air strikes Friday night seemed small, maybe just in the
dozens. But, as this incident in a tony section of town a day
before showed, even the most advanced form of warfare is rife with
personal trauma and tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ghelan, a wealthy engineer, and his wife had gone to sleep with
their children when seven-year-old daughter, Susan(CQ) said she was
scared. Now, the parents, their 20-day-old baby and their toddler
are all in hospitals with minor to serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Ghelan, 40, said he traveled to the United States twice 20 years
ago for business, but now he wants revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Mr. Clinton say they won't bomb children or
civilians,'' Ghelan strained to say from his bed in one of
Baghdad's dilapidated, antiquated, hospitals. ``(Iraqi President)
Saddam Hussein must not be quiet. He must destroy Clinton and the
(U.S.) government. The Arab people must take revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghelan had a broken jaw, broken vertebrae, a head injury and a
black eye. In a ward with six other bomb victims with little
medical equipment visible, he lay under an old tiger-striped
blanket in the same bloody sleeveless undershirt he wore when
injured.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors said they helped remove large parts of the missile
from the inside of the house. From the outside, passersby could see
several windows shattered, window frames askew and metal gratings
dangling off them. In the back, there was one hole just a couple of
yards wide. Houses next door were undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   Information on casualties has been scarce, but Iraqi officials
and those trying to survey hospitals for a count have estimated
that possibly 35 people have died, and dozens have been injured.
That is from a barrage of well over 200 missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Al Yarmouk Hospital, a major facility with 750 beds, had 50
patients through Thursday and 13 had died. Most had shrapnel wounds
and some were burned.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable seller Khamis Hatem Khuder broke his leg in four
places when the bus he was riding flipped over as the result of a
nearby missile blast. This was just after midnight Thursday morning
and was among the first volleys of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He heard the approach of the missile, which he said sounded like
an airplane, and saw it land and explode. He was thrown from the
bus and knocked unconscious, but others on board died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This accident increased my insistence to resist America,'' he
said. ``God willing, we will win.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
