<HEADER>
A7716 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRESSURE19-CO     12-18 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESSURE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEEK PACKED WITH CRISES PLACES STRAIN ON CLINTON
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fighting Iraq with one hand and impeachment with
the other, an embattled President Clinton battened down the White
House hatches Friday, ducked out of public sight and threw himself
into his job.
</P>
<P>
   A week packed with tough peace talks in Jerusalem, political
battling against impeachment and a war on Iraq has subjected
Clinton to an excruciating set of pressures that few chief
executives could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   He has made no secret, moreover, of his pain over the difficult
job of mending fences with his wife and daughter over his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton _ who hasn't partaken of his favorite stress-buster,
a round of golf, in two weeks _ pushed aside his personal and
professional anxieties Friday.
</P>
<P>
   All but ignoring the bruising House debate on his future a few
blocks away on Capitol Hill, Clinton spent the day engaged on
subjects ranging from the first federal budget of the new
millennium to the quest for an AIDS cure.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton's morale
had been boosted by the holiday atmosphere in the West Wing, where
offices were brightened by Christmas trees and stocked with enough
caramel popcorn and reindeer-shaped cookies to keep even the
grinchiest spirits afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, Clinton found himself swaying to the beat
of ''Santa Claus is Coming to Town,'' with his arm around a beaming
Hillary Rodham Clinton, at a White House Christmas gala to
recognize the the Special Olympics, a worldwide sports movement
benefitting people who are mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   He later retired for the best night's sleep _ seven hours _ he
has had all week.
</P>
<P>
   The past few days, though, haven't been all glamor, and earlier
Thursday it was clear the strains of the week had taken their toll.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared at the start of a national security briefing
looking drawn and spent, his speech lacking the punch and passion
that normally animates his every utterance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be an understatement to say that the president has
been tested over the last week,'' Lockhart told reporters. ''I
think what you can see, and what he's demonstrated, is he's up to
the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in a generation _ since President Nixon resigned in 1974 to
avoid almost certain impeachment during the waning days of U.S.
involvement in the Vietnam War _ has an American president faced
the combined stress of war and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, added another to the list, starting the week
chewing into the gristle of a Mideast peace process stalled by
broken promises on both sides of the Israeli-Palestinian divide.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the 11-hour journey from Washington to Jerusalem on
Saturday, spent Sunday in bitterly contentious talks with Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu about possible ways to restart
the peace process, then proceeded to a joint press conference
dominated by questions about the looming impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing physically drained and emotionally spent, Clinton
often could only stare, almost blankly at times, into a phalanx of
cameras and scandal-primed reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton flew by helicopter for a long day in
Palestinian-controlled Gaza, where he lent his blessings to the
notion of Palestinian statehood. Back in a Jerusalem hotel that
night, a senior administration official made clear the toll the day
had taken. Wheezing blearily through a series of questions,
including one on how he was holding up, the official said only,
''I'm awake,'' then quickly ordered a cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, after more talks and visits to holy sites in
Bethlehem and Masada, Clinton made the long flight back home across
the Mediterranean and Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Uncharacteristically, neither Clinton nor any administration
official wandered back to the press cabin at the rear of Air Force
One to answer questions about how the president was spending his
time.
</P>
<P>
   The reason became clear only Wednesday night, when Clinton
announced the air strikes on Iraq he had approved in a conference
call from Air Force One with Vice President Al Gore and key members
of the White House national security team.
</P>
<P>
   At a 7:30 a.m. meeting Wednesday _ just seven hours after he
returned to the White House _ Clinton reaffirmed his decision to go
forward with the strike, preparations for which were already well
under way.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that his staff might become despondent with
impeachment proceedings looming, Clinton left his security briefing
to make an unusual appearance at the morning staff meeting of the
White House press office.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped by, Lockhart said, ''basically to say that the
important thing for all of us here as White House staff is to
concentrate on the jobs we were sent here to do, that ultimately
the American people get it right and he believes that they will
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
