<HEADER>
A7717 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MOOD-HNS &LR;      12-18 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS, DEMOCRATS TRADE JABS DURING IMPEACHMENT DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York Democrat Charles Rangel and Georgia
Republican John Linder found themselves sharing a Capitol elevator
Friday morning as they rode up to begin the historic debate on
impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little warm in here,'' remarked Linder.
</P>
<P>
   ``And its going to get a lot hotter,'' promised Rangel.
</P>
<P>
   The doors opened and the congressmen proceeded to the House
chamber where for more than 12 hours lawmakers debated _ in heated,
solemn, and tired voices _ the fate of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The final deliberations sounded many of the same sour partisan
notes that have been heard repeatedly since independent counsel
Kenneth Starr delivered his 36 boxes of material to the House four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans bickered over everything from the time
limits for the debate to whether the discussion should be happening
at all while the United States was bombing Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   There was little suspense about the outcome, however, as even
Democrats have conceded that Republicans have enough votes to
impeach.
</P>
<P>
   And by late morning the chamber had largely emptied out as
lawmakers took turns repeating well-worn arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans recited their mantra that presidents are not above
`` the rule of law,'' while some Democrats cried ``coup d'etat.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the predicability of the debate, the gravity of what the
435 Representatives are preparing to do with votes Saturday seemed
to take hold when the clerk of the House in solemn tones recited
the resolution against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resolved, that William Jefferson Clinton is impeached for high
crimes and misdemeanors,'' he intoned before a full and silent
chamber ay 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A short while later, the members made the only display of
bipartisanship of the day when they burst out in applause after
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., implored that the
``politics of smear and slash and burn must end.''
</P>
<P>
   That message resonated with Republicans, many of them still
reeling from the latest bombshell; the confession by their new
leader, House Speaker-designate Robert Livingston, R-La., that he
had extramarital affairs while in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But for the remainder of the day the divide in opinions mirrored
the physical separation of the members, who are seated by party.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intensity of feelings, the lawmakers remained civil
on the floor. Several of them clutched Bibles, while others laced
their talks with references to Thomas Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln,
Roman law and the Magna Carta.
</P>
<P>
   One of the president's most vociferous critics, Rep. Bob Barr,
R-Ga., displayed a copy of the criminal code as he lectured
colleagues on how Clinton violated the law.
</P>
<P>
   But Barr also sparked a confrontation when he quoted former
President John F. Kennedy in a speech defending impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward the deceased president's nephew, Rep. Patrick Kennedy,
D-R.I., confronted Barr in the adjacent speaker's lobby, saying
``Anybody who has been to a racist crowd like that has no right
invoking my uncle's name.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was referring to a speech Barr gave earlier this year
before a white supremacist group. Barr has asserted he was unaware
of the organization's views when he gave the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Barr responded that Kennedy was wrong and then further annoyed
the 31-year old congressman by calling him ``young man'' and
chiding him for criticizing another representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem with that, and calling me a young man, I'm a
duly elected member of my state's delegation,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impressed, duly impressed,'' Barr shot back.
</P>
<P>
   There were moments of solidarity and support as well as
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate was unfolding, White House special counsel Greg
Craig was spotted in the marbled hallways of the Capitol chatting
with an elderly man, who asked if it would be all right to give the
president's defender a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Craig smiled, shrugged his shoulders and bent down to the man
who gave him a peck on the cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're doing a great job for the president. Tell him we're
behind him,'' the man said.
</P>
<P>
   There were few signs in or out of the building of mass public
indignation that the White House hoped might stave off only the
second impeachment of a president in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras outnumbered the smattering of
anti-impeachment protesters on the Capitol lawns.
</P>
<P>
   The spectator section in the House balcony remained largely
empty for most of the day, though there were some tourists lined up
to watch the unusual proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   And they sounded as passionately divided in their views about
the president and his fate as the lawmakers at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a law enforcement officer did what he did, he would be
removed,'' said Gail Forbes of San Diego, who favored impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lied and should be held accountable,'' said Rob Rowello, an
impeachment advocate from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But standing right in front of him, Paul Nolan, who said he
voted twice for Clinton, was opposed to Congress removing the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, an attorney from Washington D.C., called the impeachment
proceedings ``the most disgraceful public process in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath Fallin, an impeachment opponent visiting from North
Carolina, said he wanted to come to the Capitol before the vote, a
move he said was ``dirtying the whole process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
