<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RAYTHEON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKES A NEW TEST FOR RAYTHEON WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ongoing airstrikes against Iraq will test the improvements
Raytheon Co. has made to smart weapons like the Tomahawk cruise
missile, which received mixed reviews for its performance during
the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon is perhaps best known as the producer of the Patriot
air-defense missile, made famous by the earlier conflict. But a
round of acquisitions in 1997 now make Raytheon a main supplier of
offensive weapons to the United States military as well.
</P>
<P>
   With munitions like the Tomahawk and the High-Speed
Antiradiation Missile, or HARM, now in use against Iraq, defense
analysts say the US attacks will show whether Raytheon has fixed
the weapons' earlier shortcomings. For example, a new generation of
Tomahawks is being used in the current attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clearly recognized that there was work to be done (on
the weapons), even though it wasn't always admitted,'' by the
military, said Harvey Sapolsky, a professor at MIT's security
studies program. This time, ``Raytheon is out to show they work,''
said Richard Shultz, who teaches at Tufts University's Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the Gulf War, the Pentagon touted its use of
smart weapons, at one point claiming the Tomahawk had a 98 percent
effectiveness rate.
</P>
<P>
   But a 1997 report by the General Accounting Office found the
Pentagon and weaponsbuilders made overstated or misleading claims
about the effectiveness of those attacks. The GAO noted that the
Pentagon itself had concluded the Tomahawks missed their targets as
often as they found them.
</P>
<P>
   The chief builder of Tomahawk at the time of the reports, Hughes
Electronics Corp., did not respond to the findings. Raytheon, which
acquired the Hughes defense business last year, also declines to
respond to the GAO's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ancient history...that has no bearing on the current
performance'' of the Tomahawk, said Dave Shea, a onetime Hughes
spokesman now in Raytheon Systems Co.'s Arlington, Va.
headquarters. Despite the Pentagon audit suggesting a hit rate
around 50 percent, Raytheon cites older figures showing Tomahawks
struck their targets about 85 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Raytheon has been busy updating the Tomahawk, which
it builds in Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to finding its target with a satellite-based Global
Positioning System instead of pre-programmed radar flight path
maps, the newest Tomahawk missiles include better software allowing
them to fly loops in order to coordinate arrival with that of other
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of greater sophistication is considerable,'' says
Chris Hellman, senior analyst at the Center for Defense
Information, a nonprofit group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With about 3,000 Tomahawks in the Navy's arsenal before the
start of the current air strikes, Raytheon's Shea said the company
doesn't expect the military to replace used Tomahawks with a large
order anytime soon. The weapons cost between $500,000 to $750,000
apiece at current prices.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, based in Lexington, Mass., also supplies a range of
smart bombs to the military, a business it acquired from Texas
Instruments Inc. in 1997 and is in the process of moving to Tucson.
These include the HARM, now in use against Iraqi missile-defense
sites. Raytheon also produces the Joint Standoff Weapon, a glider
bomb that pilots can launch from up to 50 miles away, and the
Paveway smart bomb, whose effectiveness has also been questioned by
the GAO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
