<HEADER>
A7727 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BAXTER19-COX     12-18 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BAXTER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appearances of momentous day deceiving
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First, a word about the empty seats in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little odd, given all that was said Friday about how
historic and important this impeachment debate was, that when all
the high-flown rhetoric rose to the visitor's gallery above the
House floor, only about half the seats were filled with listeners.
To take this as a sign the public isn't paying attention would
repeat an error committed many times in the course of this story,
however.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, this was the first presidential impeachment
debate of the C-SPAN age. For all we know it may have as large an
audience as any congressional debate in history. But Americans
accustomed to the Internet and all-news television understand, as
members of Congress certainly do, that you don't have to be in the
room to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the members were in their seats when the debate began
Friday, but by midmorning the House settled into a typical pattern,
with members drifting on and off the floor as they waited their
turn to talk about their grave responsibility and their fateful
task.
</P>
<P>
   Here again, appearances could be deceiving. If they went about
it in a routine way, the import of the day did seem to weigh
heavily on many members. Rep. Saxby Chambliss of Georgia spoke of
the lump in his throat that came on during a morning interview with
a Macon radio station. Rep. Sue Myrick of North Carolina had tears
welling in her eyes when she left the floor after her speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very down for the last couple of weeks,'' the
Charlotte Republican said. ``It's kind of like getting in a funk
you can't get out of.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charlie Norwood of Georgia sat through almost all the
proceedings, although the Augusta Republican said he heard nothing
that would sway him from voting for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're past the point of me making my decision. I just feel
duty bound to be sitting there,'' Norwood said.
</P>
<P>
   For a number of House members who are not returning, their
remarks on impeachment were also their farewell addresses, and many
were the most affecting speeches of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last vote I will make in the House, and the most
troubling in all my years,'' said Democrat Bill Heffner of North
Carolina. Then he spoke of how hatred, like a tell-tale disease,
had changed even the physical appearance of his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What began 25 years ago with Watergate as a solemn and
necessary process to force a president to adhere to the rule of
law, has grown beyond our control so that now we routinely using
criminal accusations and scandal to win the political battles and
ideological differences we cannot settle at the ballot box,'' said
Democrat Charles Schumer of New York, who is leaving the House for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Democrats picked up on that theme, sometimes coming
close to public regret at their party's contribution to the descent
_ the scandal over drinking and womanizing which blocked the
Cabinet appointment of Republican John Tower, Schumer noted, was
``not too dissimilar'' to that of Clinton. Rep. Vic Fazio of
California, another member making his last speech in the House,
said some Republicans were obsessed with ``Slick Willy'' the way
some Democrats 25 years ago were obsessed with ``Tricky Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   The moments in which debate rose above partisanship were brief,
however, and the partisan rancor droned on into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
