<HEADER>
A7729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POUND-HODLER19-COX     12-18 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POUND-HODLER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC team: Sweeping corruption unproven
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The head of the International Olympic Committee's team
investigating allegations of bribery said Friday that a colleague's
claims of widespread corruption in the election of host cities are
unsubstantiated.
</P>
<P>
   IOC vice president Richard Pound said Marc Hodler, who rocked
the sports world with his claims that IOC votes for host Olympic
cities can be bought, has supplied no evidence to back his
sensational allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I have no facts; everything I hear is hearsay,' ''
Pound, a Canadian lawyer, said in a telephone interview from his
Montreal office. ``It is very frustrating for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote-buying scandal erupted after evidence emerged last
month that Salt Lake City Olympic officials had set up a $400,000
scholarship fund for 13 people, including six relatives of IOC
members. The IOC quickly set up an internal investigation headed by
Pound.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hodler, an 80-year-old Swiss lawyer who has been a trusted
member of the IOC's inner circle, turned the issue into a maelstrom
when he alleged over the weekend that agents of IOC members seek
cash bribes of as much as $5 million in exchange for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler, second in seniority on the IOC, gave numerous impromptu
interviews to media gathered for what would have been a routine
three-day IOC meeting in Switzerland, repeating accusations of
bribery, blackmail and other misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal took on global proportions when Hodler claimed
corruption abounded in the election campaigns awarding the Games in
Atlanta in 1996, Nagano in 1998 and Sydney in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch, while distancing himself
from Hodler's claims, has promised to expel any IOC member found
guilty of misconduct and to consider possible changes in the
selection of the host city.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said the investigation commission asked Hodler to
substantiate his claims, which have escalated since he returned
home to Bern, Switzerland. ``We said, `Marc, you are now
world-famous. Now come and talk to our commission.' We made a
specific point of asking him for the facts. He had no facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Pound's investigation commission is looking into
the Salt Lake City allegations only. It is expected to deliver the
results when the IOC meets again in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to follow through and start where we have some
facts,'' he said. ``If they lead us elsewhere, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound, an IOC member for 20 years who served as chairman of the
IOC Coordination Commission for the Atlanta Games, said he did not
believe the allegations would affect corporate support of the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``These rumors been around for so long, people either believe
them or don't,'' he said. ``If they did believe them, it didn't
seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back at the record, you can say there may be
questionable conduct on the part of a small number of IOC members,
but one way or the other the IOC has done a pretty good job picking
host cities. And that is more important than the process.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the process could change, Pound said. Influential IOC
members, including U.S. delegate Anita DeFrantz and gold-medal
skier Jean-Claude Killy of France, say a smaller panel, perhaps the
11-member executive board, should select the host city.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said that is one of the suggestions his commission would
``put on the table,'' although having a select few of the
115-membership making the most IOC's most important decisions could
be equally controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``What causes one to now look at the process with a fresh eye is
the dramatically changed economic impact of the Olympic Games,'' he
said. ``Before, it was find which city is prepared to invest the
most and lose the most. Now the power of the rings is producing
upwards of $2 billion, and it is an entirely different ball game.
Given that _ the prize for the host city _ it increases the
possibility of improper activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Olympic chief Billy Payne, who was dismayed this week to
be included in Hodler's broad-brush indictment, said he supports
changes in the selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any steps the IOC would consider implementing which have the
effect of leveling the playing field,'' Payne said Friday, ``is
something I would favor and something I believe they have the
courage to do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
