<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-BOS &LR;      12-18 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMBER HOUSE DEBATES IMPEACHMENT ARTICLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the clerk of the House somberly and slowly read
aloud the articles of impeachment against William Jefferson
Clinton, president of the United States, tears filled David
Schippers's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than a high moment of history for the crusty Chicago
prosecutor, who helped draft the four articles for the House
Judiciary Committee and heard them debated on the House floor
Friday. ``The single emotion I feel is sadness,'' Schippers said
later, stopping briefly below the majestic dome of the Capitol
Rotunda. ``It takes on all the aspects of a Greek tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The House was a tense and joyless place as the weight of history
and a season of sore feelings bore down upon it. The tragedy wasn't
only for Clinton, whose impeachment seemed a foregone conclusion,
but also for the institution, which has been ripped apart by
uncommon anger and raw, rancorous partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of smear and slash-and-burn must end,'' said
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, delivering the only words
in a long day of floor debate that received applause and a standing
ovation from both Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in the House already had been poisoned by the
Republicans' refusal both to delay the impeachment debate until US
military engagement in the Persian Gulf ended and to allow
Democrats to offer a resolution censuring Clinton for his
misconduct. But what also had members simmering _ and whispering _
was the bombshell of the night before, when media reports caused
incoming House Speaker Robert L. Livingston to confess he had had
several extramarital affairs in 33 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to stop this madness; it's tearing this
institution apart and creating an unworkable atmosphere,'' House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay said in an interview. DeLay, nicknamed
``the Hammer,'' has been one of the chief architects of the GOP
impeachment strategy. In January, DeLay began calling for Clinton
to be impeached and in September demanded he resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just horrible that to gain political advantage, people
will destroy a person's private, family life,'' DeLay said. ``It's
horrible that the media does it, too,'' he said, shaking his finger
at a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Ray LaHood, an Illinois Republican who once
worked for the gentlemanly House GOP leader Robert Michel and has a
passion for restoring civility to public life, was tapped to chair
the House impeachment debate. It was a sign of how extraordinarily
harsh the House has become, and how unseemly Friday's subject was,
that LaHood delivered this warning shortly after 9 a.m. as the
debate was about to begin:
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the personal conduct of the president is at issue,
the rules prohibit members from engaging in generally personal
abusive language toward the president and also from engaging in
comparisons to personal conduct of sitting members of either House
of Congress,'' LaHood said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats jeered.
</P>
<P>
   The key congressional players, except for House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, were present as LaHood slammed down the gavel to open
what is the second presidential impeachment debate in US history
and the first in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Henry Hyde, the silver-haired chairman of the
Judiciary Committee, took a seat toward the back of the chamber.
Representative Barney Frank, the Newton Democrat, paced the aisles
but didn't seem to have any of his usual parliamentary maneuvers to
offer. Representative Jesse Jackson Jr., an Illinois Democrat,
appeared to be giving Livingston words of comfort as he pumped the
speaker-designate's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber was about two-thirds full _ more Republicans than
Democrats were there _ when Hyde began an emotional 20-minute
speech defending impeachment and citing the Founding Fathers, Ben
Franklin, George Washington, Moses, Abraham Lincoln, and the heroes
of Lexington, Concord, and Bunker Hill as his inspirations on the
rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``No man or woman _ no matter how highly placed, no matter how
effective a communicator, no matter how gifted a manipulator of
opinion polls or winner of votes _ can be above the law in a
democracy,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional beep of a pager and the catlike cry of
a baby, the big chamber was quiet as Hyde's solemn words sank in.
The usual commotion of members milling around ceased while Gephardt
spoke for 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The press gallery overflowed with reporters on hand for the
start of Friday's 13 hours of debate, but spectators formed
shorter-than-expected lines to enter the House's public galleries.
Extra police were on hand for crowd control that turned out to be
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm indifferent to the whole thing,'' said Tom Lamontanaro, a
17-year-old student from Valley Stream, N.Y., who waited with some
classmates for a seat in the visitor's gallery. ``This is about the
president's personal life, and it's not the public's business.''
</P>
<P>
   For such a historic day, the American public was noticeably
absent. There were only a few demonstrators, including a man with
the inexplicable sign, ``Stella hates war,'' on the Capitol lawn.
There were hardly any tourists in Statuary Hall. And when
Representatives John Lewis of Georgia orated like an evangelist,
Martin Meehan of Lowell fumed at the GOP, and Bob Barr of Georgia
called up the name of President Kennedy to help impeach Clinton,
few of their colleagues were on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to be done to show we aren't brain dead,''
complained Representative Patrick Kennedy, a Rhode Island Democrat.
``This is as significant as anything we will ever do here, yet it's
turned into just another floor vote. Where is the emotion? Where is
the gravity?''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy showed considerable emotion in blasting Barr, one of the
president's fiercest enemies, for invoking the name of his slain
uncle. ``These Republicans are not profiles in courage,'' Kennedy
said, alleging that Barr was a ``racist'' for appearing recently
before a white supremacy group. ``They are the farthest thing from
it that I can imagine.'' A spokesman for Barr had no comment on
Kennedy's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, who some think has been overzealous in his pursuit of
the president, said Judiciary Committee Republicans showed both
courage and a sense of duty when they carried the cause of
impeachment beyond the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week I brought my four children and two grandchildren
here, to this awesome room of democracy,'' Schippers said, looking
around the Rotunda. ``I told them, `This is what grandpa has been
in Washington fighting for.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
