<HEADLINE>
THEATER OF THE UNREAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There has probably never been a time when
``surreal'' was such a common word in American parlance. ``This is
so surreal that you couldn't write a movie like this,'' said a
friend, ``where everything is so partisan.'' Or where the scenario
changes so swiftly, from impeachment to war to a House
speaker-designate's ``Oprah''-like confession.
</P>
<P>
   For all the bizarreness of what has been happening here, though,
the atmosphere seems less like a Fellini film than a Tom
Clancy-like thriller in which readers have a hard time believing
that the government could come to such a state of affairs, on both
sides of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   For a newcomer to the Beltway and its odd customs, the first
gasp is at what a very different city Washington is from Boston. It
almost feels like a different country, or at least a ``pretend''
city -- a Las Vegas feeding on politics instead of gambling, a
Disney World of ideological division where Democrats and
Republicans go at it like cowboys and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is like a giant set,'' said a Massachusetts friend
who used to call Washington home. What she means is, there's
Washington the Movie, as beautiful a city as you could imagine, but
step outside the radius of ``official'' Washington and there's some
of the most unrelenting crime and poverty in the country. It's
something like ``The Truman Show,'' the movie in which the lead
character thinks he's living a life of nonstop comfort only to find
that his life has been designed as a televised entertainment for
the rest of the world and that he can't escape the TV set.
</P>
<P>
   You can escape it here, but it takes some doing. ``Official''
Washington is steeped in historical grandeur, from its architecture
to its amenities. Charming old hotels usher you into a room with a
stereo system preset to the classical music station; a restaurant
menu offers a mouth-watering replica of dinner in the manner of
Thomas Jefferson. Buildings like the Capitol are breathtakingly
beautiful, inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy in such a world of comfort and privilege to feel
``Truman''-ized. That seems particularly so for politicians, as if
each one is the star of his ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,'' there
to do the will of the people even as they get further and further
removed from them. And of course the disconnect works both ways, as
people become disillusioned with a man who imagines there won't be
any negative consequences for using the office of the presidency,
literally, as a trysting place or for congressmen who ignore the
country's sense of what the penalty for such behavior should be.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Neil Gabler suggests in his book ``Life the Movie''
everything in the public eye is becoming a movie, nowhere is that
more evident than on Capitol Hill. As a colleague got out of a cab
at the House of Representatives Friday and saw plots of microphone
banks everywhere (with no shortage of politicians to fill them) and
as a camera turned toward him in case he was somebody, he noted,
``Just like the Oscars.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, though, the movie was ``Dull and Duller'' despite the
import of the proceedings. There were flashes of oratory, certainly
-- Henry Hyde's historical perspective, Charles Schumer's
mythological metaphors, John Lewis's thundering intonations
recalling the calls to conscience of the civil rights movement. The
late Lionel Barrymore would have been perfect to play Hyde, and
Harvey Keitel with a voice transplant could be Barney Frank, but
looking out into the gallery didn't provide much inspiration, in
any regard. Mary Bono, Sonny's widow, moved restlessly across the
chamber, from one representative to another, bringing a smile to
the face of Hyde and every other Republican male she approached.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, this could have been a convention of shoe salesmen,
and to judge from Bob Livingston's Thursday-night confession, even
the straightest-looking of straight arrows here is apt to behave
like a conventioneer. But then, in ``Washington the Movie,''
everyone gets to be Harrison Ford. Perhaps the most astute summary
was offered by California Congresswoman Zoe Lofgren: ``I share with
fellow Americans the feeling of unreality.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ed Siegel is the Globe's theater critic and critic-at large.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
