</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREAL AURA FOR ROUTINE BUSINESS IN WASHINGTON AND THE WHITE
HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-DEBATERS, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-TV,
IMPEACH-TV-NOTEBOOK.) (rl) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The president, some of his aides say, no longer
picks up the phone late at night as frequently as he used to to
reach out to friends. One friend, who once talked to him daily,
hasn't heard from Clinton since Thanksgiving. Another tells members
of Clinton's inner circle that the president is down and urges them
to call him and get his political fires burning again.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, virtually every night until Christmas Eve there is a
party at the White House. On Thursday it was a glittering dinner
for disabled athletes in the Special Olympics. This weekend, there
are two parties for hundreds of friends and supporters. On Monday,
1,500 members of the Washington press corps _not exactly Bill and
Hillary Clinton's favorite crowd _ will swarm through, bringing
along their children for sleigh rides on the South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of the disjointed nature of Washington this week,
the nightscope pictures from Baghdad that merged seamlessly with
the raucous daylong impeachment debate in the House Friday and the
whispered asides about how the president is holding up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet real life inevitably intrudes. At the National Capital YMCA,
where many of the city's leading lawyers and lobbyists sweat off
their lunch five blocks from the White House, the television sets
on Thursday night were tuned chiefly to the latest episode of
``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in and out of this city for 30 years and it's the
most bizarre atmosphere I've ever seen,'' one of Clinton's Cabinet
members said over lunch the other day. ``We plod along with the
most normal business in the world _ this morning it was the budgets
and the trade deficit _ and yet you have this sense that you're
watching a bus headed over the cliff, an no one has looked down.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was the air of unreality stronger Friday than in the
White House itself. As scenes of House members debating articles of
impeachment seeped out of television sets in every office, and the
Pentagon announced a third wave of bombing in Iraq, the president
was deep into discussions with the leaders of the European
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The hot subject of their long lunch in the Roosevelt Room?
</P>
<P>
   Bananas.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, Europe's refusal, in America's view, to
comply with a ruling from the World Trade Organization that would
end discrimination against bananas imported by two U.S. firms,
Chiquita Brands International and Dole Food Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird, seriously weird,'' one participant in the
meetings said, reflecting on how Clinton, at a moment of military
action and imminent impeachment, seemed completely engrossed in the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the president tried to change the topic. But Sir
Leon Brittan, the European Union's tenacious trade minister, kept
returning to what, in his plummy, nasal accent, sounded like ``the
bo-non-na problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Clinton finally said, ``the only thing that makes
this discussion almost tolerable is listening to you pronounce
`bo-non-nas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As the cruise missiles began to explode in Baghdad on Wednesday
night and congressional leaders were still arguing over when to
schedule the impeachment vote, Shi Guangsheng, China's trade
minister, was just settling down to an elegant dinner in the main
hall of the Commerce Department, along with 60 or so U.S. business
executives and Chinese bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William Daley stood up before the first toast
to announce that the bombing had begun. ``Our thoughts and prayers
are with our military personnel and with the people of Iraq,''
Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has opposed the action, and Shi sat expressionless. But
at neighboring tables there were gentle questions about whether
Clinton would survive _ and if he did, whether he would be so
weakened the China should not count on striking any big deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand,'' said Deng Zhan, one of Shi's aides. ``He
seems like a very capable president. He wants to understand China.
Why are you doing this?''
</P>
<P>
   If the ghost of Andrew Johnson haunts Washington, it is
doubtless wandering around the third floor of the Treasury
Building, just across from the East Wing of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The suite that Johnson operated out of for weeks after the
Lincoln assassination is now the office of the undersecretary of
Treasury international affairs _ ground zero in the recent
financial crisis. On the walls are the magazine illustrations of
Johnson meeting foreign delegations and congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just went on conducting the business of the country,'' one
Treasury official deadpanned the other day, repeating the White
House mantra about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There is one issue that seems to unify embittered Democrats and
Republicans, embattled aides at the White House, and despairing
members of the Cabinet. It boils down to this: Get me out of here.
</P>
<P>
   A senior member of the National Security Council said he planned
to get in his car as soon as the bombing stops and ``toss my cell
phone into the middle of the Beltway, where with any luck it will
be crushed by an 18-wheeler.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
