u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-515&AMP;AD     12-18 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SENATORS PAID LITTLE ATTENTION TO HOUSE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-DEBATERS, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-TV,
IMPEACH-TV-NOTEBOOK.) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, was not exactly glued to
his television on Friday as the House debated impeaching President
Clinton. The small Sony in DeWine's spacious Capitol Hill office
was not even turned on for most of the afternoon while the senator
presided over a marathon staff meeting.
</P>
<P>
   As for the final impeachment vote scheduled for Saturday, DeWine
expects to be watching his 11-year-old son play basketball instead.
``I'm not going to sit here and spend eight or 12 hours watching,''
he said. ``Life goes on and I've got a big agenda. I just don't
have the luxury of time for that.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 100 senators who would be jurors in the trial of William
Jefferson Clinton if the House impeached him, as seems virtually
certain, Friday's all-day debate was a bit like background music at
an elegant restaurant. A few paid rapt attention, but most seemed
to be listening with barely half an ear as they busied themselves
instead with legislative matters, constituent meetings and holiday
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really not paying that much attention'' to the debate,
said Mary Healy, a spokeswoman for Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore. ``He's
fulfilling his duties as a senator. Once it comes to the Senate,
then he'll have to pay closer attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Smith, most senators spent their days in their home
districts, catching only snippets of the debate on car radios or
office televisions as they rushed between meetings or family
obligations. Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., devoted his day to
visiting with grandchildren, a spokeswoman said. Sen. Jeff
Sessions, R-Ala., was too busy traveling on business and packing up
a house he has just sold to watch the debate, his spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who split his day
between New York City and Washington, was not expected to see any
of the debate because, as a rule, he rarely watches television.
``He'll probably watch `McNeil-Lehrer' and then read about it in
the newspapers tomorrow,'' said Tony Bullock, Moynihan's chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a number of senators said they watched the debate
closely. Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said she snapped on the
television set at home the moment she arose Friday morning, and
even took a radio with her when she went for a midmorning walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last act for some of them,'' said Ms. Boxer, a
former House member who showed an alumnus's fascination with the
performances of several former colleagues who are retiring this
year. ``I feel sad that it had to be devoted to this.''
</P>
<P>
   One senator-to-be had a box seat for Friday's debate: Rep.
Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who will enter the Senate in January.
After delivering a floor speech on Friday morning opposing
impeachment, Schumer marched back to his office and listened to the
debate as he packed files for the move to the Senate side of
Capitol Hill. He was not much impressed by what he heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the House in its finest hour,'' said Schumer, who
plans to vote against conviction in the Senate. ``It was very
partisan, and going over old ground.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While House members were pounding fists and expressing partisan
outrage across the street, DeWine spent his day ensconced in the
Russell office building, meeting with aides to discuss several
months' worth of legislative work.
</P>
<P>
   While DeWine munched on saltines and sipped homemade
cheese-and-broccoli soup, his aides briefed him about an upcoming
trip to Haiti, anti-drug legislation, and programs to fight hunger
in Africa. ``You want to do the rest of the world now?'' asked his
legislative director, Robert Hoffman, after they finished
discussing Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine said that he had directed aides to watch the entire
impeachment debate and interrupt him if there were significant
developments. But by 2 o'clock, the aide had yet to break into the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., also said an aide was watching the
debate, listening for particularly insightful arguments.
</P>
<P>
   But Chafee, who was in Washington for most of the day, said he
had not had much time to listen to the debate himself. And as for
the vote on Saturday, he sounded an uncertain note about whether he
would be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the Saturday before Christmas,'' he said. ``Like
everybody else, I'm way behind in my Christmas shopping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
