</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RISE AS WORLD EVENTS FAIL TO RATTLE INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Market performance chart is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors seemed nonchalant Friday as the debate on
the impeachment of President Clinton got under way and the bombing
of Iraq continued. Stocks rose, with the Nasdaq index surging 2
percent to a new high, while the other major indexes rose modestly.
Bond prices inched higher while the dollar slipped.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, even with the surprise attack on Iraq and the
sudden certainty that the House of Representatives would vote to
impeach the president, stocks rose, bond prices inched higher and
the dollar gained against European currencies, although it fell
against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street worries about one thing and that is the outlook
for the economy,'' said Alfred Goldman, director of market analysis
at A.G. Edwards Inc. in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country will do just as well if Al Gore is president for
the next several years. But if you told me that chairman Greenspan
had an unhappy home life I would be worried,'' he said, referring
to Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts think that the markets have had time to react to
the prospect of an impeachment vote against Clinton and are not
worried because it is assumed the Senate cannot muster the
two-thirds vote to remove him from office. But that does not mean
there won't be some reaction Monday after the expected vote Friday
_ especially if people begin to doubt Clinton's ability survive a
Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index jumped to its first new high since Dec. 9,
rising 42.26 points to 2,086.14. It was up 2.8 percent for the
week. New optimism on future earnings for the likes of Intel, up 3
1/8 to 120, and Cisco Systems, up 5 9/16 to 90 7/16, pushed the
index higher. ``You are seeing better than expected earnings and
estimates going up,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer
at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 27.81 points, or
three-tenths of one percent, to 8,903.63. It has been lagging in
comparison to the Nasdaq and Standard &AMP; Poor's index in recent
performance because it is short on technology stocks and heavy with
industrials like Caterpillar, Boeing, and Minnesota, Mining and
Manufacturing, all of which have issued earnings warnings recently.
For the week, the Dow rose nine-tenths of one percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks rose 8.05 points, or
seven-tenths of one percent, to 1,188.03. It is just three-tenths
of one percent below its all-time high while the Dow is 5 percent
from its peak. For the week, the S&AMP;P is up 1.8 percent. The Russell
index of 2,000 smaller company stocks finished up 3.64 points, or
nine-tenths of one percent, at 397.42. For the week, it was up just
five-tenths of one percent.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly expiration of stock futures, stock index futures
and stock index options added to trading volume but did not lead to
volatile trading Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices were little changed. The price of the
30-year bond rose 4/32 to 103 28/32 while the yield, which moves in
the opposite direction, inched down to 5.00 percent from 5.01
percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar fell to 115.61 Japanese yen from 116.13 Thursday
while it ended at 1.6641 German marks, down from 1.6681.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Fand, senior foreign exchange strategist at Bank Boston,
said the dollar's fall came in light trading. He said the declines
were really just a give back of the `knee-jerk'' gains the dollar
made on Wednesday, when an attack on Iraq by the United States and
Britain became a possibility. The actual attack was announced in
the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Fand said that currency traders are more worried about the
impact of impeachment on the dollar than bond and stock traders.
Some think, he said, that Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who has
championed the administration's strong-dollar policy, would resign
if Clinton is seriously weakened by an impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   The main concern for equity investors now appears to be
corporate earnings. Despite the improved outlook for some
technology sectors, more and more forecasts are showing a slowdown
or a decline as American economic growth eases next year. Corporate
earnings declined in the third quarter but the two main compilers
of forecasts, First Call Corp. and IBES International, are split on
the outlook for the current quarter. IBES is showing a 1.4 percent
decline and First Call a 3.4 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   But both numbers have weakened in the last week after new
earnings warnings from several companies. The IBES forecast is down
1 percentage point from last week's three-tenths of one percent
decline and First Call is off nine-tenths of one percent from a 4.3
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Friday, Merck was off 3 7/16 to 44 1/2, and 3M was
down 2 1/2 to to 70 3/4. Both made negative earnings announcements
in the last two weeks. Caterpillar, which warned about earnings
this week, rose 3/4 to 41 7/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
