<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7746 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-SANCTIONS-BOS &LR;      12-18 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SANCTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQI LEADERSHIP DEFIANT AS ATTACKS CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ The US and British missile attacks on Iraq intensified
early Saturday after pounding the heart of Saddam Hussein's regime,
leaving a trail of destruction at southern positions of the
Republican Guard, oil refineries in Basra, TV transmitters near
Baghdad, and presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
   An angry and besieged Iraqi leadership responded by sharply
redrawing diplomatic lines, and making it apparent that the UN
weapons inspectors would not return to Iraq unless harsh economic
sanctions were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   A defiant Saddam appeared in a taped statement Friday night
aired on a Qatar-based television network, telling the Iraqi
people, ``You must thank God for your success, and continue
resistance. We are the people of good morality. We are not going to
compromise to the other side of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the words of defiance, Pentagon officials said they have
been struck by the lack of military resistance from Iraqi forces.
The United States denied Iraqi claims that more than 77 US cruise
missiles had been shot down.
</P>
<P>
   The streaking red tracers and rattle of Iraqi anti-aircraft fire
over Baghdad in the predawn hours were noticeably shortlived
compared with the resistance offered in the previous two days of US
missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Following through on President Clinton's promise to step up a
campaign aimed at toppling Saddam, US military jets also dropped
leaflets on Iraqi forces in southern Iraq telling them not to worry
about being targeted unless they are defending what they referred
to as ``the Baghdad regime,'' according to Voice of America
broadcasts heard in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets also warned the forces not to threaten moderate
states in the region, Defense Secretary William Cohen and Joint
Chiefs of Staff Gen. Henry H. Shelton told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said the raids, which were a response to a U.N. report
this week that Iraq had failed to live up to its promise to
cooperate with arms inspectors, were now gathering steam.
</P>
<P>
   If there were any doubts about Clinton's vow for ``sustained''
attacks, they have been dismissed. Already more US cruise missiles
have been launched in Operation Desert Fox, as the attacks have
been dubbed, than the 289 fired at Iraq in the 1991 Persian Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in Baghdad, Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz said that UNSCOM chief Richard Butler weapons ``has
killed his job'' by ``preparing the grounds for this aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said that the US and British attacks were orchestrated
through Butler via a report to the UN Security Council that, Aziz
claimed, falsely accused Iraq of not cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   In his November speech at the end of the previous standoff with
Iraq, Clinton called off an air strike and gave Iraq a last chance
to comply. At that time he warned that if there were any other
violations, the US would attack without warning. In that speech,
Clinton acknowledged that if sustained US strikes are undertaken
that it would probably be the end of UNSCOM's work in Iraq. That
now seems to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq will not tolerate UNSCOM and sanctions at the same
time,'' said Aziz. ``If they want to keep the sanctions, let them
leave UNSCOM in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz stressed that Iraq fulfilled its responsibility in
accordance with the spirit of the letter it sent to the UN
secretary-general on Nov. 14 and that Unscom has carried out
hundreds of inspections since then. Aziz added that Iraqi
authorities had cooperated with inspectors despite
``provocations.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz also expressed anger that the United States and Britain
have attacked targets that have wounded civilians. He described
sustained missile strikes causing vast damage:
</P>
<P>
   A warehouse belonging to the ministry of trade was hit. Four
warehouses in Baghdad holding 1,000 tons of cotton were destroyed
by a cruise missile. The targets also included an oil refinery in
the southern port city of Basrah and the old ministry of defense
building in downtown Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The targets seem aimed at degrading Saddam's military machinery
as well as his grip on the civilian society.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said attacks on civilian targets were ``sinister.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The collateral damage on the ministry of defense led to the
nearby destruction of hospitals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Friday were taken to see the hospital, which had blown
out windows and moderate damage from the nearby attack. But there
were no reports of injuries to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi health ministry announced Thursday that at least 25
people have died during the attacks and 75 have been wounded in
Baghdad, but a complete casualty toll has not been announced. The
bombings in the southern cities of Basrah and Saddam's hometown of
Tikrit were certain to have caused some casualties but Iraqi
officials offered no official accounting of dead or wounded.
</P>
<P>
   At the Al Yarmouk Hospital, among Iraq's largest hospitals and
located in the Western part of the city, officials Friday said they
had received approximately 13 people who arrived at the hospital
dead on arrival during the first two days of attacks. They said
they had treated a total of 34 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital was once a crown jewel in Iraq's formerly advanced
and now crippled medical infrastructure. The hospitals are hard hit
by the crushing economic sanctions imposed in the aftermath of the
1991 Gulf War. At the entrance there are large painted signs that
read, ``Down, Down, USA.''
</P>
<P>
   In the emergency and surgical wards, those wounded lay in
rusting cots amid the bleak conditions of the hospital. Among them
was Muhsin Hadi, 20, who said he was walking home from his job
selling cigarettes on Thursday night when US cruise missiles
pounded a seven-story military industrial building in the heart of
downtown Baghdad. The blast blew him off his feet, he said, and
sent shards of shrapnel into his abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can America do this?'' he asked. ``They say they hit only
military targets, but they hit people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In the surgical ward, Jasem Zubati, 41, was listed in serious,
but stable condition with head wounds and a fractured verterbrae.
With bandages wrapped around his head and in obvious pain, he
described how his home in the Al Adel section of Baghdad was hit by
a missile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crashed through the back of our house, right into the
kitchen,'' said Zubati, a well-to-do engineer who has profited from
an import business under the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter visited the home, and saw the evidence of the damage.
There was a large crater in the rear of the house, and broken
kitchen appliances were stacked in the front of the house. Zubati
said his injuries came when the roof of his home, where he lived
with his wife and three children, caved in. He has a three-week old
son. None of them were injured, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is my house a secret, military location? Have I done anything
to America?'' he asked, shaking with anger and pain. ``I will
avenge myself if it takes 40 years. I will ask Saddam to take
revenge. I have great hatred for your government.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained difficult Friday for reporters to assess the full
extent of the damage. The Ministry of Information forbids reporters
from traveling without a government ``minder'' accompanying them,
and no reporters have been permitted to travel outside Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that the attacks seemed aimed directly at the heart of the
Iraqi leader's personal power base, Aziz said virtually all of the
sites had been inspected and heavily monitored by UN arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They attack presidential sites, they are guest houses built by
the Iraqis, they are fine buildings, they just want to destroy
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz made repeated references to the impeachment proceedings
engulfing Clinton's presidency and fixating both the American and
Iraqi people. He said that Clinton ``lied to his own people'' and
that he was now ``lying about Iraq to justify this aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can the Americn people believe a man who has lied to his
own people, to the Congress. He lies to his nation and tells the
truth about Iraq? How can that be? How can we swallow that? These
are lies, cheap lies,'' said Aziz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
