A7754 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLY-`FOX'-CLINTON-IRA     12-18 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLY-`FOX'-CLINTON-IRAQ-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYNICS MAY FORGIVE CLINTON'S DESPERATION IF STRIKES GET SADDAM  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 600-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 19 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A sense of desperation attends the decision to launch the latest
wave of air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The man who took the decision, Bill Clinton, was facing an
imminent vote in the House of Representatives on his impeachment;
what better way to show that he was worthy of the office of
President of the United States than to exercise, in a statesmanlike
way, the authority it gives him as commander-in-chief of his
country's armed forces?
</P>
<P>
   The man against whom the decision was taken, Saddam Hussein, is
desperate too, constrained by sanctions, dogged by arms inspectors,
hated by everyone and, eight years after the end of the Gulf war,
still without hope of shaking off his pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the wider world _ in different degrees frightened of
Hussein, worried about the spread of weapons of mass destruction,
apprehensive about the use of force against a sovereign country _
it too has grown exasperated, ever more conscious that the Iraqi
dictator presents problems that never seem to go away and that have
no straightforward solution.
</P>
<P>
   If all this is unsatisfactory, so too perhaps was the trigger
for Operation Desert Fox, a report by Richard Butler, the head of
the team of U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   This showed that Hussein had not fully cooperated with the
UNSCOM inspectors, as he had promised to, but it was not
unambiguously clear that his lack of cooperation had in fact been
designed to prevent UNSCOM from doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   Another, awkwardly plausible interpretation is that Hussein's
obstructiveness may have been designed to stop the inspectors, and
the Israelis to whom he assumes they pass all the information they
gather, from learning about all sorts of secrets not directly
related to weapons-making.
</P>
<P>
   Still, America _ and Britain, which has also joined the
operation _ had always said that any failure by Hussein to keep his
word would bring an attack, without further ado, and the Iraqi
therefore commands little real sympathy, whatever the public
denunciations of the decision to launch the air strikes by China,
Russia, some Arabs and, to a lesser extent, France.
</P>
<P>
   Even Arab sympathizers lost patience with Hussein on the last
occasion, in November, when he stopped cooperating with the U.N.,
and most people, whether friend or foe of Iraq, must have felt that
there was an inevitability about these strikes.
</P>
<P>
   That they should have come now, at Clinton's hour of need _ just
as an earlier strike, in August, against an apparently innocent
factory in Sudan came at another hour of need for the American
president _ is unfortunate, to say the least. Yet they should be
judged, in the end, on their effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   If they succeed in achieving their stated aim, that will be
welcome. But merely to ``degrade Saddam's capacity to develop and
deliver weapons of mass destruction and to degrade his ability to
threaten his neighbors,'' is not ambitious, and will not solve the
long-run problem.
</P>
<P>
   This, as Clinton and other American officials have been making
ever more explicitly clear, is Hussein himself.
</P>
<P>
   No one can be sure how, or when, Hussein will leave office. He
could be thrown out tomorrow, or hang on, as Fidel Castro has in
Cuba, to infuriate American presidents for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   But if this round of air strikes should prove to be the lever
that prises him from power, the world will surely judge them a
success. It may even swallow some of its cynicism about the man who
ordered them at such a fortuitous time. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 600-word article, it must be purchased
from New York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in
New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
