<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-MARKIEWICZ-TEX     12-18 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MARKIEWICZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK IT: CRUNCH-TIME GIFT IDEAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Just as moviemakers know the holidays are
the best time to roll out blockbuster films, publishers realize
Christmas is the season to peddle books.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain another, um, literary effort from a TV
comedian like Ray Romano.
</P>
<P>
   Sports books, naturally, are front and center on bookstore
shelves. What else do you get a fan who already owns a pair of
officially licensed team boxer shorts and a big-screen TV?
</P>
<P>
   Why, a book.
</P>
<P>
   But there are so many out there, and every shopper has a budget.
To that end, here are some of the top titles, with a brief synopsis
on each, to aid that last-minute shopping:
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the World''
</P>
<P>
   A book about Muhammad Ali, but not just another book about Ali.
David Remnick, who won a Pulitzer Prize in 1994 for ``Lenin's
Tomb'', offers the best sports read of the season, placing the rise
of the young Cassius Clay in the context of his times _ both in the
boxing world and in society at large. The event at the center of
the book is the Clay-Sonny Liston fight in 1964 in Miami, a
watershed moment that had a profound impact on race relations and
American culture. Remnick was granted an extensive interview with
Ali at his West Michigan home, and the result is a unique insight
into the champ. Remnick writes like a dream and the pages just fly.
A worthy gift for non-sports fans, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reflections of the Game (Lives in Baseball)''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran sports photographer Ron Modra uses his camera and,
occasionally his pen, to reflect on great and not-so-great baseball
players and moments of the past two decades. Modra's keen eye
captures scenes far beyond the standard headfirst-slide shots. His
keen ear senses special situations.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, a photo of a long-retired Mickey Mantle,
sitting alone in the stands of a baseball park in Florida one hot
summer morning. Muses Mantle: ``God, I wish I could still play.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny shots abound, like one of St. Louis Cardinals' mascot Fred
Bird, in full costume, fast-food cartons lying at his feet, sitting
in a locker room and sipping a soft drink as he reads a paper
spread out on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Bonus for Rangers fans: The cover photo of Pudge Rodriguez is
arresting.
</P>
<P>
   Former ballplayer-turned-writer Pat Jordan contributes an essay
on his time in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Love of the Game''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's life story in pix and text, in his own words.
Most of this ground has been plowed before, not surprising given
the media glare Jordan has been under his entire career. But it's
still kind of fun to read his views on Jerry Reinsdorf and Jerry
Krause, whom he dismisses as ``businessmen, not sportsmen.''
</P>
<P>
   The photos are keepers, though, particularly the ones of the
young Jordan, back when he had hair and shorter shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aikman: Mind, Body and Soul''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys quarterback's version of ``For the Love of the
Game''. Lots of original photos of Aikman in and out of games, some
working out, some just sitting on a lawn relaxing. The first-person
story, however, is even less personally revealing than Jordan's
book. You know you're not going to get much inside information when
the first sentence of the book is Troy telling you the date and
place he was born.
</P>
<P>
   There are also lines like this one: ``We \Rthe Cowboys\S feel we
are at our best when we are running and throwing the ball
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ``I've always felt that for me to be at my best, I needed
to keep in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The most telling passage might be the one where Aikman talks
about his coaches, saying every one, from Terry Donahue on down,
``influenced my career in different ways.'' He skips right over
Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pros and Cons (The Criminals Who Play in the NFL)''
</P>
<P>
   The work of investigative reporters Jeff Benedict and Don
Yaeger, ``Pros and Cons'' isn't exactly the kind of book to get you
in the Yule mood. Meticulously researched, it quantifies the extent
of criminal behavior among pro football players. Using police
reports and court records, Yaeger and Benedict spell out in graphic
detail the various beatings and assaults perpetrated by some NFL
players on their victims.
</P>
<P>
   The authors write that these accounts ``will shock and frighten
you.'' The sad thing is that many readers won't be shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Total Hockey (The Official Encyclopedia of The National Hockey
League)''
</P>
<P>
   Now, why didn't somebody think to do this before? Records of
every one of nearly 5,000 NHL players, but lots more, including
origins and history of the game, explanations of hockey strategy
and biographies. In sum, everything you'd want to know about the
game _ in an 1,878-page package. So, don't send this one in the
mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
