<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME IT'S FOR CROWN AND GLORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ It's the dream match everyone in women's
volleyball circles has been waiting for since, well, late in the
summer when the season started and both teams were laying claim to
being No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State vs. Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Finally.
</P>
<P>
   These two undefeated, unmarked, unfazed 35-0 powerhouses will
resolve their differences here this afternoon and decide, once and
for all, which one deserves to be the national champion.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed to be the first time in NCAA tournament history
that teams with perfect records will meet in a title match.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's hard to envision Brian Gimmillaro's high-leaping,
high-energy, high-scoring assassins losing to anyone, especially
after their latest exclamation point masterpiece here Thursday
evening when they swept past the Florida Gators, 15-2, 15-8 and
15-10, before the largest crowd ever to watch an NCAA women's
volleyball match, 12,327, at the Kohl Center.
</P>
<P>
   But who knows for sure?
</P>
<P>
   After all, this will be a long-awaited confrontation between the
two teams who thoroughly have dominated their sport throughout the
season, a classic Ali-Frazier, Lakers-Celtics matchup between foes
brimming with talent, pride, confidence and momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting all season to play Penn State, and I think
a lot of other people also have been waiting for the match,'' said
Gimmillaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we've been waiting for,'' said Misty May, summing
up her team's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Misty May would want to cap her dazzling career with
her first NCAA title, as much as she and her teammates want to
atone for the disappointment they suffered a year ago in this
tournament in their semifinal loss to Stanford, there is no one on
this Long Beach team who wants to win this title more than Brian
Gimmillaro.
</P>
<P>
   He's been pulling out all the motivational ploys to make sure
his players are at an emotional peak for this one, from driving
them relentlessly at practices to reminding them constantly of the
NCAA's alleged bias against them to even showing them a video in
the dressing room before Thursday's semifinal of the final minutes
and post-game celebration of last Friday's match against the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As if Long Beach needed any added help against the beleaguered
Gators, the 49er associate athletic director, Cindy Masner, hired
the University of Wisconsin band to perform for the 49ers during
their execution of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Adorned in 49er garb, the Badger musicians started off playing
``On Wisconsin,'' but also played the 49ers' fight song on an
evening when the 49ers once again dazzled an audience with their
spikes, digs, blocks and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Misty May was brilliant and this is a recording. She
recorded her sixth triple double of the season 32 assists, 11 kills
and 15 digs.
</P>
<P>
   And imagine how well she would have played had she actually been
at peak health!
</P>
<P>
   According to Gimmillaro afterward, May and several other 49er
players were hampered by colds and wore down as the late-starting
match it didn't begin here until 10:15 didn't conclude until 15
minutes before midnight, Central Standard Time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off well, but we got tired in the last couple of
games because a lot of our players aren't feeling well,'' said
Gimmillaro, who did not hide his displeasure at having to play such
a late-night affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little ridiculous that college students have to start a
match this late in the evening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it made any difference.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers ran their game-winning streak to 67. They haven't lost
one since a setback on Oct. 2 to USC.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it won't be easy for the 49ers against a resilient Penn
State team that isn't as flashy or as explosive as Long Beach is
there any team in college volleyball that is? but might be superior
defensively and might be just as disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, for the first time since Oct. 10, the Nittany Lions actually
lost a game Thursday night against Nebraska a 15-8 setback in the
third game but in between they beat the `Huskers by scores of
15-11, 15-8 and 15-11.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State's All American setter, Bonnie Bremer, might not be
Misty May, but she does many of the same impressive things for a
team that has three powerful hitters in Lauren Cicciamani, Christy
Cochran and Carrie Schonveld.
</P>
<P>
   It's a team that doesn't beat itself, and seems able to come up
with one deft dig after another, which it will have to do against a
49er team that never stopped attacking.
</P>
<P>
   But this 49ers are special.
</P>
<P>
   They might have been ailing Thursday night, and they might have
got sleep-eyed as the night went on.
</P>
<P>
   But the end result was the same another one-sided victory.
</P>
<P>
   And now they need one more to secure their legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
