<HEADER>
A7761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MARKET19-COX     12-18 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MARKET19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Economic history provides few clues on impeachment's mark on
markets
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Richard Nixon's era doesn't provide Wall Street with a
clear picture of what to expect in case of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The market fell 27.6 percent in 1974, the year Nixon resigned
before the full House could vote on the issue. But the state of the
economy gets more blame for the market's decline than political
turmoil. The Arab oil embargo had triggered a recession _ and
inflation. Wholesale prices in July 1974 jumped by what was the
equivalent of a 44 percent annual increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad economic environment,'' said Donald Ratajczak,
director of the Economic Forecasting Center at Georgia State
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you compare the two periods, we didn't know what to
do then. This time around, we think we are driving the (economy)
ship. It's not the same kind of negative time, when we were asking,
`What in the world can we do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices were behind the economic problems, but Nixon's
troubles may have contributed to what happened, Ratajczak said,
because people were leaving his administration. ``Nixon had an
incredibly competent Treasury, and they (top officials) all started
to run.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment process didn't go entirely unnoticed on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, July 27, the House Judiciary Committee voted to
impeach Nixon. On Monday, the Dow fell 13.68 points, or 1.7
percent, to 770.89. Inflation worries and ``uneasiness over
impeachment'' were cited in a Associated Press stock market story.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasiness would continue into early August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every move the market made seemed once again to be dictated by
unfolding events surrounding the question of impeachment and
President Nixon's future in office,'' the Associated Press said of
trading on Tuesday, Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Aug. 9, Nixon resigned. The next day, the stock
market slipped, but by less than 1 percent, and the volume was
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood is one of apathy,'' said one London stockbroker
describring trading to the Associated Press. Brokers in the United
States concluded that investors had already absorbed Nixon's
resignation, and were waiting on the sidelines to see what his
successor, Gerald Ford, would do.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's resignation, said Ratajczak, ``cleared the air.'' The
same thing would be accomplished if President Clinton resigned, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, Ratajczak said, would be ``down on the day of his
resignation, and then up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
