<HEADLINE>
BRITISH IRKED BY COOL FRENCH REACTION TO RAIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON -- Two weeks ago British Prime Minister Tony Blair
strolled with French president Jacques Chirac through St. Malo, a
port in Brittany from which French pirates once launched attacks on
English ships.
</P>
<P>
   It was an appropriate place for two nations whose wars once
defined European hostilities to launch a joint venture that could
redefine European cooperation. The St. Malo Declaration, signed
earlier this month, calls for the creation of a common European
Union defense policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair's separation from parts of Europe over Britain's
participation in the American bombing of Iraq shows that the
creation of a single European defense policy could prove more
difficult than the single European currency to be launched in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Gulf War, when European countries fell squarely
behind the American-led coalition, there is no European consensus
on the wisdom of bombing Iraq to force Saddam Hussein to cooperate
with UN weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombing began Wednesday night, the Spanish offered to
help, the Germans were cautiously supportive, the French were cool
and the Italians dismissed the military action as useless. By
Friday, support for the Anglo-American effort of the new German
government of Gerhard Schroeder had grown stronger.
</P>
<P>
   One British diplomat foresaw Wednesday night the fragmented
European reaction to the bombing that surfaced the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We and the Americans see and accept the threat that Saddam
poses, not just to his neighbors, but to the international
community,'' the diplomat said. ``Unfortunately, not everyone else
agrees on what to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The British are not surprised by the Italian government's
reaction, given that its new prime minister is a former communist.
But they are pleasantly surprised by the German reaction. Speaking
privately, however, British diplomats express frustration over the
reaction of the French, whom they criticize for lack of support.
</P>
<P>
   The split between London and Paris over Iraq is notable given
the significance both governments attached to the St. Malo
Declaration when it was announced Dec. 4 at an Anglo-French summit.
It marked the first time the French and British had united to
sponsor a new European Union policy.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the declaration calls for Europeans to intervene
militarily in regional conflicts such as Bosnia when the Americans
cannot or will not. The pact is part of Europe's determination to
assume more responsibility for its own region, half a century after
America helped rebuild it after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But as the situation in Iraq illustrates, while Britain
reflexively sides with American military analysis, the French
continue their legendary independent streak.
</P>
<P>
   Some caution against overstating the rift between London and
Paris in particular, and the rest of Europe in general. Gywn Prins,
senior research fellow at The Royal Institute of International
Affairs, said there is disagreement with the French over tactics,
and perhaps timing, but that talk of a serious rift between the
Anglo-American axis and Paris and the rest of the western allies is
greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday someone daubed the Cenotaph, the London monument
that honors Britain's war dead, with graffiti protesting the
bombing of Iraq. Alfred Downing, a 72-year-old World War II
veteran, paused as he walked by to decry the defacement as
disgraceful. He said he found it repulsive that China and Russia
were ``sanctimoniously'' denouncing the Americans and British.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese and Russians stick up for dictatorships because
they would prefer to have dictatorships themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that the French agree with the Chinese and Russians
that the use of force was premature, Downing furrowed his brow and
said, ``Yes, well, the French would, now wouldn't they?''
</P>
</TEXT>
