<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIGID NOVEMBER FOR COLLEGE FOOTBALL RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   College football's Bowl Championship Series (BCS) may leave
everyone cold in regards to rankings, national titles and the
priorities of bowl officials. But it did one thing: The whole month
of November was one long BCS-inspired debate.
</P>
<P>
   That did not, however, translate into success at the TV box
office. The 1998 regular season closed without a single network
package improving on its 1997 ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In 26 regionalized telecasts this year, ABC earned a 4.7 Nielsen
average, which equates into about 4.6 million homes. CBS' package
of games featuring the Southeastern Conference and Big East did a
3.2, down from a 3.5 in 1997. NBC's six-game package of Notre Dame
home games earned a 2.9, down from a 3.1.
</P>
<P>
   Cable-wise, ESPN did a 2.2 for 38 telecats, down from a 2.4, and
ESPN2's 37 telecasts did a .8, equal with its numbers from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This is bad news in two respects: With the BCS bowls leaving
more people frustrated than sated, the chance exists that all bowl
Nielsens will decline this holiday season. And these aren't the
kind of numbers which inspire, say, a Rupert Murdoch to make a
pre-emptive bid to launch a real 16- or 8-team playoff.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last year's Rose Bowl match between Washington
State and Michigan had a strong viewer profile, with WSU new to the
game and Michigan ranked No. 1. The Nielsen rating was 17.6, which
was good, but lower than the Nielsens in two other years, 1996
(19.2) when USC met Cinderfella (Northwestern) and 1995 when No. 2
ranked Penn State met Oregon (18.2).
</P>
<P>
   Also last year, the Jan. 2 Orange Bowl match between another
unbeaten team, Nebraska, and Tennessee earned a modest 13.3, much
lower than the Nielsen the Orange earned in 1995 (Nebraska-Miami,
18.9) and 1994 (Florida State-Nebraska, 17.8).
</P>
<P>
   There's little precedent that any bowl game, title or not,
outside the usual Dec. 31-Jan. 2 parameters can attract an
audience. ABC pushed the 1997 Sugar Bowl between Florida and
Florida State back to Jan. 2 so it would be unopposed in prime
time, but it did a 17.9. That's not bad, but it's not the kind of
number which inspires network wallets to open.
</P>
<P>
   If the general public looks at Florida State-Tennessee as just a
southern intrasectional, or worse, then the BCS may have to analyze
its basic premise. That might not be a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if the BCS did not exist and bowl bids and decisions
had been made the old-fashioned way, UCLA and Wisconsin would still
meet in the Rose Bowl, and Tennessee-Florida State would butt
heads, but in the Sugar Bowl, not the Fiesta Bowl. And since the
Big East had no automatic berth to any of the four major Jan. 1
bowls, Kansas State likely would have gotten a better bowl.
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) New, not improved
</P>
<P>
   The post-Nasty era at KXTA (1150 AM) is a few weeks old, and I
regret to report that the worst fears of L.A sports talk fans are
already being realized.
</P>
<P>
   Since Joe McDonnell was escorted out, there has been a lack of
anything along the lines of sports news or cogent,
</P>
<P>
   interesting talk on the station. And the vibe one gets is that
management likes it this way.
</P>
<P>
   The most prevalent topics we're heard beyond full endorsement of
the Kevin Brown deal this is the Dodgers' flagship, after all have
a Tony Robbins-like seminar next month, featuring name athletes and
coaches, that the station is directly involved; where Dean Denholm,
half of the duo replacing Big Joe, should live (I suggest Fresno);
and more testimonials to the greatness of Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mason, half of the morning team, has already departed for
New York, where he will host his own general talk show. It has yet
to be decided where John Ireland fits now, especially with
management reportedly considering a general talk show, sprinkled
with sports, for the morning slot. Ben Maller and Dave Smith have
been doing fill-in work where needed.
</P>
<P>
   Denholm and Newy Scruggs did a ``Help a Hoopa'' skit last week
that raised a small smile, but it was way too long, and I can't
imagine sports fans wanting a steady diet of it. One caller this
week got on the air and asked ``Hey, are you guys ever going to
talk about sports?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!And now the news: &UR; !off! &LR;  Not all of the college football
news was bad. The UCLA-Miami game on ESPN posted a season-high 4.5
rating for the cable net ... Check out the CBS SportsLine web site,
where the Internet company is conducting a virtual playoff for
college football based on a 16-team field ... Larry Kahn's bowl
radio package includes the Las Vegas Bowl Saturday on KLSX-FM, plus
the Gator Bowl ... Fox Sports West 2 will air the NAIA title game
between Azusa Pacific and Oliviet Nazarene Saturday at 10 a.m. ...
CBS is thumping its chest over its rapidly increasing Nielsen prime
time demographics in the lusty men 18-49 category, all due, the
network says, to the testosterone boost of the NFL package ...
ESPN's numbers for Sunday Night football are at 7.9, a six-percent
bump over the comparable cable rating in 1997. The Fish-Jet game
did a 10.8, a season high and the best since a 49ers game in
Decemver, 1995. ... CBS has benched George Seifert
</P>
<P>
   from the ``NFL Today'' pregame show for the balance of the
regular season, and industry whispers say there could be a major
overhaul next season. Look for more Mike Lombardi, the switching of
Craig Jamesfrom the college studio to the NFL studio, a goodbye to
Seifert and the reassignment of Brent Jones and/or Marcus Allento
games ...
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hill's ``Sports Central'' show on KCBS is earning better
Nielsens than the pregame show despite hitting the air an hour
earlier ... Hey NBA! Check this out. ESPN's college basketball
package, 34 games into the season, is averaging a 1.3, a 24 percent
increase over last year's Nielsens at the same time. ESPN2's
package is up 43 percent ...
</P>
<P>
   For those who still care about the NBA, Showtime airs an
all-star charity game Saturday at 6 p.m. from Atlantic City. You'd
think player advisors would suggest that putting a game on a
premium movie channel isn't exactly reaching out to the common fan
... ESPN Saturday (9 a.m.) carries the Tennessee-South Florida
college basketball game. Who cares, you say? Ex-49er coach Seth
Greenberg is South Florida's coach ... Consider this advice or an
alert: KCTD (1540 am) is carrying Tim McCarver's talk show on
Saturdays ... Showtime airs the premiere of Bud Greenspan's latest
Olympic documentary Sunday at 8 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
