<HEADER>
A7777 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-2NDTAK     12-18 0211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: news cycles. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a New York Republican who came out for
impeachment this week, even sadly suggested that the reason Clinton
had lied under oath, and thus taken the step towards impeachment,
was because like Nixon he came to hate his political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blinded by his contempt for people he thought were out to get
him,'' Boehlert said, ``the president forgot his larger obligations
to his office, to the Constitution and to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Friday the House prepared to impeach another president.
But anyone who thought this would end the cycle of political
destruction that began with Watergate had only to look at Rep.
Robert Livingston, the incoming speaker. On the eve of the
impeachment debate, he had to acknowledge to Republicans that ``on
occasion I strayed from my marriage,'' because of a story being
prepared by Hustler magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the fear of what has now been unleashed that led
to the day's one fleeting, early moment of bipartisanship. When
Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House Minority leader, thundered the
politics of ``slash and burn must end,'' he received a standing
ovation from both sides of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Then the attacks began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
