<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLUMBS DEMOCRATIC SENATORS FOR ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Though the White House has portrayed him as mostly
disengaged from the business of impeachment, President Clinton has
been calling various Senate Democrats to gauge their attitude on
the subject, while complaining bitterly that ``right-wing''
Republicans are out to get him.
</P>
<P>
   While bombs were falling on Iraq Wednesday and Thursday, Clinton
telephoned several Democratic senators, most of them liberal and
considered friendly to the White House, seeking advice and sounding
them out about impeachment, several Democratic Senate aides and
others close to the administration said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials acknowledge they have turned their focus
to the Senate, considering the prospect that Clinton will be
impeached by the House a foregone conclusion. But those officials
have been circumspect when asked about Clinton's direct efforts to
avoid becoming only the second president in 130 years to face an
impeachment trial by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Hillary Rodham Clinton broke her recent silence on
impeachment as she walked to the White House South Lawn, where she
tied a red ribbon to a Ford Explorer to discourage drunk driving
during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   With the Capitol Dome, site of the impeachment debate, visible
behind her, Mrs. Clinton said: ``I think the vast majority of
Americans share my approval and pride in the job that the
president's been doing for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``We ought to end divisiveness because we can do so
much more together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reportedly is seeking to recruit two former Senate
stalwarts _ Robert Dole, a Republican and his 1996 presidential
opponent, and George Mitchell, the Maine Democrat who helped
Clinton broker the Northern Island peace agreement _ to offer
advice on dealing with the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Though stopping short of direct lobbying, a Democratic operative
close to the White House said, Clinton is beginning to talk to
senators with whom ``the president has a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Senate aides described the president as ``angry'' about the
House impeachment vote. ``He's calling it a political process,''
one aide said about those conversations. He was ``complaining about
the right wing trying to railroad him,'' said another aide.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's aides publicly deny it, those Democratic
aides and others with ties to the adminstration say officials are
nervous about public opinion polls showing a high percentage of
Americans favoring Clinton's resignation to avoid a lengthy
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at one poll, one question and hang your hat on
it,'' said Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House special
counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, asked Friday in an interview with
American Urban Radio Networks whether Clinton would consider
resigning to avoid a prolonged Senate trial, said: ``He's certainly
not preparing to resign or even to consider resigning. People can
forget about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House Friday blamed Republicans for starting the talk
about resignation, accusing the GOP of being so determined to oust
Clinton they would do almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you're seeing, especially in the last few days,
is a shift in what has been a very cynical, political strategy by
the Republican leadership in the House from impeachment to a
building drumbeat to try to force the president to leave office,''
said White House press secretary Joseph Lockhart. He said Clinton
would ``absolutely not'' consider resigning, even if impeached.
</P>
<P>
   But two Democrats _ Representatives William Lipinski of Ilinois
and Louise Slaughter of New York _ who both oppose impeachment said
it should not be out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that resigning is something that he should consider
because his effectiveness would be reduced,'' Slaughter said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts
Democrat, said in an interview, ``If the president resigned when
this whole matter broke, it would be one thing. But at this point,
if he were to give in to the right wing of the Republican Party
that would set a very dangerous precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   During the House debate Friday, Democratic Representative Sheila
Jackson Lee of Texas said emphatically: ``Mr. President, if you can
hear me, do not resign. This is not a parliamentary form of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the impeachment battle in the Senate could shape up much
as it has in the House, falling along bitter partisan lines, Senate
Minority Leader Thomas Daschle has let word circulate on Capitol
Hill that he's interested in working on a bipartisan compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But the conventional wisdom in the Senate is that such a middle
ground may be difficult to find, Democratic aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers say the Senate is duty-bound to hold a trial, as
required in the Constitution. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
says it may be hard not to hold a trial if the House votes for one
or more articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat, has said
the Senate has ``no choice'' other than to start a trial, but he
has suggested that the articles could be dimissed shortly
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   One senator who has not been contacted by Clinton is Robert
Bryd, a Democrat from West Virgina, who is considred the most
learned and most impassioned defender of prerogatives in the
Senate. Months ago, while the House was debating the release of the
independent counsel's impeachment referral, Byrd warned Clinton:
``Don't tamper with the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Said one Senate Democratic aide: ``If you look at it on paper,
then you say to yourself, `no, it's impossible to get the 67 votes
necessary to convict'' the president in the Senate and remove him
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a concern among people here that if and when the
House votes that things could spin out of control in the Senate.
The president has never had a lot of strong allies on the Hill,''
the aide said.
</P>
</TEXT>
