<SLUG> BC-BFN-TAYLOR-SURRENDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWRENCE TAYLOR TURNS HIMSELF IN ON DRUG CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J., S.C.)  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawrence Taylor, the former Giants linebacker, turned himself in
to the police in Teaneck, N.J., on Thursday to face charges of drug
possession and possession of drug paraphernalia, authorities said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor surrendered at police headquarters without incident and
was released on his own recognizance after posting a $2,500 bond,
said Capt. Paul Tiernan of the Teaneck Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Taylor, 39, stem from an incident on Sept.
29 when the Teaneck police, acting on a tip, searched a room rented
in Taylor's name at the Glenpointe Marriott Hotel and discovered
crack cocaine and drug paraphernalia, Tiernan said. Taylor was not
in the room at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergen County Prosecutor's office will now consider whether
to indict Taylor on the charges, said James Addis, an assistant
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Taylor checked into a drug rehabilitation clinic, a
week after he was arrested in St. Petersburg, Fla., on charges of
buying crack cocaine. At the time of that arrest, he was waiting to
be sentenced on a tax-evasion conviction that arose from his
failure to pay taxes on $48,000 in income from a defunct restaurant
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Taylor was arrested in Myrtle Beach, S.C., on
charges that he had tried to buy $100 of fake crack cocaine from an
undercover police officer. His record in that case was wiped clean
after he undertook 60 hours of community service and submitted to
drug counseling and random drug testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
