<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SADDAM-SMOKEOUT-ECONO     12-18 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SADDAM-SMOKEOUT-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAWING A LINE IN THE QUICKSAND  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 19 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``i''
international news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Iraq is now under western bombardment. On Dec. 16, a month
after a previous raid was aborted at the last minute, Bill Clinton,
with Britain's Tony Blair in faithful tow, decided to punish Iraq
with missiles and bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The prompt for the current attack is a report by Richard Butler,
the chief of the U.N. inspection team (UNSCOM), that showed Saddam
Hussein had not complied with his pledge on Nov. 14 to allow UNSCOM
full access to all suspect sites.
</P>
<P>
   The response, in the Middle East and beyond, and the
consequences within Iraq itself, can only be guessed at.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been more straightforward if the attack had taken
place in November, when Hussein's behavior, in ending all
cooperation with UNSCOM's inspectors, was unequivocally condemned.
Few voices, at that time, were raised in the Iraqi dictator's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the issues are cloudier, and feelings more
ambivalent: Russia, China and France, the three other permanent
members of the Security Council, are strongly against the attack;
the Arab world's first response was to express sorrow, cynicism and
outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Butler was reporting on Iraqi compliance in the four weeks since
Iraq averted air strikes by promising to cooperate fully with
UNSCOM's demands. The report said the promise had been broken: Iraq
was helpful in many routine ways but unhelpful in other ways and
those are the ways that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's main transgression was to refuse to allow the inspectors,
who were testing Iraqi compliance with a series of unannounced
visits to sensitive sites, access to the ruling Baath Party's
offices unless they first said what they were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq had supposedly been hoping that Butler's report would open
the way for a comprehensive review by the Security Council of the
whole policy of sanctions and disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   But it plainly has things _ not necessarily of the
weapons-making kind _ that it would like to conceal from inspectors
it has come to regard as spies of America and/or Israel.
</P>
<P>
   From a military viewpoint, the American attack will test the
claim of military planners that missiles have become ``smarter''
and more accurate since the 1991 Gulf war: at least half the
explosives now being dropped on Iraq are supposed to be
precision-guided, compared with about 10 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise missiles have been fitted with satellite-based guidance
systems making it possible to readjust their course in mid-flight
and, in theory, to achieve pinpoint accuracy. But even the planners
agree that they cannot avoid civilian casualties _ or hope, by air
power alone, to destroy Iraq's capacity to make lethal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The political consequences are even more twisted. The response
of cynics, who include many Arabs, is to question the timing. The
House of Representatives' decision to delay Clinton's impeachment
debate, which had been due to start on Dec. 17, will add force to
the widely held view that attacking Iraq was a classic diversionary
tactic.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Butler's report surely cannot have been under
Clinton's control. But Clinton's explanation that the bombing had
to start immediately because it would have been ``profoundly
offensive'' to strike Iraq during the holy month of Ramadan, which
begins on Dec. 20, is unlikely to win him Muslim friends.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech explaining why the action had to be taken, Clinton
said that ``we will pursue a long-term strategy to contain
Iraq...and work toward the day when Iraq has a government worthy of
its people.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that looks like two aims. America's public aim, until now,
has been to contain Hussein _ with sanctions, inspections and arms
control. But a campaign of sustained bombing could move matters to
a different plane. Forget inspection and arms control, the aim then
would be to rid Iraq of its dictator and his entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Few, including few Iraqis, would object to that _ if it could be
done, and done without causing chaos. But could it?
</P>
<P>
   The great fear among Iraq's neighbors is that America may be
militarily successful in destroying much of Iraq, but that the
eventual political success will still be Saddam's. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 700-word article, it must be purchased
from New York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in
New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
