<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON19-1ST     12-18 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON19-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO ADDRESS NATION AFTER IMPEACHMENT VOTE
 &HT;    Eds: Retops with speech plans by Clintons.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton plans to address the nation
Saturday after a scheduled series of House votes targeting his
presidency, the White House said late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And jumping into the political fray after months of absence,
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton plans to journey to Capitol Hill
early Saturday to speak to House Democrats before members take up
four articles of impeachment against her husband.
</P>
<P>
   The president also planned to meet at the White House with House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and other members of the
House Democratic leadership immediately after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made no public remarks since Thursday morning about
impeachment, now widely seen as unavoidable. But White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart suggested that Clinton would want Americans
to know his side of the story as they absorbed news reports about
Saturday's scheduled vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect that at some point you will probably see him,'' said
Lockhart, who declined to be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials declined to characterize the purpose or
the substance of Mrs. Clinton's intended remarks Saturday. But on
Friday, she urged the country to embrace reconciliation during a
season celebrated by Christians, Jews and Moslems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in our country ought to practice reconciliation and we
ought to bring our country together and we ought to end
divisiveness because we can do so much more together,'' Mrs.
Clinton told reporters after leaving a holiday awareness event
sponsored by Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that we as a nation would turn our attention to
what we could do together, what we could do positively and how we
could build each other up,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   While the first lady spoke of national healing, Lockhart accused
Clinton's foes of ''partisanship and cynicism'' in an effort to
hound the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said House Republicans have played a duplicitous game.
He noted that after first insisting that impeachment was little
more than a green light for a more comprehensive and meaningful
Senate inquiry, Republicans have begun making the case that Clinton
should resign if impeached on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''A conscious effort was made to, in effect, dumb down
impeachment ... and say that this process wasn't important, that
the real action was someplace else, and then, having gone through
it, turn 180 degrees in the other direction and say, 'It's so
important, it's so important to this country and it's so damaging
that the president should resign,'' Lockhart said at a White House
briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is a political strategy at work here that is
cynical and is not in the best interests of the American public,''
Lockhart said. ''You don't make something right by compounding it
with another wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Since House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois
and House Republican Whip Tom DeLay of Texas suggested in Sunday
talk show appearances that Clinton resign, many other Republicans
have joined in. Even a scattering of Democrats have agreed that
Clinton should resign, or consider doing so, in order to save the
nation the trauma of a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton himself said this week, ``I have no intention of
resigning. It's never crossed my mind.'' And several people close
to the president told reporters Friday that he would never leave
office voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can forget about that,'' said Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As 13 hours of bitterly partisan impeachment debate unfolded
Friday on Capitol Hill, Clinton stayed out of sight, hunkered down
at the White House working on subjects ranging from the continuing
U.S. air strikes in Iraq to the battle against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   He did ``very little'' to help the battle against impeachment,
Lockhart said, other than spend an hour meeting with Rep.
Christopher Shays of Connecticut, an undecided Republican, in the
presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Shays said later he knew no details of the
conversation and that Shays had no plans to announce his decision
until the vote. Lockhart also declined comment about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Gore conducted a series of radio interviews arguing against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has admitted wrongdoing in engaging in an intimate
relationship with Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and then
later misleading prosecutors and the nation about the nature of
that relationship.
</P>
<P>
   He has maintained, however, that his conduct does not rise to
the level of an impeachable offense. Instead, Clinton has suggested
that the House vote to censure him in a stern rebuke that would
leave a permanent record of Congressional condemnation of his
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
