<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DWINDLING-JEWS-UKRAINE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKRAINIAN JEWS: SOON, NO MORE FIDDLERS ON THE ROOF  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Religion Editors)   (This interesting 500-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 19 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general/religion news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV _ In the shabby turn-of-the-century synagogue in Kiev's
Shchekavitska Street, a service is in rumbustious progress. Little
boys somersault on the pews and old men, leather phylacteries
strapped to their foreheads and fringed shawls over their
shoulders, debate vociferously as prayers are read from a
velvet-wrapped Torah scroll.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where KGB men once stood outside the few working
synagogues on Sabbath mornings, this scene should lift hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is poignant: every year, about one in ten of Ukraine's
300,000 Jews leaves to go to Israel, Germany or America. At the
current rate of emigration, in a decade's time Kiev's synagogues
will be empty.
</P>
<P>
   Ukrainian Jewry dates back to the ancient Greek colonies of the
Black Sea coast, predating the rise of the Slav principality out of
which ancient Rus grew.
</P>
<P>
   And Ukrainian Jewry later produced a host of famous names, from
Golda Meir and Leon Trotsky to the writers Isaac Babel and Sholem
Aleichem, whose bittersweet stories inspired ``Fiddler on the
Roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, that grand tradition is coming to an end. Since the late
1980s, when Soviet Jews started to get exit visas in large numbers,
Ukraine's Jewish population has fallen by half, reckons Leonid
Finberg, head of Kiev's Institute of Jewish Studies.
</P>
<P>
   And most of the emigrants are young, including all Finberg's
best researchers, while those who stay behind are dying off fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every child born of a Jewish mother,'' he says, ``there
are nine deaths. If the over-50s make up 25 percent of the general
population, in the Jewish community it's over 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The more people leave, the less likely it is that the remainder
will stay: ``Most of us now have close relations abroad. So
emigration isn't seen as such a tragedy as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiefly to blame for the exodus is Ukraine's dreadful economy,
which has shrunk every year since independence. Another cause is a
lack of help for those who want to rebuild Judaism at home.
</P>
<P>
   None of the five big foreign-financed Jewish businesses working
in Ukraine specifically encourages people to stay, while the
country's 16 newly opened Jewish schools teach Hebrew, to prepare
for life in Israel, rather than Yiddish, the historic
Jewish-Ukrainian tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Ukraine's two dozen or so rabbis are American Hasidim:
none admits regret that the congregations, choirs and youth groups,
painstakingly rebuilt after years of oppression, are being lost to
emigration.
</P>
<P>
   As Yaakov Bleich, an Orthodox rabbi from Brooklyn, puts it:
``Our goal is neither to rebuild the community, nor to get them to
leave. It's to educate them, to give them as much Jewish life as
possible while they're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiev's Reform rabbi, David Wilfond, is as unsentimental. His job
is not, he says, ``to keep one last fiddler on the roof while the
house burns.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
