<SLUG> BC-MA-WRONG-SPERM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE PROBES INSEMINATION MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State public health officials Friday launched an
investigation of a Stoneham fertility center's mistake in using the
wrong sperm for a patient undergoing an artificial insemination
procedure earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   It also appears Boston Regional Medical Center did not report
the incident within the time required by state regulation, seven
days by letter or 24 hours by phone, said Nancy Ridley, assistant
public health commissioner in charge of the bureau of health
quality management.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would probably get cited for that'' as a deficiency in
reporting, she said, adding that she does not yet know what, if
any, other citations might be issued.
</P>
<P>
   The center formally notified the state Department of Public
Health Friday, after media reports of the incident first surfaced,
leading to the opening of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the center said the patient was immediately told
she did not receive her husband's sperm and was given the option
``to take a contraceptive medication after the procedure,'' which
she did. ``The hospital regrets the error and has apologized to the
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The error occurred in the Stoneham hospital's outpatient Center
for Reproductive Medicine, located in a medical office building,
according to hospital spokeswoman Christine Hawrylak. A nurse
involved in the incident, which occurred the first week of
December, was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Hawrylak said the hospital didn't report the mistake to the
state sooner ``because after consulting with our legal counsel, it
was concluded that this incident did not meet the regulatory
description of `other serious incidents. . .which seriously affect
the healthy and safety of. . .patients.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we run an excellent program and we welcome the visit
of the Department of Public Health to the center,'' as part of its
investigation, Hawrylak said.
</P>
<P>
   The patient was undergoing what's called intrauterine
insemination. The center does nearly 400 such procedures a year.
</P>
<P>
   No special regulations govern fertility centers here or
nationwide, although the US Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention have proposed a ``model certification program'' for
embryo laboratories and is seeking public comment on it through
January 5. Legislation has also been filed in Massachusetts to
establish specific state standards, without success.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society for Reproductive Medicine does have
voluntary standards for embryo laboratories, however.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that the wrong sperm has been
injected during infertility treatments at facilities around the
country and the world. From Utah to Florida, New York to the
Netherlands, such mistakes have led to the wrong race child being
born to a couple in some cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
