<HEADER>
A7830 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH19-COX     12-18 1489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate sways few House members as vote forges ahead
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For only the second time in America's 222-year
history, the House is poised today to vote articles of impeachment
against President Clinton. Clinton plans an address to the nation
from the Rose Garden following the momentous vote.
</P>
<P>
   Today's scheduled vote follows hours of impassioned debate on
the House floor Friday during which Republicans argued the
president had shattered the rule of law and Democrats pleaded for
the lesser sanction of censure.
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flared throughout the long day as members brandished
copies of the Constitution and debated the significance of lying
under oath, while a half a world away U.S. and allied forces
continued to bomb Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The four counts of impeachment against Clinton all stem from his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and his
efforts to conceal the relationship before the courts, the Congress
and the public.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has insisted throughout the crisis that he sinned
but did not break the law, appeared resigned to today's vote. He
met briefly Friday with one Republican moderate, who then slipped
out a side entrance to avoid the media, but Clinton devoted nearly
all the day to monitoring the Iraqi conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Clinton maintained a stoic appearance of
doing the nation's business even as he was poised to enter history
as only the second president impeached since President Andrew
Johnson in 1868. The Senate failed to convict Johnson by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   As she has so many times during the couples' 23-year marriage,
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton gave the Clinton's only public
comment about her husband's fate. Speaking to reporters after a
meeting with Mothers Against Drunk Driving, she said ``the vast
majority of Americans share my approval and pride in the job that
the president's been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to end divisiveness because we can do so much more
together,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders predicted that at least two of the four
articles of impeachment against Clinton will prevail. Still they
left nothing to chance. In an effort to steel the resolve among
wavering members to impeach on all four counts, Republican members
shepherded some members over to the locked room where the evidence
against Clinton is kept to show them the more salacious materials
first hand.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the materials shown to Republicans included
unsubstantiated claims that the president made unwanted sexual
advances toward other women while he was in Arkansas, dating back
to the 1970s when he was state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   With the only doubt now being which articles of impeachment will
pass, the debate about what should happen next developed Friday
with gathering force.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans stepped up their demands that Clinton resign. Two
Democrats, Reps. Louise Slaughter (D-N.Y.) and Bill Lipinski
(D-Ill.), also said Clinton should consider resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to resign,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.).
``That's what's right for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart repeated Friday that Clinton has
no intention of resigning, saying the president was in a ``good
mood'' and focused on ``the important work he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd welcome a solution that's bipartisan and that puts this
matter behind us, that is short of impeachment,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Clinton's studied indifference to the historic
House debate and Mrs. Clinton's plea for reconciliation, the House
on Friday engaged in heated, sometimes angry, partisan debate over
Clinton's conduct, the meaning of the Constitution how best to
bring the Clinton-Lewinsky saga to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The historic debate was carefully scripted by both parties.
Mindful that the networks planned early coverage before deciding
whether to resume regular programing, both sides loaded their
heaviest hitting speakers for the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the gavel was brought down late Friday night, more
than 200 members, from the well-known to the lesser known, had
spoken their mind about Clinton's fate. Some members thundered.
Others spoke barely above a whisper. A few even appeared to be on
the verge of tears.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the public filled the public galleries above the
House floor, at times demonstrating more interest in the
proceedings than the members themselves. Throughout the day, the
House floor was no more than half full.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) tried to set
the tone for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matter before the House is a question of lying under
oath,'' Hyde said. ``This is a public act, not a private act. This
is called perjury. The matter before the House is a question of the
willful, premeditated, deliberate corruption of the nation's system
of justice. Perjury and obstruction of justice cannot be reconciled
with the office of the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two impeachment articles charge Clinton with lying
under oath before the grand jury and lying in his deposition in
Paula Jones's civil harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Article three charges Clinton with obstructing justice by
attempting to influence the testimony of Lewinsky in the Jones case
and his personal secretary, Betty Currie. Article four charges
Clinton with lying to Congress in answers he submitted to the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, Democrats took up Clinton's defense and hammered
away at the Republican argument that Clinton's conduct, however
shameful, did not rise to the level of ``high crimes and
misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While the president's conduct was reprehensible, it did not
threaten the nation,'' said Rep. Dick Boucher (D-Va.). ``It did not
undermine the constitutional form and principles of our government.
It did not disable the proper functioning of the constitutional
duties of the presidential office.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats angrily accused Republicans of seeking to force
Clinton's impeachment by denying a vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only conclude that you don't want our members to have
this choice,'' said minority leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.). ``I can
only conclude that this may be about winning a vote, not about
high-minded ideals.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats went so far as to accuse Republicans of seeking
to undermine the commander in chief while the country was at war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting this proceeding today may wind up costing American
lives,'' charged Rep. Martin Frost (D-Texas). ``The majority may
well have blood on its hands.''
</P>
<P>
   With history looking over their shoulder, members from both
parties quoted freely from the canons of American democracy:
Lincoln, Hamilton, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   They also quoted Lewinsky and Clinton. Rep. Bill McCollom
(R-Fla.) quoted Clinton's question to Curry after his Jones'
deposition, ``I was never alone with her, right?'' Clinton told
Currie. Rep. Bill Delahunt (D-Mass.) followed later with Lewinsky's
unsolicited remark to the grand jury, ``No one asked me to lie and
no one offered me a job for my silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Some quoted the Constitution and the Magna Carta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should look not simply to ourselves but to the past and to
the future,'' said Hyde. ``Let's look back to Bunker Hill, Concord,
Lexington, let's look across the river to Arlington Cemetery, where
American heroes who gave their lives for the sake of the rule of
law lie buried.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards (D-Texas) countered that ``the hindsight of
history will be harsh on this Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the name of the rule of law, this process ignored the
fundamental principles of due process and fairness that form the
foundation of that rule of law,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Some members dispensed with the legal and constitutional
intricacies altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot trust him again,'' said Rep. Sam Johnson (R-Texas), a
former prisoner of war, of Clinton. ``If it is in his interest not
to tell the truth, he will not tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   There were even veiled references to the Capitol's newest
scandal _ disclosures Thursday that House speaker-elect Bob
Livingston (R-La.) had sexual affairs during his 33-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica Lewinsky is not Watergate,'' said Rep. Rosa DeLauro
(D-Conn.). ``Let he who has no sin in this chamber cast the first
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most poignant remarks came from the 40 members of
Congress retiring this year and for whom today's vote will be their
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me about the venom and the hatred, and the
camaraderie that is nonexistent in this House any more,'' said Rep.
Bill Hefner (D-N.C.). ``Hate is a cancer that eats at us. It shows
in our face, it shows in our walk. And it's something you can't
treat with chemotherapy, you can't treat it with any drugs. You
have to treat it with compassion and love.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
