<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FDX AND ITS PILOTS REACH TENTATIVE CONTRACT DEAL
</P>
<P>
   FDX, the parent of Federal Express, said company negotiators had
reached a tentative five-year labor settlement with its pilots
union. The agreement, reached late Thursday, would give the pilots
a 17 percent raise over the length of the contract. It is to be
presented to the union rank and file for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   If ratified, the contract would be the first for the 3,300
Federal Express pilots. Word of the pact lifted FDX shares 8.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA SAYS NO TO TROUBLED BANK
</P>
<P>
   The president of Toyota Motor said the automaker would not give
financial help to an allied company, Sakura Bank, which like other
Japanese banks has been deeply hurt by bad loans. Sakura had turned
to Toyota earlier this year, but investors had opposed the
commitment of money to a bailout.
</P>
<P>
   GM RAISING STAKE IN ISUZU TO 49 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   General Motors will pay $456 million to acquire 232.5 million
newly issued shares of Isuzu Motors, increasing its stake in the
Japanese company to 49 percent from the current 37.5 percent. The
two companies are also broadening their cooperation in commercial
vehicle production, with Isuzu assuming full responsibility for the
development of trucks for the entire GM group.
</P>
<P>
   FORD CUTS BRAZIL WORK FORCE
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it would lay off 2,800 workers in Brazil, 35 percent
of the automaker's total work force in the country, because of
Brazilian economic problems. Most of the layoffs will be at the Sao
Bernardo assembly plant near Sao Paulo in southern Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA CLARIFIES REPAYMENT TERMS
</P>
<P>
   Russia clarified the terms for its restructuring of 281 billion
rubles in defaulted Treasury debt. It said the plan was based on an
assumption that the bonds' yield at the time of the default was 50
percent, much lower than it actually was in many cases. As a
result, many investors will get a bigger payout than they would
have at the time of the default.
</P>
<P>
   TIME WARNER LOSES JURY VERDICT
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner said its Time Warner Entertainment partnership and
other parties had lost a $197 million jury verdict related to its
former interest in the Six Flags Over Georgia theme park. Time
Warner said it would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   SACCHARIN WARNING MAY BE LIFTED
</P>
<P>
   A government advisory group has voted to give a clean bill of
health to the artificial sweetener saccharin, classified since 1981
as a suspected cause of cancer. The executive committee of the
National Toxicology Program voted Wednesday to recommend that
saccharin be removed from the government's list of suspected
carcinogens.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-WASTE SITE STUDY ON TRACK
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department reported that it had so far found no
insurmountable obstacles to its plan to bury nuclear waste in the
desert near Las Vegas, and that it was on schedule to make a formal
recommendation to the president by 2001. But the department did
identify major gaps in its knowledge of the geology of the site,
Yucca Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   DEADLINE PUSHED BACK AT WTO
</P>
<P>
   The delicate process by which the World Trade Organization is
selecting a new director-general to replace Renato Ruggiero, whose
term will end next spring, took a small step forward.
Representatives of the 132 member countries of the global trade
arbiter, meeting at its Geneva headquarters, acknowledged that the
original timetable, which called for a mid-December selection, will
not be met. They set the end of January as the new goal.
</P>
<P>
   FOR NBA STARS, OTHER SHOE DROPS
</P>
<P>
   National Basketball Association players who were expecting Nike
to supplement their income during the lockout may have to start
searching their couch cushions and car ashtrays for loose change.
Many of the more than 100 players with deals to wear the swoosh
have discovered language in their contracts that gives Nike the
right to withhold payment because of a work stoppage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
