<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., BRITAIN POUND IRAQ FOR A THIRD DAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and Britain pounded Iraq for a
third day Friday as military forces continued a furious missile
bombardment of weapons sites and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The military operation, called Operation Desert Fox, continued
as the House opened debate on impeachment charges against President
Clinton. The third round also came despite a growing rift between
the United States and Russia over the attacks and increasing
protests in Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said publicly they could not say when the
bombings might end, although some reports quoted unnamed defense
officials as saying the attacks could be halted Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to report that the United States and British forces
are continuing to attack a wide range of military targets in order
to decrease Iraq's ability to threaten its neighbors,'' said
Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be satisfied by the results, although the
strikes are not yet complete. There have been no American or
British casualties,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Iraq dead or injured was not known. Baghdad
officials last provided an estimate of 25 dead and 75 wounded
following the first attack Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon reported nearly 300 sea-launched and air-launched
cruise missiles were fired during the first two waves of attacks
against Iraq, more than in the entire 1991 Persian Gulf War. The B1
bomber, the controversial replacement for the aging Vietnam era
B-52, also saw combat action for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made no comment about the military operation,
but British Prime Minister Tony Blair said in London that ``I
believe we are on course to achieve our military objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain launched their retaliatory attack
against Saddam Hussein after arms inspectors of the United Nations
Special Commission were denied access to records and facilities.
The allies accused Saddam of attempting to hide chemical and
biological weapons that he agreed to dispose of after the 1991
Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, Saddam called on Arabs to resist the agents of Satan,
as he called U.S. and British forces. ``By God, we will not
compromise,'' Saddam said via a taped televised address to Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   The monthlong Islamic holy month of Ramadan, which requires
Muslims to fast during the day, begins this weekend, but National
Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger said it ``is not an
automatic deadline'' for ending the military assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an operation that was planned by the military ...
without regard to dates,'' Berger said. ``It has a duration and a
particular target set and I don't think we're likely to alter that.
We will continue to proceed until we believe we have done what we
can with the targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
there were 75 targets in the first two attack waves and more than
200 strike and strike-support sorties flown by U.S. and British
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said initial damage assessments indicated a small number
of the targets had been destroyed. ``Not all have gone as
planned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Tom Wilson, the Pentagon's intelligence director, said
the targets have included 18 command and control centers, which
includes radio and television transmitters, 19 weapons security
facilities, 11 weapons production facilities, eight Republican
Guard facilities and five airfields. The lone economic target, he
said, was Iraqi's Basra oil refinery, which serves as a
distribution point for Saddam's illegal oil exports.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson also said there had been varying degrees of success. ``We
realize you can't destroy it all,'' Shelton said. ``You can't
destroy it, but you can bring it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Military forces also dropped two million leaflets in Southern
Iraq to warn regular army units based there to stay in their
barracks and they would not be attacked. The army units were warned
not to move south to threaten Kuwait or to threaten allied forces.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and British forces have attacked the Republican Guard, the
30,000-strong elite force that Saddam uses to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz maintained that the
allied forces attacked civilian targets such as warehouses, radio
and television facilities, and the oil refinery. ``The same liars,
the same criminals, are repeating their lies and crimes,'' Aziz
said, suggesting that Clinton and Blair were kowtowing to Zionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing now is not a military conflict. It's a
criminal aggression by the United States and Britain against Iraq,
the Arab nation, the Muslims and against the whole international
community,'' Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-American protests broke out in a half-dozen Arab capitals,
with many saying the attacks were motivated by the president's
problems with the impeachment vote in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia has insisted that U.S. aircraft not stage from
bases within its borders, the New York Times reported. The report
said more than half of the U.S. strike aircraft at ground bases in
the region have been kept out of the attack because of the Saudi
objections.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz did not rule out allowing inspectors to return to Iraq
after the attacks but only when economic sanctions, in place since
1991 after Baghdad invaded Kuwait, are lifted and only without
Richard Butler, the UNSCOM director whose critical report fueled
the decision to attack.
</P>
<P>
   The United States said the conditions were unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A really functional UNSCOM, a strong UNSCOM with
professionals, could go in after this, and Saddam Hussein can
comply and then we can go to the comprehensive review,'' said
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also sought to downplay the growing rift between the
United States and Russia. There were conflicting reports that
Russia placed its military on alert status but Pentagon officials
said that was unconfirmed. Russia also recalled its ambassadors to
the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that clearly the Russians disagree with us about the
use of force in Iraq. They, however, have no good ideas about how
to solve the problem,'' Albright said during an appearance on
NBC-TV's ``Today Show.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton twice tried to call Russian leader Boris
Yeltsin and finally sent him a letter through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have developed a relationship with Russia that
can sustain controversy, differences and difficulties, however
sharp they may become,'' said Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary
of state and former Russian ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
