<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-INFIDELITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMORS FOLLOW LIVINGSTON ADMISSION OF INFIDELITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the impeachment debate unfolded Friday with
all the solemnity associated with an effort to remove the president
from office, discussions off the House floor focused on ferocious
rumors that there would be a full-scale outing of Republicans who
had broken their marriage vows.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Speaker-elect Robert L. Livingston's confession
that he had been unfaithful to his wife in the past, House members
debated impeachment under rules that specifically forbade them from
comparing President Clinton's sexual indiscretions to any sitting
member's ``personal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the speaker's lobby, a plush sideroom where members talk
to the press, Livingston's confession was never far from the minds
of House members who were swept up in the rumor and inuendo.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, support for the speaker-elect among some
Republicans began to waver, according to the Associated Press,
which quoted Representative Spencer Bachus of Alabama saying
Livingston's status should be reexamined.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't criticize the president's behavior as being
unacceptable and then ... just ignore this and brush it aside,''
Bachus was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Republicans, however, appeared to stand solidly
behind Livingston. And in Livingston's congressional district in
Louisiana, there are no signs that he is in any political trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the speaker-elect's infidelities became fodder for
LWWL radio's ``The Andre Show,'' broadcast live Friday from
Livingston's hometown of Metairie, La., callers rallied to his
defense and railed instead at Clinton and the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If every congressman who had an affair turned to dust, then
Washington would look like a desert,'' said Tommy from Kenner. ``On
personal matters, the media should lose freedom of the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the partisan division in Washington, everyone was agreed on
one point: what is happening tarnishes the reputation of the House
and diminishes the grandeur of its proceedings, and marks an
unprecedented period of scandal and incivility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is greatly disturbing,'' said Representative Tim Roemer,
a Colorado Democrat. ``It degrades the institution ... and
seriously erodes people's respect for this hallowed insitution. I
hope we can stop going into members' closets and throwing their
skeletons into the House.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar has been lowered, lawmakers fear, not just for
constitutional rules of impeachment, but for what is considered
political fair play.
</P>
<P>
   Congresswoman Mary Bono, a California Republican who said she is
being hounded by reporters snooping for dirt on her, called the
state of affairs ``a festival of cannibals.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats also agreed on another point: the
invasion of personal life for political purposes is inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a completely private matter,'' commented
Representative Patrick Kennedy, a Rhode Island Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, agreed.
``Many members have said that this issue isn't about sex, but a lot
of the push from the outside has been from people who think this is
exactly about sex,'' he said. The Livingston confession
``diminishes the moral superiority and indignation factor
significantly, and it reinforces the perception that there is an
ulterior motive here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut Represenative Nancy Johnson, like many
Republicans, said Livingston's admission of an indiscretion had no
bearing on his ability to lead the House _ or on the impeachment
debate. ``This is not about sex,'' said Johnson. ``It's about
perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans also pointed to the Livingston confession as
evidence of a ``scorched earth policy '' by the White House
designed to discredit Republicans _ and highlight a double standard
_ by revealing their sexual indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the president's personal defenders are engaged
in a pattern of intimidation and blackmail,'' said California
Representative Dana Rohrabacher, blaming all recent revelations of
Republican sexual infidelities on a ``ruthless'' White House.
</P>
<P>
   Rohrbacher did not say whether Republicans had evidence for such
a policy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, press reports have forced Republican
Representatives Helen Chenoweth of Idaho, Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, and Dan Burton of Indiana to
admit to sexual affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
