<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981218.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-ART20-2NDTAKE     12-18 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-ART20-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: we want.''
</P>
<P>
   The black difference
</P>
<P>
   One thing that Scarlett was not was black. And African-American
culture in Atlanta doesn't seem to suffer as badly under the
North-is-better myth that haunts white artists. ``Even during
segregation, Atlanta was known as a black oasis,'' says Michael
Lomax, former chairman of the Fulton County Commission and founder
of Atlanta's National Black Arts Festival. ``With the opening up of
the city in the '70s, the resources that came from black political
power were made available to the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is one of the capitals of the hip-hop recording
industry. Atlanta is the home of 20-year-old Jomandi Productions,
which has a sheaf of Washington Post rave reviews from its many
visits to D.C. Atlanta is also where _ in the racially balanced
Alliance repertoire of Kenny Leon _ the whole notion of ``black''
and ``white'' culture as separate monoliths is being challenged,
without undermining the integrity of either tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Poetic justice, then, that CNN, the network that Atlanta
Journal-Constitution TV critic Phil Kloer says has been
tremendously influential in spreading an image of Atlanta as
sophisticated _ at least in the technological sense _ recently
produced a national feature on Leon.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, national media may even pay more attention to local
black culture than white, apparently finding it more socially
relevant. Southern black folk art does not lack for Northern
praise. The New York Times recently ran rave reviews of Ballethnic
Dance Company and Soweto Street Beat, two Atlanta-based
African-American dance troupes, and it would be hard to find small
local white groups so anointed.
</P>
<P>
   Thicker hides, more pride
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs that outside opinion is losing its distorted
magic as well as its sting. Atlanta arts leaders have developed
more confidence, thicker hides. High Museum director Ned Rifkin
doesn't sound rattled about Wolfe's mean depiction of ``Jonathan
Myrer,'' his alter ego in the book, who praises a piece of gay
pornography in the silliest kind of academic artsbabble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolfe's always had a jaded and simplistic eye for contemporary
art _ that's what he's attacking, not Atlanta,'' says Rifkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in Atlanta we do have Charlie Crokers (the art-hating Wolfe
hero who says Myrer's speech is hogwash) then, great: I love the
opportunity to win them over,'' Rifkin continues. ``Atlanta is an
important point on the American cultural compass, and attracting
criticism is the clearest signal that we're a player. Our ambitions
are mocked because they are envied.''
</P>
<P>
   Lomax: ``Atlanta should not try to imitate some city that it
isn't; if you've got lemons, make lemonade.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Shelton Stanfill, president of the Woodruff
Arts Center(Ga.), says that the desire for outside praise is
universal _ ``Even New Yorkers want a rave in `Le Monde' '' _ and
out-of-town reviews encourage locals to see their artists in a
fresh light and contribute more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is so young, culturally speaking _ like Denver and Los
Angeles and even Washington, it built its first major arts facility
in the 1960s or '70s,'' Stanfill observes. ``We're not like older
industrial cities where waves of immigrants brought accomplished
artists with them. No one's saying Atlanta is a New York or Chicago
or San Francisco. But I'll debate anybody that it's the
Southeastern cultural center and not Miami or New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   Lomax, now president of Dillard University in New Orleans,
echoes the idea that cities' cultural reputations take centuries,
not decades, to develop and may continue long after the reality has
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Atlanta doesn't have the cultural cachet of New Orleans,
it's because of long traditions in literature and music and
individual arts patronage on the Old World model. . . . The truth
is that New Orleans today is rather poor, and in the end it's
Atlanta's money that will win.'' Lomax laughs. ``Just look at the
incredible guest artists that Emory can bring in.'' (Playwright
Wole Soyinka and Archbishop Desmond Tutu, both Nobel laureates from
Africa, recently debated on the campus.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's reputation has changed enough,'' Lomax adds, ``so
that there shouldn't be any inferiority complex just because Tom
Wolfe sees a few yahoos there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rightful places
</P>
<P>
   The recognition of Atlanta, and the South generally, is bound to
grow because of a quiet recent shift, what might be called the
Dixie-ization of arts leadership. In the words of the Coca-Cola
Foundation's Adrian King: ``Many Southerners are taking their
rightful places, sprinkled into the national arts structures.''
Examples include William Ivey and William Ferris, confirmed this
year as chairmen of the National Endowment for the Arts and the
National Endowment for the Humanities, respectively. Robert Ivy,
formerly based in Mississippi, is already showing his knowledge of
the South as editor of Architectural Record. The Alabama
Shakespeare Festival _ which used to be a punch line to Northern
ears _ sent its artistic director, Kent Thompson, to be the
chairman of a Theatre Communications Group board in New York that
also includes Leon and Chris Coleman of Actor's Ex-
</P>
<P>
   press.
</P>
<P>
   And at Americans for the Arts, the Washington-based advocacy
group, ``Atlanta is the among the two or three most important
cities in terms of the number of delegates, their energy and
ideas,'' says president Robert Lynch, citing King and Stanfill;
Harriet Sanford, director of the Fulton County Arts Council; Fulton
County Commissioner Michael Hightower; and Coca-Cola Foundation
presiden Donald Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The group will have its annual convention in Atlanta in June,
partly, Sanford says, ``because people are so intrigued by the
city. Many haven't seen enough of it to understand it, but they
want to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bravura spirit, secret heart
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta's strongest suit is bravura spirit, Sanford warns
against its excess.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of boosterism when we were bidding for the
Olympics _ Atlanta may have have oversold itself, culturally,''
says the arts leader. ``We lost the Arts Festival of Atlanta partly
because it tried to make that costly jump to the national stage.
We're not teenagers anymore culturally, but we're not established
senior citizens either. We must be wary of getting too confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Bynum, the Atlanta actress and teacher who can assume
many accents, has enjoyed Wolfe's work since the 1960s, but ``I
don't expect to learn anymore about the real Atlanta from (``A Man
in Full'') than I learned about ancient Egypt from that Disney
show. Wolfe writes for what the market wants to read and Atlanta
understands that _ this is one big fat market town!''
</P>
<P>
   The key, Bynum says, is for Southerners to hold fast to their
appreciation of their culture without turning to a so-called higher
authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South is a subtle, secret, layered thing, and you approach
it through, say, a Eudora Welty book or a Tennessee Williams play
or an independent film like `Sling Blade.' That's how you get to
the true, deep, beating heart of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
