<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-ARTS20-2TAKES     12-18 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-ARTS20-2TAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 20
 &HT;    Despite its growing national prestige, the city is still seen by
some bicoastal elites as a gangly, unrefined stepchild
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Have you noticed that at art shows, Atlantans guzzle
champagne and ``cackle, shout, bawl and shriek'' at each other?
That they ignore the art because they secretly hate it? A lot of
American readers may think it's true. Says so in this book by the
famous Tom Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   Have you noticed that gangs of anti-Semitic rubes roam the
streets? No, of course not, and playwright Alfred Uhry claims that
in ``Parade'' _ his current Broadway musical about Leo Frank, a
Brooklyn-bred Jew lynched by a Marietta(Ga.) mob _ he makes it
clear that the Frank haters were themselves victims, not rednecks,
and the episode was a shocking aberration even for 1915. But will
everyone in the Lincoln Center audience hear that message?
</P>
<P>
   Have you noticed that Atlanta audiences are pushovers, ready to
stand up and cheer for just about anything that isn't terrible?
Well, it could appear that the Disney Co. thinks so. After its
musical world premiere, ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,''
set an Alliance Theatre record with 47,000 tickets, Disney execs
felt the show was still so un-Broadway-worthy that they fired five
of the show's creative chiefs and brought in a new director from
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: The bottom line about these three events is
that they enhance Atlanta's national presence and prestige. Even
Wolfe's ``A Man in Full,'' for all its devilish debunkery of the
city, ``is the ultimate compliment to Atlanta,'' in the words of
actor-director Tom Key. The three events are just a few instances
where Atlanta stepped out on the stage of America's arts and
letters in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as Wolfe's book shows, America sometimes recognizes
Atlanta down its nose, so to speak, with a touch of condescension.
In subtle ways Atlanta's taste still is second-guessed by the
bicoastal elite: producers, writers, editors, publishers who live
in New York and Los Angeles, whose only direct experience with the
city is, say, an annoying flight connection at Hartsfield
International Airport(Ga.). As recently as 1996, New York Times
critic at large Paul Goldberger dismissed Atlanta as a cultural
center, citing not one example of an arts event that he had
witnessed.Variety, which reviews regional theater from Detroit to
Sacramento, ignored 1990s Alliance premieres of three plays
(``Flyin' West,'' ``Blues for an Alabama Sky,'' ``The Last Night of
Ballyhoo''), which in spite of that promotional disadvantage went
on to join the ranks of the most-produced works in America. The
weekly's theater editor, Charles Isherwood, says the oversight was
due to his inability to find a local stringer to review the shows,
not regional bias. But it adds to the impression that national
taste-makers are not abreast of Atlanta's swift change.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Oliverio, Woodruff Arts Center's vice president for
communications, says her primary task is to meet with national
journalists, arts leaders and travel industry executives and
``re-brand Atlanta as a cultural destination'' _ exactly the kind
of corporate jargon such journalists are inclined to ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's reputation is moving in the right direction,''
Oliverio says, ``but reaction around the country is mixed. Business
travelers want Atlanta to be a cultural center where they can bring
a spouse and stay extra nights, but they're not getting the message
that it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe's satirical scene of good-old-boy businessmen at the High
Museum of Art _ comparing the building to an insecticide refinery,
mocking an overrated gay artist _ could be adapted to any city with
some truth, but it perpetuates the stigma of Atlanta as the
Johnny-come-lately of cultural capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cultural target is more like it,'' says Dana White, professor
of urban studies at Emory University(Ga.). ``Atlanta can be a
convenient prop for Northerners trying to hold onto a sense of
superiority. When I go home to Brooklyn, someone will ask me if
they still go barefoot and chew tobacco down there.''
</P>
<P>
   A gallery of stereotypes
</P>
<P>
   That's an extreme example, of course, a blurring of Atlanta's
image with hoary rural cliches. From ``Tobacco Road'' to ``In the
Heat of the Night'' to ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,''
America loves to project its lustier, steamier self onto Georgia
settings (``Heat'' producer-star Carroll O'Connor once asked the
Alabama-born Key to make his accent ``more Southern'' for a guest
shot on the TV show). The old Georgia images are so vivid that they
may overshadow the subtler cultural reality of the state's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta has always been a special case in the South,'' says
Adrian King, head of arts and education programs for the Coca-Cola
Foundation and a former staffer for the Old South at odds the Arts.
``When I was growing up in the cornfields of eastern North
Carolina, and even in Charlotte, Atlanta was the cultural beacon.''
</P>
<P>
   A more common cliche of Atlanta today might be called the
Eternally Designing Woman, after the late 1980s-early '90s TV show
in which Delta Burke played the catty belle descended from Scarlett
O'Hara. The image drags on, aerobically toned, in the Buckhead
women of Wolfe's novel: genteel but shallow, sartorially smart but
culturally semiliterate. In ``Hysteria,'' WB's hip new cartoon show
about history, the dumbest character, Miss Information, is a perky
blond tour guide with _ you guessed it _ a Southern-fried drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Bergstrom is struggling to kill the ``dumb'' reputation as
director of cultural tourism for the Atlanta Convention and
Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country harbors _ loves to harbor _ the Southern
stereotype, and I know because I'm a Southern girl,'' Bergstrom
declares. ``We cling to these stereotypes ourselves. Look at
Southern Living (magazine), where you see such a yearning for the
old agrarian life. Atlanta is where that dream bumps up against the
new, sophisticated reality. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``And how ironic,'' Bergstrom adds, ``that Alfred Uhry's piece
(which opened Thursday) is about a Yankee who becomes the scapegoat
for bringing in the factories, pulling Southerners off the farm. We
Atlantans can never quite figure out which way of life we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
