<HEADER>
A7853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GODS-DIRECTOR20-COX     12-18 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODS-DIRECTOR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMEBER 20
 &HT;    `Gods' willing, director to stay in best picture heaven
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You won't see George of the Jungle without his loincloth in
``Gods and Monsters,'' though that was the original plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I've never talked about this,'' writer-director Bill
Condon says carefully, pausing during a recent Atlanta interview.
He's talking about a climactic moment in the movie between
``George'' actor Brendan Fraser, who plays a Hollywood yard boy,
and Ian McKellen as gay film director James Whale.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of filming, Fraser was making his mark at the
cineplex with his vine-swinging role in Disney's kid comedy. It's a
far cry from ``Gods,'' which opened Friday, Condon's complex,
sorrowful meditation about the final days in the life of
``Frankenstein'' director Whale, found drowned in his pool in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people who manage Brendan got a little nervous
about the nudity,'' Condon says. So the actor chose not to go
full-frontal. ``It's painful to say, but I think he was right,''
the director admits. ``It's such an important moment in the movie,
and there's no way you wouldn't be distracted, looking at this
movie star's genitals.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without that flash of Fraser, ``Gods and Monsters'' was
named best picture of 1998 a few weeks ago by the National Board of
Review, beating Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a feat for somebody who says, ``I was in movie jail
for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Condon means cable flicks, such as a 1991 one starring Gregory
Hines, called ``White Lie,'' shot in Atlanta. Condon's films on the
big screen, ``Sister, Sister'' and ``Candyman: Farewell to the
Flesh,'' both bombed.
</P>
<P>
   The last title, though, led to ``Gods and Monsters.'' While
shooting the ``Candyman'' sequel, Condon got to know horror-meister
Clive Barker, who became executive producer for ``Gods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Clive's first services was to let me meet with Ian in
(Barker's) big estate in Beverly Hills, and not my little house in
Silverlake (a hip, transitional neighborhood in Los Angeles),''
Condon says. And his connections helped in funding the movie's $3
million budget.
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``Gods'' is a hard movie to pitch to backers. ``You
start by saying the word `gay,' '' Condon says with a sardonic
laugh. ``You see people's eyes glaze over. Then you mention
`suicide,' and they go, `Ooh, yeah, we really want to make that our
big summer movie next year.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellen, named best actor by the National Board of Review and
the Los Angeles Film Critics Association, shared a common interest
in the script with Condon and Barker: Like the late Whale, all
three are openly gay men working in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McKellen was worried about playing a man some 10 years
his senior, having already played a 77-year-old Nazi in ``Apt
Pupil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't help wondering which character middle America would
find more repellent: the unrepentant Nazi or the homosexual film
director,'' Condon says, sardonic once more. ``He can play such a
convincing villain, but he's the sweetest guy in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
