<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN20-COX     12-18 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 20
 &HT;    Gifts that catch us unawares
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I wasn't all that poor at age 6 when Christmas didn't
come to Holley, Fla. I was staying with Aunt Liza and Uncle Will
Stevens, some of my blood father's relatives or friends. (My mother
and I had not succeeded in marrying my wonderful stepfather, Wesley
R. Sibley, by that time.) Aunt Liza and Uncle Will, always known to
me as ``folks to stay with,'' lived in a battered, paintless old
house in the country with a log cabin as its detached kitchen. They
had a garden, and that meant vegetables, sugar cane and a big
kettle where they made cane syrup. They had a hog or two and meat
in the smokehouse and a cow that provided milk and butter.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think they knew about Christmas, although at some
point that winter, a crate of oranges and apples arrived from
Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   Their boys and I were home from school so we knew it was a time
of holidays. And then one day a box arrived for me. My mother,
working in a store in Pensacola, had sent me two dresses, a little
pocketbook with two dimes in it and a celluloid doll! I was
overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   The dresses she had made. I recognized her touch _ embroidery on
the collars. And she had pinned to one a little enameled butterfly
pin. For the days left of the school vacation, I walked about
importantly carrying my pocketbook with real money in it _ two
dimes. I played with my doll, and I even wore one of my new
dresses, although Aunt Liza didn't like for me to ``make washing.''
It was no sin, she pointed out, to ``go dirty'' between washdays.
</P>
<P>
   The day I went back to school I walked along with my friends,
Aggie and Jewel, from down the road, and I said, ``I think we have
had us a Christmas.'' They weren't sure either.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe my experience is that you catch up on Christmas afterward
if you are lucky.
</P>
<P>
   They let me out of the hospital in time to take the new baby, my
firstborn son, home for Christmas. War was threatening in Europe.
The Depression still had a grasp on our country. Some people were
worried about the state of the world. We weren't. We were young and
we had a new baby _ and could there be anything more magical at
Christmastime?
</P>
<P>
   I thought that then, pulling a rocking chair close to the
Christmas tree so the baby could see the lights. And I still think
so. There have been what my country neighbors called ``a power of
young'uns'' since that Christmas _ children, grandchildren and now
great-grandchildren. And in every case they have brought meaning
and wonderment to the year's most sacred day.
</P>
<P>
   You worry a lot about money for Christmas when you have
children. Will there be enough for a tricycle? A go-to-sleep doll?
A real teddy bear?
</P>
<P>
   You sit up late aching a little over their letters to Santa
Claus. And then because it is part of the lore, you throw the
scrubby little notes in the fireplace so the wind can take their
messages in ashes to the North Pole. They might not remember what
they asked for, but you will and instead of the tricycle for one it
was three little red-painted rocking chairs I bought on Whitehall
Street and took home on the bus on Christmas Eve. I remember the
Christmas cheer _ and charity _ of those bus passengers who stood
in the aisle and fended off death by being stabbed in the belly by
a pointed wooden rocker. They called after me as I stumbled up to
the curb with my purchases, ``Merry Christmas _ and hug those
babies for us!''
</P>
<P>
   The teddy bear that Christmas was dressed in a khaki soldier
suit, and a favorite game of the little boys in the neighborhood
was sitting in the crape myrtle tree that shaded the sandbox and
dropping oatmeal boxes of sand on the little girls and their dolls
below. The cry ``Bombs awa-ay!'' almost took precedence over
``Merry Christmas!''
</P>
<P>
   And when you protest and are about to give in to thoughts on the
sadness and turmoil of the world, you have to load the youngest in
a stroller and walk the others to the school to see the Christmas
program.
</P>
<P>
   Is that your little boy in the old dining room curtain
portraying a wise man? And suddenly you see your little girl
dressed in a borrowed blue robe portraying Mary, the mother of
Jesus! She sings in a singularly sweet treble, ``De little Lord
Jesus, no crib for he bed!''
</P>
<P>
   The custom of sharing your Christmas dinner with somebody
needier than yourself was a smaller gesture in those days. You
simply brought the old street newspaper peddler or the retired
snake charmer home with you and put another plate on the table.
</P>
<P>
   I asked the children recently if they had learned anything from
our street friends. One mentioned sharing, one mentioned continuing
and undiluted gratitude. But one remembered the safecracker's
mother who told them a line from Emerson: ``To the wise, life is a
festival.''
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
