<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New two-pill-a-day AIDS drug is approved by FDA
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new AIDS drug approved Friday by the Food and Drug
Administration is a welcome option for people with the AIDS virus
who have exhausted other treatment options.
</P>
<P>
   But the drug, Ziagen, has a serious side effect that has caused
at least one death and possibly a second.
</P>
<P>
   Ziagen, a twice-daily tablet, was developed by the
pharmaceutical company GlaxoWellcome of Research Triangle Park,
N.C. Its wholesale price is $3,540 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is a needed addition to the steadily but slowly growing
arsenal of AIDS drugs, which now numbers 14. HIV swiftly develops
resistance to drugs, forcing many people to change medications
frequently. Also, AIDS drugs tend to have debilitating side effects
comparable to those associated with chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Ziagen has convenience going for it _ AIDS drug regimens
involving dozens of pills are common. But it can cause a rare but
potentially fatal allergic reaction. From 3 percent to 5 percent of
those taking Ziagen experience fever, skin rashes, nausea and
diarrhea. Those who experience it must immediately stop taking the
drug and cannot resume it.
</P>
<P>
   Because many of the initial symptoms of the reaction are shared
by other AIDS drugs as well as the flu, people on Ziagen and their
physicians may have a tough time determining that Ziagen is the
culprit, doctors warn. Physicians also say they need more
information on Ziagen's effectiveness before they begin widescale
prescription. The FDA granted Ziagen accelerated approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the blessing of a new drug: It gives us new options,''
said Dr. Jeffrey Lennox, who heads Grady Memorial Hospital's(Ga.)
infectious diseases program. ``But the curse of a new drug is that
we're trying to get these things out as fast as possible, and we're
not always sure how to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziagen belongs to a class of drugs called nucleoside reverse
transcriptase inhibitors. Glaxo-Wellcome makes two other drugs in
this class, including AZT, the oldest AIDS drug, approved in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
