<SLUG> BC-BALSAMINN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMEBER 20
 &HT;    Balsam Mountain Inn elevates body and spirit
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALSAM, N.C. _ Nestled on 26 acres and surrounded by peaks
rising higher than 6,000 feet, the Balsam Mountain Inn is a place
of comfort and joy throughout the year. But at Christmastime, a
special cheer enfolds the 42,000-square-foot inn, less than a mile
from the Blue Ridge Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   Built 1905-1908, it's the sort of place where magic happens _
like the shooting star I witnessed from the front porch one frosty
autumn eve.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks sought warmth near the crackling back-to-back
fireplaces in the sprawling yet cozy lobby. Some were enticed by
the cushioned wicker furniture to sit a spell with a magazine.
Others played Scrabble or worked on a giant jigsaw puzzle. Later
that evening there would be traditional mountain music performed in
the lobby by Anne and John Lough on guitar and dulcimer.
</P>
<P>
   But until then, I could not resist bundling against the chill,
stirring up a steaming cup of hot chocolate and planting myself in
one of the big green-painted oak rockers on the 100-foot-long,
two-tiered porch. Moravian star lights dangling from the ceiling
cast a soft glow.
</P>
<P>
   I sat alone, silently exhaling frosty breath into the crisp
night air and taking in the fragrance of evergreens and the aroma
of wood smoke curling over the inn. As I gazed out on the Great
Balsam Mountains to the east and the clear, inky sky above, I saw a
lone star make a quick but graceful exit. Its fire was gone in the
blink of an eye, but the enchantment of the moment lingered.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the holidays are here, energetic innkeeper Merrily
Teasley _ who hops around the premises, cell phone in hand, making
sure her guests are comfortable _ is working even more magic on the
grand old inn.
</P>
<P>
   She and her staff decorate every nook and cranny with nine
Christmas trees bedecked with handmade ornaments, red-ribboned
evergreen wreaths and garlands, bright red poinsettias, red candles
in brass candlesticks, stockings hung on the hearth, carved wooden
Santas and a whimsical clay creche with jolly shepherds and wise
men. The red walls of the well-stocked library are the perfect
backdrop for Teasley's miniature Christmas village and tiny balsam
trees atop the bookcases.
</P>
<P>
   If perchance it's a white Christmas, Teasley will haul out inner
tubes for some impromptu sledding down the hill in front of the
inn. (The offer stands all winter, and Teasley even maintains a
list of guests who want to be contacted when snow's in the
forecast.)
</P>
<P>
   Teasley's daughter, Noell, the inn's chef, is busing planning
holiday menus for Christmas and New Year's. The inn's dining room
features such creative dishes as apple-smoked pork with caramelized
leek sauce and apple stuffing and pecan-encrusted catfish with red
pepper sauce. Breakfasts are bountiful repasts featuring herbed
scrambled eggs and cheese grits or stuffed French toast, served
with bacon, fruit and fresh-baked breads and muffins.
</P>
<P>
   The main dining room is darkly romantic at night with flickering
candles. The sun room addition, with a purple, green and white tile
floor designed by Teasley to suggest a mountainscape and accented
with purple and green floral fabrics, is filled with light in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The night of the shooting star, Ethan and Robbie Shapiro of
Raleigh were sipping wine by the fireplace before dinner, chatting
with other guests and looking so at home you'd find it hard to
believe they checked in only a couple of hours before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people you meet are friendly here,'' says Robbie Shapiro.
``You can just sit down and strike up a conversation. That just
doesn't happen when you stay at Holiday Inn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shapiros, although first-time visitors, are typical of the
inn's guests, many of whom make frequent returns in search of
relaxation and good company. In fact, so many are repeat visitors
that Teasley has instituted a ``Twelfth Night'' promotion. Stay 12
nights, get one free.
</P>
<P>
   Had Teasley not come across the three-story inn while hiking in
the area in 1989, the lodge might not have been given a second
lease on life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sign that said it was closed for the season,''
said Teasley, ``but in fact, it had been condemned. I saw a For
Sale sign and stopped to pick up a brochure.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, she could see its potential despite its dilapidated
state: 125 broken windows, a sagging front porch, a leaky tin roof
and burst pipes. Meticulous restoration began in 1990, and the
buttercream-and white-hued inn reopened in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The inn _ now listed on the National Register of Historic Places
_ was built by Walter Scott Christy and Joseph Key Kenney,
brothers-in-law from Athens. Guests arrived at the old rail depot,
which, at 3,314 feet above sea level, once was at the highest
elevation of any station east of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the same furnishings and most of the architectural
details those early guests enjoyed are still in place.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the inn's 50 guest rooms has its own character. Beds are
either white-painted antique iron, wicker or bent-twig made by
local craftspeople. Victorian trim, beaded board walls and heart
yellow pine floors are found throughout, including the 10-foot-wide
hallways (built wide enough to accommodate steamer trunks).
</P>
<P>
   When day is done, the simply decorated bedrooms are havens of
rest: beds are stacked with pale blue and white cloud-like duvets
and plump pillows. Heat comes from radiators Teasley salvaged from
a remodeled Western Carolina University dorm. Old claw foot tubs _
a few with showers _ invite long soaks.
</P>
<P>
   If a holiday vacation is not in the stars, don't worry. Long
after the decorations are boxed for another year, the inn will
continue to extend its welcoming warmth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there:
</P>
<P>
   Take I-85 north to U.S. 365 and continue as highway changes to
U.S. 441/23, then take U.S. 23/74 toward Waynesville and look for
signs. The turn-off will be on the right hand side of the highway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rates:
</P>
<P>
   $85-$145 Sundays-Thursdays, $90-$150 weekends and holidays. All
rooms have private baths. Full breakfast included. Dinner with
dessert and a glass of wine runs about $25.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-224-9498.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
