<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LAREACT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Livingston's confession no biggie in his district _ men `all
have affairs,' locals say
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   METAIRIE, La ._ There's one thing everyone seems to agree on in
Speaker-elect Bob Livingston's congressional district: All men
cheat on their wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have affairs,'' said Joe Ruffino, who was having coffee
Friday at his ``second home,'' the Morning Call, a legendary coffee
shop once in the French Quarter and now in Metairie.
</P>
<P>
   It came as no surprise here in suburban New Orleans when
Livingston, the fabled ``boy scout'' of the Republican party,
admitted Thursday to extramarital affairs. His confession had
little effect on his constituents' opinions of him. He is a popular
congressman who usually runs unopposed, and, hey, everyone cheats,
right?
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone forgives apparently. A bomb squad rushed to
Livingston's district office in Metairie on Friday to inspect a
suspicious package that turned out to contain a rock and a note
referring to his adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Marcello, who was having coffee with Ruffino, said
Livingston was stupid for admitting the affair. And he drew a
distinction between Livingston and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex is not bad, I'm not against sex, but it's sex in the wrong
places,'' he said. ``Clinton fooled around with an intern in the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the marble counter where Tennessee Williams is
said to have written his steamy play, ``A Streetcar Named Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone started having sex on that counter, that would be
wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even at a bridal shop, cynicism ran high when it came to men and
faithfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have been doing this for centuries, since the beginning of
time,'' said Sue Kandoul, a bridal consultant at Pearl's Place in
Metairie. ``They say Livingston is better than Clinton because he
admitted it, but he's just as bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing between racks of wedding dresses, Alicia Lissard, who
will be a June bride in 1999, said that, sadly, she believes most
men cheat on their wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching television with my fiance when we heard about
Livingston, and I immediately said something derogatory about
men,'' she said. ``He said, `Not all men are like that.' But the
majority of men at one time or another stray on their wives. I hope
my husband won't cheat, but they have that tendency.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this talk of unfaithfulness, marriage is serious
business here. Adultery is a crime in Louisiana, although the law
no longer is enforced, and this was the first state in the nation
to adopt covenant marriages, a much stricter marriage license that
couples can choose when they tie the knot. It makes it more
difficult to get divorced.
</P>
<P>
   If feelings about men were uniform, feelings on impeachment were
more varied. Ruffino was against impeachment, as were Kandoul and
Lissard, but Pearl's Place owner Elaine Schulman thinks Clinton
deserves the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't care about his personal life if he hadn't lied to
me and to the world,'' she said as she pulled out a beaded satin
dress for a customer. ``He should be impeached not for sex, but for
lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people felt the White House put the spotlight on
Livingston's affairs to derail the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is a sociopath and he'll do anything to get out of the
heat,'' said John Distelhorst, who was visiting from Florida but
used to live in Metairie. ``I don't see any correlation between
what Clinton did and what Livingston did. Livingston didn't abuse
his power. He didn't lie under oath.''
</P>
<P>
   Iole Messina, a government worker from Metairie, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an underhanded way to forestall the proceedings,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette Cotter, who works with Messina, said Clinton should
resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the man had any honor whatsoever he'd resign,'' she said.
``It scares me that he thinks he's smarter than the rest of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   But for every person who was for impeachment, there was someone
who was against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Livingston will encourage his party to extend the same
courtesy of forgiveness to Bill Clinton that they are offering
him,'' said Aly Roberts, who was grocery shopping Friday in
Metairie. When Republicans heard Livingston's confession Thursday,
they applauded his honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have gotten too self-righteous,'' Kandoul said. ``It's
easy to point your finger but you better sweep your own doorstep
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Kandoul said this week's confluence of historic events makes her
feel uneasy, and she blames the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people realize what jeaopardy they're putting
the United States in,'' she said. ``We're bombing Iraq, the
Democrats and Republicans are ready to tear each other's throats
out, and we are impeaching the president. We're leaving the country
wide open for anarchy or terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
