<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 20
 &HT;    Can't bear to part with your pooch? Then take him along, even to
castles and six-course dinners in France
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gatsby never had it so great.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old Jack Russell terrier from Atlanta vacationed in
the south of France for a week in October, sleeping in castles,
sampling foie gras in the 13th-century walled city of Domme,
exploring honey-colored stone villages, and sniffing and strolling
through fields and forests in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Ouaf-ouaf! A dog's life, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   His owner, Atlanta real estate agent Natalie Spalding, booked
them on the Dordogne Doggie Walk, offered by Europeds, a tour
operator in Monterey, Calif. Europeds, which has organized walking
and cycling tours in Europe for 17 years, became an industry
pioneer when it inaugurated doggie walks in Dordogne and Provence
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone like myself who runs and can't bear to be parted
from her dog, this is the ideal trip,'' says Spalding, 53.
</P>
<P>
   She and Gatsby were joined by Spalding's friend Kathy Standard
of Sarasota, Fla., and her year-old Jack Russell, named Deacon.
</P>
<P>
   The two women flew to Paris with their four-footed friends in
coach, the dogs curled up in cozy Sherpa pet carriers under the
seat, sleeping off a mild tranquilizer. Once on foreign soil,
Spalding says she exclaimed to her pooch, ``You're here, Gatsby!
You're really in France!''
</P>
<P>
   Then they traveled by train to Les Eyzies-de-Tayac to begin the
six-night tour of the Dordogne River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The tour group was made up of eight people and six canines.
After a get-acquainted session and a short walk, it was time for
dinner at the chateau.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the dogs went into the dining room,'' says Spalding, ``and
with all the dogs lying at our feet, we had a six-course dinner.
The dogs behaved like little angels.'' (Although the dogs were fed
their usual rations, they did get kibbles such as bites of French
bread and cheese as after-meal treats.)
</P>
<P>
   The tour included overnight stays in Les Eyzies-de-Tayac, Vitac
and Montignac-Lascaux, with daily four-to-five-mile treks along
marked walking trails. A van accompanied the walkers, carrying
luggage, picnics and water and providing lifts for the weary.
</P>
<P>
   No one in canine-loving France thought it odd that dogs were
traveling with their owners, Spalding says. The pooches were able
to go almost everywhere the humans did, including restaurants, the
bustling market at Sarlat and the Romanesque abbey church of St.
Cyprien. But the Font-de-Gaume cave, with 15,000-year-old drawings
on its walls, was off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   Spalding says the dogs got along famously. ``They were like a
pack. They formed a bond. One day we were in a restaurant and
another dog came in and they all howled until he left.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, they behaved themselves. Only once did Gatsby
attempt a side trip. ``He took off down a deer trail,'' Spalding
says, ``and he was gone, gone, gone. But we got him back. Let me
tell you, it was a frightening moment.''
</P>
<P>
   And Deacon caused a farmyard flap when he chased a chicken _ and
caught it. The tour guide came to the hapless fowl's rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that the dogs got along is unusual,
especially for Jack Russells,'' Spalding says. ``All the people got
along because we had a strong common bond: We are all dog lovers.
This trip is custom-made for people like us. Like the woman from
California said, `Where else can you spend 24 hours a day with your
dog?' ''
</P>
<P>
   While Gatsby didn't exactly become bilingual, Spalding says he
knows exactly what to do when she commands, ``Asseyez-vous.''
</P>
<P>
   He sits.
</P>
<P>
   Bon chien! (Good dog!)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Although Europeds' 1999 trips and rates have not
been set, you can get a good idea of the kinds of tours that will
be available by checking the Web site at http://www.europeds.com.
The price for the 1998 Dordogne Doggie Walk was $2,245, including
lodging, breakfast and dinner. For a brochure, call 1-800-321-9552.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
