<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a Pocketbook Poll, Optimism About '99 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Financial turmoil continues to roil markets from Japan to Russia
to Brazil, corporate earnings are shaky and analysts are decidedly
mixed in assessing how the U.S. economy will play out in 1999. But
most Americans continue to be optimistic about their financial
situation, and many expect no change in the economy next year.
</P>
<P>
   Those were findings of a national survey by Yankelovich Partners
for the Lutheran Brotherhood, a group in Minneapolis that offers
financial products and services to church members. Phone interviews
with 1,047 adults found that more than half _ 52 percent _ saw
their families as being better off next year than in the current
year; the same percentage gave that response in last year's survey
about 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significant, only 20 percent said they expected
their families to be worse off _ about half the 39 percent that
thought so in the survey just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   People are less optimistic, though, about the overall economy.
Almost a third _ 32 percent _ expect some sort of downturn in 1999;
last year, only about one-fifth expected the economy to worsen in
1998. Twenty-one percent said the economy would improve next year,
and 41 percent said it would stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   The more money, the more concern: Only 16 percent of those
earning more than $50,000 a year predicted an improved economy, vs.
26 percent of those earning $20,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   _ DANIEL M. GOLD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Time for Giving &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before getting to 1999, more than six of every 10 Americans plan
to make charitable contributions this holiday season, according to
a survey commissioned by Intuit, which makes the Turbotax
tax-preparation software.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey of 1,011 American adults last month, Bruskin
Goldring Research found that of those contributing, nearly 60
percent said they would give the same amount as last holiday season
and 21 percent said they would give more. Only 13 percent planned
to give less than they did last year.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of donors _ 57 percent _ said they would direct
their giving to help the poor and homeless. Asked why they give to
charity during the holidays, 70 percent of the donors agreed that
``it's the right thing to do.'' Just 6 percent mentioned tax
purposes as a reason.
</P>
<P>
   _ DANIEL M. GOLD &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
