<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSY-SHOPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSIEST HOLIDAY SHOPPING WEEKEND IS HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Today marks the start of what is traditionally
the busiest weekend of the holiday shopping season, when
procrastinating consumers realize that time is running out and
descend on local malls in mind-boggling numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds are expected to be particularly big this weekend,
given that this holiday season is expected to be one of the best in
recent years for merchants. And given recent trends, shopping
centers likely will be madhouses today.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last three years, the Saturday before Christmas was
the top shopping day for the holiday season,'' said Marjorie
Fowler, a spokeswoman for Houston-based check authorization service
TeleCheck.
</P>
<P>
   Or as retail analyst Richard Giss puts it: ``(Today) I would
expect to just be huge. Pity the poor people like myself who waited
till the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   With holiday sales at the Burbank Media City Center mall in
Burbank, Calif., already up 5 percent to 7 percent over last year,
general manager Daniel Millman expects things to be especially
hectic this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be very busy, with lots of customer
traffic,'' Millman said. ``And I would expect we'll ring up some
very good sales this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep things moving smoothly, the mall has beefed up traffic
direction along exterior roadways and in its parking garages, and
added more custodial staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``And certainly the merchants have staffed up with seasonal
sales help,'' Millman said.
</P>
<P>
   Giss, a partner with the trade retail services group at the
accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP, said the season has
maintained its muscle after getting off to a strong start the day
after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the anecdotal evidence he's received, Giss said holiday
sales among Los Angeles retailers should be 4.5 percent to 5
percent higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sales) continue to be very, very good, and we continue to
kind of get positive reports that sales are strong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers will extend their hours this weekend, especially
the large retailers like Macy's and Robinsons-May. Among them is
Dutton's Books in suburban Valley Village in Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley, which owner Dave Dutton said has seen an 8 percent
to 10 percent sales increase compared with last year's holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   He suspects this is partly due to the closure earlier this year
of a Super Crown bookstore up the street on Ventura and Laurel
Canyon boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton said he has added hours to some of his part-timers'
schedules to carry the store through the weekend. He also expects
Christmas Eve to be just as busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, in our business the season builds to a climax at
the end, we build toward our crescendo toward Christmas Eve,''
Dutton said. ``We seem to be a destination for a lot of last-minute
shoppers.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend will likely be busy, but it won't be the end of the
frenzy. Last year, three of the top-five busiest days were within
five days of Christmas Day, Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives you a sense that not only is it the big Saturday,
but a number of those days in the last week, that are crucial
shopping days,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
