<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-FOX-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FOX DECIDES TO IMPEACH, SAYS HE WASN'T LOBBIED
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON, Dec. 18 -- Outgoing Congressman Jon Fox announced
Friday his last vote in Congress will be to impeach President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County Republican said he believes the president
perjured himself and broke the law -- meriting impeachment by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way I expected it to end when I began this
Congress with a popular re-elected president,'' Fox told reporters
as the impeachment debate forged ahead in the background. ``The
last thing I thought I would have to do is vote on impeachment. I
never thought I'd do that in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he hadn't finalized his decision until the eve of the
vote. He was among the last members of Congress to make up his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me this has been a painful solemn and difficult
assignment,'' Fox said. ``The President has signed my legislation
into law and has invited me to participate in the final adoption of
the Wye Peace Accords.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he accompanied Clinton on his recent trip to Israel, Fox
said he and the president did not discuss how Fox would vote on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we talked about in Israel was Israel -- and Iraq,'' Fox
said. ``I wasn't lobbied by either side, not the White House and
not by congressional leaders.'' Fox said he read the records of
Clinton's grand jury testimony, talked with colleagues from both
political parties and consulted the Federalist Papers before
reaching a decision. His professional work in the legal system also
influenced his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't swayed by one thing in particular. It was an
amalgamation of everything,'' Fox said. ``As a former Montgomery
County assistant district attorney, I cannot imagine a system of
justice where those who bear witness and swear to an oath can
select when they tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Responses from constituents who contacted Fox's office indicated
their feelings were split on whether Clinton should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Fox realized his vote may not be popular with some constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a popularity contest,'' Fox said. ``People elect
us to enact the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's seat will be taken by Democrat Joe Hoeffel next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such an important vote,'' Fox said. ``Many people in
Congress will only be remembered by how they vote on this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
