<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7879 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-SPI &LR;      12-18 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS, RELUCTANTLY, PREPARE FOR NEXT STEP IN IMPEACHMENT
PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the impeachment process all but certain to move to the next
phase, the Senate is reluctantly preparing to take up the task of
serving as President Clinton's jury, hoping it can rise above the
bare-knuckles partisanship of the House, according to Northwest
senators.
</P>
<P>
   They worry, however, that a lengthy impeachment trial will
submerge national issues like reforming Social Security as well as
regional matters from salmon to the Hanford Reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every issue will be colored by impeachment process until it is
over,'' Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., a member of the Senate leadership,
said at a Portland conference this week that the impeachment train
rolling out of the House caught the Senate somewhat by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most Americans, we hoped we'd never have to deal with
it,'' said Gorton, who advises Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott on
legal matters. ``I don't really have any idea of how it will be
handled.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same conference, Oregon's freshman GOP Sen. Gordon Smith
reflected on a possible impeachment trial, saying: ``I wasn't
elected to do this. I take no pleasure in doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton predicted that impeachment will likely be ``greatly
consuming of time'' at a time when Congress has a narrow window of
opportunity to enact needed, long-term reform of the Social
Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, too, warned that a trial of Clinton will put all other
business on the back burner. ``Senate rules do allow us to proceed
on legislative business, but it would be extremely difficult for
anybody to bring up another issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was disturbed at the raw anger of Friday's House debate
and the rigid rules governing what could be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole thing has been handled with a lot of
partisanship and rancor, and has created a tremendous divisiveness
in the country,'' Murray added. ``I hope the Senate can take this
up in a fair and just manner, bring reason back to the process and
do it quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Often dubbed the world's greatest deliberative body, the Senate
was crafted by America's founders to withstand passions of the
moment. Its members serve six-year terms, compared to two years in
the House. Senators represent entire states, meaning multiple
constituencies and diverse viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Smith, the Senate is a more collegial place,
and likely willing to ponder options _ like censuring and fining
the president _ that GOP leaders blocked the House from
considering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate's comity is genuine,'' Smith said. ``Elbows are
sharper in the House. The issue is much closer over here.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, censure has been proposed by such Republican
elder statesmen as former President Gerald Ford and former Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should exclude that,'' Smith said. ``It
should be on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Murray agreed. ``A number of national leaders,
respected on both sides of the aisle, have made sound proposals. We
should consider them.''
</P>
<P>
   No rule requires that the Senate carry an impeachment trial
through to a verdict. The trial can be adjourned at any time. The
Senate could substitute a censure resolution and send it back to
the House for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has seemed to shut the door on a quick compromise, telling
reporters earlier this week that the Senate would go ahead with a
trial. Some on both sides of the aisle speculate that Lott may draw
out the process in hopes of swinging public opinion and pressuring
Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton is keeping his opinion on the Dole proposal to himself,
for the time being. ``Any idea from outside the Senate or House
will be given the weight that the idea deserves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans may have a self-interest incentive to take the path
recommended by Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment ``makes no political sense,'' said Smith. If Clinton
is convicted or resigns, added the conservative Oregon senator,
``we would simply be giving Al Gore a two-year start on the 2000
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is not known for moving quickly, however. ``Almost
any member can stop anything at any time,'' Gorton noted.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, although Republicans hold only a narrow majority,
leaders were able to dictate rules that precluded a censure vote
and forced members to vote up or down on four articles of
impeachment. A simple majority was required for passage.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Senate will work to adopt rules for the
impeachment trial that ``will meet the approval of members of both
parties,'' Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds vote in the Senate would be needed to convict
Clinton and remove him from office. Republicans will hold a 55-45
advantage when the 106th Congress convenes in January. The majority
caucus includes four moderate-to-liberal GOP senators from New
England states where Clinton's public support runs strongest.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is now feeling its way down a path not traveled since
1868. It has been 130 years since the Senate held its first and
only impeachment trial, in which President Andrew Johnson was
acquitted by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that when senators met two or three weeks ago
to elect our leaders, this was not even a subject that we
discussed,'' Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal year, the Senate would officially convene Jan. 6,
then recess immediately until the president's State-of-the-Union
address on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton predicted, however, that the Senate will stay in session
and immediately take up impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Lott earlier said the Senate would take the first ``preliminary
steps'' toward a trial either the day it convenes or the following
day. He said there would then be a pause of several days for the
White House to submit its pleadings, a formal response to
allegations in articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate would seek to conduct a trial ``with reasonable
dispatch in a way that does not eliminate discussion of nationally
important issues,'' Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1868 trial of Andrew Johnson lasted for more than a month,
with sessions running up to five hours a day. The Senate was kept
in session six days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist would preside at a
Senate trial. Senators would sit in silence during the proceedings.
They would get to speak only at the hour of judgment, standing
beside their desks to say ``Guilty!'' or ``Not Guilty!'' to the
impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sobering job, one that Murray said she is approaching
``with a lot of trepidation. It is a tremendous responsibility. It
will be incredibly difficult. It is a tremendous weight to have to
make a judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Gorton: ``An oath to administer impartial justice is one
that every member will take very seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
