<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMBAT-WOMEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE FIRST TIME, WOMEN ARE FLYING IN COMBAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time, U.S. female military aviators are flying
combat missions as Operation Desert Fox continues against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen female naval aviators are flying from the aircraft
carriers USS Enterprise and USS Carl Vinson, and others are
operating with Air Force units stationed in the Persian Gulf
region, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy fliers include four EA-6B crew members from Whidbey
Island Naval Air Station assigned to squadrons aboard the two
carriers, said Capt. John Cryer, commander of the Pacific Fleet
Electronic Combat Wing at the Oak Harbor, Wash., base. They include
one pilot and three electronic countermeasures officers who operate
the Prowler aircraft's powerful jamming gear, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time where women launched and fired
weapons,'' said one Pentagon Navy official, who asked that his name
not be used. Female naval aviators, who first were allowed into
warplane cockpits in late 1993, have flown thousands of hours in
patrol missions such as Bosnia and the ``no fly'' enforcement over
southern Iraq that preceded the combat operations this week, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth female Prowler aviator from Electronic Attack Squadron
130 aboard the Enterprise was killed with three male shipmates when
their EA-6B crashed on the carrier flight deck last month as the
ship was leaving the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force spokesman in Washington said the number of women in
the service's bomber and fighter units now in the Persian Gulf was
not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon in 1993 terminated a decades-old combat exclusion
rule that prohibited female aircrew from flying in combat aircraft,
but the first female pilots and crew personnel did not enter the
fleet until the following year, the Navy official said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, their ranks have steadily grown. As of June there
were 326 women aviators _ 229 pilots and 97 naval flight officers _
with another 163 student aviators in the training pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, 68 warships and 57 noncombatant vessels have become
open to female crew members, and there are now 11,204 women serving
at sea, the Navy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the 51,251 female personnel on active duty comprise
about 13 percent of the Navy's total force of 393,481 personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole integration of women has been so transparent up here
we don't even think of it,'' said Cryer, the EA-6B wing commander.
He said each training class of about 18 EA-6B students has two or
three women, a level that has remained constant in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Serving in the Gulf, in addition to the four female Prowler
aircrew, are five F/A-18 Hornet fighter pilots; one pilot and three
naval flight officers in F-14 Tomcats; three naval flight officers
in the S-3 Viking patrol plane; and six SH-60 Seahawk helicopter
pilots for the search and rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   The female aviators serving in the conflict have declined
requests by news media for interviews, the Pentagon official said.
``They don't want to stand apart (from male squadron mates) because
they consider themselves Navy aviators first and foremost,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, to us it doesn't matter that they are male or
female,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is not naming the women, or other personnel
involved in combat missions, for security reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
