<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-18 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A CASE FOR FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joseph R. Yandle is one of the most prominent success
stories in the recent history of the Massachusetts prison system.
Now he has become a pawn for politicians trying to out-tough one
another on the issue of crime.
</P>
<P>
   After three years on parole, Yandle was returned to MCI-Concord
in August, after disclosures that he fabricated a history as a
Vietnam veteran who developed the drug habit that led him to a life
of crime, including a 1972 murder. He was sent back to prison for
violating parole, and may spend the rest of his life there.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Yandle was wrong to use the Vietnam tale to
win his release. But sending him to prison for the rest of his life
_ as Acting Governor Paul Cellucci and incoming Attorney General
Thomas F. Reilly want to do _ would be ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, it would make a mockery of the notion that the state
should rehabilitate prisoners so they can become contributing
members of society. Few prisoners have ever been more successfully
rehabilitated than Yandle. If that counts for nothing, the whole
system is built on a falsehood.
</P>
<P>
   Yandle went to prison for being the getaway driver in the 1972
Medford package store holdup in which Joseph R. Reppucci was
murdered. He began mounting a crusade for release in the 1980s,
pointing to his two college degrees earned in prison, and aided by
bogus military records.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Council commuted his sentence in 1995, and he was
paroled. But though his phony image as a Vietnam hero helped boost
his cause, it was his rehabilitation and the fact he was the
getaway driver that won him his freedom. Yandle moved to Vermont to
live with the wife he had married while in prison and their young
son.
</P>
<P>
   At Cellucci's insistence, he was returned to prison in August.
But now the council and the Parole Board, which actually released
him, must decide whether he remains in MCI-Concord or goes free.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Council held a nine-hour hearing on Yandle's case
last Wednesday, and is scheduled to vote on whether to take back
its commutation of his sentence this Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yandle's hoax embarrassed Cellucci. But the state plainly had
not done its homework on Yandle _ allowing him to submit fraudulent
military records to the Parole Board in the late 1980s rather than
obtaining official documents.
</P>
<P>
   When Yandle's hoax unraveled, Cellucci was in the midst of a
fierce Republican primary battle with Treasurer Joseph D. Malone.
So the acting governor did what politicians often do under
pressure: He postured. His earlier support for Yandle evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Reilly also made the case for Yandle's continued
incarceration, maintaining that he had been sentenced to life in
prison and had won his freedom through fraud. Yandle, he said, was
and is a con man.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of support, dozens of Yandle's Vermont neighbors
attended the hearing, with many of them testifying about his
extensive community service.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone would have to sympathize with the Reppucci family, who
sat in silent dignity at the hearing Wednesday. But it's hard to
see what good it does anyone to put Joe Yandle back in prison. This
is hardly someone who's evaded responsibility: He served 23 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly has changed. Yes, he lied. But he also grew into a
good citizen, husband, and father. Not even the most zealous
advocate of returning him to prison claims to consider him a threat
to public safety.
</P>
<P>
   If a major goal of our prison system is to reform criminals so
they can lead productive lives among us _ a task at which it most
often fails, miserably _ then the governor and the attorney general
should applaud someone like Yandle, who counsels kids and drug
addicts, coaches Little League baseball and has been a role model
for his community in three years of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Governor's Council votes in Yandle's favor on
Wednesday, as they probably will, Yandle may still not be freed.
</P>
<P>
   Because Yandle is technically free on parole, the final decision
on his fate rests with the Parole Board, which will consider his
case on Jan. 21. That gubernatorially appointed board will probably
vote to keep Yandle in prison, at Cellucci's direction.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a shame. What Yandle did to win his freedom seems
less important than what he has done with that freedom. Not many
convicts ever go straight. Joe Yandle has. That should count for
something.
</P>
<P>
   (Adrian Walker is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
