<HEADLINE>
GOLFER NORMAN PULLS OUT OF BUSINESS JET SET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He was the high-profile first customer for Boeing's
new Business Jet line.
</P>
<P>
   But golf pro Greg Norman has canceled his order for one of the
new 737 business models, The Boeing Co. confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's order for the $35 million Business Jet, which has been
on the market for more than two years, was highly publicized by
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The company centered an advertising campaign around the
golfer-businessman even before the jets began rolling of the
assembly line this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Norman could not be reached for comment, but a Boeing executive
blamed Asia's economic woes for yet another jet cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Norman ordered his jet in June 1997, the month before the plunge
of the Thai baht set off the economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was doing a lot of golf course design in Asia,'' said Lee
Monson, Boeing Business Jet's vice president of sales. ``Like the
rest of the world, he faced some real downturn in that part of his
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Though based on the new generation 737, the Business Jet
typically has extra fuel tanks for long flights. It can fly
non-stop from New York to Tokyo, carrying more payload than smaller
corporate jets. But it weighs 171,000 pounds compared with under
100,000 for the heaviest corporate jet. Its weight keeps it out of
small airports with thinly paved taxiways _ just the sort of
airports Norman has been flying to recently to work on golf courses
in rural America.
</P>
<P>
   Monson said Norman has been flying in a Gulfstream IV.
</P>
<P>
   Norman canceled his order for the Business Jet in the second
week of November. Boeing declined to discuss the financial terms of
the cancellation. ``We never discuss those,'' Monson said, ``and
they're all a little bit different.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman's plane was nearly out the door, and ``just getting ready
for flight test,'' Monson said. The custom interior hadn't been
installed, because that work isn't done by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The company has sold the plane to another customer.
</P>
<P>
   This is the program's first cancellation. ``We don't anticipate
it significantly affecting our business,'' Monson said. ``You don't
see multimillion-dollar decisions made because Greg Norman owns one
of these airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes not. Forty-seven Business Jets have been
ordered, with eight scheduled to be delivered by the end of this
month. Of the eight, one is going to General Electric, one will be
a Boeing demo, and six are to undisclosed buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Customers, who include corporations and heads of state, mostly
don't want their names made public. Norman didn't mind, and Boeing
paid him to appear in its ads.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no more Greg Norman ads. And Monson added, ``I
think you won't see another high-profile type advertisement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
