<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Dec. 20,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE story &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAYMOR-TITUS-FILM (Rome) _ The vast white marble piazza before
the Palazzo della Civilta del Lavoro, is a solemn building of
marble arches that looms over EUR, the grandiose exhibition park
Mussolini ordered built in the 1930s to fuse Roman Empire and
Fascist might. And that was what drew the theater director Julie
Taymor to select it as a site for ``Titus,'' her film adaptation of
Shakespeare's tragedy ``Titus Andronicus.'' Whatever its quality is
eventually judged to be, this is no ordinary venture. It is Ms.
Taymor's first feature film, with a starry cast headed by Anthony
Hopkins in the title role, Jessica Lange and Alan Cumming. This is
Ms. Taymor's first major venture since her extraordinary success
last year with Disney's ``Lion King'' _ a show that she transformed
with her direction, design and musical choices from a potentially
potted theatricalization of a cartoon movie into Broadway's biggest
hit. By Alessandra Stanley. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-UNDERSTANDING (Undated) _ Present an unfamiliar piece of
music to a randomly chosen audience member, ask an opinion, and I
challenge you to get a simple expository sentence in response. The
body language will be one of retreat; the words will be quick to
equivocate. ``That was interesting,'' or ``I didn't understand it,
but maybe I will next time,'' or ``I should know more about it
before I tell you what I think.'' One longs to hear, ``That was
beautiful,'' or ``I hated it,'' or ``It bored me to death,'' for
this is what those answers really mean. The crucial word here is
``understand,'' for the fear of not understanding is great. Failing
to understand marks the unhappy listener as dense, out of the loop,
ill educated. By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   GEENA-DAVIS-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ The Academy Award-winning
actress Geena Davis is back, or at least working at a comeback
after a two-year hiatus and a divorce. And she has made it clear
that she is willing to play just about anything _ except a
weakling. Her new movie ``Stuart Little,'' based on E.B. White's
classic 1945 children's book about a family whose new son turns out
to be a mouse, symbolizes the critical juncture where Ms. Davis,
who is 41, stands. By James Sterngold. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-FILMS (Undated) _ This week, five films that can
legitimately be described as British will be showing in American
theaters. Given the anxiety of holiday marketers, that number is in
itself an eye-popper. What's more surprising, though, is that not
one of these British films is about expendable laborers trying to
salvage self-regard in a renovated upland city, or about young
professionals contemplating themselves in the sleek surfaces of the
new London. These films _ ``Elizabeth,'' ``Little Voice,''
``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``The General'' and ``The Theory of
Flight'' _ don't represent anything as grand as the renaissance of
a national industry that looked so healthy in the 1960s and then
again in the 1980s. By Will Joyner. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   GLEESON-GENERAL-FILM (Dublin, Ireland) _ Brendan Gleeson bears
an uncanny resemblance to Martin Cahill, the maverick Dublin
gangland boss whom he plays in John Boorman's new movie, ``The
General,'' which opened Friday in New York. Yet there was another,
more subtle, reason for casting the burly Irish actor as the
mobster. In order to convey why Dubliners came to admire this
hardened criminal, murdered by the IRA in 1994, Boorman needed a
likable Cahill. And Gleeson is very likable. But he also has what
the veteran director calls ``essential goodness,'' which is why he
almost turned down his biggest movie role to date. By Alan Riding.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   ISADORA-DUNCAN-BOOK (Undated) _ Earlier this year, a conference
of dance scholars retired from a long day's meeting to an oyster
house, where the oyster lovers set out to seduce the skeptics into
sampling the delicacy. A quotation from the modern dancer Isadora
Duncan's autobiography, ``My Life,'' persuaded the final holdout.
``You know what Isadora wrote, don't you?'' said a clever
historian. ``That she began to dance in her mother's womb, in
response to her mother's diet of oysters and champagne, the food of
Aphrodite.'' ``My Life'' turns 71 this month, a lifetime much
longer than that of its author. By Ann Daly. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-SINGERS (Undated) _ Not since the czarist era have
Russian singers attained the unfettered mainstream exposure they
currently enjoy, once more regularly appearing in Western opera
houses and signing contracts with major record labels. Perhaps the
most conspicuous example of their resurgence can be found on the
Philips label, on which the indefatigable conductor Valery Gergiev
spearheads a seemingly endless series of Russian operas, including
many obscure works. Largely as a result of his efforts, several
soloists have emerged as stars in their own right, including the
soprano Galina Gorchakova, the mezzo-soprano Olga Borodina and, to
a lesser extent, the baritone Dmitri Hvorostovsky. By David
Mermelstein. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MAHLER-MUSIC (Undated) _ The Philharmonic, the answer came back,
was holding the big gun in reserve, hoping to follow with a set
consisting entirely of Mahler's music. Now that release has
impressively materialized on 12 CDs as ``The Mahler Broadcasts,
1948-82'' (NYP 9801/12), and the obvious question becomes: Among
the 10 conductors represented, why no Bernstein? Leonard Bernstein,
after all, though he did not single-handedly revive the
Philharmonic's Mahler tradition, as is often supposed, certainly
took it to its loftiest heights in a series of performances
throughout his tenure as music director, from 1958 to 1969, and
beyond. Again, the Philharmonic is quick to reply. Bernstein's
omission, it turns out, is not for lack of trying. Sedgwick Clark,
the set's producer, explains in booklet notes that of all the
Mahler works the maestro performed with the Philharmonic, all but
two are represented among Bernstein's commercial recordings with
the orchestra, which remain in more or less continual circulation.
By James R. Oestreich. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   DVORAK-MUSIC (Undated) _ Big and powerful are adjectives that
spring to mind when listening to the Eroica Trio, but a more pithy
description might be intelligent. The group's second recording,
``Dvorak: Piano Trio Dumky'' (EMI 7243 5 56673 2), represents
thoughtful music making of a high caliber. By Anne Midgette.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   SUBWAY-ART (Los Angeles) _ When the Red Line subway station on
the corner of Beverly Boulevard and Vermont Avenue opens here next
year, the first thing commuters will see is a giant escarpment of
sandy-colored rock that straddles the entrance tunnel. The
sculpture, by George Stone, was commissioned by the Metropolitan
Transit Authority to enliven this station. What Stone calls his
``art rocks'' _ three more hang from the roof of the pristine,
marble-floored station below _ are part of one of the most
imaginative public art programs in the country. By David Hay.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BODY-XRAYS-ART (Undated) _ The Julie Saul Gallery in Manhattan
has had the piquant idea of displaying together early medical
X-rays and more recent works of art that borrow from X-rays and
Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI). The exhibition, ``Skin/Deep: A
Survey of Interior Imaging From X-Ray to MRI'' (through Jan. 16),
assembles approximately 40 images from 1896 to the 1990s _ not
exactly a survey but proof once more of how eager art has been to
pilfer from the treasury of science and how readily scientific
images seen in an art context assume some of the characteristics of
art. By Vicki Goldberg. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   FEMINISM-TV (Undated) _ Is feminism dead? In shows like ``Ally
McBeal'' and ``Sex and the City'' it may just be. By Karen Durbin.
(moved).
</P>
<P>
   DAVID-KELLEY-TV (Undated) _ Jerry Seinfeld put it as well as
anybody. ``I mean,'' he said of David E. Kelley, ``this guy has
done actual things.'' Kelley may be this decade's dean of the
quality series, but when the Museum of Television and Radio in Los
Angeles honored him and Seinfeld on the same night two months ago,
the speakers seemed to have trouble describing the essence of the
Kelley greatness. Dylan McDermott, of Kelley's ABC law series,
``The Practice,'' used the words ``quirky, idiosyncratic,'' because
somebody had to. Calista Flockhart, of Kelley's Fox law series,
``Ally McBeal,'' went for the sentimental, describing Kelley as one
who ``tells us what it's like to be people.'' By Anita Gates.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CHU-ART (Paris) _ In the fifth century B.C., Confucius
questioned the practice of burying people alive alongside the dead
in funerary rituals, calling it a waste of human life. But it was
not until 100 years later that the Chu people of Southern China
abandoned human sacrifice, replacing the living in such rituals
with carved and lacquered wooden figures. Chu artists produced
haunting effigies of concubines, slaves, deer and tigers, all
common in the retinues of Chinese rulers during the late Warring
States period (fourth century to third century B.C.) and the Han
Dynasty (206 B.C. to 220 A.D.). A large number of Chu works have
been excavated over the past 20 years, and recently such works have
become more visible in the market. The Chu figures are now both the
subject of scholarly study and are being actively collected by
museums. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Browsing the Web's newsstand. By L.R.
Shannon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GRENADINES (Undated) _ Under saill through the
Grenadines. By Carey Goldberg. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DISNEY (Anaheim, Calif.) _ Disney's revised Tomorrowland
is at its best when technology runs amok. By James Sterngold.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-INTERNET (Undated) _ Cautiously, travelers shop on the
Internet. By Adam Bryant. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Car users face increasing feed.
By Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Japanese-American Museum is expanded;
The Peninsula Hotel: A touch of Hong Kong; Signing up for camping
in the national parks; Christmas in the home of the reindeer.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions and answers on travel. By Ray
Cormier. (Moved).
