<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALT-LAKE-CITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC COMMITTEE ETHICS PANEL TO BEGIN A BRIBE INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The organizing committee for the 2002 Winter
Olympics on Friday empowered its ethics panel to begin
investigating whether bribes were offered to secure the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking an independent investigation, the organizing committee
said it would allow the five-member ethics panel to bring in
outside attorneys and accounting firms as it determines whether
improper payments, gifts and services were made in an effort to
sway votes of members of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics panel is to make its report by Feb. 11. The
organizing committee said the report would be made public but did
not say whether the report would contain a detailed explanation of
payments made and the names of people who were paid.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is also conducting an investigation after one of its
senior members, Marc Hodler of Switzerland, charged last weekend
that Salt Lake City and other Olympic cities participated in
vote-buying schemes. Salt Lake City officials have acknowledged
spending $400,000 on scholarships and athletic training for 13
people, including six relatives of IOC members, but have denied
that there was bribery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acknowledge the seriousness of the matter, and we regret
any and all embarrassment this has caused the city and state of
Utah,'' Robert Garff, chairman of the organizing committee's board
of trustees, said at a news conference. He said that organizers
would do everything possible to ``ensure the Games go forward with
the highest level of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I can say these kind of incidents should not have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said it was premature to say whether any Salt Lake
City Olympic official would be fired. One city councilwoman, Deeda
Seed, has called for the resignation of Frank Joklik, the chairman
of the Olympic organizing committee, and of Dave Johnson, senior
vice president of the organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
   Seed has also characterized the ethics panel investigation as a
``toothless tiger'' because it lacks subpoena power, sufficient
independence and the ability to enforce its own recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers sought to counter such charges Friday by saying that
the ethics panel would be allowed to operate on an unlimited budget
and to employ the necessary outside firms to conduct the bribery
investigation. Organizers said they planned to follow the ethics
panel's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics panel is headed by Gordon Hall, a former chief
justice of the Utah Supreme Court; Patricia Hanna, dean of
humanities at the University of Utah; David Jordan, a former U.S.
attorney; Merrill Norman, an accountant, and Barbara Lockhart, a
former Olympic athlete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
