<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTES-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TWO RECEIVERS OUT, GIANTS THINK CREATIVELY FOR KANSAS CITY
GAME 
CHIEFS' MORRIS STAYS INBOUNDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There has been a clamor for Giants Coach
Jim Fassel to open up the offense and take some unconventional
risks as the season winds down. Giants fans may soon be getting
their wish.
</P>
<P>
   Does a 275-pound split end sound unconventional enough?
</P>
<P>
   Should the 275-pound Howard Cross, the team's starting tight
end, end up split wide as a receiver on Sunday, it will not be an
attempt by Fassel to be unorthodox, however. It will be a move of
desperation brought on by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several days the Giants have lost the wide receivers
David Patten and Joe Jurevicius to knee injuries, and a third
receiver, Chris Calloway, is also hobbled by a knee injury, though
he is expected to play against the Kansas City Chiefs on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel has elevated the rookie Brian Alford, who has not been in
uniform all season, to the fourth receiver sport. Alford also has
practiced this week as the team's third receiver since Calloway has
been resting his knee. But if Calloway suffers a setback or another
wide receiver gets hurt Sunday, the Giants will turn to Cross or
running back Tiki Barber if they want to run their four-receiver
formations.
</P>
<P>
   There is quite a disparity between the two since Cross, who is 6
feet 5 inches, is big for a tight end and built more like an
offensive tackle. Barber is 5 feet 10 inches and 205 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But it could be an important choice since the Giants have used
four receivers more often since Kent Graham took over at
quarterback. Graham, who will start his fourth game this season on
Sunday, likes to throw the ball deep, spreading more receivers in
various parts of the field. The Giants entire two-minute offense _
which yielded the winning touchdown against Denver last weekend _
requires four wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   So Alford will most likely be on the spot. So might Cross if any
of the other receivers falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an emergency plan,'' Fassel said Friday after
practice. ``I don't know that I want to see it under any other
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   In 14 games this season, Cross has caught 13 passes.
</P>
<P>
   The blessing for Giants fans is that they should see Alford in
action for the first time. Alford, a former Big Ten track star who
ranks fourth in the conference in career receiving yards and
touchdowns, has looked impressive in practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   CHIEFS' MORRIS STAYS INBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   When the Chiefs considered signing running back Bam Morris
earlier this season, they passed because his weight had ballooned
to 264 pounds. In October, the Chiefs acquired the former
Pittsburgh Steelers star, who had since lost 16 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Schottenheimer, the Kansas City Coach, said he was not
worried about Morris' previous off-the-field problems, which
included a 90-day jail term on a drug offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met with Bam, I had planned to tell him that if
he crossed the line again he was out of here,'' Schottenheimer
said. ``But I never had to mention it because it was obvious to me
he knew the consequences of his actions and was accountable for
them. If he was to err in his ways, he is being held accountable to
a far more important court than the Kansas City Chiefs, and that's
the judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris said: ``I've made a lot of dumb mistakes in my life, and
it may have taken me a long time to learn from, but I did and I'm
still here. Marty Schottenheimer can count on me because I'm going
to be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
