<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-PLAYERS-550&AMP;A     12-18 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-PLAYERS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
16 LOCKED-OUT PLAYERS TAKE TO THE COURT SATURDAY NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ They have been portrayed as self-centered,
greedy and completely out of touch with their once-fawning public.
And that is just the minimum-salary guys.
</P>
<P>
   So Saturday night at the Atlantic City Convention Center, 16
locked-out National Basketball Association players will not only
get to put on shorts and sneakers and dunk again, but they will to
try to quell the backlash and recapture the interest of their
apathetic followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a lesson in this, it's that players are going to
definitely have to relate with the fans again,'' said Dominique
Wilkins, one of 14 current or former NBA all-stars who will play in
the game. ``You look at baseball. Four years after the strike, it
took Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa to generate that kind of interest.
The NBA is also going to have to make a conscious effort to win
back support. You have to be sympathetic to what the average fan is
about.''
</P>
<P>
   When plans for the game were announced earlier this month,
organizers planned to use 90 percent of the proceeds to help
cash-poor players. They later reversed course amid an avalanche of
public criticism. Now they are calling the exhibition at the
Atlantic City Convention Center ``a gift to the fans for the
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, the game may be a referendum on how the public
perceives the players in their economic fight with the owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially we had other plans, but we came to see that all of
the proceeds should go straight to charity,'' Alonzo Mourning said
at a news conference Friday. ``That would be best for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardaway added: ``Tomorrow night I'm hopeful that the fans
will come out and give us a standing ovation. It'll be hard to win
the fans back, but people are starving out there to see basketball.
They're going to welcome us back.''
</P>
<P>
   Billed as ``The Game on Showtime,'' the event will be televised
on the cable network at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The game's organizer, Curtis Polk, said more than 8,000 tickets
had already been sold for the game, including blocks of tickets
bought by corporations. If more than 10,000 of the 12,500 seats at
the Convention Center are filled, the game _ announced only 12 days
ago _ would exceed live gate expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one ticket agent was quoted in The Press of Atlantic City
as saying only 574 tickets _ priced at $25, $50, $100, $200, $300
and $500 _ had been sold through his agency as of Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The agent Arn Tellem, who is co-promoting the game with David
Falk, said about $700,000 from the game will be donated to
Philadelphia-based charities. UNICEF and Save the Children have
been designated as the two national charities that will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first nationally televised game featuring NBA
players since June 16, when Michael Jordan stole Game 6 of the
finals from the Utah Jazz and led the Bulls to their sixth title of
the decade. Jordan, scheduled to play golf with Hale Irwin in the
Lexus Challenge in La Quinta, Calif., Saturday, is not expected to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, the union president, will lead the red team,
along with Tim Hardaway, Shawn Kemp, Dan Majerle, Karl Malone,
Reggie Miller, Mitch Richmond and Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning heads the white team, which includes Tom Gugliotta,
Anfernee Hardaway, Allan Houston, Gary Payton, Glen Rice and Chris
Webber.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for risk of injury, the promoters have arranged for $20
million in disability insurance for each player.
</P>
<P>
   The game features members of the last four teams selected to
represent the United States in international competition. Charles
Barkley will coach the red team and Oscar Roberston will coach the
white team. It is Showtime's first basketball telecast since the
depressing sight of Kareem Abdul-Jabbar eating up Julius Erving in
a one-on-one game featuring two Hall of Famers several years past
their primes. That game, Feb. 28, 1992, was also in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Though NBA players are competing, a league logo will be hard to
find. Because of copyright infringements, the announcers for the
game cannot use the term ``NBA'' or refer to the players as being
from the ``Knicks'' or the ``Heat,'' also league trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   But it is professionals playing basketball. And until the two
sides can agree on a deal and salvage what is left of the season _
no meetings between the NBA commissioner David Stern and the union
chief Billy Hunter are scheduled for the weekend _ that is
apparently enough for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss each other,'' Mourning said. ``Our body clocks are
going off. At this time of year, you need to play basketball
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
