<HEADLINE>
PENULTIMATE GRAF.)  
 REPUBLICANS' APPROVAL RATING ERODES IN POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: SUBS TO INSERT NEW 10th and 11th GRAFS AND TO REMOVE(ART ADV: A poll graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-DEBATERS,
IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-SENATE,
IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-TV, IMPEACH-TV-NOTEBOOK.) (htv) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON with MICHAEL R. KAGAY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican Party's standing with the public has
dropped significantly, matching its lowest rating in the past 14
years, as the House moves toward a vote on impeaching President
Clinton, the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   While impeachment by the House now appears all but inevitable,
half the public still expects some other outcome, suggesting at
least the possibility of further erosion in the Republican party's
image when the reality of the second impeachment in American
history sinks in.
</P>
<P>
   Six in 10 Americans said Republicans in Congress were out of
touch with the public's wishes on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The public's opposition to impeachment _ 62 percent said they
wanted their representative to vote against it _ is reflected in
every sector of society: every region, every age group, every
income group, with the exception of self-described Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs that public opinion could prove treacherous for
Clinton in the weeks ahead: About four in 10 Americans believe that
if the House sends articles of impeachment to the Senate for trial,
it would be better for the country for Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in many ways, the poll found remarkable stability in
public opinion across a year of turmoil and scandal. The public
continues to distinguish between the man and the president: as in
January when the Monica Lewinsky scandal was first disclosed,
Americans are critical of his personal character and give him high
marks for his performance in office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's job approval rating stands in sharp contrast to that
of President Richard M. Nixon after the House Judiciary Committee
recomended his impeachment: 65 percent approved of Clinton's job
performance this week, while only 24 percent held that view of
Nixon just before his resignation in 1974, as the House moved
toward an impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was based on telephone interviews conducted
nationwide with 1,666 adults on Sunday, Monday and Tuesday, and
another 326 on Thursday, after Clinton ordered the bombing of Iraq.
The margin of sampling error for the entire poll is plus or minus
two percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that, at least in this snapshot of public
opinion, Republicans have paid a heavy price for their aggressive
pursuit of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of Americans who held a favorable view of the
party _ 40 percent _ was at its lowest level in the 14 years that
the New York Times/CBS News Poll has been asking the question,
statistically matching the level of 43 percent recorded in early
1996 after a budget impasse resulted in a partial shutdown of the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In October, before the 1998 midterm elections, public opinion of
the Republican Party was evenly split, 45 percent favorable and 46
percent unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   The party's image worsened as the week progressed: 42 percent of
respondents had a favorable opinion of the Republicans early in the
week; that dropped to 33 percent among people polled on Thursday,
as the reality of impeachment set in among the public and
Washington grappled with the remarkable confluence of crises at
home and abroad. The margin of sampling error for the one-night
finding was plus or minus 6 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the number of people holding a favorable view of
the Democratic party held steady over the week at 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By a ratio of more than two-to-one, Americans said the
impeachment vote should have been postponed while the United States
is engaged in military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that, by a ratio of two-to-one, Americans
believe that the timing of the airstrikes against Iraq had more to
do with the need to respond quickly to Saddam Hussein's defiance of
U.N. weapons inspectors than with any effort by Clinton to divert
attention from impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, designed to measure day-to-day shifts in public
opinion during this climactic week, found that the public was only
just beginning to recognize that the House was on the verge of
impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, 31 percent of those responding said they expected the
House to impeach the president, with 50 percent predicting that the
matter would be resolved through a compromise such as censure.
</P>
<P>
   By the eve of the expected impeachment, only half of Americans
expected it to actually occur; the rest still foresaw some lesser
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The public did, however, want to see some punishment for the
president. Fifty-four percent said Congress should censure Clinton
for what he has done, an option that the Republican leaders have
consistently refused to permit.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of the opposition to impeachment was that even
Republicans were divided over it, with 76 percent of self-described
conservative Republicans favoring, while all other Republicans were
split, with 49 percent in favor and 41 percent opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls have shown higher support for the president to
resign, if, in fact, he is impeached by the House. But because a
minority of the public still confuses impeachment by the House with
removal by the Senate, the Times/CBS News Poll pointed out the
difference as part of the resignation question: ``If the full House
votes to send impeachment articles to the Senate for a trial, then
do you think it would be better for the country if Bill Clinton
resigned from office, or not?'' Forty-three percent said better, 53
percent disagreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
