<HEADLINE>
UNDECIDED LAWMAKERS GRAPPLE WITH IMPEACHMENT DECISION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as the historic debate on whether to impeach
President Clinton began Friday, a handful of undeclared lawmakers
were agonizing over what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Some were still reviewing reams of documents on the Monica
Lewinsky affair and looking to both the criminal code and the Bible
for guidance as their colleagues began framing the issue of whether
Clinton should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   But by the close of the 12 hours of debate, most had made up
their minds even if they chose not to take the floor to announce
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, who issued a
statement saying that he would vote for articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is one of the most somber days I have known since coming
to Congress 20 years ago,'' Stenholm said, adding that ``it doesn't
get much worse'' than voting to impeach the president at the same
time U.S. forces are engaged in conflict in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Stenholm said Clinton had lied ``to protect himself
at the expense of others,'' leaving ``an indelible mark on the
presidency of the United States,'' and he must be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who have the honor of holding public office should
hold ourselves to a higher standard,'' Stenholm said.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to support articles of impeachment was not
unexpected. But Democratic leaders had held out hope that he might
stand with them against what they view as highly partisan movement
to drive the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   The Abilene congressman acknowledged that he was ``troubled'' by
some Republicans, whom he described as uninterested in ``fairness
and objectivity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been motivated by political blood lust,'' he
observed. But in the end, he said the facts of the case were clear:
``Our president has admitted to wrongdoing. ... Lying under oath
and repeated disregard for decency by our nation's top elected
official is a serious offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Those facts were not as clear to other undecided or undeclared
members who looked to the Constitution to justify their opposition
to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Rep. Solomon P. Ortiz, D-Texas, acknowledged that
Clinton's ``behavior and the lie'' about it ``was immoral.'' But he
cautioned members not to set a ``dangerous constitutional precedent
in a partisan setting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand jurors in our judicial system today have to exercise
good judgment about stopping a bad case when the evidence is not
there to fortify it legally,'' he said. ``In our role today we have
the added weight of exercising good constitutional, democratic and
political common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton certainly injured the national trust ... but
he has not injured the Constitution, our democracy, our government,
or any political movement in our country,'' Ortiz added.
</P>
<P>
   At least four moderate Republicans, including Amo Houghton and
Peter King of New York, who came out against impeachment echoed
that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe that that for a president of the United
States ... to be impeached, for an election to be undone, there
must be a direct abuse of presidential power,'' King said during
the debate.
</P>
<P>
   He admonished his Republican colleagues for their partisan
attacks on Clinton and setting a standard that he said would make
the government ``subject to the whims of independent counsels'' and
``the frenzied politics of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   For two other Republicans who had been undecided the decision to
vote for impeachment came down to whether Clinton had violated the
``the rule of law'' that governs all Americans. Reps. Frank Riggs
of California and Heather Wilson of New Mexico said that to let
Clinton off the hook would show contempt for average citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice is blind so that every citizen will be treated equally
under the law,'' said Wilson, who announced that she would vote to
impeach because she could not ``turn from the truth and the
evidence that supports it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stenholm and other undecideds spent most of the day holed up in
their offices reviewing the House Judiciary Committee's
recommendation that Clinton be impeached or seeking the advice of
friends and constituents.
</P>
<P>
   A few members sought refuge on the crowded streets of the
nation's capital where they mingled for a time with government
workers and Christmas shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Some members ordered up historical information from the Library
of Congress on the 1868 impeachment of President Andrew Johnson and
parts of the criminal code dealing with perjury and obstruction of
justice. Others looked to the Bible for help.
</P>
<P>
   Stenholm chose ``all of the above'' to help him decide, said
spokeswoman Julie Turner. ``And one other thing ... He listened to
his constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other members of Congress, Stenholm's office had been
inundated with phone calls. Turner said the calls, emails and
letters _ hundreds each day _ from the predominantly Republican
17th District were running about 50/50 for and against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He considered everything. He went over every aspect of the
case. ... That's why his decision was so slow in coming,'' Turner
said.
</P>
<P>
   A few members took even longer.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Greenwood, R-Pa., who called himself ``one of the last
few holdouts,'' still had not revealed how he planned to vote by
late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood was spotted earlier in the day pausing for a moment
near a small nativity scene set up on the steps of the Capitol by
Rita Warren, whose business card identifies her as a ``prayer
specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Greenwood sought out Warren's advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
