<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PRODUCTS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Wis., Mass.)  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brenda J. Gondron didn't want to go. Neither did her husband.
And her employer wishes desperately that she were still at her
desk. But federal rules said there was no choice: She had to take a
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gondron is a vice president at Texas First Bank. A
little-known anti-embezzlement rule requires bank employees in
sensitive positions to be away from their desks and duties for two
consecutive weeks every year. The idea is to give any hanky-panky
they might be up to a chance to come to light while they are away.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gondron has been working overtime for months on the bank's
new computer system, and having her absent now is a real hardship,
said Matthew T. Doyle, the bank's chief executive, but no matter:
Off she had to go. And banks across the country are in the same
situation, chasing some of their most diligent workers out the door
to comply before the year ends.
</P>
<P>
   The decades-old vacation rule _ embodied in a supervisory
guidance letter from the Federal Reserve and echoed in many state
regulations _ had fallen into disuse, but was revived after several
blockbuster scandals in recent years, most notably the case of
Toshihide Iguchi, a workaholic bond trader at Daiwa Bank who
embezzled (and lost) $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classic profile of bank defalcators is that they don't
break for lunch, much less take vacations,'' said Ellen C. Lamb of
the Conference of State Banking Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   _ PAUL SWEENEY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out of La Crosse, Wis., comes a new product with truly dangerous
implications: The executive napping kit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the gift of sleeping on the job,'' says the announcement
from the Company Store, a division of Hanover Direct, a
specialty-catalog marketer, about an item it hopes will be ``most
welcome and practical'' in ``a sleep-deprived America.''
</P>
<P>
   The $89.99 kit consists of a foldable goose down-filled
``productivity pillow'' with pillow case and a copy of a book
called ``The Art of Napping,'' packaged in a monogrammable fabric
tote bag with shoulder strap that looks vaguely like a briefcase,
``for discreet carrying.''
</P>
<P>
   But the company seems to hope you won't need the camouflage. The
product announcement is full of quotations from academic sleep
experts and business trend watchers about the wondrous benefits of
a workday snooze and ``progressive nap policies'' at corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying book, written by a Boston University professor,
calls for mass protests in favor of sanctioned napping at work. The
battle cry: ``It's time for nappers to lie down and be counted.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
