<SLUG> BC-WHITTAKER-OFFER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDER MAKES OFFER ON WHITTAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. -- A shareholder of Whittaker Corp. on
Friday said he has made an unsolicited bid to buy the aerospace
parts company.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles investment banker Michael Tennenbaum, who holds
about 5 percent of Whittaker's stock, is offering to buy the
company for a reported $18.50 a share -- a $208 million total
value. Tennenbaum would not confirm the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   If successful in his bid, Tennenbaum said he expects to take
Whittaker private. He said he wants to keep Whittaker's management
in place, as partners.
</P>
<P>
   On news of the bid, Whittaker opened higher in trading Friday.
It touched a 52-week high of $16.625 during trading hours and
closed at $16.50, up $3.4375. Trading volume was 247,100 shares,
eight times the six-month daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker, which has rebounded from two fiscal years of losses,
had mentioned that it would entertain merger or acquisition offers.
</P>
<P>
   But company Chief Executive Officer Joseph Alibrandi said
Tennenbaum's offer was too low and it included a host of other
conditions such as an exclusivity period and breakup fees that
Whittaker didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   Alibrandi said offers for the company should start at more than
$20 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the company put together a ``poison pill''
shareholder rights plan to discourage hostile takeovers. The plan
would dilute severely the shares once an investor acquires 25
percent or more of the company, forcing him or her to negotiate
with the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make sure the shareholders get the best possible
price,'' Alibrandi said. ``It in no way precludes the company being
acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Key ingredients to a successful bid are a good price and a buyer
that would help Whittaker thrive, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker is exploring a merger or acquisition -- whether it's
the seller or the buyer -- to achieve greater business muscle to
better grow the company.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker has been on a rebound since Alibrandi came back. He
was called out of retirement in 1996 to rescue Whittaker from an
unprofitable attempt to diversify, said Brett Hendrickson, an
analyst at B. Riley &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After Alibrandi left Whittaker in 1994 to retire, his successor
diversified into network communications by first buying Hughes' LAN
Systems and afterward Xyplex, a network access company.
</P>
<P>
   Straying away from its core business of selling aerospace parts,
Whittaker piled on debt and bled red ink. In 1996, total debt stood
at $168 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's directors called back Alibrandi, who was building
his house in Malibu and getting involved in improving education in
California.
</P>
<P>
   He shut down the Hughes unit, except for a small operation that
served existing contracts, which was later sold when contract
obligations were met. Alibrandi sold Xyplex to Chatsworth,
Calif.-based MRV Communications and disposed of Whittaker's defense
electronics business.
</P>
<P>
   The gain from the sales: $53 million. By improving business,
Whittaker was able to pay down debt, which now stands at $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year ended October 1998, Whittaker made money for
the first time in two years: Profits were $48.5 million (or $3.98 a
share) on revenues of $131.5 million, compared with a loss of
$163.6 million ($14.68) on sales of $89.8 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the company back on track, Alibrandi will stay to guide it
for now. But once a merger or acquisition occurs, he said he might
reconsider his options. Beckoning to the 70-year-old is
California's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a strong interest in education,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
