<SLUG> BC-ARMED-RANGERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON PARK RANGERS WILL GET GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THOMAS SHAPLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ Washington park rangers will soon be armed for
the first time in the park system's 85-year history, the state
Parks and Recreation Commission decided Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the unanimous vote, commissioner Robert Petersen said he
had at first strongly opposed issuing sidearms to park rangers as a
response to growing crime and safety concerns, ``but I have had to
face the fact that the world has changed. We have to change, too. I
can see problems but I don't think there's any half-way ground
here. We have to bite the bullet and say `let's do it and let's do
it all the way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Going all the way meant arming all rangers, rather than arming
rangers in selected areas or increased staffing with unarmed
rangers.
</P>
<P>
   While the commission vote was ultimately unanimous, support for
the proposal is apparently less than unanimous among park users,
the general public and even park rangers.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Washington State University survey of park users
and the general public, there was a nearly equal split between
those favoring and opposing armed park rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The park rangers themselves are divided, according to a survey
by the Washington State Center for Information Services. When asked
what was ``the best option for your safety,'' 62 percent of those
responding chose the option of arming them all. Sixty-nine percent
said they'd had at least one incident in the past two years in
which they feared for their safety because they didn't have a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the state Parks and Recreation Department
recommended the action. They said many of the state's 250 park
rangers work alone at night in remote areas, where backup from
police or sheriff's deputies is 30 minutes away. In 1995, 27
rangers were involved in physical tussles with park visitors. Only
one ranger was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Park rangers in Washington and 34 other states have full law
enforcement authority, but only Washington and Michigan don't
authorize rangers to carry firearms. Washington rangers now carry
handcuffs, pepper spray and batons. They also are issued body
armor.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for firearms to be issued only to rangers who
``meet established law enforcement standards ... psychological and
enhanced background checks, and agency fitness standards and who
choose to go through firarms trasition training.'' For those who
are unable to meet those standards or who choose not to carry a
firearm, ``staff will redefine work activities.''
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
