u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-RAMADAN-1219-1ST     12-18 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RAMADAN-1219-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 2nd, 9th grafs, clarifies to that Al Adel is section of
Baghdad . . .
 &HT;    FOR IRAQIS, RAMADAN ALSO SIGNALS CHANCE FOR VENGEANCE with
US-IRAQ-1219.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ High above a house that has been gutted by one of the
most feared weapons known to modern warfare, four figures gestured
towards the pink sunset Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   In a tower of the neighborhood mosque, in the Al Adel section of
Baghdad, they looked for a crescent moon to deliver salvation an
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   After all, air war or not, this is the custom as the Muslim holy
period of Ramadan approaches. According to tradition, when a
follower finds the first sliver of the new moon, the month of
fasting and piety begins.
</P>
<P>
   So, in addition to the distant rumble of missile explosions and
the popping of anti-aircraft guns that occasionally sounded over
Baghdad Friday, there was a series of cannon blasts to officially
announce the beginning of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   In most years, that would mean that following morning would
start the month of daytime fasting to mark when the prophet
Mohammed received the Koran from God. This year, it could mean
relief from nightly missile attacks from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. President Bill Clinton has said he resorted to air strikes
to set back Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's ability to build
weapons of mass destruction, but he wanted to avoid attacking
during Ramadan for fear of offending the world's more than 1
billion Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Friday, Pentagon officials would not say whether
the start of Ramadan will indeed bring an end to the air strikes by
U.S. and British forces.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqis, anyway, do not believe that the holy period figures into
American decision making. Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
called such claims ``an insult to Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   Any Muslim can report the sighting of the new moon, which must
be done in the minutes after sundown and witnessed. The sighting is
then certified by religious authorities here and in Saudi Arabia.
The men in Baghdad's Al Adel mosque did not see the moon Friday,
perhaps obscured by clouds. But other Iraqis did, as did Saudis.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the appearance of the new moon served to emphasize
the religious filter through which any action in the Middle East is
viewed, especially war. For centuries, even the most bitter enemies
have ceased fire for Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   There is an irony in that Iraq is a highly secular nation
compared to most other Arab countries. Alcohol is sold openly, and
women can wear Western styles of clothing. Saddam has a history of
especially tough repression of religious Muslims, though several
years ago he added the words, ``Allah is Great,'' to the Iraqi
flag.
</P>
<P>
   Many Muslims opposed Saddam in his past aggressions, including
attacks on fellow Muslims in Kuwait and Iran. But to many Iraqis,
encouraged by officials seeking to drive a wedge between the United
States and Arab countries, the missiles falling on Iraq have
nothing to do with United Nations weapons inspections. They are an
attempt by the Americans to wipe out the Arabs and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Ramadan will come and God will pour his anger on these
aggressors,'' said 30-year-old auto parts salesman Abdel Hakeem,
after descending the dark spiral staircase in the minaret at the
Taqwa'a mosque -- roughly translated as ``the mosque of those who
fear God.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his friends say Clinton is a modern crusader bent on
conquering and persecuting Muslims as European crusaders did in the
11th Century.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam, on the other hand, they say, leads the Arab effort to
destroy Jews and that is why Clinton opposes him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a theme also sounded by Deputy Prime Minister Aziz in a
press conference Friday, repeatedly saying Clinton is backed by a
``Zionist clique'' out to make war on Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
