<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT GETS TROJANS REFOCUSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As USC's football team returned to practice Friday
for the first time in six days, coach Paul Hackett admitted that
the Trojans' conditioning is his biggest concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in horrible shape,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as bad as it sounds, however, because Hackett said
there is more than ample time to fix that after USC took most of
this week off because of final exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 10 days to get ready,'' Hackett said. ``It's enough.
I don't think the preparation of what we do is going to be a
problem. I think the priority was clear-cut this week. The
classroom, academic side of it were most important. Monday, the
priority shifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 players missed Friday's practice taking finals. USC's
last day of finals is Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like a spring practice,'' linebacker David Gibson
said. ``We're worrying about getting into shape.''
</P>
<P>
   One player who didn't practice Friday was offensive lineman
Travis Claridge, who's been suffering from the flu.
</P>
<P>
   __ Iacenda released: Hackett said that former Hart High School
running back Ted Iacenda has been formally given his release from
the university and is free to transfer to another school.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda, who left the team two weeks ago, would like to transfer
to a Division I-A school.
</P>
<P>
   __ Claiborne's unanimous: USC linebacker Chris Claiborne was
named to The Sporting News All-American team, which made him a
unanimous All-American. Claiborne is the first Trojans linebacker
to be a unanimous selection, and USC's first overall since wide
receiver Keyshawn Johnson in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   __ Big weekend: USC has about 12 recruits on campus this
weekend, the Trojans' biggest recruiting weekend to date.
</P>
<P>
   __ Number change: The Sun Bowl should be quarterback Carson
Palmer's last game wearing No. 15. He will switch to No. 3 next
season, the same number he wore in high school.
</P>
<P>
   __ No news: Although offensive coordinator Hue Jackson's name
has popped up for a similar position at California, Jackson said he
has not talked to Cal coach Tom Holmoe about the position.
</P>
<P>
   Cal offensive coordinator Doug Cosbie resigned last month, and
Jackson was the Bears' offensive coordinator in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
