<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-IRAQ     12-18 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR STRIKES CONTINUE AS SADDAM REMAINS DEFIANT
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS and LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Pressing their high-tech air strikes against Iraq
into the first hours of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan on
Saturday, U.S. and British forces pounded Iraqi defense,
communications and oil facilities in a campaign to shatter the
spine of Baghdad's military regime.
</P>
<P>
   As dawn broke, operation Desert Fox continued after more than 75
targets had been destroyed or badly damaged during the night by
cruise missiles and guided bombs fired from warships and an aerial
armada that has flown more than 200 sorties since Wednesday, the
Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's attacks included the first-ever combat mission of the
$200 million B-1 strategic bomber, built during the Cold War to fly
high-speed, low-level missions deep into the heart of the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Friday, U.S. and British forces had suffered no
casualties, according to the Pentagon, though Iraq claimed that at
least 30 people had been killed in Baghdad alone.
</P>
<P>
   In his first direct address since the bombing began Wednesday
night, Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein went on television Friday
night to urge his countrymen to stand strong in the face of an
onslaught they've thus far been powerless to defend against.
</P>
<P>
   ``By God's will, you will be victorious,'' Saddam, dressed in an
olive-drab military uniform, said in a ten-minute taped address. He
vowed not to ''compromise or kneel'' to his adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't know where Saddam was during the continuing strikes.
He owns some 80 palaces around the country and keeps his movements
secretive for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   But his Deputy Prime Minister, Tariq Aziz, told reporters in
Baghdad that Saddam was ``in good shape, thank God,'' despite air
strikes targeting a number of his residences.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we are witnessing is not a military conflict,'' said
Aziz. ''It's a criminal aggression by the United States and Britain
against Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters
that Saddam was not the target of the continuing air strikes. By
diminishing his military and intelligence strength, however, the
air campaign was clearly striking at the heart of Saddam's grip on
power.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not seeking to destabilize his regime,'' said Cohen.
''We are seeking to prevent him from in any way
</P>
<P>
   compromising this operation and from communicating under these
circumstances with his other forces (which)
</P>
<P>
   could pose a threat to our pilots who continue to conduct
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, U.S. and British forces continued pummeling Iraq's
surface-to-air missile (SAM) sites and related radar and
communications gear needed to effectively operate them.
</P>
<P>
   As of midday Friday, some 27 such sites had been attacked and
either seriously damaged or completely destroyed, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The southern Iraq air defense system has been degraded,''
Cohen said, reducing the risk of U.S. pilots being targeted by
Iraq's Soviet-era SAMs. ''We have not had SAMs fired at the
aircraft to our knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said raids have also targeted:
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters buildings and barracks of the Republican Guard, an
elite military group central to Saddam's control of the country and
active in trying to conceal Iraq's efforts to manufacture weapons
of mass destruction;
</P>
<P>
   Missile production, repair, research and development sites
integral to Iraq's ability to launch weapons of mass destruction
against its neighbors, and;
</P>
<P>
   An oil refinery in the southern port of Basra that Cohen said
had been used by Saddam to circumvent United Nations restrictions
on Iraqi oil exports.
</P>
<P>
   When he launched the attacks earlier this week, President
Clinton said he was sensitive to the start of Ramadan, an annual
month of daytime fasting and prayer recognized by Muslims around
the world. But neither he nor Cohen pledged to end the air strikes
before the religious period began early Saturday in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has said that the attacks would end after the U.S. and
British forces work their way through a pre-set list of targets.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't comment on the length of the operation,'' Cohen said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to pin down Iraqi troops near the Kuwaiti border south of
Baghdad, U.S. forces dropped thousands of leaflets warning the
soldiers _ in their native Arabic _ to stay put or face the threat
of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It basically said 'Stay where you are, stay put, do not
threaten anyone and you will not be hit,''' U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff Chairman Gen. Hugh Shelton told reporters during a Pentagon
briefing. Pentagon officials have expressed concern that Saddam
might send his tank forces toward Kuwait or Saudi Arabia in an
attempt to draw the United States into a land battle.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad during Saturday's pre-dawn darkness, an intense
volley of missile attacks and anti-aircraft fire sent plumes of
flames and streaks of light across the skies. A cruise missile was
seen streaking above a downtown avenue and slamming into a
building.
</P>
<P>
   By 4:45 a.m. Saturday, the pounding had subsided. Roosters and
the call to prayer over a mosque amplifier echoed through the city.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi authorities continued to restrict the movements of foreign
journalists. Reporters were taken on guided tours where Iraqi
officials showed them selected examples of damage from the air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad itself seemed largely untouched by the attacks. Some
government buildings were heavily damaged, but there did not appear
to be much to civilian structures. Electricity and phones appeared
to work throughout the city, and television and radio stations
continued to broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the attacks on Iraq, President Clinton spent Friday
girding for a series of impeachment votes Saturday in the House of
Representatives. But Cohen said the political troubles of the
commander in chief would have no bearing on the tasks of the troops
in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those people involved in this operation are focused on one
thing, and that's carrying out the mission,'' Cohen told reporters.
''Whatever else is going on at this particular moment is probably
of little concern to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the air campaign on Wednesday after months of
frustration with Iraq's obstruction of United Nations inspection
teams charged with verifying the destruction of Iraq's chemical and
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   While Saddam claims he has no such weapons, U.N. inspectors have
never been able to verify that and evidence continues to surface
suggesting that Iraq continues to build and stockpile arms that can
kill indiscriminately with lethal chemicals and deadly germs.
</P>
<P>
   (White House correspondent Bob Deans reported from Washington.
Middle east correspondent Larry Kaplow reported from Baghdad).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
