<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUDGE HIGGINBOTHAM'S PATH; WILLIAM GADDIS' PROSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Dec.19:
</P>
<P>
   The son of a cleaning woman and a laborer, raised in a
segregated New Jersey town, A. Leon Higginbotham Jr. rose to become
a respected federal appellate judge and legal historian. His
productive career following his 1993 retirement from the bench
spanned the worlds of Harvard University, where he taught, and the
corporate boards on which he served, including that of The New York
Times Company.
</P>
<P>
   But Higginbotham, who died this week at age 70, never forgot his
roots, or his personal debt to the civil rights movement that
opened doors of opportunity long shut for African-Americans. From
Higginbotham's early struggle to overcome poverty and racial
discrimination came a lifelong commitment to civil rights and
social justice that shone through his judicial writings and his
works of scholarship. Over the years, the judge tried to repay the
teachers who helped him by acting as a mentor to talented black
lawyers. Their contributions to the law and society are an ongoing
part of his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In his final years, Higginbotham's passionate opposition to the
dismantling of affirmative action programs saw him attack the
conservative legal views of Justice Clarence Thomas with a ferocity
that even some of his friends questioned. But Higginbotham was
acting out of a deeply felt concern about reversing the nation's
march toward racial justice.
</P>
<P>
   READING WILLIAM GADDIS
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty William Gaddis presents to a reader is this:
learning to follow the mercurial glance of a writer who gives you
no warning where he will look next but who always looks with rapt
attention and who commands raptness in the language itself.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gaddis is dead at 75. He was never as aloof as Thomas
Pynchon, and the outline of his life makes an interesting narrative
in its own right. But the one essential thing to know about Gaddis
can only be found in his prose.
</P>
<P>
   He published four novels, ``The Recognitions,'' ``JR,''
``Carpenter's Gothic'' and ``A Frolic of His Own.'' Each of them is
at once dour and baldly funny, ironic and scarifying. But only an
intrinsically hopeful man ever made prose like Gaddis', so
self-aware, so unyielding and, for a reader who is happy not to
insist on a swift denouement, so generous. In Gaddis, every
sentence is its own denouement, and that is more attention to the
world and its linguistic echo than many readers can stand.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to reading Gaddis is to read the words one at a time,
one after another, just as he arranged them. That is all the
difficulty there is, and beyond it lies a sprawling, worldly
entertainment. Before he died, Gaddis had finished a new novel. May
it be as fat and rich as his early works, as fat and rich as ``Don
Quixote'' itself.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
