<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER WELCOMES CHALLENGE   OF THE WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects Ann Arbor to East Lansing in lede)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Anson Carter went to school at Michigan State in East
Lansing, slightly more than an hour outside Detroit. He never went
to Red Wings games, though. And he'd watch on television only if
one of his friends was facing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at the other team,'' Carter said. ``I try to
focus on my own team.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's team is the Bruins, and Saturday night, they'll be
focusing on the Red Wings _ the mighty Red Wings, that is, winners
of the last two Stanley Cups and 5-3 conquerors of Boston Wednesday
in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Carter took note of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they have a lot of experience and they're pretty deep
in talent,'' he said. But he also knows something about his club:
``If we're playing well, we're tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   And he acknowledges that the presence of the Wings gets the
juices flowing, even if that wasn't the case in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get pumped up because of their Stanley Cup
championships,'' he said. ``Every night you try to get pumped up
just because you're in the National Hockey League and you have to.
Anybody can beat anybody on any given night. The fact that they're
the Stanley Cup champions does make you a little more fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   But he won't be hyperventilating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to play within yourselves,'' Carter said. ``Sometimes
less is more. If you get fired up too much, you tend to try to do
too much and give something up and get in a hole it's tough to
battle back from.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now Carter is trying to battle back from a slump. He has 3
goals and 9 points in 16 games after missing the first 12 in a
contract dispute, and Friday before practice, coach Pat Burns had a
talk with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see a little bit more from Anson,'' Burns said.
``I think he worries too much about everything else that goes
around him instead of making it a simple game. He's such a good
skater, a strong individual, he's got to skate down the wing and
take the shot to the net and go to the net. You can't defense
against those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter isn't overly concerned by his numbers. ``I try to play in
all three zones,'' he said, ``and if I do that, points will come.
I'm doing a lot of things well, to tell you the truth. I just carry
the puck in my danger zones, and sometimes I'm playing left wing,
sometimes right wing, and sometimes center. I've got to make sure I
stay sharp mentally because my role can change from shift to shift.
I've got to be ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame Carter's slump on missing training camp. He got in
plenty of work skating with Michigan State, Team Canada, trainer
T.R. Goodman, and the International Hockey League's Utah Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right when I got here, I felt I was ready to go,'' Carter
said. ``All the coaching staff did a tremendous job in preparing
for the season. It was a learning experience with Utah. It wasn't
the NHL but just a step below it. It did a good job of preparing me
for the NHL level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHL players are the best in the world _ faster, bigger,
and stronger. But it's hockey no matter where you go. It's moving
two feet and playing in game situations.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knows the Red Wings bring it to another level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
