<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON BUSINESS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS BACKERS STILL CHEERING GOP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are already debating whether their impeachment drive
will backfire in the 2000 elections. But they appear unlikely to
suffer defections by business leaders who back them. ``I'm proud of
the Republicans, in the face of the polls, doing what they think is
right,'' said Robert Mosbacher, President Bush's secretary of
Commerce and a Houston oilman.
</P>
<P>
   David H. Koch, a senior officer of Koch Industries, the nation's
second-largest private firm, says an ouster of President Clinton,
far from rattling the economy, might aid it. ``After Nixon was
removed from office, there was a huge improvement in morale,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some other leading Republican donors late last week were pushing
for a less radical solution. ``I would be satisfied, thinking about
the short-term interests of the country and the economy in
particular, with censure,'' said Harlan Crow, the Dallas
real-estate magnate. ``I'd like to have it over quickly.'' But,
with his 3-year-old son calling the president a liar when he sees
him on TV, Crow acknowledges having second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, head of the Center for Responsive Politics in
Washington, sees signs that even business leaders who have
questioned the Republicans' case might come to see the president's
resignation or removal as the quickest way to stability. `` `Enough
already' has helped the president,'' Makinson said. Should the
House vote to impeach, he added, ``that could kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Allen R. Myerson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SILVER CUPS DON'T RUN OVER  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Victor Niederhoffer, the money manager who lost all his shirts
last year, marvels that his silver-trophy collection barely fetched
the price of a ``mediocre Impressionist painting.'' Sotheby's
raised $2.6 million Tuesday, in the middle range of its estimate.
``Apples and oranges,'' Kevin Tierney, the Sotheby's silver guru,
said of the comparison. ``Everybody, after all, can recognize a
Renoir over the mantlepiece.''
</P>
<P>
   The prize piece, a five-foot horn of plenty once owned by
Sweden's King Charles XV, was bought by an Ecuadorean collector for
$140,000. Niederhoffer said he didn't make a profit on the sale and
would use the proceeds to repay debts and cover college tuition
costs for his six children. He says he held onto just one item, the
Manchester Cup, bestowed upon the winner of the Steeple Chase in
Manchester, England, in 1904, to serve as a mascot for his new
firm, Manchester Trading LLC. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A PERILOUS PARALLEL FOR RUBIN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For almost as long as Robert E. Rubin has been Treasury
secretary, there have been rumors that he was about to leave his
post. His cabinet colleagues were convinced this summer he would be
gone by year-end if the markets only calmed. Then Russia's economy
collapsed, Wall Street swooned and Brazil needed a quick $40
billion. But after the Democrats' strong showing in November and
the Dow's comeback, the rumors resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Rubin has shrugged off the reports, saying he
plans to be around ``for some time'' _ defining ``some time'' with
the same fuzziness he reserves for discussion of exchange-rate
policy. Now, with the executive branch in turmoil, the assumption
at Treasury is that he cannot jump ship. So does Rubin feel like
Hugh McCulloch, President Andrew Johnson's Treasury secretary, who
not only stuck out the impeachment hearings but engineered a huge
tax cut along the way?
</P>
<P>
   The other afternoon, Rubin conceded that he has given little
thought to McCulloch. But wandering over to a framed print over the
credenza in his office, bearing the pictures of all past Treasury
secretaries, he declared: ``Here he is. Pleasant-looking fellow.''
McCulloch did a return run as Treasury secretary under Chester A.
Arthur in 1884-85. When Rubin heard that, he cringed.
</P>
<P>
   _ David E. Sanger &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IVORY TOWER RETIREMENT POWER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIAA-CREF, the private pension fund for teachers, urges schools
to put new hires into their retirement plans from Day One, even
though its own employees have to wait five years before they
qualify for benefits. But that seeming contradiction doesn't bother
John H. Biggs, the fund's chief executive. Professors at many
institutions often have to switch jobs to reach the Holy Grail of
tenure, he reasons, leaving fewer years for accumulating benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get them in right away,'' he said. By
contrast, many TIAA-CREF workers are clerical workers or people
right out of high school or college, who haven't yet settled on a
career. ``It's a different job market,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ David Cay Johnston &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
