<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      12-18 1770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SETS STAGE FOR IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unswayed by military conflict, House Republicans
Friday launched a determined final push for President Clinton's
impeachment in a showdown that bordered on a political morality
play.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's career at a perilous crossroads, the House surged
toward approving at least one article of impeachment Saturday
stemming from the president's extramarital affair with former White
House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Only a ``miracle'' will prevent Clinton's impeachment, his top
allies said, as Representative Henry J. Hyde, chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, vowed that GOP leaders will ``keep our
appointment with history'' by recommending the president's removal
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, apparently hoping to deliver the miracle
her husband will need, urged the country to ``practice
reconciliation'' and made plans to appear at the Capitol Saturday
for a Democratic caucus before the historic vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people's trust has been betrayed,'' Hyde said Friday at
the start of a climactic, 12-hour debate on Clinton's fate. ``Let's
declare unmistakably that perjury and obstruction of justice
disqualify a man from retaining the presidency of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats plan to walk out of the House chamber en masse
in protest Saturday after they are denied a vote on a censure
alternative. They intend to return in time to vote against the
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's debate, Democrats decried the GOP's
pro-impeachment juggernaut as an obsessive crusade aimed at staging
a bloodless coup against Clinton as the latest act of retribution
in a partisan struggle that has roiled since the fall of President
Richard M. Nixon in the Watergate era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are permitting a constitutional coup d'etat that will haunt
this body and the country forever,'' said Representative Edward J.
Markey, a Malden Democrat. ``A constitutional clause intended to
apply to a Benedict Arnold selling out his country will now be
expanded to cover every personal transgression.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the origin of the charges, a consensual sexual
relationship, Representative Barney Frank, a Newton Democrat, said,
``This House is launched on an historically tragic case of
selective moralizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders refused to postpone the debate despite
Democratic complaints that they could undermine the ongoing US
attack on Iraq by orchestrating what Representative Ike Skelton of
Missouri portrayed as ``the political decapitation of the commander
in chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they could agree on little else, members of both
parties agreed the impeachment clash coincided with the steady
decline of American political standards. The debate unfolded the
morning after the speaker-designate, Robert L. Livingston,
acknowledged his extramarital affairs following Roll Call
newspaper's disclosure of his infidelity on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In the bitter aftermath, Republicans accused Clinton's allies of
clandestinely engineering the episode, while Democrats said GOP
leaders are so bent on bringing down Clinton that they have
overzealously pursued charges stemming from the Lewinsky episode.
``The politics of smear and slash and burn must end,'' said House
Democratic leader Richard A. Gephardt, prompting a standing ovation
from lawmakers in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to turn away from extremism and inquisition and return
to a sense of moderation in our political system,'' Gephardt added
in pleading unsuccessfully for a vote on a censure alternative to
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Amid moments of high drama Friday, laced with seething tensions,
there were tears, jeers, and cheers, acrimony and anxiety. A week
before Christmas, the standoff stretched through the wintry day
after the House chaplain, the Rev. James D. Ford, opened the
proceedings by praying for love, unity, and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, a Lutheran minister, read the Prayer of St. Francis of
Assisi, which he later said former speaker Thomas P. O'Neill Jr.
once told him was a sign that a grave issue was facing the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monsignor,'' Ford quoted O'Neill as telling him once, ``when
the going gets tough, you always reach for St. Francis.''
</P>
<P>
   The House impeachment debate is the first since the post-Civil
War era, when President Andrew Johnson survived a highly partisan
Senate trial in 1868 by a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces four charges in House Resolution 611: two counts
of perjury and one each of obstruction of justice and abuse of
power. The House is scheduled to vote on each article Saturday and
is expected to pass at least one perjury count by a narrow margin,
almost entirely on party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resolved that William Jefferson Clinton, president of the
United States, is impeached for high crimes and misdemeanors and
that the following articles of impeachment be exhibited to the
United States Senate,'' the House reading clerk, Paul Hayes, said
solemnly to open the historic debate.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, dozens of Republicans strode to a wooden
podium to declare Clinton unfit for office because of allegations
that he engaged in an elaborate effort to cover up his affair with
Lewinsky. Many of them had withheld their opinions until Friday,
and none delivered good news for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the drumbeat of calls for Clinton's resignation
quickened during the day, even among several Democrats who have
said they oppose his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's behavior has been deplorable, reprehensible,
and immoral,'' said Representative William O. Lipinski, an Illinois
Democrat who plans to vote against the impeachment charges. ``I
think it would be best for the country if he would resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore downplayed the chance of Clinton
resigning. ``I think the results of a meteor strike are more likely
than the resignation of the president,'' Gore said. ``He is just
not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In another setback for the White House, Representative Paul
McHale of Pennsylvania became the fourth Democrat to say he will
support Clinton's impeachment. Clinton also lost a key swing
Democrat, Representative Charles W. Stenholm of Texas, who said,
``It is clear that the president's actions are sufficient to charge
him with high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton picking up no undeclared member who had not been
expected to back him, his top allies abandoned all pretense that he
might elude impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, asked about the best development that Clinton's
supporters could hope for Friday, said, ``A flood.''
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, the White House began gauging Clinton's
support in the Senate, where he is believed to have the 34 votes he
would need to block impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet House Democrats spared little in their final assault on the
impeachment resolution and its Republican backers.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the showdown spilled into the stately speaker's
lobby, as Representative Patrick J. Kennedy, a Rhode Island
Democrat, angrily confronted one of the most ardent impeachment
advocates, Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, on the House floor, had accused Clinton of committing ``a
frontal assault on the Constitution'' and had quoted President John
F. Kennedy as saying, ``Americans are free to disagree with the
law, but not to disobey it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kennedy, the president's nephew, stepped into a throng
of reporters who were interviewing Barr and cited the Georgian's
address last year to a group that promotes white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Barr, anybody who has been to a racist crowd like that has
no right invoking my uncle's memory,'' Kennedy shouted.
</P>
<P>
   The two exchanged several gibes before Kennedy stormed off.
``The nerves are a little bit raw,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said later, ``When you have people with racist
backgrounds like that invoking my uncle and railroading this
president, I guess you can say tensions are high and frustrations
are great.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the debate alternately had the flavor of a dime-store
romance, a detective novel, a constitutional law thesis, and a
partisan position paper. There was wrangling over intimate details
of the Lewinsky affair, the four-year investigation of Clinton by
the independent counsel, and weighty issues involving the
separation of powers and world affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In defending the refusal to permit a censure alternative,
Representative F. James Sensenbrenner Jr., a Wisconsin Republican,
cited a 1970s account of Watergate that quoted O'Neill as telling
the Republican leader at the time that he was ``bitterly opposed''
to allowing a censure vote on an impeachment resolution against
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a South Boston
Democrat and longtime friend of O'Neill, to the House floor. ``In
1974, when Richard Nixon was being considered for impeachment,''
Moakley said, ``Thomas P. O'Neill was not speaker of the House.
Carl Albert was. Furthermore, no resolution to impeach President
Nixon ever came to the House. President Nixon resigned before that
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, the president met for an hour at the White House
with Representative Christopher Shays of Connecticut, one of the
few undeclared Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   As day turned to night and the House spectator galleries began
to thin, two Massachusetts Democrats who serve on the Judiciary
Committee _ Representatives William D. Delahunt of Quincy and
Martin T. Meehan of Lowell _ spearheaded Clinton's legal defense
amid unrelenting criticism from Republican lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Both are former county prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we prepare to render our verdict on President Clinton, the
American people, and history itself, are sitting in judgment on
us,'' Delahunt said. ``And I believe they will judge us harshly
because we have failed in our duty to the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan struck a similar theme: ``I am sick at heart, for I fear
that the words used to describe the Johnson impeachment will come
to characterize what this House is about to do _ impeach based not
on reason but on rancor.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II, a Brighton Democrat who did
not seek reelection, is one of nearly 40 House members who will
cast their final House votes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, he attributed the impeachment crisis to a
group of conservative House Republicans ``who cannot find
forgiveness'' for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so sorry the final vote I cast here on the House floor is
going to be on an issue that is so partisan in nature,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
