<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-18 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S DAY OF RECKONING AT HAND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in 130 years, the House on
Friday began debating the impeachment of a president, deliberations
heavy with bitter, partisan rhetoric against a backdrop of
international crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Poised to impeach President Clinton for trying to conceal his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, Republicans
invoked their duty to uphold the Constitution, while his Democratic
defenders condemned the proceedings as unfair and counter to the
will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the four articles of impeachment _ two accuse Clinton
of perjury, one alleges obstruction of justice, and one accuses him
of abuse of office _ were set for a vote before noon, EST,
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of sex. Sexual misconduct and adultery are
private acts and are none of the Congress' business,'' said
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill. ``The matter before
the House is a question of willful, premeditated, deliberate
corruption of the nation's system of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt said the House GOP
leadership had rejected the course of ``moderation'' and ``common
sense'' by refusing consideration of a censure resolution, an
alternative favored by Democrats and two dozen moderate
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to vote your vote of conscience and I respect that
right,'' the Missouri Democrat said to the Republicans, who hold a
228-206 majority. ``All we're asking for is that we get to vote our
conscience,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   While House members debated into the late hours Friday, the
president was monitoring U.S. air strikes against Iraq. For the
third day, U.S. air and naval forces attacked Iraqi military
targets.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N.-sanctioned strikes began Wednesday, which angered
Republicans when House leaders decided to delay the impeachment
debate set for Thursday. Less than 24 hours later, GOP leaders,
worried that holiday plans by some members might reduce their slim
edge, decided to forge ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the nation emerged from the Civil War, when Andrew
Johnson was in the White House, has a president been accused of
``high crimes and misdemeanors,'' the constitutional standard for
removal. Johnson was impeached by the House, but the Senate fell
one vote short of the two-thirds needed to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the House Judiciary Committee recommended articles of
impeachment against President Nixon in the wake of the Watergate
scandal. A week later, before the full House took up the matter,
Nixon resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, a telephone survey of House members by The
Associated Press found 219 lawmakers saying they would support at
least one article of impeachment, one more than the majority needed
to send the president's case to the Senate. Another 201 members
were opposed.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times/CBS News Poll released Friday found 62 percent
of Americans want their representatives to vote against
impeachment. By a 2-1 margin, Americans said the debate should have
been delayed until the Iraqi showdown was over. At the same time,
six in 10 Americans said Republicans in Congress were out of touch
with the public's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also shows 40 percent of Americans saying it would be
better for the country if Clinton resigns should the House impeach
him.
</P>
<P>
   Reconciled to being impeached, Clinton and his lawyers have
turned their attention to preparing his defense before the Senate,
White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president was considering making a statement after
Saturday's voting, aides said. Before the vote, House Democrats
were anticipating a private meeting at the Capitol with first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has vowed repeatedly not to resign, and Vice President
Al Gore on Friday renewed that vow, saying ``the results of a
meteor strike are more likely than the resignation of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who would assume the presidency if Clinton
quits or is removed before his term expires in January 2001, said
Republicans are ``dead wrong'' to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said in an interview with the American Urban Radio network:
``And they (the Republicans) think people are not going to remember
this. Well I think they may be dead wrong about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Debate on the four articles of impeachment began shortly after
the House convened at 9 a.m. EST, but not before the Republican
majority had to turn back, 225-183, a move by Democrats to adjourn
until Iraq air strikes cease.
</P>
<P>
   Once the parliamentary debate began, many members drifted into
the cloak rooms, corridors or to their offices to watch the
proceedings by television. For most of the day, the public
galleries were half full. Shortly before noon, the lines of
tourists waiting to get into the Capitol to watch the historic
debate were shorter that the lines of people waiting to get into
the National Gallery to see the Van Gogh exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the debate, presiding officer Rep. Ray LaHood,
R-Ill., read from the House rules about prohibitions against
engaging in ``generally personal, abusive language toward the
president, and also in engaging in comparisons to personal conduct
of sitting members'' of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Loud groans and hisses rose from the Democratic side. Rep.
Albert Wynn, D-Md., said, ``The hypocrisy of the situation speaks
for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the last use of the word hypocrisy, a not-so-veiled
reference to Speaker-elect Bob Livingston's confession Thursday
night to several instances of carrying on sexual affairs and
misleading a reporter who raised questions about the Louisiana
lawmaker's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day, Livingston was missing from the House
chamber. He was expected to address his colleagues Saturday. Also
missing from the debate is current Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.,
who is quitting the House at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Their absence was noted by Rep. Lloyd Doggett, a Texas Democrat
who said he and most Americans are ``disgusted'' with the GOP
refusal to consider a resolution rebuking the president instead of
impeaching him. Doggett characterized the proceedings ``as so
shameful that neither ... Mr. Gingrich or Mr. Livingston will
preside'' over the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, a Texas Republican, said: ``Whatever happens,
whether the president is impeached or not, our nation will endure.
We are a strong people, and we have a Constitution that works.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Rep. John Conyers, the ranking Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee, who served in Congress during Watergate,
accused the GOP leadership of misusing impeachment in its effort to
end Clinton's presidency. ``Impeachment was designed to rid this
nation of traitors and tyrants, not attempts to cover up an
extramarital affair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate at times was emotional as lawmakers shuffled to the
microphone, some reading from remarks they had written in longhand,
others from typed notes with revisions scribbled in the margins.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Dickey, a Republican who represents the area of Arkansas
where Clinton grew up, was near tears as he defended his decision
to support impeachment over the objections of many Arkansans. ``The
issue today is no longer the character of Bill Clinton, it is about
the character of the nation,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   While LaHood made frequent use of his gavel to maintain decorum
in the House chamber, his authority did not extend to nearby
corridors where Democrats railed about the Republican witch hunt
and lynch mobs. GOP members angrily accused the White House of
feeding the news media tips about Livingston's adultery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 2256EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
