<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STUMPEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUMPEL'S SLUMP HAS KINGS STUMPED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ He arrived and immediately performed as
advertised, instantly becoming the Kings' best center since they'd
traded a guy named Wayne Gretzky a couple of years before that.
</P>
<P>
   But as the midway point of Jozef Stumpel's second season as a
King draws near, the memories of his impressive arrival grow dim,
almost as dim as the hopes the Kings (8-19-3) have of reaching the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel's statistics limp off the page: One goal in the 17 games
this season. Two goals in the final 21 regular-season games last
year. One goal in the playoffs. Four goals in his last 42 games
overall.
</P>
<P>
   And he's supposed to be the Kings' best and most important
offensive player.
</P>
<P>
   There have been injuries, to be sure, and the 26-year-old
Stumpel's reputation has been built more on passing than shooting.
But four goals in 42 games? Philadelphia's John LeClair and Florida
rookie Mark Parrish each scored that many this season _ in one
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying everything,'' said Stumpel, a native of Slovakia,
who had 22 goals last season and was 10th in NHL scoring with 79
points. ``It looks like nothing wants to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   The bummer of 42 began on Feb. 28, when Stumpel went without a
goal in a loss to the St. Louis Blues. One game became three and
then he was sidelined four games with a bruised kidney. When he
returned, he went goal-less five more games, and by the end of the
Kings' playoff run, Stumpel scored only three goals in 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the time, he doesn't shoot enough,'' said
Kings coach Larry Robinson, whose slumping team begins a three-game
trip tonight in St. Louis. ``He's always looking to make that next
play. That's his biggest problem. He's got a hell of a shot. He
just doesn't use it enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel's reluctance was evident in Thursday's 5-4 overtime loss
to the New York Islanders. He passed up a good scoring opportunity
late in the third period to make an extra pass that misfired. But
Robinson was displeased after the game with much more than Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's playing well, he's getting involved, jumping on
loose pucks, finishing checks,'' Robinson said. ``If he doesn't get
involved in the play, he's not at his best. When he's at his best,
he's playing physically and doing all those little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, who had 58 assists last season but has only five this
year, began the season injured, though he didn't tell anybody his
hip was bothering him until after he'd gone scoreless through four
games. He then was in and out of the lineup for more than a month,
with the hip injury and a sprained ankle, and his statistics
suffered as a result. But Robinson says injuries alone cannot be
blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting pretty much frustrated,'' Stumpel said. ``I can't
figure it out even myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is not the first time Stumpel has struggled
during his six-year NHL career. The biggest knock against him when
he was with Boston was a lack of consistency. During the 1995
lockout season, he scored just five goals in 44 games.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1996-97 season, in which he had 76 points, the Bruins
traded Stumpel and winger Sandy Moger to the Kings for center
Dmitri Khristich _ who is among the NHL's scoring leaders this
season _ and Byron Dafoe _ who has emerged as a top-flight goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the impetus for the deal was an impending contract
impasse between Stumpel and the Bruins. After the trade, Stumpel
signed a two-year, $3-million deal with the Kings that expires
after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Stumpel's struggles, Robinson remains patient, insisting
he expects his No. 1 center to snap out of his slump. ``Eventually,
the goals will go in,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Stumpel, ``I don't know what I should do. Maybe I should
close my eyes and shoot. If that's going to work, I'd do it every
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
