<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGTRDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS TRADE FOR AUDETTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. - Los Angeles Kings general manager Dave
Taylor beat the holiday roster freeze and improved his slumping
team at minimal cost Friday, acquiring the rights to veteran right
wing Donald Audette from the Buffalo Sabres for a second-round
draft choice in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, 29, has not played this season while trying to resolve
a contract dispute with the Sabres. The restricted free agent
signed a two-year, $3.6-million contract with the Kings after the
trade was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, who had 24 goals and 44 points for the defensive-minded
Sabres last year, is expected to be in the lineup tonight when the
Kings begin a three-game trip in St. Louis, and among the things he
brings is the right-handed shot that the team has needed to improve
its power play. With the additions of Audette and rookie right wing
Pavel Rosa - who scored two goals in his NHL debut Thursday - the
Kings have added two right-handed shots in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change my role,'' said the 5-foot-8,
184-pound Audette. ``I think my role is scoring goals, playing hard
and showing up every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said, ``I think he brings some qualities to the team that
we can use. He's a proven goal-scorer, he's good on the power play,
he plays with some grit and he goes to the net hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (8-19-3) have struggled all season, and most trade
speculation had focused on higher-profile players who were sitting
out for one reason or another while in disputes with their teams.
</P>
<P>
   But to acquire Vancouver holdout Pavel Bure, or New York
Islanders star Zigmund Palffy, the price would have been
considerably higher, in terms of dollars the Kings would have had
to pay Bure or Palffy and players the Kings would have had to give
up to complete a trade. Palffy signed a five-year, $25-million deal
with the Islanders on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some good young prospects in the system we don't
necessarily want to give up,'' said Taylor, adding that he does not
expect to make another deal before the eight-day holiday trading
freeze begins today.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, a native of Laval, Quebec, had a rather strange
holdout, at times seeking less money than the Sabres were offering
because, under terms of the NHL's collective bargaining agreement,
if he made below the league average, it ultimately would enable him
to become an unrestricted free agent. Audette said he at no point
believed he would have to sit out the entire season, a belief that
became reality with Friday's trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, I probably would have considered Europe,''
Audette said. ``But as long as we were talking to other teams, I
knew something would happen. I love the game too much to miss an
entire season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
