<HEADER>
A8118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-REACTIONS19-COX     12-18 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-REACTIONS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public reacts to Iraq invasion
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On a day when The History Channel could have
gone live _ impeachment here, bombing there _ life rolled along as
usual for the members of Alley Oops in their Friday Night Early
Birds league.
</P>
<P>
   Five people. One bowling team. A cross-section of what has
become the greatest divide in American politics, a rift far deeper
than Democrats vs. Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On one side: Who cares? On the other: Who couldn't?
</P>
<P>
   And during a period of bombs and bombshells, the division was a
bright line as the Alley Oops members _ folks who have bowled
together on Friday nights for almost two years but never talk
politics with each other _ tried to climb from eighth place in the
14-team league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay attention to any of it,'' said Michael Skurka, a
single, 38-year-old state computer specialist carrying a 150
average into Friday's competition. ``I heard about the bombing from
someone else. I don't pay any attention to the news.''
</P>
<P>
   He views the impeachment process as overpublicized,
``insignificant'' and ``irrelevant'' to his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will effect my life, but in a way I have no control over,''
said Skurka, expressing the views of the politically disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of talk that confounds teammate Merlene Taylor, a
65-year-old who spends much of her time doing water colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why people aren't interested in politics,''
said Taylor, who spent Friday night working on her 120 average at
Showplace Lanes in North Austin. ``It influences them in everything
they do. And it is going to influence us a lot if he gets
impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, an independent who voted for Bill Clinton in 1992 and
1996, said she believes that the president deserves punishment but
that the process should be put on hold until the bombing in Iraq is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Taylor, Merlene's husband and teammate, also can't
understand why so many people can't get interested in history being
played out live.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be off to the side for most people. That does
surprise me. People ought to be more interested because it does
have a direct effect on us, on the way our government runs,'' said
Jerry Taylor, a state employee whose Friday night goal was to pump
up his 138 average.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor votes Republican more often than not and did not vote for
Clinton in either race. He has watched some of the impeachment
proceedings. His wife said she has seen most of it.
</P>
<P>
   Willis Delhomme of Alley Oops, a Round Rock resident, security
supervisor and team leader with a 176 average, says he has watched
a little of the Iraqi bombing campaign, but none of the impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't interest me. It doesn't concern me for the simple
reason that if he would have come out with it the first time, we
wouldn't be going through all this malarkey, bullcorn, horse
hockey, whatever you want to call it,'' said Delhomme, 53.
</P>
<P>
   Just get it over with, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should drop it and leave it be,'' said Delhomme, who did
not vote for Clinton. ``It's costing us too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   Willis' wife, Shirley, a Round Rock school bus driver, fears the
impeachment process is talking time away from subjects that matter
to her, like education and care for the elderly. She has heard
little about the impeachment battle, but knows all she cares to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work, and I just don't pay attention to it because I don't
even want to know about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While many Americans are watching something they've never seen
before, Willis Delhomme is convinced it's nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turned into a sideshow,'' he said between frames. ``It
will come and go because just about every president we have had has
done some sort of thing like he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
