<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-FRESNOST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia, Fresno State limp to rematch
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In March, Georgia guard G.G. Smith enjoyed a career
game against Fresno State, scoring 27 points on a school-record
nine 3-pointers in the consolation game of the NIT in New York.
</P>
<P>
   When those teams meet again today in the Delta Air Lines Holiday
Classic for Kids in the Georgia Dome, both backcourts will be
hampered by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the Bulldogs' undisputed floor leader, has battled a
sprained right wrist for more than two weeks. Smith was hurt when
he fell over a basketball during halftime of Georgia's 63-47 win
over Furman on Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State senior Chris Herren, averaging 16.2 points and 7.5
assists, will miss the game with a severely sprained right ankle.
Fresno State coach Jerry Tarkanian is expected to start sophomore
Demetrius Porter or junior Shomario Richard in Herren's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a 5-foot-10 senior, will be looking to rebound after two
tough outings in which he scored a combined nine points on 2-of-12
shooting against Appalachian State and Georgia Tech. In Georgia's
first seven games, Smith hit 52 percent of his shots, including 16
of 32 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``G.G.'s got a sprained wrist, and he hasn't shot the ball well,
which I think has been noticeable,'' Bulldogs coach Ron Jirsa said.
``It hasn't kept him out of games, but it's a disappointing injury.
He was one of the hottest shooters in the country before that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa has backcourt help on the way, but freshmen Terrence
Edwards of Tennille and Shawn Fields of Lexington, both of whom
officially join the team today, won't play until Tuesday's game
against East Carolina in Stegeman Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a football signee, and Fields, who signed with Jirsa
last year but didn't academically qualify, will enroll at Georgia
for spring semester. Because the fall semester officially ended
Friday, however, both players are eligible to practice and play in
games beginning today.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs were left with only three scholarship guards _
Smith, senior Ray Harrison and freshman D.A. Layne _ after junior
Adrian Jones was lost for the season with a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is looking to bounce back from Sunday's 84-79 overtime
loss at Georgia Tech, in which the Bulldogs blew a 15-point lead in
the final eight minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important game for us to bounce back, especially since
we're getting another chance to play in Atlanta,'' Jirsa said. ``I
think last year we played an underrated team (West Virginia). ...
Fresno State is very athletic. We need to handle the ball well
against a team that presses and traps all over the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
