<HEADER>
A8148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SALTLAKE19-COX     12-18 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALTLAKE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SLOC starts self-inquiry
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Salt Lake City's Olympic organizing committee
empowered an ethics board Friday to determine if its bid for the
2002 Winter Games was tainted by bribery.
</P>
<P>
   The executive committee, meeting behind closed doors in a 5
1/2-hour emergency session, took great pains to demonstrate its bid
for integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member ethics board's investigation will be entirely
independent of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, chairman of the
board of trustees Robert Garff said.
</P>
<P>
   However, SLOC is funding the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The five members of the ethics board must report to the board of
trustees by Feb. 11 with their recommendations about the scandal
that erupted over a scholarship fund administered by the bid
committee. The International Olympic Committee, which is
investigating the acceptance of bribes by its members, hopes to
complete its own probe in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very united front,'' said Henry Marsh, a former
Olympic steeplechaser and member of the board of trustees. ``The
whole thing is we want everybody to know the facts, and we'll have
a totally independent group and counsel come out with them.
Everything's going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh said the meeting did not address details of the
scholarship fund, because that will be left to the investigating
board.
</P>
<P>
   He also defended Atlanta, another city implicated in the bribery
scandal by IOC vice president Marc Hodler. Marsh was an athlete
representative when Atlanta was bidding for the right to be the
U.S. representative for 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy (Payne, who headed the Atlanta organizing committee) was
such a class guy, he did everything right by the book,'' Marsh
said. SLOC is pledging full cooperation by its trustees, officers
and past and present employees, including Tom Welch, the former
SLOC head who developed the scholarship fund. Welch resigned in
1997 in the wake of a domestic abuse case.
</P>
<P>
   Welch was not present at the meeting Friday and did not phone
in, but he has promised to aid the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret any and all embarrassment this has caused the
citizens of the state of Utah,'' Garff said.
</P>
<P>
   He handled most questions at a press briefing while Frank
Joklik, the embattled president and CEO, calmly sat next to him.
Critics have called for Joklik and Dave Johnson, the vice president
implicated in the scholarship fund, to resign or be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Garff said that the committee has confidence in the two men
until the ethics panel reports, and said speculation would be
``premature and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department is also investigating the
allegations and prosecutions could follow.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Pace, a critic of the Games, brought refreshments to the
SLOC offices Friday: a cake with a file sticking out of it.
</P>
<P>
   John Ruger, an athlete representative on the board of trustees
believes that the Olympic movement will benefit from the scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this problem is taken care of, then future cities can bid
in an unfettered environment,'' he said. ``This could be very
positive in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, with the Games a little more than three years
away, securing sponsorships is imperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the steps that have been taken today by the executive
committee ... will be a matter of reassurance to sponsors,'' Joklik
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, board member Ken Bullock believes that big money is to
blame for the atmosphere that led to corruption in the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Games aren't about athletes, and aren't about people,'' he
said. ``It's an international business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
