<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Cats press to take on a hurting Tech lineup
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech knows it faces a tough assignment when it
plays Kentucky tonight in the Delta Air Lines Holiday Classic for
Kids.
</P>
<P>
   Before an 81-80 Tech win in 1991, the last time the Yellow
Jackets won was when Whack Hyder was coaching in 1964. Kentucky has
won 54 of 68 meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing Kentucky, but we get our (butts) kicked every
time,'' coach Bobby Cremins said. ``But they kicked a lot of
people's (butts).''
</P>
<P>
   This Kentucky team, 9-1 and ranked No. 3, is deep, experienced
and dangerous. Four Wildcats average double figures, and the famous
smothering Kentucky defense is as lethal as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to come after us with everything they've got,''
Cremins said. ``But I feel we'll be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Floyd, Tech's most consistent scorer with a 17.9 average,
knows the Jackets are in for a long night unless they can cut down
on turnovers and keep their minds on the task at hand. ``They are
going to focus on denying our guards the basketball,'' he said.
``We've got to go out and set great screens for our guys to get
open and we're going to have to deal with their pressure defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Jones, averaging 10.8 rebounds and 11.4 points, agrees.
``I think we're going to have to handle their pressure and take
care of the ball and not make mental mistakes,'' Jones said.
``We've got to play together now more than ever. Kentucky can make
you look real bad if you're not ready and focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech is aware of the famous Kentucky full-court press and
constant pressure defense. The Jackets have spent an inordinate
amount of time this week working on bringing the ball up against
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets' collective health is a worry for Cremins.
Starting forward Jon Babul, who has missed three games with a
severely sprained right ankle, is listed as doubtful. Power forward
Jason Collier, who has scored 44 points and grabbed 18 rebounds in
two games, including Tech's victory against Wofford on Wednesday,
has bleeding ulcers. Tech lost Dion Glover to a knee injury before
the season started.
</P>
<P>
   Collier does have a history of playing against Kentucky. The
former Indiana center has faced the Wildcats twice while in a
Hoosiers uniform. He averaged 11.5 points and seven rebounds in
those two encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need Babul,' Cremins said, ``but I'd say he's
doubtful.'' A 6-foot-7 sophomore, Babul was averaging 9.4 rebounds
and 8.4 points before he was injured in practice. Tech needs his
inside presence to help combat a Kentucky starting front line of
6-6 Heshimu Evans, 6-10 Michael Bradley and 6-9 Scott Padgett.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
