<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia State collapses under Miami pressure
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the first time this season, Georgia State coach
Lefty Driesell had all 11 of his players ready to go against Miami
at GSU's Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But on a night when 6-foot-11, 265-pound junior center Brad
Stricker saw his first playing time in a Georgia State uniform, and
senior forward Quincy Gause played for the first time this season,
the Panthers were blown away by the Hurricanes 76-55 before 2,189
fans Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore point guard Kevin Morris, out the previous six games
because of fractured foot, was also in the starting lineup, but
that didn't matter. Miami (5-2) used its tenacious defense to get
the game in hand at 51-28 with 15:48 remaining to play.
</P>
<P>
   Miami guard Johnny Hemsley scored 24 points and the Hurricanes
demonstrated why they led the nation in defensive field-goal
percentage last season.
</P>
<P>
   While contesting every pass and every shot, the Hurricanes
forced the Panthers (2-6) into 24 turnovers, blocked nine shots and
limited them to 33.9 percent shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''Defense is what we've built our program on,'' Miami coach
Leonard Hamilton said. ''There were some years when we weren't very
good offensively, so we figured that if we were going to win, we
had to play great defense. Tonight was our best effort of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Miami's pressure, Morris turned the ball over nine times
and made only 3 of 9 attempts from the floor. Junior guard Anton
Reese, the Panthers' leading scorer, made only 6 of 17 attempts
from the field and finished with 16 points. Gause scored 14 points
and had 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''They took us out of everything we tried to do _ flat out
kicked our butts,'' Driesell said. ''Everybody was taking bad
shots. They're pretty good. It was a tough team to be playing for
those guys who haven't played for us this year. I just hope it
doesn't affect their confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogler's comments start feud
</P>
<P>
   Letters of ``admonishment and reprimand'' were sent by the
Southeastern Conference to Florida coach Billy Donovan and South
Carolina coach Eddie Fogler because of comments made at the SEC
Media Days last month.
</P>
<P>
   Fogler had questioned Florida's recruiting practices. When asked
about the letter Friday, he responded, ``I have no comment at this
particular time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogler said a former SEC basketball player had put together a
10-day trip to France last summer that benefited Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``For (Fogler) to attack my integrity and the integrity of
anyone from Florida shows he doesn't have enough class, enough
courage to come right out and confront me about it ... it shows
absolutely no guts on his part,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
