<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAMAL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `I want to be somebody teams have to account for'
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In compiling nearly 1,600 yards in 14 games, Falcons
running back Jamal Anderson came to depend on Bob Christian. Often,
the fullback was the light to Anderson's train, leading the way
into rugged, dark territory. Now, Christian is gone, tearing up his
left knee last week in New Orleans. It was a sight that shook
Anderson _ because of his feelings for Christian and his dependency
on one of the NFL's best blocking fullbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a group of players, primarily tight end Bob Kozlowski, and
backs Gary Downs and Harold Green will combine to try to replace
Christian. Or at least Anderson hopes so. Anderson talked this week
about running without the fallen fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will it be like for you playing without Christian?
</P>
<P>
   A: He was in the meetings (Wednesday). That kind of threw me off
a little. It's going to be difficult. I'm going to try to work with
Koz, Harold Green and Gary Downs. But Bob is a big loss. Guys have
to step up and make plays. I think they're capable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You played much of the fourth quarter without Christian. How
did that go?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was hard. Koz came up to me about what to do on a play,
and I just couldn't talk to him. I told him to talk to George
(Sefick, offensive coordinator). Bobby just goes out of his way. He
kind of blocks everybody. I'm serious. He'll block a tackle and
then go on and block a linebacker. I can't tell (Christian's
replacements) what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did you know Christian was a special blocker?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, when I first signed with the Falcons, Craig
``Ironhead'' Heyward used to talk about this guy and how hard he
worked. He said I wouldn't believe it. Then he came here. I told
Bob, `I know about you.' Since then, we've talked a lot. I wanted
to get into his head. After the sixth or seventh game last year, we
really started getting on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the other sideline Sunday will be Barry Sanders. What's it
like when people say you've risen to his level?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't want to start a commotion. When I talk about running
backs, I take Barry out of the equation. It's Barry Sanders and the
rest of us. But when I play against a big back, I want to make it a
dual situation. When people talk about the best backs, I don't want
to be left out. I want to be somebody teams have to account for.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your contract is up after next season. Is it important for
you to test the free-agent market?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, not at all. I have every intention of playing my last
year of my contract. ... The reason I signed with Atlanta is I saw
stability. ... We could be like Dallas (of the early '90s). My goal
is to remain a Falcon, to play my career out in Atlanta. Look at
our offensive line. They're all young. I expect 1,500 yards for
years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
