<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No more incentives needed
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has not been an easy week to focus for the Atlanta
Falcons, who have functioned without coach Dan Reeves, recuperating
from heart bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Falcons (12-2), perhaps, they will have
plenty of built-in incentives Sunday at Detroit (5-9).
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta wins, the Falcons will realize several
accomplishments. Hence, the message on the bulletin board in the
lockerroom:
</P>
<P>
   W _ Det.
</P>
<P>
   2nd seed playoffs
</P>
<P>
   Division Champs
</P>
<P>
   (Bye week)
</P>
<P>
   A win by the Falcons would clinch the NFC West title for just
the second time in 33 seasons and give them a bye in the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need more motivation than that, you're playing the
wrong game,'' interim coach Rich Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   A bye would buy much-needed additional time not only for Reeves,
but also for starting weakside linebacker Cornelius Bennett
(sprained left knee), defensive end Lester Archambeau (broken
thumb), among others.
</P>
<P>
   Both players will start Sunday, however.
</P>
<P>
   If the Vikings (13-1) win at home over Jacksonville, Minnesota
will lock up overall home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Early inactives
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons de-activated rookie safety Omar Brown, safety Chris
Bayne, center-guard Dave Widell, and rookie tight end Roderick
Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Batch still mending
</P>
<P>
   Detroit rookie quarterback Charlie Batch, who injured his lower
back in Monday's 35-14 loss at San Francisco, did not practice
again Friday, but coach Bobby Ross has not ruled him out as the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   If Batch does not play, 14-year veteran Frank Reich will start.
</P>
<P>
   Laying down
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's game, Lions players were asked if they quit once
the game got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do it mentally, without realizing that you're going
through the motions,'' wide receiver Herman Moore said. ``I think
we're not human if we don't do that. It seemed like late in the
third quarter we lost a little something. We kept playing hard, it
seemed, but it's the fire, something that was just missing. You
could feel it, you could sense it even on the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes
</P>
<P>
   With fullback Bob Christian (knee) out for the season, reserve
tight end Brian Kozlowski (6 feet 3, 255 pounds) will be the
primary fullback. Also, running back Harold Green (6-2, 222), who
caught 29 passes last season as the team's primary third-down back,
will return to that role in two-back sets. Jamal Anderson will
handle one-back sets. Running back Gary Downs (6-1, 218) might see
playing time at fullback. ... Reserve tight end Ed Smith, who has
not caught a pass in two seasons with the Falcons after nine years
in minor-league baseball and one on Washington's practice squad,
will be the No. 2 tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket talk
</P>
<P>
   About 27,000 tickets for the first home playoff game go on sale
at 9 a.m. today at the Georgia Dome ticket offices and at
Ticketmaster outlets. A lottery drawing at 8 a.m. will determine
the order in which fans may purchase a maximum of 20 tickets at $60
each.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
