<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-18 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES19-COX     12-18 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'I've been blessed': Reeves considers his experience a miracle
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves, released from Piedmont
Hospital four days after quadruple bypass surgery, spoke Friday
about the gift of life and said he had undergone ``a life-changing
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly breaking into tears, Reeves, 54, gave thanks to God,
his family, doctors, team employees and fans, two days before the
12-2 Falcons play for the second division title in their history.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, conceding the frailities of the human condition,
admitted that he nearly paid the ultimate price for his original
inclination to tough out his medical condition until the season
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blessed,'' he said during a news conference. ``I
understand how precious life is. You do break down a little bit
more; you do cry a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   There were few dry eyes in the house. None belonged to Reeves,
whose wife, Pam, was at his side.
</P>
<P>
   He put his arm around team physician Charlie Harrison, who
helped diagnose Reeves' condition after the coach complained of
chest pains, lightheadedness and a burning sensation in his throat
after Sunday's 27-17 win at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I want to thank God for the miracle,'' he said,
pausing and then looking at Harrison, ``because this doesn't look
like an angel right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves experienced similar symptoms in August 1990, when he was
coach of the Denver Broncos. He underwent an angioplasty to clear
blockages, a procedure that was repeated five months later.
</P>
<P>
   He was told then that he should be wary of similar symptoms for
the rest of his life. They returned a few months ago, although he
said nothing while the Falcons became one of the great stories of
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up my mind about three or four months ago,'' he said.
``I had these symptoms that I wasn't going to mention. I didn't
want to do anything to distract the football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said his discomfort was especially intense on game days,
when his heart rate increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that's normal because you're heart starts beating,''
he said. ``It was just a little bit stronger in New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   A series of circumstances, including a pre-game prayer in New
Orleans by free safety Eugene Robinson and Harrison's presence in
New Orleans, led to a telltale evaluation of Reeves' heart Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Harrison doesn't normally go with us on the road,'' Reeves
said. ``From Eugene Robinson giving the pre-game prayer _ just the
whole thing fell together. For some reason, and I believe it's a
miracle. I mentioned it to Dr. Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to be so tough,'' he said, then paused. ``I didn't
want to do anything to distract our football team. Anyway, I asked
Dr. Harrison if I was being smart by waiting until the season was
over, and he said, 'Heavens no. You need to get it checked out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, one of the team's most spiritual players, seemed
surprised later Friday to learn of Reeves' comments. ``The Friday
before the game, I couldn't sleep,'' he said. ``The Lord kept
impressing on my mind. It seemed like I was going to be the one to
pray before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Reeves normally designates someone to pray, and he asked
(cornerback) Ray Buchanan. Ray said, 'No, but Gene will,' and he
didn't even know about my dream or anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my prayer,'' he said, ``I was talking about the blessings
God has bestowed upon Coach Reeves.''
</P>
<P>
   On Harrison's advice, Reeves checked into Piedmont Hospital
about 6:30 a.m. Monday. Dr. Charlie Brown performed an angiogram,
passing dye through various arteries to see if there were
blockages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think that you're imagining everything,'' Reeves said.
``When Dr. Brown did the angiogram, he did the dye in the first
artery, and he said, 'Well, you're not making it up. You have a
reason to be concerned.' And then he went to the second, and same
thing, and the third, and same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I still thought, 'Well, we'll do an angioplasty. I'll be
out of here tomorrow or something like that.' All of a sudden, he
called Pam in and called Dr. Harrison in, and said, 'We'll have to
do a bypass.' Bypass hits you in the head, and starts ringing in
your ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say, 'What's the alternative? Can you do the bypass when
the season is over?' And they both said, 'We won't let you out of
the hospital tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of the three arteries appeared to be blocked entirely, and
the other two were more than 80 percent blocked. Harrison said
earlier this week that if a second artery had closed it could have
been ``catastrophe,'' a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Harrison said, ``I'm just glad we didn't play on Monday
Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery, performed by Dr. James Kauten, used veins from the
inside of one of Reeves' legs and from the back of his chest wall
to bypass the blockages.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have called Reeves are Saints coach Mike Ditka,
Jets coach Bill Parcells and Falconsoffensive coordinator George
Sefcik, all of whom have had heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outpouring from all people, the prayers, the gifts, it's
all been incredible,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   After thanking the doctors and others at Piedmont, Reeves,
pausing often, said, ``But it goes deeper than that. This is the
kind of stress I can't handle. People really cared, from the pre-op
room, to the operation room, to the recovery room. They constantly
kept my family abreast of what was going on. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been blessed,'' he said. ``The Falcons family, the
owners, the players, the fans, everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   As Reeves gathered himself to say more, Harrison said, ``He just
passed the stress test. He's a lot better than he sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' recovery is on schedule, but he won't make the trip to
Detroit for Sunday's game against the Lions. ``My goal is to go out
(to team headquarters in Suwanee) to at least say hello to the team
before they go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he hopes to be involved in some planning for the
Dec. 27 home game against Miami. Defensive coordinator Rich Brooks
will serve as interim coach until Reeves returns. ``You go by what
you feel like you can do,'' Reeves said. ``I've already found out
you get tired doing things you take for granted. The Lord's been
good to me. I haven't done anything to damage my heart. I've got a
strong family to support me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, through maturity, you change some of the things you
do. I still got to be myself, and I'll be myself until the first
bad call (in the football game). And then I'll go crazy again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
