<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV-NOTEBOOK-1     12-18 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV-NOTEBOOK-1STLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE SHARES AIR TIME WITH IRAQ, NETWORK COMMENTATORS AND SOAP
OPERAS
</HEADLINE>
 - WRITETHRU-NYT (EDS: Adds sentence to sixth graf with choices offered by ABC; no
other changes.) 
 (rl) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The television screen showed the House of Representatives more
than three-quarters empty. And if Congress wasn't watching, why
should we? The House floor was meant to be the site of
history-making drama, but the action Friday was all off-stage. It
was definitely on camera, though, captured in the talk of reporters
and commentators who helped shape the political spin and
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The day and the television coverage had started with a far
different tone, dramatic and anachronistic in its aura of ceremony
and historical import. Paul Hays, the house reading clerk, read the
four articles of impeachment against President Clinton. A balding,
nondescript man, he looked like Middle America, an odd touch of
realism in the midst of chiseled television correspondents and
politicians with conspicuous hair weaves.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of the impeachment process seemed to sink in further
each time he repeated the words ending each article: ``William
Jefferson Clinton has undermined the integrity of his office, has
brought disrepute on the presidency, has betrayed his trust as
president.'' The portentousness did not come exclusively from the
content; every network and cable channel focused on this reading
without commentary, creating the rare, unanimous sense that this
was truly a moment of history.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, there was a passionate argument on the floor, as Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the Judiciary Committee chairman, spoke in
favor of impeachment and Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the minority
leader, objected to having the debate during the U.S. military
attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But as the speeches became familiar echoes of the Judiciary
Committee hearings, the networks cut away to talking heads. In the
most lightweight and ludicrous instance, while most network cameras
were still focused on the House floor, NBC went to a Maria Shriver
interview with Rep. Mary Bono, R-Calif., whose on-screen
identifications included ``Elected in 1998'' and ``Widow of Rep.
Sonny Bono.'' In this celebrity-driven moment, as Ms. Bono repeated
without analysis the often-heard Republican line that the
impeachment was about ``the rule of law,'' it seemed as if Vanity
Fair magazine were setting the tone for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The serious news came with updates from Baghdad, as these two
stories continued to veer erratically in and out of each others'
paths. The networks carried a briefing by Defense Secretary William
Cohen. The cable channels (and, briefly, NBC) cut away from
Congress to cover a news conference by Tariq Aziz, the deputy prime
minister of Iraq. But, when word came that the debate would
continue until 10 p.m., with the impeachment vote scheduled for
Saturday, the networks returned to their soap operas. (NBC and CBS
offered local stations a choice of network news coverage or
entertainment shows. ABC offered its regular shows or House images
without commentary.)
</P>
<P>
   There was every reason to leave. The votes had been counted if
not cast. As Tom Brokaw said on NBC, in words often echoed through
the day, ``Barring an unforeseen miracle on behalf of the
president, he will be impeached by noon tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable channels dutifully dipped in and out of the debate all
day. But when Judy Woodruff of CNN looked at the nearly-empty House
floor and described ``this building, where all the action is
today,'' it sounded like a rote lesson from an outdated history
book. The action was clearly elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos offered a more sophisticated sense of the
battle that was actually taking place. As he had pointed out the
previous day on ABC, the Democrats knew the impeachment fight was
lost; it was now a matter of who would win the spin.
</P>
<P>
   That made a briefing by White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart
at least as relevant as what was happening in the House. Lockhart
said Republicans were ``dumbing down impeachment'' and using a
``cynical political strategy'' in first playing down the importance
of impeachment and then using an impeachment vote to call for
Clinton's resignation. Analyzing that news conference on MSNBC,
Brian Williams said, ``Notice the talking point: dumbing down
impeachment. It's been handed to the Democrats; you will hear it
all day.'' (He was right; the term had already been heard in the
House debate.) Don't think for a second that dissecting a press
conference is trivial or merely time-filling. It is crucially
important in this political equivalent of a chess game, with
Republicans and Democrats looking several moves ahead to a possible
trial in the Senate, and floating every idea on television.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the cable channels went to Baghdad every time an air
raid warning sounded. In one false alarm, what seemed to be a new
bombing attack turned out to be a cannon set off to announce that
Ramadan would begin at dawn. Though the pictures from Iraq
continued to be startling, a fresher turn in the coverage came
after the first attack Wednesday. In daylight, reporters have been
making it clear how short a leash they are on, being led to see the
damage the Iraqis want to show, unable to wander freely to verify
damage or deaths independently.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, reporters and commentators were looking ahead to the
statement promised from the president after the impeachment vote,
and beyond that to a Senate trial or (possibly floating ideas for
both sides) a censure deal.
</P>
<P>
   And, looking at the empty House floor, some commentators
speculated that the representatives and the public were following
the debate on television. There was no reason to think they were,
or that they should, when television's talking heads were so
clearly the ones moving this process along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
