<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-DOCUMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ind.)  
 UNDECIDED REPUBLICANS SHOWN DOCUMENTS ON '70s CLINTON ALLEGATION  
(rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Democrats complained Friday that some
Republicans who were undecided on impeachment had been shown sealed
documents that the House Judiciary Committee received from the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, which include investigative materials pertaining
to an unsubstantiated encounter between President Clinton and a
woman in the 1970s, were shown to lawmakers like Reps. Mark Souder
of Indiana and Christopher Shays of Connecticut, Republican
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The document referred to by the officials was an affidavit filed
in the Paula Jones case. Officials said it was forwarded from
Kenneth Starr's office to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   One official said he did not know who had alerted Souder but
that Souder had been told that anyone voting against impeachment
would look bad if the document became public. The official said the
document seemed to have bothered Souder, who worried it might be
true. The White House has previously denied the allegation in it.
</P>
<P>
   But the official said that Souder might still vote against
impeachment since the document was not part of the impeachment
record. Shays has not announced a decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-98 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
